<HEADER>
A7750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DOMINICK-DUNNE-ART-NY     01-27 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICK-DUNNE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PASSIONATE STORYTELLER, RECOVERING FROM HIS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years Dominick Dunne went around saying that it was Tommy
Skakel, a nephew of Ethel Kennedy's, who had beaten Martha Moxley
to death. Last week, nearly 25 years after the unsolved killing of
the 15-year-old Greenwich, Conn., girl, Tommy's younger brother
Michael was indicted in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I guilt-ridden about Tommy?'' says the novelist and Vanity
Fair journalist, glaring, as he sits beside a crackling fireplace
in his jewel box of an apartment. ``No!''
</P>
<P>
   And what if Michael is not guilty, as he pleaded last week?
``No, there's no possibility,'' insists Dunne, who had given leaked
confidential documents about the killing to Mark Fuhrman, the
detective he met while covering the O.J. Simpson trial. The
re-examination of the case by Fuhrman and others may have been what
prompted the authorities to take a fresh look.
</P>
<P>
   There is a furious absolutism to Dunne, whose 1993 novel, ``A
Season in Purgatory,'' was based loosely on the Moxley case. ``I
hate defense lawyers,'' he says, chief among them the lawyer who
represented John Sweeney, the Ma Maison chef who strangled Dunne's
22-year-old daughter, Dominique. Convicted in 1984 of manslaughter,
Sweeney was released after serving two and a half years of a
six-and-a-half-year sentence. The death of Dunne's daughter and her
killer's trial left a permanent raw wound; much of Dunne's fiction
and journalism continues to be about rich, powerful people trying
to get away with murder.
</P>
<P>
   But short of violent crime, Dunne has an unusual capacity for
forgiving spectacularly seamy behavior, as one who not only has
witnessed it intimately for much of his life, but who was a
wallowing participant for a long, ugly stretch.
</P>
<P>
   At 50, Dunne was a cocaine-sniffing alcoholic who sold his West
Highland white terrier because he needed $300. Now 74, Dunne, who
has an Upper East Side pied-a-terre bought by ``The Two Mrs.
Grenvilles,'' a country home paid for by ``An Inconvenient Woman''
and a beloved Jaguar purchased by his articles on the Menendez
murder case, relishes his fame, fortune and party invitations with
bottomless gusto.
</P>
<P>
   He comes from money. The Irish Catholic clan headed by an
autocratic patriarch in ``A Season in Purgatory,'' widely assumed
to be a conflation of the Skakels and the Kennedys, was drawn from
Dunne's household. ``We were lower-case Kennedys,'' he says,
comparing his family to the dynasty he views with envy, admiration
and outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up Catholic, rich but disdained in Hartford, then a city
dominated by Protestant aristocrats, gave Dunne a piercing
insider-outsider perspective that has never left him, a relentless
desire to dance in inner circles. The second of six children,
Dunne, slight and unathletic, was the family's storyteller, shamed
into silence by his father, a surgeon, who beat him so severely
that he lost some hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, snow falls on his terrace; inside, Dunne recounts tale
after tale, dramatic, dishy, hilarious, jumping up to act out
parts, self-absorbed, yes, enamored of his own storytelling, yes,
but with the evident pleasure of a man exulting in a strong,
authoritative voice unleashed after decades of self-doubt. His
latest book, ``The Way We Lived Then: Recollections of a Well-Known
Name Dropper,'' is an extended scrapbook detailing his years as a
B-list television and movie producer and A-list social butterfly
and climber in Hollywood, where he partied compulsively with the
glamorati about whom he writes so knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   Why, given how assiduously he ploughs back hush-hush stories
into his work, do people with something to hide invite him to
parties?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a quiet listener,'' Dunne says. ``I keep in touch with a
great many people and have a great many friends, and I keep up with
everybody.'' Friends confide, then he publishes. A feud follows
and, often, reconciliation. Nick, as he is known, inspires a gruff
fondness.
</P>
<P>
   As his head hit the ceiling of his Hollywood career in the '60s,
Dunne began drinking heavily, outspending his income. In a druggy
haze, he set fire to his hotel room; a drug-sharing stranger beat
him up. Prostitutes, a drug arrest. Divorce. ``I had a secret
life,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't get that out of me,'' he replies stiffly.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he became his own worst nightmare: a social pariah.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to a book-signing recently at a Connecticut bookstore, 25
years after his flight to an Oregon cabin, where he dried out,
started writing and decided to move to New York, living near his
son Griffin, the actor and producer. He would go on to resurrect
himself into a best-selling author, becoming nationally recognized,
thanks to the televised Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   At the bookstore, a state trooper somberly asks him to step
outside.
</P>
<P>
   He freezes, this man whose brother committed suicide and nephew
died in a plane crash, whose middle son once was missing for a week
while hiking, whose former wife died from multiple sclerosis, whose
daughter was strangled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Dunne, someone hit your Jaguar,'' the trooper says.
</P>
<P>
   The sobbing offender stands by the smashed prize, terrified,
expecting Dominick Dunne to explode.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he laughs loudly, looking heavenward. Then, wrapping
his arms around her, he gives the startled woman a bear hug. ``It
can be fixed!'' he shouts, between guffaws.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
