</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTING ON THE BIG GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The overriding obsession among many people observing
Sunday's match between the St. Louis Rams and Tennessee Titans is
not who will win, but, instead, who will cover the seven-point
spread.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is no other single sporting event in America that
inspires such wide-spread wagering interest as the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been estimated one out of every three adults in this
country has a stake in the game either in an office pool, a
friendly wager with a friend or a bet with a bookmaker or in one of
the legal sports books,'' says Las Vegas gambling figure Jimmy
Vaccaro. ``At least $75 million will be wagered on the game in the
Nevada sports books. Another $150 million will be bet in the
off-shore gambling outfits in the Caribbean. And six times that
amount will be bet with the illegal books around the country. I
wouldn't be surprised if more than a billion dollars winds up being
bet on this game.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many people risking so much money on the NFL's most
high-profile event, one idly wonders about the origin of the
seven-point line that favors the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   How did it come about? Who's responsible for it? From where did
it originate? What went into the process?
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the entire Super Bowl line process unfold Sunday and
it was pretty fascinating,'' says Peter Ruckland, general manager
of the Gambler's Book Club store in Las Vegas who's writing a book
on the history of sports betting in America.
</P>
<P>
   Ruckland was at the two-story Las Vegas headquarters of the
appropriately-named Las Vegas Sports Consultants, the Michael
Roxborough-founded company that has been supplying the official
sports odds to most betting entities in America for the past 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got there early in the morning before the NFL conference
championship games even started,'' relates Ruckland. ``There are
basically eight people involved in the entire process, Their names
are Scott Kaminsky, Cesar Robaina, Peter Korner, Jason Been, (cq)
Karol (cq) Lucan, Tom Vanderhoof, Dan O'Brien and John Harper. And
there is also an outside oddsmakers they use as a consultant. They
post lines not only on football, but also on all the other sports
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``They watch games on TV sets that are all over the place, and
gab back and forth throughout the day. Even before the games
started, they had made up an imaginary line for four possible Super
Bowl matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the Rams 10 over Tennessee and 6 over Jacksonville.
They had Jacksonville 8 over Tampa Bay. And they had Tennessee 5
over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as the day went on and Tennessee looked impressive in
beating Jacksonville and the Rams struggled against Tampa Bay, they
came in with a lower point spread for the Ram-Titan matchup. At
about 4:45, perhaps the most important employee in the Las Vegas
Sports Consultant operation, Chris Chavez, the company's computer
administrator, punched in the opening spread 8 points to outlets
around the country. Why is Chavez so important? Can you imagine the
chaos Chavez could create if he sent out the wrong number?''
</P>
<P>
   While the Las Vegas Sports Consultants disseminates the numbers
they also opened the unders/overs line at 48 its clients use the
price more as a guideline and often go with their own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, while the Stardust's sports book manager, Joe
Lupo, opened the Super Bowl Sunday evening at 7, the Hilton's Art
Manteris' made it attractive for the chalkies gamblers inclined to
bet on favorites by opening it at a mere 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   But, almost immediately, after a flurry of back and forth
betting, the price steadied at 7, where it's remained the entire
week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one wonders how the Rams wound up as a touchdown favorite
in the Super Bowl even though they had the same regular season
record as the Titans, 13-3, and even though they were beaten by the
Tennessee team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest question I'm asked is what actually goes into
deciding a point spread,'' says Scott Kaminsky, senior oddsmaker
for the Las Vegas Sports Consultants. ``I mean, it's not like we
have power ratings, or feed a bunch of data into a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just more of a gut feeling among those making such
decisions. The Rams are the favorites in this game because they
have been a more dominating team than Tennessee this season. You
also try to come up with a number that will result in two-way
action. If we had opened the Rams as 10-point favorites after
Sunday's game, all the money would have come in on the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a line is really not as exciting or as mysterious as
most people think. It's pretty boring, humdrum stuff. Basically,
for the Super Bowl, there were four of us who ultimately came up
with the line me, Cesar Robaina, Jason Been and a guy we use from
the outside named Eugene Buanthony (also known as Gene Bennett).
</P>
<P>
   ``When we opened it at 8, all the early tidbit money came in on
Tennessee, and that's why the spread dropped to seven. But it won't
surprise me if the public will come in strongly on the Rams this
weekend. The public has a long history of betting favorites in the
Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaminsky has worked for Las Vegas Sports Consultants since
Roxborough, a legendary numbers whiz, put the company together in
1984. Roxborough recently sold it for an estimated $6 million to
the San Mateo-based Data Broadcasting Corporation, and is now
living in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas Sports Consultants doesn't get involved in exotic
wagers like some of the goofy ones now up at the Imperial Palace in
Las Vegas (Will Kurt Warner's completion total exceed Kobe Bryant's
point total Sunday against Houston? Will Marshall Faulk's rushing
total exceed David Duval's final round score at the Phoenix Open?
Will Steve McNair's passing yardage exceed the Lakers-Rockets point
total?, etc.).
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotels put up those kind of bets to stir the interest of
customers who aren't necessarily football fans,'' says Kaminsky.
``There are some pretty funny ones. We don't have the time here to
mess with those kind of wagers. Remember, the Super Bowl is just
one game for us. We're busy this time of the year putting out daily
lines on college basketball games, hockey games, NBA games, tennis
matches, golf matches and car races.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel you've put out the right line when there is a lot of
betting on both sides. And that's been the case this week with this
Super Bowl. There's been a lot of two-way action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
