<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BURDENS OF BEING HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A test for voters, an old one, but it still works.
</P>
<P>
   PART I
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a candidate who is outspoken, opinionated and litigious,
who rewards loyalists, assails critics and berates reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this candidate as a man. See him in your mind's eye
(which in this case is not very difficult). What adjectives come to
mind? Be honest with yourself. Strong. Aggressive. Tough. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine this candidate as a woman. The adjectives change a
bit, don't they?
</P>
<P>
   PART II
</P>
<P>
   Consider a candidate (male or female) with opinions about
everything, who ducks rarely and knows the issues inside-out.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider a candidate who ducks and parries, who rehearses
spontaneity and seems frightened of candor.
</P>
<P>
   Which candidate do you prefer?
</P>
<P>
   A month into the Senate election year, and two of Hillary Rodham
Clinton's three big problems (see below for the third) are as
crystal clear as the ice on her Chappaqua driveway. She had it
half-right on Tuesday in Albany, when asked why some New Yorkers do
not seem to like her. She cited her positions, adding, ``and maybe
a little of it is because I'm a woman taking those positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Any woman who has ever been in a position of responsibility
knows that it is still more difficult for women to succeed than for
men. That's just how it is. Women in public life still have to be
on their guard. They cannot be as combative or, heaven forfend,
emotional. They have to be candid, but not aggressively so. Direct,
not cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they just can't win.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani can be angry in public and it seems to
help. Three years ago, when Vanity Fair ran a nasty, anonymously
sourced story claiming that his marriage was in trouble and that he
was having an ``intimate'' relationship with an aide, he angrily
denounced the story as ``scurrilous'' and ``untrue,'' did not
directly answer questions about the status of his marriage and said
he'd have no more to say. End of episode.
</P>
<P>
   When a radio reporter in Buffalo recently asked Mrs. Clinton if
she'd been faithful to her husband, even if she'd been unfaithful
with Vincent Foster Jr., the Clinton friend and adviser who
committed suicide, the protective wall came up. Mrs. Clinton chose
her words carefully. She kept her voice even, saying, ``Those kinds
of questions are really out of bounds, and everybody who knows me
knows the answer to those questions.'' When the reporter pressed
her _ ``Is the answer no?'' _ she answered, ``Well, yes, of course
it's no.''
</P>
<P>
   A pundit or two have argued that she should have lost her temper
and refused to answer. Sure. And then the tabloids would have gone
on and on asking why didn't she say no? What is she hiding? Critics
would have denounced her for unsenatorially losing her cool.
</P>
<P>
   In the artificial game of politics, women simply have to do even
heavier role-playing than men.
</P>
<P>
   But why does Mrs. Clinton appear equally careful and calculated
when the questions are not personal, when the political burdens of
sex are irrelevant? She said in Albany that she had probably
alienated some voters because of her positions. But polls show that
many voters agree with her. The problem is not her positions, but
how she shares them. Gingerly. That does not work with New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers like attitude. Hyperbole. Confrontation. Equanimity
is OK for Aspen. New York demands flair.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the word was that Mrs. Clinton was ready to mix
it up. But her ballyhooed appearance with David Letterman, while
beautifully performed, was orchestrated. She favors campaign
finance reform, but is about to set a record for spending. She
favors the ``concept'' of mayoral control of education, but not
with this mayor, and she won't even say whether Elian Gonzalez
should go home to Cuba, punting to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said weeks ago that the boy should stay here. Agree or
disagree, the mayor's got a position.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has given herself a tough job. Not only is she a
controversial woman who has to figure how to be guarded but not
artificial, she also has a lot of baggage (big problem No. 3):
she's got that husband, her health care debacle, the ``vast
right-wing conspiracy,'' Whitewater, her commodities deal and a
conflict: how can you be a convincing feminist while acting like a
female victim in a Jacqueline Susann novel?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, campaigning is harder for a woman. Mrs. Clinton can't
change that. Nor can she lose that baggage. But she can control the
core of her candidacy _ how she conducts herself and talks about
issues important to voters. One out of three ain't bad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
