<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REST FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal is on pace for a career high in
minutes played, and based on coach Phil Jackson's clear
disenchantment with the Lakers' bench, O'Neal just might lead the
league. If he doesn't collapse first.
</P>
<P>
   After playing 55 minutes against the Utah Jazz on Monday,
O'Neal's per-game average is up to 40.1 -- tying him for fifth in
the league, and putting him on pace for 3,249 minutes this season.
The most he's ever played was 3,224 in 1993-94, his second NBA
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' only backup centers are Travis Knight and John
Salley, and Jackson offered a blunt assessment of that twosome:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not compelling,'' he said Wednesday. ``It doesn't feel
compelling to have to play anybody off the bench behind Shaq. As a
tired player, he's probably better than what we have to offer, and
that's pretty obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves a barren free-agent market or a trade as the only
solutions . And nothing is imminent. Contrary to reports out of
Washington, team sources say the Lakers have little interest in
Wizards center Ike Austin, primarily because he's due $11 million
over the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So Jackson will continue to play O'Neal as much as necessary,
giving him quick, one- or two-minute breaks at the end of quarters.
He doesn't trust the Lakers to play extended periods without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him a rest at the end of the third quarter for two
minutes aga inst Utah, we fell what...six points down? (The Lakers
went from a one-point lead to a 66-61 deficit). We just can't
afford to do that,'' Jackson said. ``And that's the unfortunate
part about it, is that when we do take him out of the game...(we)
lost a lead to fall behind going into the fourth quarter. So
there's a certain sense about how to play it and how to do it
(without O'Neal), and we're not quite there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad chemistry: The Lakers' early struggles against Utah produced
a rare sight: a five-man substitution by Jackson. After leading by
nine points in the second quarter, the Lakers watched the Jazz go
on a 14-2 run to take a 37-34 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson called timeout with 3:17 to go in the half and sent in a
whole new unit -- A.C. Green, Devean George, Ron Harper, Derek
Fisher and O'Neal went in for Robert Horry, Glen Rice, Brian Shaw,
Kobe Bryant and Knight. It was a first for Jackson this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing really poorly, and we just needed to make an
overall substitution of people in there,'' he said. ``It was a
pretty pathetic offensive group of guys out there. We just had to
take people out and get a new mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   The move stemmed the bleeding, but the new group went into
halftime still trailing by a point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
