<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   2 DEMOCRATS ADVISE McCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain on Wednesday listed two prominent Democrats
among his foreign policy advisers, Zbigniew Brzezinski, the
national security adviser under President Jimmy Carter, and R.
James Woolsey, President Clinton's former director of central
intelligence. Also on a list of advisers released Wednesday were
Republicans like Henry Kissinger, Jeane Kirkpatrick, Robert
McFarlane and Lawrence Eagleburger.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES ON HAWKS
</P>
<P>
   On his first full day of campaigning in New Hampshire, Steve
Forbes appeared at a defense contractor in Nashua and called for
increased military spending saying, ``A cheap hawk is a dead
hawk.'' He added: ``The U.S. is the only superpower. If our country
gets in trouble then the rest of the world gets in trouble.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GORE ON HEALTH CARE
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday praised the Clinton
administration's overhaul of the welfare system. Welfare, like the
economy, has improved over the past eight years, Gore said. ``OK,
it's been a success, what now?'' Gore said at a circuit-board
manufacturer in Manchester. ``We need to keep building on this
success.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS: CLOSE PLAY AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   Even in his home state, Sen. John McCain of Arizona is in a
tight race with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, a recent poll found.
The Arizona State University poll, conducted Thursday through
Sunday, found that Republicans who voted in the past two
presidential primaries supported McCain over Bush, 37 percent to 30
percent, but the margin of sampling error was four percentage
points. Support for other candidates was in single digits.
</P>
</TEXT>
