r s BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN     01-27 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DESPERATE FOR SPLIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the Pac-10 title. Forget a top seed in the NCAA
Tournament. At 11-5 and sixth place in the conference, UCLA's
priority should be (ital)qualifying for(end ital) the Tournament.
The journey continues this week in Oregon, where the Bruins
desperately need a split.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, every Pac-10 team with at least 18 wins
and a .500 or-better league record has made the Tournament (14 of
14).
</P>
<P>
   To reach 18, the Bruins must win seven of their last 14 games.
They have four very difficult games left (Arizona, Syracuse and
Stanford twice). Four others will be tough: USC and Oregon at home;
Arizona State and Cal on the road.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins lose twice this weekend, starting tonight at
Oregon State tonight, they'd have to win their remaining home games
(including Stanford) or win six at home and one on the road.
Considering their recent play, they can't count on beating anyone,
day or night, home or road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We win a game and then we get too satisfied,'' UCLA forward
Matt Barnes said. ``We don't stay hungry. Everyone's out to beat us
every game, and I don't think some people realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   He's back: Oregon State received a boost last weekend when
center Jason Heide returned from a sprained ankle and broken thumb.
He is the Beavers' best low-post scorer and has averaged 10 points
in three games against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ankle injury was difficult, but it was a blessing in
disguise because it allowed the thumb to heal more than it might
have,'' Beavers coach Eddie Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on strong: Barnes practiced this week as well as he
played against Arizona State and might join the starting lineup
tonight. (Rico Hines is out with a sprained toe).
</P>
<P>
   If Barnes starts, Jason Kapono will slide from small forward to
wing guard, giving the Bruins four starters 6-7 or taller.
</P>
<P>
   After several subpar games, Barnes scored a career-high 17
points Saturday. He also played well defensively and committed just
one turnover in 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing with greater intensity defensively, and that
allows us to extend his minutes, and as a result his offense comes
into play ,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
