<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNER HOPES TO REDSHIRT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USC forward Jarvis Turner is currently on crutches with a
fractured left ankle that could sideline him the rest of the
season, but the senior says he would like to explore the
possibility of redshirting and returning for a fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to think that I've played my last game at USC,''
Turner said. ``If it's possible, I'd like to come back, but I still
have to look into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's chances for a redshirt year are not good. He has played
in seven games, which would be more than the 20 percent limit for
redshirt candidates. Turner also played in USC's 16th game, which
would place him past the halfway mark of the season, another litmus
test for redshirts. He could still try and petition the NCAA
claiming a medical hardship.
</P>
<P>
   No regrets: Even with the recent rash of injuries, USC coach
Henry Bibby said he doesn't have second thoughts about the
transfers of forwards Greg Lakey (Loyola Marymount) and Shannon
Swillis (Fresno State) following last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have any regrets? No. Not at all,'' Bibby said. ``The
guys that left, I'm glad they left. It shows no commitment on their
part. Every kid decided it was not in their best interest to stay
here. Do I play favorites? Yes, the guys that play best I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said he's happier that he has less players available, if
they are happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at our basketball team right now and I can't find
anyone that's complaining,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Scalabrine: Forward Brian Scalabrine said he believes
teammate and roommate Sam Clancy (broken foot) will be out the
minimum six weeks and return for the final two games of the
conference season. That goes against the medical opinions following
last week's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing Sam has is amazing genes,'' Scalabrine said,
referring to his father, former NFL player Sam Clancy Sr. ``And
I've been telling him to drink milk. The only milk he got today is
cheese from a Wendy's cheeseburger.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Turner and Clancy made the trip to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Step it up: Bibby said he has been disappointed in the play of
junior guard Jeff Trepagnier the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything the last two games,'' Bibby said. `` I
didn't see it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he forgot that Trepagnier made three critical plays
that sent the Arizona State game into overtime last week. But
Trepagnier agreed with Bibby's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's probably right,'' Trepagnier said. ``I'm one of
the main guys the team depends on, I can't let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice reception: The Trojans are noticing a different reaction
around campus this week, no doubt the result of their 5-0 Pac-10
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, when I went to class people said `Great game,' ''
Trepagnier said. ``Last year, when we were losing they didn't even
pay attention to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Added forward David Bluthenthal: ``Every day, one of my teachers
talks about how I'm in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Foul problems: Bibby said one of the main goals for tonight's
game against Oregon is to keep his starters from committing dumb
fouls. ``We talked about it as a team yesterday,'' Bibby said.
``Three players get two silly fouls every night -- Jeff Trepagnier,
Brandon Granville and Brian Scalabrine -- hopefully, we can
minimize that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
