<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOAT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT     01-27 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
 
 (nk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Battling from behind to stage a stirring
comeback on a strange, fickle day better suited for water-skiing
than for yacht racing, Paul Cayard's America One overtook Italy's
Prada Challenge on Thursday and won by 1 minute 33 seconds to even
the five-of-nine final round of the Louis Vuitton Cup at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Cayard cemented his reputation as a never-say-die
competitor who is never out of a boat race, no matter how deep the
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's light-to-moderate wind contest, Cayard hoped
to see more substantial breezes in the 12-to-15 knot range on
Thursday. But the conditions proved far more challenging for this
second race of the challenger series to determine the opponent for
New Zealand's defense of the America's Cup next month.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the race committee postponed the start for nearly an
hour, waiting for a fluky swirling wind to fill and settle. But
from the very beginning, it was apparent that the patchwork breeze
would play a major role in the day's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a 7-to-9 knot zephyr eased in from the southeast, and
the committee sounded the gun to start the afternoon's proceedings.
Both skippers worked their helms gingerly throughout the prestart
sequence, fearful of committing a foul and knowing that quick,
tight maneuvers were out of the question in the light air.
</P>
<P>
   At one stage, the America One tactician, John Kostecki, firmly
stated, ``I want the left,'' a comment picked up by the onboard
television mike. But after a slow-motion tussle with about a minute
to go, it was Prada sailing to the course's left-hand side, while
America One peeled inside the committee boat and off to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard's boat enjoyed an eight-second lead at the start as both
boats diverged on opposite tacks. When they tacked and closed for
the race's inaugural crossing, America One still held the
advantage. But after Cayard planted a tack directly in front of
Prada, the Italians again spun out to the left to escape the
disturbed wind flowing over America One's sails.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Americans, however, Kostecki's original
assessment was dead on. Working the left for all it was worth,
Prada soon took over the lead. Once there, the Italians found
better wind pressure and began to extend their lead, showing a
pronounced edge in boat speed in conditions generally thought to
favor America One.
</P>
<P>
   Prada found even more breeze at the top mark, and rounded with a
solid 1:49 lead. America One discovered a tad more pressure and,
aided by a botched Italian jibe, closed Prada's lead to 1:04 at the
bottom mark.
</P>
<P>
   But the breeze continued to shift and oscillate, and Cayard
summed up the conditions succinctly. ``Squirrelly day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Working to the left of the Italian boat, Cayard found good
pressure from a favorable direction and soon, remarkably, clawed
back into the lead. But Prada was still positioned to pull back in
front with a favorable wind shift.
</P>
<P>
   But Cayard was just getting going. And a torn gennaker, a
light-wind sail, sustained seconds after America One rounded the
mark and hoisted the sail did not deter him from sailing a
sensational downwind leg. America One's crew recovered quickly,
sending up a new sail to replace the ripped one and, for the second
time, overtaking Prada.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom mark, America One rounded 1:27 ahead of Prada. It
was the first time the Americans led around any mark in the
challenger finals. And, it was the first time the American team
relaxed all day.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was simply a matter of covering the Italians and
denying a passing lane. Cayard completed the exercise and squared
the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
