<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7769 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAMPO-HNS     01-27 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAMPO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones won't have any shopping to do
when he gets to the Super Bowl. He found his next head coach right
at Valley Ranch.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jones announced he was promoting defensive
coordinator Dave Campo to the spot vacated when Chan Gailey was
fired two days after the Cowboys lost their wild-card playoff game
at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are also expected to hire New England quarterbacks
coach Jack Reilly to be their offensive coordinator, a role that
was occupied by Gailey previously. Riley, who spent Wednesday at
Valley Ranch meeting with Jones, was a former Dallas quarterbacks
coach under Ernie Zampese.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary coach Mike Zimmer will likely be promoted to defensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   In hiring Campo, Jones said he wanted to shorten the transition
period. The Cowboys went through one disruption two years ago when
Gailey was hired to replace Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come from within the staff, it reduces the transition that
would always come and has come any time a person from outside our
organization has come in,'' Jones said. ``We have a sense of
urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo, 52, has been with the team for 11 years, since Jones
bought it in 1989. Among the group of assistant coaches Jimmy
Johnson brought with him from the University of Miami, Campo rose
to the position of defensive coordinator five years ago. He was
part of three Super Bowl championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a feeling of pride when we can look at our staff and
find the man with the qualities to coach the Dallas Cowboys,''
Jones said. ``There was no doubt in my mind that the best man was
right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo becomes only the fifth head coach in the Cowboys' history,
but he will be the fourth in eight seasons. Gailey, who served only
two seasons, was the only Cowboys coach not to earn a Super Bowl
ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will give it everything I have to bring those expectations
and aspirations back where they should be,'' Campo said. ``In this
business, you work to try to be the best you can be. That's
something I've tried to do all my life _ not worry about what
obstacles were in front of me but try to get around those
obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo has been examining NFL head coaching vacancies with
interest and was frustrated that his name hadn't been included in
any previous speculation. He saved the stories mentioning the
``hot'' candidates, tacking up a list, with his name noticeably
absent, for motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me,'' Campo said in December before Gailey's
firing. ``I enjoy being here in Dallas. But I want to be a head
coach. You'd like to think things were on merit. Sometimes it's not
merit. But that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Campo's defenses have ranked among the league's top 10 in three
of the past four seasons. This season, the Cowboys started near the
bottom after a woeful season-opening performance in Washington.
They finished 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Campo was a three-year starter at defensive back at Central
Connecticut State before moving into the coaching ranks. He has had
stops at his alma mater as well as Albany State, Bridgeport,
Pittsburgh, Washington State, Boise State, Oregon State, Weber
State, Iowa State, Syracuse and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But he seems to have settled in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been part of this organization for 11 years,'' Campo
said. ``I feel like I'm part of family in this organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry and I have the same philosophy, and that's to win the
Super Bowl. We've been together, and we know how we each think. I
think that makes it a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo and kicking coordinator Steve Hoffman are the only coaches
remaining from Johnson's initial staff.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0012 </DOCNO>
