<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-GUARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 MALE GUARDS IN WESTCHESTER ARE ACCUSED OF JAIL RAPES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DEBRA WEST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAWTHORNE, N.Y. _ Four of the roughly two dozen guards who
oversee the women's quarters in the Westchester County jail were
arrested Wednesday on sex-abuse charges, including raping and
sodomizing prisoners and forcing them to strip in exchange for
medication.
</P>
<P>
   County Executive Andrew J. Spano said that the sexual
mistreatment by the four male guards was such an abuse of power
that he would change the jail's work rules by requiring that only
women guard the female prisoners' residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an abuse of power by the corrections officers
involved,'' Spano said Wednesday at a news conference. ``We think
that a change of procedures is warranted. We don't want men any
longer to have access to the living quarters of female prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said that although the investigation would
continue, no other sexual abuse or wrongdoing was suspected. They
also said that other corrections officers apparently had no
knowledge of what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   In the six-month investigation, the authorities interviewed 33
current and former female inmates, said the county district
attorney, Jeanine F. Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pirro told of one woman with a toothache ``who was in
extreme pain, and who could not get medication until she took her
top off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And when she wanted more, she had to expose another body
part,'' Ms. Pirro said. ``Two days later, she had a tooth
extracted.''
</P>
<P>
   The men arrested were also suspended from their jobs. Under a
state law adopted in 1996, any sex between an inmate and a guard is
deemed third-degree rape, or statutory rape, because prisoners are
not free to give their consent.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, at least three other guards at the Westchester
County jail have been convicted of sex-related crimes against
inmates, Ms. Pirro said.
</P>
<P>
   Spano, the county executive, said only a few of the guards who
work in the women's housing unit are women; county officials said
the exact number was not available. Of the 750 guards at the jail,
135 are women.
</P>
<P>
   The jail can hold up to 200 women prisoners. They are kept there
while they are awaiting trial, or when their convictions call for
sentences of less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mishi Faruqee, director of the Women in Prison Project at the
New York Correctional Association, a nonprofit watchdog group, said
coerced sexual relations between female prisoners and guards was a
common problem, although statistics are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Women inmates feel they must surrender to advances to win or
retain privileges, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, officials praised the women who told their stories of
sexual abuse in the jail, which allegedly began in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very strong women,'' said Detective Glenna Lunn, who
interviewed the women. ``They should be proud of themselves for
coming forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7776 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     01-27 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPO LANDED TOP JOB OLD WAY: HE EARNED IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dave Campo's niche in franchise history will be
that he is the first Dallas Cowboys assistant ever elevated to the
role of head coach.
</P>
<P>
   And despite what you may not know about the man, despite what
you may think of the owner, there is something very righteous and
encouraging about that.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 years, Campo paid his dues as a loyal staff soldier. He
arrived not long after owner Jerry Jones arrived. Like Jones, he
learned the league. He watched the Cowboys' family prosper _ and
now suffer.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a normal football organization, if this were a real
football team _ and not the NFL's most-watched soap opera _ Owner
Jones could have swallowed hard and imported a brand new head
coach. That new coach would have had full rein to gut the current
staff and surround himself with his own nest of assistants.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a normal NFL team, there would have been a bold new
look at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   But as Owner Jones said Wednesday, ``I didn't give that much
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   A completely new coach would have meant a new philosophy, Jones
explained, and that could well have meant a new offense and
defense, with accompanying new opinions on personnel. The new coach
might not have been as enamored of Troy Aikman, of Emmitt Smith, or
of Darren Woodson. He might not even have liked Jerry's habit of
wandering onto the sideline in midgames.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, at the wise and experienced age of 52, Campo became the
franchise's fifth head coach Wednesday. He deserved it as much as
any assistant coach since Jimmy Johnson's staff began to disperse.
</P>
<P>
   As Campo himself said, ``I believe I've paid some dues.''
</P>
<P>
   His first coaching job came at Central Connecticut State 28
years ago. In his 11 seasons with the Cowboys, he toiled loyally
and achieved success in every area where he was assigned. Five
seasons ago, some thought that Jim Eddy would have been the better
choice as defensive coordinator. Campo has since disproved that.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't need Jesse Jackson to get hired. He didn't need a
special task force of the NFL commissioner. He didn't need a letter
of recommendation from Jimmy Johnson or Don Shula or a phone call
from Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Campo got the job the old-fashioned way, by earning it.
</P>
<P>
   He is not large in stature _ Owner Jones is taller than his new
coach _ but he is Italian. And as one of the other Cowboys
assistants once said, Campo speaks ``a lot taller'' on the practice
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at the background,'' Jones said, ``I see energy.
There's intelligence. This is one of the smartest people we have in
our organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I see toughness. You don't coach the players he's had and
have the success he's had without being tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to some local thinking, therefore, ``Campo'' is not the
Italian word for doormat. If Jones steps on future toes, Campo will
say something. If players try to re-enact the owner's-office end
run that scuttled Chan Gailey, Campo will say something.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is too proud and feisty a man not to say something if he
feels he's being undermined. His resume is solid. He could walk
away from this organization and be hired as somebody else's
assistant coach in less than a month. And Campo might have, if Joe
Avezzano had been named head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Campo never said that publicly, but Owner Jones had to weigh the
possibility. Thus, Campo was not only the smarter choice, but the
more expedient one.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted the job and, within hours of Gailey's departure, Campo
gave the owner a list of reasons why he should get it. Some might
call it politicking, but Jones cited it as an example of how
organized Campo is.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Cowboys' occasional episodes of discombobulation
in recent seasons, a little organization couldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jones said he saw the pointlessness in continuing to make
phone calls, trawling the coaching waters, ``to try to find someone
to beat him out.'' At this stage, the owner implied, no one was
going to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I know the direction of this organization,'' Campo
said. ``I also know the direction of Jerry. I know the buttons that
need to be pushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have in place some outstanding football players. I just
think we need to get refocused.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter is hard to argue. As Campo outlined his coaching
philosophy, he mentioned things like enthusiasm, discipline and
motivation _ words that should perk ears among Cowboys fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe that you can motivate athletes,'' Campo said.
``My No. 1 objective is to develop an attitude. We have got to get
that attitude back.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Campo, the longtime loyal soldier, do it? Owner Jones, it
says here, had to find out.
</P>
<P>
   There are buttons to be pushed. There's a fire to be rekindled.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, as well as anyone that Jones could have hired, knows
what's expected. Some of us will be surprised if he comes up short.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
