<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY FIRE BROADSIDES IN TESTY DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs throughout to put the candidates' statements and positions in
better context, while tightening and/or eliminating some of the
less-important exchanges)  
 (also see DEMS-DEBATE-TEXT)  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Facing questions about the vigor of his
campaign and under frequent attack from Vice President Al Gore,
former Sen. Bill Bradley attacked Gore on Wednesday night over
abortion, welfare reform, health care plans that ``nibble around
the edges'' and for working ``hand in glove with special
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   In their seventh and most combative debate, held just six days
before the New Hampshire primary, Gore hammered Bradley on familiar
subjects, accusing him of voting with congressional supporters of
President Ronald Reagan against children and of offering a health
plan that did not do what it promised.
</P>
<P>
   The testy, one-hour debate was punctuated with contradictions
and quarrels. Each Democratic presidential candidate accused the
other of conducting a negative campaign, and Bradley even raised
the specter of President Richard M. Nixon. With Bradley hoping to
regain his political footing and avoid a second consecutive defeat
after Monday's drubbing in Iowa, his aggressiveness was
particularly notable while Gore's was more familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we believe that you will tell the truth as
president if you won't tell the truth as a candidate?'' Bradley
asked. ``Any politician can pick a fight, but only a leader can
move a country forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore defended his record against the special interest charge
when he said, ``I have fought for working people against every
lobby that exists in Washington.'' And he spoke up for President
Clinton, too, saying, ``People are tired of the whole discussion
about the president's personal mistake. They think that by and
large he has been a great president, in turning this economy
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion was the first issue joined. Even as the Republican
presidential candidates are competing to assert their credentials
as opponents of abortion, Gore and Bradley are arguing their
records as defenders of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates' positions are now identical, favoring
no change in the Roe vs. Wade decision and supporting a change in
the law, to require Medicaid to pay for abortions for poor women.
But Bradley pointed out that National Right to Life, an advocacy
group, had given Gore an 84 percent positive rating in his early
years in Congress, when he opposed Medicaid abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your campaign shouldn't go around saying that you've always
been for a woman's right to choose, because the record shows you
did not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore defended himself, saying ``It's true that early in my
career I wrestled with the question of what kinds of exceptions
should be allowed to the general rule that Medicaid should also pay
for this procedure. I have come to the strong view that all women,
regardless of their income, must have the right to choose, and
that's my position.'' He added ``If you want to manufacture a
distinction, OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's first salvo came on an issue Bradley has
tried to make his signature, a pledge to ``end child poverty in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, ``The '81 budget cuts that Ronald Reagan proposed
resulted in an increase of 1 million children losing health care
under Medicaid and one and a half million children living in
poverty. Why did you support those changes?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley replied, ``My job was to try to diminish the effect of
those budget cuts. We succeeded in doing that. Ultimately, I voted
for the Reagan budget,'' he said. ``But it was an act of
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then asked his rival why he had voted against the welfare
overhaul, which Gore said ``moved 7 million people from welfare to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley fired back by asking ``why you think it's working so
well when because of welfare reform there are one million children
in this country who don't have health insurance.'' He said the
October 1996 vote to pass the bill ``was a gamble with kids for
re-election.'' He said ``I was not willing to take that gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   As they have throughout the campaign, they quarreled about each
other's health care proposals. Gore said his plan would ``get to
universal health care for all Americans in a step-by-step way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley replied, ``You've said again tonight you're for
universal health care. The problem is you don't get anywhere close
to getting there. You nibble around the edges and indeed you have
nothing in your budget for the next ten years to get the universal
health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore attacked the Bradley plan, as he often has before,
contending that it provided too little money to buy the insurance
plans it was supposed to furnish. ``People here in New Hampshire
would really be left out in the cold,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the policy arguments were sedate in comparison with the
personal exchanges, with Bradley comparing Gore to Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Gore accused him of negative campaigning and said, ``If you're
going to talk about a higher standard, live by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said, ``When Al accuses me of negative campaigning, that
reminds me of the story about Richard Nixon. They said Richard
Nixon is the kind of politician who would chop down a tree, then
stand on the stump and give a speech about conservation. It just
won't wash.''
</P>
<P>
   The former senator then quoted a Boston Globe article saying
Gore was the favorite of Washington lobbyists. He asked, ``How can
you be fighting for the people when you're working hand in glove
with the special interests who are fighting against the people?''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president replied, ``If that's not negative, I don't
know what it is. You know, I have never been afraid to stand up to
the special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have fought for working people against every lobby that
exists in Washington for 23 years now,'' Gore added. ``I have
fought for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley answered that all Gore offered was ``politics as
usual.'' He said, ``And that's a thousand promises and a thousand
attacks. Promised to every little special interest group, attack,
attack, attack every day. That's been the nature of it. And quite
frankly, I think the people are fed up with it, but from your
standpoint, nothing is changed, the lobbyists are still in charge
in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
