<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HSIEH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HSIEH PING-YING, 93, A CHINESE FEMINIST AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By ERIC PACE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hsieh Ping-ying, a Chinese feminist author known for her
autobiographical work, died on Jan. 5 in San Francisco. She was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Hsieh moved to San Francisco in the mid-1970s from Taiwan,
to which she had fled from mainland China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Hsieh ``pioneered the literary construction of a soldier
image for women _ as imaginative as it may have been _ and thereby
influenced this kind of literature in China for decades,'' said
Charles A. Laughlin, professor of modern Chinese literature at Yale
University.
</P>
<P>
   Her first book was ``War Diary,'' published in 1928 in Shanghai.
Laughlin recalled that, in writing the book, Miss Hsieh accompanied
soldiers of the Chinese Nationalist army in 1926 and 1927, when it
was trying to bring warlords in the eastern half of China under
control and while she was a ``girl soldier'' with propaganda
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when Chinese women were trying to find new modes of
identity in the 20th century after having shed the shackles of
traditional Chinese feminine identity, there were many different,
alternative identities available to them,'' Laughlin said, ``and I
think she was the first to create this very military one.''
</P>
<P>
   A scholar's daughter, Miss Hsieh was born in a village in Hunan
province. Before she was 20, she enrolled in the Wuchang Central
Political and Military School. The academy trained young women to
be uniformed propagandists attached to the regular military.
</P>
<P>
   After her relatively brief military service Miss Hsieh returned
to her village and an arranged marriage. In 1940 her book ``Girl
Rebel: The Autobiography of Hsieh Pingying'' was published in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   After her marriage ended, Ms. Hsieh was charged with being a
Communist and radical and was imprisoned. After her release she
studied Chinese literature and worked as a roving writer, editor
and teacher. In 1937, when Japan invaded China, she again became a
``girl soldier,'' accompanying Chinese combat troops to the front.
Diary entries about her experiences appeared in newspapers and in
another book. After World War II she escaped to Taiwan, where she
taught and wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Her second husband, Earl Chia, died in 1988. The couple became
American citizens after moving to San Francisco. She is survived by
a daughter, Lily Chia Brissman of Nacogdoches, Texas; two sons,
Luke, of Palos Verdes, Calif., and Wen, of Ambler, Pa., and four
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7791 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-GOLDBERG-SPI &LR;      01-27 2913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GOLDBERG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY CENTRAL: TRUST KEY TO AGENT-STAR BOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It makes tremendous sense, when you think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years ago, when Brian Goldberg was a student at the
University of Cincinnati, he found himself in a class with Ken
Griffey Sr., the Big Red Machine outfielder who decided to use the
off-season to take some college courses.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, now 39, sat in his office 43 floors above downtown
Cincinnati and recalled that fateful class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was `Interpersonal Relationships,''' Goldberg said,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   How perfect, when you consider the unique relationship that was
struck between the 20-something undergrad and the major league
ballplayer whose son and namesake, Ken Griffey Jr., would turn out
to be the most popular player of a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg went on to law school. Griffey Sr. left the Reds and
went on to play for the New York Yankees and Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as the unlikely pair cultivated their
friendship, Griffey Jr. grew from a 9-year-old to the biggest thing
in baseball since Babe Ruth, Mickey Mantle, Hank Aaron and Willie
Mays.
</P>
<P>
   One day along the way, after Goldberg had begun practicing law
in Cincinnati and representing a few minor league ballplayers, the
relationship between Goldberg and the Griffeys took a decidedly
interesting turn.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg had never asked Griffey Sr. for anything, not an
autograph or a free ticket to a game. It didn't take long for
Griffey Sr. to figure that this young aspiring attorney was someone
he could count on. A friend.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1987, when Ken Jr. was a senior at Moeller High
School and Senior had to report to spring training, the elder
Griffey turned to Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had me over for dinner and Senior said, `I'm getting
ready to leave. Birdie's here with the kids. The scouts are
starting to call and interview Junior. They're going to give some
aptitude tests and they're thinking about drafting him pretty high,
so we just want to be ready,' '' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to get too specific about why he didn't want
his existing agents to represent Junior, but he told me, `Kenny's
gotten to know you. I have my own reasons for not wanting to expose
him to them.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So that was him asking if I wanted to work with Junior. I
can't reiterate enough what  &UR; rr &LR; I owe their family. That's the
thing sometimes I think fans who see players from a distance really
don't see what a lot of times these people are like as people.
Kenny as a husband, father and son _ it's the real deal. He's a
real close member of his family. I give him a lot of credit because
in professional sports, there are so many factors stacked against
you to not be a good father or husband. There are so many things
that can draw you away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Ken Griffey Jr. Central.
</P>
<P>
   Though not exactly a shrine to the Mariners' All-Star center
fielder, Goldberg's office high above a presently wintry Cincinnati
does have an acutely Junior-esque motif.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the photographs of Goldberg's wife, Robin, and their
two young daughters, Emily and Lauren, that occupy prime real
estate on Goldberg's desk, Griffey is the overwhelming theme.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging on the wall between two windows is a monstrous poster of
Griffey. He is wearing a now outdated teal Mariners jersey. He is
jogging off the field, his famously impish face peering out from
under the bill of his Mariners cap. The caption reads: ``Junior.
The Finest In The Field.''
</P>
<P>
   Over in a corner, the bookshelves hold statues and figurines of
Griffey. There are also a half-dozen pair of Griffey's signature
Nike cleats.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Goldberg's desk, on a shelf, there is a thick stack of
Rawlings gloves bearing the gold imprint of Ken Griffey Jr.'s
autograph. Off to the right is a hat rack holding six caps Griffey
has worn during Mariners games, All-Star games, playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   And to the left, on another wall next to Goldberg's desk, hang
two framed baseball jerseys. One is a Reds shirt, No. 30. That's
Ken Griffey Sr. The other is No. 24 from the Mariners. That's
Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The law degree from the University of Toledo that Goldberg
earned after meeting the Griffeys is framed and hanging in the
office, too. And though the attorney handled a few cases early in
his career, almost all of what Goldberg does and has done for the
past 12 years is handle Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   All Griffey, almost all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The phone calls come in bunches. The receptionist buzzes
Goldberg's office every few minutes _ about 40 calls a day on
average. There are the Nike people, the Upper Deck folks, General
Mills, Nintendo, Nabisco, Duracell and AOL.
</P>
<P>
   There are the Make-A-Wish Foundation calls, verifying Griffey's
availability and thoughts on visits with kids. At the moment,
Griffey is working on a deal to be the national spokesman for Child
Abuse Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never envisioned it would be like this,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first sign of it was this guy in Edmonds, Mike Kramer, who
owned a company called Pacific Trading Cards. He was the guy who
had the idea for this,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Goldberg stands and fishes for something. Soon,
he is handing over two Ken Griffey Jr. candy bars. One is wrapped
in blue, the other in gold, like the old Mariners uniform colors.
</P>
<P>
   They are history, relics, and they remind Goldberg of where this
all started.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little dusty now. I'd hate to see what it looks like
if I opened it up. But it was his (Kramer's) idea to make and sell
one million of these,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was in April of '89, after Kenny made the team. He
started off hot but tailed off a little after two or three weeks.
But Mike felt he was going to stay up all year. That was the first
time I thought, `Wow, this is something different than just a good
player or even a great player.' And they did sell their million
bars.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   How long ago do those days seem now?
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years after Ken Griffey Jr. soared into the baseball
constellation, his star and his status with the Mariners has dimmed
this winter. Or, at least, the uncertainty about where and when he
will leave the one big-league team he has ever played for has made
for serious intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   The off-season began with a fateful November meeting in Orlando,
Fla., where Griffey, his wife, Melissa, and their two children
live. In that meeting, Griffey told the Mariners he wanted to be
traded to a team closer to his home in Orlando. The Mariners
contend that Griffey did not even want to return in 2000, for what
is supposed to be the final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he (Griffey) said, `No way (I'm ever coming
back).' But at the time, he didn't think he'd be back long term,''
Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people are going to take this the wrong way. People are
going to think there's some sort of rivalry, and there's not. But
he could have gone the route of (Alex Rodriguez) and just said, `I
don't want to be traded. I just want to stay, but I'm not going to
sign an extension.' That's also a function of the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after that meeting, Mariners partner and CEO Howard
Lincoln, club president Chuck Armstrong and general manager Pat
Gillick headed back to Seattle, where they held a full-court,
spin-city news conference at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   They took the offensive, calling Griffey ``courageous'' for his
decision to want to be closer to home. They issued a ``joint
statement'' that outlined Griffey's trade request.
</P>
<P>
   All this did was set the Mariners, Griffey and Goldberg on a
course that, by now, is strained and unresolved. The Mariners are
unwavering in their resolve to stick to ``the statement,'' a tactic
that Goldberg says insults fans' intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statement. That was probably the problem. Players and star
players are getting talked about and traded all the time. Juan
Gonzalez gets traded. Other guys I'm sure are being offered where
it's not talked about,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame myself for that statement. Not because it was untrue
or insincere at the time, but because it seems to lock in something
and not take into account that, through no one's fault, situations
can change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's no statement, maybe there's a rumor about how the
Mariners are shopping Junior. But if a trade is not made, then
that's all it was was rumors and not some official word coming out.
People can speculate all they want. Maybe the team acknowledges
they talked about Junior to other teams, maybe they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, who like Griffey puts a premium on relationships and
loyalty, has a word for what has happened.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Sideways' is the way I talk about it,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my own opinions and views about why things went the way
they did. Suffice it to say, the Mariners were looking for some
finality, which after the meeting brought about the statement.
Would I have done that again? Probably not. Not because it wasn't
true or it wasn't what Ken was feeling at the time, but because it
didn't take into account that factors and situations can change,''
Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was to know that most of the teams on Kenny's list had
reasons for not being interested in the beginning and most of them
made it perfectly clear that the reason they weren't interested is
not because they weren't interested in Kenny. But what it had to do
with, they didn't think it made that much sense to trade for a guy,
give up a lot, not knowing if he was going to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why teams were saying, `Sure, we'd love to have him,
but it doesn't make sense for us to try and make a trade.' That's
when things got sideways, and it's not anybody's fault. That's
where the fans have a hard time. They expect us to be blaming the
Mariners for why this thing went sideways. Or the Mariners to be
blaming us for this thing going sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg acknowledged that Griffey's first choice was the
Atlanta Braves, whose spring training facility is near Griffey's
Orlando home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might have been the ideal situation, and I think it was,
in the beginning,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves immediately responded by saying the asking price
was too much for Griffey, and they would not enter discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Griffey had apparently clocked the distance between his
home and the Houston Astros spring training facility, believing
that a trade to the Astros would mean he could ride his bike to
work during the Grapefruit League. But the Astros would make no
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the New York Mets were contacted but told the Mariners
they were more interested in Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the Reds and Mariners got into a squabble when
Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden shut down negotiations
because the Mariners insisted on too much, including second baseman
Pokey Reese.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the deal-making dragged on, and the more Gillick
floated proposals from teams other than the four on Griffey's list,
Goldberg and Griffey finally said they were done.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said Griffey believed the Mariners were not operating
in good faith by talking to other teams. Then, a deal with the Mets
was refused by Griffey, who was called at 11 p.m. one night with a
request from the Mariners to get back to them in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there could be only a trade to the Reds or a return
to Seattle for the 2000 season _ these are the only two options
Griffey still held open to the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Mariners are worried about another ``Randy Johnson''
situation, Goldberg dismisses any concern about Griffey being
distracted or sub-par next season in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken not being happy doesn't mean you don't play through it.
They talk about him being a lame duck, but they don't get specific.
. . . This guy's got a lot of pride in how he plays the game and
how he conducts his life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said Griffey's feelings about Safeco Field have been
somewhat misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people don't understand is that he didn't say anything
positive about the field because people might assume he's going to
stay. If he said anything negative, people would assume he was
going to leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then Goldberg clarified that it is ``not the dimensions''
that are an issue, but the ``elements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take Coors Field and push the fences back 10 feet, the
ball is still going to fly out of there. At Safeco, you could push
the fences 10 feet in and the ball still isn't going to carry.''
</P>
<P>
   And though neither side will discuss it, there is some truth to
the idea that as the player with the most clout, Griffey is more
likely than any other Mariner to initiate a request to close the
roof in order to enhance the ball's flight. Griffey may be saying
what several other Mariners hitters are also expressing.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wider view of where things stand between the Mariners
and Griffey, Goldberg contends that Griffey is merely playing by
the rules set by Major League Baseball. As a 10-year veteran with
more than five years of service with the Mariners, he controls his
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so quick to find somebody to blame when things
don't go 100 percent correct. You have to step back and say what's
going on here is not anybody's fault. It's a function of the rules
and the way the rules are set,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should Ken Jr. stay and play out and fulfill his contract,
which looks like the most likely scenario, the Mariners end up
drawing the short straw. But they're not getting screwed by
anybody. It's a function of the rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not forget that Kenny spurned free agency twice.
I don't think there's anything wrong with Alex (who says he wants
to stay in 2000 and will keep an open mind about a long-term deal,)
doing once what Kenny's already done twice, which is sign an
extension,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, Alex would get the benefit of something we never did the
first two times Kenny re-signed, and that is ripping up the last
year of the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Winter is in full swing in the Ohio Valley. From 43 floors up,
Cincinnati is dusted white against a heavy, gray sky.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out the windows of Goldberg's office, one can see how
the night's cover of snow has softened the concrete shell of the
new Bengals football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slated to open in time for the preseason,'' said
Goldberg, tapping the window pane.
</P>
<P>
   Like any good American city, this is a sports town. The city's
skyline and its heart are defined in large part by the teams, the
games and the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``And right over there is Cinergy Field, home of the Reds,'' he
said, pointing through the glass and across the Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball lore, Cinergy Field will always be Riverfront
Stadium, because that's where the Big Red Machine churned out all
those National League pennants.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Pete Rose gave up the body; where Tony Perez earned
his place in Cooperstown; where Lou Piniella and the Nasty Boys
brought home another World Series despite the headache of working
for a dog-lover named Marge Schott.
</P>
<P>
   It is this history of good times that makes Cincinnati baseball
fans tingle with the idea that Ken Griffey Jr. might come play
here, too.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg shakes his head and smiles. Talk has been rampant about
Junior's homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   Though some sports radio jocks in Seattle have chirped about
conspiracy theories and how Goldberg must be plotting with the
Reds, the truth is Goldberg is closer to the Mariners front office
than the Reds'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been a Reds fan since I was 10 years old,'' Goldberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   And, in reality, it is tough to pin down whether Goldberg really
believes Griffey will be best suited for a stint in Cincinnati.
Griffey has always talked about playing for the Reds, where his
father is the bench coach and next in line (it is presumed) to be
the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Griffey's grandmother lives there, and Goldberg says
Griffey talks about wanting to play in a place she can come watch.
</P>
<P>
   But as for the urgency of a deal? The Reds refuse to part with
much in order to obtain Griffey for the 2000 season. And the fans
understand the big picture requires more logic and planning than
simply gutting a good, young team _ even for Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, they're excited about the possibility of Kenny
coming here. But, at the same time, they're realistic. Baseball
fans here are conservative. It's taken them a long time to come
back to the game after the '94 strike,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Kenny, they know it doesn't make a lot of sense to
give up all the young players who won so many games for the Reds
last season to get Kenny,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, for now, Goldberg maintains Griffey seems headed
back to Seattle, where baseball will be just baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice idea, especially for Griffey _ the kid who made a
name for himself chasing down fly balls no one else could dream of
catching, swinging that sweet swing, wearing that ballcap backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the season starts, no one can mess with him. He'll be
fine,'' Goldberg said about his friend and client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he's between those white lines, he's in his glory.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
