<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S BALLOT MACHINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 27:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain's uphill quest to run on ballots throughout New
York state in the March 7 Republican presidential primary received
a boost Wednesday from helpful Democrats. With encouragement from
their party's legislative leaders, the two Democrats on the
four-member state Board of Elections refused to supply the votes
needed to invalidate McCain's delegate petitions in eight upstate
districts.
</P>
<P>
   The move _ a rare instance of the state's partisan election
machinery working in favor of democracy _ thwarted, at least for
the moment, the state Republican Party's effort to keep McCain off
the presidential primary ballot in much of upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   This development was all the more heartening because it came
just one day after McCain's campaign suffered a reversal. On
Tuesday, New York City's Board of Elections, in response to a
challenge from the state Republican Party, knocked McCain off the
ballot in Brooklyn's 12th Congressional District because of a truly
trivial mistake. A worker gathering names for a McCain petition
inadvertently wrote down the wrong house numbers in listing the
addresses of two signers. Invalidating those signatures left McCain
one signature shy of the minimum number the rules require.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust settles, McCain could end up being knocked off the
ballot in about half of New York's 31 districts. But he is not the
only would-be president whose place on the ballot is at risk.
Petition challenges brought by Texas Gov. George W. Bush's camp
have succeeded in removing Steve Forbes from the ballot in several
Long Island districts for minor errors. The fact that Forbes could
throw $1 million into a petition drive and still be so vulnerable
speaks volumes about New York's ridiculous ballot requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The state party's drive to purge the ballot is not only an
embarrassment to New York but to both Gov. George Pataki, Bush's
patron, and Bush himself. These are two politicians with national
ambitions who are engaged in a systematic effort to deny the voters
a choice. It is a scheme that both should be ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, meanwhile, is mounting court challenges in some
districts against Bush's petitions. These challenges do not help
the voters any more than the Bush challenges do. The only good
thing that can be said about these ballot machinations is that they
have strengthened the case for federal court intervention to
establish once and for all free elections in New York state. The
issue is due to be joined Friday in the Manhattan courtroom of U.S.
District Court Judge Edward Korman. Korman is familiar with New
York's ballot regime, having written the decision four years ago
that opened the state's presidential primary to some of Bob Dole's
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In response to that ruling, the state Legislature and the
Republican Party tinkered a bit with the petition requirements. But
the current outbreak of ballot warfare vividly demonstrates that
the ``undue burden'' on voting and democracy that led to Korman's
1996 ballot ruling still persists. The situation calls for an even
stronger decision this time _ one that mandates a full statewide
ballot March 7, and then requires the Legislature to do a wholesale
rewrite of the ballot rules to comport with common sense and the
Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-COURTS-CAMERA     01-27 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-COURTS-CAMERAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMERAS IN COURTROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 27:
</P>
<P>
   Justice Joseph Teresi of New York State Supreme Court has struck
an important blow for constitutional rights and an open judicial
process by allowing cameras to televise the murder trial of the
four New York City police officers who shot Amadou Diallo. Justice
Teresi, who sits in Albany, ruled that the New York state law
imposing an absolute ban on television cameras in courtrooms was
unconstitutional. The public and press have a constitutionally
protected right to view criminal trials, and the use of television
cameras is a natural and reasonable extension of that right. The
justice found that given the great interest in this case, and the
limited seating available, the right of the public and press to
observe the trial would be curtailed if not denied without
television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The officers are accused of second-degree murder in the killing
of Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant who was shot in a hail
of police bullets in the doorway of his apartment house in the
Bronx. An appeals court moved the trial to Albany on the grounds
that an unbiased jury could not be found in the Bronx. However, the
move will make it extremely difficult for interested members of the
Bronx community to attend the trial and has heightened suspicions
in minority communities about the integrity of the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   New York is one of only three states that do not allow some form
of audio-visual coverage of court proceedings. Some lawmakers worry
that cameras might compromise the rights of the litigants. But a
10-year experiment with courtroom cameras showed that televised
access enhanced public understanding of the judicial system without
harming the legal process. New York's backwardness on this issue
hurts public confidence in the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Legislature acts to allow cameras back into courts,
judges in New York should follow Teresi's cogent constitutional
analysis and allow the public _ not just those able to get in the
courthouse door _ to see and hear what happens in the courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NEV-HOTEL-NYT &LR;      01-27 0258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NEV-HOTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FATE OF RENO'S MAPES HOTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Jan. 27:
</P>
<P>
   When it opened in December 1947, the Mapes Hotel in Reno was the
embodiment of a Nevadan idea of luxury _ a place to eat, dance,
drink, sleep and gamble, all within a 12-story Art Deco building.
There was a Sky Room on the 11th floor, a Turkish bath in the
basement, and all the amenities in between. In 1982 the hotel
closed, and 16 years later it was placed on the National Trust for
Historic Preservation's list of the 11 most endangered historic
buildings. But now, if the City of Reno has its way, the Mapes
Hotel will be imploded at 8 a.m. on Jan. 30, Super Bowl Sunday,
while Reno residents and film crews watch.
</P>
<P>
   Behind this turn of events lies a complicated story. Reno is
renovating its riverfront district, an area anchored by the hotel,
which overlooks the Truckee River. In 1996 the city purchased the
hotel for $4 million and began the search for a plan to redevelop
it. Several financially sound proposals, including one _favored by
the Historic Trust _ to convert the Mapes into upscale senior
apartments, were presented to the city's Redevelopment Agency Board
but were ultimately turned down.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of this building will mean a significant loss of
architectural and community heritage in a city undergoing swift
transformation, a transformation that should make a national
landmark like the Mapes all the more valuable.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-LEONSMITH-HNS &LR;      01-27 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEONSMITH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
While Dallas Mavericks rookie Leon Smith was with his team,
representatives of the National Basketball Players Association were
concerned the franchise did not surround the troubled teen-ager
with people who could provide proper guidance.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the union has paired Smith, 19, with a man who spent time in
prison for forgery and has convictions for theft and solicitation
of prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Delton Carter, known as D.C., is an employee at Westside Tennis
Club, where the Rockets practice. It is at the Rockets' practice
facility that Carter met Smith, who was in the care of players
union president Billy Hunter and Purvis Short, the NBPA's director
of player programs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Carter was sentenced to five years for four counts of
felony forgery but served less than six months before being
paroled. He was also convicted of misdemeanor theft in 1994 and
convicted of solicitation of prostitution, a Class B misdemeanor,
in 1997 and was sentenced to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was unavailable for comment Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has been supervising Smith's afternoon workouts in
Short's absence and escorting the 6-11 center to Rockets games,
where they have been guests of Linda and Jim McIngvale, who own
Westside Tennis Club and Gallery Furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Short said it was he who approached Carter about working with
Smith, and admits he did not run a background check on Carter and
was unaware of his history.
</P>
<P>
   But sources questioned the wisdom of pairing Smith, who has a
Feb. 3 court date in Chicago to face misdemeanor charges of
aggravated assault, damage to property and violation of a
protection order, with Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we run a background check? No,'' Short said Wednesday.
``Should we have done that? In retrospect, I guess I would have to
say yes. But in my opinion, and I am not speaking for the (players)
association, whatever he (Carter) has done, he has paid his debt to
society. Everybody has problems in their past. He's atoned for
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my recommendation (that Carter work with Smith). A lot
of it was because he worked for Mac (Jim McIngvale) and Linda. I
felt there was no need for a background check.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a Chicago high schooler who was attempting to jump to the
NBA, was suspended without pay by the Mavericks on Dec. 6 after a
series of incidents that included two arrests within a 24-hour
span. Smith then attempted suicide, swallowing 250 aspirin Nov. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Smith spent the next month in a Dallas psychiatric facility
before coming to Houston, where he has been supervised by Short,
for workouts in anticipation of a release by the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The McIngvales said they felt responsible for the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad because they (the union) didn't do a background
check because D.C. had worked for us,'' Linda McIngvale said
Wednesday. ``They would have done the check, but since he worked
for us, they didn't feel it was necessary. Everyone wants what's
best for Leon, so I'm very concerned about the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it ended today. D.C. will not be allowed to work with Leon
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, Short said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to abandon D.C. because of what he did in the
past,'' he said. ``I'm not going to jump ship. I've dealt with
people who have done far worse than this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in life the best teacher is experience, so I don't
look at this as so much of a negative but a positive. I know that
Leon has benefited from his association with D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to look upon him (Carter) any differently. We've
all made mistakes. Everyone's worried about who we have with Leon.
Well, where were all these people when this kid was in his darkest
hour? I'll stand by my decision. I can live with the criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
