<SLUG> BC-FBN-CAMPO-PROFILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER MANY YEARS, CAMPO GETS HIS SHOT AS COWBOYS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Contrary to popular thinking, Dallas Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones didn't stumble upon the idea that Dave Campo had the
stuff of a head coach because of a diminished pool of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Jones considered Campo for the job when he hired former Steelers
offensive coordinator Chan Gailey two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, wanting to bring in someone new following a 6-10 season
in 1997, said it wasn't the right time for Campo. But he always
believed that ``Campo's time will come.''
</P>
<P>
   The right time for Campo, 52, came Wednesday when Jones
introduced him as Gailey's successor and the fifth coach in Cowboys
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most exciting moment in my life,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, who has been with the Cowboys since 1989, including the
past five as defensive coordinator, has been the front-runner for
the position since Gailey was fired Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he made the decision to go with Campo partly because
of his stellar coaching credentials _ the Cowboys defense has
ranked among the league's top 10 units four times under Campo's
guidance, including a ninth-place finish in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And partly because Campo represents stability and continuity,
while also bringing back a taste of the glory days as a staff
member during the team's Super Bowl title runs in 1992, 1993 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
   While Campo offers familiarity, it's also safe to say that his
Cowboys predecessors _ Tom Landry (stoic), Jimmy Johnson (fiery,
controlling), Barry Switzer (laid back) and Gailey (unemotional)
were nothing like Campo, who is equal parts intense, emotional and
a free-spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams coach Joe Avezzano might be more the famous of the
singing Cowboys coaches. And Carolina coach George Seifert and
former Jets coach Bill Parcells might be the first coaches to sing
on national television.
</P>
<P>
   But Campo, who cut a record during his high school years in
Connecticut and considered becoming a professional singer before
deciding to play college football at Central Connecticut State,
already holds a tune better than any coach in the league.
</P>
<P>
   However, though Campo said Wednesday that one of his major goals
as head coach is to be a good motivator, don't expect him to break
out in song at a team meeting for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact Campo, who has been known to ``crank it up a bit'' at a
karaoke bar during training camp at Wichita Falls, intimated during
the season that if he became a head coach he would leave his
part-time crooning behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to present an image,'' Campo said. ``I think there is a
fine line between being able to get up in front of a team and get
respect. You have to be careful not to be to much one way or
another. No one will have to question whether he's a singer or
entertainer or a football coach. I'm a football coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo has proved that consistently during a nomadic 32-year
coaching career that included 13 stops, including such football
locales like his alma mater Central Connecticut, Albany State and
Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   An underdog as a player, the 5-foot-7 Campo's modest coaching
resume and slight stature caused people to underrate his coaching
abilities at times.
</P>
<P>
   Campo overcame the misperception and the bad rap because of an
intense work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Campo's size has never been an issue in the Cowboys
locker room. More importantly, his production has been large.
</P>
<P>
   Campo's defenses, which had to overcome the obstacles of mass
free-agent upheavals and Jones' penchant to spend more money on
offensive players, routinely took on the personality of their
feisty leader, as they were always better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   This past season was a prime example, as the Cowboys defense
opened training camp considered to be team's weak link and finished
the season as the team's strength _ all while negotiating a rash of
injuries that sidelined starting cornerbacks Deion Sanders and
Kevin Smith for several games and defensive end Greg Ellis for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also had to overcome an eight-game suspension for
defensive tackle Leon Lett.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that Campo has earned the respect of the
defenders who know him best.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Chad Henning said believes the emotional Campo
will be able to light a fire under the entire team the way he has
done with the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't hide his emotions, which makes it great for
players,'' Hennings said.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Darren Woodson, who came into the league when Campo was
the Cowboys' secondary coach, said his ascension to head-coach is
long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have got the job two years ago,'' Woodson said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's Campo's time now.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's worth singing about. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
