<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COORDINATORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REILLY SAID TO BE HIRED AS COWBOYS OFFENSIVE COORDINATOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Reilly will be hired as the Cowboys' offensive coordinator,
possibly as early as Thursday a source said, which will put Troy
Aikman back into an offense that was used by the Cowboys to win
three Super Bowls during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, 54, was the Cowboys' quarterbacks coach for one season
(1997) before serving the past two seasons in a similar capacity in
New England.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is that Reilly will be hired as Dave Campo's
offensive coordinator and that Ernie Zampese, a Jerry Jones
confidant, will be brought aboard in some kind of advisory
capacity. Jones picked Zampese's brain for free on several
occasions at last week's Senior Bowl practices in Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese, 63, earned Aikman's trust as the Cowboys' offensive
coordinator for four seasons (1994-97) before being fired by Jones
in the head-coaching switch from Barry Switzer to Chan Gailey after
the '97 season. Zampese spent the past two seasons as the Patriots'
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Reilly nor Zampese is expected to be back in New
England. Since Pete Carroll was fired as head coach, Reilly and
Zampese have prepared themselves to be canned as soon as a
successor is named.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation around Valley Ranch is that backup quarterback Jason
Garrett, if he chooses to retire, will be the Cowboys' quarterbacks
coach, a situation reminiscent of Denver, where then-Broncos'
backup quarterback Gary Kubiak became John Elway's position coach
and later offensive coordinator. Garrett turns 34 in March.
</P>
<P>
   The future is unclear for Cowboys quarterbacks coach Buddy Geis,
who was hired along with wide receivers coach Dwaine Painter and
tight ends coach Les Miles by Gailey before the 1998 season. Gailey
was fired Jan. 11. Geis and Miles are under contract for next
season. Painter is not.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is that with Campo being promoted, secondary coach
Mike Zimmer will become the new defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   If Zimmer, 43, succeeds Campo, then former Cowboys special-teams
star and now special teams/defensive assistant Bill Bates would be
a candidate to replace Zimmer as secondary coach.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Avezzano, special teams coach since 1990, was disappointed
that he lost to Campo for the head-coaching job, but took the high
road when Jones' announcement came down Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave Campo and I go back 25 years. I know him well,'' Avezzano
said. ``And I'm looking for us to win a bunch of football games
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Avezzano, Hudson Houck and Clarence Shelmon _ special teams,
offensive line and running backs coaches, respectively _ are
believed to be safe in their present roles.
</P>
<P>
   The focus now is on the offense. What will the Cowboys run? Who
will run it?
</P>
<P>
   In New England, Zampese and Reilly were criticized for nearly
getting quarterback Drew Bledsoe killed in the second half of last
season. In the final eight games (2-6, including a victory against
the Cowboys), the Patriots scored nine offensive touchdowns, while
Bledsoe threw six TD passes, 17 interceptions and was sacked 33
times. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
