<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7816 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-     01-27 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPO STEPS UP, WITH AGGRESSIVE ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys promoted longtime assistant Dave Campo from
defensive coordinator to head coach Wednesday and will hire former
Cowboys quarterbacks coach Jack Reilly as their offensive
coordinator, possibly as early as Thursday, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   By staying inside the organization with Campo, Jones is banking
on the path of least resistance to jump-start his Cowboys down the
road to another Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar face ... fewer delays.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Campo became Jones' choice to replace Chan Gailey, who was
fired Jan. 11 after two seasons as head coach and offensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reduces the transition,'' Jones said during a news
conference at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the head-coaching search lasted 15 days, less than half
the time Jones took to hire Gailey to replace Barry Switzer. This
time, Jones didn't interview a candidate outside the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave will be overseer and ultimate decision maker,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones learned two years ago in interviewing defensive-minded
George Seifert, now head coach at Carolina, that a football man can
gain knowledge about offense from spending years devising schemes
to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is banking on Campo becoming a 2000 version of Seifert.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, 52, apparently is on the same page as Jones on offensive
philosophy. Sources say the next offensive coordinator will be
Reilly, who was at Valley Ranch on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (separate head coach and offensive coordinator) is a
departure,'' Jones said. ``We don't want to be in the same
offensive system we were the last two years'' when the Cowboys
offensively ranked eighth and 16th in the NFL in 1998 and 1999,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, the New England Patriots' quarterbacks coach, is an
Ernie Zampese disciple. He works with the offense Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman is most comfortable running, the offense
the Cowboys used in winning three Super Bowls in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to run on throwing downs and throw on running downs,''
said Campo, who wouldn't tip his hand about Reilly. ``I want us to
attack and be aggressive. My No. 1 objective is to develop an
attitude on this team.'' Jones is hands-on, but he also wants a
coach who will show discipline with his players. Campo has that
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys led the NFL in penalties and penalty yardage this
season. They were 1-8 on the road, including a first-round playoff
loss at Minnesota. The Cowboys, 8-9, blew fourth-quarter leads in
six of their nine losses.
</P>
<P>
   Jones wants these negative trends quickly reversed, adding that
there is ``a sense of urgency'' with every NFL team today and his
Cowboys in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is ``uniquely qualified to coach the Dallas Cowboys'' _
Jones' words _ which means that after 11 seasons with the team,
Campo can't possibly be surprised by anything that occurs inside an
organization in which Jones is hands-on owner and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make a decision like this, you receive a great deal
of input,'' said Jones, who used the past two weeks to interview
countless coaches, scouts and front-office types around the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of input that I received had a very
common thread, and the theme was very simple: `You have a man on
your staff who is very smart, extremely talented and ready to be a
head coach in the NFL.' And that was from third parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones passed over special-teams coach Joe Avezzano, who also
wanted the promotion, to go with Campo, who came into the league
the same year (1989) as Troy Aikman, Jimmy Johnson and Jones.
Avezzano arrived one year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weighing all the information, it resulted in my not
interviewing anyone outside our organization, either the NFL or the
college level,'' said Jones, who decided more than a week ago to
stay in-house. ``There became a point where there was no doubt in
my mind that the best man to be the head coach of the Dallas
Cowboys was right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo has the two most-important qualities Jones wanted from
becomes his fourth head coach in 12 seasons: passion and
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Campo also brings loyalty, familiarity and ``big-picture''
awareness to the table. Jones took into account times during staff
meetings when Campo put the success of the team overall ahead of
the needs at his specific areas of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Campo becomes one of only 10 NFL head coaches who
have been a part of a winning Super Bowl staff, and one of only
four NFL head coaches who have been a part of three winning Super
Bowl staffs.
</P>
<P>
   What sold Jones on Campo was his ability to adjust, both in the
course of a game and from week to week during the season.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen Campo get down. He also has seen Campo attack a
problem and enthusiastically come up with a positive resolution for
it the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Campo's strengths are needed immediately. There are no shortages
of problems to solve around Valley Ranch. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
