r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PLAYERREA     01-27 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PLAYER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' PLAYERS GET COACH THEY WANTED
</HEADLINE>
 REACTION-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys haven't had much to cheer about since their
season ended Jan. 9. But Cowboys players applauded Jerry Jones'
hiring of defensive coordinator Dave Campo as head coach Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a long wait,'' Cowboys safety Darren Woodson
said. ``He should have been a head coach three years ago, if not
here then somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for him. I know he's an aggressive
guy. He's a very intense person. He really gets after the players.
He will gain the respect of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys ended an 8-9 season with a 27-10 loss to the
Minnesota Vikings in an NFC wild-card playoff game. Two days later,
Chan Gailey, who was 18-16 in two seasons, was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had guys going on different levels,'' Cowboys defensive
lineman Greg Ellis said. ``We didn't do enough, and we didn't jell
enough. Last year, we had a good football team, but we didn't get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's offensive philosophy never blended with the team's
personnel. This season, the Cowboys finished 16th in the NFL in
total offense, including 24th in passing, and they were 11th in
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Thursday, the Cowboys will announce New England
Patriots quarterbacks coach Jack Reilly as their offensive
coordinator, sources said. Reilly is an advocate of the offense Don
Coryell developed and used as coach of the San Diego Chargers in
the 1980s, an offense the St. Louis Rams used to lead the league in
yards gained and points scored this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams who have success score points,'' Cowboys quarterback
Troy Aikman said. ``They throw the football, and we haven't had
success at that the last few years. The objective is to score
points. The emphasis the last few years has been the running game,
and we have to be effective in the passing game. You have to be
able to make big plays to score points and that was something that
was lacking last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably a couple of players away from being a dominant
offensive football team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was what Campo did with the defense that won him the job.
</P>
<P>
   Despite big losses to free agency, Campo's defense was among the
top-rated in the league in his five seasons as defensive
coordinator. Last season the Cowboys ranked ninth in total offense
and fifth in points allowed.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Jones began his coaching search, the Cowboys
defenders were on the campaign trail. They got their man elected
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about coach Campo is he'll tell you like it is,''
Cowboys defensive lineman Ebenezer Ekuban said. ``He'll either say,
`Fellas, you're not doing well,' or `Fellas, you're doing good.' He
doesn't beat around the bush.''
nn
</P>
