<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICSMAGIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC BEAT CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ The coach looked like a ghost, and it wasn't from
watching his team try to play defense. Rick Pitino was under the
weather from the flu Wednesday night. His team played in his
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino managed to stick it out for the full 48, which could not
have been good for what was left of his state of mind. In between
sips of a hot beverage and holding his face in his hands, he
managed to witness his team complete a back-to-back Florida Flop by
getting pounded, 111-89, by the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Coming 24 hours after a 115-89 bludgeoning by the Heat, you
could make a case that this brief swing through the so-called
Sunshine State was a waste of time. It was. The weather was cold,
so cold that Wednesday night the radio heads were reminding people
to bring in their plants and pets for the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic, on the other hand, were quite warm, shooting 60
percent as the Celtics once again unveiled their Camembert Defense.
Orlando made 13 of 17 shots in a game-turning, third-quarter blitz,
which turned a tie game into an 18-point Orlando lead. The Celtics,
playing again without Paul Pierce, who hopes to be back Friday,
never made a serious run in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Associate head coach Jim O'Brien got to face the music after the
game due to Pitino's condition. He cut right to the chase: ``Bottom
line, you need to play better defense on the road and we didn't do
it,'' he said. ``You play tough defense on the road, you have a
chance. You give up 60 percent (shooting), you have absolutely no
chance. None.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have lost three straight games, all on the road,
and, in each case, the opponent has shot 52 percent or better. The
Heat shot 55 percent on Tuesday night, the Hornets shot 52 on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And since the midway point of the first quarter in Charlotte, or
a span of 138 minutes, the Celtics have led exactly once _ for a
stretch of 33.4 seconds Wednesday night near the end of the second
quarter. Yes, they actually were in this thing for a half. Antoine
Walker had 19 of his 26 points in the first half, looking dazzling
at times.
</P>
<P>
   But the Magic quickly tied it up before the half (a Darrell
Armstrong steal and dunk) and then blew the game open in the third,
outscoring Boston, 35-17. The immortal John Amaechi (16 points)
started a quick run that blew the lead out to 10.
</P>
<P>
   At 61-51, the ultra-energized Bo Outlaw accounted for 8 points
in an 11-0, turn-out-the-lights run that expanded the margin to a
hefty 21. Outlaw started with a 3-point play over the overmatched
Adrian Griffin, who returned to the lineup only because Pitino felt
the club had no chance to win without him.
</P>
<P>
   Outlaw added a free throw, Tariq Abdul-Wahad added a 3-point
play, and then Outlaw closed the run with two layups off two Boston
turnovers. (Orlando had 25 points off 17 Boston giveaways.) In both
cases, Walker, was slow getting back on defense, allowing the
opening for Outlaw to pounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just mentally broke down in the second half,'' said a
chagrined Kenny Anderson, who may be starting to feel the effects
of his hamstring injury. He was 1 for 9 against Miami. He was 3 for
8 in just 23 minutes Wednesday night. Asked about his injury, he
said, ``Nothing new. Same old, same old.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had no inside threat and resorted to the 3-pointer,
hoisting 24, to match their season high. Walter McCarty made 1 of
7. Walker made 2 of 6. It's hard to make a run taking threes,
especially when you do nothing at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando run pushed the lead to 81-63 after three quarters
and coach Doc Rivers kept running in fresh bodies as if he had a
Strat-O-Matic lineup. Maybe he does. Everyone plays here. The
patterns and minutes may vary, but everyone plays. No Orlando
player went more than 31 minutes Wednesday night. Only one player
(Armstrong) averages more than 28 minutes a game. Only two
(Armstrong and Abdul-Wahad) have played as many as 40 minutes in a
game this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics tried to make things interesting in the fourth. They
got to within 14 on two occasions, but the game then turned into a
foulathon. The teams attempted 47 free throws in the quarter, which
took 36 minutes to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
