<HEADLINE>
RAMS' TUCKER FINALLY HAS A SHOT AT WINNING A TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At first glance, you would think that being on a
championship team was old hat for St. Louis offensive lineman Ryan
Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the four-year stint at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was brought up in the football-crazed environment of
Midland Lee High School, the current king of football in Texas,
considering its back-to-back state titles in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, he has to know what being a winner feels like, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, during Tucker's day, times were a little different.
Football in the state was dominated by a school less than 30 miles
away from Midland. It still pains Tucker to talk about bitter rival
Odessa Permian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Odessa Permian was running things then,'' Tucker said. ``We
had a good team. We went to quarterfinals but ran back into
Permian. They went on to win state. They just kept beating us.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of Midland Lee's recent dominance of Permian and
everybody else hasn't been lost on Tucker, who said he has kept up
with everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great coach now and a couple of back-to-back
titles,'' Tucker said. ``I've talked to them. They are doing a
great job.''
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say that the folks back in Midland are keeping up
with Tucker, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the NFL and ultimately in the Super Bowl has long
been a dream of Tucker's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kid dreams about this,'' he said. ``First you want to
play in the league. Once you get here, you want to play in the
Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   He just didn't know what position he would play.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was recruited to TCU after a standout high school career
as a tight end.He knew those days wouldn't last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I didn't have the speed to be a big-time tight
end,'' Tucker said. ``I was a guy that could catch the ball. As far
as after the catch, I wasn't known for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was moved to the interior offensive line his sophomore
year at TCU and became a standout center as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   He was drafted by the Rams in the fourth round of the 1997
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Tucker, a reserve lineman, has had his biggest
impact on the Rams' improbable run to the Super Bowl at his old
position.
</P>
<P>
   Used as a jumbo tight end on goal-line situations, Tucker has
caught two touchdown passes _ one in the regular season against
Detroit and one in the playoffs against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``They usually play backup linemen as tight ends in
short-yardage situations,'' Tucker said. ``They put me out there.
And they said they were thinking about throwing me a couple of
balls and wanted me to run a route. I said `Hey, I can catch the
ball. I used to play tight end.' And they put in the game plan.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
