<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER COOLS OFF HOTTEST TEAM IN FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a seven-game winning streak, the Tennessee Titans
are the hottest team in football. But that will do little to warm
them during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a wind chill in the teens, the Titans are practicing
outdoors at Georgia Tech University this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be outside,'' Titans quarterback Steve McNair
said. ``But it's something we're just going to have to deal with. I
think that regardless of whether we're outside or inside, we still
have to go out there and stay focused on what's at hand here.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Fisher said the Titans could move their practices
inside the Georgia Dome late this week if the predicted snowfall
hits tomorrow. But for now, Tennessee will brave the cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just as soon stay out,'' Fisher said. ``Our guys are
used to situations like this. They'll go out and practice and
prepare.'' SCOUTING REPORT
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things the Titans' defensive coaches did Monday
was to call the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. The Bucs held the Rams, the
third-highest scoring offense in NFL history, to 11 points in the
NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Tampa Bay did against St. Louis as well as anyone I've
seen in years is tackle extremely well,'' Titans defensive
coordinator Gregg Williams said. ``In the past four or five years,
I can't remember seeing a team tackle as well as they did on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to their staff, and one of the keys we came away
with was making sure to minimize the yards after the catch.'' TURF
TOE
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Titans quarterback Steve McNair needed was the
Super Bowl to be played on artificial turf. But McNair, who has
turf toe, has no choice. Sunday's game will be played inside the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were my choice, I wouldn't play on artificial turf due
to my circumstances,'' McNair said. ``But it \Rhis toe\S feels a
lot better at this time than it did last week. It's improving.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who, as a precaution, is walking around in a protective
boot, practiced Wednesday. He will start Sunday. LIONS FOREWARNED
</P>
<P>
   Titans rookie defensive end Jevon Kearse is hoping the Detroit
Lions are watching him in Super Bowl XXXIV. Kearse said of the 15
teams that passed on him, he was most upset with the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   When Detroit's turn came at No. 9, Kearse was sure he was headed
there. Instead, the Lions drafted Southern California linebacker
Chris Claiborne. Claiborne started 15 games for the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had told me, if I was available, they were going to draft
me,'' Kearse said. ``That just motivates me to show them that
Detroit missed out on something special.'' THE SPACE SHUTTLES?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the former Houston Oilers still playing for the Titans
have been discussing possible nicknames for Houston's new
franchise. Texans, Roughnecks, Roughriders and Wranglers are among
the names that have been suggested for the expansion team that
kicks off in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't come up with any good ones, but we thought it
should have something to do with space, like the Rockets, Astros
and Comets,'' free safety Marcus Robertson said. ``I would love to
go back there one day and be part of the administration or coaching
staff.'' SAME TIME, NEXT YEAR
</P>
<P>
   For defensive tackle Jason Fisk, it is here today, gone last
year. He was with the Minnesota Vikings last season when they went
15-1 in the regular season and were heavy favorites to win the
Super Bowl until losing to Atlanta in the NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   During the off-season, he signed a free-agent contract with the
Titans. A trip to the Super Bowl was an added bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite a turnaround for me,'' Fisk said. ``I thought
I'd be here last year. To be honest, I wasn't thinking the Titans
would go to the Super Bowl in my first year. I thought we'd be
good, but not this good yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
