<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-JET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP OFFICIAL COMPLAINS ABOUT FIRST LADY'S USE OF JET  
 (ATTN: N.C.)
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Republican congressman accused Hillary Rodham Clinton on
Wednesday of putting politics ahead of official U.S. business by
appropriating an Air Force jet that had been scheduled for use by a
congressional delegation to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cass Ballenger of North Carolina said that his delegation
was forced to take two six-seat Air Force jets on the trip to
Central and South America last week because a 14-seat jet that he
had reserved was taken by Mrs. Clinton's staff for a political trip
to New York City and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The expenditure of government resources is a complicated matter
for both Mrs. Clinton and her likely opponent in next year's Senate
race in New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City. Both
Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani have security and governmental staffing
needs even when they are traveling as political candidates to
campaign or raise money. Their aides have traded accusations in
recent months about the use of governmental resources for campaign
events.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the expenses must be shared by the appropriate
government agency and the candidates' campaign committees. The
expenses and reimbursements to the government by the campaigns are
supposed to be included in the semiannual expense filings required
by the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani campaign and other New York Republicans, including
the state party chairman, issued statements criticizing Mrs.
Clinton about the airplane but offered no evidence of wrongdoing.
Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, referred questions about
Ballenger's complaint to the White House, but also accused Giuliani
of using his City Hall staff members for campaign work.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House, said: ``Any
suggestion that the first lady or the White House directed that
they be bumped to a smaller plane is absolutely false, and in fact,
if we had known that Congressman Ballenger and his wife were having
trouble getting a bigger plane, perhaps we could have helped. He
should have called.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint raised by Ballenger involves Air Force jets from
the 89th Air Wing that are used for top government officials,
generals and other dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   But because the 89th Air Wing operates a large pool of aircraft,
White House officials said, it was impossible to know if the plane
Ballenger had reserved was the same one assigned to Mrs. Clinton
for her trip to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Higher level officials are typically given priority when it
comes to using the aircraft, Ballenger said. ``A senator can get a
plane immediately,'' Ballenger said. ``You have to have three
congressman before you can get a plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballenger said that in late November, he requested the 14-seat
plane for a trip that involved touring areas of Venezuela that had
been devastated by mudslides and attending meetings about antidrug
efforts in Colombia, Mexico and Guatemala. Three other legislators,
two staff members, and Ballenger's wife, who has done charity work
in Latin America, also went on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Ballenger said a member of his staff called him in North
Carolina on Jan. 13, three days before the trip was scheduled to
depart, to say, ``The bad news is Mrs. Clinton took your plane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really teed me off,'' Ballenger said. ``Why in the world
couldn't she have taken one of the little planes to New York?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
