<SLUG> BC-LAPD-CORRUPT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD CORRUPTION PROBE EXPANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(NEW VERSION CORRECTING LEAD) 
BY BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The toll from the LAPD corruption scandal mounted
Wednesday when chief Bernard C. Parks announced 99 defendants
involved in 57 cases were framed by a former Rampart Division
officer turned informant.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said investigation of the criminal misconduct of former
Los Angeles Police Department Officer Rafael Perez has reached the
point where the focus will shift to the actions of officers with
whom he worked at Rampart Division station.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said 52 of the people in the compromised cases were
interviewed, including three in prison. Their arrests and
prosecutions were found to be so tainted by fabricated evidence or
perjured testimony provided by Perez that the police chief wants
District Attorney Gil Garcetti to resolve them immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department feels the criminal cases involving these 52
defendants have been severely tainted and cannot be salvaged,''
Parks said during a press conference at Parker Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe at this time it is in the best interest of the city
to dispose of these charges against the 52 in mass, vs. a piece by
piece, small-group process that can only prolong the obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   The department is particularly eager for the release of two
people incarcerated on the basis of what police now believe is
either tainted evidence or perjured statements, Parks said. The
third person, though involved in a compromised case, was
incarcerated on an unrelated matter.
</P>
<P>
   Parks added he has requested the recall of fugitive arrest
warrants against eight criminal defendants in tainted cases.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 47 individuals identified in the clouded cases
were not interviewed: Seven are expected to be interviewed soon,
one has died, nine refused to talk, 16 have been deported, two
could not be located, and a dozen have outstanding felony arrest
warrants.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney's Office spokeswoman Victoria Pipkin said the
cases identified by the LAPD would be reviewed before a decision is
made on whether they should be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the district attorney has overturned 22 cases as part of
the corruption investigation, resulting in the release of six
people from jails and state prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will expedite our review,'' Pipkin said, but she added that
the seven full-time prosecutors working the corruption probe will
need additional information before they decide on the new cases.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Mayor Richard Riordan said that while the
number of cases was startling and disappointing, the mayor supports
the aggressive manner in which Parks identified the corruption at
the outset and has worked to root it out of the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside is that he is taking swift action to take care of a
number of cases and not have them dribble out,'' said Deputy Mayor
Noelia Rodriguez. ``The mayor supports the chief and believes he's
moving in the right direction. This shows he is on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the 57 cases linked to Perez after a two-month
debriefing of the former officer only a ``milestone'' in the
mushrooming LAPD corruption inquiry, Parks said investigators now
are poised to question officers named by Perez as possible
participants in illicit law enforcement activities. Parks would not
estimate the number of police officers who might be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this juncture, all of our investigations have been
surrounding the issues that former Officer Perez has identified as
his actions,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition of this investigation will begin as it relates
to other officers Perez has identified as being involved in other
activities. Some of these officers work throughout the city, but it
appears as though their connection is that they did once work at
Rampart.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said his announcement was in keeping with his promise to
the city, at the outset of the investigation 18 months ago, that he
would provide regular updates on the corruption probe by the
department's Rampart Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have brought this investigation to this point. I think the
public confidence is there,`` Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
