<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGE-REMEMBERED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGE BACKHAND: THE SHOT FOR THE AGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With OBIT-BUDGE, which moved in ``a'' category) 
(Eds.: Neil Amdur is sports editor of The New York Times) 
(sw) 
 By NEIL AMDUR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even before he discovered tennis and became the world's best
tennis player, Don Budge played baseball. And although he threw a
ball and wrote with his right hand, Budge batted left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Grasping the bat near the handle with his right hand, Budge
swung with an efficient motion, his wrist and arm held rigid. It
was the same swing that he would carry to the tennis court to
unleash his flawless one-handed backhand, the most defining ground
stroke ever hit by any tennis player.
</P>
<P>
   Once asked to assess the Budge Backhand, George Lott, a
serve-and-volley rival during the 1930s, said, ``When you came in
against Budge's backhand, he hit such a heavy ball, you'd swear you
were volleying a piano.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was more to Budge's game than one stroke, just as
there was more to Budge than his red hair, gentleman's demeanor and
unflappable court courage.
</P>
<P>
   Until the age of 19, Budge, who died on Wednesday at 84, used an
unconventional Western forehand grip, which gave him topspin and
power but left him vulnerable to low balls and slice, and inhibited
his volley. Taking the advice of friends, Budge switched to the
more traditional Eastern or shake-hand grip in the winter of 1935,
a move that hindered his short-term preparation but produced a more
fluent stroke that was still careful and calculated in its
execution. Two years later, he dominated the tour as no player ever
had.
</P>
<P>
   The intangibles that made Budge one of the sport's greats were
less visible to spectators. He was always physically fit, as strong
in the fifth set of a match as he was at the start. His timing was
impeccable, and he saw the ball as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to most professional advice,'' Julius Heldman wrote,
in assessing Budge's style, ``he did not `feel' the ball on his
racket for any length of time. Most players will flatten or lay
back their wrists as they hit in order to hold the ball as long as
possible. If they then mis-time the ball, they still have a very
good margin for error. There was no margin on Don's shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Budge's achievements assured him of immortality. In 1937,
he won the most significant Davis Cup match in history by rallying
from two sets down and 1-4 in the fifth set against the stylish
German Gottfried von Cramm, with the Interzone final series tied at
2-all. The match was played at a neutral site, Wimbledon, and was
the equivalent of the Joe Louis-Max Schmeling heavyweight title
fight after von Cramm received a prematch good-luck phone call from
Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances,'' recalled Ted Tinling, who was in
the office of the All England Club with von Cramm when Hitler
called, ``that match stands alone for what it represented at the
time. It was the ultimate test.''
</P>
<P>
   Half a century later, Budge speculated on what Hitler had said
to von Cramm, his friend. ``Hitler was apparently telling Cramm
that they had had enough of the Americans winning everything in the
Olympics over there,'' Steve Flink quoted Budge as saying in his
book ``The Greatest Matches of the Twentieth Century'' (Rutledge,
1999). ``They were hoping _ and Hitler was hoping _ that Cramm
would beat me and bring the Cup back to Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   By becoming the first player to win the four major singles
championships in a single calendar year in 1938 (Australian,
French, Wimbledon and United States), Budge achieved the sport's
first Grand Slam. In present usage, the words ``Grand Slam'' have
been woven into tournament terminology, as in Pete Sampras' number
of Grand Slam titles. But Sampras has yet to achieve the sweep that
Budge and Rod Laver did, and the Grand Slam stands by itself.
</P>
<P>
   Long after he had departed the amateur game for the pros and
then into retirement, Budge was a familiar sight in his blue blazer
with a regal presence that earned him the distinction as the
sport's Mr. Tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he would offer the weekend player, he said:
``Discipline is the importance of doing anything well, whether it's
tennis, basketball or whatever you are doing. But first of all, you
learn how to hit the ball correctly. If you have good strokes, then
work on your conditioning because your strokes are sound. If you
are in great shape physically, you can really write your own
ticket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
