<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-WASHBURN-H     01-27 2118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-WASHBURN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ A few minutes after the Tennessee Titans defeated
Jacksonville to reach the first Super Bowl in franchise history,
players and coaches celebrated on the makeshift stage at Alltel
Stadium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As owner Bud Adams accepted the Lamar Hunt trophy for winning
the AFC Championship Game, defensive line coach Jim Washburn stayed
about 20 yards outside the roped-off area. Washburn stood alone for
a few minutes, and when he was offered congratulations, he had
tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about my family and how much I've been
blessed,'' Washburn said Wednesday. ``I was reflecting and thinking
that it was a miracle I was there. When I thought about where I'd
been and what I'd been through, well, it's so improbable it's
unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, people treated me like the plague.''
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, Washburn couldn't even get a high school
coaching job. No one would touch him. He thought his coaching
career was over. Now, he will have a chance to win a Super Bowl
ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to be associated with me for a long time,'' he
said. ``Now, I'm so happy to be here. I did wrong, and I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn went from being out of football, an object of scorn
within the profession, to reaching the pinnacle of coaching _ the
Super Bowl. Such coaches as Dick Vermeil, Fred Akers, Danny Ford,
Frank Broyles, Kim Helton and Jeff Fisher came to his aid.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how Washburn feels to be coaching in the Super
Bowl, you have to see where he has been.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1989, Washburn was indicted on charges that in the
mid-'80s he obtained steroids for players at the University of
South Carolina, where he was the defensive line coach under Joe
Morrison. There was a huge scandal that began with a first-person
story by former Gamecocks defensive lineman Tommy Chaikin in Sports
Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   After a federal investigation, Washburn pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor count of purchasing steroids and dispensing them to
players. He and two other former South Carolina coaches _ Tom
Kurucz and Keith Kephart _ were originally sentenced to three
months in jail, to be served in a halfway house in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after a plea-bargain agreement, Washburn's sentence was
changed to three years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone who gets a federal conviction gets off
scot-free,'' assistant U.S. attorney John Barton said at the time.
``These individuals paid a substantial penalty, not in the
traditional or classic format of going to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge G. Ross Anderson eliminated the sentence
after listening to character witnesses testifying on the coaches'
behalf. Akers, the head coach at Purdue at that time, put in a good
word for Washburn, as did Cole Proctor, a Utah assistant coach in
1989 who is now a scout for the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, 1990, Washburn pleaded guilty in Anderson's court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a sacred trust, but five years ago I violated that,''
Washburn told the judge. ``I'm very sorry. I've done all I can do
to rectify that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a table in the Titans interview room Wednesday,
Washburn's eyes turned red as he recounted his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I messed up,'' he said. ``I did something wrong. I didn't mean
to. I was trying to keep a kid from getting steroids off the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so grateful to be where I am today. I didn't think I'd
ever get another coaching job for a long time, and here I am in the
Super Bowl. I'm a real insignificant part of this team, but I'm
awfully proud to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played our first preseason game in Kansas City, I
stood out there and about burst into tears. I looked at that sign
on the goal post. It said, `Feel the power.' I don't feel the power
of the NFL. I feel the power of the Lord, who put me in this
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   His players don't care about his past. It's obvious from their
performance this season that they respect Washburn, who has done a
good job of developing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the leader of the army, the leader of the dog men,'' said
Titans defensive tackle Josh Evans, who is having his best season.
``I think he's the spice in the gumbo, the ingredient we needed. He
came in here and really believed in us from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks to us about what happened to him. He tells us to not
make the mistakes he made, to take care of ourselves and our
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn lost everything but his family. He lost his house and
went broke in the process. When he couldn't get a coaching job, he
mowed the grass at a golf course and drove a truck for a feed mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to eat,'' he said. ``I drove that feed truck for a long
time. I had to do whatever I could to put food on the table for my
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived on a dirt road where nobody knew where I was except
the State Bureau of Investigation, my lawyer, the federal
government, my father and my wife's family.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his indictment, Washburn was working for Akers at
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Akers gave me another chance when no one else would,''
Washburn said. ``He sort of rescued me by taking me in when all
that stuff (the investigation) was going on in South Carolina. When
the story broke that I was targeted by a federal grand jury, they
let me go. I was an embarrassment to the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only there for spring ball. We'd bought a house (in West
Lafayette, Ind.), and I lost it. Looking back, I was just fooling
myself. I knew I'd done something wrong. I guess I was hoping to
outrun it, but it caught up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn drove to the Indianapolis airport to return home to
Shelby, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The low point of my career was at the Indianapolis airport,''
he said. ``When I got to the airport, I took all my football films,
tapes and cutups and threw them in a Dumpster. I thought my career
was over.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Titans arrived in Indianapolis for their second-round
playoff game against the Colts two weeks ago, Washburn thought
about that April day in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the same airport, and I even saw that Dumpster,''
he said, softly. ``I was so thankful for getting a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   After going broke, Washburn had to repay his debts. It has taken
a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we beat Jacksonville, it brought me back even,'' he said
of the playoff check. ``I'm proud of that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said, `Hey, Wash, what are you going to do with your
playoff money?' I told him I was going to pay off my '93 truck and
then get a new set of tires.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how many of his friends stuck with him, Washburn
said, ``Besides my family? Well, my wife (Sandy) didn't leave me.
That was a real plus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washburns have three children _ Jeremiah, Brady and Jessica.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids learned something from my mistakes, so it's worked
out,'' he said. ``I didn't hear from many people, but I'll tell you
what, there were a lot of good things that came out of the whole
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It forged the character of my two sons. There's no question my
sons wouldn't be the kind of men they are today if we hadn't gone
through that. My marriage is stronger. Shoot, I'd be afraid to go
back and change anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I was brought up in a Christian home. Going through
all that humbled me and brought me to my knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn thought about pleading innocent and going to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told the truth,'' he said. ``My wife said, `You can lie
and get out of it, or you can be a man and tell the truth and mean
something to your children. You can face the music and be a real
example, no matter if you've got to serve time or not.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if I had to go to prison I'd go, but I was going to
tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   After being out of football for two years, Washburn made a
commitment to return to coaching, no matter the level. His first
job back was as the head coach of a minor-league football team, the
Charlotte Barons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that our offices were on Little Hope Road,''
he said. ``I think that's kind of ironic. We were in a drug
neighborhood, but hey, I was coaching again.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn won the championship and got a job as an assistant for
the London Monarchs of the World League of American Football, which
became NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Washburn was able to return to college coaching. Ford,
who coached against Washburn when he was head coach at Clemson,
hired him at Arkansas. Ford had to get the approval of athletic
director Frank Broyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year Danny got there, I was sort of on the fringe of
football,'' Washburn said. ``He offered me a job, but when they
(the administration) looked at my past, they said no. The next
year, Danny tried to get me involved again, and this time they were
kind enough to give me a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil, a college football analyst at the time, offered his
support by calling Broyles and recommending Washburn. On Sunday,
Washburn will be trying to keep Vermeil, the Rams' coach, from
winning his first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like coaches who like to work, who're talented and have a
passion for the game,'' Vermeil said Wednesday. ``I watched him
coach in the World League in an unbelievably negative environment
in regard to the facilities and the whole thing. He did a hell of a
job. I respected it. I'd hire him myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ford was fired at Arkansas, Helton hired Washburn at the
University of Houston. He thought he had a job at Michigan State
working for Nick Saban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a job with Nick, but somebody told him about that Sports
Illustrated article,'' Washburn said. ``He read it, called me back
and said he couldn't hire me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kim Helton just felt sorry for me. What a good guy he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   After coaching one season under Helton, Washburn was interviewed
by Fisher at the Senior Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a defensive line coach who would teach the players
how to walk before they could run,'' Fisher said. ``I wanted a
motivator, someone who lived and died football. When Jim was first
recommended to me (by Titans director of college scouting Glenn
Cumbee), I talked to a lot of people about him. I found out what
the circumstances were, and when I talked with him I looked beyond
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After visiting with him at the Senior Bowl for 30 minutes, I
knew Jim was the kind of coach I was looking for. He just wanted an
opportunity. I think everyone deserves a second chance. What
happened to Jim is behind him. It doesn't concern me. He's done a
fantastic job.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Titans had 30 sacks, including 13{ by the defensive
line. This season, they set a franchise record with 54, including
37{ by the linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn benefited, of course, from getting to coach their No. 1
pick, defensive end Jevon Kearse, who set a rookie record with 14{
sacks, was voted NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year and will start in
the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take Don Shula to coach Jevon Kearse,'' Washburn
said. ``When I took that job, I knew I was in the catbird seat.
There was plenty of talent in that room. When I got there, I told
the players we were going to break the (team) sack record and go to
the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse knows how much Washburn has meant to his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those coaches who has these sayings,'' Kearse
said. ``He's a great motivator. He'll say things to me that make me
get tears in my eyes and make me want to line up and play some
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fisher and his family moved out of their house and into a
new one they built, Washburn rented the old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were leaving,'' Fisher said, ``I wrote with a power
washer in my driveway, `More Sacks.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was Fisher who encouraged Washburn to tell his story at the
Super Bowl. Players and coaches are fined by the NFL if they don't
show up for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he can be an inspiration, Washburn said, ``I'm just a
regular guy, but I'll tell you the best thing I did. I'm a
Methodist, and there's a publication the Methodists have that's
called The Upper Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote an article, and this guy read it and wrote me back.
He's a college coach who had cancer. He wrote me that he had my
article framed and put it on the bulletin board. He said it gave
him the hope to try to beat cancer. And he did beat cancer. Man,
that made me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the Titans organization feels good this week and
appreciates the opportunity to play in Super Bowl XXXIV. But no one
feels better or appreciates it more than Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, everyone knows about the Music City Miracle,'' Washburn
said, referring to the kickoff return that beat Buffalo in the
first round of the playoffs. ``Well, it's a real miracle I'm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
