<HEADLINE>
KINGS FALLING FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS -- If you think this winless streak against the Dallas St
ars is long, consider this summer if the Kings don't make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Kings are on the outside looking in at t
he postseason. And though Wednesday's 3-1 loss to the Stars in
front of 17,001 at Reunion Arena extended their slump to 22 games,
it might be worse that they have been caught by Calgary and
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers and the were the small market teams the Kings were
supposed to leave behind when they upgraded their roster last
summer and moved into the Staples Center. Instead, it is the Kings
in ninth place in an eight team race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what is going on,'' said veteran defenseman Garry
Galley. ``We wake up every morning and see what the standings are.
But it is not time to push the panic button. If we play the rest of
the way the way we played tonight, we get some wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Kings' 11th consecutive loss to the Stars
was goaltender Ed Belfour, who stopped 38 of 39 shots including 18
in the third period. The only goal he allowed came in the final two
minutes of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Kings' other three losses to the Stars this season,
Dallas did not set the tone. In addition to the shots on goal, that
included eight by Rob Blake and six by Ziggy Palffy, the Kings took
27 shots that missed the net.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had just 18 shots on Kings goaltender Jamie Storr and
missed the net just eight other times. But it was the fourth time
Dallas be at them this season. Last year, it was six straight,
including five victories by one goal.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Kings beat Dallas was April 6, 1995. The two
teams, which have had three games in January, play again Feb. 11
and April 7, both at Staples Center. Wednesday's loss also set a
franchise record for both clubs. The Kings were winless (17-0-4) in
22 straight against Dallas' ancestors the Minnesota North from
March 31, 1970 to Dec. 11, 1973 . The NHL record is 34 by the
Montreal Canadiens against the Washington Capitals in the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak is out there, there is nothing you can do about it,
but think the next time is going to be the one that stops it,''
Kings coach Andy Murray said. ``Most nights we have played with
great effort. We didn't win, but we played very well tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings admitted the Stars, who have been decimated by
injuries after their Stanley Cup-winning season, looked flat. The
Kings had a chance to tie the game in the final seconds, but
against Belfour it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   After pulling their goalie, the Kings had a chance to tie the
game with 25 second left in regulation when Palffy fired a low shot
that Belfour kicked away for his 38th save of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven seconds later, Brett Hull added an empty netter after
a pass from Mike Modano, who had a goal and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   For Belfour, the victory raised his record to just 18-19-13, but
he is 4-0 since he was snubbed for the All-Star game in place of
New York's Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   As they have done all season, the Stars scored first and put the
Kings back on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   Marko Tuomainen had just come back on the ice midway through the
first period, when former King Darryl Sydor first a slap shot from
the point. Brett Hull got the rebound but was stopped by goaltender
Jamie Storr.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings couldn't clear the puck and Modano poked in his
19th goal of the season to make it 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like he has been doing that to us all season,'' Galley
said. ``But we held our own. We can't worry about what the other
teams are doing. We know everyone is close. We know we belong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
