<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT BEATS CAPRIATI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ Ten years ago, 13-year-old Lindsay Davenport admired
Jennifer Capriati, the tennis player: ``We're the exact same age,
but Jennifer's out of my league.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Davenport feared Capriati, the image: ``I'm
gonna be careful. I don't want to go what she's the gone through.
I'm in no hurry. I'm gonna graduate from high school and go to the
senior prom.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport said, ``It's really strange _ and great for her _ that
Jennifer and I wound up in the Australian Open semifinals. I'm so
glad for her, that she could come back after all her problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But Davenport, the 6-foot-3-inch Wimbledon champion, was
determined to be an added problem herself, and held together under
a fierce Capriati assault to power her way into Thursday's final,
6-2, 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
   Davenport will go against Martina Hingis, a 6-3, 6-2 winner over
Conchita Martinez, for the title. Hingis, who is riding a 27-set
Aussie streak, is bidding to become the first player in the open
era to win the Australian four straight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer kept me on my heels the way she was slugging,'' said
Davenport, who was toppled by Capriati's rugged forehand in the
10th game of the second set as she served for the victory at 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, who has risen from No. 101 to No. 21 in two years, was
matching Davenport's firepower, shot for shot.
</P>
<P>
   But in the tiebreaker, it was Davenport's harmless-looking,
changeup kicker second serve that did Capriati in, making two vital
points. Capriati overhit them, the first a backhand that looked a
winner that would have given her a minibreak _ but it just missed
the sideline so that Davenport was at 3-3. The lone mini, to 5-4,
went to Davenport on Capriati's error, concluding a blistering
exchange of 21 strokes. Davenport fooled Capriati with another slow
66 miles per hour kicker to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Then Davenport, making her third major final, served it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't adjust with my feet. They were just too easy . . . I
didn't know what to do,'' said Capriati, who plunked a last
forehand into the net, ending her 82-minute challenge that roused a
late-morning gathering of 12,000 to constant shouts of ``Come on,
Jennifer!''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years had passed since the ill-starred Capriati last
ventured this far in a major championship, the US Open semifinal
that she barely lost to Monica Seles. A gloomy morning brought rain
and forced closure of the retractable roof of the Rod Laver
Stadium, transforming their struggle into a hot-house engagement
that Davenport seemed about to run away with.
</P>
<P>
   In 23 minutes, Davenport had pocketed the opening set, running
up a 5-1 lead and splintered Capriati's serve to start the second.
The depth of Davenport's weighty ground strokes and her dynamite
serve killed Capriati.
</P>
<P>
   But Capriati, ever a fighter, came roaring back to score her
first service break 2-1 at the half-hour mark, subsided 2-4, then
began to outhit her faltering foe to catch her at 4-4. ``Jennifer
had me going. But I hung in when it mattered,'' said Davenport. ``I
am so happy for her, and I know she is happy again. But I didn't
want to make her any happier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
