<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7850 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     01-27 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR FACES BRING GLITTER TO SUPER BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ah, finally. Star quality at the Super Bowl. And not a
moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway. Wayne Gretzky. And, a personal favorite, Michael
Jordan _ the only NBA owner with a fadeaway jumper worth a damn.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, just as the earnest, honorable Rams and Titans vowed
to get down to the serious work of preparing for the Big Game, the
AARP trinity of our sporting era showed up in not-so-hot 'Lanta.
(Temperature 28. Wind chill 14.)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Elway, Gretzky and Jordan were all in one room. Buddies.
Business partners. The three amigos and, gosh, the mind just about
warped in the presence of such megawatt people wearing really
expensive suits.
</P>
<P>
   What must it be like to be one of those rich and famous and
wildly talented guys, hanging around those other two rich and
famous and wildly talented guys?
</P>
<P>
   This question suddenly seemed as important as who's going to win
Sunday, if anyone in the world is seriously contemplating that
question.
</P>
<P>
   As Super Bowl XXXIV begins to thaw, apologies are extended to
the likes of Kurt Warner, Steve McNair, Eddie George, Marshall
Faulk, Orlando Pace and Jevon Kearse.
</P>
<P>
   This is your Super Bowl, fellas. And your teams are deserving.
Your records valiant. Your play-making commendable.
</P>
<P>
   But, hate to say it, no one directly involved in this Super Bowl
is a big enough star to get past the bouncer at the Gold Club. Not
unless strip club patrons such as Patrick Ewing or Latrell Sprewell
take them for a spin.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive us for being temporarily blinded by the light of our
favorite retirees. We are, after all, talking Jordan, Elway and
Gretzky _ a veritable sports-god triumvirate who showed up
Wednesday to unveil their new virtual venture, MVP.com.
</P>
<P>
   If the holy rollers of hoops, hockey and hut hut want to get
together and hawk sporting goods on their new Web site, who are we
to stop them?
</P>
<P>
   And, more to the point, who are we to ignore them, especially
when we get to see so little of themnowadays?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's not just selling kayaks and pucks and sneakers and
pitching wedges that makes MVP.com so cool, the Big Three say. The
site is also about getting inside the minds of these
fourth-quarter, final period, last-minute saviors. There are all
sorts of tidbits and insights from the three Mr. Clutches.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said his contribution, besides a serious cash
investment, will be tips on hockey stick blade curvature.
</P>
<P>
   Elway will give important advice on how much you should blow up
the protective lining inside your kid's football helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want it tight. But then again, you don't want it too
tight,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent point. Sales will no doubt be swift. Wall Street
a-flutter. When's the IPO?
</P>
<P>
   As for Jordan, well, he had the best suit and the biggest
diamond stud earring, which was good to see. These things helped
distract some attention away from the fact that Sir Air can't much
distinguish between a mouse and a motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting up to speed on the Internet situation,'' Jordan
said, as if he were a member of the Cabinet, addressing some
confounding overseas conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did promise that as a director of this new Internet
company, he is a bona fide creative and business contributor. His
new job as king of the Washington Wizards won't stand in the way.
Nor will his work with Tweety Bird or the Hanes underwear people.
</P>
<P>
   And, most important, Jordan is answering almost all his e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``John writes me every day and I'm getting good at getting right
back to him,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it takes awhile. Jordan is practicing the
hunt-and-peck method on his laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Guess Typing 101 was not required up there at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is encouraging to see Jordan stretching himself with
this new business opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just lending my name to this enterprise. I'm willing
to roll up my sleeves and go to work,'' Sir Air confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   No telling if Jordan will be at the inventory warehouse come the
Christmas rush, like so many other e-commerce robber barons who
actually do pack boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Jordan can pull a shift in gift-wrapping. Or, better
yet, he could hold inspirational meetings with customer service
people and warehouse workers, show them what it's like to raise
their game.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did that this week with his other new toy, the Wizards.
Sir Air apparently schooled his underachieving team, running the
floor and hitting jumpers and exhorting the players to be a little
more like Mike.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the Wizards declared that Jordan would be the NBA's
leading scorer if he were playing this season.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the man also likes to pour his competitive heart into
whatever task is in front of him, as do Elway and Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be as successful after football as I was during my
career. And this is a good way to start now that our best playing
days are behind us,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   To which Jordan quickly responded, ``Mine aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the three amigos were gone, leaving behind some much
appreciated stardust and a personality vacuum that guys such as
Warner, Kearse, Faulk, McNair, Pace and George will, bless them,
attempt to fill.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
