<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSON'S BUZZER-BEATER SINKS NETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It might have been the most efficient two seconds of
basketball that Chuck Person ever played in his 14 years in the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Inserted for his shooting ability with 1.8 seconds remaining in
the game, the reserve forward calmly hit a 3-pointer at the buzzer
as the Sonics narrowly escaped with a 95-92 win over the New Jersey
Nets Wednesday night before 13,340 fans in KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew exactly what I needed to do when I went in there,''
said Person, who is nicknamed ``The Rifleman'' for good reason. ``I
don't get all that excited anymore and it was just another shot,
but it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Road-weary and lethargic, the Sonics played most of the game as
if they had been snowed in after leaving the frigid East Coast for
the normally temperate and friendly confines of their home court.
</P>
<P>
   They came out cold and never seemed to warm to the occasion
until the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs are a little bit tired and my shot was a little bit
flat,'' guard Gary Payton admitted after a 6-for-22 night from the
field in which he managed just 17 points, six below his season
average.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Shammond Williams (18 points off the bench) still had
the hot hand from his last game against the New York Knicks on
Monday night, and Person had the one last-second miracle shot in
his arsenal as the Sonics staved off overtime and ended their
three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a beautiful thing. That's one of the reasons we have
Chuck on this team. He's a clutch shooter and he has range,''
Sonics coach Paul Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   As a shooter, Person said, sometimes ``you get a feel for
whether it's going in or not. I shot it straight. ... So when I saw
the good rotation, I kind of felt it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets had a chance to win the game with 7.5 seconds left in
regulation, but Johnny Newman's layin was blocked by Ruben
Patterson, setting up the final play to Person. It atoned for an
otherwise sub-par effort on both sides of the court.
</P>
<P>
   During one particularly odious stretch during the second
quarter, the Sonics and Nets exchanged four turnovers in a row,
followed by a shot-clock violation on both sides. For the game, the
Sonics had 20 turnovers, while the Nets had 22.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone in the building assumed overtime was in order
when the Sonics first tried an inbound play for Payton, but the
ball was deflected out of bounds by Nets guard Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   The failed play, however, allowed the Sonics to get the ball
closer to the hoop for the final jumper from Person off a pass from
Emanual Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much time, but there was plenty,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   The way the play was designed, Person passed the ball to Davis
and was left wide open for the 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dangerous guy on an inbound play is the guy that
takes it out if there is enough time,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Nets coach Don Casey took responsibility for setting up a
defense in the last seconds that double-teamed Payton while leaving
Person open down the side of the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle made two big-time plays. They made a defensive stop
and we made a bad tactical move,'' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were looking to put an end to a three-game skid after
road losses to the Knicks, Raptors and Celtics during their East
Coast swing. They also had a three-game home winning streak on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets forced the action early and the Sonic reserves
never seemed to get in tune with the rest of the starters.
</P>
<P>
   Rashard Lewis was particularly cold in the first half, missing
all three of his field goal attempts and hitting only one basket
for the game. Davis, who was starting in place of the injured Brent
Barry, also struggled, hitting just 1-for-8 from the floor and
scoring five points in 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Barry was out with a concussion suffered on Monday against the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Also sputtering in the first half was Payton, who had just six
points on 3-for-11 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who was ejected in the first quarter on Monday, played
like he was still smarting from the disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   During the road trip, Payton had admonished some of his
teammates to work harder on the boards and on the floor, but it was
Payton who had the most difficulty getting into the game Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trip took a lot out of me and we just have to get back to
where we were,'' Payton said. ``A lot of these guys were tired but
we sucked it up and a did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal also shook up the starting lineup in the second half,
inserting Williams and Jelani McCoy at center after Horace Grant
pulled out with a calf contusion.
</P>
<P>
   Williams immediately made an impact, hitting a layin and
collecting a put-back jumper off a Vin Baker miss to give the
Sonics their first lead, 55-54 with 6:30 left in the third quarter.
He then calmly canned a 3-pointer on the next possession to stretch
the lead to four points.
</P>
<P>
   The much-improved Nets had won 15 of their last 24 games heading
into KeyArena. They were led by Marbury's 24 points, followed by 18
points by former Sonic Kendall Gill and 14 points each for Newman
and Keith Van Horn, who missed most of the second half with a
bruised knee.
</P>
<P>
   Baker led the Sonics with 23 points and 13 rebounds, and
Patterson had 17 points and eight rebounds as the two forwards kept
the Sonics close throughout the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't sustain their run,'' Marbury said. ``They kept
the game close and then they got a lucky break.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics now have two days off before they host former coach
George Karl and the Milwaukee Bucks on Saturday at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of these three-game losing streaks and then you win
three. We just have to be consistent a little more,'' Payton said.
``It was good that we could get this win tonight and now we're
going to get a couple of days when we can rest.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Angelo Bruscas can be reached at 206-448-8010
</P>
<P>
   or angelobruscas &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
