<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-U.S. (Undated) _ American investigators have uncovered
what they believe are links between a group of Algerians who have
been charged with plotting a terrorist attack in the United States
and Osama bin Laden, the exiled Saudi accused of bombing two U.S.
embassies in east Africa, law enforcement officials said on
Wednesday. Exclusive. By David Johston, Judith Miller and William
K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-BUSINESS (Damascus, Syria) _ They have luxury cars,
marble-floored offices, satellite dishes, tailored suits and
high-end computers. But young Syrian entrepreneurs are feeling
distinctly bankrupt. On the horizon, they can see the outlines of a
new world, one in which Syria's inefficient and inward-looking
producers will have to compete in a newly energized Middle East
free of trade barriers. And while an end to the 52-year-old state
of war between Syria and Israel is also in sight, many businessmen
fear they will not be able to reap any of the economic dividends of
peace. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Washington) _ The aftermath of a gene therapy
test and the questions it raises about informed consent and the
inherent conflict of interest between researchers and their
subjects. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-NY (New York) _ As Al Gore prepares to return to New York
for a second primary, on March 7, this time as the vice president
and the favorite to be his party's presidential nominee, he is a
very different candidate from the one whose campaign collapsed on
the steps of Mayor Edward Koch's City Hall in 1988. And there is
probably no better place to chart that evolution than in this same
state that provided Gore with a brutal lesson in presidential
politics. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
