   CLINTON-SPEECH _ In advance of his Thursday evening speech, we
compare President Clinton to the various presidents he has pledged
to be in past State of the Union addresses. Have his incarnations
lived up to expectations? By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MULTIPLEXES (Dunkirk, France) _ Bruno Frydman had few
illusions when he set up shop in Paris in 1993 to build the kind of
multiplex theaters that helped revolutionize moviegoing in the
United States. It took him six years to get his latest and biggest
project built _ a 20-screen, 4,010-seat site in a harborside
shopping center in Dunkirk. His experience shows that he was right
not to underestimate French resistance to big multiplex developers.
By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNICATIONS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Own BCE stock? If so, you
were probably very happy Wednesday. Own Nortel stock? You were
probably not happy Wednesday. Call it ``A Tale of Two Shareholder
Bases,'' one that underscores some of the financial dislocations
that can emerge as certain parts of the communications industry
grow far faster than others. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTS-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Typically before the Super Bowl,
account activity along Madison Avenue slows as agencies turn their
attention to finishing commercials scheduled to run during the
game. Given how frenetic business has been lately, though, it's no
surprise that several large advertisers made decisions Wednesday
involving accounts. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
