<P>
   ETHNICITY-HOUSES (Undated) _ As the cultural melting pot seeps
outwards, away from the cities, it brings with it a new kind of
ethnic diversity to the previously all-white enclaves. Nowhere is
this more evident than in the town of Iselin, N.J. By Alastair
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SEED-CATALOG (Union, Conn.) _ By sunrise one day last week, it
was 6 below in this frozen burg. But the wind made it feel like 30
below as it knifed through the pine trees and banged on the metal
doors of a secondhand trailer across from Marilyn Barlow's old
farmhouse. By 8 a.m., this slumbering world was buzzing with the
dreams of spring. The first of hundreds of gardeners started
calling. When would the Select Seeds catalog arrive? Was it too
early to start kiss-me-over-the-garden-gate? (Yes.) What about
poppies? (Scatter them outside, over the snow.) Orders poured in,
by phone and fax, for America, a fragrant, cherry-red-and-white
sweet pea dating to 1896, and for a little fringed
raspberry-scented flower that Napoleon carried from Egypt to
Josephine. Three women hunched over computers, typing in orders,
surrounded by postcards. By Ann Raver.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIVORCED-ROOMMATES (New York) _ Breaking up is hard to do,
especially in Manhattan's tight housing market. Faced with the most
expensive rents in the country, skyrocketing co-op prices and a
paltry vacancy rate estimated at less than 1 percent, an increasing
number of Manhattan couples are living together long after their
relationship dies. Call them room-exes; their existence recalls
Soviet-era Moscow, when the chronic housing shortage forced most
divorced couples either to live together or move back in with their
parents. By David Wallis.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   HUMANS-AS-PREY (Helena, Mont.) _ Dan Dodge's 12 year-old son,
Jake, was playing outside the family home in this mountain-ringed
town when his father heard him yell, ``There's a mountain lion!''
Dodge looked out the window to see a dun-colored cat crouched about
30 feet away from a picnic table, moving stealthily toward his son.
Dodge ran to his bedroom, and grabbed a .270-caliber rifle. Firing
from inside the house, he dropped the 115-pound female cat with
several shots. Dodge called to alert the Montana Department of
Fish, Wildlife and Parks, which approved his course of action. Pete
Johnson, the conservation officer who investigated the shooting,
said: ``Lions are unpredictable. If the kid had taken off running
it could have triggered the predatory response in the lion.'' By
Jim Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
