r a BC-MARS-LANDER-SFCHRON &LR;      01-27 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-LANDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAINT SIGNAL SETS OFF NEW SEARCH FOR LOST MARS LANDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  NASA mission controllers renewed their effort to contact the
lost Mars Polar Lander Wednesday after mysterious faint signals
raised hopes that the spacecraft might still be alive and signaling
from somewhere on the Red Planet.
<P>
   But scientists described the chances of making contact as ``a
real long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of radio engineers from Stanford University and SRI
International, the Menlo Park, Calif., research outfit, reported
this week that their 150-foot dish antenna overlooking Interstate
280 had picked up faint signals from Mars on December 18 and
January 4.
</P>
<P>
   In the hope of renewing contact, NASA controllers at the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena radioed three fresh sets of
messages Wednesday instructing the spacecraft to signal. And the
Stanford team spent the day fine-tuning the big dish to catch any
tiny response.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and Stanford officials said it would take a day or more of
analysis before they would know if they had succeeded in
communicating with the wayward spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're cautiously optimistic, but it's no more than that,'' Sam
Thurman, the Polar Lander's flight director, told reporters in a
telephone conference call Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Morale among the lander's team members has certainly taken an
upward swing from the gloom of last week, when NASA officials
announced that they had abandoned all hope and the search for the
lost lander was ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure blew our minds,'' Thurman said of the Stanford team's
tantalizing hints that their spacecraft, however badly wounded,
might still be alive. ``It's like going to the funeral of a friend
and suddenly learning that he may not be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The $165 million spacecraft had been on its final approach to
the planet, within minutes of landing near the Martian south pole
to search for water ice, when it vanished December 3.
</P>
<P>
   NASA immediately began an experimental effort to communicate
with the downed craft, and it selected the Stanford radio dish
because of its sensitivity and its ability to focus tightly in any
direction in space.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford dish is also capable of picking up radio signals in
the ultrahigh-frequency wavelengths that NASA mission controllers
use to communicate with the Mars Global Surveyor, which is now in
orbit around the planet. The lander was to have relayed some of its
collected data to Earth on the UHF band through the Surveyor above
it.
</P>
<P>
   The signals that the Stanford dish picked up _ and hoped to have
picked up again Wednesday _ were extremely faint but seemed to come
from the right direction, according to Mike Cousins, a radio
engineer from SRI who works on the dish.
</P>
<P>
   But Thurman cautioned that the faint sounds may well have come
from nearby UHF television stations, inadvertently ``leaking''
their signals into Stanford's big dish receiver.
</P>
<P>
   If the signals do come from the lander, ``at best we'll only get
a handful of bits,'' Thurman said. But even those few bits of data
could tell the scientists whether the lander is lying on its side,
or perhaps on the slope of a hill.
</P>
<P>
   And if signals are repeated again and again, it may be possible
to pinpoint just where within the lander's target area near the
south pole it came to grief.
</P>
<P>
   All that will take many weeks of data analysis if the signals do
come from the lander. And scientists say there is no possibility
that the spacecraft could ever pursue its mission of digging for
water and characterizing the frozen soil in the planet's
southernmost region.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman and his team at mission control will continue their
effort Friday, sending three more sets of signals up to the lost
lander _ in the hope that the ship's radio will reply _ with even
the briefest and feeblest of messages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
