<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A SCENE RIGHT OUT OF A THRILLER  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ T he police lieutenant puts aside the official
cop-to-media language and talks like a proud dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officer (Danielle) Feccia, she just got engaged, she's a
lovely woman, she's on this guy like 50 wildcats. Then you've got
(Officer Michael) Glickman, the avenging angel.''
</P>
<P>
   (Why isn't Lt. Mark Swendsen of Park Station writing cop
novels?)
</P>
<P>
   ``The (suspect) is 5-11, 190,'' he explains, ``and Officer
Feccia took his ass  &UR; down. &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, it was jumpin' Tuesday evening up on Corbett Ave., just
off Market Street, where Market starts winding up the big hill.
Someone somehow got into a 51-year-old man's apartment and beat the
man unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, it would turn out, is on parole after doing time
for rape and has a decade-long record of very violent crime and
parole violation.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor heard a scuffle, then screaming and whimpering,
called 911, and soon the Feccia-Glickman tag team arrived. They
covered the second-floor apartment front and back, and the perp,
who wore shades and had bloody socks on his hands, jumped out a
front window.
</P>
<P>
   Feccia, who is 5-foot-4, hopped onto the suspect's back. He
fought to his feet and tried to throw her off, yelling, ``Just
shoot me! Just f_ shoot me!''
</P>
<P>
   She grabbed his hair and pulled him backward, but he broke free
and ran. She chased him down to Market, where he bolted through
heavy traffic, jumped into the passenger side of a van, got shoved
out by the van driver, and ran some more.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Glickman arrived in the squad car and tried to head
the guy off. Feccia grabbed the suspect again from behind, but he
swatted her away. Glickman got out, joined the foot chase, caught
up with the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He duked it out with the guy, toe to toe, for four blocks,''
Swendsen says proudly. ``Running through traffic, chase and fight,
chase and fight, chase and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally Glickman made a tackle, both men sliding into busy
Market Street, and the chase was over.
</P>
<P>
   So no more cracks about cops and doughnuts, OK?
</P>
<P>
   UP TO YOUR cubits in rainwater?
</P>
<P>
   If you're in San Jose, the Emergency Operations Center will
supply you with sandbags. Just call 1-888-HEY-NOAH.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRITY NEWS: George Hamilton, who has contributed to global
warming by soaking up so many solar rays, has moved to San
Francisco and is living with author Danielle Steele. Where does he
tan? ... Jane Fonda, Christian zealot. Gives new meaning to the
phrase, ``Feel the burn!'' ... Did you see Dick Clark on the Golden
Globe Awards? Dick's next power gig: Valet-parking the stars'
limos.
</P>
<P>
   HALLMARK, getting hip to the fact that people don't want to
spend more on the card than the gift, has come out with a line of
99-cent greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   And they're branching out into nontraditional areas. Like:
``Troubled Relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   I want to say ``sorry'' but not blow a whole buck.
</P>
<P>
   WHO WANTS to be a millionaire? Anyone who bet $5,000 on the Rams
to win the Super Bowl, early in the season when Vegas was giving
200-to-1 odds.
</P>
<P>
   If I were the Rams, I'd have people hanging with QB Kurt Warner
this week, making sure he doesn't eat any shellfish or accept any
rides from strangers.
</P>
<P>
   YOU CAN'T CATCH a cab in the city, my expert says, because so
many of the cabbies are new hires, many from out of country, with
no knowledge of the city. So they keep it simple, hanging at the
airport, avoiding the confusing streets downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Gavin, how about a mandatory cabbie qualifying school _
Taxi Tech?
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE REASON why this century is far superior to the 20th:
Silicon Valley now has an online dry cleaner. They download your
cleaning request, come right to your desk and virtually take you to
the cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   SEAL ROCK continues in the grand local tradition of misnamed
islands. Alcatraz, for instance, got its name when an English sea
captain goofed on his map and slapped the name of another island _
Isla de Alcatraces (pelicans) _ on the Rock. The former Pelican
Island became Yerba Buena Island, which became the retirement home
of Willie Brown's girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Seal Rock never had seals, it had sea lions, which split for
Pier 39 a decade ago, so one reader suggested calling it Birdpoop
Rock, or something close to that, since that's all you can see on
the island now.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Ryugo says you can't call Seal Rock Birdpoop Rock,
because there already is a Birds_ Rock. Actually it's Bird Rock,
just north of Point Bonita, and the pelicans, cormorants and gulls
have made the island look like a snow-capped mountain, so fishermen
know it as Birds_ Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should change Seal Rock to Sealfree Rock. And why not
give Alcatraz's name back to its rightful owner, Yerba Buena
Island, and call Alcatraz Jailhouse Rock?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
