<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 03:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-STATE-UNION-SFCHRON &LR;      01-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-UNION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FLURRY OF PROPOSALS EXPECTED IN CLINTON'S STATE OF THE UNION  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thursday night, President Clinton is expected to
deliver his last State of the Union speech as if it were his first
_ with a blizzard of proposals and the unspoken message that the
vision he brought to office can be carried forward by the man
seated directly behind him, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always placed much weight on this annual address to
the joint session of Congress. For his first, seven years ago, he
was making changes up until the moment he arrived at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Clinton will seek to establish his legacy as the
steward of a booming economy and world peace, and to inform the
nation that he will remain an activist president until his final
moment in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked very hard on the speech, and I'm still working on
it,'' Clinton said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's last year comes for him much too soon. He recently
told reporters that he wished he ``could go without sleep for a
whole year'' so that he ``could milk every last second'' of his
final days as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never known previous presidents to be quite as almost
maudlin about the prospects of leaving office,'' said Stephen Hess,
a presidential scholar at the Brookings Institution. ``I can't
remember presidents ever spending quite so much time talking about
their legacy. It's kind of a narcissistic manner that defines
Clintonesque.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, the Clinton administration has announced
a new initiative almost every day. The president has already
announced $150 billion in new spending for next year _ from
multibillion-dollar expansions of Medicare to a tiny $27 million
program to battle wage discrimination against women _ and several
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's speech is expected to include a number of new
proposals, notably ClickStart, a new program to provide up to $100
million to buy computers and Internet access for low-income
households.
</P>
<P>
   First suggested by Bay Area computer executives, ClickStart
melds the Internet Age with classic liberal social policy. Its name
derives from Head Start, the low-income preschool program begun by
President Lyndon Johnson in the 1960s, and its model is President
Franklin Roosevelt's Rural Electrification Administration of the
1930s, which brought electricity to rural homes.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative will underscore Clinton's efforts to bridge the
``digital divide,'' a major plank in Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Just as President Ronald Reagan seemed to win a third term with
Vice President George Bush's election, a Gore presidency would
affirm Clinton's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   As the titular head of the Senate, Gore will sit just behind the
podium where Clinton speaks, creating a visual link between
candidate Gore and the president as Clinton describes a booming
economy, a world at peace, declining crime, shrinking welfare rolls
and a raft of proposals to improve education, clean the
environment, protect Social Security and expand health care.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has emerged from his victory against Sen. Bill Bradley in
the Iowa caucuses with a newfound enthusiasm for aligning himself
with Clinton, telling audiences that he is ``deeply honored'' to be
Clinton's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Clinton's speech will be aimed at ``trying to get Al
Gore elected and help the Democrats win back the House,'' said GOP
strategist Bill Kristol.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really would be, more than anything else, his real
vindication, taking the House back from the Republicans who
impeached him and electing his vice president to succeed him.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the policy initiatives that Clinton will propose,
and all the activism that he promises until his last hour in
office, there is scant chance that much will pass Congress this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are clinging to a five-vote margin in the House, and
Democrats see a majority within reach, making prospects dim for
bipartisan agreement on anything.
</P>
<P>
   Pacts could be reached on a handful of small, popular tax cuts,
such as reducing the so-called marriage penalty, along with some of
the high-tech industry's agenda, equally popular with both parties.
Clearing China's membership in the World Trade Organization is also
in play, although that is already getting bogged down in
election-year politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has always made highly effective use of his State of
the Union speech, whether to reframe his presidency after
Republicans captured the House in 1994 or, as last year, to reclaim
it after his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington pundits discount his State of the Union speech,''
said Kristol, ``but they get huge audiences and have helped him a
lot in the past. I don't minimize the extent to which he might
begin framing the issues for the general election on Gore's behalf,
while Gore is still otherwise occupied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0305EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
