<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEBATES-NH-SFCHRON &LR;      01-27 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-NH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEMOS NASTY, REPUBLICANS A BIT MORE CIVIL IN LATEST DEBATES  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Democratic presidential candidates clashed
bitterly over health care, voting records and campaign tactics
Wednesday night, while Republicans sparred over abortion, trade and
even the dignity of mosh pits.
</P>
<P>
   The final debates before next week's primary produced some of
the sharpest exchanges of the campaign, as Vice President Al Gore
and Texas Gov. George W. Bush were accused by their chief rivals of
being beholden to special interests and conducting poll-driven
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, I wonder whether, if you are running a campaign
that is saying untrue things, whether you'll be able to be a
president that people can trust,'' former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley said in an exchange that grew increasingly unfriendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Bill,'' Gore shot back, clearly annoyed by the intensity
of the attack, ``I haven't accused you of lying. If you feel that
you are defensive on the substance of an issue, then change your
plan. Don't shoot the messenger.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate among the leading Republican candidates lacked the
bitterness of the Gore-Bradley exchange. But Arizona Sen. John
McCain tried to make the same point as Bradley _ that the GOP
front-runner represents monied interests and politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Bush's assertion that McCain's budget plans sound
like Gore's, McCain shot back: ``If you're saying that I'm like Al
Gore, then you're spinning like Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bradley and McCain have placed enormous emphasis on New
Hampshire. Most strategists agree that this state, with its fierce
contrarian streak and distaste for slick politics, gives the two
candidates their best, and perhaps their only, shot to slow the
front-runners' momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The debates, held 30 minutes apart in the same downtown
Manchester television studio, came six days before the nation's
first primary and just as Granite State voters are becoming fully
engaged in the close race.
</P>
<P>
   With as much of a quarter of the electorate still undecided, the
last week of campaigning will be crucial in each contest, which
polls suggest are too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back format also offered a rare glimpse into the
differences between the two parties, providing a preview of the
fall campaign, in which divisions on the issues will be more
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans repeatedly returned to social issues and
offered private-sector solutions on matters ranging from trips to
Mars to the distribution of computers to the poor, Democrats
offered government initiatives to address health care and education
matters.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's most surreal moment came when GOP candidate Gary
Bauer questioned rival Alan Keyes about his jumping into a mosh pit
earlier this week after a rally, as supporters passed him hand over
hand to the sound of blaring rock 'n' roll music.
</P>
<P>
   Reminding Keyes that he had previously criticized McCain for
joking about the senator's fondness for the band ``Nine Inch
Nails,'' Bauer, a former adviser to President Ronald Reagan, asked
Keyes how he could be so blase as his supporters played the music
of the band Rage Against the Machine, which Bauer branded as
``anti-family (and mispronounced as Machine against the Rage.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think you owe an apology? Do you think that was
consistent with the dignity of the office of the presidency?''
Bauer demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, a former State Department official who describes himself
as the only true conservative in the race, said, ``I'll leave that
to the judgment of the American people,'' though he added that one
reporter noted that Keyes was the only person the reporter had ever
seen emerge from a mosh pit with his tie still straight.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that exchange, which drew uproarious howls from the
adjoining press areas, Republicans battled on familiar turf: who
was most committed to abortion, who was hardest on China, and
whether Bush had been an effective governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stood up to a pointed attack by Forbes about his record on
education and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many half-stories, so little time,'' he sighed, pointing
out that he was re-elected by the people of Texas with more than 70
percent of the vote. Exuding a combination of confidence and
caution throughout the debate, Bush also alluded to his
electability, mentioning that Texas carries a huge electoral punch.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes pressed McCain on his commitment to ban abortions, asking
McCain why he had said that if his daughter was raped, it would be
a family decision whether she got an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is opposed to legal abortion except in the case of rape,
incest or when a woman's health is at risk.
</P>
<P>
   McCain calmly said he was proud of his pro-life record, before
sternly adding that ``I will not draw my children into this
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly angered by the question, McCain returned to the point
more than an hour later, turning to Keyes and saying: ``I've seen
enough killing in my life. I know how precious human life is. And I
don't need a lecture from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Steve Forbes was repeatedly attacked for his pro-trade
stance by both Keyes and Bauer, who seemed intent on derailing
Forbes' momentum from his second-place finish in the Iowa caucus
and his assertion that he is the most viable social conservative in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the tightness of the Democratic race, the debate
between Gore and Bradley evolved into a meandering tit-for-tat, as
both candidates appeared rattled, off their game, and annoyed with
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Gore questioned Bradley about his votes against welfare reform,
and for the budget cuts proposed by Reagan in the early 1980s,
asking Bradley at one point: ``I just don't see how you can vote
for Ronald Reagan's tax cuts, and then campaign like Robert
Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley questioned Gore's liberal credentials, asking why he had
cast votes against federal funding of abortions as a member of the
House 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the most bitter exchange erupted over a longstanding debate
over health care plans. Bradley favors replacing Medicaid with a
government subsidy that would guarantee health insurance for 95
percent of all Americans. Gore favors retaining Medicaid and has
offered a more limited proposal to insure health care for all
children.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the debate, Gore charged that Bradley's plan would
leave New Hampshire residents ``out in the cold.'' He later accused
Bradley of using dirty campaign tactics in distributing a flyer in
November that accused Gore of dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to talk about a higher standard, you need to abide
by it,'' Gore said. The barbs appeared to get under Bradley's skin.
Tensing up, Bradley said: ``In politics, people sometimes make
misleading statements because they don't know better. But you know
better. You know better.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, neither shook the other's hand. Gore shunned
the press area where the GOP candidates had appeared after their
debate. Bradley came out and made a terse statement, saying the
event was ``a debate of old politics versus new politics.''
</P>
<P>
   He left without taking any questions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
