<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 09:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7943 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-NFC-LITTLE-COX     01-27 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-LITTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tragedy hits home for St. Louis family, Rams LB
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill Gutweiler slipped into bed early that night.
</P>
<P>
   He had to get up at 4 a.m. the next morning for his job
delivering magazines to stores in St. Louis. So the plan was for
his wife, Susan, to pick up Michael, their 16-year-old son, after
he got out of a concert.
</P>
<P>
   He kissed her good-night and told her the same thing he had been
saying for 31 years, ever since that night when he proposed at the
drive-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he casually added something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see you later.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the phone rang. It was Michael. His mother
hadn't shown up. Bill Gutweiler hopped in his car. He drove until
he saw the flashing lights. And the crumpled Thunderbird.
</P>
<P>
   That was Oct. 19, 1998. But sometimes it feels like it was
yesterday. Especially this week. Especially when he turns on the TV
and sees the face of the young man who killed his wife _ St. Louis
Rams linebacker Leonard Little.
</P>
<P>
   You want to know why you shouldn't drink and drive?
</P>
<P>
   Talk to a 54-year-old man in St. Louis. Listen to him describe
how for the past 15 months, he hasn't been able to slip back into
in that bed. Their bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried it two nights,'' he said. ``I made it through one
full night once. But usually I'm back on the couch, under the
afghan. I just can't stay in that bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to this man. But also talk to a 25-year-old football player
in Atlanta. People say he got off easy. And to some extent that's
certainly true. He is alive. He has many things to look forward to
_ including a place in Super Bowl XXXIV on Sunday at the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no such thing as easy in stories like this.
</P>
<P>
   There are only degrees of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Little trudged into the ballroom Wednesday morning and
took a seat at the table with a sign bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters were waiting, camped out at his table. It wasn't
because he is a star. He is primarily a special teams player. He
made six tackles this season.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons the crowd gathered was because Little was even here.
Plain and simple. Fifteen months after celebrating his 24th
birthday by taking part in a Celebrity Waiters Night at a bar in
the Adam's Mark Hotel, after getting in his sports utility vehicle,
after running a red light and killing a 47-year-old woman, he was
sitting in the lobby of an expensive hotel and preparing to play in
the most celebrated sports event in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Little eventually pleaded guilty to involuntary manslaughter. He
was sentenced to spend 90 nights in jail. And although that might
sound like preferential treatment for an athlete, it actually is
pretty standard in Missouri for this crime _ which is why in
November, Mothers Against Drunk Driving held a rally to coincide
with his return after an NFL eight-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is eight enough? St. Louis, it's time to get MADD,'' said one
banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonard Little got too LITTLE and I'm MADD,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   The group gathered at the corner of Market Street and Memorial
Drive _ the place where Little plowed into Gutweiler's car _ and
marched to the Trans World Dome. Little said he supported them.
Said they were doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   He had just celebrated another birthday. Spent it at home. Cut
off the phones. Watched television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll ever do anything on my birthday again,'' he
said. ``Ever. Never. I can honestly say that.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that for two months, he didn't stop crying. He says he
stopped eating. He says he went from 245 pounds to 210. He says
that if there is one thing in his life he could change, it would be
getting in his truck that night.
</P>
<P>
   He says this again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it changes anything. Not for him. And certainly not for
Bill Gutweiler.
</P>
<P>
   They grew up in the same neighborhood in South St. Louis. She
lived two doors down on Indiana Street. He still remembers what
they ate on their first date.
</P>
<P>
   Imo's pizza. Thin crust. Sausage and hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked sausage; she liked hamburger,'' Gutweiler explained
Wednesday from their home in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   He raced motorcycles back in those days. But he eventually sold
his bike so he could buy something more important. An engagement
ring.
</P>
<P>
   When he popped the question and she said yes, they quickly
eloped. Her father wasn't thrilled. She was only 16. He was 21. So
everyone figured it was a mistake. Figured it wouldn't last.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they were together 31 years. Until Leonard Little separated
them.
</P>
<P>
   Gutweiler already had lost a brother, Tim, in a car accident.
And in 1980, he and Susan lost their daughter, Jill, then 7 years
old, when she ran out in front of a car driven by a 16-year old.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't go in Jill's bedroom after that. Sue had to handle
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always the strongest,'' he said. ``She was the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   She was the one who made him stop smoking. She saved the butt
from the last cigarette that he smoked. He stumbled upon that not
too long ago. Just another thing to make him cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried so much at the beginning,'' he said. ``Now the sadness
just comes over me sometimes, like a sickness. I'll be sitting
there, thinking about something and I'll pick up one of our albums
and start going through it and I'll start crying all over again.''
There are so many things that can make him think of her. It can be
something as simple as a song by the Moody Blues. Or the sight of
their son walking out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep myself from getting mad at him,'' he said.
``Even when I am, I just keep thinking that he's all I have left. I
can't stop thinking about the chance that I could lose him.''
</P>
<P>
   He also can't stop thinking about what happened on Oct. 19,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   One night, he tried to retrace Little's path. The police report
said he was going 46 mph. So Gutweiler floored it until he reached
46 mph when he went through the green light at the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that he didn't even touch the brake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Little grew up in Asheville, N.C. His mother was a
Cowboys fan. He remembers her making him watch a Super Bowl. He
doesn't remember which one it was, just that the Cowboys were
involved _ and that one day he wanted to play in one.
</P>
<P>
   He went to University of Tennessee. Became an All-American. Was
drafted in the third round. Ended up in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's every child's dream to play at the Super Bowl,'' he said.
``Growing up, you always want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Only this isn't how he envisioned it.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, while his teammates answered questions about
stopping Tennessee's Steve McNair and Eddie George, he was being
asked: Do you think the Rams should trade you? Do you think you
should be able to play in this game? Have you talked to the family
of Susan Gutweiler? What would you say?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tough,'' he said, rubbing his eyes. ``That's a tough
question.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained he wants to say something to the family, that he
hopes to set up a meeting after the season. When asked if football
is an escape, he shook his head. He said that nothing is an escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, there was an awkward silence at the table, allowing
everyone sitting there to hear what a reporter nearby was asking a
teammate: Do you think it's right that Leonard Little is even in
uniform?
</P>
<P>
   Little's eyes began to tear up. He started to stand up to leave.
A Rams public relations official, William Bryant, put an arm on his
shoulder. He sat back down, closed his eyes for a moment, then
answered some more questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always going to be there,'' he said. ``It's never going
to leave. It's something I'll deal with for the rest of my life.
Time heals a lot of things. Time has helped me out. But it's always
going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the interview session ended. His teammates left the
room in bunches, laughing and smiling. He left by himself.
</P>
<P>
   At first, on those rare occasions when he could sleep, Gutweiler
had these dreams. He was in a room with Little. He was pounding on
him with his fists. Beating him to death.
</P>
<P>
   Now his anger seems to have shifted. Some of it still is
directed at Little. He wonders why he didn't say anything at the
trial; why he hasn't met with the family yet. But more than
anything he seems to be mad at the legal system. Mad at the Rams
for not trading Little. And mad at Rams coach Dick Vermeil for
defending the player who killed his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell Dick Vermeil a little bit about crying,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   All of this makes what has happened in the last month even
harder. The rest of the city of St. Louis is giddy with excitement.
Everywhere you turn there are Rams jerseys, Rams signs, Rams
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Every one is a reminder of his wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   So now there is this. A Super Bowl game. Gutweiler isn't sure if
he will try to watch. Isn't sure if he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole town is going crazy,'' he said. ``I really feel
kind of alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 0907EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
