<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-BUDGE-BOS &LR;      01-27 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BUDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE PUT THE GRAND INTO SLAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was John Donald Budge on the birth certificate but became
known across the globe as Mr. Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   A congenial, willowy 6-foot-1-inch son of a Scottish immigrant,
reared in a modest Oakland family, Don Budge would feel the
grateful rain of a 1937 ticker-tape parade in New York, saluting
him for rescuing the Davis Cup and bringing it home to America
after a decade abroad in French and English possession.
</P>
<P>
   Few champions at tennis or anything else were as lionized as he,
and the following year he set out to do the undone: winning the
four major championships, Australian, French, Wimbledon and US,
within a calendar year. He put together the quintessential
quadrilateral that would be entitled the Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Budge, who shook their hands to congratulate merely four others
successfully following his extraordinarily challenging route, died
Thursday of cardiac arrest in Scranton, Pa. He was 84. Budge was
seriously injured Dec. 14 in northeastern Pennsylvania when he
apparently lost control of the car he was driving and it went off
the road. He was hospitalized in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., until Jan. 8,
when he was transferred to a nursing home in Scranton.
</P>
<P>
   Budge dined out a long time on his Grand Slam, later emulated by
Maureen Connolly in 1953, Rod Laver in 1962 and 1969, Margaret
Smith Court in 1970, and Steffi Graf in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Budge's oft-repeated line whenever he was honored: ``I'm glad to
be here today. I'm glad to be anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He was everywhere during an amateur and pro career that spanned
20 years and left him remembered as a giant, listed on every
all-time top 10 list published. As a self-effacing righthander with
all the shots in his grasp, he was particularly fearsome with a
booming backhand that stands as an historic superweapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That damn backhand down the line broke my back,'' lauded
Ellsworth Vines, a fellow member of the International Tennis Hall
of Fame whom Budge supplanted as the pro boss in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Immaculate in flaming strokemaking and appearance, his bright
red hair crowning a limber form draped in tailored flannel
trousers, Budge made the US top 10 at No. 9 in 1934. He was 19, on
his way to world No. 1 three years later. He might have gotten
there in 1936 had he been able to cash either of his match points
against Fred Perry in the US final. But after that, as Perry joined
the pro tour, the globe was Don's tennis ball for five sensational
years. He ruled the amateurs in 1937-38, then the pro odyssey of
one-nighters for the next three years until World War II shut down
international tennis.
</P>
<P>
   A shoulder injury suffered on Air Force duty reduced his
effectiveness after the war. Though he narrowly relinquished his
pro crown to Bobby Riggs, 23-21, in a coast-to-coast head-to-head
series, Budge remained an attraction, winning the US Pro tournament
twice, losing the final four times, the last at age 38 to Pancho
Gonzalez in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the last six majors he entered, starting with Wimbledon
'37, Budge seemed left with no new worlds to conquer after the
brilliant 1937 campaign that included his most renowned victory.
Budge's stirring five-set revival against German Gottfried von
Cramm, 6-8, 5-7, 6-4, 6-2, 8-6, on Wimbledon's Centre Court assured
the US of prying loose the Davis Cup that the French seized in
America in 1927, and the British had held since 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Budge had beaten the stylish nobleman, Baron von Cramm, for the
Wimbledon title on the same lawn only two weeks before in straight
sets. But von Cramm, playing for the fatherland was renewed (even
though he detested the Nazi dictator, Hitler, and refused to join
the party).
</P>
<P>
   Budge liked to revisit that day. ``Henner Henkel beat Bitsy
Grant to make it 2-2, and as Gottfried and I were leaving the
dressing room, heading for the court for the deciding match, he was
called to the phone. All I could hear him saying was, `Jah, mein
fuhrer . . . jah, mein fuhrer . . .' He said it was Hitler.
Probably ordering him to win. Gottfried was pale, serious. He
played as if his life depended on it, and got a great start.''
</P>
<P>
   Don caught him at 2-sets-all, but von Cramm spurted ahead again,
4-1 in the fifth. Gene Mako, Budge's good friend and cannily
supportive doubles partner (they won US titles at Longwood in 1936
and 1938), remembers the afternoon well. ``A wonderful match. Of
course Don was in trouble at 1-4. But it was one break and I felt
he'd do it. Don was so stubborn in everything he did, and it
usually paid off in competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Budge caught up again to 4-4, cracked von Cramm's serve to 7-6,
but couldn't serve it out through an electrifying passage. The
German erased five match points as the neutral crowd went bonkers.
On the sixth, Budge related, ``I never saw it. Gottfried hit a
sharply-angled crosscourt forehand, and I tore after it. I threw
myself at the ball and landed on my face. But I could tell from the
crowd that I'd hit a winner. That really meant the Cup because both
we and the Germans were favored over the holder, Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, back on Centre, Budge &AMP; Co. made it official,
4-1 over the home team. A Budge-von Cramm rematch at Forest Hills
resulted in Don's first US singles title. He was voted athlete of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   And another conquest formed in his mind. ``I was the best
player, but I needed a goal, an incentive for one more amateur
year. I decided to try to win the big four titles. Nobody had done
it in one year, although Jack Crawford came close in '33, losing
the US final after winning the Australian, French and Wimbledon.
The only person I told was Mako. I didn't want the pressure that
would come from announcing it ahead of time.''
</P>
<P>
   His 1938 was relatively short since amateur tennis in those
pre-open times was primarily a summer diversion. Budge won six of
eight tournaments, 43 of 45 matches including those over Aussies
John Bromwich and Adrian Quist as the US kept the Cup. Only after
winning the US again did his two-year streak of 14 tournaments and
92 matches end at the hands of Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Mako says, ``I saw all his matches and nobody came close _
including me in the last one at Forest Hills, although I won one of
the four sets he lost. But it wasn't called a Grand Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That came later,'' Budge said. ``Allison Danzig, the New York
Times writer, picked up on a phrase used by their columnist John
Kieran, when Crawford was trying to make it. Kieran said it would
be like a grand slam in bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Mako feels Budge's ``greatness stemmed from the fact that he
took the ball so early and hit it so hard. Opponents were always
back on their heels from his groundstrokes or potent serve. Don't
forget he's the only man to score three major triples _ singles,
doubles and mixed _ Wimbledon in '37-38, the US in '38.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically it was another car crash that Budge felt ``luckiest''
about. ``Just before departing for Australia in '38,'' he recalled,
``I fell asleep at the wheel, went into a culvert and totaled my
Packard. It rolled over several times. When they got me out I had
only slightly sprained my wrists. I was lucky not to be killed.
There was nearly no Grand Slam before it even started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
