<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-0130-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: JUST WHO IS AT THE U.N. HELM(S)?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 30
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Imagine the fire storm that would occur if a
hard-line member of the Russian Duma, where the communists control
160 of 450 seats, were to come before the U.N. Security Council to
denounce the United States and extol the virtues of the former
Stalin era.
</P>
<P>
   No such great outcry was heard the other day after a hard-line
member of the U.S. Senate, where the Republicans control 55 of 100
seats, denounced the United Nations to its face and extolled the
virtues of the former Reagan era.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Helms' highly confrontational debut before the Security
Council raised two issues.
</P>
<P>
   One: did the novel bid to the chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee to play U.N. diplomat for a day muddle a
constitutional system that puts foreign policy burdens squarely in
presidential hands? Two: did what the North Carolina senator have
to say in that planetary chamber make any sense?
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke used his month-long leverage
as the council's rotating president to prepare the way for Helms'
unique diplomatic perch. While Holbrooke dreams of one day
succeeding Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, he knows that, no
matter what, the Senate will probably remain in Republican hands
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by several key Democratic senators, Albright was obliged
to take the same chair as Helms had sat in a week earlier to
respond to his sweeping attack. ``So let me be clear,'' she said.
``Only the president and the executive branch can speak for the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that once again the Clinton administration has
been caught trying to have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   In his unprecedented turn at bat, Helms scored brownie points
when he noted that the United States _ branded by many in that
chamber as a deadbeat bent on bankrupting the world body _ had
funneled $1.4 billion in 1999 to the U.N., plus another $8.8
billion in Pentagon funds ``to support various U.N. resolutions and
peacekeeping operations around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Helms went over the top when he raised his main beef:
Americans, as he put it, see ``the United Nations aspiring to
establish itself the central authority of a new international order
of global laws and global governance.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, judging by the talk show circuit, which Helms once
rode, the senator enjoys some company in harboring such beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   An unbeliever is Britain's Sir Jeremy Greenstock, who reminded
the crusty Helms that ``the United Nations is not a separate organ
to which we turn, like a fire service.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the ambassador added, ``it is the member states, and the
United States owns 25 percent of the power and the resources of the
United Nations. What it does well, the U.S. gets credit for. What
it does badly, the U.S. must bear some responsibility for.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke had done well in arranging for a picture-taking
session for Helms and his family with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan. But the extraordinary event that followed the snapshots
turned out badly as yet another ordinary embarrassment for the
Clinton White House and its befuddled diplomatic minions.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
