<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN30-COX     01-27 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Iowa's religious right 53, Bush 41
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The religious right was declared politically dead last year but
_ the mummy walks!
</P>
<P>
   That was the news from the Iowa caucuses, not the fact that
Republican front-runner George W. Bush and Democratic front-runner
Al Gore ran in front.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Iowa plurality was solid, but even so he lost to his
party's cultural and religious right. Steve Forbes's 30 percent,
Alan Keyes's 14 and Gary Bauer's 9 added up to 53 percent to Bush's
41.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, the former head of the Family Research Council, came to
the campaign straight from the family-values right.
Hellfire-and-brimstone Keyes is more preacher than politician.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes broke into presidential politics four years ago with a
bottomless checkbook and a faddish pitch for a flat income tax. But
where he pooh-poohed abortion as an issue last time, this time he
has worked the anti-abortion fence line hardest. His flat tax has
gone the way of other aging panaceas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign is in no big numbers trouble from Iowa. His
immediate, and serious, challenge is from maverick John McCain in
New Hampshire. But Iowa gives Bush a potentially major political
headache for the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a la Bob Dole in '96, the putative GOP nominee has
to prove himself to his party's rightward fringe before then
turning to general-election voters and trying to convince them he's
not a captive of the very forces he has just been kowtowing to.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to happen this way.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to outfit Bush with pre-emptive money, gather the
party's establishment to him early and persuade activist
conservatives that any conservative Republican president _ and Bush
would be one, despite occasional moderate gestures _ is preferable
to any archconservative Republican loser.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then could skip the ideological issues that are fingernails
on a blackboard to middle-ground voters.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario was abetted by an organizational slump in the
religious right. The animating Christian Coalition lost its boy
wonder, Ralph Reed, to private political consulting. The outfit
lapsed to televangelist Pat Robertson, who promptly made a hash of
it and into the bargain has bought into Bush's go-with-a-winner
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But like his father before him, this Bush, too, has never been
quite trusted by the most adamant cultural and religious
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's outcome signals that that's especially so at the
grassroots, even though Bush first swore by Jesus and then, late in
Iowa, emphasized his anti-abortion militance, even to the point of
stopping just a rhetorical hair short of promising to appoint
Supreme Court justices who would overturn Roe v. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural and religious right voters are generally accounted 20
percent of the national GOP electorate, as much as 40 percent of
the Iowa GOP. The outsized right-wing muster for the most
ideological candidates in Iowa's caucuses suggests Bush has not
fully convinced the religious and cultural right of his bona fides,
at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
