<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Elian Gonzalez and the Cuban kaleidoscope
 &HT;    (For immediate release.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ While you were enthralled (or revolted) by the Elian
Gonzalez circus, a comparable news item drew scant attention. It
was out of Havana and happened on the very day that Elian's
grandmothers flew back to Miami for a meeting with the 6-year-old
pawn of a 41-year-old Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Havana ``detained'' four opposition figures for
several hours before releasing them with a warning against trying
to form a movement. About 18 persons were supposed to meet at a
Havana home with the intent of organizing. The arrests pre-empted
the meeting and were another indication of Fidel Castro's
unwillingness to tolerate any dissent. These were not militant
counter-revolutionaries; they represented, instead, feminists,
laborites and religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across the Florida Straits, one of the grandmothers
was caught trying to slip a cellular phone into the room where she
met with Elian, ostensibly to have the child talk with his father
out of hearing of the Miami relatives, an opportunity not afforded
by the INS mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's people apparently demand free speech in the U.S. but
not in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the Elian ordeal, the two grandmothers _ one dour and
stoic, the other an aggressive shoe pounder _ have become TV
celebrities, given time on the morning network shows and elsewhere
to plead their case. It is not an unjust thing they seek, the
reconciliation between father and son.
</P>
<P>
   But they have been orchestrated, as are the Miami people who
have Elian. The 21-year-old cousin who stays close to Elian and the
Cuban paternal grandmother have perfected the art of weeping on cue
not seen since the last June Allyson film.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is so much about Elian Gonzalez as it is about
politics. I do believe the Cubans involved _ both in the U.S. and
Cuba _ could wage a similar brawl over possession of a cocker
spaniel.
</P>
<P>
   What is real and what is imagined do not matter in this case.
The Miami Cubans, dead set against lifting the economic boycott of
Cuba while electing local, state and national officials solely on
the basis of their anti-Castroism, would have us believe that Cuba
is a place only to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Yet thousands of them return to the island each year, bringing
with them goods and money that, whether they care to admit it or
not, enriches the treasury of the communist state. With a special
dispensation not given to others, our government allows them to
traffic with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   When they go to the island, there is not any of the discord we
see in the Elian Gonzalez proceeding. They have reunions; they hug,
they kiss, they give money, they sit down to dinner together.
</P>
<P>
   This is what is so puzzling about the familial standoff of the
past few days, the negative passions between a family straddling
the straits.
</P>
<P>
   Polls of the American people strongly favor returning the child
to his father, based simply on a law that sets the rules for who
speaks for a minor.
</P>
<P>
   That is the central theme in this case. Strip away the drama,
the chicanery, the tragedy of the situation and what you have is an
ideological struggle: She won't do this, he won't do that,
anti-Castroites are in the house next door, there's a Cuban
Interest Section man hiding in the plane, the nun is anti-embargo,
the nun favors the exiles _ every bit of bilge and drivel possible.
</P>
<P>
   Little Elian could become a U.S. citizen or he could be shipped
back to Cuba. That really won't change anything. The icy
relationship between the U.S. and Cuba will continue because
there's always something to be ``icy'' about.
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to get the feeling that Americans outside of South
Florida really don't care about it anymore. They just want all this
to end _ so we can get on to those charming presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
