<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To the rescue: Saving a mouse bound for my cat's mouth
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My cats have turned into killers, sparked
no doubt by the influence of La Nina, which has turned January here
behind the Pine Curtain into an early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Critters that normally would have hunkered down for the winter
are out in force, giving the cats ample opportunity to bring home
fresh kill nearly every night.
</P>
<P>
   Their fare consists mainly of big bugs and small field mice
caught in the woods next door, the eviscerated carcasses deposited
for our viewing pleasure on the door mat. Every once in a while,
Otto, the 15-pound tomcat, will catch a genuine rat, which causes
considerable consternation, this not being a household overly fond
of rats.
</P>
<P>
   Over the Christmas holidays, with a houseful of children (our
home serves as a central sleepover point for much of the city's
male teen population and a sizable number of the female pre-teens),
Otto slipped in the back door with a rat in his mouth. I was dozing
in the recliner and dreaming about getting the correct final answer
on ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' when there arose such a
clatter, as the Christmas poem goes.
</P>
<P>
   Children were whooping, hollering, and standing on chairs as
Otto looked for a place to light and enjoy some rodent tartare.
Luckily I was able to herd him out of the house, rat still clamped
between his jaws. Since then, both cats get a thorough inspection
to make sure there isn't an animal between their whiskers before
being allowed back inside.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, Otto deposited his kill on the mat in the garage,
and I stepped square on it in my stocking feet while leaving for a
dinner with some company colleagues. Talk about doing some fast
high-stepping. There is nothing like stepping on a dead rat to ruin
one's appetite. I don't leave my shoes in the garage anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The cats usually kill field mice, which don't harm anything and
don't deserve to die, but you can't stop a cat from trying to kill
a mouse or a bird, so I put up with it, grateful that odds are
great no pink-tailed little rodent will ever attempt to take up
residence inside the house with the killer cats on the prowl.
</P>
<P>
   That's before I read ``The Green Mile'' by Stephen King last
week. The film version just came out, which means I'll get to see
it in a year or so when it goes to video. The book is about an
extraordinary man on Death Row, the guards who eventually come to
admire and respect him _ and a little mouse called Mr. Jingles. Mr.
Jingles becomes the pet of one of the condemned prisoners and
learns to fetch and do other dog-type tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Without revealing the plot for those who plan to see the movie
or read the book, Mr. Jingles is a pretty special mouse. I finished
reading the book while sitting on the back porch the other night.
Not long after, Kiki, the Siamese step-cat, showed up, playing
Great White Hunter, stalking something in the grass, batting it
around, letting it loose, then starting all over. You know, cat
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, it was a tiny field mouse who managed to get free
from Kiki, a cat that is, shall we say, developmentally challenged
and bred a tad too fine somewhere down the line. The mouse
scampered onto the porch and hid in the corner while Kiki looked
unsuccessfully some 10 feet away in the rose bushes. Kiki would
starve if it wasn't for a bowl of Little Friskies each day.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about Mr. Jingles, rolling his spool with his nose
back to the prisoner, warming the hearts of men previously thought
to have no hearts. While the step-cat continued to flail around in
the roses, I grabbed a pair of gloves and tried to catch the mouse,
which was about the size of a hairball.
</P>
<P>
   Fast, though. Unaware of my intentions, the mouse darted this
way and that, until settling in under the barbecue pit where I
couldn't reach him. By this time, Otto had shown up, which means
the mouse's minutes were numbered. Otto is a big, fast cat, who
survived on the streets for several years until taking up with me.
This Mr. Jingles lookalike would be no more than an hors d'oeuvre
for Otto.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse kept squeaking, barely audible to me but music to
Otto's ears. Kiki, of course, was still searching in the rose
bushes. Finally, the mouse made a desperate dash for the back yard
and freedom, and I made a lucky snag, grabbing up the mouse in a
leather-enclosed hand. Otto sniffed and walked off, Kiki looked
confused, and I took the mouse back to the woods and set it free.
He squeaked as I tossed him into the brush as if to say, ``Thanks,
buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   That was my good deed for the day, saving a mouse. Let's hope he
doesn't tell his larger brethren about the kind-hearted fool in the
brick house next to the woods. I won't be so tolerant of rats.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
