<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A sight for sore eyes
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ There's a TV commercial that's asks the
question, ``What would the you of 20 years ago think of the you of
today?'' Although the commercial is designed to sell a sporty car,
I think the me of 1980 would have more pressing issues to discuss
than what kind of car I'm driving today.
</P>
<P>
   If the 25-year-old me ran into the 45-year-old me, it might go
something like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Lord, I didn't know we could put on so much weight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Has Grecian Formula been outlawed?''
</P>
<P>
   ``At least our eyes have held up, I see we're not wearing
bifocals yet.''
</P>
<P>
   While the extra pounds and a bit more salt among the pepper are
things I could do something about if I had the mind to, I've always
considered bifocals as the unavoidable sign of aging. But what the
younger me wouldn't know is that in the past 20 years, there have
been great strides in the field of vision. Today, instead of old
fashioned bifocals, I wear new fashioned multifocus lenses.
Invisible to the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   I've worn glasses since the seventh grade, but up until about
five years ago, my eyesight had changed little. Almost to the
minute I blew out the candles on my 40th birthday cake, my eyes _
blinded by the light _ have never been the same.
</P>
<P>
   I was visiting the other day with a friend I've known almost my
entire life, who also has made the leap to secret bifocals and we
were comparing notes on how we had adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of taking her glasses off to read, my friend merely
has to tilt her head back like a bird taking a drink to see
clearly. And walking has become a new experience what with the
ground now a fuzzy haze.
</P>
<P>
   Someone said it is not the prospect of death that we can't deal
with. We all know we're going to die. It's growing old that comes
as a shock.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen the future and it is blurry.
</P>
<P>
   So even though the 2000 model of me has some miles on the
odometer, the younger me would no doubt be impressed with the car
I'm driving. It's a sporty red convertible designed to draw
attention away from the heavy, gray, visually impaired driver.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
