<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN28-COX     01-27 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hutchison challenger faces tough road
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For Republican true believers, Kay Bailey
Hutchison's U.S. Senate re-election race this year could be called
Snow White and the Five Dwarfs.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-year incumbent Hutchison, a favorite of the oil-and-gas
crowd, started the year with $6 million in the bank and the ability
to bring in additional money gushers if needed.
</P>
<P>
   The five angling for the Democratic nomination are perennial but
never-successful candidate Gene Kelly _ not the movie dancer _ of
Universal City; H. Gerald Bintliff, a retired American Airlines
clerk from Leonard, northeast of Dallas; Don Clark, a business
manager from Mesquite; Bobby Wightman-Cervantes, a Dallas lawyer
who sought office unsuccessfully as a Republican; and former state
Rep. Charles Gandy of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Because the only one who has held office is Gandy _ who jokes
that he may call himself Charles ``Fred Astaire'' Gandy after
another movie dancer _ we asked why he'd sign up for what seems a
suicide mission against Hutchison and her cash.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, Gandy said. The money she's attracted from special
interests made him feel he couldn't just sit on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The influence of money on politics today has created a corrupt
system that I think needs to be changed, and I don't think Kay
Bailey Hutchison is going to do anything to change it,'' Gandy
said. ``I'm sure Mrs. Hutchison is a fine individual. But if she
spent every day last year raising money, she had to raise $16,000 a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   That's time not spent dealing with health care, urban gridlock
and other problems, Gandy said. If elected, he'd vote for the
McCain-Feingold bill to cut down on special-interest
money.Hutchison opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy, 41, who said he makes a passable middle-class income as a
``livable communities consultant,'' was elected to the Texas House
of Representatives in 1982 from Mesquite.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it didn't last long. In 1984, Gandy was un-elected _
defeated by Republican Bill Blackwood during the Ronald Reagan
re-election landslide that beset several Dallas County Democrats
that year.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy's proudest legislative accomplishment was sponsoring
passage of child safety-seat legislation. But his former colleagues
remember him best as the guy who took the rap for arranging a
Strip-O-Gram just outside the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy, 22 at the time, and several other colleagues chipped in
to help observe the birthday of Rep. David Patronella (D-Houston).
Patronella was slammed into a chair set outside the chamber where
the lobbyists gather. Then the stripper appeared, turned on her
boombox and got to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charley says she was just supposed to take off her gloves,''
said one former state representative, who would only discuss the
event if his name was withheld.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't stop there at all. She took her dress off. She had
on thong underwear and a bra, and she took her bra off _ just as 60
senior citizens came down the staircase. The pictures went out on
the AP wire. I think our approval rating went to an all-time low.''
</P>
<P>
   Gandy admits it wasn't the finest beginning for a freshman
legislator _ and says if he had it to over again, he wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   So, Gandy got to start a new career. He consults with cities in
several states, helping to find ways to reduce gridlock, to create
communities ``that are healthy for raising kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cities, Gandy said, ``there are traffic jams around
every elementary school because parents are afraid'' to let their
children walk or bike to school.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy, who was director of advocacy programs for the Bicycle
Federation of America, helped push successful efforts to get a
percentage of federal and state transportation money earmarked for
bicycle and pedestrian paths, rail and other means of reducing
traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a very popular program around the state with
mayors and county officials and legislators,'' Gandy said.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy also had the idea years ago to hold a North vs. South
Austin tug-of-war, spanning Town Lake, to raise money for a youth
hostel. With the help of Austin American-Statesman columnist John
Kelso and others, it raised $20,000, Gandy said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to use the Internet and e-mail, plus travel the state
and meet real people _ ``a combination of high-tech and
high-touch,'' Gandy said. A few days after announcing Jan. 1, Gandy
said he'd already contacted 20,000 people through the Internet and
raised more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has vacuumed up the special-interest money,'' Gandy said
of Hutchison. ``The money I'm getting is from people who think the
system is corrupt and needs to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison doesn't seem worried.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
