<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One way to empathy is to see others at lower altitudes
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``You have the same profile today as when you were
tiny,'' my wife said the other day to our 17-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   She's right, and was expressing something that occurs to most
parents as they realize their children have sprung skyward.
</P>
<P>
   He does have the same profile: That abrupt chin. That
beginner's-slope nose. That all-business brow. Truly, it is a face
unchanged, though everything else has changed. That once-squat
torso is long and rubberized. Those long legs _ from where did they
spring?
</P>
<P>
   The legs are what really distort. Take them away and he's still
a little boy. Any parent of a teen does this deconstruction on a
regular basis. We take away those legs to remind ourselves our
child is still a youngster, a kid in a mostly grown-up body.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally you tense up to see a stranger _ a fidgeting body
of maybe 6 feet in height. Then follow the bean pole to the top and
see a most childlike head. Take away the legs and you've got a
fourth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   When you do that _ when you subtract the long legs _ you
immediately are inclined to ease up, give the child a degree of
slack for being childish.
</P>
<P>
   We all get angry at little children. But it's hard to be angry
at them for long. I've been visiting grade-schoolers for many years
at a local school. I can honestly say that of those children, a
couple hundred of them at least, only three or four fried my bacon.
Only three or four would have me tensed-up to see on the street or
approaching them with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   That's because I viewed them all as they were _ children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons why we have loyalty to next-of-kin or
longtime friends, even when they do something stupid, yes even
illegal, is that we ``knew them when.'' We've known them from a
vantage point others don't possess.
</P>
<P>
   That element of human nature ought to help us perceive strangers
or potential combatants. The fact is, seeing people with empathy is
nothing more than a simple math exercise: Subtract legs.
</P>
<P>
   This in mind, returning back to work from a recent school visit,
I tried the equation on what could have been an annoyance. A truck
driver was walking across to his rig on the road I was traveling,
walking much more slowly than the prudent person would do as
vehicles came upon him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of blasting him with the horn or ruffling his pate with
my chrome, I imagined him with grade-schooler legs, and saw a kid
crossing the street. It was easy. And it worked. I eased off.
</P>
<P>
   It would work in all sorts of situations.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that empathy of this sort doesn't always work.
Sometimes it can't work. That's particularly the case when people
in authority are acting like children _ like Rep. Bob Barr or Rep.
Tom DeLay when they are chasing the president with sticks and Silly
String, or like the president when he's caught chasing ...
</P>
<P>
   When one lowers one's self voluntarily, it's hard for a
bystander to lower that person any further for empathy's sake.
(``Not a leg to stand on.'') Taking the legs from that already
lowered authority figure reduces him to a head of hair scurrying
along the ground, an object of empathy, maybe, to a squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, though, the formula of seeing someone,
particularly a stranger or a teen, as the child he or she once was
is a great way to attain a sense of commonality. This particularly
ought to get one past prejudices against people of different colors
and different faiths. They were all children once. Like you.
</P>
<P>
   I'll forgive my boys for a lot not just because they're my own
but because I've watched them grow, because we've been through a
lot together, because we share so much. In essence that should hold
for all in the family of man
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
