<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONEYMOONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traveling abroad or close to home key honeymoon choice
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ For young couples these days, taking the plunge
can mean more than getting hitched. The trend of newlyweds
incorporating adventure and experience into their honeymoons could
even include taking a spin in a real-life submarine for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a submarine coming out that will let couples stay
under water for a couple of days at a time,'' said Lori Seto,
travel editor for The Knot, a New York-based wedding planning
company. ``I think it will be popular because it's such a unique
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   While a trip to the underwater world isn't for everyone, many
couples these days want to go on educational or experience-based
honeymoons, travel industry experts say. Some couples are choosing
to stay at five-star hotels that also offer culinary classes hosted
by the hotel's chefs. Others are taking yearlong backpacking trips
through Thailand or taking monthlong safari tours of the African
Serengeti.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the picture of people sitting on the beach all week is
not what everyone wants,'' Seto said. ``With all these
opportunities out there people are going further and packing more
in.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, for those newlyweds who can afford the cost
of flying half-way around the world and who have the time. Those
restraints and the desire many couples have to keep things simple
have created a wide variety of honeymoon trips.
</P>
<P>
   And even for some who can afford more exotic trips, traveling to
a secluded place with few side attractions is still popular, travel
agents say. Quiet romance still takes top priority for many
newlyweds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who take shorter trips down to the
Gulf of Mexico to South Padre, Galveston, New Orleans or other
spots along the coast,'' said Kathy Babitzke of Waco-based The
Travel Planet. ``For most honeymooners, they aren't interested in
side trips. What they want is a nice place to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   10 DAYS AND $3,500
</P>
<P>
   The average honeymoon these days lasts about 10 days and costs
$3,500, but travel experts say you can cut back as needed and make
your post-wedding vacation enjoyable and economical. Popular
destinations include places like Las Vegas, Disney World in Florida
and Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   But the most popular trips, and many times the most economical,
are the all-inclusive getaways to places like Cancun and Cozumel,
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're on a budget, this is a great way to go because you
don't have to worry about how much food or beverages cost,'' said
Tracey Dean, owner of Welcome Aboard Travel in Prior, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   A four-night trip to Cozumel from Dallas is $776 per person. A
seven-night stay is $1,100 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Playa del Carman, a secluded area south of Cancun, has become
popular for couples who want to get away from crowds of people.
Another popular spot is Hawaii, which has breathtaking views of
mountainous landscapes and plenty of activities for those who want
to add some adventure to their honeymoons. A 7-day trip to Hawaii
for two, including airfare and hotel but no drinks or food, runs
about $2,500, travel agents said.
</P>
<P>
   All-inclusive trips can really mean all-inclusive, as many
cruise lines are finding out. In 1999, Carnival, one of the largest
cruise lines in the world, averaged almost six weddings a day
aboard its 14 ships. Royal Caribbean International performed close
to three weddings a day aboard its 11 ships.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the ships also are catering to older couples who have
children from previous relationships. Seto said many ships and
resorts have honeymoon packages that let the newlyweds have private
time while the youngsters are entertained in sports activities and
day care.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of couples these days are on their second or third
marriage and already have children,'' she said. ``They want to
bring the kids along but there have to be things for them to do.
The industry has begun to accommodate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents say the best way to have a good honeymoon is to
plan ahead. Once couples have decided when they're getting married,
then they can begin deciding what would be the best honeymoon
package. Soon-to-be newlyweds also should look at their finances,
how much time they have and what type of vacation would best suit
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a couple is having a huge wedding where they're stressed
out and dealing with all kinds of things they may want to go
somewhere laid-back,'' Seto said. ``They may not want to go to a
place where they don't know the language or have to meet a daily
sight-seeing schedule. You have to know yourself and pick somewhere
that's going to the most enjoyable for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Budgets many times are the biggest determining factors in where
newlyweds go and how long they stay. Wedding planners say
stretching honeymoon dollars often is about priorities. A thousand
dollars a person can get you out of the country to a nice resort
with little fanfare and added features, like horseback riding or
scuba diving. Or a couple can stay close to home and put most of
the money into staying at a five-star hotel, complete with fine
cuisine and bottles of exotic champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can spend it all on where you go,'' Seto said, ``or how
nice of place you stay. It's up to the couple.''
</P>
<P>
   And it does matter what time of year you're getting married. A
wedding in the fall is fine, but vacationing in the Bahamas or
other islands in the Atlantic can be risky that time of year,
because fall is hurricane season. Prices come down during this time
_ September, October, November and early December _ but travel
agents say it probably isn't worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
