<HEADER>
A8019 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-VEGAS28-COX     01-27 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VEGAS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In new Vegas, gambling isn't everything
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In the new Las Vegas, showgirls and mobsters are
out. Artists and acrobats are in. Mom, dad and the kids on a budget
are out. Conventioneers on corporate expense accounts are in.
Streetwalkers are out. Escorts are in.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs and trendy restaurants are on hotel marquees, not big
names playing big rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In the new Las Vegas, it's easier to find a coffee bar than a
liquor bar.
</P>
<P>
   Caesars Palace has a Zen meditation room and a replica of a
famous Buddhist landmark, Thailand's Brahma Shrine.
</P>
<P>
   The sidewalk in front of the Bellagio resort's fake, eight-acre
Lake Como is packed for operatic water-fountain shows.
</P>
<P>
   If bloated Elvis were alive in the new Vegas, he'd be a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Vegas is now an adult theme park with long walks, long lines,
high prices and gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bellagio hotel, tourists line up, 12 bucks in hand, to
see 25 paintings by masters including Monet, Matisse and Miro.
</P>
<P>
   At the Venetian hotel, a gondola takes tourists through a mall
on a romantic ride past Brookstone and Banana Republic for $10.
</P>
<P>
   At the Paris Las Vegas hotel, a trip to the top of the fake,
50-story Eiffel Tower is $8.
</P>
<P>
   The Vegas Strip, this planet's most neon-drenched street, offers
moving sidewalks, escalators and trams connecting monster,
3,000-room hotel-cities _ four new ones in the past two years _
that re-invent Vegas' tradition of themed hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all oriented around money,'' says Larry Mullen, a
professor at the University of Nevada Las Vegas. ``The hotel
occupancy rates have to be 90 percent or above or they get nervous.
But they somehow manage to maintain that. It's one-upmanship. `I
can build a bigger and better and more interesting, more glitzy and
glamorous whatever to attract people and get them to stay at my
hotel.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They're already talking about the Mirage. It's been up about
10 years, and they need to reinvent that,'' says Mullen, who's
working on a project that chronicles history and changes in Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Wynn is kinda the brains and economic brawn behind the
mega-resort, theme-park ideas here,'' concludes Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn started the monster hotel frenzy when he opened the
3,044-room Mirage in November 1989. The son of a bingo supplies
salesman spent $620 million to build the Mirage and its
fire-spewing volcano, lobby rain forest and 20,000-gallon aquarium
with sharks. Wynn again upped the stakes last year with his
Bellagio resort.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn's lust to attract the gold-credit-card crowd is starting to
pay off. His Picasso at Bellagio and Renoir at the Mirage are the
first Vegas restaurants to win Mobil five-star restaurant ratings.
(The Four Seasons is the only top-rated hotel in Vegas, having
earned the American Automobile Association's five-diamond rating.
The Four Seasons' 424 rooms and suites, $200 to $3,900, occupy
floors 35-39 of Mandalay Bay.)
</P>
<P>
   Pick your theme and book a room: Italy (Bellagio, Venetian),
France (Paris Las Vegas), pirates (Treasure Island), ancient Egypt
(Luxor), medieval (Excalibur), wild animals (MGM Grand), Roman
Empire (Caesars), rock music (Hard Rock Hotel/Casino), tropical
islands (Mandalay Bay, the Mirage), Mardi Gras (Flamingo), NYC (New
York, New York). And this summer, add an Arabian theme at the new
$1.3 billion Aladdin.
</P>
<P>
   In the new Las Vegas, change comes down to this: Guys in shiny
suits with pinky rings and rap sheets who answered to families have
been replaced by corporate bottom-liners in Armani who answer to
stockholders. Vegas abandoned the early '90s marketing drive to
attract families. The amusement park MGM built behind its hotel is
closed and being downsized. At Bellagio, a guard stops anyone with
children and allows the kids through only if they're registered
guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis now is going after the convention business,''
explains author Andres Martinez, whose new book, 24/7 chronicles a
monthlong gambling marathon in the new Vegas. ``Some of these
resorts now make more money on stuff other than their casino, which
would have been sort of heresy in the good ol' Vegas of the '50s
when they would give away everything to suck people into the casino
_ cheap buffets, cheap rooms, free drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now at new resorts like Bellagio and Venetian, you can
spend $200, $300 a night if you're there for a convention,'' says
the former Wall Street Journal reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've very wisely become what I like to call a
permanent World's Fair,'' says Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   While shows in Vegas have never been a bargain, today you pay
premium prices for big, bigger, biggest. Half-nude showgirls are
for nostalgia freaks.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest ticket _ $100 _ is for Cirque du Soleil's aquatic
acrobats in O. Siegfried, Roy and their tigers have a money-making
show and upscale zoo called Secret Garden at The Mirage. The MGM
Grand's big show, EFX, is advertised this way: ``250 special
effects, 70 singers, dancers, aerialists, 450 costumes, 6,000
lights, 85,000 watts of stereo sound and Tommy Tune.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rat Pack _ Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Sammy Davis Jr.,
Peter Lawford, Joey Bishop _ that defined Sin City for decades is
now a lounge nostalgia act of impersonators produced by David
Cassidy.
</P>
<P>
   People no longer go to Vegas just to gamble. They go to shop:
Vuitton, Gucci, Dior, Tiffany, Chanel. And eat: China Grill, Le
Cirque &AMP; Osteria del Circo, Picasso, Wolfgang Puck's and Emeril's.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 report by the Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority
showed that for the first time, dining, shopping and entertainment
surpassed gambling as a lure for tourists. But that doesn't mean
gambling is being diminished as Vegas' No. 1 money-maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the big corporate players there, they like having
revenue streams that are more predictable than casinos,'' explains
Martinez. ``That's why there's a renewed emphasis on slot machines
_ because those are predictable. You're not ever going to have any
nasty surprises on your bottom line at the slots because those
things pay only a certain amount.''
</P>
<P>
   As Martinez details in his book, serious gamblers still get free
meals, rooms and even airfare. But it's more like collecting
frequent-flier miles than being a familiar face. Swipe cards
electronically keep track of how much gamblers wager, which earns
them comps.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just gambling that makes Vegas an over-21 town.
</P>
<P>
   You can't walk anywhere on the Strip day or night without being
offered a variety of sex magazines and cards selling escort
services that cops say are fronts for prostitution. And in the new
Vegas, even that business has changed. Besides the sidewalk
handouts, you can now use the Internet to do escort-service
business.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the new Vegas seems to upset civic and casino
pioneers, says Mullen at UNLV. ``The old-timers think it's just Las
Vegas, and there's no place like it. They'd have it no other way.''
</P>
<P>
   In this city that delights in making spectacles of blowing up
old hotels to build bigger ones, there's at least Old Las Vegas
downtown on Fremont Street marked by the famous neon sign of cowboy
Vegas Vic. Downtown draws small-time, old-time gamblers and
tourists who don't mind cramped casinos where you can still get a
99-cent shrimp cocktail, $6.99 prime rib dinner or play penny slot
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Mullen has lived in Vegas six years. His report is due
out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what's really struck me is the huge opportunities and
the huge amount of money that flows through this place,'' he says.
``And how quickly it all changes. It's unbelievable, almost
frightening. But that's just Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: paullomartire(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
