r l BC-FASHION-MACKIE28-COX     01-27 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MACKIE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mackie's haute fashion tip: To thine own shape be true
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bob Mackie can work fashion miracles
with tulle, chiffon, bugle beads and pearls.
</P>
<P>
   And though pieces from his romantic spring collection won't
magically endow you with the outlandish style of Cher (whom he has
designed for extensively) or the bodacious bod of Barbie (for whom
he also creates out-of-this-world looks), they can make you feel
pretty darn close to princesslike.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old designer recently visited Saks Fifth Avenue here
to show off shapely Mackie gowns, shake hands with longtime
admirers and sign autographs for Barbie collectors. Before he
greeted fans, we grabbed him for a quick chat in a Saks fitting
room:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Any advice on dressing up if you're used to dressing down?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Evening clothes are fantasy clothes. You can become someone
else for the night. But if you feel like the dress is wearing you,
instead of you wearing the dress, dress closer to the way you would
during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you typically wear jeans and would feel lost in
a ballgown, opt for a cashmere top and beaded pants. You wear suits
to work? Try an elegant pantsuit with a fitted jacket. The key is
to know thyself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women don't know what's best for them and so they try to
dress to please their husbands or their boyfriends, and that often
misfires,'' Mackie says.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget to have some fun: ``You can dress like
Pocohantas or Guinevere or Marie Antoinette!'' (Or Queen Elizabeth
I _ that was Mackie who transformed Whoopi Goldberg into the Virgin
Queen at last year's Academy Awards.)
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who have been your favorite women to dress?
</P>
<P>
   A. Different ones for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mitzi Gaynor because she was his first client and she loved
colorful, theatrical clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Burnett because he did such a variety of work on her
variety show, ``which is tricky _ dressing someone to get a
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Cher and Diana Ross ``because they're amazing. You can let your
fantasies go.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will you design Cher's Grammy get-up next month?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``I don't know. She could show up in torn jeans and a beaded
shirt _ you never know with her. She always waits till the last
possible minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is real, old-school Hollywood glamour gone for good?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``The work I used to do doesn't happen anymore _ movie
musicals, variety shows ...'' (A seven-time Emmy winner, Mackie
received Oscar nominations for his costumes in ``Lady Sings the
Blues,'' ``Funny Lady'' and ``Pennies from Heaven.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Mackie has no trouble keeping busy. In addition to his
ready-to-wear collections and highly collectible Barbie work, his
signature is on eyewear and fragrances, and his home-furnishings
division will expand to include bed and bath products this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Mackie name on sofas, lamps and rugs? ``People are spending
more money on their homes than on their backs,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What were the most heinous fashion don'ts of the last
century?
</P>
<P>
   A. Stretch pants forced to stretch too much, leggings on overly
large legs, and micro-minis that left absolutely nothing to
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   As for today, Mackie doesn't care for the way so many women and
teen-age girls bare their often squishy stomachs with cropped tops
and low-slung pants. ``It's so unattractive.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what it boils down to: ``Anytime something is really
extreme and the wrong people are wearing it, it's a don't.... It's
like they say, `What's the best accessory a woman can have? A
three-way mirror.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
