<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8024 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-STYLE-MAKEUPSALON28-C     01-27 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-MAKEUPSALON28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salons try to offer women one-stop shopping
 &HT;    (EDs: This story is not for use by NYTNS clients)
 &HT;    By Sheryll Poe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ No longer content with just cutting and styling
hair, salons are branching out _ trying to be everything to every
customer.
</P>
<P>
   The cosmetic and beauty industry racked up more than $40 billion
in U.S. sales in 1998. Salons are looking to expand their markets _
selling everything from pantyhose and shampoos to home furnishings
and coffee table fountains.
</P>
<P>
   Just think of these stores as the Home Depots of the beauty
industry. Smooth, light wood counters, bright lighting, fresh
coffee and flowers are backed up by aisle after aisle of shampoos,
hair dryers and bath beads.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new entries into the Austin market is Ulta Salon, an
Illinois-based beauty store and salon. Last fall, Ulta opened three
locations in Austin that feature phone jacks for modems at each
styling station, CNN on a television above a coffee and juice bar,
and fax machines amid aisles of razors and shaving cream, Paul
Mitchell shampoos and Versace makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept is one-stop shopping for women,'' said Ulta
salon manager Lisa Castiglione. ``What we offer is a consistent,
nonintimidating environment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Ulta. Other salons, including Bella and The Beauty
Store, Salon and Spa offer a variety of choices, services and
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are providing a level of service which department stores
are no longer doing and drugstores never did supply,'' said Marlene
Eskin, president of Market View, an Austin-based cosmetic industry
research firm. ``They bridge the gap between drugstores and
department stores.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be a formula for success, with about 100 customers a
day walking through the frosted green glass and brushed stainless
steel doors since Ulta opened. Ulta does not release sales figures,
but industry watchers believe the larger stores, such as the one in
Dallas, could do as much as $7.5 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bella, a popular salon and day spa where clients can indulge in
a ``Day of Beauty'' for $330, opened its Bella Home store six
months ago. The 5,000-square-foot contemporary home furnishings
store carries tables, lamps and couches starting at about $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its massages, facials and cafe, Bella has
expanded its retail product sales, including $40 bottles of
shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want these services because in today's society, people
are stressed out,'' said Bella operations manager Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Beauty Store, which has four locations in Austin, offers
similar products and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can all benefit from the emergence of Ulta,'' said Darryl
Labens, its director of operations. ``Anything that increases
awareness of products will benefit specialty retailers in the long
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Long a bastion of beauty, the cosmetic counters at mall
department stores may not be able to offer the same variety of
products, but they do offer lines that sometimes cannot be found
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our customers are label-conscious,'' said Angie Chase,
a local Chanel counter manager.
</P>
<P>
   Bella, like the department stores, prides itself on the
exclusivity of its product lines. ``I find that customers like the
fact that they aren't going to find our stuff anywhere else,''
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Ulta also gets endorsements from its shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it here,'' said 24-year-old Caren Stearns, pointing to
a lip liner and lipstick display. ``This place is always neat and
clean and you find what you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
