<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-POSTMENOPAUSE     01-27 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-POSTMENOPAUSE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clothing line focuses on post-menopausal women
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Like many women over 50, Alice Boylan noticed the
mirror wasn't being as kind to her silhouette as it had been in the
past. Department store clothing punished her, too.
</P>
<P>
   Her crime? Biology.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all post-menopausal women experience changes in their
body shape, stature and distribution of weight, which can turn a
shopping spree into a frustrating, if not laborious, experience.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Boylan, her granddaughter, a New York-based
fashion designer, was able to make her specially tailored clothes
that fit her proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Hanley has since turned that labor of love into a new
business, Alice B. Inc., a line of clothing named for her
grandmother that uses a specially designed sizing chart to address
the shifts in an aging women's silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   According to Threads magazine, some women's bodies change form
head-to-toe, from reduced height, to narrowing chests, to
protruding abdomens, to flattened seats.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Gibbs, vice president of marketing for Alice B., said most
women _ even those who have always been thin _ can expect to grow a
one-to-three-inch abdominal paunch and to shrink in height about
the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``No manufacturers have taken this into effect,'' she said. ``So
women are forced to wear elastic waistbands or (boxy dress styles)
and don't have anything stylish to wear.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an issue that Linda Dizmon sees many women struggle with.
As women's fashions manager at a local Sears, where about 30
percent of women's clothing shoppers are seniors, Dizmon has
noticed that older women often can't fit into the sizes they once
bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's troubling, and most customers have a good sense
of humor about it or say they are aging gracefully,'' she said.
``But I think that the need is to come up with styles that are
flattering that fit that figure.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the national market research firm NPD Inc., women
over 65 spent $13.2 billion on clothes for themselves in 1998,
about 14 percent of the total dollars spent on women's apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet unlike other specialty sizes _ petites and plus sizes, for
example _ designers have not yet pushed a ``silver size'' concept
into their mainstream lines. Dizmon said some designers, such as
Sag Harbor and Apostrophe, offer tops and bottoms as separates,
allowing women to mix and match different sizes. Others are making
dresses and skirts more midlength for women who don't like short or
long looks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Micki Wagner, assistant area sales manager for the women's
department at a local Dillard's, said some name-brand designers,
such as Liz Claiborne, carry their designs through misses, petites
and plus sizes. So women can match different sizes from different
departments if they need to. Many of the same designers offer
petite clothing in larger sizes to accommodate women's typical
weight gain and height loss as they age, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Alice B.'s ``silver size'' system takes fitting problems a
step further by including features just for aging women's
proportions and lifestyles. Skirts have built-up waistlines with
Velcro fasteners and flat fronts to make abdomens appear flatter,
Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackets usually hit just below the abdomen to give shorter women
a nicer line than longer jackets that cover more of the body, she
said. Blouses allow for aging women's spinal curvature with more
fabric across the back and less across the front. This design
avoids extra fabric from bunching up, which happens when women buy
blouses that are too big.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs said Alice B. clothing also accounts for senior women's
lifestyles. For instance, they are machine-washable and buttons are
in the front to accommodate women who may live alone or cannot
reach around to the back.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Alice B.'s designs are only available by catalog or on
its Web site (www.alicebfitsu.com), but Gibbs said the company will
attempt to introduce them into specialty stores later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes are different in three areas _ fit, function and
fashion _ because those are the most important aspects of aging
women's clothing, Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   One local retailer would add one more word to the list _ fun!
</P>
<P>
   Sally Odegaard, owner of Olga's specialty clothing shop in Waco,
said many clothes can transcend age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really carry `dowdy' things,'' she said. ``My
customers, no matter what their age, want to look pretty, current
and smart.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she often has 35-year-old and 65-year-old customers who
buy the same outfit and wear it differently. One with a flat
stomach might tuck in a T-shirt, she said, while another wears it
out to hide a her tummy. An older woman may wear a black dress with
a jacket, while a younger one would wear it with a scarf.
</P>
<P>
   Odegaard, herself a 57-year-old who enjoys twirling batons and
eating M&AMP;Ms, said seniors' active lifestyles have changed their
perceptions of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little old lady is no longer around,'' Odegaard said.
``She's going to Vegas, and she's wearing a lot of cute things.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Census Bureau reports that senior citizens are the
fastest-growing population group in the country. Does the fashion
industry plan to keep up?
</P>
<P>
   If a recent event by the Fashion Association and Sporting Goods
Manufacturer's Association is any indication, the coming-of-age
baby boomers may be wearing clothing that better fits their bodies
and their lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   TFA and SGMA collaborated last October to present ``Active and
Ageless: Generations of Style'' fashion show. The clothing
presented clothes for ``typical'' American seniors' lifestyles,
including ski outfits, workout wear and cruise attire. Until the
fashion industry weaves that attitude into the threads of its
clothing, Gibbs said, senior women should not feel forced to buy
clothes that don't fit them or their lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them have a hard time with aging, but a majority are
proud of their age, proud of being mature. They know what they
want, and no department store will tell them they need it,'' she
said. ``Women need to go into stores and demand a better sizing
system and better quality garments.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
