<HEADER>
A8026 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-PARTIES28-COX     01-27 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PARTIES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A future world with cybersleaze that feels real
 &HT;    By Lynn Kalber
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Gibson's greatest writing strength _ aside from his
clear, flowing prose _ is his native ability to welcome readers
into a world that mixes the familiar with the incredible, where the
story makes a believably strange kind of sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Tomorrow's Parties'' is a sequel to the well-received
``Idoru.'' Lead characters Rydell, Chevette and Laney are back and
still involved in saving the world _ or worlds _ as they know
it/them.
</P>
<P>
   In a race through Gibson-land both physical and ephemeral, these
three are joined by Buell, a hard-drinking, country-song-singing
good ol' boy; Harwood, a Bill Gates/Donald Trump combo with an ego
to match; Silencio, a boy with a watch fixation; and Fontaine, a
bridge resident who guards the past.
</P>
<P>
   From Japan to San Francisco on land, and through all kinds of
cyberspace, time beats toward a grand finale, as people and things
become intertwined. Looming over all is the Golden Gate Bridge, now
home to hundreds and the place for a high-noon showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The novel's killer also finds the bridge:
</P>
<P>
   ``Above him, beyond the tank traps, lift the ragged, swooping
terraces, the patchwork superstructure in which the bridge is
wrapped. Some aspect of his mood lifts: it is a famous sight, a
tourist's postcard, the very image of this city.''
</P>
<P>
   The bridge's residents have built cubbyhole homes all the way up
the famous girders, and formed a large high-rise community. Scraps
of metal, wood and cardboard with glass and plastic windows house
retailers who own shops on the bridge, residents who commute to
work in the city and, of course, drug dealers and other criminals.
</P>
<P>
   For the real world, there is a climax coming, like a bomb
ticking away the last seconds of what most know as reality. The bad
guy is being used by the cyber crowd to make sure the end of the
world happens. When that's done, only a cyber world will exist, and
that's just fine with them.
</P>
<P>
   Rydell's job is to stop the ticking. That can put a cramp in a
guy's social life.
</P>
<P>
   Life on Earth hasn't gotten easier. There are lots of nifty
technological gadgets but with an accompanying rise in the sleaze
factor. Just plain nice people are at a premium. The author's ideas
for dealing with society's ills are startling and provocative.
</P>
<P>
   For graffiti artists, he envisions ``a finish that ate graffiti.
The gang kids would come and tag it; twenty minutes later these
flat, dark, vaguely crab-like patches of dark blue would come
gliding around the corner. . . . They seemed to be embedded, a few
millimeters down into the surface, which was a sort of non-glossy
gel-coat affair, but able to move around under there. Smart
material, he'd heard that called.''
</P>
<P>
   There are ATM machines that don't tolerate loitering or
tampering: they either spritz such customers with pepper spray or
electrocute them _ ``. . . the thing would mist you and itself down
with water and then electrify itself.''
</P>
<P>
   And humans' fascination with creating life is explored in the
Another One dolls: ``These are in fact life-sized dolls,
manufactured in the closing years of the previous century for the
solace of distant grandparents, each one made to resemble
photographs of an actual infant.''
</P>
<P>
   Other gadgets the characters can't live without: eyephones with
built-in display screens and built-in phones and speakers.
</P>
<P>
   For a high-tech world, ``All Tomorrow's Parties'' is
surprisingly tactile. That, too, is one of William Gibson's
strengths, and he uses it to good advantage here. It's a relief to
see that the writer who coined the word cyberspace is definitely
still at the head of his genre.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Kalber writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
