<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grammy nods boost Macy Gray
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Macy Gray is the new R&AMP;B singer everybody seems to
have heard of _ but nobody's buying. At least not at the rate you
would expect, considering that for six months she's had the kind of
``hot new thing'' buzz that gets you covered in newsweeklies and
invited to perform at Talk magazine's Statue of Liberty launch
party.
</P>
<P>
   Her debut, ``On How Life Is,'' has dwelled in the basement of
Billboard's Top 200 charts for most of the 25 weeks it has been
around.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Slater, the manager she shares with pop's Fiona Apple,
concedes that Gray's hip-hop-inspired soul album has gotten little
radio airplay because ``Macy's made a sophisticated record in terms
of what's considered mass appeal, and what's selling these days.''
</P>
<P>
   But since the 30-year-old with the young Tina Turner voice
received two Grammy Award nominations earlier this month _ for best
new artist and female vocal R&AMP;B performance _ ``On How Life Is''
has jumped from No. 102 to No. 66 to No. 54, on this week's chart.
</P>
<P>
   We had three questions for a deservedly upbeat Gray:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does it seem like, finally, you're going to get the kind of
sales to match the attention you've received?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, yeah, it's already happening. We're almost gold (500,000
in sales). And we've sold more than 2 million worldwide. So in my
mind, I'm doing well. Maybe if you compare what I've done with the
Backstreet Boys, moving a million every week, things could be
rough. But it's been a slow, good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've gone about this a bit differently than your peers.
Though you had a splashy video (for first single ``Do Something''),
you also hit the road early. Who made that decision?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was natural. I was playing before I had a deal. I love
playing. I was actually kind of proud when I read a magazine that
said I was an underground star. Most people have heard of me
through word of mouth, in the clubs, playing in stores or reading
an article. From the street level. Which is a real cool way to
start. But I'm definitely ready to move on now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The first time you performed here it seemed like you had a
lot of cheering family members up front. Do you have any ties to
Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have a lot of loud uncles and aunts (laughs). I used to
stay there when I was a kid during the summers, mostly in Decatur
or over by Greenbriar Mall. Then as I got older Freaknik was my
thing. I still go to the Underground and Fat Tuesday. My cousins
take me out clubbing and shopping. But I can't go to the Gap
anymore. That's how I know things have changed. I went to the Gap
the other day and a gang of kids just rushed me. It was cool
though.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
