</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-FILMS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women moviemakers prove they've got the right stuff
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ Mary Harron has some advice regarding the
abundance of women filmmakers at this year's Sundance Film
Festival: Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see there being any going back now,'' says Harron,
who's made one of the most talked-about films at the fest _ the
violent, sex-obsessed ``American Psycho,'' which is scheduled to
open in theaters in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a fair division now,'' she says, eating
yogurt while sitting in her condo dressed head to toe in black
knit, the preferred color of Sundance attire. ``Maybe next year
won't be so good for women, but I still think you're not going to
stop the process of women coming into film.''
</P>
<P>
   Women have indeed arrived in a big way here at Robert Redford's
annual 10-day celebration of independent movies, which ends Sunday.
Of the 32 independent films and documentaries competing for juried
prizes at this year's festival, 47 percent involve women sitting in
the director's chair. English-Indian director Gurinder Chadha's
Thanksgiving-themed ``What's Cooking?'' was the opening night
feature of the fest. And more movies made by women are playing here
this year than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful that more and more women are being recognized
because of the quality of their work,'' says Tina Gee, vice
president of theatrical distribution for Seventh Art Releasing in
Los Angeles. ``That opens doors. It makes the Hollywood studio
heads think. They realize women can work as directors.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Today has already dubbed this year's Sundance Film Festival,
a celebration of 112 full-length movies, documentaries and shorts,
a sort of ``indie chick flick'' bonanza. But many of the women who
make films are slightly put off by a label that suggests their work
can be lumped into a category that Hollywood normally defines as
romantic weepers and light relationship comedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you kind of ignore the words `chick flick,' it's OK,'' says
Anne Makepeace, director of ``Coming to Light: Edward S. Curtis and
the North American Indians,'' a documentary about the photographer
who spent three decades chronicling the vanishing culture of the
Hopi, Navajo, Blackfoot and other tribes at the beginning of the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time it was a guy film world,'' Makepeace says.
``Women do have to work harder. I graduated in 1982 from film
school at Stanford with an award-winning drama, and if I had been a
guy, I would have had a lot of offers from Hollywood to direct. It
could have been the nature of the script, but guys with the same
credentials seemed to get development deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Many here believe the number of women included in the festival
is due, in part, to a dramatic rise in the quality of their works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diversity in content is quite broad,'' says festival
co-director Geoffrey Gilmore. ``It certainly dispels this notion of
humorous, romantic chick flick. It's the substantive qualities that
seem to be increasing. There's far fewer of that twenty-something
angst film, the Quentin Tarantinos of years past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Psycho'' is certainly one of the leaders in
hard-edged content.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Bret Easton Ellis' take-no-prisoners tome of '80s
greed, Harron's often funny, decidedly violent film stars Christian
Bale as a monied psycho killer stalking Wall Street. It's been
slapped with an NC-17 rating not for its vicious bloodletting but
for its intensive display of soulless, threesome sex (Harron and
the movie's distributor, Lions Gate Releasing, are appealing the
rating).
</P>
<P>
   Other movies by women being screened at this year's festival
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Committed.'' Lisa Krueger's biting take on a woman (Heather
Graham) obsessed with tracking down the husband who has
inexplicably bolted their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Girlfight.'' Karyn Kusama's tale of a female teen's
stereotype shattering foray into pugilism.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Tao of Steve.'' Jenniphr Goodman's revealing portrait of
a guy who possesses a kind of Steve McQueen gene that effortlessly
attracts women.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``First Person Plural.'' Deann Borshay Liem's documentary of
her own adoption, in which she discovers the name she'd been given
is not hers but belongs to a sister she didn't know she had.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Stranger With a Camera.'' Elizabeth Barret's frank
documentary about the slaying of a renowned Canadian documentarian
in her native Appalachia.
</P>
<P>
   These follow on the heels of Kimberly Peirce's devastating
``Boys Don't Cry,'' the violent, true-life tale of a Midwestern
woman posing as a man. One of last year's Sundance Film Festival
success stories, ``Boys'' was screened as a 20-minute work in
progress to distributors and is considered a shoo-in for an Oscar
nomination this year for its star Hilary Swank.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Psycho's'' Harron has a theory about why it has taken
so long for women to play a stronger role in moviemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a rock journalist and I remember in the '70s
there were no women rock musicians,'' she says. ``There were
singers and songwriters. Then came Talking Heads with a woman
playing bass. It was the first time I had seen that and it was such
a shock. We'd never seen a woman just in the background playing an
instrument. Then for years there were loads and loads of women in
bands. We just needed someone to break the mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock music just moves faster in the culture,'' she continues.
``What took three years in rock music has taken 10, 15 years in
movies. It's a slower moving part of the culture. It's the
apparatus of it. Films take a longer time to be developed. It's a
much more cumbersome process.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the result is changing not only how movies get made,
but what audiences see on screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Cooking?'' star Alfre Woodard says there's a big
difference in how female directors run a set. ``It's calmer, more
humorous, less angst-driven,'' she says. ``A male-driven set
establishes a tone of `this is the most important thing going on in
the world.'''
</P>
<P>
   And Susan Todd, co-director with husband Andrew Young of the
prize-competing documentary ``Americanos: Latino Life in the United
States,'' believes her perspective allowed the film to place a
greater emphasis on strong Latino women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The segment that's devoted to a Midwestern low-rider festival
features a young woman interested in cars and she not only
competes, but judges,'' Todd says. ``Andrew might not have thought
of including her.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that the Sundance Film Festival is featuring
more works from women, Hollywood appears to be testing the waters,
though with an overall less risky comedic bent.
</P>
<P>
   This year, several major studios will release films helmed by
women. Among them: Diane Keaton's ``Hanging Up,'' Sally Field's
``Beautiful,'' Bonnie Hunt's ``Return to Me,'' Nora Ephron's
``Numbers,'' Betty Thomas' ``28 Days'' and Amy Heckerling's
``Loser.''
</P>
<P>
   For women, ``what remains to be seen is whether they can be
truly commercial, that their works start to find audiences,'' says
the film fest's Gilmore. ``The hardest thing to do is to see what
sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   And some female directors, like Chadha of ``What's Cooking?''
say that powerful Hollywood men aren't always a woman's stumbling
block.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met some scary women,'' she says. ``Ultimately, it boils
down to ideas and getting people interested in your ideas. If you
can make money, people will talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
