<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Few people today have ever seen a lynching; few
people, at one time, had never seen it. To see it in photographic
retrospective is to look not so much at the dead as the living _
those who thrilled to see someone stripped bare, bull-whipped and
put to death in whatever macabre manner suited the audience. The
dead are only mutilated corpses that have to be disposed of. For
anyone who opens ``Without Sanctuary: Lynching Photography in
America,'' an extraordinarily impressive documentary of American
vengeance and bestiality, agonizing death induces a sucking in of
breath, only to be followed by somber contemplation of the pleasure
it brought spectators _ ``lingering in the woods, circling after
the kill,'' as James Allen writes. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 41.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
</P>
