<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8031 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-EARRING28-COX     01-27 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EARRING28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lust for (still) life
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the middle of the 17th century in the Dutch town of Delft.
A tilemaker has been blinded by an explosion, so his oldest
daughter goes to work to support the family.
</P>
<P>
   Griet is sent to the home of an artist, to do the laundry, to
watch the children, to do whatever her master wishes. His name is
Johannes Vermeer.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Chevalier's Girl With a Pearl Earring is less a
conventional biographical novel _ famous man observed by a
fictional sidekick _ than it is a very canny, believable and
well-executed speculation about history and the uses of artists'
erotic impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Griet becomes increasingly fascinated by Vermeer, an infatuation
that is, in his fashion, returned. Unlike the other servant girl,
Griet has a sensitivity to color and some vague sense of what
Vermeer is trying to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Griet is a wise girl and navigates instinctively through a
difficult household; the jealous, acquisitive and perennially
pregnant wife Catharina; Vermeer's mother-in-law; the children; the
other servant. Charged with cleaning his studio without moving
anything, she realizes how painstakingly he works.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seemed to be no changes to the painting, as hard as I
looked for them. At last one day I discovered that another pearl
had been added to the woman's necklace. Another day the shadow of
the yellow curtain had grown bigger. I thought too that some of the
fingers on her right hand had been moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Vermeer asks her to model for him, and the long hours
spent working together on Griet's portrait lead to a culmination
that is far from obvious but altogether satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeer matters to us because of his solitude, his sense of
discretion. His pictures don't tell us everything, and his
contemplative portraits imply things happening just outside the
frame. He's Edward Hopper recast as a Dutch Master.
</P>
<P>
   Chevalier's first-rate novel honors that emotional imperative.
She doesn't characterize Vermeer heavily, thus leaving his
essential mystery intact:
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a long, angular face, and his expression was steady, in
contrast to his wife's, which flickered like a candle. He had no
beard or mustache, and I was glad, for it gave him a clean
appearance. He wore a black cloak over his shoulder, a white shirt,
and a fine lace collar. His hat pressed into hair the red of brick
washed by rain.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's all. Chevalier is helped by the fact that we really
don't know much about Vermeer. He had a lot of children, he painted
slowly, he died deeply in debt, and he rearranged reality to make
his compositions more beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Girl With a Pearl Earring assiduously avoids making any great
imaginative leaps. It keeps to a quotidian reality, assembling its
considerable drama through the accumulation of a thousand small
details: the way a servant girl in the 17th century had no legal or
moral standing; courtship rituals among the working class; cleaning
regimens among the middle class; the way Dutch Catholics lived
apart from everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Chevalier's novel communicates indirectly, between the
lines. Other men of Delft make their desires bluntly known, but
Vermeer is repressed, contents himself by watching and thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Girl With a Pearl Earring is not a tease; it's not about
anything so crass as will-they-won't-they. Its most overt erotic
moment comes when Vermeer reaches out and strokes Griet's lips. The
effect is electric, akin to Hester Prynne's letting down her hair
in the woods in The Scarlet Letter.
</P>
<P>
   There is a deeply satisfying coda to this lovely novel, a final
confrontation in which Griet realizes that Vermeer was always much
more interested in his painting of her than he was in her.
</P>
<P>
   He was, she realizes, an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
