<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EYMAN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Sue Grafton and editor, `P' is now for Putnam
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sue Grafton is leaving Holt, where her character Kinsey Milhone
and alphabet-titled murder mysteries have been the primary mortgage
lifter for many years, to follow her editor Marian Wood to Putnam.
</P>
<P>
   This underscores the extent to which writing remains a trade
founded largely on relationships. Many writers trust editors in a
way they would never trust their spouses. A common feature of
contracts for successful writers is an editor clause, which states
that should a specific editor leave the house, the writer can go
with them with no penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Whodunit . . .
</P>
<P>
   Fort Lauderdale author Kristy Montee has had her first mystery
novel published in paperback by Pinnacle, following its hardcover
publication last year by Kensington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark of the Moon'' is about a biracial cop named Louis
Kincaid, who returns to a Mississippi town to take care of his
dying mother.
</P>
<P>
   Montee, writing with her sister Kelly under the name P.J.
Parrish, has already completed the second Parrish novel ``The Dead
of Winter,'' to be published this fall, also by Kensington.Body
slam!
</P>
<P>
   Add another name to the list of wrestlers writing
autobiographies. Bill Goldberg, who drops his first name
professionally, will be writing write a book for Crown, in concert
with his older brother Steve.
</P>
<P>
   ``My story is much too cool and bizarre to keep it to myself,''
he told Publisher's Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Next?'' will be published in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In other, more serious sporting news, Little, Brown will be
publishing the autobiography of Jim Morris, who became the big
league's oldest rookie last year. After losing a bet with the high
school team he was coaching, he tried out and won a spot pitching
in relief for Tampa Bay at the age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming . . .
</P>
<P>
   Bliss Broyard, the daughter of the late, superb New York Times
book critic Anatole Broyard, had a volume of short stories
well-received last year and has just signed with Little, Brown for
two more books. One is a memoir of her father called Mixed Blood _
Broyard was black but passed as white to everyone, including his
family _ the other a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, comes this item from Publisher's Weekly, about a
novel that was rejected by 25 U.S. publishers before being bought
in England. The English publisher sold it to several other
countries, at which point the novel that had been unpublishable in
America was suddenly hot. Picador has bought ``Music for the Third
Ear'' _ about a Norwegian couple who take in Bosnian refugees _ and
will publish it next year.
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of playing the game is knowing when you have lost. If you
have been flatly rejected by ten well-chosen editors then you will
almost certainly be turned down by the next hundred. It would be
far better to spend your time rethinking your idea, reworking your
proposal, or maybe even abandoning that particular idea and moving
on to something else.'' _ John Boswell
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
