<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I have seen the future and
it is blurry. So even though the 2000 model of me has some miles on
the odometer, the younger me would no doubt be impressed with the
car I'm driving. It's a sporty red convertible designed to draw
attention away from the heavy, gray, visually impaired driver.
(Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My good deed for the day
was saving a mouse. Let's hope he doesn't tell his larger brethren
about the kind-hearted fool in the brick house next to the woods. I
won't be so tolerant of rats. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher
of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AUSTIN, Texas _ For Republican
true believers, Kay Bailey Hutchison's U.S. Senate re-election race
this year could be called Snow White and the Five Dwarfs. But
former state Rep. Charles Gandy of Austin is ready to give it a go.
(McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _The formula of seeing someone,
particularly a stranger or a teen, as the child he or she once was
is a great way to attain a sense of commonality. This particularly
ought to get one past prejudices against people of different colors
and different faiths. They were all children once. Like you. (John
Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
