<P>
   WOMEN-FILMS _ From the Sundance Film Festival: movies from the
woman's point of view. More women filmmakers are participating at
Sundance this year than ever before. Mary Harron is debuting
``American Psycho'' (it debuts in theaters in April) based on the
controversial Bret Easton Ellis book. Lisa Krueger (``Manny &AMP; Lo'')
has ``Committed,'' with Heather Graham. Karyn Kusama has
``Girlfight,'' about a ferocious teen. In documentaries, there is
Anne Makepeace with an in-depth look at Edward S. Curtis, Deann
Borshay Liem with a first-person tale of Korean adoption gone awry;
and Frances Reid and Deborah Hoffman's view of South Africa's Truth
and Reconciliation Commission. We interview women filmmakers,
executives like CNN's Pat Mitchell and others about the growing
role of women in independent filmmaking and the subtle and not-so
subtle bias they find in the industry. (Longino, Cox News Service).
40. MOVED
