<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ The literary ring is getting crowded with wrestling
books. Dwayne Johnson's memoir, ``The Rock Says,'' has landed at
No. 2 on the New York Times List, four notches above Mike Foley's
``Have a Nice Day!.'' In the works are more tomes from Bill
Goldberg and Jesse Ventura. In other book news, Helen Ellis comes
to town to promote her debut novel, ``Eating the Cheshire Cat,'' a
satirical story set in Alabama. Ellis' boss at Chanel had such
faith in her abilities that he gave her every Friday off to write.
Now she's on a ``maternity leave'' for the book tour. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GOETZ _ DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Saints are terrible role
models,'' the Rev. Joseph Goetz writes engagingly in his little
book, ``Mirrors of God'' ($6.95, Forward Movement Press). Saints
are bigger than life; how can we ever measure up? We can't, of
course. That's why Goetz offers six, very flawed female models.
(Jesse, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EARRING _ Review of the book ``Girl With a Pearl
Earring,'' by Tracy Chevalier. There is a deeply satisfying coda to
this lovely novel, a final confrontation in which Griet realizes
that Vermeer was always much more interested in his painting of her
than he was in her. He was, she realizes, an artist. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EYMAN _ Sue Grafton is leaving Holt, where her character
Kinsey Milhone and alphabet-titled murder mysteries have been the
primary mortgage lifter for many years, to follow her editor Marian
Wood to Putnam. Scott Eyman's weekly book column (Eyman, Palm Beach
Post). MOVEDBOOKS-PARTIES _ Review of the book ``All Tomorrow's
Parties,'' by William Gibson. It is surprising tactile. The writer
who coined the word ``cyberspace'' is definitely still at the head
of his genre. (Kalber, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
