<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PACIFICA-LABOR-DISPUTE (San Francisco) _ About 40 employees
Pacifica's national news division have threatened to strike
beginning Monday over what they say is a pattern of censorship by
Pacifica's management. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER-ADS (San Francisco) _ Some Bay Area transit
agencies have pulled graphic ads that show a photo of a
bare-chested woman who has scars from a double mastectomy. The ad
agency with exclusive rights over advertising in San Francisco bus
shelters has refused to run the ads because they are ``too
traumatizing.'' By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHARRO-SINGER (San Antonio) _ Six decades before the Ricky
Martin crossover explosion, a young ranchero singer captured
audiences in the United States and Mexico. His name was Tito
Guizar, and like the gun-slinging, ballad-singing American cowboy
Roy Rogers, Guizar embodied the typical screen hero _ tall,
handsome and dashing. By RAMIRO BURR.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-ETIQUETTE (Houston) _ The Gentlemen School of Etiquette
dispenses advice about manners and manhood, part of its quest to
civilize young people. The school was started by two graduates of
Southern University in Baton Rouge, La., and a graduate of Texas
Southern University in Houston. By JEANNIE KEEVER. (Photos
available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A readers asks, ``Could you tell me
whether misting helps my houseplants?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY
HUBER.
</P>
