<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ETIQUETTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISH TRIO DISPENSES ADVICE ABOUT MANNERS AND MANHOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: La.) 
 
(Eds. Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By JEANNIE KEVER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ They sat there, dressed in their white shirts and
ties, as still as several dozen middle school kids could possibly
sit.
</P>
<P>
   Then James Tennard III brought up a topic guaranteed to make
them squirm.
</P>
<P>
   Kissing.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Tennard quickly broke this news: ``Kissing is not
important for your age. Don't even worry about it,'' he told the
students at Johnston Middle School. ``The time will surely come.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennard and his partners in the Three Gentlemen School of
Etiquette were dispensing advice about manners and manhood, part of
their quest to civilize the city.
</P>
<P>
   At school visits and lessons delivered at their southwest
Houston offices, they talk about the rules of fine dining, personal
grooming and all manner of social interaction, from dating to
business deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are things that people just don't know,'' said Robert
Hayes III. ``I've met older men, 35 and up, who don't know how to
tie a tie. They're afraid to put on a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Hayes, Tennard and the third gentleman, Donnell Cooper. They
are impeccably stylish suit-and-tie guys in a Dockers world.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it wasn't always this way _ Hayes' mother, Kelso
Elementary School Principal Debra Hayes, says he occasionally was a
bit slow to open the door for her when he was a child _ but it's
been pretty close.
</P>
<P>
   Three well-mannered boys, grown into well-mannered men. Now they
want to pass on the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, 24, and Tennard, 25, grew up together in Houston; Hayes
and the 23-year-old Cooper met as students at Southern University
in Baton Rouge, La., where both earned degrees in sociology.
Cooper, who also grew up in Houston, later completed a master's
degree in public administration at Texas Southern University.
</P>
<P>
   They returned home to Houston in 1998 and began their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper is a parole officer for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice; Hayes is a resident adviser at Covenant House, an
organization for runaways and street kids. Tennard, a senior
criminal justice major at TSU, is a Harris County Juvenile
Institution officer.
</P>
<P>
   One day during a casual conversation, they realized they all
felt that manners mattered.
</P>
<P>
   They signed up for a class with local etiquette doyenne Ann
Miller, who was so proud of her young proteges that she arranged a
meeting and photo with Houston Mayor Lee Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Thus inspired, they launched plans for their own school,
targeting boys and young men.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being dismayed at the competition, Miller says she is
happy to welcome them as colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann Miller cannot save the world,'' she said. ``They can reach
areas that I would never reach, the little boy. ... These three
guys can be role models.''
</P>
<P>
   She's even interested in sending her 14-year-old son through
their program, not because she hasn't taught him etiquette _ she
has, of course _ but because she thinks the lessons will be more
powerful coming from three polished young men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not teaching anything new,'' Hayes said. ``We're
teaching something that gets passed down from generation to
generation, but it's getting lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Their curriculum is a mix of the rules they grew up with,
lessons from Miller's classes and common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we teach how to make others feel comfortable in any
situation,'' Tennard said. ``That's how you make a boy into a man
and a man into a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   They started out holding classes at Westbury United Methodist
Church before moving to their tastefully furnished suite of
offices, equipped with an assortment of grooming aids _ toiletries,
shoe horns and the like _ and four place settings of china and
silverware.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Cooper said, they have spent several thousand dollars
setting up the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good etiquette is a universal language,'' said Westbury Pastor
J.D. Phillips. ``Good manners, kindness ... is craved by human
nature as much as anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But he sees a deeper benefit to what Cooper, Hayes and Tennard
are trying to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it contributes to a good self-image,'' Phillips said.
``When people feel like they know how to respond in a situation,
they feel better about themselves. If you don't have the proper
social skills to comfortably interact with people, you're still
lost, and you're uneducated.''
</P>
<P>
   The session at Johnston Middle School was a chance to address
that.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 boys from the school's Gentlemen's Club, along with a
handful of girls from a corresponding club for young women,
listened attentively as Cooper, Hayes and Tennard talked about
grooming, dining and dating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might not use it today,'' Cooper told them as he explained
the importance of good grooming. ``But you're getting older. One
day you will.''
</P>
<P>
   The club started several years ago to teach some of life's finer
details, Assistant Principal Charles Cade said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to teach our young men how to act in a nice
place,'' Cade said. ``It builds up self-esteem. They feel good
about themselves. They feel knowledgeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Club meetings also cover financial topics such as stocks, bonds
and mutual funds, even ``how to become CEO of a big company,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to expose students to loftier goals. ``A lot of our
kids, they come from a single-parent home,'' Cade said. ``They
don't have a dad. They come to me to tie their ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Cade's father died when he was a child, he said. ``If it hadn't
been for a high school coach, I don't know where I'd be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Three Gentlemen seek to fill the void, too, covering topics
of interest to kids.
</P>
<P>
   What, Tennard asked the students, should you do if you escort a
young lady to dinner and, upon opening the menu, discover you don't
have enough money to cover the bill?
</P>
<P>
   ``Order soup,'' one boy offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to an ATM machine,'' another said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennard suggested honesty. ``She'll appreciate that,'' he
said, and dinner at a less expensive restaurant will still be fun.
</P>
<P>
   He, Hayes and Cooper are flawlessly dressed for their school
visit, all in black _ black shirts and ties, black suits, spiffily
shined black shoes.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of their appeal, Phillips said. ``They're role
models. They dress nice. They're an alternative to the type of
images that are dangerous to young people: the drug dealer who
makes a lot of money. The violent person on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This says to a person, `Hey, you can be cool in this way.' ...
Everybody can't play basketball. Everybody's not going to be a
great athlete or entertainer. But everybody can be a decent human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's young gentlemen said they were impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're true gentlemen,'' 11-year-old Brandon Balque said. ``I
learned a lot about taking out a date.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he date yet?
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   But these kids are thinking about the future. ``I really want to
learn about etiquette,'' 12-year-old Geronimo Ibanez said. ``My
mom, she says you need to be classy.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the etiquette session offered forward-thinking advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know how you're supposed to take a lady out,''
Geronimo said, ``because I'm going to need that later in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly, the gentlemen say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Youth today are scared to put on a tie, to wear nice clothes,
because of what their friends might say,'' Hayes said. ``They're
growing up not even knowing how to tie a simple tie, let alone a
bow tie or a Windsor knot.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hayes and his partners will teach that and try to inspire
their young charges to something more.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Cooper said, they want to restore some of manhood's
lost luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to rebuild as many men as we can.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about the Three Gentlemen School of
Etiquette, call 713-785-2490 in Houston.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
