<HEADLINE>
HOUSEPLANTS LIKE A HIGH HUMIDITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: Could you tell me whether misting helps my
houseplants?
</P>
<P>
   A: Misting once or twice a day helps, but this is a short-term
solution to a continued problem of low humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Most plants prefer a relative humidity of 50 percent to 60
percent. But our homes have a relative humidity of only 10 percent
to 15 percent during the winter, often causing leaf margins to
brown and flower buds to brown and drop.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is a humidifier to raise the relative humidity
throughout your home or in the area where the plants are located.
If a humidifier is out of the question, try growing the plants in
the kitchen or bathroom, where the air is usually more humid. Or
group the plants on a tray of moistened pebbles, which raises
humidity. Or at least group the plants so that water vapor given
off by each plant benefits the others.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have to prune my wisteria several times a year to keep it
from overrunning its available area. I have always done this at
random times, as it seemed to become necessary, with the result
that in some years I get no blooms. Could you please tell me in
which months I should try to avoid pruning to avoid interfering
with bloom cycles?
</P>
<P>
   Could you tell me in which months I should avoid pruning
pyracantha so I won't interfere with berry production?
</P>
<P>
   A: Do not prune wisteria when dormant as you will remove most of
the flower buds and encourage rampant green growth in spring. Wait
until the vine has bloomed, and then, in July, remove straggly
growth but leave some branches so the vine can climb.
</P>
<P>
   Cut shoots back a third to a half their length, which includes
the short spurs upon which next season's flower clusters are borne.
</P>
<P>
   Your vine will flower best in sun and a well-draining soil.
Don't overwater, and don't apply a lot of nitrogen or you'll get
green growth at the expense of blooms.
</P>
<P>
   You can try fall applications of a phosphorus fertilizer to
encourage flowering, but don't overdo that either. Phosphorus
buildup can occur, and if phosphorus is tied up in the soil, the
plant can't use it. Epsom salts can help various plants flower, as
it provides magnesium and releases certain elements in the soil
that plants need to bloom.
</P>
<P>
   If you prune in summer, give the plant plenty of sun, and if it
still doesn't bloom, try root pruning. Come out about two feet from
the trunk of the vine and drive a sharp spade about a foot down.
Repeat this around the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Pyracanthas bloom in spring and produce green fruit that turns
red in fall. The plants often hold the berries in winter. I would
do major pruning in late winter, even if this means removing
lingering berries. If you prune just before spring, you'll diminish
blooms, which, of course, diminishes your berry count.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, TX 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
