<HEADLINE>
ROBERTS, GERE A GREAT MATCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `RUNAWAY BRIDE'
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a ``Notting Hill'' sequel for Julia Roberts and
Hugh Grant. Although some critics marveled at their chemistry, the
actors reportedly detested each other.
</P>
<P>
   But Roberts and Richard Gere are another thing. They've been
pals and New York neighbors since their 1990 hit, ``Pretty Woman,''
and they'd often considered scripts for a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   None was good enough. Happily, the two found a suitable
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Runaway Bride,'' Gere and Roberts rekindle their
romantic-comedy sparks as different characters.
</P>
<P>
   He plays Ike, a columnist for USA Today. (In reality the paper
is in Washington, D.C., but for the film it shifts to New York.)
She plays Maggie, a hardware-store owner in a small Maryland town.
(Seems like nearby D.C. would have been a natural fit, but what do
we know?)
</P>
<P>
   When Ike learns Maggie has dumped three grooms at the altar, he
attacks her in print, followed by close encounters when he heads to
her town for a follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   As she grooms her fourth groom, will Maggie again get cold feet,
this time thanks to her secret attraction for the snide yet
disarming journalist? Duh.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's sheer wish-fulfilling fantasy. But it's also sheer
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Director Garry Marshall (who also helmed ``Pretty Woman'') keeps
a loose, light touch on the proceedings while giving this screwball
comedy moments of redeeming soulfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bride'' is packed with Marshall's trademark funny bits, often
improvised on the set. When Roberts makes a strange face or dangles
from a church-bell rope, that's Marshall saying, ``Julia, do the
thing with the thing, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Gere and Roberts also are as charming as ever, and Gere has
never been more self-effacing and funny.
</P>
<P>
   A solid supporting cast includes Joan Cusack in the obligatory
``friend'' role and Hector Elizondo (also of ``Pretty Woman'') as
Gere's supportive colleague.
</P>
<P>
   One big problem: The film shamelessly lets itself off the hook
when it comes to Maggie's left-behind beaus. While wildly divergent
in their lifestyles (one's a rocker/mechanic, another is a priest),
they are uniformly sweet and understanding about the bride they
lost. This lets Maggie check her guilt at the door _ not that she
shows a trace of it.
</P>
<P>
   The film's fantasies also extend to the impossibly idyllic town
and the stars' amazing wealth trappings.
</P>
<P>
   Gere has a jaw-dropping Manhattan apartment that Donald Trump
might envy, while Roberts' hardware-store gal wears simple yet chic
clothes that only could come from the big city.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep telling yourself: It's only a movie.
</P>
<P>
   As such _ and as escapist entertainment _ ``Bride'' works. Don't
take it too seriously, and don't scrutinize it ... just enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG, Paramount, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MOONLIGHTING' ARRIVES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Moonlighting,'' newly syndicated on Bravo, is also on video
with a collector's edition from Anchor Bay. The 93-minute tape
($14.98) has the original pilot along with Bruce Willis' screen
test for the hit TV show that also starred Cybill Shepherd, with
Allyce Beasley.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD ($24.98) adds a recent audio commentary by Willis and
creator Glenn Gordon Caron, as well as a 12-page booklet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SEE THE WORLD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New on DVD from MPI is ``Baraka,'' a superb world tour of 24
countries offering such striking sights as Mount Everest and the
pyramids at Giza.
</P>
<P>
   Shot on 70mm film and melded with music, ``Baraka'' already was
on tape, where it's been reduced to $14.98. The DVD is $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GETTING A `HOOK' ON DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg is slowly dragging himself onto the DVD
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   So far, his only film on DVD has been his latest, ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' But on March 21 he'll have another: 1991's
``Hook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hook'' _ a mishandled spin on ``Peter Pan'' _ isn't exactly
what Spielberg fans are frothing to get on disc. ``Raiders of the
Lost Ark,'' ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' ``Jurassic
Park,'' ``Jaws'' and ``E.T.'' still wait.
</P>
<P>
   Like his good pal George Lucas, Spielberg seems content to let
others lay the groundwork for DVD before he jumps in to exploit it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`ALLY' ON TAPE, DISC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'' is on video with three tapes, each featuring two
episodes and costing a suggested $14.98. Or you can get all six
shows on a two-disc DVD set costing $39.98.
</P>
<P>
   The three tapes also are sold as a set for $39.98, but the two
discs aren't sold individually.
</P>
<P>
   The first volumes of both the DVDs and tapes have the pilot
show, as well as ``Cro-Magnon,'' the so-called ``Dancing Baby''
episode.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`PAYBACK' MARKED DOWN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mel Gibson's ``Payback'' has been marked down to $14.95 on tape,
where it now includes interviews and behind-the-scenes material.
</P>
<P>
   The film's DVD remains the same, costing $29.99 and adding a
trailer and behind-the-scenes footage. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`SIMPSONS' GIFT SET &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating its 10th anniversary, ``The Simpsons'' has a new
Hollywood-theme gift set featuring three videos with two episodes
each for $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   Volume 1 also is sold separately for $9.98 and has a never-seen
montage of Bart's long-running crank calls to Moe's Bar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
