<SLUG> BC-TV-COUNTERPROGRAMMING-SUPER-BOWL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEEP-BEEP' INSTEAD OF THE BIG GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: all times PST ... check for times in your area) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given how so many Super Bowls are tedious blow-outs, you might
want to consider Cartoon Network's counter-programming offering:
``Roadrunner vs. Coyote: The Big Game,'' an ingeniously packaged
pile of old cartoons, which boasts another guaranteed lop-sided
score and play-by-play from Fox sportscasters John Madden and Pat
Summerall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Game'' parodies Super Bowl hoopla _ a belabored Slate
Rock &AMP; Quarry Co. Pre-game Show features the bickering ex-pro
football stars of HBO's ``Inside the NFL'' (only Jerry Glanville
feels poor old Wile E. Coyote has a chance of triumphing). In a
``bio'' of Roadrunner, the narrator intones, ```Beep-beep:' Words
that to this day ring out like two big, ringing-out things.'' (Even
the protracted nature of the pre- game show is part of the dadaist
joke it plays on Bowl hype.)
</P>
<P>
   It also pokes relentless fun at the grindingly obvious
conventions of the cartoons themselves. There's a special report on
Coyote's disastrously ill-advised endorsement deal with Acme, and
Madden and Summerall become weary with the Coyote's relentlessly
self-immolating attempts at capturing his prey (Madden explains
each in instant-replay on his telestrator with the same insight he
brings to NFL match-ups.) Here's the money quote: Self-flagellation
has never been so much fun! ``The Big Game'' airs on Cartoon
Network from 1-5 p.m. Sunday, but for those who insist on watching
Tennessee-St. Louis, it's also on Saturday night from 6-10 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
