<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-BOS &LR;      01-27 1759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT QUESTION, KURT WARNER HAS BEEN DISCOVERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The goatee was gone, Kurt Warner's face clean-shaven.
``It was getting too long,'' said Warner, answering his 188th
question of the morning at the St. Louis team hotel out here in
basic Georgia suburbia. ``It was starting to itch . . . but it'll
be back by Sunday, I promise you that.''
</P>
<P>
   The only change. That'll be it.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity has come and Warner has not changed. He still praises
the Lord and passes the football. Money, millions and millions of
dollars, will come to this man who may be the Most Valuable Player
in the NFL but is paid the minimum salary of $254,000 _ although
the Rams did find room in their salary cap to throw an extra
$500,000 toward Warner. But Warner guarantees he will not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wants me to pay me for what I'm doing, fine,''
said the Rams' quarterback whose tale _ this remarkable tale that
defies reality and leaves even the most jaded sportswriter
awestruck at its improbability _ is being told and retold in this
Super Bowl week of media overkill.
</P>
<P>
   Cinderella merely had to live her fairy tale and never had to
tell her tale 100 times each and every day. But Warner does.
Sometimes reluctantly, sometimes gladly.
</P>
<P>
   Even though, as Warner put it, ``I've been asked the same
questions the last 20 weeks and I just answer 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to change. Money is coming, barrels of money, armored
trucks full of money, and Warner is asked _ basically _ if he is
human. Will the money change him?
</P>
<P>
   No, replies Warner. He is not materialistic. He is the same
Warner who was stocking shelves at the Hy-Vee supermarket in Cedar
Falls, Iowa, for $5.50 an hour at 3 a.m., maybe standing up once in
a while to throw a football from the meat rack at the end of Aisle
7 to a pal down by the detergent boxes in Aisle 8 ``so I could keep
practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   Novelists, Greek poets, and Shakespeare might have to be called
back to keep an eye on Warner, to see how life's lures entice _ or
don't entice _ a man who has found peace in God and _ finally _
action on an NFL football field. If the Tampa Bay Buccaneers might
have rattled his confidence a bit last Sunday, money won't shake
him. Warner guarantees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the Lord wants us all to prosper and wants us all to
be successful,'' said Warner. ``And He has already given me so many
blessings this year that I can't even begin to talk about them all.
But I believe that the things I already have in my life are much
more important than any amount of money I will make, or any amount
of fame I can receive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, don't get the wrong impression. Kurt Warner is human, very
human. Clearly.
</P>
<P>
   As an Iowa boy, for instance, he dreamed ``every Iowa boy's
dream,'' to go to Iowa City and the University of Iowa ``and play
in Kinnick Stadium in front of all the Iowa fans . . . but it
didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It hurt. It hurt that he made only an ``unofficial visit,'' as
he put it, ``to Iowa and then I never heard from them after that.''
Iowa State was worse; the Cyclones were not interested in him at
all. Only one school in all of America showed any real interest and
that was Division 1-AA Northern Iowa, a notch below the big boys in
Division 1-A _ and the Panthers could offer him ``only
three-quarters of a scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   The football experience at Northern Iowa was not pleasant. Terry
Allen, now the coach at Kansas, chose to sit Warner until his fifth
year. And when Warner recalls those mostly-unhappy years, many of a
human's unhappy emotions pour forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a difficult situation for a while,'' said Warner, who
once was so unhappy at Northern Iowa that his mother had to
convince him not to quit the team. ``I love Coach Allen . . . I
think he's a great coach . . . I respected all the coaches there on
that staff . . . it was just a difficult time for me because there
were times when I just felt I should be playing. I felt I could
have played and been successful at that level. I just didn't get
the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Warner repeated how unhappy were those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most difficult times I've had as far as
football is concerned because I wasn't able to get out on the
field,'' he said. ``But I learned a lot at that time. I think that
was a situation that helped to strengthen me a lot. But . . .
really . . . it was probably the most difficult thing I've ever had
to go through in my football career. I realize now how it helped
get me to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Warner was very human over in Europe, playing for the
Amsterdam Admirals of NFL Europe. He doubted whether football in
Europe was right for him, because he was so far from his family in
the United States ``and I was in Amsterdam, which obviously is full
of temptations. The environment got difficult because I was away
from my family and it was hard being a family man for so long. That
was a difficult thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But money?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Warner. Money will not be a temptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because that stuff is not important to me,'' he said.
``I believe in other things. I believe in things that are more
important to me than money and fame. People can believe that if
they want. But I know that's not going to be the case. I'm grounded
in what I believe in, and my faith and my morals are all going to
stay the same.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if it weren't for Rodney Harrison, none of this would ever
have happened.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Harrison plays for the San Diego Chargers. In the Rams'
third exhibition game, St. Louis QB Trent Green dropped back to
pass. Harrison rushed.
</P>
<P>
   So much had already been accomplished in St. Louis. The Rams had
shown their commitment to winning by spending millions to get Green
from the Redskins and more millions in signing running back
Marshall Faulk after a trade with the Colts. Coach Dick Vermeil had
listened to his assistants and had lightened up, no more of
training camp being a ``boot camp.'' All seemed in place,
especially since Green had played so well in the Rams' first two
exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   But Harrison changed all that. While on the turf, he reached out
and grabbed for Green's leg as the QB was throwing a pass. Green
went down and his knee was busted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players were in tears on the sidelines,'' recalled Vermeil.
``I remember (wide receiver) Isaac Bruce on his hands and knees
just pounding the turf in frustration.'' All that had seemed in
readiness now was gone. The St. Louis Rams were without a
quarterback. The Rams' season was over an exhibition game before it
started.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Vermeil announced in a team meeting Warner would
replace Green. Ram after Ram recalled the moment, players looking
at each other and thinking the same thoughts, that instead of Trent
Green as their quarterback, they now had this refugee from European
football; even worse, from the Arena Football League. Or, as
Vermeil put it, ``I could see players looking over at each other
and saying, `He was the scout team quarterback last year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Rams' coaches felt the same about Warner as did
the players. They had no idea what kind of quarterback he would be.
Mike Martz, the offensive coordinator, had ridden Warner
mercilessly to toughen him, to see if he could play in the NFL . .
. as a backup. Now, he was the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to figure if I was good enough to be the
backup and if I could hold that role,'' said Warner, recalling the
moment. ``So, in preseason, they were focusing in on getting me a
lot of (repititions), getting me a lot of time to really get a good
feel of what I was about as a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite literally, no one in America, least of all his coaches,
those who saw him the most, can say, ``I told you so,'' about what
happened to Kurt Warner. Except for one person.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Warner himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I just had the chance, I could perform,'' he said.
``I thought I could thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `God has a plan for all of us,'' is Warner's explanation of what
so many call this fairy tale of a season. ``He does everything for
a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner is a born-again Christian and wears his faith proudly. It
is impossible to explain Warner without mentioning the prime role
of his beliefs, but the subject is sensitive. After all, this is a
football player who throws passes and he is the subject of
attention because of how well he throws those passes. Time and
again, though, he expresses his beliefs ``because I want to be the
best role model I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker expressed some of his social beliefs last month and
set off a national firestorm. Warner time and again expresses his
religious beliefs and, from time to time, some sportswriters' pens
droop and the red light of television cameras switch off. Warner
acknowledges the conundrum, that his beliefs are ``a touchy
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there on both sides of the spectrum who
believe in the Lord and He is the focus of their lives, and there
are people who don't,'' he said. ``And I realize if people start
throwing that in every article, they might lose readership. But a
lot of times, I bring it up to share the story. Some people try to
get the full story when they deal with me and guys like Isaac
(Bruce) and that's who we are and I think it needs to be in there.
Yet, there are other times when it doesn't need to be in there. But
there are other (media) people who are afraid to go into depth on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Az-Zahir Hakim is a Muslim, just as Warner acknowledges
there might be other non-Christians or atheists on his team. This
``doesn't tear the team apart,'' said Warner, ``because I think we
all believe in each other and we all know we come from different
backgrounds, and we accept that part of it even though we'd might
want everybody to come to where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, Warner has answered questions about his amazing
tale, and interspersed in his answers are strong beliefs about God.
And it is precisely this faith in God, he said, that guarantees his
belief that the millions of dollars coming his way will not change
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the person I am and the beliefs I have,'' said
Warner. ``Money is not going to change me or my beliefs. And I
don't have a problem with people trying to emulate me or be like
me. I live my life the way I think it should be lived and I don't
have a problem with people looking up to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR-2TA     01-27 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE MCNAIR ARMS TITANS' ATTACK WITH HIS LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Off the field, his left foot is imprisoned in a hard,
gray, plastic walking cast, a shield for an angry, relentless case
of turf toe and raging bone spurs that throb overnight like a
toothache screaming for Novocain.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't stop Steve McNair from running. Nothing does.
Not the pleas of his Tennessee Titans coaches to hit the ground
when that seems the prudent course of survival in general, and
protection for his surgically repaired back in particular. Not the
specter of voracious defensive linemen who seemingly have him just
about devoured, dictating a judicious dumping of the football to
spare himself a crunching reminder that he isn't shatterproof. Not
even the impression _ more lingering and nagging than any injury _
that while his feet keep moving, his right arm must have fallen
off.
</P>
<P>
   That's the unjust irony. Although nothing prevents McNair from
running, running may have prevented him from receiving his due as a
bona fide National Football League quarterback. Certainly in five
pro seasons, he has never approached the gargantuan numbers _
14,496 yards, 119 touchdowns _ he launched as a small-college
legend at Alcorn State in Lorman, Miss., where the ball was in the
air so much that it seemed like a miniature blimp hovering over the
gridiron.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, 26, acknowledges this dilemma. ``My running may have
overshadowed my passing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even running back Eddie George, while trying to pay tribute,
doesn't advance his teammate's cause when he observes, ``He's a
running back who can throw the ball very well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fact the Titans' offensive philosophy is as adventurous as a
slow-growth stock investment merely feeds the stigma that McNair's
job basically is not to get in the way while George carries the
load.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem a contrast that would cause consternation for a
quarterback whose college exploits inspired a dashing nickname _
``Air McNair'' _ and earned him a third-place finish in the 1994
Heisman Trophy balloting, matching the highest by a representative
of a Division 1-AA school.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his growing reputation as ``Don't Err'' McNair doesn't
bother him in the slightest, at least not for public consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to make plays,'' he said. ``I like to do whatever it
takes. I think a quarterback has to do more than throw. I take
pride in my running.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he can take greater pride in something else. If he's an
underrated quarterback, so be it. All that matters is he's a Super
Bowl quarterback _ the second African-American to earn the
distinction, 12 years after Doug Williams was the MVP in the
Washington Redskins' 42-10 win over the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I was going to put up the numbers I did in
college,'' McNair said. ``I knew things were going to change. Maybe
not as drastically as they have, but that's what happens in an
offense that emphasizes running the ball. You've got to accept it.
Quarterbacks who throw for 4,000 and 5,000 yards aren't here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McNair's passing totals are hardly breathtaking. In the
regular season, limited to 11 games by disk surgery, he threw for
2,179 yards, with 12 TDs and 8 interceptions. In the Titans' three
playoff victories, he passed for just 300 yards, with 1 TD and 2
interceptions. The emphasis is on his running: 337 yards (a 4.7
average) and 8 TDs during the season, 145 yards (6.6 average) and 3
TDs in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   His most impressive accomplishment is considered his 51-yard
bolt that set up his 1-yard TD, which put the Titans ahead for good
in their 33-14 win over the Jaguars in the AFC Championship Game.
And in three seasons as the starter, he has surpassed 3,000 yards
through the air, the benchmark for excellence, once _ and then just
barely, with 3,288 last season.
</P>
<P>
   McNair will concede that with a shrug of his 6-foot-2-inch,
225-pound frame and offer one irrefutable rebuttal: Look who's
here, waiting to take on the St. Louis Rams for the world title
Sunday in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people get caught up in statistics,'' he said. ``I
believe my job is to put us in a position to make plays, not make
mistakes. It's not about numbers, it's about winning. That's the
Titan way. When you have a great running back like Eddie George,
who is a complete back, you don't have to put up great numbers as a
quarterback. You don't have to take it all upon your shoulders. All
I try to do is put our team in the best possible position to win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got the critics there. McNair was 9-2 as the starter as
Tennessee compiled a 13-3 regular-season record, and the Titans'
unlikely postseason run has brought the franchise its first Super
Bowl berth in its 40-year history, 37 of them as the Houston
Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's not enough to satisfy some. There were cries to
reinsert journeyman Neil O'Donnell _ who went 4-1 as the caretaker
during McNair's convalescence _ when McNair endured a six-game
drought without a TD pass. In fact, two-thirds of his scoring
passes were condensed into two games: three in a 36-35 win over the
Bengals in the season opener, for which his reward was surgery when
his back gave out in practice the following Friday, and five in a
41-14 wipeout of the Jaguars Dec. 26. Otherwise, there was a dearth
of high-octane performances, which a host of other AFC quarterbacks
turned in routinely.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's riposte: ``Did they win or lose? There have been a lot
of 300-yard passers who didn't always win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such attention to the bottom line is why McNair always has had
the imprimatur of the Oilers/Titans coaching staff, which made him
the No. 3 pick in the 1995 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to the draft, we had a plan to get a veteran
quarterback, then draft Steve,'' said coach Jeff Fisher. ``We
wanted to bring him along slowly, watch a veteran be successful.
Never at any time did we say, `This is when he's going to be
ready.' He'd say when he was asked, `It's up to the coaches.' Then
when we asked if he was ready, he said, `OK.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The staff asked him after two years as an understudy to Chris
Chandler. McNair proceeded to guide the team to a pair of 8-8
finishes as the franchise endured the trauma of leaving Houston for
various Tennessee locales before its new home in Nashville
(Adelphia Stadium) and new nickname were ready this season.
</P>
<P>
   McNair recalls that after his bombs-away days at Alcorn State,
he had some misgivings about Fisher's approach. ``It was very
frustrating at first,'' he said, ``but Coach Fisher set me down and
filled me in on his style of play. It was a tremendous change from
throwing for 4,000 yards a year and throwing at least 40-50 times a
game. But now it's like playing in a more controlled offense. This
team is a team that wants to keep the chains moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Which McNair does, one way or another. And the modus operandi
doesn't bother Fisher in the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a winner,'' said the coach. ``He's not a 400-yard-a-game
passer but he's an athlete. He gets things done. He'll run, pass,
make plays. If he needs to throw for 350 or 400 in a game, he'll do
that, given the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those shackles again. Opportunities are the major lack
in McNair's passing abilities. Offensive coordinator Les Steckel,
for whom an ultraconservative attack would be considered a gamble,
said, ``We believe in throwing the ball downfield. But our attitude
is low-risk because second and 10 isn't fun to look at. But there's
no doubt he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McNair once was actually ordered to do it. In a season
pocked by so much pain _ McNair says, ``I tell the trainers when I
retire, I'm going to be a head trainer at somebody's school because
I know all there is to know about the body with all the injuries
I've had'' _ he must have thought deafness had been added to the
list when he received his instructions before the opener. Hoping to
exploit Bengals mismatches he had detected, Fisher told Steckel to
aim for a 35-point output.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
