<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-27 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONKEYING AROUND FOR A SEXY PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chevy Chase will have a leading role in my movie about the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm George W. Bush and you're not!''
</P>
<P>
   How about Kevin Spacey as Bill Bradley? Could he project that
enigmatic aura Bradley is so famous for?
</P>
<P>
   Even now, at an undisclosed location, an army of monkeys is
strumming away at computers, working to produce the screenplay. My
movie about the election will bear no resemblance to real events.
Who would buy a ticket to be bored senseless?
</P>
<P>
   My election movie will have plenty of sex and violence and
criminal behavior and all the other exciting elements we've come to
expect of politicians, once they're in office anyway. It will be a
two-thumbs-up, major, must-see, box office blockbuster. An instant
classic. The monkeys are sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when we expected politics to be serious, even
movies about politics to be serious. ``Advise &AMP; Consent.'' ``The
Best Man.'' ``All the Kings Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we expect real politics to entertain us.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the primaries have been a disappointment,
entertaiment-wise. Potential scandals haven't panned out. The
debates have yielded only the odd joke, the rare deviously clever
response, as when the born-again Bush was asked, ``Would you take
an expression like, `What would Jesus do?' into the White House?''
and he responded, ``I would take an expression into the Oval Office
of `Dear God, help me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The monkeys promise there will be no religious posturing in my
movie. What would Jesus do indeed. He wouldn't run in the first
place. If he drove the money-lenders out of the temple where would
he send some of these major campaign contributors?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, my movie will have plenty of lucrative
product placement. The candidates will wear jumpsuits, like race
car drivers, to display the names and logos of their big-money
supporters, the corporations, and special interest groups _ Disney,
Standard Oil, Sony, etc. _ who have an interest in their election.
It's just a movie. It would never work real life, would it?
</P>
<P>
   What does it say about our culture that millions of us are more
interested in what will happen on the next episode of ``The
Sopranos'' than who will prevail in the New Hampshire primary?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' has dramatic tension, plus sex, violence, waste
management, and assorted crime. Will Livia survive to plot and
scheme some more? Will Meadow get into Bates? Who squealed to the
Feds? And what about Uncle Junior's broken hip? Where's the
suspense in this election? We know who's going to win. They're just
dragging the thing out as long as possible to sell more
commercials, just like they do for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But back to my movie. James Caan would be perfect as John
McCain. Tough, charming, potentially volatile. In another time,
when people expected politics to be serious, McCain would have
passed the foxhole test, as in, ``Which candidate would you want
next to you in a foxhole?''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question we ask about each candidate is, ``What is he
trying to hide?''
</P>
<P>
   And we ask the question hopefully. Because maybe he's trying to
hide something really interesting, something that will capture our
attention, entertain us.
</P>
<P>
   In my movie we'll find out what they're all trying to hide.
Although the monkeys insist on the following disclaimer: Any
resemblance to actual sins and felonies committed by any or all
candidates is purely coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Who will play Al Gore? A challenging casting decision. Gore has
the Tom Selleck problem, a big, good-looking guy with a girly-man
voice. Is Selleck available? Is he a bad enough actor? What do the
monkeys say?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
