<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWO-MICROSOFTS-OPED-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT MICROSOFT INTO TWO COMPANIES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: COMMENTARY, Technology Editors)   (This 675-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' general/technology news files.)  
  
 By T.K. CHANG  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ As a college classmate of Microsoft's Bill Gates and
its new chief executive, Steven Ballmer, I have long harbored some
pride in our distant association and shamelessly name-dropped on
more than one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as a frustrated user of Microsoft products, I cannot help
but wish that Microsoft were broken up into two companies.
</P>
<P>
   One company would continue to be the guardian of Microsoft
Windows, which controls more than 90 percent of the market for the
operating-system program that is required on every computer.
</P>
<P>
   The other company would compete fairly and squarely in the
marketplace for software applications, by making better products
for word processing, e-mail and other applications.
</P>
<P>
   I use the computer for e-mail, word processing and browsing the
Internet. I do not do desktop publishing, spreadsheets, financial
or scientific analysis or anything else fancy. But I have three
computers at home, and I am now shopping for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   I used to have two computers, a desktop for my children and a
laptop for traveling. Then one day last year, my daughter came home
in tears over unfinished homework.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that her school had just switched to using
Microsoft's Word 97 word-processing program. We only had on our
home computers the older Word 6.0 program that I also used at my
office. The Word 6.0 program was incapable of deciphering documents
that had been typed in Word 97.
</P>
<P>
   That night, I took my daughter to the local store and discovered
that Microsoft's products were bundled in such a way that we had to
buy the entire Office 97 suite of programs, including Excel and
Powerpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Office 97 required much more computer memory than was
on my computer, as well as more hard-disk space and a faster CPU.
We ended up buying a new computer, which, of course, meant a sale
of Windows for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, my office installed a new e-mail program, Microsoft
Outlook 98. With the Outlook program loaded, my laptop, which I
rely on during frequent business trips, began to crash regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The program required more computer memory than I had on my
laptop. I had to explain to my clients that my computer just wiped
out their e-mails. That is why I am now shopping for my fourth home
computer, which means another sale of Windows for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   It does not take a Harvard education to figure out that
Microsoft will make more money by selling bigger and more bloated
software that requires much more computer memory than is necessary.
This strategy forces its customers to buy new computers, thereby
selling more copies of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, Microsoft announces more top-heavy versions of its
software that render obsolete its customers' existing computers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft and the cheerleading PC magazines that depend
on it for advertising have trumpeted the fact that Microsoft's new
Office 2000 will be ``backward compatible'' with Office 97, many
features of Office 2000 will not be usable without the user also
getting the new Windows 2000 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Some early reports have concluded that Windows 2000 may need as
much as 156 megabytes of computer memory in order to run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   If the programmers at Microsoft who write the applications
software were separated from the division that sells Microsoft's
cash cow, Windows, then perhaps they would be free to write better,
more innovative (and smaller) applications software.
</P>
<P>
   They might also improve on the Word word processing and Outlook
e-mail programs, which many will agree are among the most
bug-ridden, crash-prone and poorly thought-out software on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up Microsoft could also result in the shares of the
separated companies being worth more in the aggregate than the
original Microsoft shares. That would make the shareholdings of Mr.
Gates and Mr. Ballmer even more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone would benefit: consumers, business customers,
Microsoft's shareholders and, not least of all, the class fund for
our upcoming 25th college reunion. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: The writer, T.K. Chang, is a lawyer based in Hong
Kong who has been involved in matters relating to antitrust in the
computer industry.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 675-word commentary from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
