<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DEPLETED URANIUM: THE EVIDENCE LIES DYING IN BASRA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Provocative Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S BACKGROUNDER: ``Independent'' correspondent Robert
Fisk has long denounced the use of depleted uranium (DU) shells in
both the Gulf War and NATO's conflict in Kosovo last year. After
repeatedly citing evidence of an alarming increase in cancer cases
linked to DU, particularly in the southern Iraqi city of Basra _ as
well as its possible link to the deadly ``Gulf War Syndrome'' in
Allied troops _ Fisk and several human-rights groups have now
pressured scientists from Britain's Royal Society to carry out an
independent investigation into the dangers of depleted uranium.) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ In Iraq, there are doctors aplenty who would like to
meet the six scientists from Britain's Royal Society chosen Monday
to investigate the damage, human and environmental, wreaked by
Western use of depleted uranium (DU) shells in both the Gulf War
and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the main Basra teaching hospital, the cancer sufferers who
live near the fields where depleted uranium shells (DU) were fired
by the hundreds in 1991 queue at the door of the tiny cancer clinic
each morning.
</P>
<P>
   But will the British scientists meet them? Will they go to Iraq
and study the documentation of Basra's leading cancer specialist,
Dr. Jawad al-Ali, who has maps showing the rate of leukemia growth
in the areas where Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's tanks were torn
apart by DU in the last days of the war?
</P>
<P>
   I think not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-COVERUP-URANIUM-IRAQ-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VETERANS OF GULF WAR WELCOME NEW DU POISONING TESTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY JOHN DAVISON, The Independent of London &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ A team of scientists from Britain's Royal Society is to
carry out an independent investigation into the dangers of depleted
uranium (DU), amid growing evidence that use of the material in
shells and missiles is a cause of Gulf War Syndrome and has led to
an increase in cancers among those in close contact with the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The move will fuel accusations by veterans and human-rights
groups that inquiries so far undertaken by Britain's Ministry of
Defense (MoD) have been little short of a whitewash.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons were first used by British and American troops
during the Gulf War, and they have been the subject of controversy
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   A recent series of tests on British veterans suffering from Gulf
War Syndrome found DU traces in 30 out of 48 cases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-NEW-LOOK-GULFWARSYNDROME-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish these articles, they must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
