<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-27 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR ELIAN TO RETURN HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the center of the maelstrom stands a 6-year-old boy. Just a
little kid.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what Elian Gonzalez really thinks _ though there
are plenty of people who seem willing to think for him.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, braving the Straits of Florida like thousands of
refugees before him, he landed near Fort Lauderdale aboard a raft.
Seven people died on the trip while only three survived it. Elian's
mother was among the casualties.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief hospitalization, Elian was released to relatives
in Miami, and ceased being a mere child. He became a celebrity,
then the unwitting pawn in a political chess match.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to end the game. It's time for Elian to be returned to
Cuba and reunited with his father and grandparents. Time to stop
chronicling his every move, showering him with gifts and trips to
Disney World. Time for the clock to strike midnight, and for him to
return to his real life.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment of his arrival, Elian has been used in the fight
against Fidel Castro's regime. Exile activists in Miami quickly
found allies to block his return to Cuba. One of the first to dash
into the spotlight was Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire, who
proclaimed to waiting television crews that he would sponsor
legislation to keep Elian in the United States. What this has to do
with the Granite State is anyone's guess _ but it is an election
year, and the GOP covets the Cuban-American vote.
</P>
<P>
   For years, America's shores were wide open to refugees from one
of the more repressive regimes in the hemisphere. That changed in
the mid-1990s, when a tide of refugees ran headlong into
anti-immigration sentiment in other parts of the country. The
standard practice of the past five years has been to return
refugees to Cuba, via the US military installation at Guantanamo
Bay. But not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, supporters of asylum for Elian are on thin ice, and
they know it. For all their claims that he must not be thrust back
into the arms of an evil nation, it is not enough simply to be a
refugee from a communist country. There must be a well-founded
claim that one would personally face persecution if returned, which
is not true in this case. Just the opposite, Elian would likely
return to Cuba as a national hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the basis of his claim _ that he comes from Cuba?''
asked Ira Kurzban, a renowned immigration lawyer in Miami. ``If
that were the standard, we'd have another 5 or 6 million Cubans in
the country, and probably a billion Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the idea that custody, which legally rests now with
Attorney General Janet Reno, should be granted to his distant
relatives in Miami, both state and federal law give heavy priority
to parents. No one has made a serious claim that his father is an
unfit parent, only that he lives in an unfit country. That isn't
the legal standard.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Elian's father has called for his return to
Cuba. Those pleas have counted for little in some quarters, shot
down by those who, to give them the benefit of every doubt, find it
immoral to ship a child from a free country to one under communist
rule. Elian's father, they insist, must have been coerced.
</P>
<P>
   Few political figures tap raw emotions like Castro. For two
generations of exiles, especially in Miami, he has been the
ultimate frustration, the immoveable force. Even after
assassination attempts and 40 years of protest and economic
embargo, he is still there. Nearly a decade after communism
collapsed in most other places, he remains in power, smoking cigars
and making very long speeches.
</P>
<P>
   One activist told the Miami Herald a couple of weeks ago, ``This
boy must not become a trophy for Fidel.'' But does it follow that
he must become a trophy for the other side?
</P>
<P>
   The law at every level encourages uniting families, yet in this
case that commitment evaporates. Reno, who could have settled this
with early decisive action, waffled instead. No state judge in
Miami, where judges are elected, is going to send Elian back to
Cuba. The White House seems happy to leave the case, and the
political fallout, to Congress. All sides are showing political
courage as we've come to know it.
</P>
<P>
   All but lost in this is a child. One who must have little sense
of what is happening around him, who probably thinks TV trucks
follow everyone in this strange new country. It's no way for a
child for grow up, as the prize in a war. It isn't just the law
that demands his return to his father. Common decency does as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker can be reached by e-mail at walker(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
