<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERS-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF OF MASS., N.H. ELDERLY WITHOUT DRUG COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Half of all elders in Massachusetts and New Hampshire
lack any insurance coverage for prescription drugs, a new survey
has found, magnifying the problem beyond earlier estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely cited previous figure, used by the
pharmaceutical industry, is that one-third of Americans over age 65
lack drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey, made available to The Boston Globe Wednesday,
``indicates there is a higher proportion of elders than we thought
who have no drug coverage at all,'' said Nancy Turnbull, a Harvard
School of Public Health researcher involved in the survey. ``I
really think the crisis we have in prescription drug coverage is
getting dramatically worse in a very short amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The data come at a time when prescription drug coverage is
rising on the national political agenda, with proliferating
proposals from both parties in Congress and a surge in state
legislation on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   A working group of the US Conference of Mayors Wednesday passed
a strongly worded resolution calling on Congress to add
prescription drug coverage to Medicare, investigate price
regulation of pharmaceuticals, and consider a ``windfall profits''
tax on pharmacuetical companies to fund drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're raising the visibility of this issue among mayors,''
said Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino, who sponsored the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical industry representatives have met with top
Clinton administration officials twice this month to discuss adding
drug coverage to Medicare. An industry-connected group has abruptly
changed the tone of television ads on Medicare drug coverage, from
one warning of government interference to a more conciliatory
search for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of frustrated people throughout the country
and they're very active in expressing their frustration,'' said
Jeffrey Trewhitt, a spokesman for the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America. ``We've got to be aware of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Four out of five Massachusetts and New Hampshire residents 65
and older say prescription drug coverage and other health issues
will be important factors in the way they cast their election-year
ballots, the new survey found.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more than half of the surveyed elders said the health
positions of presidential candidates will be an ``important
factor'' in their vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those numbers are very high,'' said Brad Bannon of Bannon
Communications Research, a Washington polling firm that conducted
the survey among 400 Massachusetts and New Hampshire elders. The
survey has a 5-point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the surveyed elders said they often worried
about not being to afford prescription drugs or out-of-pocket
medical costs. This was more than those who said they worried about
not being able to choose their own doctors and hospitals or not
being able to get needed tests and other medical services.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was commissioned by the Massachusetts Health Policy
Forum, a group of academic institutions and consumer organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers not connected with the new survey said its
finding that half of all elders have no drug coverage may actually
understate the problem, since many elders who do have pharmacy
insurance often have inadequate or only intermittent coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to adjust for how lousy the coverage is in many
plans, a 50 percent coverage rate is really a gross underestimate
of the need,'' said Stephen Soumerai of Harvard Medical School and
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR-2ND     01-27 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ATLANTA: ... point output.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``So we had to throw,'' said Steckel. ``You can't get 35 points
running the football. So we just came out and threw the ball all
over the lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two times in all. McNair completed 21 of those passes for
341 yards in the 1-point squeaker. ``He liked that,'' said Steckel.
</P>
<P>
   Probably because it rekindled such fond memories. During his
glory days at Alcorn, 341 yards would have represented about three
quarters of production.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the collegiate level, that's what he did _ the vertical
passing game,'' said his Alcorn coach Cardell Jones. ``There wasn't
a pass he couldn't throw. He can throw that 20-yard out, the
toughest pass there is, and throw it on a line.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones should know. He was about the only college coach willing
to put the ball in McNair's hands.
</P>
<P>
   McNair came out of tiny, remote Mount Olive, Miss., where he and
four siblings were raised by their mother, Lucille, in a trailer
home. He had his pick of Division 1-A powers. Miami, Mississippi
State, Florida, and Notre Dame all wanted him. As a defensive back.
McNair didn't want that. Or them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My decision was based at what level does Steve McNair want to
play at in college,'' he said. ``I wanted to be a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   His problem was that in addition to his passing prowess, he had
led Mississippi defensive backs in interceptions. That was the
statistic that interested the big football schools. Which was
Jones's good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had done a lot of work studying him,'' said Jones. ``I saw
he had a fluid motion, about 4.4 or 4.45 speed (in the 40-yard
dash), and he was as elusive as any tailback. I don't think (the
high-profile colleges) realized what an impact he could make on
offense. I've always felt you couldn't have a good offense without
a triggerman.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones hadn't intended to give McNair the gun so quickly. He
had a junior installed as the starter and, like the Oilers, planned
to groom McNair gradually.
</P>
<P>
   The freshman toppled that timetable in a hurry. In his first
scrimmage, he hit all eight of his passes, of every sort. In his
second scrimmage, he went 10 for 12. And in the season opener,
against one of Eddie Robinson's legendary Grambling powerhouses,
Alcorn struggled early, so Jones threw in McNair to see what he
could do. McNair proceeded to throw Grambling for a loop. He
accumulated 447 yards in total offense, accounted for 3 TDs, and
led Alcorn 87 yards for the winning score in the final two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The aerial circus was on, only to be grounded by professional
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Jones finds that somewhat curious, but he understands the
context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is a tremendous passer,'' said the coach. ``But I know
he's a great team player and I know he wants to fit in to the team
confines. He's totally unselfish.''
</P>
<P>
   His Titans teammates fully appreciate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the situation, and McNair knows that people
think he is not going to win,'' said fullback Lorenzo Neal. ``And
he just wins. He finds a way to win, whether they're scoring 14
points or 41 points. All he does is get the wins.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the carping continues that he's not a total
quarterback, that's the only quarterback total that matters to
McNair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      01-27 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION INTEREST SEEMS ON THE SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution have compiled one of the best
attendance records in Major League Soccer. But after four
successive losing seasons, the buzz around the team appears to be
leveling off, judging by the lack of media at the Foxboro Stadium
bubble this week.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the lack of attention is timing and the
inhospitable combination of cold weather and indoor training.
Interest should increase once the regular season draws near _ the
Revolution visit Miami March 18 _ but four years of on-field
underachieving have done less to stimulate than to stifle
imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we achieve good things this year,''
midfielder Leonel Alvarez said Wednesday. ``We need to play well
and get results at the beginning of the season to recapture the
fans who have gone away because of losing.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 410,000 spectators attended soccer matches at Foxboro
Stadium last year, but the most spectacular attendances were for
the MLS Cup and Women's World Cup matches. The average Revolution
crowd was 16,629, a decrease of about 2,000 per game from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the last two seasons, the Revolution won only 16 of 64
games in regulation time, and most of those victories could be
credited to the goalkeeping of Walter Zenga last year and his
coaching the year before.
</P>
<P>
   So, managing director Sunil Gulati and coach Fernando Clavijo
have started to make changes. They have yet to restore the defense,
but the points of reference in midfield and attack are being
established with Alvarez, Eduardo Hurtado, and Mauricio Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are clicking with each other and I am seeing some
very good soccer,'' Clavijo said. ``This team can only improve. And
I am not going to rest until we make improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   It was pointed out that there is no guarantee that conditions
will improve with the Revolution, who have finished with the
ninth-, eighth-, 12th-, and 11th-best records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can get worse,'' Clavijo said. ``But not with me. Even
if I have to play with five rookies, we will have a good team. Even
if you have good players do not necessarily mean you will have a
good team. But I think we are two starting players, plus a good
bench, away from having a team which can challenge for the
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution will have to galvanize quickly. They will
play five exhibition games in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., starting Feb.
8 and four in Guadalajara, Mexico, starting Feb. 29. The first four
MLS games are in Miami, Tampa Bay (March 25), Los Angeles (April
1), and Dallas (April 8).
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get results wherever you are playing, and if you
are a good team you can do that,'' Alvarez said. ``The important
thing is to qualify for the playoffs and the way you accomplish
that is by working every day toward a goal. All of that starts now.
And we want to achieve more than just make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only been together for three days, so it is hard to
make any profound statements. But there is harmony and friendship
on this team and the coaching staff is not only serious and
responsible, but also part of this harmony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
