<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCIS' ISOLATION SHOWS TYSON IN CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Who the story is was clear from the empty seats on the
bus to Aldershot Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime officials had arranged a two-hour bus trip for the
media to the British Army barracks where 35-year-old Julius Francis
was preparing, under military supervision, for his Saturday night
bit of hand-to-hand combat with Mike Tyson. The theory was a story
or two would come out of this visit to the tiny cubicle where
Francis has been bunking each day while Tyson luxuriated in a hotel
suite at the Grosvenor House when he wasn't across the way at the
posher Park Lane Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It was costing Tyson $750 a day for lodging (meals not included)
as he prepared to earn $12 million. It was costing Francis 28
pounds five (also known as about $50 a day) for three hots and a
cot at Aldershot. Obviously, this was an interesting story. It was
also a story only five people chose to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   That's because this week, as usual, Tyson is the story in the
United Kingdom, just as he is when he fights in the United States.
He is the one people are pursuing. He is the reason 21,000 tickets
were sold in less than two days at new MEN Arena in Manchester. He
is the reason arrangements were made by Showtime officials to air
the fight on tape delay at home. That way it could be shown live on
prime time pay-per-view in England, instead of in the wee hours of
the morning as is usually the case when a major American boxing
star comes to Europe to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Everything being said or done this week is about Tyson, which is
not only to be expected but was part of the plan formed by trainers
Tommy Brooks and Jay Bright, manager Shelly Finkel, and Showtime
executives from the start. The idea was to find some way to rebuild
the confidence Tyson once seemed to possess in abundance when he
was in the ring. Some way to remind him ``TYSON'' still exists,
even if Tyson doesn't quite believe it any more.
</P>
<P>
   Buster Douglas took some of that away from him. Evander
Holyfield erased the bulk of it when he gave Tyson a schoolyard
whipping, and then broke his mind down in their rematch and forced
him to disqualify himself for illegal ear tasting. Then life piled
on Tyson, to hear him tell it, and he became a professional victim.
Not an interview went by in which he didn't proclaim some form of
slight or unwarranted attack had been put upon him.
</P>
<P>
   In the States, the public grew weary of that. But it's all new
over here, so he has been lent a more sympathetic ear. And what has
grown from that, Tyson's people believe, is a renewed belief that,
as Jesse Jackson would put it, ``I am somebody!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's refreshed,'' said Bright, who has known Tyson since they
grew up in Cus D'Amato's legendary old farmhouse in Catskill, N.Y.
``He has a renewed interest in his performance in front of people.
The public reaction here has made him want to perform exquistely in
front of them on Saturday. He hasn't felt that way for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's people will tell you he hasn't felt that way because he
has been beaten up by guys like Holyfield and beaten down by the
press and the public in the States who, he says, have tormented and
exploited him.
</P>
<P>
   To a degree, Tyson is right. But at the end of the day, it all
comes back to him. To the choices he has made, and the lifestyle he
has led, and continues to lead even here.
</P>
<P>
   For example, TYSON made headlines this week when Tyson spent
$1.6 million on an emerald bracelet and watch combination for TYSON
at a time when Tyson still has serious financial woes and unpaid
legal bills back home. Over here, it was a brilliant shopping
spree. In the United States, it would have been the actions of a
lunatic who can't count.
</P>
<P>
   And so you have it. Same guy, two perspectives, one attempt to
renew an aging fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be good for him,'' Finkel said. ``The reception
has been incredible. Even before the problem with his last fight
(when he was nearly disqualified for hitting Orlin Norris after the
bell and ended up with a one-round no-contest in Las Vegas), I told
Mike I wanted to go to someplace outside the U.S. I thought it
would be good for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mob scene everywhere he goes and that's renewed him a
little bit. He goes for a run in the park and it's like locust
following him. Here the people just want to see Mike. They don't
even care who the opponent is.''
</P>
<P>
   That was made obvious by the 30 empty seats on the bus to
Aldershot. Few people wanted to talk with Francis, a born-again
ex-con with a story of his own to tell. It's an interesting story
too and we'll get to it one day if we have enough time before he's
left unconscious on the floor . But for now the story is TYSON
reborn, not merely The Troubles of Tyson, which was the idea all
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different attitude over here,'' Finkel said.
``They see him differently.''
</P>
<P>
   They do indeed. He is still a star here not merely a freak show
or a train wreck waiting to happen. He is still ``Iron Mike'' as
they call him even now, long after the iron has begun to rust. In
the United Kingdom, he is ``MIKE TYSON'' and his handlers are
hoping he'll feel the same way by the time this trip is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm TYSON,'' Tyson said. ``At home I'm Mike. He's a
different person. He's a father and husband. But out here I'm
TYSON. I'm nobody. You understand what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Not really, but what he probably means is there is Mike Tyson
the man and then there is the phenomenon known as TYSON.
</P>
<P>
   So far Mike Tyson growls like TYSON and hits like TYSON and
inspires fear like TYSON and sells tickets like TYSON. Whether he
can fight like TYSON anymore is a different matter however, a fact
the former champion admitted no amount of hype can change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not all the way back yet,'' said Tyson, now 33. ``My
balance. My footwork. I'm working on the little things, because if
you don't remember the little things, you won't remember the big
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm doing some things better than when I was champion.
I know I punch harder. But I have a litle ways to go yet. I just
wish I was as good as everyone says I look.''
</P>
<P>
   So there it was, buried deep but not yet washed away in the
10-day explosion of hype and hysteria that has surrounded him in
England. Even amidst all that, the doubt remains.
</P>
<P>
   It lingers inside Tyson even as the public in England has
elevated him back to a sporting superstar, hanging behind iron
gates in front of his hotel all day in hopes of getting just a
glimpse of him.
</P>
<P>
   TYSON may have been reincarnated here but doubts do not
disappear as quickly as a star can be reborn. Doubts remain inside
about many things. Deep inside.
</P>
<P>
   But after 10 days of hype there was no doubt about who the story
is in England today.
</P>
<P>
   All those empty bus seats to Aldershot proved that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
