<HEADLINE>
CREATING OFFENSE HIGH ON BRUINS' CHECKLIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Firewagon hockey it is not, but the Bruins have been
noticeably more proactive, sometimes even risk-takers, on the ice
in the last week. They've abandoned the neutral-zone trap and gone
back, at least in tiny spurts, to a slightly uptempo forechecking
game that has two forwards pressuring the defense.
</P>
<P>
   New century. Old-time hockey. Not only are the results slightly
better, but it's a more interesting _ dare we say entertaining? _
product to watch.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, is it more fun?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it is,'' said veteran forward Steve Heinze. ``It's
more fun when you're forcing guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It was noticeable Thursday night in Tampa that the Bruins,
dropping like a rock in the Eastern Conference standings the last
two months, finally moved away from their mid-ice tug of war that
was quickly making them a non-contender. They exchanged a few
back-and-forth rushes with the Lightning and finished with a 4-2
victory. They weren't quite as bold two nights later against the
Panthers, a 4-3 loss in overtime, but again there were some flashes
of speed and some improved playmaking. Ditto Monday night in
another overtime loss, 4-3, to the Flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting there,'' said Heinze. ``It's so close, you can
almost taste it. You score a couple of goals, win a game, and it's
like, `OK, here it comes again.' It's like it's right there, just
out of your grasp. We're not quite there yet, but I think we're
getting closer.''
</P>
<P>
   At least they are skating, moving their legs, proof that they're
more involved. The trap worked well for two seasons, the Bruins
able to clog up the middle, typically with only one forward
forechecking, and win their share of games with defense and
goaltending and an offense initiated by opposition mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   For myriad reasons, that laid-back, wait-and-see,
cash-in-on-miscues approach failed miserably over the course of
40-plus games this season. They have 32 games remaining, including
Thursday's visit by the Canadiens. It appears the Bruins' only hope
to reach the playoffs is now pegged to their ability to get back to
pursuing the puck, create their chances, and turn on-ice
opportunities into on-the-scoreboard results. Mired in the trap,
they barely were getting a handful of legitimate scoring chances
each night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to create more offense,'' said veteran
winger Rob DiMaio. ``It's a little different out there, that's all.
Your first thought is to react one way _ because you've been
playing a certain system for a long time _ and this game is all
reaction. Is it more fun? Well, it's not that much different,
really. The key is, get two men on their (defensemen), limit their
time and space. We were so trap-oriented before that maybe we were
backing off too much.''
</P>
<P>
   As the forwards attempt to keep the play up ice, and keep play
toward their offensive net, the Boston defensemen also must move up
a zone. Rather than being backed into their own zone, with play
headed their way, ideally they're in the neutral zone, taking the
puck away and springing the transition game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more involved on defense,'' said Kyle McLaren. ``We're
standing guys up more in the neutral zone this way. But still, our
No. 1 issue is defense. We have to play solid defensively, because
we can't run and gun with teams. But if our forwards move up, we
have to move up, too, you've always got to be aware of keeping that
gap closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the new approach, there undoubtedly will be growing pains.
Case in point: the overtime goals by Florida and Calgary. But for a
club that was destined to be booted from the playoffs before the
calendar flipped to March, the forechecking game essentially
presents itself as a 20-man lifeboat in a sea of certain defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Somethin' was broke, and for now, the forecheck is a possible
fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pressure more, you'll give up chances,'' said coach
Pat Burns, who slowly has yielded to the inevitable. ``But, you'll
probably get more, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
