<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON COACHES GO WITH THE RAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The jury is in and the verdict goes to St. Louis.
Unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Super Bowl participants, St. Louis and Tennessee, had
four common opponents this season (San Francisco, Cleveland,
Cincinnati, and Baltimore).
</P>
<P>
   This week, the coaches from those teams _ Steve Mariucci, 49ers;
Chris Palmer, Browns; Bruce Coslet, Bengals; and offensive
coordinator Matt Cavanaugh of the Ravens (head coach Brian Billick
was in the Caribbean on a family vacation and could not be reached)
were asked to analyze the game, pick a winner, and a possible
score.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what they had to say:
</P>
<P>
   --Mariucci: ``I would have felt a lot better about making this
pick before St. Louis played Tampa Bay. I didn't think Tampa could
play them that tough (11-6), and it's the first time I saw St.
Louis a little uncertain this year on offense. Plus, Tennessee is
coming into this game playing the best football of the season. They
seem to be hitting a peak. We beat Tennessee early in the year, but
they weren't playing the way they are now. (Quarterback Steve)
McNair was out of the lineup then. Neil O'Donnell played. McNair is
an unusual weapon. He showed that in Jacksonville. When you have a
passer who can run out of there and make four or five big plays in
a game in the running game like he did, then this will put added
pressure on the St. Louis defense. I think Tennessee will try to
contain (Marshall Faulk) and then come after (Rams quarterback)
Warner. I think it's going to be a very close game. Turnovers will
be the difference. Tennessee has been winning games getting
turnovers, and making the most out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``An important factor will be the Tennessee kickers against the
St. Louis returners. (Tony) Horne on kickoff and (Az-Zahir) Hakim
on punt returns, are explosive. (Titan punter Craig) Hentrich is
going to have to spot the ball well in places where the coverages
teams have a good shot at pinning those guys in on the sideline.
Same way on the kickoffs. I watched the film of the first game they
played each other. Tennessee got three turnovers in the first half
and went up 21-0, then St. Louis adjusted and dominated the second
half. They lost, but they were the better team at the end. I like
St. Louis in a close game, 28-27, but turnovers will make the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   --Cavanaugh: ``St. Louis is a big-play team, and you can get
some big plays on the Tennessee secondary. We played them late in
the year, and we had a lot of big plays on them, and we don't have
all of the weapons that St. Louis does. Tampa did a great job in
shutting down St. Louis by playing a tough zone defense, and making
it difficult for Warner to throw on time. He was out of rhythm.
Tennessee plays one style of defense, and one only. Most of the
time they are almost in an eight-man front when they move (Blaine)
Bishop up there, and their corners are in man-to-man. It's very
hard, I think, to play St. Louis man-to-man. Tennessee has to count
on Eddie George having a big day running the ball, and controlling
the clock. McNair is not a big threat in the passing game, so St.
Louis will concentrate on stopping George, and forcing Tennessee to
throw more, which they don't want to do. The game is on turf and
St. Louis is the faster team. I think it will be St. Louis,
27-17.''
</P>
<P>
   --Coslet: ``I love the St. Louis defense. Everyone talks about
their offense, but to me, their defense is as good as any team we
played against this year. This (defensive end) Kevin Carter is an
outstanding player. Don't sell their defense short. I'm not sold on
McNair. I don't think he is a great passer. He is a wonderful
playmaker, and a great runner. He had won a game late in the season
when he was unconscious and had a spectacular day against
Jacksonville, but outside of that he has been just average throwing
the ball. And it will hurt them that (Yancey) Thigpen is not
playing. He's their best wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched Warner all year and I think the kid is for real.
He can play. He is a very accurate passer and what he really does
well is get the ball to the receivers on the front half of their
body, so they can catch it in stride and keep going upfield with
it. This is why (St. Louis's) wide receivers are so good after the
catch. He hits them on the run. (Coach Jeff) Fisher does a great
job with the Tennessee defense. They are a physical bunch. They
always have seven or eight guys around the ball, playing hard,
looking to strip it and get turnovers. If (the Titans) play their
usual type of defense, then I think St. Louis will hurt them in the
passing game. The score for me would be St. Louis, 27-17.''
</P>
<P>
   --Palmer: ``Tennessee plays an automatic (defensive) front and
the same coverage all year. They work everything they do off of
that. A big part of what they did was (free safety) Marcus
Robertson. He's a very good player, and important to their scheme.
It's going to hurt them with him not playing. (Anthony) Dorsett is
an athletic kid, with good speed, but the way St. Louis plays
offense, is going to cause Dorsett a lot of problems. St. Louis is
shifting and moving players around on offense every play. Dorsett
has never played against something like this before. I think there
will be many times in the game he will be confused, and if he does
make some big mistakes, then St. Louis will take advantage of that
and make big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``On turf, St. Louis will have the speed advantage. I said last
week before the Jacksonville game, and I'll say it again: You must
tackle McNair. If youdon't tackle him and get him on the ground, he
will kill you with his running. He is harder to tackle than Eddie
George. And if St. Louis doesn't get him on the ground, he'll make
big plays against them, just like he did in Jacksonville. To me a
big question for St. Louis is can (smallish linebacker London)
Fletcher tackle McNair? I think St. Louis will win something like
35-14. Tennessee will need a lot of turnovers to stay with them and
with Robertson and Thigpen out with injuries, I don't think they
will play as well as they have been.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consensus seemed to be that St. Louis has the edge because:
</P>
<P>
   1.) Tennessee has key players injured.
</P>
<P>
   2.) McNair cannot score a lot of points in the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   3.) The Rams have the better chance to gain the field-position
advantage with their two exceptional return men.
</P>
<P>
   4.) Tennessee will not be able to run the ball consistently
against the Rams' league-leading run defense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
