<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING OUTRAGE TO BETTER USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Linda,'' says a friend, ``you have a problem with outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me,'' I reply. ``I'm in the process of solving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Let me give you an example.
</P>
<P>
   I own some knee-high winter boots that look as if they're made
of an exotic golden fur. I saw an identical pair years ago in a
Denver airport on a beautiful, long-legged blonde rushing for a
plane, and immediately realized that the only thing she had that I
could ever possess was her boots. Finding a pair, I bought them and
have been wearing them every winter for the past 10 years. They
create quite a stir wherever I go, especially with youngsters. This
day I'm in a doctor's waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at those boots, Mommy!'' whispers a 4-year-old. As she
and her younger sister stare, I call them over and deliver my
standard speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are polar bear boots,'' I explain as they pet the
synthetic fur, ``but they're not real polar bear fur. They're fake
polar bear fur because I would never, never hurt a real bear just
so I could have a pair of boots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would,'' proclaims the mother loudly.
</P>
<P>
   What would you do?
</P>
<P>
   One choice is to say, ``People are jerks.'' Shrug. Thumb through
a magazine. Go numb rather than crazy. This response unfortunately
is not available to a person whose idea of true happiness consists
of observing a family of deer for hours at the Grand Canyon,
watching beavers at dusk in Vermont, and looking forward to seeing
the pair of woodpeckers who visit her bird feeder every day.
Little, big, reptile, mammal, crawling, flying, swimming _ it's all
the same joy to me as long as the creatures with whom I'm sharing
life on this planet are wild and free. All it took for me to
encounter the depths of my own capacity for awe was to follow the
elaborately well-executed and well-traveled path created by
leaf-cutter ants for a quarter of a mile in the jungle in Belize.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of one of history's greatest period of mass
extinctions, my passion for all living things is a liability, not a
strength, but it does make it impossible for me to brush off a
mom's suggestion that a dead polar bear is a small price to pay for
a handsome pair of boots.
</P>
<P>
   I could have confronted her. I can imagine options, from
engaging in an earnest discussion to hitting her over the head with
my boot, but what would I have accomplished? I know a futile
undertaking when I see one.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I decided to label this mom's words my Outrage of the
Day. It became that day's sign that civilization is definitely
doomed, that our undue influence on earth will end because of our
own fatal limitations, and that nature will then promote some
other, more promising creature into the limelight. Why I feel
compelled to reach this conclusion almost every day of my life, I
do not know. (``Mom, was it something you said?'' ``Dad, am I your
pessimism recycled?'')
</P>
<P>
   Still, being who I am, I can't avoid outrage entirely. I can't
imagine ever accepting insanity as normative _ whether it's as
seemingly insignificant as
``just-another-example-of-pop-culture-fun-and-games'' or something
as disheartening as 
``man's-all-too-usual-inhumanity-to-his-perceived-as-loathsome-enemy
-of-the-moment.'' But given my nature, I have figured out that a
single outrage works just as well as 50.
</P>
<P>
   Just think what can happen if I succeed at this.
</P>
<P>
   One really good Outrage per Day confirms that I am a person who
still cares about the degree to which love is absent from so many
aspects of life on this earth. Task accomplished. I can now move on
to the real business of my life: trying to make my own love felt by
the few people whose lives I actually influence in the small space
I actually inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, I suspect being outraged at others is one way of
avoiding disappointment in myself. It is my way of diminishing by
comparison my myriad failures to follow my own higher impulses. It
is also a way of dissipating energy I could put to far better use
by making reparations for acts and attitudes I don't want to take
responsibility for.
</P>
<P>
   Someone else will have to take over my portion of outrage about
Pinochet's callousness, about corporate greed, about demonizing the
tiny island of Cuba, about widespread indifference to the plight of
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'll work on being a little less callous, a little less
greedy, a little less demonizing, a little less indifferent myself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
