<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-27 1592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING TOGETHER ON COMING APART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Child psychologist Arnold Stolberg of Richmond, Va., had
counseled nearly 500 divorcing parents on how to talk to their
children when he found himself needing to follow his own advice.
But even years of professional experience didn't prepare him for
how his eldest son, then 9, would respond to the news of his
parents' impending divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh told a joke and walked away,'' says Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, his voice still registers surprise.
</P>
<P>
   How parents tell their children that they're breaking up and how
children react to that news is complicated stuff. For instance,
it's important to know a child's stage of development because it
affects how she'll cope, but stage of development isn't an
influence we need to consider in the telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is devastating news at any age. What you say isn't that
different for different-aged children,'' says Carlotta Miles, a
child psychiatrist and psychoanalyst in private practice in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there are some guidelines:
</P>
<P>
   --Be brief. Miles and Stolberg recommend 25 words or less:
``Your mother/father and I are getting a divorce. Your mom isn't
going to live here anymore; she's getting her own apartment.''
``Children are too overwhelmed to hear anything else right away,''
says Stolberg. A specialist in children's adjustment to divorce, he
is director of doctoral training in clinical child psychology at
Virginia Commonwealth University .
</P>
<P>
   --Tell them together. This is preferable if it's possible. It
eliminates the possibility of them thinking, ``Maybe Daddy doesn't
really want to,'' or ``I can talk Mom out of it.'' If you can't
tell them together, says Miles, be clear it's a joint decision:
``Mom and I both decided . . .''
</P>
<P>
   --Be timely. As soon as you reach a decision and you have a
plan, tell your children, says child psychologist and author Donald
Gordon. ``There's no such thing as delaying the agony, plus you
don't want to risk they'll hear from someone else,'' he says. A
professor at Ohio University, Gordon is co-author of ``What About
the Children: A Guide for Divorced and Divorcing Parents'' (Center
for Divorce Education).
</P>
<P>
   There are caveats, however. Breaking the news too far in
advance, a month for instance, produces more anxiety, not less.
``Children feel the stress of living in a toxic environment and
feel caught in the middle as mediator or therapist,'' says child
psychologist Anthony E. Wolf of Longmeadow. If they have too much
time, they also begin to doubt that it will really happen; when it
does, it's like a double whammy. Stolberg prefers that you tell
them two weeks in advance; Wolf and Gordon, two or three days. They
all advise having the first conversation early Friday evening, not
close to bedtime, so children have you with them over the weekend
to ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   --Be honest. Say ``We're still trying to work things out'' only
if you really are. If the separation is a prelude to divorce, say
so. ``The less room for the imagination to flourish, the better,''
says Stolberg, although there will always be some of that no matter
what you say. If a spouse leaves abruptly and you are in shock, go
for honesty but stop short of blaming the other parent. Not ``I
can't believe your mother did this,'' but: ``This is hard for me,
too. As soon as I figure out what's happening, I'll tell you.''
Honesty also counts in how you paint the future. It's OK to say
``Just think: You won't have to listen to our fights anymore,'' but
not ``You're so lucky! You're going to have two homes now!''
``That's a crock and every kid knows it,'' says Miles.
</P>
<P>
   Once the news is out in the open, children of every age need
many follow-up conversations, preferably with each parent. Don't
expect them to come to you, though. Josh Stolberg, for instance,
kept to himself in those first few days. When his father would try
to get him to talk, he'd say, ``I don't want to. I'm OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Letting it go at that is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Stolberg knew that since Josh was 9, his reaction was at least
partly developmental: ``He thought that by not talking about it, it
wouldn't bother him.'' So Stolberg kept going back to his son, not
just to let him know he was available but also to send a message
that talking is important, even when it's uncomfortable. It helps a
child when you are concrete: ``If you don't express your feelings
about it, you'll spend your time in school or on the football field
thinking upsetting thoughts, and then you'll flunk a test or run
into a tree because you were distracted and not concentrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though children of all ages will ask why you're getting a
divorce, the question has different meaning depending on where they
are developmentally. Children 7 or under, for instance, are
egocentric so Miles translates their ``Why?'' as, ``What about me?
What will happen to me?''
</P>
<P>
   A good response is to talk about what will stay the same and
what will change: ``I'm going to live at Nana's and you and your
mom will still live here. You'll go to the same school, and sleep
in the same bedroom. We both still love you and we will both still
take care of you. What's different is that I'll talk to you every
day on the phone. I'll see you on weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think your young child really does want to know why,
don't say, ``Because we stopped loving each other.'' That's
frightening. ``They'll think you could stop loving them, too,''
says Gordon. Answers he sanctions: ``We argued too much; we
disagreed too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Children as old as 12 typically think the divorce is their
fault: ``I didn't eat my vegetables; I didn't clean my room.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf advises addressing this thought early on, even if a child
doesn't voice it: ``Tell her, `This has nothing to do with anything
you did. It's not your fault.' '' Repeat it often, he says, even if
she tells you with great annoyance, ``I know that!'' Wolf is author
of ``Why Did You Have to Get a Divorce? And When Can I Get a
Hamster?'' (Noonday Press).
</P>
<P>
   When teens ask why, parents tend to think we can be truthful,
especially if they verbalize our thoughts: ``This wouldn't happen
if Dad weren't so selfish.'' This is a developmental response,
however, not a cognitive one. ``They feel betrayed. They're looking
for someone to blame: `Dad is breaking up our family! How could he
do this to me?' '' says Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   He tells parents to resist the urge to agree with the assessment
or to assign blame ourselves. That's information and a level of
intimacy that's too much for even a mature teen, says Miles. Not
only will she feel responsible for you, but it could also put her
in emotional jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you critize the other parent, children take it
personally,'' says Gordon. ``They know they have learned from that
parent or that they have that parent's genes so their thought is,
`If Dad is thoughtless, I must be, too.' '' Indeed, he says teens'
self-esteem often drops during divorce because they take to heart
any negatives they hear about a parent.
</P>
<P>
   In the first month after parents separate, children of all ages
show upset through behavior. Preschoolers may regress or have big
reactions to little things, crying easily, hitting or biting,
overreacting to a sibling's teasing. School-age children's grades
often dip due to loss of concentration. You may also notice a loss
of interest in friends and activities, or a change in eating and
sleeping patterns. Older children may flip-flop from anger to
nonchalance. None of this is abnormal. In fact, says Stolberg,
``the child I worry most about is the one who looks unchanged.
She's trying too hard to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick for parents is not to over- or underreact. Gordon says
the starting point is empathy: ``I know this is hard for you,
probably harder than I realize.''
</P>
<P>
   When children don't talk to you, it's likely because they are
afraid of making you more upset. ``They need explicit permission,''
says Gordon: `` `I want you to know that it's OK to talk to me,
even if it upsets me sometimes. I can handle it.' '' You can ease
the way by making guesses about their distress: ``I bet you feel
really alone, 'cause none of your good friends has ever gone
through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents typically let uncharacteristic behavior pass because
they feel a combination of shock, guilt, sadness, and sympathy. But
the message children take from that is that we don't care anymore
or we're too upset to be a good parent.
</P>
<P>
   That's scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to change your limit-setting, but you also want
to get to the heart of the matter,'' says Stolberg.Point out what
you see _ ``You look sad; I wonder if you're feeling upset about
the divorce'' _ but reinforce limits: ``Even though we're all
upset, there are still rules in our family. You can't hit your
sister/you still have to do your homework.''
</P>
<P>
   As tough as the first month is, Stolberg says, what happens now
sets the stage for later. Knowing that helped him with Josh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a kid who tends to hold things in, so I knew I needed to
keep trying,'' he says. It paid off. Now 15, Josh is doing very
well. ``More than anything, that influences my belief that we need
to help kids not repress feelings,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ A wonderful gift for new parents: ``Baby Love: A
Tradition of Calm Parenting,'' by Maud Bryt (Dell).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz can be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
