<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      01-27 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINT THINNER WILL REMOVE FILM FROM HARDWOOD FLOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Some special stuff for floors was put on my hardwood floors,
and left a film. I would like to remove this film and revarnish,
but how?
</P>
<P>
   D.I., Lynn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It would be nice to know what this ``stuff'' is, because
without knowing, the handyman can only guess. It may be a wax or
polish; there are so many kinds out there that one runs the risk of
ruining a perfectly good varnished floor by choosing one or
another. If the ``stuff'' was buffed by a power buffer, it is wax.
Otherwise it is a self-polishing wax or polish, or even an oil
soap.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what this film is, I think generous use of paint
thinner will remove it. Apply the paint thinner liberally in a
small area, let it sit for two to five minutes without evaporating
(add more if it starts to evaporate), scrub with a soft scrub brush
or sponge, then wipe with a dry cloth. Repeat as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   This will clean the surface and dull the finish, which can be
restored by buffing with a clean cloth. If the floor shines up
again, you may not need another coat of varnish. But if you like,
you can do it anyway by sanding lightly but thoroughly, and
applying one or more coats of high-gloss polyurethane varnish. If
the original varnish is water-based, use that for the finish. If
the original varnish is oil-based, use that.
</P>
<P>
   If the film does not come off, the heck with it; sand the floors
and revarnish. And use an oil-based polyurethane varnish; two coats
are good, three coats better.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, put nothing on a varnished floor. Varnish is its
own protection; any wax, polish, oil, or ``stuff'' is a waste of
money and effort, since it does no good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am refinishing a small floor of wide pine boards. My wife
thinks we can strip it; some of the varnish has worn off, and
something needs to be done. It is only 4 feet square, with another
small area of fir boards that also needs refinishing. Should I use
paint remover or any other stripping material? Or what?
</P>
<P>
   TOM PONTICELLI, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Paint stripper will do a quick job on the varnish, but will
not do much for the worn area. If you like the idea of paint
stripper, that is fine; you can give it a final sanding to lighten
up the worn area.
</P>
<P>
   But since both areas are quite small, I suggest that you rent a
belt sander, and sand the floor with coarse, medium, and fine
sandpaper, just as you would sand a larger floor. The handyman did
this years ago but in two larger rooms, from which he removed the
boards so that the work could be done in a neighbor's garage. He
will never do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Belt sanding is not for entire rooms, but for your small areas
it will be ideal. Then apply three coats of a high-gloss, oil-based
polyurethane varnish. Area rugs will prolong the life of the new
finish, virtually indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I got myself into a mess through my own fault, so can you
help? 1. I cracked a curved plexiglass windowpane. Where can I get
a replacement to match? 2. My glassed-in sunroom is basically
useless; too hot in summer, too cold in winter. I do not have
natural gas. What kind of heat can I use? 3. My terra-cotta tiles
are all white, and no amount of cleaning helps. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   D.S., Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. 1. Try a regular glass store; it might carry what you need or
can bend a piece of acrylic or plexiglass to match. Or, try a
window specialist.
</P>
<P>
   2. There is not much you can do about the heat in the summer
except to open the windows and get some air circulating. In winter,
I would not suggest an electric heater, but what about extending
your present heating system? It is possible with a hot-air or
hot-water system. If your heating system is big enough, it can be
extended to the porch. Or, install a gas fireplace stove _ one in
which you can see the dancing flames _ that is power vented, not
needing a chimney. Since you have no natural gas, you can use
propane, which is expensive, but you will be heating a small area.
Or, install a pellet stove, which is also power vented and really
quite easy to operate. All these stoves are sold by energy and
stove stores such as Energy Unlimited of Wayland.
</P>
<P>
   3. The terra-cotta tiles, also called quarry tiles, are unglazed
and a big pain to keep clean. Water probably caused your tiles to
turn white. To clean, scrub with steel wool dipped in paint
thinner. They will clean up nicely but won't stay clean. To protect
them after cleaning, apply a thin coat of Future, an acrylic finish
that will provide a shine and make the tiles water resistant and
more easily cleaned. Try the Future in an obscure area to make sure
it does not change the color of the tiles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
