<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8113 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PARISH-NURSING-ART-BO     01-27 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARISH-NURSING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PARISH NURSES TEND TO PATIENTS' BODIES AND SOULS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WESTBOROUGH, Mass. _ Julie Basque is a nurse who carries
communion wafers, not catheters.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse who does more ministering than medicating.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse who works for a church, not a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   An example of a new phenomenon driven by intersecting changes
taking place in the health care industry and the religious
community, Basque, who works for St. Luke the Evangelist Church
here, is a kind of cross between a visiting nurse and a eucharistic
minister, a new kind of RN called a parish nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Together with an estimated 150 other parish nurses in the
metropolitan Boston area, and perhaps 6,000 such nurses nationwide,
Basque is helping to usher in a new _ and, for some, unsettling _
era for churches, nursing, and the health care system, as each
adjusts its role in changing times.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers, seeking to keep costs down, are limiting hospital
stays, so more people are returning home requiring follow-up care _
the kind of care parish nurses provide.
</P>
<P>
   Churches, facing declining numbers of priests and nuns, are hard
pressed to find enough clergy to minister to the sick, but also are
seeking to strengthen their connection to communities.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses, their roles at acute-care hospitals reduced as hospital
stays are shortened, are following patients from hospitals into the
community, even as some express doubts whether it is wise for
parishes to pick up the slack left by insurers worried about their
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many people _ sick and well, clergy and laity
_ are expressing an interest in the intersection between physical
and spiritual, or psychological, health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Churches are philosophically coming to accept more ministry by
the laity, state practice laws now permit nurses to function more
independently, and people are looking for alternative ideas about
care,'' said Rosemarie Matheus, director of the Parish Nurse
Preparation Institute at Marquette Univeristy, a Jesuit school in
Milwaukee. ``This started in the late '70s and early '80s, but we
have just come to a point where we have our identity, and the next
step is to validate that we make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Short, director of parish-based health for Caritas
Christi, the Boston Catholic Archdiocese's medical arm, said the
rise of parish nurses is driven by changes in health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are in acute-care hospitals for such a short period of
time now, when they return home somebody else needs to tend to
their heart, mind, and soul,'' he said. ``People face loneliness,
isolation, stress, and a need for spirituality, and by and large a
church is the only community left in our society where people
gather together.''
</P>
<P>
   The beneficiaries are people like Paul Mitchell, a 70-year-old
retired state trooper in Westborough. When doctors said they wanted
to remove his cancerous right lung, Mitchell told his pastor he was
prepared for death. But he lived, and it was living for which he
was unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   A big man at 6 feet 3 inches, Mitchell stopped eating and
dropped 40 pounds. A protruding hip bone caused him pain. Cold
weather made it hard for him even to exercise. A daily communicant
before the surgery, Mitchell is no longer strong enough to get to
church.
</P>
<P>
   So Basque visits Mitchell several times a week. Sitting in a
small living room still decorated with a creche, a doll-sized
procession of the three kings and a Christmas tree adorned with
angels, Basque counsels Mitchell about his health, chats with him
about their shared church community, and then leads him in prayer
and gives him communion from a gold container called a pyx that she
wears around her neck.
</P>
<P>
   Their interaction provides medical and spiritual benefits for
Mitchell. Basque helps him interpret his doctors' instructions,
advocates for him when he needs new medication, and keeps him
connected to the ritual and community of his church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was new to me,'' Mitchell said of parish nursing. ``But
she's been very helpful in her visits to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Parish nursing, which began at a Lutheran hospital in Chicago
two decades ago, is finally spreading to New England, years after
it has taken hold in much of the country. The practice got a
national stamp of approval in 1998, when the American Nurses
Association declared it a new form of practice and laid out a set
of standards for practitioners to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, parish nursing crossed an important threshold last
week, when Boston College inaugurated a joint master's degree in
nursing and pastoral ministry and began offering a new course on
nursing in faith communities.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of parish nursing involves, as its name suggests,
nurses hired by parishes to provide spiritual and medical
assistance to parishioners who are sick, homebound, or in need of
advice. The nurses offer a mix of services: visits, support groups,
counseling, education, advocacy and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why parishes? Because they're the one place in our community
that we all come together,'' said Susan Chase of Boston College's
School of Nursing. ``Why nurses? Nurses understand a lot about the
human condition.''
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of the country, parish nurses are employed by
health care providers. In New England, most parish nurses are
employed by churches or work as volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The Archdiocese of Boston has taken the lead in supporting and
coordinating the work of parish nurses working for a variety of
Christian churches throughout the metropolitan area; in central
Massachusetts, the Worcester County Ecumenical Council plays a
similar role.
</P>
<P>
   Most parish nurses work in the suburbs; parish nursing groups
are working to promote their practice in inner-city churches.
</P>
<P>
   In Westborough, a fast-growing commuter suburb on Interstate
495, there are now four parish nurses, two Catholics and two
Methodists. The two Catholic nurses, Basque and Michelle Parsons,
split a salary only recently paid to a nun.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I thought this was useless, that it would be
stupid for the church to do things other people do,'' said the Rev.
George Lange, pastor of the 1,900-family St. Luke the Evangelist,
who said he worried the nurses would simply duplicate tasks done by
health care or social workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Lange gave it a try. He agreed to pay Basque and Parsons,
who share a position, for a total of 16 hours a week. Pleased with
the results, he now pays them for 50 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people fall through the cracks,'' he said. ``The
parish has all these people who are alone, who are sick and they
(the nurses) see them, and bring them not only spiritual help . . .
but talk about their health.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lange's initial concerns are echoed by others, who believe
it is great to mix health and spirituality, and useful for parishes
to find new ways to connect with parishioners, but who don't want
to make it easier for the health care system to reduce direct
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to fill in cracks that shouldn't be there,''
said Mary Rose Leach, parish nurse coordinator in Worcester. ``The
parish nurse optimally is working with the health care system to
get the best possible health care for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Parish nurses are barred from conducting invasive medical
procedures. The most elaborate medical tasks they do is taking
blood pressure. But they often act as advocates or interpreters for
patients confused by their medical situation and unable or
unwilling to push for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly what she does is she guides people through medical
mazes,'' said the Rev. Mark Beckwith, pastor of All Saints
Episcopal Church in Worcester, describing the medical services
offered by his parish nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, for example, works with a new mother, 28-year-old Jenn
McGrath, who developed high blood pressure while pregnant. McGrath
meets regularly with Parsons, who takes McGrath's blood pressure
and talks about hypertension. In the process, Parsons has persuaded
McGrath to join a support group for new mothers, building community
and her connection to the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been doing visiting nursing and hospice nursing, but I
knew the shakeups in health care were making for a more unstable
job market,'' said Parsons. ``At the same time, I wanted to do
something for my parish with nursing. I wanted permission to
express my spiritual side.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons describes parish nursing as ``bringing the church back
to its roots,'' saying that Jesus was a healer. And, she says,
parish nurses supply a spiritual companionship the health care
system just can't offer: ``The heart of our ministry is the one
with people who are shut in and profoundly lonely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
