<HEADLINE>
TWO LETTERS WORTH SHARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We get letters. Not a lot, but a few, so I try to answer them.
Here are two worth sharing, both about trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an elm tree in my front yard, but I don't know if it's
a Camperdown. Enclosed are the leaves,'' wrote Lucille Wallace of
Lynnfield, Mass. Nice elm leaves they are, too, neatly taped flat.
She was responding to a column on the Massachusetts Horticultural
Society's search for someone to donate a mature Camperdown elm for
an Italianate garden being restored at the society's Elm Bank
center in Dover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Lucille, truth be told, I wouldn't know a Camperdown elm
if it fell on me. I'd know the one at Elm Bank that the society
wants to match, because I've seen it, and I could tell if yours was
a possible Camperdown if I saw it in leaf and had some reference
books with me, but I could not identify one from individual leaves.
</P>
<P>
   I use two reference books for trees. One is the Peterson ``Field
Guide Eastern Trees,'' which lists native and other trees in the
wild. It has pictures and detailed descriptions. It uses charts to
compare the details (size and shape of leaves and buds, coloration,
etc.) that help one discern one kind of elm from another.
</P>
<P>
   This book is of absolutely no help to me in identifying a
Camperdown elm. For one thing, I keep it at our cottage in Canada,
where I have occasion to tramp around looking at trees and such in
the wild. For another, since a Camperdown elm is a cultivar of a
Scotch elm (Ulmus glabra) usually grafted onto another, Ulmus
americana, it isn't in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   So I turned to one of the great reference books, Michael Dirr's
``Manual of Woody Landscape Plants.'' Here's what I learned: A
Camperdown elm is ``a round-headed, pendulous-branched type that is
usually grafted about 6' to 7' high on the understock.'' Its leaves
would be typical of Scotch elms: alternate (not paired opposite
each other), simple, oblong-ovate to elliptic or obovate leaves,
3-7 inches long, 1 1/2-4 inches wide, sharply serrated leaves. Your
leaves fit that bill, Lucille, but so do those of a few other kinds
of elms.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it's all moot. John Peterson, president of the
Massachusetts Horticultural Society, tells me a donor tree never
was found, though he was deluged with calls from people offering
everything but. So the society acquired one, an eight-inch-caliper
tree, from the trade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Baudanza of Woburn, Mass. has two apple trees. ``I spray
them with fruit spray and also spray them with oil, but they get
rotten inside, no worm holes,'' he wrote. ``Maybe you could tell me
what to do.'' He also has a similar problem with two peach trees.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to horse around with this problem, I went right to
an expert, Dominic Marini, retired University of Massachusetts
Extension agent in Plymouth County.
</P>
<P>
   Apple maggot is the most likely culprit, he told me. The fly
lays eggs under the skin of an apple, and the maggot tunnels in.
You will find brown streaks through the fruit, and it eventually
can rot. He suggested that some people stop spraying too early.
``Maggots don't come on until July and August, so you have to
continue right through August about every two weeks,'' he said. An
organic method of control is to hang plastic red apples coated with
sticky Tangletrap. The flies land and don't leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another possibility is a boron deficiency, and with boron
deficiency you get brown spots right around the core of the
apple,'' Marini said. To counter that, spread about a quarter-pound
of borax (more would be bad) on the ground under the tree.
</P>
<P>
   While boron deficiency produces brown corky spots right around
the core, calcium deficiency, called bitter pit, gives brown spots
right under the skin, and the apples taste bitter. To counter that,
add calcium under the tree. Baldwin and Northern Spy apples are
notorious for this, while ``maggot is very fond of Delicious
apples,'' Marini said.
</P>
<P>
   The peach problems, he suggested, may be caused by plum curculio
or by oriental fruit moth. Start spraying with combination fruit
spray early in the season and spray every week to 10 days; after
June, spray every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   John, I hope that solves your fruit problems. I know it's been a
help to me. Thanks Dominic. I'll be hanging that red sphere to trap
the apple maggot flies and spraying more this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
