<HEADER>
A8118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-REAL-BOYS-BOS &LR;      01-27 1896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-BOYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL BOYS SHOULD CRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your 12-year-old son comes home from school complaining, whiny,
and teary-eyed because his best friend picked a fight with him.
You:
</P>
<P>
   A. Shrug and tell him: ``That's life. You have to learn to deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   B. Tell him to put a lid on it and stop his crying _ he's too
big for that nonsense now.
</P>
<P>
   C. Pass the tissue box and encourage him to share his vulnerable
feelings. After all, boys today can never get enough nurturing and
you don't want him to hide his true inner thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   A decade or two ago, a parent might have picked A or B and not
given the matter a second thought. A boy crying at 12 _ and over a
fight? What if other kids saw him? They'd make his life miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the old psychology. The art of parenting boys seems to
have taken on new weight in these times, and the politically
correct answer to the question is definitively C _ at least
according to a new crop of books by local authors on raising boys.
Although each book approaches the matter differently, all share the
same point of view, a view that would have been unimaginable a
generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today's boys, the books agree, have dangerously fragile
self-esteem due in large part to outdated rules and stereotypes _
the ``Boy Code'' as one of the authors calls it _ that make boys
ashamed of vulnerable feelings, fearful of being sensitive, and
prone to stoicism, frustration, and anger.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the authors, psychologist William Pollack, somberly
concludes in his book ``Real Boys'': ``Boys today are in serious
trouble, including many who seem `normal' and to be doing just
fine. Confused by society's mixed messages about what's expected of
them as boys, and later as men, many feel a sadness and
disconnection they cannot even name.''
</P>
<P>
   How worried should the average parent be?
</P>
<P>
   It is true, of course, that the rocky terrain of family dynamics
is always being mined for new truths and plumbed for new problems.
Just a few years ago, the problems of adolescent girls _ in the
context of their environment _ were being analyzed microscopically
by authors such as Mary Pipher, who wrote ``Reviving Ophelia,'' and
psychologist Carol Gilligan at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the authors _ from Pollack to psychologists Dan
Kindlon and Michael Thompson (``Raising Cain'') to pediatrician Eli
Newburger (``The Men They Will Become'') _ seem to be advocating
nothing less than what Pollack describes as a whole new ``male
model'' of connecting with boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a national crisis of boyhood in America. I
think it is serious, it is real, it is not hyped up,'' Pollack, a
Harvard psychologist and director of the Center for Men at McLean
Hospital in Belmont, Mass., says in an interview. ``Do a majority
of boys suffer from this pain? Absolutely. Their pain is palpable,
close to the surface, and they spend every day of their lives
trying to suppress it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack's message is probably the most pessimistic of the three
books. He contends that even boys whom adults would deem
``high-functioning'' are in serious trouble, thanks to a
society-sanctioned ``boy code'' that dictates they should cover up
the more vulnerable sides of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many feel a sadness and disconnection they cannot even name,''
Pollack writes, citing new research that shows in school boys are
performing worse academically than in the past and in comparison
with girls, and that the rates of depression and suicide for boys
are rising.
</P>
<P>
   He says society places boys in a ``gender straitjacket,''
judging their behavior against outmoded ideas about masculine
autonomy and strength _ even as we tell them to share their
vulnerable feelings. And society pushes boys to separate from their
mother prematurely, as early as age 5 or 6, and also in early
adolescence, with too little preparation and emotional support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that boys, feeling ashamed of their vulnerability,
mask their emotions and ultimately their true selves,'' Pollack
concludes. They are full of anger, and unless parents rethink the
way they raise them, their boys will become emotionally limited
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising Cain'' _ written by Kindlon, a Harvard psychologist
and therapist specializing in boys, and Thompson, staff
psychologist at Belmont Hill School in Belmont _ reflects similar
themes, although the authors use examples drawn from their clinical
practices and seem less willing to apply them to boys in general.
Nevertheless, they emphasize that boys need to become more
``emotionally literate'' and lament the ``stereotypic images of
masculinity'' that are still with us, despite lip service paid to
the new age of the ``sensitive male.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most discouragingly, they describe an emotional gulf
separating most sons from their fathers, which ``remains a lifelong
source of sadness, anger, bitterness, or shame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys describe their fathers . . . as men who don't listen,
don't understand, and demand respect without offering it,'' they
write. ``Many women are angry with their husbands for not being
more involved in their sons' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Men They Will Become,'' Newberger of Harvard Medical
School and Children's Hospital offers a guide to understanding and
influencing boys' character so they will turn out to be what he
calls ``admirable males.'' The assumption, of course, is that the
task isn't intuitive to everyone and a lot of parents aren't on top
of the game of parenting boys.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, he says, that ``in the main, boys are reasonably
well off and can make their way in the world. I think most boys
grow up happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``most parents are curious about and desiring of
improving their acts,'' he says in an interview. And even though he
believes common sense is important in raising children these days,
``things are more complicated than they used to be. There are drugs
and violence _ a lot of family violence. And we know a lot more
about temperament now, and self-control, and learning disorders and
hyperactivity. The point is, our knowledge has improved and there
are specific things parents should know about. We do have a crisis
of character at the end of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Pollack, these include: giving boys undivided
attention at least once a day, encouraging the expression of a full
range of emotions, avoiding ``shaming'' language, expressing love
and empathy openly and generously, and letting boys know they don't
need to ``act like a man'' and that it's OK to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Even, presumably, when they're 12 years old and just had a bad
day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But are things really this bad? Are we raising a generation of
detached and insensitive males? At least one expert on boys is
leery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the picture that is being painted is an
oversimplification and in some ways erroneous,'' says psychologist
Mark Kiselica of the College of New Jersey in an interview.
Kiselica is also president of the Society for the Psychological
Study of Men and Masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The picture is of boys as emotional mummies, and that tends to
be viewed as the primary factor involved in a host of problems that
boys experience. Well, I'm a soccer coach and the parent of two
boys, and I spend a lot of time in schools. I can tell you that
boys are not emotional mummies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get guys who know each other well, they do talk about
their feelings, they know each other inside and out. But they are
selective about to whom and when they express it. I was in a locker
room last night and the guys next to me in their jockstraps were
talking about their wives. They weren't looking face to face, but
let me tell you, there was a lot of personal stuff coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``I do want to acknowledge the important message that
Bill (Pollack) and the others have stated. They have very clearly
raised our nation's consciousness about some of the expectations
about masculinity we place on boys _ like it is unacceptable to
cry, and that it's better to fight than walk away. But on the
whole, we are raising fairly well-adjusted kids, and our nation
needs to remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of the hands-on experts _ the parents raising these
boys?
</P>
<P>
   Megan Adley, who has four boys ages 4 through 8 and a baby
daughter, says she can't relate to the premise that boys are
emotionally disconnected. ``If my boys are hurting, I say, let them
cry. If they hurt, then they need a big hug. I'd say to them that I
don't want them to whine, but I'd say that to my daughter, too. My
husband has the same philosophy (about boys being emotional). He
gets tears in his eyes, sometimes, like when he thinks about his
father who died. And that is all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Powers, who has an 8-year-old son and a 12-year-old
daughter, has read Pollack's ``Real Boys'' and found it both
``helpful'' and ``reassuring,'' though some of the conclusions were
``surprising.'' Powers has also read ``Raising Ophelia,'' about the
crisis facing adolescent girls. ``Maybe it's because I was a girl,
but I could really identify with that,'' she says. ``I thought it
was very clear that girls are not getting things that they need,
like self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on the boys' side, I always thought boys had everything. I
thought `Real Boys' made it all seem a bit too drastic. I think
most kids, boys and girls, are just doing fine, in the same way
most people I grew up did just fine. I don't believe most boys in
America are in that much pain. How could they get out of bed in the
morning?''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there is her car-pool partner, Pam Russell, mother
of 9-year-old Matthew. Russell describes him with pride as a
``sensitive, compassionate'' boy who recycles trash because he
cares about the environment and cries when he sees road kill on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Russell, a single mother, gets pressure from
relatives to be careful not to let him turn into a ``sissy,'' and
pressure from other adults to get him off his coed soccer team and
transfer him to an all-boys' team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I am swimming upstream against society,'' says
Russell, who keeps the book ``Real Boys'' on her bedside table.
``It is really hard to raise a boy with the traits that I, as a
mother, consider worthy of having, like sensitivity and love of
nature and compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Matthew has already observed that there is a
special way that boys have to act around others. For example, even
though he likes the girls in his car pool and talks to them in the
car, he is careful not to talk to them at school because some of
the boys might tease him.
</P>
<P>
   When doing a presentation in school, ``boys have to act cool,''
he says, demonstrating by putting his hands on his hips. ``And
girls do just regular.''
</P>
<P>
   When they're angry, boys act differently, too, he says. ``They
flip out totally. One time there was a boy who was mad and he
slammed his desk. Boys go, ``I hate you, even to the teacher. Girls
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the classroom crayfish swallowed his favorite goldfish,
he felt terribly sad but ``could not say I was sad out loud,''
Matthew says. ``The other kids would have said, `Crybaby, crybaby.'
''
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with having a bad day, Matthew concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Most boys, he says, ``can't let anyone know that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
