<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGMAKERS AND MUCKRAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ, PATTI HARTIGAN, AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hordes of reporters crammed into neighboring New Hampshire
for Tuesday's primary are there for two contests. One will anoint
the winning presidential hopefuls. The other could determine which
news outlets end up playing a key role in the battle for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign 2000 is unfolding in a brave new media world. The
``boys on the bus'' are yielding to the index finger on the
computer mouse, the Beltway pundits making way for the unmediated
gaze of the C-Span camera. A porn king like Larry Flynt is as
likely to dredge up a major political scandal as a senior
Washington reporter. And thus far, the most memorable journalism
moment in the race was a pop quiz sprung on George W. Bush by
WHDH-TV's bad boy Andy Hiller.
</P>
<P>
   In this volatile environment, it's hard to predict which
personalities, journalists, and information sources will make their
mark in the campaign. But here's a roster _ from Web sites to
tabloids, from TV talk hosts to journalistic sleuths _ of media
players to watch out for. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Tim Russert: Host of NBC's ``Meet the Press With Tim
Russert''; NBC Washington bureau chief
</P>
<P>
   During one debate, GOP hopeful Alan Keyes testily inquired
whether moderator Russert ``would declare his candidacy.'' That
might actually dilute his clout. His ``Meet the Press'' show is a
major newsmaker, and the best debate so far took place between Gore
and Bradley under Russert's expert prodding. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Gwen Ifill: Host of PBS's ``Washington Week in Review''
</P>
<P>
   Look for the first black host of a major political talk show to
seek out unconventional wisdom among the reporters who spend each
week along the campaign trail. And look for her to get beyond the
Beltway; this week she's bringing ``Washington Week'' to New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Matthews: Host of MSNBC's ``Hardball With Chris
Matthews''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews is hard to pigeonhole, and even harder to shut up. But
behind his pugnacity is a penetrating analytical mind bent on
delivering cant-free TV. He's audacious enough to believe that
politics should be fun, which makes his show must-see television
for political junkies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --www.salon.com
</P>
<P>
   This aggressive on-line zine could drop the bomb about the next
Whitewater (or white powder) scandal. During Monicagate, it dug up
Republican senator Henry Hyde's 30-year-old affair, noting, ``Ugly
times call for ugly tactics.'' And two weeks ago, it had a major
scoop about collusion between television networks and the nation's
antidrug czar.
</P>
<P>
   --Zack Exley, webmaster of www.gwbush.com
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old computer geek from Somerville didn't expect to
become a cause celebre when he set up gwbush.com, which parodies
the Republican front-runner. But George W. fought back, calling
Exley a ``garbage man.'' In fact, he's one of hundreds of amateur
cyber-sleuths sniffing for dirt on the presidential trail.
</P>
<P>
   --www.freedomchannel.com
</P>
<P>
   They call it video on demand _which means that you can hear the
talking heads 24-7. This nonpartisan Web site is one of several
that post streaming videos of the candidates' television ads, as
well as short videos of their stands on the issues. For the
campaign aficionado, this is the cyber C-Span. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Michael Isikoff: Newsweek investigative reporter
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it was Isikoff, not cyber snoop Matt Drudge, whose
reporting ferreted out Monica-gate. As his recent piece on George
W. Bush's money machine indicates, Newsweek has him poking around
the candidates. A dogged investigator, he can detonate a bombshell
at any time.
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Bartley: Wall Street Journal editor
</P>
<P>
   Bartley's activist, conservative editorial pages don't endorse
candidates, but they can make life miserable for them. Bartley's
already published tough investigative pieces on Bush and Gore, and
if he sees this as a race between squishy moderates, the
front-runners better head for the bunkers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The supermarket tabloids
</P>
<P>
   If there's a skeleton rattling in the closet, the tabs are sure
to hear it. The Star's impressive track record includes unearthing
the Gennifer Flowers-Bill Clinton tryst and catching Clinton aide
Dick Morris partying with a prostitute. These guys pay cash for
trash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
