<HEADLINE>
KEEPING WARM WHEN YOU CAN'T PUSH UP THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So want to keep warm when it gets cold?
</P>
<P>
   Cold not only outside, but inside, which sometimes happens
during a long cold snap _ and goodness knows we have one right now.
</P>
<P>
   That is when no amount of pumping up the heat, boosting the
thermostat, seems to do much good. Why is it that 65 in summer, out
in the yard enjoying the weather, feels so good and so comfortable,
while 65 indoors in the dead of winter is chilly and miserable?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it is probably the humidity or the lack of
humidity in the house in winter. You know, the house is dry as a
bone, your mouth is dry and your nose gets all caked up. And,
static electricity is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   The cure there is easy: Install a humidifier on your hot air
furnace. If you have hot water heat, you cannot put a humidifier on
the boiler. But you can put in a room humidifier, a console type
appliance that produces enough humidity to make you feel a lot
better, not necessarily warmer but certainly more comfortable. Keep
the unit full of water and put one upstairs as well.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, it is difficult to get the relative humdity up to the
ideal of 40 percent, let alone keep it there. But you can try. If
you get it to 30, that's pretty good, and it will make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   There are some ways to heat up the house, which is costly, but
there are more ways to make yourself more comfortbale when the
house cannot get any warmer. We are not talking about putting in
more insulation, fixing the windows and caulking; these are not
accomplished in a day or two. They take a lot more time than that.
</P>
<P>
   What we are talking about are quick fixes, often permanent, that
we all can do without running off and buying all kinds of
insulation, new windows and other essentials.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing. Wear a hat. It's no insult, to the host or anyone else
living in the house; it was done often in the past. A simple hat _
stocking, skullcap, beret, cap _ will do to keep the head warm. It
is true that one loses the most heat through the head, whether the
head has a gorgeous mane or no hair at all.
</P>
<P>
   Wear layered clothing, not tight, and warm socks. Wool is the
best material for most purposes, and if your feet and head are
warm, and your hands, you are pretty well warm all over.
</P>
<P>
   Invest in thermal underwear. There are new fleece products that
are lightweight and toasty, not to mention trendy, including vests,
shirt-jackets and sports pants.
</P>
<P>
   Wear a scarf _ wool (cashmere is the best) or silk, which is
very warming.
</P>
<P>
   Keep active. No sitting around doing TV. Find a project; your
activity will keep you warm.
</P>
<P>
   Pile on the blankets. When you go to bed, use plenty of
blankets; wool is good but sometimes heavy, and some sleepers are
allergic to it; quilts are good but comforters are best, if you can
keep them from sliding off the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Use passive solar heat: Let the sunshine in. Open curtains and
draperies on the south side of the house (or the sunniest side)
during the day to let the sun heat the interior air. Keep them open
as long as the sun shows in the room. Close them at night.
</P>
<P>
   Tend to the heating system. If you have a forced hot air
furnace, keep its filters fresh by changing them every month. Clean
registers, to make them work their best.
</P>
<P>
   Use that duct tape _ check ducts for leaks and separations and
seal them so you're not needlessly heating uninhabited areas such
as basements or attics.
</P>
<P>
   A long-term fix is to insulate the ducts in a hot air system.
This will keep the hot air in the ducts until it can be delivered
to the rooms without losing the heat to the basement, where it is
wasted. Insulate hot water pipes where accessible.
</P>
<P>
   If you have hot water heat, clean the baseboard radiators and
other radiators as needed to maximize heating capability.
</P>
<P>
   Adjust the heating system. Sometimes you can adjust a hot air
system to bring more heat in often-used rooms and reduce the heat
to bedrooms or rooms that are not used as often.
</P>
<P>
   Go in the basement and inspect the round ducts leading to rooms
from a larger rectangular trunk duct. Where the round duct leaves
the big trunk duct, you may see a little metal lever. This is a
damper; if the lever is parallel to the round duct, it is open; if
is at right angles to the duct, it is closed.
</P>
<P>
   You can open or close those dampers to certain rooms. It may
take some experimenting, but it is possible to make a difference,
and get more heat into the room where you want it most.
</P>
<P>
   You could try closing the registers in the rooms themselves, but
this is less effective.
</P>
<P>
   Caulk and caulk. Use caulks and seals to plug drafts around
doors and windows _ and don't forget to seal around electrical
boxes and plumbing fixtures. Most of this work is done indoors so
you won't have to go out in that frigid air.
</P>
<P>
   Any caulking around the window and door frames (they can lose a
lot of heat) on the inside will not show if a neat bead is applied
from a caulking gun. Besides, with draperies and curtains in place,
you won't see that bead of caulking anyway.
</P>
<P>
   If your windows feel cold and drafty, they are cold and drafty.
So, install an inside storm window, not a fancy permanent one, but
one that you can install with little effort and cash outlay.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a storm window kit at a lumber store; it consists of a big
picee of Saran type plastic and a border system that eases the
chore of setting it against the inside window frame. It will pevent
a lot of drafts and reduce the loss of heat through your windows,
at a fraction of a cost of a regular glass or plastic inside storm.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot find the kit, buy polyethylene plastic and tape it
to the frame.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy foam covers for double plug outlets and switch boxes
as well. Unscrew the cover, insert the foam cover and put the solid
cover back in place.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these tricks can make you more comfortable in a cold
house, as long as the house is not really cold.
</P>
<P>
   When it's really cold. But what happens when you are in a condo
or apartment and the heating system in a large building is just not
good enough to get it up beyond 60? Now, that is cold.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes heating systems are undersized in large buildings.
This is done on purpose to save money; besides, the thinking goes,
the really cold snaps will be short, and when the temperature
staggers back up to 30 or so, the heat in the condo or apartment
will go up, too.
</P>
<P>
   For this miserable situation, auxiliary heaters are the answer.
These heaters are electric, and in light of the recent cold snap,
may be hard to find. An auxiliary heater will heat people, so they
have to be relatively close to the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Some heat with a high resistance wire; that is, the wire gets
red hot, protected by a cage to keep the hot wire away from the
person.
</P>
<P>
   These heaters are fast, usually equipped with a fan, and drying,
but here is one idea to add humidity to the house: Put a large,
shallow pan full of water in front of the heater; as the fan blows
the warm air over the water, it will move water vapor toward you
and your caky nose.
</P>
<P>
   Such a heater is safe because it has a tip switch that turns the
heater off if it is tipped over.
</P>
<P>
   But with that pan of water in front of the heater, be extremely
careful that the water and heater do not come in contact with each
other, and that you do not touch the water and the heater at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   Another good electric heater is a metal affair that looks like a
radiator and in fact is one, full of water. It produces a low, even
heat, is long in warming up but long in cooling off. The water is
sealed in the unit. It too is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Always be careful that you don't use a heater that is too big
for the circuit; you could overload the circuit or cause a short.
Some of the water-filled radiators have two switches, one 900
watts, the other 600 watts. Do not use them together if the ciruit
is not big enough to handle it. Alone, the 900 or 600 setting is
probably OK.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't fall for the ads that say that certain heaters
are great heaters and save you money, too. 'Tisn't so.
</P>
<P>
   You will get the same heat out of one 600-watt heater as any
other 600-watt heater. Any difference in efficiency will be minor,
and probably undetectable by you as you bundle up in the Hudson's
Bay blanket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
