<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK ENTERS MARKET AS INSURANCE STOCKS SUFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball greats Sammy Sosa and Hank Aaron will be on the floor
of the New York Stock Exchange to mark the debut of John Hancock
Financial Services as a public company.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Hancock's initial public offering to knock the
ball out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, insurance stocks are about as welcome on Wall
Street as insurance solicitations during dinner time. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's index of life insurance stocks is down 18 percent this
year after a substantial fall last year.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks reek of the old economy at a time when investors are
enamored with the new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stack these stocks up against tech stocks, they put
people to sleep,'' said Lanny Thorndike, a portfolio manager with
Century Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   The life insurers, Hancock included, have respectable earnings
and have been meeting their numbers. These days that isn't good
enough. At the end of trading Thursday, Hancock is likely to have a
market value of between $5 billion and $6 billion. There are
high-tech companies in Massachusetts with minuscule sales and no
earnings that are worth considerably more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the life insurers are suffering from more than a lack of
sex appeal. Money managers and analysts point to three factors that
are depressing the stocks. They include:
</P>
<P>
   --Rising interest rates. Insurance companies stash a lot of
their money in bonds. As interest rates rise, those bonds lose a
portion of their value and the spread the insurers earn on some of
their investments shrinks.
</P>
<P>
   With three interest rate hikes by the Federal Reserve last year
and possibly another two or three still to come, the insurers are
hurting along with the rest of the financial services business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets hammered when rates go up,'' complained James E.
Moynihan III, an analyst with Fleet Financial Services.
</P>
<P>
   Both insurers and analysts insist investors' fixation on
interest rates is misguided. Like the banks, insurance companies
have gotten quite skillful about managing in any rate environment.
In this case, however, perception is reality, and there is not much
the insurance companies can do about it but wait for rates to peak.
</P>
<P>
   --Intensifying competition, especially in annuities. The basic
life insurance business grows roughly in line with the economy, 3
percent to 5 percent a year. Companies that have done better have
done so by finding faster-growing niches. The best niche in recent
years has been variable annuities _ products that blend life
insurance with mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The annuity business is still strong, but everyone and his
brother _ insurers, banks, mutual fund firms _ has jumped into it,
squeezing margins in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't rocket science,'' said Kevin Callahan, an insurance
analyst with Loomise Sayles. ``Everyone is looking for a way to
grow a little faster and they are all looking in the same places.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock is only a tiny player in the variable annuity business,
but once again, the pall on annuities is affecting the whole
industry.
</P>
<P>
   --Too much supply. Think of Hancock as the first plane on the
runway with a number of other planes stacked up behind it waiting
for takeoff. Following close on the heels of the Hancock deal are
IPOs from Sun Life Assurance, which owns Massachusetts Financial
Services; Metropolitan Life, owner of State Street Research; and
Prudential Insurance Co. of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the market is asking: `Do we really need another $50
billion worth of life insurance stock?'' said Lanny Thorndike.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hancock, the others are all mutual insurers who feel they
need to be investor-owned companies to participate in the coming
consolidation of the financial services business.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, the rush to go public is likely to keep the
whole sector depressed.
</P>
<P>
   What would it take to light a fire under life insurance stocks?
Some sign that interest rates were heading back down again, say
analysts. Assuming the Fed succeeds in slowing the US economy, such
a turning point could come later this year.
</P>
<P>
   A collapse in some of the high-flying tech stocks might help
too. As long as investors are focused on the techs, it will be hard
to get them interested in solid, steady performers like life
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is consolidation. There is broad agreement that
this country has too many insurance companies and too many banks.
As those numbers shrink through mergers, costs should come down,
margins should increase, and investors should be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   With its better-than-average return on equity and recognizable
brand name, Hancock may do better than many of its competitors over
time. Just don't look for any home runs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
