<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HN     01-27 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, Jan. 27, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following for Friday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EDUCATION (Washington) _ In his State of the Union
address, President Clinton calls for a doubling of federal spending
on after-school programs and summer school to help children in
failing schools achieve high academic standards, and expansion of
Head Start by $1 billion. The ambitious plan is likely to encounter
resistance in a Republican-controlled Congress that wants less
federal involvement in education, not more. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-NEGOTIATIONS (Washington) _ As White House and Puerto
Rican officials meet to discuss permanently closing the Navy's
bombing range on the island of Vieques, Sila Calderon, San Juan's
mayor, blasts the service for its ``appalling'' and ``shameful''
treatment of the island's 9,000 residents. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-N.H. (Stratham, N.H.) _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley presses
his attack on Vice President Al Gore for ``misrepresenting'' his
policy proposals and insists that a candidate must speak the truth
on the campaign trail. Bradley _ who has previously criticized the
president for misrepresenting his health plan _ says if a candidate
does not tell the truth in the campaign, the American people can't
trust him to tell the truth as president. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The message of the dissolving
candidacy of former Sen. Bill Bradley is that if you hold yourself
out as more principled and high-minded than your opponent, it
better be true and you better stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to reverse his political slide, Bradley suddenly
dropped his mask of statesmanship in the New Hampshire debate,
negating the theme on which he had intended to distinguish himself
from Gore. No more Mr. Nice Guy. But Gore is smoother at the tough
guy tactics. A frustrated Bradley got too personal in his attacks
on Gore and came across as a mean-spirited whiner. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ This year's presidential campaign
demonstrates how disproportionately important opposition to
abortion and the Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade ruling that legalized
it in 1973 have become to Republicans. In their debate the other
evening, the five Republican presidential hopefuls discussed issues
that one would require the attention of the leader of the world's
most powerful nation: taxes, trade, national defense, health care,
education, immigration, campaign finance reform and how to allocate
the budget surplus. But no issue generated more heat or triggered
more passionate declarations than abortion. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
