<P>
   ISRAEL-FUNDRAISING (Jerusalem) _ Israel's attorney general
opened a criminal investigation Thursday into the campaign finances
of Prime Minister Ehud Barak's party. The state comptroller also
fined the party (already bankrupt) $3.2 million. In his report to
Parliament, the comptroller said the financing practices of Barak's
One Israel party had ``trampled on the law'' and he called the
matter ``grave.'' He said Barak should have known about the
allegedly illegal activity. Barak said that he didn't, and that the
campaign finance law was unclear. By Deborah Sontag.
