<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAMPAIGN-COMEDY-NYTSF     01-27 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-COMEDY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE ALREADY KNOW THE BIG CHEESES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``As expected, Forbes said he had beaten the expectations.'' _
From an AP story about the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be honest: Nobody, not even Iowans with dual degrees in
Cornstalk Management and Political Science, understands all the
intricacies of the caucuses _ although I'm pretty sure they're
about as binding as Drew Carey's Sans-a-belt slacks after he's
downed a 12-pack of Buzz Beer.
</P>
<P>
   What I do know is that ``caucus'' is a Native American word for
``suckers,'' which is the term used to describe anyone who got
swept up in the predictably ridiculous coverage of the Iowa sort-of
elections.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, according to the wizards who analyze, speculate,
prognosticate and just plain fill up the airtime on all the MSNBC's
and Fox News Channels and CNNs up and down the dial, it's naive and
simplistic to call Al Gore and George W. Bush the shoo-in winners.
</P>
<P>
   No no no. This is still a horse race!
</P>
<P>
   See, you can't put on your parka, grab your microphone and stand
in front of the town hall and say something like, ``Here in
Ottumwa, it occurs to me that this is all a charade _ that Al Gore
and George Bush are obvious choices for their respective
nominations, unless it's revealed that Bush went on a bank-robbing
spree in the 1970s and Gore was once a woman'' _ even though you'd
be scoring points for honesty with such a speech.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to perpetuate the illusion that the nominations are
still in doubt, that Iowa and New Hampshire are the political
equivalent of the first round of the NCAA tournament _ even though
we're already at the tail end of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   So you try to convince yourself and your audience that it's all
about expectations and projections and polls. Who did better than
expected and who did worse than expected and who did just about
what was expected _ which would have to be considered a
disappointment because everyone sets low expectations so you can
crow about having exceeded expectations once the votes are in.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that retarded logic, Steve Forbes with his 30 percent
and Alan Keyes with his 14 percent in Iowa were jubilant and fired
up, even though Bob Dole (you remember him?) has a better chance of
winning the Republican nomination than either of those two.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John McCain was receiving kudos for not even trying
to win before New Hampshire _ even though some pundits were saying
his 5 percent showing was about 5 percent lower than what his
advisers would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, we know lots of important things from the primaries _
like what? We know that ... well ... Bauer remains considerably
shorter than all the other guys, and Hatch apparently doesn't golf
and had nothing else to do but goof around on the campaign trail
before shutting down his campaign as predicted.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bill Bradley, his pre-election spin was that a 31 percent
total in Iowa would be a nothing-but-net night for him, as that was
the number attained by Teddy Kennedy against Jimmy Carter in 1980.
(Of course, Carter eventually kicked Kenney's Chappaquiddick before
getting his own hat handed to him by Ronnie Reagan, but never
mind.) Bradley wound up with 35 percent, so he bested that 31
percent mark and that means he'll end up, um, losing to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's post-election take: ``This isn't an end, it's a
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, the beginning of you thinking about Campaign 2004, my
friend. Might I suggest a discreet waddle-tuck? It's just too
distracting.
</P>
<P>
   As for New Hampshire ... hey, everybody knows it's a grand
tradition to hold the first legitimate primary there.
</P>
<P>
   In the first one, in 1952, Sen. Estes Kefauver upset President
Harry Truman, thus setting the tone for the New Hampshire primary
as an overblown but ultimately irrelevant event. I mean, it's not
like we ever had a President Estes Kefauver, right?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes losers in New Hampshire claim to be winners because
they exceeded those artificial expectations. George McGovern in
'72, Ted Kennedy in '80, Bill Clinton in '92, Pat Buchanan that
same year. And of course, the winners in those same elections were
painted as losers. It's all about spin and perspective and oh yeah,
bull----. (I love it when I have to censor myself.)
</P>
<P>
   So as you're watching all the pre-election coverage in the
coming days, just keep the following little picture in your head.
</P>
<P>
   Think of 275 cheeseburgers, stacked in a pyramid. Now remove a
single cheeseburger from that pile. If the population of our
country is represented by that big mountain of cheeseburgers, New
Hampshire would be the lone burger.
</P>
<P>
   And regardless of who wins that cheeseburger, George W. Bush and
Al Gore have already been anointed as the big cheeses of their
respective parties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
