<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EMPLOYEES THREATEN STRIKE AT LANDMARK RADIO STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY DELGADO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Some 40 news employees of the Pacifica
Foundation are threatening to go on strike Monday in a dispute with
management of the landmark broadcast organization.
</P>
<P>
   The employees claim the Pacifica management removed its popular
national news director in November after he aired a story detailing
a boycott by 16 Pacifica affiliates over a censorship issue. The
disgruntled employees also say that Pacifica has continued a
pattern of censorship and program cancellations throughout its
stations since a bitter labor dispute at KPFA-FM in Berkeley was
settled late last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Glantz, a frequent national news contributor and KPFA's
Sacramento bureau chief, said he had been feeling good about the
resolutions between staff and management that ended the strike at
KPFA and was disappointed to see similar issues arise on a national
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sooner do I get back (from a trip) that I find out that the
news director has been fired because he wouldn't buckle under to
censorship,'' said Glantz, who will join a planned three-month
strike that will begin Monday if worker demands are not met. ``It's
really depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica Radio, established in 1949, is the nation's first
listener-supported radio network. In addition to the Berkeley
station, it operates KPFK in Los Angeles, WBAI in New York, KPFT in
Houston, WPFW in Washington, D.C., and has nearly 60 affiliates in
27 states.
</P>
<P>
   Among its nationally syndicated programs is the Pacifica Network
News, a weekday evening newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Pacifica Foundation chairwoman Mary Frances Berry were
not returned.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter written to Berry, the group of free-lancers,
reporters and producers demanded a reinstatement of
Washington-based Pacifica Network News Director Dan Coughlin and
written assurances that acts of censorship will immediately end.
</P>
<P>
   If those and other demands are not met, the 40 employees pledge
to go on a three-month strike. The work-stoppage would affect about
70 percent of the national news gathering that is distributed to 70
Pacifica-affiliated stations throughout the nation in daily
half-hour broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   The censorship charges echo the same issues that prompted KPFA
staffers to strike last summer amid strong public support and heavy
media coverage. On-air personalities at the time complained that
they were censored and reprimanded for doing stories that were
critical of issues related to management. As the strike heated up,
the Pacifica management locked workers out of the station and hired
armed guards to keep them out.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute lasted for nearly a month in July and August and
ended when the management and KPFA employees hammered out an
agreement that returned operations of the station back to station
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Glantz said Coughlin was also the target of censorship efforts
by management after he aired a report on a protest involving 16
affiliated stations who were disgruntled with Pacifica management.
The report aired on a Friday and by Monday, Coughlin had been
removed from his position and reassigned to another job without
listed job duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that censorship at Pacifica is becoming a way of
life,'' the workers wrote in the letter to Berry. ``These acts
started with the crisis at KPFA, and although that station is once
again on the air, these acts continue.''
</P>
