<HEADLINE>
DETROIT SEES THE FUTURE _ AND THERE ARE A LOT OF TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Immersion in a massive display of cars, trucks, and
SUVs, as happens at venues such as the North American International
Auto Show here, can be like a trip to the art gallery to view
pointillist works.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you have to step back from the seemingly random
scattering of dots to see the whole picture.
</P>
<P>
   Once I stepped back from the acres of vehicles showcased at
Detroit this year, that picture was clear: trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Pickup trucks, in myriad forms _ brutes, sleek throwbacks,
truck/SUV hybrids _ dominated this show. Trucks are the hot
immediate future in the industry and almost everybody is looking
for the truck that will appeal to the most folks. Even Volkswagen
offered a pickup prototype that still managed to look like a coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge showcased a rig called the MAXXcab, cab-forward in design,
part luxury SUV, with a pickup truck bed. GMC rolled out the
Terradyne, a bulky, rugged brute of a prototype. Chevrolet showed
its SSR, a pickup with enough car blended in that I could not help
but think of an updated El Camino. It seems as if everybody's got a
four-door pickup in the works or on the way, and bed extenders,
once the domain of aftermarketeers, come right from the factory
now.
</P>
<P>
   But in Detroit, two trucks in particular emerged and should be
watched closely, one ballyhooed and ready to roll, the other
quietly plopped on the show floor with no fanfare but quickly
drawing plenty of fans.
</P>
<P>
   The first was the Chevrolet Avalanche, the second the Ford
Equator. I suspect they'll be going head-to-head soon.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy calls the Avalanche a sport-utility pickup. That just
makes it part of rising wave when it goes on sale in the first
quarter of 2001. It's got a short pickup bed, a four-door cabin,
much like an SUV, and a distinct truck look at the grill. What it's
got that sets it apart from all others _ and keep this word in mind
_ is a midgate. Until now, the problem with SUV-truck hybrids has
been a bed too small for, say, a sheet of plywood.
</P>
<P>
   What the midgate does is solve that problem. The bed in the
Avalanche is a shade over five feet long. However, when the rear
seats are folded down, the window is removed and stored on board,
and the midgate, which separates bed and cabin, is folded down,
voila: eight-foot bed. The bed can also be securely covered and
locked as you would lock a car trunk to protect tools, groceries,
or whatever you are carrying.
</P>
<P>
   It will be built on a spinoff of the same platform that gives us
the Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra and the Chevy-GMC lineup of
sport utes. In fact, it's about the size of a Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bold move for Chevrolet and puts it right back in a
market _ four-door pickups _ that has exploded. Chevy, however,
failed to catch the first wave in a way that Ford did so
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, curiously, chose to quietly slip what could be its entry
into the midgate race onto the show floor. While it has pushed hard
for the F-150 SuperCrew, a four-full-door pickup, and rolled out
the Sport Trac, an SUV-with-bed based on the Explorer, it was
subtle in plopping the loud Equator concept into public view.
</P>
<P>
   The Equator combines the F-150 (length) and F-350 (width) for a
wide and rugged stance. It's got a certain Hummer-like boldness to
it, and it's also got Kevlar bumpers, fenders, wheel wells, and
lower trim for protection in offroad driving.
</P>
<P>
   Its doors are high, and side panels drop down to form running
boards when the doors are open.
</P>
<P>
   Ford reportedly has been working on a midgate design that would
have the window descend into the middle panel _ much like the back
on a station wagon _ before the panel is folded down into the
passenger compartment. That would be a good thing and would avoid
what I suspect could be the annoying problem of taking a window out
and storing it onboard.
</P>
<P>
   If Ford builds the Equator, it will need a midgate of some sort
because the bed is simply too tiny for hauling loads of any
consequence, and without a midgate, it will cede this niche in the
expanding world of trucks to Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1449EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
