<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      01-27 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAAB'S 9-5 WAGON HAS A SLOW, STEADY ANSWER TO WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally we get some snow, and a chance to test the latest in
``winter'' drive modes that are increasingly common on
non-four-wheel-drive autos.
</P>
<P>
   Saab does not let us down.
</P>
<P>
   We're in a 9-5 wagon as it crawls on narrow roads that lead to
empty summer houses that dot a lake. The roads are hard-packed snow
and ice with a fresh dusting of snow atop that. They wind so much
that getting up speed to approach any of the steep hills is
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Saab is stopped halfway up one of these hills. It is set in
winter mode. Then the gas pedal is pushed.
</P>
<P>
   My Uncle Harold used to say that driving in snow meant you had
to (curious expletive) drive like you've got an egg between your
foot and the gas pedal. Indeed, it was a tricky, touchy thing to
walk the fine line between just enough power for progress and
spinning wheels that ended in a backslide.
</P>
<P>
   Saab handles the egg part for you. Push the gas. The engine
roars _ roars so loudly you assume the wheels must be spinning out
there. They are not. Instead, the engine is straining because it's
producing enough power to start the car barely creeping in what
feels like third gear from a dead start. It works wonderfully, and
that helps make this front-wheel-drive wagon a perfect New England
car. All that, and sportiness, too.
</P>
<P>
   This is no box of a wagon being built as wagons are in the midst
of a minicomeback. It's low and sleek up front, rises in a wedge
over windshield and roofline, and ends above the rear lid with a
subtle, aerodynamic curl toward the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The Saab wagon was launched last spring, and offered a
4-cylinder, 2.3 liter, 170 horsepower, low-pressure turbo engine as
its base model. For 2000, you can get a 3.0 liter V-6 that cranks
out 200 horses, but I stuck with the smaller engine base model in
this test and it got about 22 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   It's an admirable engine, moving the car effortlessly at highway
speed, climbing hills with a comforting, powerful surge when extra
power is needed. Its low- and mid-range torque is remarkable, but
you should expect that from a company that has been featuring
turbochargers for 20 years now.
</P>
<P>
   I've always liked Saabs, though their standard transmissions
were not my favorite _ long throws, a bit sloppy _ but the 4-speed
automatic on the test car was superb. Shifts up and down were
seamless, with no jolts, no lags.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomically, the dash setup is wonderfully simple. The leather
front seats (part of an optional package) were broad and supported
thighs, back, and head very well. Take them out and put them on a
swivel base and they'd make fine furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The rear seats were comfortable _ for two, not three _ but
legroom back there is limited. Since a wagon is often a family car
used for long trips, it is good that storage space is spread
throughout the car. There are bins in the lower front door panels,
pockets on the front edges of the front seats, pockets on the
seatbacks, a bin in the console, nets on the B pillars, more bins
in the rear cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo area has an industrial look _ and utility _ to it,
with sliding tie-downs and straps that let you safely store luggage
and heavy loads.
</P>
<P>
   There's a standard sliding sunroof, and even the glove
compartment is unique: Hooked to air-conditioning ducts, it can
keep drinks cooled to 42 degrees in hot weather. And the 9-5's got
the neatest cup holder I've ever seen: A vertical slit in the dash
pops out at touch and a circle, a la gyroscope, rotates to
horizontal to hold your drink.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of what makes Saab such a fine niche car with a
loyal following. Plus, it's a safe car. There are crash ``load
paths'' designed to distribute the energy of a collision out and
around passengers. And those passengers are sitting in a steel cage
of high tensile steel.
</P>
<P>
   Front airbags are supplemented by head and torso dual airbags
that deploy from the outside edges of the front seat backs,
cradling passengers in soft protection.
</P>
<P>
   The ride was smooth and stable on highways, with minimal lateral
forces felt during lane changes at speed, and on rough backroads
you could feel the suspension absorbing all the road could hand
out.
</P>
<P>
   That suspension is springs, antiroll bars and shocks all around,
with struts up front and multilink independent in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   There was some hint of understeer when powering through a
corner, but that's not uncommon in front-wheel-drive and you soon
get used to it. Stopping was quick and crisp with discs fore and
aft using diagonally split hydraulics, assisted by ABS.
</P>
<P>
   This is a car meant to compete with other high-end wagons such
as the Audi A6, BMW 528i, Mercedes-Benz E320, and Volvo's V70. If
you're ready to hand over $35,000-$50,000 for a wagon, I'd suggest
you try them all because all are good and the choice becomes
personal. If you're looking for a comparison with a cheaper wagon,
try the new Volvo V40 at around $25,000; it's a bit smaller, but
still a fine car.
</P>
<P>
   If you intend to do a lot of upcountry driving in the winter,
make sure you get winter mode. If Uncle Harold were still alive,
he'd be asking, ``Which came first, the Saab or the egg?''
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches
</P>
<P>
   --The rubber ``toggle switches'' that control air flow from the
dash vents.
</P>
<P>
   --The doubled-up visors. Great to be able to block out that low
winter sun both from the side and the front without moving a single
visor back and forth as you change directions.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --A subtle rasping sound that seemed to emanate from the dash
whenever the defroster was turned on.
</P>
<P>
   --Small interior door handles. Hard to get more than a couple of
fingers behind them and, on quick cold runs to fetch the morning
paper, impossible in gloved hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Base price: $31,850 &QL; 
Price as tested: $35,445 &QL; 
Horsepower 170 /Torque: 207 lb-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 106.4 inches / 189.3 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 70.5 inches/ 58.9 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 3,530 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
