<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CLUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY TRENDS AND PHO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sunday afternoon rolls around and that means
soup's on.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the tables crammed together in the back of the
Vietnamese dive are packed with music industry executives, Internet
entrepreneurs, venture capitalists, and recent college graduates.
Elbow to elbow, they slurp steaming bowls of noodle soup and swap
ideas, their opinions given equal credence during the weekly
ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Pho (pronounced ``fuh'' and named after the soup served
at the Pho 87 restaurant in Los Angeles's Chinatown), the group is
open to anyone with an interest in the intersection of music and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In those circles, over the scores of Sundays since it started in
May 1998, Pho has become a buzzword for innovation and free advice.
Even the food was free until recently, when brunch attendance began
topping 100 on occasion and Jim Griffin's hat was passed around.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, Griffin, the group's founder, picked up the check
himself, even on the Sunday it reached $700. Griffin, who created
and ran the technology department at Geffen Records before
launching a consulting firm called Cherry Lane Digital-One House,
said he simply wanted to share his good fortune. He also wanted a
place where colleagues whose phone calls he couldn't return could
find him every weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people in this business think about the cost of
everything and the value of nothing,'' said Griffin, who was an
early convert to the power of the computer and is considered one of
the most forward thinkers in the music industry. ``But this is the
soup I love. It was a way for people to find me. That's how it
evolved.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also expanding. A handful of people shared that first
meal; a typical Sunday now draws at least 50 to Pho. The largest
crowd so far was 162, when a major Internet music conference was
held in Los Angeles last year. More recently, swarms of Harvard MBA
candidates dropped by for soup.
</P>
<P>
   Pho offshoots have sprung up in Seattle, San Francisco, Chicago,
New York and Minneapolis, although not every group meets on Sunday
and not always at a pho restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But in an industry where Wednesday is yesteryore, Pho
aficionados crave contact more than once a week. For them, there is
the invitation-only Pho e-mail list, which sometimes gets so out of
control with postings that one participant recently issued a
desperate plea to ``remove, remove, remove'' his name from the list
sponsored by OneHouse.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every branch of the music industry is represented on
the Pho list, which numbers about 200, from CEOs to producers to
managers to attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   What they share is concern over changes in the entertainment
industry in general and the music business in particular now that
people can download videos and songs from their computers.
Griffin's aim is to help them harness and direct that change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful resource, an opportunity for folks in the
business to bash out an idea, just grab it by both ears until
something makes sense,'' said Kevin Doran, a Manhattan-based music
and Internet consultant who posts at least one e-mail a day to the
Pho list. ``It's a lifeline to thinking people in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent discussions include the Time Warner/AOL merger,
intellectual property rights, the ethics of not paying artists for
their music when it is downloaded via computer, and almost every
announcement coming from the fast-growing world of digital music.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of creating a Pho Web site set off friendly but
heated debate over the security inherent in a relatively exclusive
mailing list versus opinions offered for consumption by the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   In between, one participant invited everyone to a party at a Las
Vegas computer show, another to visit her company's booth at
Cannes, and another to attend her course on career advancement in
the music business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pho has become a place where people can come together and find
one another,'' said Griffin, who now helps young Internet companies
develop through his incubator Evolab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contacts are being made. Deals are being made. That's good,
because some people have great ideas and some people have the money
to fund them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, much of the most important networking takes
place at the Sunday gatherings, where people can put a name to a
face and talk more freely than an electronic format allows. When
the crowds swell, the waiters know with a glance to bring more
chairs. With no other way to reach the far side of the L-shaped
table _ actually many tables shoved together _ the waiters carry
the chairs out the front door and hand them through a side
door.Then everyone scoots over to make room.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one gets up to speak, no one calls anything to order,''
said Mike Griffin, Jim Griffin's younger brother, who moved to Los
Angeles in September to join Evolab. ``You see people who might be
CEOs of companies in T-shirts and shorts. It's nonconformist.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Omega Medina was among the newcomers, invited by a
friend who had been turned on to Pho by another friend, as often
happens. Medina, who is a senior awards coordinator for the
National Academy of Recording Arts &AMP; Sciences, said she was there
to ``pick brains,'' and get in on the discussion that will help
determine how music is delivered to the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point where there's no turning back,'' Medina
said. ``It's a Web world, a Web lifestyle. The question is: What's
the right way to go?''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rafael Quezada never misses a meeting ``unless
something absolutely pulls me away.'' An attendee since April, the
former general contractor turned Internet security specialist said
he knows that the ideas hashed out over soup will be the ideas that
guide music on the Web for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music needs structure more than anything in this new world
that's cyberspace,'' Quezada said. ``The business models haven't
yet been defined and when they are, the people in the room will be
in the best position possible. This room is a seething hotbed of
creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   The room also happens to be rather dumpy, Griffin noted, which
makes it the perfect place for a free exchange of ideas. No suits,
no pomp, just the circumstance of a shared meal in an otherwise
quiet restaurant with no music playing in the background.
</P>
</TEXT>
