President Clinton gives his final State of the Union address to a
closely divided Congress in an election year. (Dart, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WINTER-SEAST _ More rotten weather is in store for the
Southeast, still recovering from the monster snowstorm that hit the
East Coast this week. Sleet greeted motorists in portions of
central Mississippi today, heralding what was shaping up as a major
winter event in this Deep South State. Weather watchers said the
arrival of a frigid Canadian air mass, coupled with a
moisture-packed system moving in from the west, promised to bring a
full range of winter precipitation _freezing rain, sleet and snow _
to all areas except the Gulf coast. In North Carolina, officials at
Raleigh-Durham International Airport in North Carolina are hoping
to reopen later today after clearing 20 inches of snow. (Manuel,
Atlanta Jourrnal-Costitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLU _ ATLANTA _ The flu bug hit many states earlier and harder
than expected, the CDC reported Thursday. The 1999-2000 flu season
began to increase in mid-December, four weeks earlier than in the
1997-98 season, and almost eight weeks earlier than in the 1998-99
season. The good news: Influenza cases appear to have already
peaked for the season. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ABERNATHY _ ATLANTA _ Former State Sen. Ralph David Abernathy
III says he has turned his life over to God. But his immediate
future rests in the hands of a Fulton County Superior Court judge.
McConnell is scheduled to sentence the son and namesake of
Atlanta's famed civil rights leader on Jan. ??. A jury found
Abernathy guilty last month of a scheme to pocket taxpayer funds.
Although his first trial ended in a mistrial, he was convicted by
the second jury on 18 counts _ five of theft by taking involving
$5,700, five of false swearing, five of violating his oath of
office, two of forgery and one count of influencing a witness. A
decision to appeal is being weighed. Attorney General Thurbert
Baker has indicated that his office will seek incarceration.
Abernathy's lawyer, Theodore Lackland, plans to ask the judge to
spare his client jail time. And most lawyers think the sentence
will not be harsh, based on other sentences for politicians.
(Whitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   SICK-WILLIE _ ATLANTA _ How do you treat an ailing 400-pound
gorilla? Any way he wants. Lots of good details on the illness and
treatment of the famed Atlanta Zoo gorilla Willie B, including
costs, details on how the vets get to him, etc. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COURT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Court Watch releases a report on
insurance votes at the Texas Supreme Court over the past decade.
(Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Texas editors.
</P>
