<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BREAST-CANCER-ADS-HNS     01-27 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ADS SHOWING WOMEN WITH MASTECTOMIES DON'T GO OVER IN SAN
FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Look. A woman in a bare-chested, provocative
pose stares at you with pursed lips, one hand on a rounded hip, the
other on a thigh.
</P>
<P>
   It is the classic sexy pose. But for one disturbing fact: The
woman in the poster has scars where her breasts had once been.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph of the woman with a double mastectomy is part of
an ad campaign by the Breast Cancer Fund, a San Francisco
nonprofit, designed to bring attention to the disease that affects
1 in 8 American women.
</P>
<P>
   But in this liberal city where anything goes, this won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very rough poster,'' said Lew Lillian, head of the San
Francisco office of Outdoor Systems, which has exclusive rights to
bus shelter advertising in city and turned down the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see it - a four-by-six-foot picture of a woman's
torso and you see these two bare red scars, I mean, to see a
woman's terribly, terribly scarred body, it's just not for public
consumption on the streets of San Francisco where children and
others can be traumatized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian said he had recoiled when first shown the ad, made to
look like a mock Cosmopolitan magazine cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked away,'' he said. ``It's too shocking. Too upsetting.
Too provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad shows the scarred chest of Andrea Martin, 53, the
director of the Breast Cancer Fund, superimposed over a model's
body.
</P>
<P>
   Two other posters, mimicking ads for Victoria's Secret lingerie
and Calvin Klein perfume, feature models with a single mastectomy.
The Victoria Secret-type ad reads: ``It's no secret society is
obsessed with breasts, but what are we doing about breast cancer?''
</P>
<P>
   The ads are meant to be unsettling, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Turning down the ad, she said, is like saying, ``It's way too
upsetting to see the ramifications of this disease and would you
please leave us alone?''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said she finds it ironic that San Francisco turned down
the ads while they are posted in about three dozen bus shelters in
more conservative, suburban Contra Costa and Santa Clara counties.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Board Supervisor Alicia Becerril doesn't think ads
depicting mastectomies belong in bus shelters for the same reason
Lillian and his staff turned them down. The image is too graphic
for the general population, she said, especially children.
</P>
<P>
   But she thinks the message is an important one that belongs in
locations where it could best target women.
</P>
<P>
   A similar ad in a woman's magazine prompted her to get a
mammogram last year, Becerril said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Judith Luce, co-director of the Breast Clinic at San
Francisco General Hospital, doubts that an ad depicting a
mastectomy would either prompt women to run out to get or avoid a
mammogram.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a political message rather than a health message,`` said
Luce, who like Becerril had not seen the ads. ``If it's dramatic,
it's going to get people upset and angry and talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Luce has no objection to placing the ads in bus shelters. She
said she found the fear that it would scare children a
double-standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all the other crap on TV and movies and all over the
place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin, who had one breast removed in 1989 and the other in
1991, understands why the photographs can be upsetting for some
because she had trouble coping with the visual image of herself for
a long while.
</P>
<P>
   What the ads hope to do is stir discussion and outrage, Martin
said. They ``hit something on a real visceral level,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1503EST &QL; 
