<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8214 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-27 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAYING GOODBYE TO PRESIDENT CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It really hit me when I heard George W. Bush
say, through his perma-smirk, that his victory in Iowa marked ``the
beginning of the end of the Clinton era.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to miss that old boy. If Clinton is replaced by the
son of a Bush he beat in 1992, I'm going to miss him an awful lot.
We can't go back to a Bush, a lesser one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Lately Clinton has been gloriously relaxed, living in a Martha's
Vineyard of the mind while the snow piles up outside.
</P>
<P>
   He's been talking philosophy and football with the reporters he
used to hate, dragging out press conferences as long as he can and
hatching more idealistic schemes than he ever did when he had an
outside chance of getting them through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Tax incentives to invest in depressed areas. Computers for the
poor. Funds for basic research. Another increase in the minimum
wage. Sure, the Republicans will go for all those as soon as they
are stirred by Clinton's final State of the Union speech Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton looks marvelous, though, and that's what counts, at
least when you're facing a temporary separation from your wife.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba has slimmed down. He's wandering around in the snow in
blue jeans, boots and a brown suede jacket looking like some kind
of freewheeling Bob Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Clinton and I have had a special relationship,
although not as special as some he's had. Whenever he betrayed his
alleged beliefs, the truth or the public trust, I'd trash him.
That's a lot of columns.
</P>
<P>
   Man, he's been fun, for consumers of politainment as well as
providers.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest symbol of the symbol-ridden Clinton presidency, at
least to me, was in 1997. I learned that he wanted to start his
``national conversation'' on race at a college commencement and he
picked UC-San Diego, which didn't even have a university-wide
commencement.
</P>
<P>
   So UCSD created a huge commencement for Clinton on the athletic
field, renting folding chairs and making laid-back faculty members
rent colorful academic robes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced his fake national conversation on race at an
invented commencement and the national press covered it as if it
were real. It was pure Clinton. The man is the world's best
salesman of cold-pressed, extra-virgin, nouveau snake oil.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to that conversation on race? For some reason
we're talking about that ``symbol of heritage,'' the Confederate
flag, and having a national shouting match over a 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are constantly saying they're voting for The W
because he can win and because ``He's our Bill Clinton.``
</P>
<P>
   That's what they say. Sorry, I know Bill Clinton, and he's no
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is the Teddy Ruxpin of politics. He's cute and
cuddly, but there are only a limited number of things he has to say
when someone pulls the string.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Teddy Ruxpin, Bush has a tendency to muff his
pre-programmed lines. Not just muff them, but mangle them.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking a week ago about the fall of our former adversary,
the Soviet Union, he spewed pronouns the way his dad once spewed
sashimi.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was coming up, it was a dangerous world and we knew
exactly who they were,'' he told his Iowa audience. ``It was us
versus them and it was clear who them was. Today, we're not so sure
who the, they are but we know they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. may have the finest advisors from the finest
conservative think tanks, but if he gets elected, we're going to
have to listen to stuff like that for four years.
</P>
<P>
   His position on Roe vs. Wade, as expressed in Iowa, was, ``I
felt like it was a case where the court took the place of what
legislatures do in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, what? I felt like this was not the finest syntax or legal
reasoning I'd ever heard. His handlers didn't like him talking
about abortion at all. They have to get him past the rhetoric into
the White House so he can appoint anti-abortion judges.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is good when he's on the spot. He can talk cogently on
any subject at the drop of a question, a subpoena or an intern.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to miss our Bubba when he's gone, and it almost
seems like he's gone already.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
