   GERMANY-FUNDRAISING (Berlin) _ Christian Democrats in state of
Hesse turn up more tainted millions. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND-MYANMAR (Bangkok) _ The tiny jungle base of God's Army,
the Burmese rebel band led by twin 12-year-old boys, was overrun by
the army of Myanmar on Thursday, Thai officials said. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Whether or not Super Bowl XXXIV
is remembered for the game the St. Louis Rams and Tennessee Titans
will play on Sunday, it will certainly enter the annals of Madison
Avenue as Dot-Com Bowl I. But will consumers recall it as a
dot-comedy of errors or the day that Internet advertisers joined
the ranks of Super Bowl mainstays like Anheuser-Busch, Federal
Express, PepsiCo and Visa? More than a dozen of the 30-plus
companies spending an estimated average of $2.2 million for each
30-second spot will be Web sites and electronic commerce
entrepreneurs. Last year, there were only two dot-com advertisers
during the Super Bowl, three if you count a commercial from the
Victoria's Secret unit of Intimate Brands promoting an online
fashion show. The stakes have never been higher for companies
gambling that the impressions they make by exposing themselves to
the 130 million or so Americans watching the game will justify the
huge outlays to buy commercial time. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-EURO (Undated) _ The euro, which had been flirting with
parity with the dollar all week, falls below $1 in value in early
currency trading, as the dollar is bolstered by expectations of
stronger growth and higher interest rates in the United States. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   GILLETTE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Looking at Gillette in the wake of
the apparent interest P&AMP;G had showed in it. Gillette is expected to
report fourth-quarter earnings after the stock market closes.
Forecast is for 32 cents a share. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly econmoic column. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   HANCOCK-IPO (New York) _ Shares of John Hancock begin trading,
rising just $1 from its offering price. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-FORUM (Davos, Switzerland) _ Looking at the opening of the
World Economic Forum in Davos. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-NATWEST (London) _ Bank of Scotland improves the terms
of its hostile bid for National Westminster Bank by replacing a
controversial 120-pence special dividend with a special stock unit,
effectively raising the bid's value. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
