<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-OLDCITY-$ADV30     01-27 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-OLDCITY-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YEARS AFTER INTIFADA, ISRAELIS RETURNING TO OLD CITY
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ These days, Israeli Yael Boksenboin(cq) can visit
Jerusalem's Old City like a tourist: With her toddler daughter and
without the rifle she used to carry.
</P>
<P>
   She was a soldier here during the Palestinian Intifada uprising
that swept the region 10 years ago. Then, this tourist haven _ an
ancient walled district in downtown Jerusalem _ was the scene of
frequent attacks on Jews by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   There was a permanent Israeli presence in the small Jewish
Quarter. But most Israelis stopped their frequent shopping or
dining excursions to the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   When the Intifada ended in 1993, the fear remained. So did
Israeli troops, stationed along the narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the last year, Israelis have been rediscovering the Old
City. Especially on Saturdays, Hebrew can be heard sprinkled among
the Spanish, English and Italian of the foreign sightseers and the
Arabic of the locals.
</P>
<P>
   When Boksenboin, a 30-year-old lawyer, visited a couple months
ago, it was the first time in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   She strolled by the Western Wall, sacred to Jews. She took in
the scents of the bazaar's spices and hummus, which she recalled
from her visits as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I was here I was a soldier and I walked with a
gun,'' she said. ``I don't have to look behind my back like I used
to. It's feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why Israelis are returning now is not clear. People cite
the current rarity of political violence. Some say that progress in
the peace process makes them feel more at ease among Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Israelis are feeling more at home in the
heart of their cherished, yet disputed, capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good sign,'' says Israeli Meron Benvenisti, who
was a top city official during the Intifada and saw the decline in
Israeli visits to the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to define the whole thing as the geography of fear.
People are overcoming the fear,'' said Benvenisti, whose book
``City of Stone'' describes the city's ethnic tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis still rarely venture into other Arab areas of
Jerusalem. Benvenisti is skeptical that the political climate is
responsible for their return to the Old City. He said that the lack
of recent violence has prompted Israelis to simply rediscover a
delight they had missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real a phenomenon,'' said Israeli tour guide Doron Bar,
who was leading a group of Israelis recently.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the group toured China. With Bar, they were
visiting the Old City's Church of the Holy Sepulcher, believed by
many to be the site of Christ's crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit may belong to an exhibit of works from
American glass sculptor Dale Chihuly. Opened in July in a museum
garden just inside the Old City walls, it has sold nearly 700,000
tickets to foreigners and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   From the exhibit, many venture further to Old City shops and
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The stone streets of the Old City, which is less than a square
mile in area and dates back more than 3,000 years, are lined by
more than 3,000 shops. They sell everything from tacky tourist
T-shirts to the meat, vegetables and clothes used by the locals.
They also offer fine jewelry, pottery and carpets from throughout
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Around the shops live the residents. The large Moslem Quarter is
home for more than 20,000 Palestinians. The Christian Quarter is
also mostly Palestinian. There are smaller Armenian and Jewish
Quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Israel took total control over the Old City when it captured it
from the Jordanians in 1967. Palestinians seek to govern their own
affairs there and most countries officially consider the matter up
for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian merchants seem pleased to see Israeli shoppers
returning.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Palestinian Adel Kawasmi has seen the return of a few
Israelis who came to his shop regularly before the Intifada. They
would share tea and buy his glass bowls and drinking glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy to see them here, of course,'' he said. ``The
business is much better.''
</P>
<P>
   And Israelis don't mind that Arab merchants have commercial
motives for wanting them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt really welcome. They all said, 'Please come in,'''
said Anat Inbar, a 24-year-old television producer. ``I know it's
for economic reasons, but that's good. That's normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
