<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-0128-COX     01-27 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-0128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI POLICE TO PROBE BARAK'S ELECTION CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With public support crucial for his efforts in peace
talks, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Thursday faced the first
scandal of his administration as police started a probe into his
campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Attorney General Elyakim Rubenstein ordered the probe
based on a report from the government's independent comptroller,
issued earlier Wednesday. The report fined Barak's campaign more
than $3.2 million for using non-profit organizations to get around
campaign spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited 11 other parties with violating the rules and
Rubenstein ordered that four, in addition to Barak's One Israel
faction, be investigated. But, nearly half the 62-page report
focused on One Israel, which it said was clearly the worst
violator.
</P>
<P>
   Barak won a landslide election victory in May and has presented
himself as a man Israelis can trust with the life-and-death
decisions in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   He came before reporters Thursday to deflect the allegations and
say he may appeal the fine to the Israeli supreme court(CQ).
</P>
<P>
   The former army commando is known for his meticulous attention
to detail. As prime minister, he has overseen every step of peace
negotiations and doubled his role by serving also as defense
minister. But Thursday, he said he was not aware that his campaign
was raising millions of dollars through non-profit groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave clear guidelines to act only within the framework of
the law,'' he said. ``It is not reasonable to expect the prime
minister candidate to make sure all his instructions are carried
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak had been questioned briefly during the probe by Israeli
Comptroller Eliezer Goldberg. In his report, Goldberg said Barak
should have known what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially with the wide range of the activity explained in
this report, the candidate should have seen a red light,'' Goldberg
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The report and the police probe cap a series of unrelated
political scandals rippling through Israel's upper echelons. Former
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is under investigation for gifts
he accepted on the job. President Ezer Weizman, whose role is
mostly ceremonial, is under investigation for taking nearly
$500,000 in cash from a wealthy French supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's opponents in the right-wing Likud Party, who have seen
limited success leading opposition to Barak's approach to peace
talks with Syria and the Palestinians, seized on the elections
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should stop whining and take responsibility,'' said Likud
leader Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Barak's campaign used recently formed
groups like ``Advancement of Taxi Drivers in Israel'' and ``Our
Hope is Not Lost'' to collect money from donors whose identities
were concealed. The money then went to pro-Barak campaign
activities, such as conducting polls and rallies.
</P>
<P>
   The spending allegedly put Barak's campaign over the
approximately $21 million spending limit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report said that a top campaign manager, Yitzak
Herzog, used money for the campaign from the estate of deceased
European philanthropist Octav Butner. The report said Herzog was
managing the estate, but that the money was supposed to go to
charities.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
