<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN-CERAMICS (New York) _ ``Korean ceramics from the Museum
of Oriental Ceramics, Osaka'' is not, as Yogi Berra might have
said, a case of deja vu all over again. More than 35 of the nearly
50 pieces in this serenely beautiful show were part of a larger
exhibition of ceramics from the same museum that traveled to
Chicago, San Francisco and the Met in 1992. But it scarcely
matters. The recidivists, like the first-timers, constitute the
masterworks of the Osaka museum's extensive Korean holdings. By
Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-MINNEAPOLIS (Minneapolis, Minn.) _ Snow paralyzes some
American cities and disheartens others. But Minneapolis and its
unidentical twin, St. Paul, cope with it. More than that; many
people here positively revel in it. Winter is their favorite
season. Our peripatetic correspondent R.W. Apple Jr. reports from
the Twin Cities.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BACH-ANNIVERSARY (Undated) _ The last Bach year wasn't so long
ago: 1985, to be exact, the 300th anniversary of the composer's
birth. And although Bach had to share the celebration with other
masters born in the fateful, fertile year 1685, Handel and
Scarlatti, he did not lack for attention. Now, in the calculus of
births and deaths, centenaries and quarter-millenniums, and points
in between, comes another Bach year: the 250th anniversary of the
composer's death. Not complaining, mind you. In addition to the
commercial aspects _ books, records and scores; concerts, recitals
and festivals _ and the odd bit of flimflammery, such
commemorations typically give a jolt to scholarship on the subject
as well as a boost in public awareness. By James Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
