<HEADER>
A8245 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-CANCER-VICTIM-SPI &LR;      01-27 2284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-VICTIM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLINDSIDED BY DISEASE, LIFE, SHE FIGHTS TO SURVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Italics) Ann gives (the chemo) slowly, with pauses to run
saline through the line. She talks non-stop throughout the 45
minutes it takes to give me the drugs. Calmly and cheerfully, she
runs down the list of possible side effects. I have a printed sheet
in my hand so I can follow along . . . (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeanne's Diary
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jeanne Sather has learned a lot about possible side
effects since she was first diagnosed with cancer 17 months ago.
She's learned about nausea, headaches, hair loss, the usual things
that go with cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   And she's learned about some things you don't always hear about
_ orange urine, pink tears.
</P>
<P>
   Getting fired.
</P>
<P>
   Call them the unwritten side effects, the collateral damage of
serious illness that no one mentions _ friends who disappear
because your mortality reminds them of their own. Jobs that vanish
without explanation. These are the side effects you don't prepare
for because you don't see them coming.
</P>
<P>
   Sather wasn't sure what to expect Jan. 11 when her supervisor at
OnHealth Network Co. in Seattle called her into his office.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her cancer treatment, Sather had shared her most
private thoughts in the most public of forums _ the Web. As an
editor for OnHealth.com, Sather chronicled her cancer ordeal in an
online journal that drew hundreds of correspondents and national
media attention to the then-fledgling Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst of her battle, she thought, was behind her. She
had completed her second round of chemo and radiation. She was
looking forward to new projects at work and savoring a newfound
serenity in life. She was feeling healthy again.
</P>
<P>
   She was shocked when her supervisor closed the door and told her
she was being let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally blown away,'' Sather said. Officially, she was
told the company didn't have room for her anymore because of a
redesign of the Web site. Her supervisors said they hadn't been
entirely happy with her performance. They offered her two months'
severance pay.
</P>
<P>
   Sather, however, believes that she was fired because having
cancer interfered with her ability to work without adjustments to
her schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials would not comment specifically on the reasons
for her dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Her dismissal came two working days after OnHealth had received
a letter from her physician recommending she be allowed to work
flexible hours while her body recuperated from her second round of
chemo and radiation. It came one day after the company had abruptly
canceled her previously scheduled performance review.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the company, Dr. Robert Livingston, professor of
medicine at the University of Washington and Sather's primary
oncologist, wrote: ``For women who have had the cancer treatment
that Jeanne has had _ mastectomy, chemotherapy and radiation _ it
usually takes a year to return to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston recommended she be allowed to leave the office after
six hours to take a nap, then complete her work from home in the
evenings, an ``accommodation'' Sather and her doctors felt was
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Under both the Washington State Law Against Discrimination and
the Americans with Disability Act, employers are required to make
reasonable accommodations for employees with short- or long-term
disabilities, said Kelby Fletcher, an attorney specializing in
employment law who is representing Sather. Sather declined the
severance offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired her knowing full well she had cancer,'' said Mary
Bruno, senior vice president of publishing for OnHealth Network.
``In fact, it was on the strength of Jeanne's Diary that we offered
her a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which provides information for consumers about
health, was looking for someone who could provide a personal touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very much in keeping with our editorial philosophy,''
Bruno said. ``We're providing good medical information from a
consumer point of view, trying to remove that sense of professional
chill and provide a kind of warmth. I think Jeanne's Diary hit that
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diary was very well written with a great narrative voice.
It touched a chord with users.''
</P>
<P>
   No warning:
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) I don't remember exactly the words I used back in
September when I told my sons I had cancer, but I was dreading the
conversation. Finally, after worrying for a week, I simply told
them that I had breast cancer, that I was having surgery to remove
the breast, that I'd have some other treatment after the surgery,
and that I'd be fine. Then I waited for their questions ... Akira,
my 14-year-old, wanted to know what it was about cancer that hurt
you. So what if those cells were growing, where was the harm in
that, he asked. I couldn't answer that one. (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   The end of her job, like her cancer, came without warning, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sather was 43 and had no known risk factors for breast cancer
when she found out she had a tumor growing in her breast. She never
felt the lump. Neither did her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really fortunate _ I just went in for an annual exam _
and it was all fine,'' said Sather, who sports a brush cut of
strawberry blonde hair, thanks to chemotherapy. ``The doctor told
me to get a mammogram and I really resisted. I had one when I was
40 and wasn't convinced I needed another one yet. But she was
pushy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably saved my life. It gives you chills.''
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) The night before my mastectomy, I said goodbye to my
right breast in the shower as I scrubbed with a special
antibacterial soap to prevent infection in the operating room. I
washed my breast, knowing that by the same time the next day it
would be gone, part of it off to a lab for analysis, the rest sent
to an incinerator, I suppose, with the other medical waste. There
is a tremendous feeling of unreality: This is not happening.(End
italics)
</P>
<P>
   Sather, then a freelance writer and editor, started work on a
half-time contract basis for OnHealth.com in October 1998, a week
after her mastectomy. In December, she began writing the online
journal for the company as a free-lancer. The site had links to
information about breast cancer, as well as a bulletin board where
cancer patients and others could respond to the journal. Sather was
staggered by the response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had women telling me their happy stories, and their sad
ones,'' she said. ``I put a human face on it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) But let me tell you what my friends did for me in
those early weeks: They brought me stories of women who had
survived. They gave me phone numbers of more women who had survived
breast cancer and who could tell me, with authority, that I would
survive it, too.
</P>
<P>
   These women told me that I would cry when my hair fell out, that
I would feel sick with chemo, that I would sometimes feel very
sorry for myself, that I would laugh sometimes at the indignity of
it all, but that I would get through it, as they had.
</P>
<P>
   They were the greatest gift, these stories.(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   New priorities:
</P>
<P>
   Sather has always loved her work. With a master's in journalism
from the University of California-Berkeley, she has worked for a
variety of news organizations, including a five-year stint as a
reporter in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   After her diagnosis, she made adjustments, but never considered
quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suddenly realized, it's really true _ life's finite,'' she
said. ``I've tended to slow down, cut a lot of things out. My
children are my first priority, and my work and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, OnHealth made Sather a permanent, full-time
employee when it hired her to direct promotions. She continued to
do some writing and editing in addition to promotions work.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after getting hired full time, her cancer came back.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) There I was, lying in bed on a sunny Sunday morning
with the newspaper and a cup of coffee, enjoying feeling well.
After five months of cancer treatment and five more months of
recovery _ gaining energy day by day, remaking my life to fit my
new values _ it was the kind of moment I'd learned to savor: The
sun through the blinds, buttery yellow and warm, but not too hot;
the coffee, strong and rich with cream. And then I rubbed my hand
across my chest where my right breast used to be and felt a
lump.(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   She froze. The odds of surviving breast cancer are 80 to 90
percent for a localized tumor, she said. If the cancer spreads to
other organs, ``it's a whole other ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was lucky. The second lump was a local recurrence, which
happens in only about 3 percent of cases, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors recommended more surgery to get ``clean margins,'' then
a course of chemotherapy with Taxol, and radiation five days a week
for 6{ weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This time, she was determined not to let cancer be the center of
her life.
</P>
<P>
   She took her younger son, Robin, 9, with her to appointments.
``He'd play Nintendo and I'd get zapped,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) Facing chemo again, I made several promises to myself:
First, to stay away from people who seem to believe I am going to
die or people who depress me with their own fears about cancer.
Second, to exercise through my treatment if at all possible ... And
third, I decided not to let the cancer treatment take over my
life.(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   She scheduled chemo for Fridays so the worst of it would be over
by Monday morning when she had to go to work. A former marathon
runner, she was accustomed to pain, but this was different.
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) My joints ached as if I'd run a marathon and
contracted the worst flu of my life at the same time. I spent the
next three days hiding in my bed crying with pain. Late on the
third day, I was able to walk around a bit. On the fourth, still
feeling achy, I went back to work, and for a swim afterward.(End
italics)
</P>
<P>
   Taxol treatments came every three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked through it,'' she said. In the fall, the company put
her on special projects so she could do more work from home. She
finished treatment in early November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been really fortunate,'' she said. ``I'm strong, and it
didn't beat me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she returned from her special projects assignment, OnHealth
Network gave her a written job description for the first time, she
said. It specifically declared her job was a ``full-time on-site''
position. She figured it meant they wanted her in the office 40
hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   She canceled doctor appointments and physical therapy
appointments to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In early January, she went for her two-month, post-treatment
checkup and was told she was working too much.
</P>
<P>
   That's when her doctor wrote the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Her sudden dismissal two days later upset her for practical
reasons _ life and health insurance are difficult for a 45-year-old
cancer patient to obtain, and crucial for a single, working mother
of two children.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also the principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a health Web site, and here's somebody asking for
accommodation,'' she said. ``And yet they were not willing to work
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was her willingness to be absolutely candid in her journal
that attracted ``hits'' to the site. Readers followed her through
her bout with medication-induced depression, her first purchase of
a breast prosthesis, and her forays into alternative treatments
(light therapy, vitamins, hypnotism).
</P>
<P>
   They commiserated over side effects such as weight gain and
``chemo brain.'' They laughed when she nicknamed her ``sluglike,
jiggly'' prosthesis ``Jabba'' (after the Star Wars character). A
friend later brought her a box for it labeled ``Jabba's Hut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my life on the Web,'' Sather said. ``And it brought them
a lot of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mails continue to this day, she said. Her journal was
mentioned in media reviews of the Web site, including ones in the
Los Angeles Times and AV Video.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity helped fuel OnHealth's breakneck growth. OnHealth
was launched in June 1998 by Robert Goodman, formerly of MSNBC.
Since then, the company, which now has about 125 employees, has
attracted more than 100 advertisers and e-commerce partners,
including American Express, Merck, Glaxo Wellcome and Johnson &AMP;
Johnson. It is considered one of the most successful health Web
sites in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Reality check:
</P>
<P>
   Two days after losing her job, Sather got the news every cancer
patient dreads: her X-rays appeared to show a spot on her lung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd lost my job, and I was very upset about that. But my life
is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, more tests showed her lungs are clear. But the
scare forced her once again to focus on priorities. These days, she
walks with friends, plays with her kids and works on free-lance
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have so much energy,'' she said. ``And I can't put it
into being angry. I have to put it into being healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Italics) It is too soon to write the last word on what breast
cancer means to me, or even to write the next-to-last word. But
looking back, I can say cancer made me bold _ bold enough to
buzz-cut my own head, bold enough to go out in public without a
hat. Bold enough to write this diary and put it up on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer made me brave _ brave enough to tell the people I love
most that I have cancer, brave enough to face the changes in my
body and the possibility of a shorter life, brave enough to say,
``I need help right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer made my priorities crystal clear, even when so much else
was not clear.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer made me laugh. I had to laugh. (End italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
