<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8250 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV3     01-27 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ABORTION, SUPREME COURT CONSUME THE GOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Jan. 30)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service Clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the hour approached for the five remaining
Republican presidential hopefuls to begin sparring on the New
Hampshire field of debate, a reporter asked Sen. John McCain of
Arizona what he would do if his teen-age daughter were pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Would he sanction an abortion or would he demand that she give
birth to the child and rear it as a single mother?
</P>
<P>
   McCain replied that the decision would rest with his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, as news services and television reporters
spread word of McCain's answer, the Arizonan claimed he had not
understood the question and announced that he wished to correct his
answer. The matter, he said, would be considered by his whole
family prior to a decision.
</P>
<P>
   News of the incident, a seemingly minor matter, demonstrated how
disproportionately important opposition to abortion and the Supreme
Court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade ruling that legalized the procedure have
become in the GOP quest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In their debate that same evening, the five Republican
presidential hopefuls discussed issues that would require the
attention of the next president: taxes, trade, national defense and
how to allocate the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   But no issue generated more heat or triggered more impassioned
declarations than abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Former diplomat Alan Keyes, the most eloquent and reactionary of
the five, accused McCain, a former Navy pilot and Vietnam prisoner
of war, of displaying a ``profound lack of understanding'' of the
abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, the most plain-spoken and independent of the
Republican hopefuls, pointed out that he was the only one of the
five who has voted on the Senate floor for the ``preservation of
life of the unborn.''
</P>
<P>
   He was, said McCain, ``proud of my pro-life record.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the senator reveled in a 6-3 Supreme Court decision
upholding a Missouri law limiting the amount of money that an
individual can contribute to a candidate for public office. McCain
was a co-sponsor of a bill to overhaul the nation's campaign
financing laws, legislation that was defeated by the Senate's
Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   McCain contended that the high court decision was a
``magnificent affirmation the effort I've been making for years.''
</P>
<P>
   His fellow GOP senators had claimed such limits on campaign
contributions were unconstitutional because they violated the
guarantee of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who triumphed over other Republicans
in the Iowa caucuses last week, repeated his contention that a
limit on campaign contributions would hurt the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who did not compete in the Iowa caucuses, replied that
he has always believed that what is good for America is good for
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   When the two contenders for the Democratic presidential
nomination, Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley, mounted the stage following the GOP debate, they were not
troubled with abortion or restrictions on campaign contributions.
Both Democrats defend a woman's right to choose and they have
expressed support for changing campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the candidates in both parties demonstrated that
they had done their homework and were prepared to speak
knowledgeably on matters that are vital to the future of America.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Gore and Bradley got bogged down in charges and
counter-charges about they have campaigned against each other.
Therefore, much of their hour-long debate was consumed with
assertions about the personal conduct of the candidates rather than
a fuller explanation of their positions on critical issues.
</P>
<P>
   What was incredible about the evening was the amount of heat and
anger displayed by Republicans over abortion, which is one of the
most divisive issues confronting the men who seek to lead the
world's most powerful nation.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, former Reagan administration aide Gary Bauer cited
Justice David Souter, who wrote the Supreme Court's decision on
campaign spending, as the kind of judicial activist who should not
be appointed to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Bauer, Bush grinned nervously but said nothing.
It was his father, President George Bush, who appointed Souter,
with the consent of the Senate, to the court. In words tinged with
disgust, Bauer also noted that seven of the nine justices were
named by Republican presidents.
</P>
<P>
   He might also have noted that four of the six justices who ruled
in favor of limits on campaign spending were nominated by the last
four Republican presidents _ Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford, Ronald
Reagan and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite obvious that as the campaign continues, the
Republican presidential candidates will distance themselves as far
as they can from the Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
