<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS AND NOTES FROM THE NEW YORK ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Depiction Of Progress
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three years ago the Russian emigre Conceptual artist
Ilya Kabakov created ``Monument to the Lost Glove,'' a giant glove
made of red plastic resin, which was bolted to the traffic triangle
where Fifth Avenue and Broadway cross at 23rd Street. Organized by
the Public Art Fund, which presents art around the city, the glove
was meant to seem as if it had dropped from nowhere. It became one
of the Public Art Fund's most popular projects.
</P>
<P>
   Kabakov and the fund have teamed up again with a more ambitious
endeavor. From June 13 to July 15, they will present ``The Palace
of Projects,'' originally commissioned and exhibited by Artangel, a
nonprofit group that organizes art projects in England and at the
Reina Sofia Museum in Madrid. It is to be shown at the 69th
Regiment Armory, Lexington Avenue at 26th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a strong project that spoke to the
millennium,'' said Tom Eccles, director of the Public Art Fund.
``But also an intellectual humanistic project.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palace of Projects'' is a collection of 65 model
environments with explanatory texts, drawings and sketches that
explore the improvement of the human condition. It is housed in a
40-foot-tall spiraling wooden structure in which one room follows
another, up several levels.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the enormousness of the project, the armory was one
of the few spaces in Manhattan that could house it. It was also the
site Kabakov chose for the installation _ the longest event ever
held at the armory, since most last only a few days. It will cost
$300,000 to produce, making it one of the Public Art Fund's most
expensive projects. Bloomberg News has agreed to be the show's main
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   To raise money for the project, Kabakov has created a pair of
limited-edition lithographs for sale through the Public Art Fund.
They cost $600 each or $1,000 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palace of Projects is a summation of Kabakov's work,''
Eccles said. ``It's also an incredible moment to have a Russian
artist in the process of becoming an American citizen exhibiting in
an active military armory.''
</P>
<P>
   Met's Web Site
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the Metropolitan Museum of Art created its Web
site. It was a pretty rudimentary affair, with only calendar
listings and basic information about the museum. This week, after
two-and-a-half years of intense planning involving every department
in the museum, the Met has introduced a new, undated web site
(www.metmuseum.org). It is packed with images, including a large
portion of the Met's vast collection, and information including an
interactive calendar, exhibition previews and 26 educational
features.
</P>
<P>
   The site has sections called ``My Met Gallery,'' which allows
visitors to store their favorite images, and ``Explore and Learn,''
which offers extensive resource modules on ancient Egypt and on
Byzantine art. Users can create ``My Met Calendar,'' a personalized
list of preferences, and request e-mail reminders about particular
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see what's happening today or six months from now,
when you know your mother will be visiting,'' said Emily Rafferty,
senior vice president for external affairs, who headed the project.
``The entire site is meant to be a microcosm of who we are, to
create a sense of depth that mirrors the museum.'' Every aspect of
the Met, from fund-raising and subscriptions to education to the
collection, is represented.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rafferty said the site would be updated daily. ``It is like
a house that can be added to, either out or up,'' she said. Over
time, the museum plans to add virtual-reality tours of some
galleries, including the period rooms of the American Wing, and to
double the number of objects from its collection that may be viewed
online.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney Curator
</P>
<P>
   The final piece of the Whitney Museum of American Art's
curatorial puzzle is in place. This week, Lawrence R. Rinder,
director of the CCAC Institute at the California College of Arts
and Crafts in San Francisco, who was one of the freelance curators
of this year's Whitney Biennial, was named curator of contemporary
art.
</P>
<P>
   New Role at Christie's
</P>
<P>
   Although Christopher Burge is now honorary chairman of
Christie's in America, not its chairman as he has been for six
years, he said he would still be the principal auctioneer,
presiding over major sales in New York. He plans to continue
working with experts on attracting business. Stephen Lash, vice
president of Christie's, will become the new chairman in the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
