<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: HIGH STYLE AND CHARM IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Palm Beach, Fla., the premier social event of the winter
season is traditionally the Red Cross Ball, a huge charity dance
that brings out Old Palm Beach society in couture gowns and real
jewelry. Now another Palm Beach party is beginning to attract
attention: the preview of the Palm Beach International Art and
Antique Fair, which this year will be on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The fair opens to the public next Friday and runs through Feb.
13.
</P>
<P>
   This vernissage, a benefit for the Norton Museum of Art in West
Palm Beach, cannot boast the Red Cross Ball's parade of diplomats,
its detachment of military men who present the flag, or a society
band, but it does pull an affluent crowd, which is all you want if
you are one of the 78 exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   The New York interior designers Mario Buatta and Ann Downey are
co-chairmen of the Collectors and Connoisseurs Committee, whose
mission is to encourage collectors and Norton Museum benefactors to
attend the fair. This year the committee includes high-profile
decorators like Lars Bolander, Tom Britt, William Diamond, Anne
Eisenhower, Juan Pablo Molyneux, Juan Montoya and Bunny Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become a social evening where you go to see and be
seen,'' said Buatta, who was chairman of the Winter Antiques Show
in New York for 17 years. ``The party attracts people from South
America and all over. It brings in new clients for the dealers.''
</P>
<P>
   The fair's organizers, David and Lee Ann Lester, instituted some
changes this year, their fourth. ``In the past, the fair suffered
from not having enough antiques,'' Lester said, ``so we cut down
the number of paintings dealers and added more furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 30 dealers from the United States, 31 from Britain, 10
from Paris and one each from Argentina, Austria, Canada and
Germany, Lester said. ``We have more diversity this year,'' he
added, ``including specialties like antique pianos at Maximiliaan's
House of Grand Pianos, numismatics at Louis DiLauro and gilded
furniture at Ossowski.''
</P>
<P>
   New dealers from London include the Silverfund.com (vintage
Georg Jensen silver), Graham Gallery (18th- and 19th-century
English furniture), Windsor House (19th-century Continental
furniture), Adrian Alan (19th-century Continental furniture) and
Marilyn Garrow (antique textiles).
</P>
<P>
   Among the first-time American dealers are Charles Edwin Puckett
of Dallas (antique maps and prints), Kenneth W. Rendell of New York
(autographs and manuscripts), Elise Abrams of Great Barrington,
Mass. (Tiffany and Limoges antique tableware), Antonio's of San
Francisco (18th- and 19th-century Italian furniture) and Earle D.
Vanderkar of Knightsbridge Inc. (ceramics) from New York.
</P>
<P>
   For people in South Florida, the influx of outside dealers
offers an opportunity to learn as well as to shop. Many dealers
have been in business for decades. One exhibitor, for example, is
Florian Papp, a New York company founded in 1900, whose famous
clients have included Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis and her sister,
Lee Radziwill. It is now run by the granddaughter of the founder,
Mindy Papp, with her brother William and their mother, Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Because Florian Papp has a large stock of 18th-, 19th- and early
20th-century English and Continental furniture, it is particularly
popular with designers charged with the instant decoration of
50,000-square-foot ``megahouses'' in Long Island, N.Y., and Palm
Beach. Nina Campbell of London, the Chicago architect Stanley
Tigerman and the New York designers Greg Jordan, John Saladino,
Kitty Hawks, David Easton and Stephanie Stokes are in this group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mindy used to have all period furniture, but now she has
decorative pieces as well,'' Ms. Stokes said. There still is a lot
of period furniture at Florian Papp, a three-floor gallery on
Manhattan's Madison Avenue. ``My mother is basically interested in
18th-century English furniture,'' Ms. Papp said. ``My brother
William studied at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London and got
us into 19th-century English, with Aesthetic Movement and Arts and
Crafts pieces and 20th-century Art Deco. I don't have any special
period. In an average week, I review about a thousand antiques and
buy one or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that the job of an antiques dealer ``is to provide
things you wouldn't find elsewhere,'' Ms. Stokes elaborated:
``Mindy has the eye of an art director. All her pieces have some
special detail that sets them apart from the ordinary and makes
them interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach, for example, Ms. Papp will show a cabinet with
chinoiserie decoration. It is an example of a Western type of
furniture decorated with Western-painted Chinese motifs, as opposed
to a piece of Western-style furniture made by the Chinese for
export.
</P>
<P>
   The black lacquered piece is a Regency Pagoda cabinet that sits
on a stand. It was made in England about 1810 and has a
pagoda-shaped roof that was inspired by the Royal Pavilion at
Brighton, England, a folly made between 1802 and 1831 that boasts
one of the richest chinoiserie interiors ever created.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet has a two poly-chromed chinoiserie panels depicting
Chinese figures in a temple. The black lacquered cabinet legs and
panel borders are decorated with small motifs in parcel gilt. The
cabinet is delicate, unusual and charming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so interested in age, provenance or country of
origin,'' Ms. Papp said. ``A piece has got to be pleasing to the
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   It is completely unlike another, more traditional chinoiserie
bureau bookcase she is offering at the fair. This one is an
18th-century English form, with a double dome top and a slant-front
desk. It is the kind of cabinet particularly popular among
Anglophile Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Buatta recalled that the decorator Rose Cumming, a famously
flamboyant person, had three such bureaus in one room of her house
on West 53rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rage for chinoiserie got started with the Duchess of
Windsor, who had a brown-lacquered one,'' Buatta said. ``They
became popular here because of Colefax &AMP; Fowler, a London
decorating firm founded by Nancy Lancaster, a decorator from
Virginia. Later on, Eleanor Brown, the founder of McMillen &AMP; Co.,
had a red one made in Spain. Americans think that chinoiserie
bureau bookcases are high style; the English like lacquer in the
Chinese style, but for them it's not so serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Buatta added that he has shopped at Florian Papp for 40 years.
``Most dealers play it safe,'' he said, criticizing the ``boring
brown furniture'' he sees in some other galleries, particularly
common antiques in the Chippendale and Hepplewhite styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most New York dealers sell chickendale and hecklewhite,'' he
said, laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
