 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; FRIDAY &LR; , Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Atlanta) _ Sports of The Times column on Bill
Belichick, who after weeks in limbo is a free man and on his way to
New England, where he will become the Patriots' general manager and
head coach. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Atlanta) _ Sports of The Times column on
Trent Green, who was ticketed to be the St. Louis Rams' starting
quarterback this season, but was hurt in an exhibition game and saw
unknown Kurt Warner take his place and end up as the league's most
valuable player. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BELICHICK (Undated) _ Bill Belichick's battle to shake free
of the Jets is over. A late-night phone call involving the Jets and
Patriots leads to a deal in which Belichick is now free to take
over New England's football operations as both coach and general
manager, with New England compensating the Jets for letting
Belichick go. By Judy Battista and Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS-FASSEL (Undated) _ Giants Coach Jim Fassel gets a
one-year extension on his contract, which was due to run out after
the 2000 season. Fassel wanted a longer extension, but ultimately
accepted what the Giants offered him. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-TEAMS (Atlanta) _ Both teams vying for the National
Football League championship, the Tennessee Titans and St. Louis
Rams, have relocated three times, leaving rankled fans and civic
leaders in their wake. Each has an owner who could be described,
charitably, as colorful. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MATCHUP (Undated) _ Two looks at Sunday's Rams-Titans Super
Bowl, with two predictions. By Mike Freeman and Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NETS-VANCOUVER (Vancouver, B.C.) _ N.J. Nets at Vancouver,
10 p.m. EST start. By Chris Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN (Melbourne) _ Action at the Australian Open,
including Agassi's defeat of Sampras. By Christopher Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
