<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-MINNEAPOLIS-AR     01-27 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-MINNEAPOLIS-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNEAPOLIS: WHERE WINTER'S A WONDER AND SMILES ARE SINCERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Snow paralyzes some American cities and
disheartens others. But Minneapolis and its unidentical twin, St.
Paul, cope with it. More than that; many people here revel in it.
Winter is their favorite season.
</P>
<P>
   Come here the morning after a blizzard, and main roads have
already been cleared. One time my wife, Betsey, and I, inured to
snow-induced civic inertia in Washington, watched dumbfounded as a
miniature street-sweeping machine brushed snow from downtown
sidewalks as soon as it fell.
</P>
<P>
   Take a ride out to Lake of the Isles, southwest of downtown
Minneapolis, on a crisp, cold Saturday, with the skies a pure,
cerulean blue and the snow heaped eye-high in front of wonderful
big Prairie Style houses by gifted acolytes of Frank Lloyd Wright
like George Washington Maher and George Grant Elmslie. Young men
and women play exuberant pick-up hockey on the frozen lake, like
figures in an Avercamp painting, while more sedate souls glide past
on cross-country skis. At times like that, ``Winter Wonderland'' is
more than a song title.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard polar winds blow, people here say ``You
betcha,'' just the way they did in the movie ``Fargo.'' They smile
and urge you to have a nice day, so earnestly that they convince
you they mean it. So sincerely that cynics call Minnesota ``the
Land of the Bland,'' a dubious epithet for a state with a
counterculture that gave the world Bob Dylan and an electorate that
chose Jesse Ventura, a bullet-bald former wrestler, as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans and Scandinavians who flocked here toward the end of
the 19th century were used to cold weather. The Vietnamese,
Mexicans and Somalis who came here toward the end of the 20th
century were not, but they quickly got the hang of it. And a good
thing, too: from December to March, there is an average of about 6
inches of snow on the ground; in January, midday temperatures often
struggle to reach the balmy double digits.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Twin Cities are so far north. Seattle and
Montreal, London and Berlin and even Paris are all nearer the
Arctic Circle than Minneapolis and St. Paul, but they're all
reasonably close to the sea. The Twin Cities lie hundreds of miles
from the Atlantic or Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged by this newspaper's assertion in 1885 that Minnesota
was an American Siberia, a group of civic boosters founded the St.
Paul Winter Carnival, which has evolved over the years into a sort
of Arctic Mardi Gras. Every year, with unfailing regularity,
Vulcanus Rex, the king of fire, drives wintry King Boreas from his
throne, insuring the return of spring. Otherwise sane men and women
run in the world's frostiest half-marathon, and in some years an
ice palace weighing millions of pounds is constructed.
</P>
<P>
   The humorist Garrison Keillor, the pot-roast poet laureate,
whose weekly radio program, ``A Prairie Home Companion,''
originates most weeks from the Fitzgerald Theater in St. Paul, once
said that ``true Minnesotans have a fondness for storm fronts, a
lack of fashion sense and a belief that there is moral worth in
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, The Wall Street Journal ran a piece about John
Glotzbach, one of a group of nutty Minnesota Vikings fans who
regularly watch the team's games not from seats inside the
relatively toasty Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome but on portable
television sets outside their cars in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got offered tickets, but I hate the dome,'' he said, with
all the righteous zeal of an ice fisherman. ``It's way too
corporate.''
</P>
<P>
   An extreme case, obviously. Less masochistic Twin Cities
residents keep frostbite at bay during their brutal winters by
spending a lot of time indoors. The world's first enclosed shopping
mall, Southdale, opened in Edina, a Minneapolis suburb, in 1956. It
was a smash hit, soon copied in other suburbs. Alarmed, downtown
merchants invented the Skywalk, a system of enclosed passages a
story above the street, linking buildings and making it possible to
reach shops, restaurants and offices without venturing outside. Now
100 buildings in Minneapolis and 65 in St. Paul are linked.
</P>
<P>
   Musical and Stage Riches
</P>
<P>
   For such relatively young cities _ Minneapolis was not
incorporated until after the Civil War _ these two have a
startlingly rich artistic tradition. Philanthropic families like
the Pillsburys, Cowleses and Daytons have helped build orchestras,
museums and theaters of national repute.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Orchestra (formerly the Minneapolis Symphony),
which will celebrate its 100th birthday in 2002-3, has been led by
conductors of the caliber of Eugene Ormandy, Dimitri Mitropoulos,
Antal Dorati and Neville Marriner. Its home is Orchestra Hall in
Minneapolis, whose superb acoustics are enhanced by a distinctive
``icefall'' of white cubes that runs across the ceiling and
cascades down the wall behind the players.
</P>
<P>
   Eiji Oue, the Hiroshima-born incumbent conductor, came here as a
complete unknown, on the recommendation of Seiji Ozawa, the music
director in Boston. Some critics praised his work, including
Anthony Tommasini of The New York Times, who wrote in 1998 that Oue
seemed to be ``making good things happen.'' But he has never earned
the full confidence of the orchestra, and attendance has fallen
from 84 percent of capacity to 69 percent during his tenure. He
will leave in 2002, ``by mutual agreement,'' and the orchestra is
seeking a big name as his replacement at a time when big names are
scarce and at least a half-dozen orchestras in America, plus
several in Europe, are in the market.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Paul Chamber Orchestra, the closest American counterpart
to such European groups as the Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields,
is also losing its leader, Hugh Wolff. A successful successor to
Christopher Hogwood and Pinchas Zukerman, among others, he has been
the principal conductor in St. Paul since 1988 and the music
director there since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Music is served here in other ways as well _ by the Minnesota
Opera, a tireless promoter of new music, based at the Ordway Center
for the Performing Arts in St. Paul, which plans to move next year
from four productions annually to five; the Viennese Sommerfest,
founded by the conductor Leonard Slatkin; and Minnesota Public
Radio, long a national leader in classical-music programming.
</P>
<P>
   An Irish stage genius named Tyrone Guthrie, fresh from triumphs
at Stratford in Canada, gave the Twin Cities a theatrical showplace
in 1963, with an unconventional thrust stage like those of ancient
Greece and Elizabethan England. Under another Irishman, Joe
Dowling, the Guthrie company is enjoying its greatest successes
since the early days, with classics like Shaw's ``Misalliance,''
O'Neill's ``Ah, Wilderness!'' and O'Casey's ``Plough and the
Stars,'' plus modern fare like John Guare's new play, ``Lake
Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   It wants to do more, and Minneapolis has just released a plot of
land downtown, previously reserved for a baseball stadium, for a
proposed new Guthrie Theater containing three auditoriums of
various sizes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Art and Architectural Depth
</P>
<P>
   The Walker Art Center is one of the nation's foremost museums of
modern art, second only, in some people's thinking, to the Museum
of Modern Art. It rotates its collection constantly, to make space
for special shows, so many of its iconic pictures, like Franz
Marc's ``Large Blue Horses,'' are always in storage. But its
holdings of Jasper Johns and Donald Judd, Ellsworth Kelly and
Robert Rauschenberg are large, and a selection is always on view.
So is more contemporary stuff, like a 1997 sculpture by Charles
Ray, a life-size plastic cast of a wrecked Pontiac. Is it a comment
on the fragility of modern life or modern culture, or perhaps both?
</P>
<P>
   A large sculpture garden occupies most of a block across from
the museum, dominated by Claes Oldenburg and Coosje Van Bruggen's
hilarious giant teaspoon, topped with a brilliantly red cherry.
</P>
<P>
   A second major museum, the Minneapolis Institute of Arts,
aspires to mini-Metropolitan Museum of Art status, with collections
sampling all of world art history. After a 10-year restoration
ending in 1998, its collections have been reinstalled, with 4,000
objects now on view, as against 1,125 in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Its strengths lie in German art between the wars (lots of Ernst
Ludwig Kirchner, a great Max Beckmann triptych, an extraordinary
Emil Nolde, all orange and blood-red); in Impressionism and
Post-Impressionism, including major van Goghs and Gaugins; in
Chinese jade, and in American decorative arts. A hall from one of
Wright's triumphs, the Francis W. Little house on Lake Minnetonka,
demolished a number of years ago, is on display here, along with
furniture by Wright, Maher and Elmslie. (Another part of the Little
house is in the Met.)
</P>
<P>
   The main museum building is a finely detailed Beaux Arts temple
by McKim, Mead &AMP; White, the Minneapolis counterpart of St. Paul's
great hilltop landmark, the state capitol by Cass Gilbert, a
hometown boy. With its refined marble dome and gilded quadriga by
Daniel Chester French, the capitol can hold its head high in the
company of Boston's and Richmond's.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Minneapolis, two of the most dramatic structures,
the IDS skyscraper by Philip Johnson and the Hennepin County
government center by John Carl Warnecke, have large glazed atriums
perfectly suited to the climate. The seven-story Crystal Court at
the IDS Center is particularly felicitous, a meeting place for the
city, with a ring of water dropping from the ceiling into a pool.
The opening of ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' set in the Twin
Cities, was filmed there.
</P>
<P>
   Eliel Saarinen and his son, Eero, built a spare Lutheran church
in Minneapolis that might be in rural Finland. Marcel Breuer built
a much-praised, Corbusier-influenced concrete chapel at St. John's
College in nearby Collegeville. But neither dazzles quite as much
as Frank O. Gehry's shimmering Frederick R. Weisman Art Museum
(1993), at the University of Minnesota, a kind of dress rehearsal
for his Bilbao Guggenheim, which changes color with the changing
weather. Clad in brushed stainless steel, its lopsided cubes and
irregular cylinders tumble down the east bank of the Mississippi
like Duchamp's ``Nude Descending a Staircase'' in three dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Big Suburbs, New Ethnicity
</P>
<P>
   These are not river towns in the sense that St. Louis or Memphis
are, but the Mississippi, which rises in Lake Itasca, near Bemidji,
220 miles northwest of here, flows right through the middle of the
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis is mostly but not wholly on the right bank, St. Paul
mostly but not wholly on the left. Which is a shame, because it
spoils the otherwise telling gibe of Trevor Fishlock, an English
journalist, who wrote after spending some time here that the Twin
Cities ``are divided by the Mississippi River and united by the
belief that the inhabitants of the other side of the river are
inferior.''
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis is often called a small big city, St. Paul a big
small town. Once Minnesota consisted of the Twin Cities, the
prairies and not much else, but in recent years the suburbs have
taken over. Today Minneapolis and St. Paul have only about 500,000
people between them, yet there are roughly 3 million in the
metropolitan area, a seemingly uncontrollable sprawl that now ranks
15th in population among the nation's urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Out there, due south of Minneapolis, stands the humongous Mall
of America, incorporating no fewer than 500 stores, 49 restaurants,
14 theaters and 12,000 employees, a walk-through aquarium and a
seven-story Ferris wheel. People fly to the Twin Cities from Europe
just to shop there.
</P>
<P>
   The old ethnic order has changed rapidly in the last
quarter-century. No longer is Minneapolis mostly Swedish and
Lutheran and St. Paul mostly German, Irish and Catholic. After the
Vietnam War, Minnesotans opened their arms to boat people and other
immigrants from Southeast Asia, notably the Laotian hill people
known as the Hmong. They poured into the cities, followed by
Latins, Africans and others. John W. Milton, an old college chum
who grew up in St. Paul, told me that children in the St. Paul
public school system came from households in which no fewer than 63
languages were spoken.
</P>
<P>
   By now, there are 60,000 members of the Hmong in the area. They
are passionate about education. Joua Xiong, a semiliterate
health-care attendant who grows vegetables for sale in a farmer's
market to make ends meet, has six children with university degrees.
One of them is working on a doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   Robber Barons' Legacy
</P>
<P>
   The old economic order has changed, too. The first great
fortunes hereabouts were made from flour, timber and railroads; you
can sense how big those fortunes were by visiting the enormous
Richardsonian Romanesque mansion of James J. Hill on Summit Avenue
in St. Paul. It has 18 bathrooms, 35 fireplaces, a pipe organ and a
two-story art gallery. When built in 1891, it was the largest house
in the Midwest. Hill, a notoriously obstreperous gent, came to St.
Paul when it was still named Pig's Eye and built the railroad that
linked the Twin Cities to the wheat fields and to the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   West of Hill's pile, along a four-mile section of Summit Avenue,
his fellow robber barons built Belle Epoque piles of their own,
most of which have been diligently preserved. In the homely
brownstone at 599 Summit Ave., which he described as ``a house
below average on a street above average,'' F. Scott Fitzgerald, a
St. Paul native, spent the summer of 1919 finishing ``This Side of
Paradise,'' the novel about Princeton that made him famous.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A block south of Summit runs Grand Avenue, the capital of the
New Bohemia in the Upper Midwest _ young, hip, brainy, almost
Bostonian. At the corner of Grand and Victoria, you'll find the
nexus of the local cafe culture, chockablock with bookstores and
coffee houses. Cafe Latte, in an old Studebaker showroom, serves a
deservedly famous three-layer turtle cake, dripping chocolate,
caramel and pecans, indescribably rich, improbably light. Betsey
spent a half-hour trying to figure out how to get one home.
</P>
<P>
   Big business seems far away, but it isn't. The Twin Cities have
lost some headquarters lately; Norwest Bank bought Wells Fargo, but
its CEO and its main office moved to San Francisco, and the new
bank took the Wells Fargo name. Honeywell, an old Minneapolis firm,
has been sold to Allied Signal; the merged operation will be called
Honeywell but will move East.
</P>
<P>
   Still, plenty of big names remain, like Northwest Airlines, 3M
(Scotch Tape, Post-Its and $16 billion in annual sales) and the St.
Paul Companies (insurance). With Pillsbury, now a part of the
British conglomerate Diageo PLC, Cargill and General Mills
(Wheaties, Betty Crocker), Minneapolis remains the greatest
grain-milling center in the world. Dayton Hudson, which owns big
department stores here, in Chicago and in Detroit, is changing its
name to Target to reflect the national scope of its discount
stores. Innovators abound. The Radisson Hotel chain, once regional,
is now international. The Best Buy retail chain has made its
founder, Richard Schulze, a billionaire. Medtronic and St. Jude
have flourished in the realm of new medical technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Fitzgerald cult has survived in the face of all these
changes, proving to be hardier than Fitzgerald himself. Keillor
campaigned successfully to have a restored St. Paul theater named
for him, and there the whimsical Minnesotan and his lively
co-conspirators tell tales about a Thanksgiving turkey that fell in
love with a dog, and reassure us, no matter how frazzled we may be,
that there is one place where ``the women are strong, the men are
good-looking and the children are all above average.''
</P>
<P>
   That place, of course, is Lake Wobegon, as important a part of
the Minnesota landscape as Lake Minnetonka near Minneapolis and
White Bear Lake near St. Paul. Upward of 2.6 million people listen
to the Wobegon news each week on 450 public stations across the
nation. But the Twin Cities are worldly, civilized places. They
resemble Lake Wobegon no more than they resemble another North
Country stereotype, Sinclair Lewis' ``Main Street,'' based on his
proverbially provincial hometown, Sauk Center, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvest of Politicians
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the Twin Cities sent politicians on to prominent
roles on the national stage. Every four years from 1948 through
1984, with only a few exceptions, a Minnesotan sought the
presidency or vice presidency _ Harold Stassen, a serious contender
before he became a standing joke; Hubert H. Humphrey, Eugene J.
McCarthy, Walter F. Mondale. Several others, like Orville Freeman
and Donald Fraser, played significant supporting roles.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey, a garrulous, big-hearted electoral warrior, made his
national debut at the 1948 Democratic convention. As ``the boy
mayor of Minneapolis,'' he fought the South, exhorting his fellow
delegates to step ``out of the shadow of states' rights and into
the bright sunshine of human rights.'' Two decades later, Humphrey
came agonizingly close to the White House, even though he found
himself, as Lyndon B. Johnson's vice president, saddled with
support for the hugely unpopular Vietnam War. Not until late on the
morning after Election Day 1968 did he finally, tearfully concede
defeat to Richard M. Nixon in the ballroom of the old Leamington
Hotel here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a wonderful political culture,'' Mondale said over
dinner one night recently. ``Clean, progressive, tolerant.
Minnesota had a magnificent moderation then.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, that is gone. Neither of the not terribly prominent
current senators, Rod Grams, a Republican, and Paul Wellstone, a
Democrat, fits the old mold. Each resides on the ideological edge
of his party. Americans for Democratic Action, a liberal pressure
group, gives Wellstone a perfect score of 100 and Grams a zero.
Humphrey's son, Hubert Horatio Humphrey III, called Skip, ran for
the Senate in 1988 and for governor in 1998, but despite a good
record as state attorney general, his feet never quite reached the
stirrups.
</P>
<P>
   Flamboyant Centrist
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Jesse Ventura, elected governor on the
third-party Reform ticket in 1998, who is still a highly popular
figure in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   As a wrestler, under the nom de guerre Jesse the Body, he wore a
feathered boa, and he has lost none of his flamboyance. But beneath
it all, he is a centrist, not an extremist, who won in part because
the voters were tired of far-out politics. A political libertarian
on cultural issues, who stands firmly against gay-bashing, Ventura
is also a fiscal conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style may be fire-engine red,'' Professor Steven Schier of
Carleton College observed not long ago, ``but his politics are
beige.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of attractions in Minneapolis and St. Paul, ,
along with travel information:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   NICOLLET ISLAND INN, 95 Merriam St., Minneapolis, (612)
331-1800. Built as a sash-and-door factory in 1893, this modest,
three-story hotel sits in mid-Mississippi, just upriver from the
stone arch bridge constructed by James J. Hill to carry his
railroad west. Antiques in the lobby and guest rooms give the place
a rural feel, and an agreeable restaurant with sweeping river views
occupies the glassed-in former loading dock. Room rate: $125 to
$160.
</P>
<P>
   HYATT WHITNEY, 150 Portland Ave., Minneapolis, (612) 339-9300.
An atypical Hyatt, installed in a cleverly converted flour mill,
the Whitney offers 96 rooms, slightly spartan in mood. The best are
duplexes, with sitting rooms linked to sleeping rooms by spiral
staircases, facing the Mississippi at the spot where Minneapolis
began. A red sign across the way _ ``Pillsbury's Best Flour'' _
recalls the city's economic roots. Room rate: $185 to $210 week
nights; $99 to $210 weekends; $25 to $35 more for duplexes.
</P>
<P>
   MARQUETTE HOTEL, 710 Marquette Ave., Minneapolis, (612)
333-4545. Built into the IDS skyscraper, and now managed by the
Hilton chain, the Marquette has a prime location, with connections
to the Skywalk system. In a city of mammoth hotels, it is
manageable in size and individual in character. The oversize rooms
on the upper floors have steam baths and attractive views over the
city, but there is no valet parking and the staff can be dim. Room
rate: $240 week nights; $119 weekends.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ST. PAUL HOTEL, 350 Market St., St. Paul, (651) 292-9292. If
business or pleasure takes you to the smaller of the Twin Cities,
make a beeline for the St. Paul, the region's best hotel. Built in
1910 and brought up to date 75 years later, blessed with a good
concierge, furnished with a lavish hand (Oriental carpets,
exuberant flower displays), it has an ideally central site. The
hotel's grill is St. Paul's finest restaurant. Room rate: $180 week
nights; $125 weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   AQUAVIT, 75 S. Seventh St., Minneapolis, (612) 343-3333. A
branch of New York's top Scandinavian restaurant in America's top
Scandinavian city seems like a no-brainer. But instead of mailing
it in, Marcus Samuelsson, the chef at both places, brings witty,
sometimes wacky ideas to the Twin Cities, aided by a bigger
kitchen: smoked salmon and mango foam wrapped in newspaper (fish
with no chips?); lobster wrapped in tuna and gravlax, bathed in a
spicy tomato broth.
</P>
<P>
   D'AMICO CUCINA, 100 N. Sixth St., Minneapolis, (612) 338-2401.
In his two years at the helm of this urbane, understated
establishment, J.P. Samuelson, who worked for David Bouley in New
York, has developed a vivid style. A smoked trout salad with
horseradish creme fraiche and lots of flat-leaf parsley explodes
with flavor, as does crisp flatbread with prosciutto, gorgonzola
and rhododendron honey. The all-Italian wine list is a revelation,
packed with Barolos from the 1970s and '80s, from Aldo Coterno et
al. Except for the snowdrifts outside in wintertime, you could be
in Piemonte.
</P>
<P>
   LA BELLE VIE, 312 S. Main St., Stillwater, (651) 430-3545. After
a long stint at D'Amico Cucina, Tim McKee opened this bistro in a
picture-book village on the St. Croix River. Spanish, Moroccan and
Portuguese influences, as well as French and Italian ideas, are
evident in his brightly seasoned, deeply flavored dishes and on the
imaginative wine list. Harissa, mojo verde and Serrano ham on the
American steppes? You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   GOODFELLOWS, 40 S. Seventh St., Minneapolis, (612) 332-4800.
Newly installed in a magnificent Art Deco space that once housed a
cafeteria, with black glass and silvery grillwork, this longtime
local favorite features regional products like walleyed pike and
pheasant. The cellar holds dozens of superb American wines at
sensible prices. Unhappily, the kitchen sometimes resorts to empty
Asian flourishes in pursuit of culinary fashion, and the service is
often klutzy.
</P>
<P>
   LUCIA'S, 1432 31st Street West, Minneapolis, (612) 825-1572. A
double storefront, with uncovered floors and plain tables, this is
a Twin Cities Cafe Chez Panisse, with short weekly menus and a
commitment to ``locally grown, organic and naturally raised
ingredients.'' Killer eggs Benedict with perfectly timed yolks for
weekend brunch, on smoked pork tenderloin.
</P>
<P>
   QUANG, 2719 Nicollet Ave., Minneapolis, (612) 870-4739. Take it
from someone who learned the hard way, this is real Vietnamese
food: a long list of soups, including several kinds of pho;
caramelized shrimp and onions on rice, and the best cha gio (spring
rolls) I have eaten _ greaseless, crisp and flavorful. Bright,
clean and always packed, Quang may be the best of the small Asian
and Latin eateries, spawned by Twin Cities ethnicization, that
stand shoulder-to-shoulder along Nicollet Avenue, ``Eat Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   FITZGERALD THEATER, 10 E. Exchange St., St. Paul, (651)
290-1221. ``A Prairie Home Companion,'' with the Cajun band Beau
Soleil featuring Michael Doucet, tomorrow at 4:45 p.m.; with Druha
Trava, Czech bluegrass band, Feb. 5 at 4:45 p.m. Tickets: $10, cash
only; on sale at 4:15 p.m. the day of performance.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA ORCHESTRA, Orchestra Hall, 1111 Nicollet Mall,
Minneapolis, (612) 371-5656. The first half of the program features
works by George Gershwin, Richard Rodgers, Kurt Weill, Henry
Mancini and John Williams; the second half, Debbie Reynolds
performing with the orchestra, conducted by Scott Terrell, Jan. 28
and 29 at 8 p.m. Tickets: $20.75 to $39.75. ``Adventures in Music:
A Cowgirl in the Old West,'' a one-hour family concert conducted by
Giancarlo Guerrero, including Copland's 1942 ballet ``Rodeo'' with
original choreography by Ballet Arts Minnesota. Jan. 30 at 2 and 4
p.m. Tickets: $17 to $29.50; $11 to $21.50 for children.
</P>
<P>
   ST. PAUL CHAMBER ORCHESTRA, (651) 291-1144. Conducted by Max
Pommer. J.S. Bach's Brandenburg Concerto No. 6 and No. 1; Vivaldi's
Concerto Grosso in D Minor from ``L'Estro Armonico,'' Concerto in D
Minor from ``Madrigalesco,'' Concerto in G for String Orchestra,
Concerto in G Minor for Flute from ``La Notte''; Tartini's Sinfonia
in D. Jan. 28 at 8 at Wooddale Church, 6630 Shady Oak Road, Eden
Prairie. Tickets: $17 to $45. Jan. 29 night at 8 at St. Paul's
United Church of Christ, 900 Summit Avenue, St. Paul. Tickets: $26
to $45.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA OPERA, Ordway Center for the Performing Arts, 345
Washington St., St. Paul, (651) 224-4222. ``Der Rosenkavalier'' by
Richard Strauss. Jan. 28 at 7:30; Jan. 29 at 8 p.m.; Jan. 30 at 2
p.m. Tickets $25 to $80.
</P>
<P>
   GUTHRIE THEATER, 725 Vineland Place, Minneapolis, (612)
377-2224. George Bernard Shaw's ``Misalliance.'' Jan. 28 at 7:30;
Jan. 29 at 1 p.m.; Jan. 30 at 7 p.m. Tickets: $16 to $39; $11 to
$34, students and the elderly; $8 to $19.50, childen.
</P>
<P>
   WALKER ART CENTER, Vineland Place at Lyndale Avenue South,
Minneapolis, (612) 375-7577. Hours: Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Thursdays, to 8 p.m.
Admission: $4; $3, students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS INSTITUTE OF ARTS, 2400 Third Avenue South, (612)
870-3131. Hours: Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.; Tuesdays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Thursdays, to 9 p.m. Suggested
donation: $3.
</P>
<P>
   FREDERICK R. WEISMAN ART MUSEUM, University of Minnesota, 333
East River Road, Minneapolis, (612) 625-9494. Hours: Tuesdays
through Fridays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Thursdays, to 8 p.m.; Saturdays
and Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES J. HILL HOUSE, 240 Summit Avenue, St. Paul, (651)
297-2555. Hours: Wednesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 3:30 p.m.
Admission: $5; $4, the elderly; $3, children.
</P>
<P>
   HUBERT H. HUMPHREY METRODOME, 900 S. Fifth St., Minneapolis,
(612) 335-3370.
</P>
<P>
   ST. PAUL WINTER CARNIVAL. Through Feb. 6. Information: (651)
