<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOHL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL-ED CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Germans are learning that the political machine of former
chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Party was lubricated
with a hidden flow of illegal funds. For Germany, as for its
allies, the scandal over Kohl's slush fund should serve as a
political allegory.
</P>
<P>
   There is first of all the familiar spectacle of a politician who
accomplishes great feats for his people but succumbs to the
attrition of power.
</P>
<P>
   With Kohl, as with lesser political figures in town halls and
chancelleries around the world, too long a turn in office induced a
common syndrome. The symptoms include an addiction to one's
position, a belief that one must do whatever it takes to remain on
top, and finally the fatal decision to break the rules so a
sovereign people will not be deprived of their indispensable
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The rules Kohl has admitted breaking were the heart and soul of
a democratic polity. He sold influence, or the illusion of
influence, for money _ reputedly to a shady arms dealer, among
others _ and then used that money to buy loyalty. Having an
unreported slush fund at his disposal enabled him to ensure that
restive members of his Christian Democratic Party would not even
think about replacing him as their leader.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's covert peddling and purchasing of influence violated the
principle of transparency that distinguishes representative
governments from those in China, Syria, or Sudan. The moment an
elected leader takes secret funds from undisclosed donors, he
ceases to be the leader chosen by voters or party members. If he is
for sale, he belongs to any buyer who pays his price, not to the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   There is always a certain pathos when a statesman capitulates to
the temptation of corruption, but the case of Kohl is more pathetic
than usual because he earned a place in history as the chancellor
who peacefully retrieved East Germany into a single democratic
German state and integrated that state into a stable, harmonious
Europe. But money, which has no conscience, can erode even the
finest of democratic reputations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
