   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-UNION (Washington) - President Clinton will propose a
$350 billion tax cut in his final State of the Union address,
urging relief from the marriage penalty and a new program of
retirement savings accounts. By GREG McDONALD.CLINTON-EDUCATION
(Washington) _ In his State of the Union address, President Clinton
calls for a doubling of federal spending on after-school programs
and summer school to help children in failing schools achieve high
academic standards, and expansion of Head Start by $1 billion. The
ambitious plan is likely to encounter resistance in a
Republican-controlled Congress that wants less federal involvement
in education, not more. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECH (Washington) _ What a difference a year makes.
When President Clinton last addressed Congress, he had been
impeached by the House and was on trial in the Senate. This year,
he is laying out his most ambitious agenda ever, an election-year
potpourri of health programs and tax breaks. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   SPEECH-GORE (Washington) _ When President Clinton stands before
Congress, Vice President Al Gore will be perched over his shoulder.
At times, Gore likes to be identified with this president, and at
others he wants some distance. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   SPEECH-SUPREMES (Washington) _ The nation's highest court will
be a no-show at President Clinton's last State of the Union speech.
Supreme Court officials delivered a brief note to the House
sergeant-at-arms that said, ``No justices will be in attendance.''
By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-NEGOTIATIONS (Washington) _ As White House and Puerto
Rican officials meet to discuss permanently closing the Navy's
bombing range on the island of Vieques, Sila Calderon, San Juan's
mayor, blasts the service for its ``appalling'' and ``shameful''
treatment of the island's 9,000 residents. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-BOXER (Washington) _ Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.,
reiterates her threat to filibuster any legislation that would
grant citizenship to Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban who was
rescued from the Atlantic in November. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
