   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-N.H. (Stratham, N.H.) _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley presses
his attack on Vice President Al Gore for ``misrepresenting'' his
policy proposals and insists that a candidate must speak the truth
on the campaign trail. Bradley _ who has previously criticized the
president for misrepresenting his health plan _ says if a candidate
does not tell the truth in the campaign, the American people can't
trust him to tell the truth as president. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-GORE (Manchester, N.H.) _ Former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley has ``had it'' with Vice President Al Gore and has decided
it's time to throw a few elbows around. No more Mr. Nice Guy High
and Mighty, he declares in New Hampshire. From now on, it's time to
attack. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.GOP-2000 (Manchester, N.H.) _
Presidential hopefuls George W. Bush and John McCain dicker over
who's more liberal. Although each claims the conservative mantle,
they also join President Clinton in the ranks of those offering tax
cuts. By R.G. RATCLIFFE and CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GORE-CALIF (Sacramento, Calif.,) _ With the New Hampshire
primary only days away and California about to become every
candidate's prom date, a new poll shows Vice President Al Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush remain the favorites among California
voters. By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The message of the dissolving
candidacy of former Sen. Bill Bradley is that if you hold yourself
out as more principled and high-minded than your opponent, it
better be true and you better stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to reverse his political slide, Bradley suddenly
dropped his mask of statesmanship in the New Hampshire debate,
negating the theme on which he had intended to distinguish himself
from Gore. No more Mr. Nice Guy. But Gore is smoother at the tough
guy tactics. A frustrated Bradley got too personal in his attacks
on Gore and came across as a mean-spirited whiner. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
