   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ This year's presidential campaign
demonstrates how disproportionately important opposition to
abortion and the Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade ruling that legalized
it in 1973 have become to Republicans. In their debate the other
evening, the five Republican presidential hopefuls discussed issues
that one would require the attention of the leader of the world's
most powerful nation: taxes, trade, national defense, health care,
education, immigration, campaign finance reform and how to allocate
the budget surplus. But no issue generated more heat or triggered
more passionate declarations than abortion. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
