<HEADER>
A8334 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-DEALING-WITH-FAM     01-27 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-DEALING-WITH-FAME-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING IN THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Leonardo
DiCaprio in a scene from ``The Beach'' and Winona Ryder in a scene
from ``Girl, Interrupted.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Talk to movie stars, especially these days, and you'll notice
one theme that keeps coming up.
 &HT;    No matter which multimillionaire actor you talk with, you can
count on hearing about the terrible toll of fame, the plague of the
ever-bolder media and the pressure of never being able to simply
disappear into the crowd.
 &HT;    In short, they're saying that, having achieved what they dreamed
of from childhood _ as did many others who never realized those
dreams _ they still aren't satisfied.
 &HT;    Promoting her movie ``Girl, Interrupted,'' Winona Ryder talks
about the pressures that sent her into a mental hospital in her
late teens. Gwyneth Paltrow complains that winning an Oscar for
``Shakespeare in Love'' (l999) left her a virtual prisoner in her
own home, hiding from a swarming horde of ruthless paparazzi.
 &HT;    Such complaints are nothing new, of course, and it's not always
mere attitude _ fame can be debilitating: Drew Barrymore was an
alcoholic at 10 and a drug addict at 12. Charlie Sheen, another
prominent second-generation star, has had recurring drug problems.
In November Matthew McConaughey was arrested after police in
Austin, Texas, found the handsome actor naked in his living room,
banging on bongo drums and surrounded by drug paraphernalia.
 &HT;    Fame can also have practical drawbacks for actors. After all,
their job is to observe human behavior, and that's difficult to do
when the whole world seems to be observing you. Add in a paparazzi
corps which, these days, often acts little better than a gang of
criminals, and it's understandable if actors sometimes have second
thoughts about stardom.
 &HT;    But as a rule it's hard to sympathize with people who, after
devoting their lives to chasing fame and riches, start complaining
as soon as they succeed _ especially since they're usually quite
happy to manipulate the publicity machine when it suits them,
jumping restaurant lines and copping free invitations to the
hottest sports events and social affairs.
 &HT;    The latest star singing the fame blues is Leonardo DiCaprio, who
has pocketed $20 million for his role in ``The Beach,'' which will
open Feb. 11.
 &HT;    DiCaprio's life was, of course, turned upside down by his
success as the romantic artist Jack Dawson in ``Titanic'' (l997).
He became the darling of the teen crowd, whose fanatic devotion
made the movie the all-time box-office king of the world.
 &HT;    Wearing a wispy goatee beard and looking anything but the hunk
his worshippers consider him, DiCaprio is casually dressed in a
baggy T-shirt, blue jeans and sandals as he meets the media at the
Ritz Carlton Hotel on the Hawaiian island of Maui. His look is
almost a rebuttal to the idea of Hollywood glamour, which he admits
he finds overwhelming.
 &HT;    ``I wish someone had written a book about what to do to
survive,'' he says. ``It's a monster you have no control over. They
advised me to become a hermit and stay out of sight _ but I
thought, why do that? So I became a party animal.
 &HT;    ``As a result,'' he adds with a crooked smile, ``there were some
pretty weird stories being published.''
 &HT;    Those kinds of stories are rarely written about stars who choose
not to live their private lives in public, of course. Paul Newman
and Robert Redford, for example, have managed to be big stars while
still keeping their private lives more or less out of the public
eye for decades.
 &HT;    But once you've become tabloid catnip, it's difficult to go back
to being just a working actor. And as the papers scramble to top
their last stories, the reports tend to get more and more lurid.
 &HT;    During the Thailand shoot of ``The Beach,'' for example, there
were stories that DiCaprio had been attacked by sharks. He was also
said to have become obsessively fearful of being poisoned, to the
extent of hiring food-tasters. Furthermore, the tabloids reported,
he'd impregnated his leading lady, French actress Virginie LeDoyen.
 &HT;    ``All rubbish,'' DiCaprio says. ``I think it's sad that they
have to make up that stuff.''
 &HT;    His main buffer between himself and the madness, DiCaprio says,
is his family. His parents divorced when he was a child, but both
remain his closest advisers.
 &HT;    ``Leonardo is not the kind of actor who comes with a huge
professional entourage,'' notes Danny Boyle, director of ``The
Beach.'' ``And he's not someone who asks for huge perks. The only
perk he has in his contract is that he gets extra money to fly in
his friends and family to wherever he happens to be on location.''
 &HT;    But they can't be with him all the time, and it's when he's out
on his own that the bizarre realities of celebrity hit home, the
actor says.
 &HT;    ``I was at an airport and this young girl ran to me, threw
herself on the floor and attached herself to my leg,'' DiCaprio
recalls. ``And she refused to let go. I looked down at her and just
wanted to say, `I'm just an ordinary guy,' but I could see in her
eyes she wouldn't believe it anyway. It got crazy.
 &HT;    ``I've seen `Titanic' four or five times,'' he adds, ``but I'm
told some young women have seen it 100 times or more. That's sad,
because there's so many other good movies out there.''
 &HT;    Many stars blame the tabloid press, and especially its
photographers, for their increasing problems. Alec Baldwin even
came to blows with one paparazzo, who was trying to photograph the
actor and his wife, Kim Basinger, as they arrived home from the
hospital with their new baby.
 &HT;    Paltrow learned firsthand how uncivilized the paparazzi could be
when, one day, she was out driving and ran out of gas.
 &HT;    ``There are pictures of me walking down the street with a gas
can, looking for the nearest service station,'' she says. ``No one
had the decency to give me a ride. They just wanted those demeaning
pictures.''
 &HT;    Ryder is 28, and unlike DiCaprio or Paltrow has been under the
spotlight for virtually her entire life.
 &HT;    ``I grew up in front of everybody,'' she says. ``I went through
puberty on film and even had my first period, literally, on film.''
 &HT;    At the same time, Ryder understands that the public is often
impatient with the constant ``poor me'' refrain from celebrities.
 &HT;    ``We're sickeningly well paid,'' she admits. ``We get these
amazing bonuses and lead these very charmed lives. But along with
it there's demons the public doesn't see.''
 &HT;    Like Ryder, DiCaprio admits that he enjoys the up side of his
fame.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to sound bitter,'' he says, ``because my
celebrity has given me a world of opportunities that others can
only dream of.''
 &HT;    Instead of complaining, he hopes to cool the media heat by
playing fewer romantic leads, re-establishing himself as one of his
generation's best actors, not simply a teen stud. His quirky role
in ``The Beach'' plays into that plan.
 &HT;    ``I didn't want to play another doomed romantic,'' he says.
``I'd gone from `Romeo and Juliet' (l996) to `Titanic,' and was
looking for a harder-edged character, one that wouldn't be so easy
for an audience to identify with.''
 &HT;    The only real escape he has, DiCaprio adds, is in the anonymity
of the highway.
 &HT;    ``It's getting into my car and just driving around
anonymously,'' he says. ``Sometimes I have to get a friend to whisk
me away secretly to where I've parked my Lexus _ and then I hit the
open road.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood
Stars and other features. &QL; 
