<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STELLA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STELLA DOES TRICKS': BLEAK, PERCEPTIVE AND CONVINCINGLY ACTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stella McGuire is a nice-looking, reasonably bright and
occasionally mischievous teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Her problem is that she is a prostitute with a past of childhood
sexual abuse by her widowed father in Glasgow and a present in
thrall to Mr. Peters, a polished middle-aged pimp in London who
looks as if he might be running a major corporation instead of a
string of adolescent whores.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly because Stella, despite her haunting psychological
wounds, shows some spirit and gives evidence of an inner life that
lies beyond the reach of Mr. Peters, she is his favorite. He turns
to her for sexual relief at their outdoor meetings. Giving her
extra money, he fancies himself her generous benefactor. But fully
aware of his power and her damaged psyche, he takes offense at the
possibility that Stella might actually seek to break away from her
demeaning, perhaps deadly, life.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility lends poignancy and suspense to ``Stella Does
Tricks,'' Coky Giedroyc's bleak, perceptive portrait of the
prostitute as a young girl torn between a need for genuine love and
a career of sexual exploitation. Knowing that it can lead only to
ruin, she possesses the intelligence to realize what she should do.
The question is whether she possesses the psychological strength to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   Written by the novelist A.L. Kennedy, ``Stella Does Tricks,''
which opens Friday at the Screening Room, is convincingly acted by
a cast that includes Kelly Macdonald of ``Trainspotting'' and
``Elizabeth'' as Stella; James Bolam as the smooth, evil Mr.
Peters; Ewan Stewart as Stella's father, McGuire; and Hans Matheson
as Eddie, the weak young drug addict with whom she hopes to make a
fresh start when she leaves Mr. Peters.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the other young prostitutes kept by Mr. Peters
in a shabby bed-and-breakfast hotel seem resigned to their fate, a
streak of anger and yearning remains alive in Stella, seen in
flashbacks as a happy little girl whose childhood is corrupted by
her father, a talentless stand-up comic who enchants her with his
dreams of fame and fortune in London.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, Stella's rage erupts in acts of vandalism as
she scratches the finish of cars, rips off their aerials and
mirrors, and kicks in their headlights. One night, after one of her
colleagues has been assaulted by a bunch of punks, Stella enlists
Eddie in finding the car of the ringleader and dropping a match in
its gas tank.
</P>
<P>
   The assault convinces her that she should try to make a new
life, but not before the fatherly Mr. Peters, who is not above
meaningful torture, sends three brutes to the hotel to make an
example of her for the other prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   And after Stella, accompanied by Eddie, pays a visit to her
unsuspecting father in a Glasgow club to wreak vengeance on him,
she sets out to better herself by working at a flower stand.
</P>
<P>
   But in the world Stella inhabits, the dream of love still comes
at a price.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `STELLA DOES TRICKS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Coky Giedroyc; written by A.L. Kennedy; director of
photography, Barry Ackroyd; edited by Budge Tremlett; music by Nick
Bicat; production designer, Lynne Whiteread; produced by Adam
Barker; released by Strand Releasing. At the Screening Room, 54
Varick St., TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kelly Macdonald (Stella), James Bolam (Mr. Peters), Hans
Matheson (Eddie), Ewan Stewart (McGuire) and Andy Serkis (Fitz).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 97 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
