<HEADER>
A8340 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-BUSH-GORE-CALIF-HNS &LR;      01-27 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE, BUSH TOP PICKS IN CALIFORNIA POLL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Refiling to fix byline.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY AND ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ With the New Hampshire primary only days
away and
</P>
<P>
   California about to become every candidate's prom date, a new
poll shows Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush
remain the favorites among California voters.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco Examiner/KTVU poll of 806 registered voters
found Gore capturing 29 percent of those surveyed, including 54
percent of the Democratic vote in the statewide poll while Bush
captured 26 percent of those surveyed, including about 49 percent
of GOP voters.
</P>
<P>
   Well behind them are former Democratic Sen. Bill Bradley and
Republican Sen. John McCain. Both candidates received 12 percent of
the voters surveyed, about the same level of support in previous
polls. The poll's margin of error is plus or minus 3.5 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   In order to have a shot at winning California Bradley and McCain
will have to focus on the state's independent voters who will be
able to vote for the first time in the state's new ``open'' primary
on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   But, only votes from registered Republicans will count in
selecting GOP delegates and only votes from registered Democrats
count in selecting Democratic delegates for the national
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you break it down, there is not much of a race right
now,'' said Del Ali of Research 2000 in Rockville, Md., which
conducted the Examiner/KTVU poll between last Friday and Monday.
``Those numbers could change, however, depending on what happens in
New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Bradley and McCain need big wins Tuesday in New
Hampshire to gain momentum for California on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley _ who has a much more significant campaign operation in
California than McCain _ was damaged in Monday's Iowa caucus votes.
He spent an estimated $2 million in Iowa, but lost to Gore 63
percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley faces other difficulties in California as well. He's
been running on the anti-establishment platform, continually
telling voters that if they prefer the status quo, then they
shouldn't vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Californians have resoundingly said they
like the status quo. With the economy roaring, voters in the 1998
gubernatorial race picked a middle-of-the-road candidate who looked
a lot like former GOP Gov. Pete Wilson: Gray Davis, a centrist
Democrat and Gore supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Also, California voters like Clinton much better than do voters
in other states. The poll found continued high approval rates for
the president. When asked to rate Clinton, 58 percent said he was
doing a good or excellent job. Thirty-two percent said he was doing
a fair job and 10 percent rated his job performance as poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley's support (in Iowa came) significantly from Democrats
who do not like Bill Clinton personally and do not approve of
him,`` said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a senior associate at the School
of Politics and Economics at Claremont Graduate University.
``California has been very supportive of the president over time.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Bebitch Jeffe said, McCain faces even larger obstacles
capturing the Golden State, in part because he doesn't have the
money or the campaign operation that Bradley does in California.
</P>
<P>
   McCain currently leads Bush in most polls in New Hampshire,
though the Bush camp is counting on momentum from their first-place
finish in the Iowa caucuses. McCain needs a victory in New
Hampshire to mount a challenge in California to Bush, who is much
better funded, said Jack Pitney, an associate professor of
government at Claremont-McKenna College.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's early edge in polls, analysts still see a chance
for Bradley here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be premature to declare a Bradley defeat in
California,''
</P>
<P>
   said Tim Hodson, professor and director of the Center for
California
</P>
<P>
   Studies at Cal State Sacramento. ``If he does better than
expected in New
</P>
<P>
   Hampshire, he could hit California as the comeback kid, as the
center of
</P>
<P>
   media attention. He could attempt to parlay his image as the
outsider, the
</P>
<P>
   one impatient with conventional politics into a major message.''
</P>
<P>
   But that same attitude could help McCain especially if he picks
up a win New Hampshire and does well in South Carolina and his home
state of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Californians again could look at McCain as being different,
unconventional, not afraid to break with the past,'' Hodson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
