<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     01-27 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELBY LYNNE: ``I Am Shelby Lynne'' (Mercury). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shelby Lynne's sixth album is the latest installment of Life
After Nashville, an ever-growing story with contributions by Willie
Nelson and Steve Earle, among others.
</P>
<P>
   A special, urgent quality _ mordant but free _ emanates from
albums made shortly after artists have cut themselves away from the
songwriting, producing and marketing practices of the country music
capital, and this is a good example.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lynne, whose first five albums failed to sell her to a
mainstream country audience, is from Alabama and sounds like it;
for country credibility, there's a song recalling a water parade
near her hometown. But for her wider frame of reference _ the
reason she left Nashville _ there's the rest of this
not-really-country record, indebted to sources as disparate as
Dusty Springfield, Phil Spector and Doug Sahm.
</P>
<P>
   There's a trombone solo oddly stuck in the middle of a shambling
country-rock tune; lush string orchestrations, Floyd Cramer piano
chords and steel guitars, the ghosts of her Nashville past, are
matched with self-consciously low-tech rhythm machines. (The record
is produced by Bill Bottrell, whose mixes and production _ just
different enough from the roots-rock norm to lodge in one's brain _
enlivened Sheryl Crow's album ``Tuesday Night Music Club.'')
</P>
<P>
   Her stout but resigned voice lingers over lyrics that are almost
gothically depressing, often about ended relationships or the
constitutional impossibility of having one at all. (She's got a
voice that used to be described as tragic.)
</P>
<P>
   But musically, the record changes instrumentation and character
so many times that its sadness doesn't become overwhelming; it's
cranky, but shrewd and original.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
