<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRENZY-FILM-REVIEW-NY     01-27 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENZY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOT LOVE, JUST FRENZY': A DARK FARCE FROM SPAIN: ALMODOVAR? NOT
THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ``Not Love, Just Frenzy'' were a Renaissance painting, it
might be attributed to the school of Almodovar. It hardly takes a
connoisseur to recognize the hallmarks of the master's style: drag
queens, crowded Madrid discos, an atmosphere of exuberant
polymorphous perversity and a plot that scrambles together elements
of farce, melodrama and film noir.
</P>
<P>
   But whereas Pedro Almodovar at his best composes gaudy, vibrant
tableaux that hold silliness, cruelty and earnest emotion in
perfect balance, his epigones Alfonso Albacete, Miguel Bardem and
David Menkes, who share writing and directing credits for ``Not
Love, Just Frenzy,'' have made a movie that, perhaps unwittingly,
lives up to its title.
</P>
<P>
   All the elements are in place, the colors have been studiously
applied, but the result is too neat and too sloppy, as though
painted by numbers with an unpracticed hand.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which came out in Spain in 1996, has no doubt been
released in this country to capitalize on the success of
Almodovar's recent masterpiece, ``All About My Mother.'' Lacking
that movie's mature dignity and stylistic assurance, ``Not Love,
Just Frenzy'' instead recalls lesser, messier incarnations of
Almodovarismo.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie to see if your videocassettes of ``Dark Habits''
and ``Tie Me Up! Tie Me Down!'' are finally starting to wear out,
and you're desperate for a fresh infusion of post-post-Franco
Iberian fabulousness.
</P>
<P>
   And who isn't? Who but the sourest of scolds could be immune to
the charms of a gamine heroine named Yeye (Ingrid Rubio), her best
pal, Alberto (Gustavo Salmeron); and the assorted friends, rivals
and lovers (would-be and ex) who populate this happy muddle of a
movie? And who, for that matter, could resist a film that features
Bibi Andersson _ the erstwhile Bergman ingenue who has become the
leading Swedish actress in modern Spanish cinema _ as a high-class
lesbian pimp?
</P>
<P>
   And what about those drag queens, decked out as Daliesque
visions of Jackie O, Cindy Crawford and Dolly Parton? Or a finale
that features a costume party gone haywire, a naked artist's model
greeting sunrise on a rooftop and a showdown in a nightclub men's
room?
</P>
<P>
   The nightclub, by the way, is called Frenesi, the frenzy of the
title, which also, we're informed by a pop song on the soundtrack,
refers to sex. There is plenty of frenzied sex on screen: between
Alberto and Alex (Javier Albala), a handsome man with a secret,
then between Monica (Cayetana Guillen Cuervo), Yeye's slutty,
hard-boiled roommate, and Max (Nancho Novo), the brooding gigolo
who once broke Yeye's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Max, sad to say, is not only a cad, a philanderer and, possibly,
a murderer; he's also a drag, and not the glamorous, subversive,
gender-bending sense. His dour machismo dampens the film's general
insouciance, and the story lines that go with him _ about an
apparent sex killing, a vengeful cop and his star-crossed
relationship with Yeye _ are off-putting and implausible.
</P>
<P>
   The best parts of ``Not Love, Just Frenzy'' present the casual
outrageousness of the characters and their milieu with humor,
tenderness and tact. The romantic dreams of a student radical named
Clara; the easy, loving banter between Yeye and Alberto; the sight
of three female impersonators boarding a bus _ moments like these
are humane and comic in the best Almodovarian tradition. The rest
is just frenzy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `NOT LOVE, JUST FRENZY'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Alfonso Albacete, Miguel Bardem and
David Menkes (Peliculas Freneticas); in Spanish, with English
subtitles; director of photography, Nestor Calvo; edited by Miguel
Angel Santamaria; music by Juan Bardem; production designer, Alain
Bainee; produced by Fernando Colomo and Beatriz de la Gandara;
released by Jour de Fete Films. Running time: 103 minutes. This
film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Nancho Novo (Max), Cayetana Guillen Cuervo (Monica),
Ingrid Rubio (Yeye), Gustavo Salmeron (Alberto), Bibi Andersen
(Cristina) and Javier Albala (Alex).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1701EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8351 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-27 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRADLEY BLOWS IT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The message of the dissolving presidential
candidacy of former Sen. Bill Bradley is that if you hold yourself
out as more principled and high-minded than your opponent, you
better walk the walk and not just talk the talk.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, desperate to revive his flagging fortunes, suddenly
dropped his mask of statesmanship in the New Hampshire debate
Wednesday evening, abandoning the image he had hoped would
distinguish him from the pragmatic, aggressive Gore. No more Mr.
Nice Guy.
</P>
<P>
   But what appeared in Nice Guy's place was a mushy-thinking
whiner who came across as petulant and mean, accusing his
Democratic rival of lying and complaining that Gore was
``demeaning'' him. ``Why should we believe you that you will tell
the truth as president if you don't tell the truth as a
candidate?'' Bradley inquired sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a negative attack?'' Gore responded wryly. Later,
Gore warned, ``If you are going to talk about a higher standard,
you need to live by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's new attack mode was a stunning role reversal for a
fellow who has made a big deal of being too intellectually aloof to
run a negative campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The above-the-fray pose wasn't working, but neither will the new
pitch. Sometimes, the rule is if you can't beat them, you join
them. But there's a giant political chasm here between the two
approaches. Bradley does not come to mind as a tough-minded slugger
who will do anything legal to win.
</P>
<P>
   And voters want a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is more practiced at the tough guy tactics and better at
them. He repeatedly challenged Bradley's interpretation of the
issues on which they differ. But he cloaked his attacks in the
language of policy wonkery that is more politically acceptable than
the personal insults Bradley was hurling.
</P>
<P>
   And the voters who like Bradley do so precisely because they
prefer a candidate with a softer focus than the hard-charging Gore.
Bradley sold himself as a ``different'' kind of politician who
would restore dignity and gentility to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Now he doesn't look different at all. He sounds like Sen. Bob
Dole, growling after Vice President George Bush beat him in New
Hampshire's Republican primary in 1988: ``Tell him to stop lying
about my record.'' The voters didn't buy such sour grapes then and
are unlikely to do so now. The preferred posture for losers is to
behave like gracious good sports.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, both sides predictably shaded their
interpretations of what the other was up to. The differing impact
of their competing health and education plans can be argued fairly
with all sorts of legitimate variations. This is complicated stuff
to explain in a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That's politics. Harping on the other's ``distortions'' is
standard campaign fare. Believe whatever makes the most sense to
you.
</P>
<P>
   But this debate was supposed to be the forum to get Gore, except
it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   It started when CNN anchor Judy Woodruff challenged the vice
president to explain if he was operating on ``misinformation'' or
just ``being political.'' She cited his complaint that Bradley's
support of private school vouchers would siphon off money from
public education. ``Which is not the case,'' she opined.
</P>
<P>
   Gore fired back. And he's right. Bradley's proposal says nothing
about overtly subtracting money from public schools, but in fact
that is what would happen. Many teachers and educators are opposed
to such vouchers because the pool of tax money for education is
limited; tax dollars that go to subsidize pupils in private schools
are not available for public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it was good theater. Gore pushed Bradley to explain
his Senate vote for Ronald Reagan's budget cuts in 1981, opposed by
most Democrats and so severe that much of the excised funding was
soon restored. ``I just don't see how you can vote for Reagan's
budget cuts and then try to campaign like Robert Kennedy,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley countered that he had actually worked to diminish the
effect of the budget cuts, adding that Gore's complaint reminded
him of Richard Nixon _ ``the kind of politician who'd chop down a
tree, then stand on the stump and give a speech about
conservation.''
</P>
<P>
   But amid the hyperbole and hypocrisy, Gore came out looking the
most forceful, decisive and confident. (If only he would junk that
jarring blue-striped tie. Bring back the comfy earth tones.)
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ended the debate badly, claiming that regarding his
personal medical records he has ``done the same thing Al Gore has
done, which is to lay out the latest doctor's report.'' Gore
properly interjected that ``I don't want to be put in the same boat
here. I've released all of mine fully.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Bradley's medical records is relevant in the light
of his recent problems with irregular heartbeat. If he has nothing
to hide, why did he incorrectly pretend he has disclosed as much
about his health as Gore has?
</P>
<P>
   It would not be wise for Gore to make an issue of this, and he
won't. But Bradley has just done it himself. Can Bradley stand up
to the pressures of the presidency? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SICK-WILLIE-COX     01-27 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SICK-WILLIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zoo's fight to save ailing Willie B.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Question: How does a famous, beloved, elderly,
seriously ill 400-pound gorilla get his sweet potatoes?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Any way he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   And when the hulking primate happens to be Willie B. _ weak from
chronic heart disease, receiving intensive care _ he wants those
yams cooked with the skins on one day. Then he wants them raw and
skinless the next day. That day, he doesn't care how many pounds of
cooked, unskinned sweet potatoes you've just stockpiled in the Zoo
Atlanta kitchen. No, if you hand him one of these offending cooked
tubers, the 41-year-old alpha male turns over his massive mitt with
the delicacy of an opera diva, dumping the yam on the floor. Or he
pushes it through the wire mesh into the neighboring gorilla pen.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes his handlers exasperated _ and hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good sign, actually,'' says senior veterinarian Dr.
Rita McManamon, who has ministered to His Hugeness since 1984. The
mere fact that Willie wants to play food games shows he may be
feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he's not eating enough, we have people there constantly
trying to entice him with a smorgasbord of foods. He's a smart
fella, he knows the game. He's working this angle for all it's
worth.''
</P>
<P>
   The zoo staff looks for any tiny, promising sign, because the
underlying reality is that Willie B. is a very, very sick gorilla.
He suffers from cardiomyopathy, a weakness of the heart muscle that
can't be cured, only managed. The zoo won't allow reporters or
other outsiders to see the star _ infection from human germs is a
danger _ but staffers decribe an ape much changed from the lordly
one who has held court at the zoo for 39 years. Sometimes he leans
his head wearily against the wall. Keeper Charles Horton can see a
``crestfallen'' expression in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   While the staff administers daily oral heart medication, usually
mixed with tempting yogurt and M&AMP;Ms, Willie's kept in his own
indoor cell, because in recent weeks he was eating and drinking
much too little when he had to compete with younger, jostling apes.
All 23 gorillas are kept indoors and off exhibit when the
temperature goes below 40 degrees, and the members of Willie's
troop _ his five children and five grown females _ often cram into
a small ``visiting room'' where they can make visual and vocal
contact with poppa.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know something is wrong and they're agitated, breaking
into more fights because Willie's not there to settle them,'' says
Horton, Willie's main keeper for 25 years. ``They're reassured when
they can see and hear him _ and he is, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A crack medical team
</P>
<P>
   Horton first knew something was wrong in late December when
Willie allowed a female in his troop to break gorilla etiquette and
sit close, right in front of him, to eat. It was, Horton says, ``a
clear sign that he wasn't feeling so macho.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie was one of several gorillas suffering from the flu _ the
same virus that commonly affects humans. In his case it led to
pneumonia, which in turn strained his already faltering heart. The
titanic one was anaesthetized and wheeled on a gurney into the
zoo's gorilla clinic for X-rays, ultrasonograms and other tests by
outside specialists, including a cardiologist and pulmonologist.
(Based at such institutions as Emory University and volunteering
their free time for Willie, these specialists have asked to remain
anonymous, citing time constraints, zoo officials say.)
</P>
<P>
   When advanced cardiomyopathy was diagnosed, the medical team
prescribed daily heart medications, which are adjusted daily to
offset the worrisome fluid that keeps collecting in Willie's mighty
chest. The specialists consult daily on the phone with McManamon
and her assistant vet, Maria Crane. Because he is still a dangerous
animal _ in 1980 he slipped out of his cage and ``played'' with a
keeper, breaking his leg _ Willie must be put under for even the
simplest exam or test. But anesthesia itself can strain his heart.
</P>
<P>
   To further complicate matters, Willie's illness is an expensive
burden for Zoo Atlanta, a non-profit institution, costing an extra
$2,500 a week in medication, special foods and overtime, plus
intermittent lab tests at $4,000 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo would go to these lengths to save any animal,
spokeswoman Gail Eaton says, ``But let's face it _ there's only so
much you can do to save a rattlesnake. Since a gorilla is so much
like a human, we know more ways to help Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   Since news got out about Willie's illness, some people have sent
get-well cards, often with candy that the ape likes. This support,
however, doesn't pay the bills. ``We don't need people sending us
any more candy for Willie,'' Eaton says, ``but we could sure use
money.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend's night vigil
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the extras that can't be captured on a ledger
sheet, like the devotion of Horton, who has spent half of his 50
years with Willie: tickling the gorilla's toes when he was younger,
playing tug-of-war with a rope. Watching with amazement as the
middle-aged silverback played tenderly with his first infant
daughter, Kudzoo.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, in a clean-looking zoo work room powerfully
redolent of gorilla waste, Horton's sleeping bag was stretched out
on a counter. The lifetime Atlantan has shared a few of Willie's
worst nights here _ as close to his old friend as he can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he's meant more to me than I have to him,'' Horton
says. ``Right now we still can't accept that we might not have him
with us. The emotion is something you try to hold in.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Horton's duties is manning the ``smorgasbord'' table,
tempting Willie with such items as bananas, celery, candies and
white bread (an experiment with healthier whole wheat was a
fiasco). The gorilla will gaze at an item, and when Horton puts his
hand on it, Willie will confirm the choice with a grunt.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, for the first time in weeks, he ``barked'' when
the other gorillas were getting bamboo. Translation: ``What about
me?'' It was another tiny hopeful sign.
</P>
<P>
   Says Horton, ``I like it when he's finicky.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1704EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
