<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BACH-ANNIVERSARY-4TAK     01-27 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACH-ANNIVERSARY-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVIGATING THE KEYBOARDS WITH BACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Optional sidebar at end of article) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last Bach year wasn't so long ago: 1985, to be
exact, the 300th anniversary of the composer's birth. And although
Bach had to share the celebration with other masters born in the
fateful, fertile year 1685, Handel and Scarlatti, he did not lack
for attention.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the calculus of births and deaths, centenaries and
quarter-millenniums, and points in between, comes another Bach
year: the 250th anniversary of his death. Not complaining, mind
you. In addition to the commercial aspects _ books, records and
scores; concerts, recitals and festivals _ and the odd bit of
flimflammery, such commemorations typically give a jolt to
scholarship on the subject as well as a boost in public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   And in this case, the proximity of the years allows for a happy
connection. Among the events best recalled from 1985 were recitals
by the pianist Andras Schiff, devoted to the Partitas and the
``Goldberg'' Variations, at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Now, in
the first major Bach event of the year in New York, Schiff begins a
monumental survey of Bach's keyboard works, with the English Suites
on Wednesday and the French Suites on Feb. 5, at Alice Tully Hall,
and the Partitas on Feb. 13, at Avery Fisher Hall. The series picks
up in the fall at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff must compete with much accumulated wisdom on the subject,
including some of his own, retained in memory and on records. So
the classical-music critics of The New York Times provide a partial
backdrop by choosing favorites among the CDs of the keyboard works
available.
</P>
<P>
   But oh, yes; along with these choices, expect any number of
additional releases in this Bach year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES R. OESTREICH
</P>
<P>
   Here are some favorite Bach recordings of the classical-music
critics of The New York Times. Many are available in two-CD sets
or, in one case, a six-CD set. Prices range from $5.98 to $12.98
for a single CD, to $32.99 for a two- or three-CD set, to $38.94
for the set of six. )
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Holland
</P>
<P>
   ``The Well-Tempered Clavier,'' Books 1 and 2 (BWV 846-93).
</P>
<P>
   Bach's early admirers knew him as the father of harmony. This is
a specific rather than a general eulogy and refers to ``The
Well-Tempered Clavier,'' 48 preludes and fugues in every major and
minor key. ``Well-Tempered'' is a system of tuning. Bach did not
invent it, but he promoted it heavily in these pieces as a
reasonable solution to theoretical turmoils that had preceded him
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   To oversimplify, purely tuned scales render a C sharp and a D
flat that are slightly different; by jimmying intervals out of
their pure state, the two pitches can be made to occupy the same
black key on a piano. Without this compromise, most of Wagner's
harmonic wanderings and Schubert's abrupt modulations would sound
dreadful. (Organists using old systems complained that fifths in
distant keys howled like wolves.) The well-tempered method is not
quite the equal temperament generally accepted now, but it is a
direct predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The tuning wars, despite continuing skirmishes, are behind us,
and Bach's preludes and fugues are honored as the ``daily bread''
(Schumann's term) of every keyboard player. Beethoven memorized
them as a child, and every student who has laid hands to keyboard
knows their ability to teach the ear to hear the inner voice and
the hand to respond accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   There are two books: the first from 1722, the second from nearly
20 years later. Book 1 tends toward open drama and pleasing
sentiment. Book 2 has, with exceptions, a more dour air. Maybe this
is why we know it less well, or maybe we become too bogged down in
the riches of Book 1 to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Period instruments have less moral force here. ``Clavier'' is
18th-century German for just about any instrument played on keys.
But if the harpsichord pleases you, turn to Gustav Leonhardt, who
plays Book 1 on splendid modern copies of Bach-era instruments and
addresses the music with a caring sobriety (Deutsche Harmonia Mundi
77011-2-RG, two CDs). Excitement is at a minimum in Leonhardt's
playing, but then our preoccupation with excitement is not one of
music's admirable traits.
</P>
<P>
   Andras Schiff plays both books using a modern piano (London 414
388-2 and 417 236-2, two CDs each). The modesty is admirable, the
mood almost placid; the pianist muses quietly by himself. Also on
the piano is Keith Jarrett's recording, brisk and correct (ECM
21362 and 21433, two CDs each). Edwin Fischer's expansive piano
playing in Book 1 (Pearl GEMS 0016, two CDs) adopts Bach into the
Romantic era. Mieczyslaw Horszowski's twilight Book 1 (Vanguard OVC
8046/7) has the quiet innerness of an 87-year-old and some of the
technical strains as well. For a wonderfully operatic treatment
based on sound musicianship return to Wanda Landowska playing her
souped-up Pleyel harpsichord (RCA Victor 6217-2-RC, two CDs, and
7825-2-RC, three CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Treat Glenn Gould (Sony Classical SM2K 52600 and SM2K 52603, two
CDs each) as a series of clever pranks occasionally interrupted by
playing of astonishing beauty and originality. Gould plays against
the grain of these pieces: with staccato where legato is
compellingly implied; at tempos that are either ridiculously slow
or ridiculously fast. The fugue textures are amazingly clear, and
it is all great fun, but I hear there are serious students who take
his ``Well-Tempered'' as gospel. That is a horrifying thought.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Griffiths
</P>
<P>
   Keyboard Partitas (BWV 825-30).
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Gould, of course. It is not surprising that Gould's
recordings (Sony Classical SM2K 52597, two CDs, with preludes and
fugues) are as extraordinary now as when they were made some 40
years ago. The surprise is that current recordings of the complete
set offer no satisfying alternative. The closest approach comes
from Sergey Schepkin (Ongaku 108/9, two CDs, with other pieces),
but highly accomplished as Schepkin is, he sometimes undervalues
the rhythmic life of the principal voice and sometimes
overornaments.
</P>
<P>
   With Gould such criticisms are impossible because he always
means exactly what he plays. The results will usually be unexpected
because responses so complete and detailed are bound to be
unforeseeable and they may be extreme. In the fugal Allegro from
the opening movement of the C minor Partita, for instance, Gould's
staccato seems satirical, exposing an element of pomposity. But
there is no gap between the performer and the composer. If one
finds the section funny, one is smiling either at Gould and Bach or
with them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most other performers fail at the first challenge of Bach's
music, which is to keep each movement in the air, despite
intermittent endings at the closes of phrases and sections, until
the final cadence. This is not a problem, though, in two classic
recordings, available in mixed programs: Dinu Lipatti's recording
of the B flat Partita (EMI Classics, 7243 5 67003 2; or Great
Pianists of the 20th Century (Philips, 456 892-2, two CDs) and
Martha Argerich's discs of the C minor (Great Pianists of the 20th
Century, Philips, 456 700-2, two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   The Lipatti is miraculously fluent, all grace. It is not full of
ideas in the way that Gould's performances are. Ms. Argerich, by
contrast, establishes continuity more by unassuageable tension.
Some movements seem to get more impassioned as they go on, without
any sacrifice to tonal brilliance or rhythmic definition. The
Allemande is just a wonder.
</P>
<P>
   In the same partita, Grigory Sokolov (Opus 111, OPS 529116/7,
two CDs) offers a grander view, but a strongly compelling one, with
plenty of contrapuntal life: the coupling is ``The Art of Fugue.''
Sokolov, no less than Gould, can be utterly persuasive in doing
something odd, as in his performance of the Sarabande in detached
notes, an idea he makes beautiful and moving.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Fiorentino (Appian, APR 5558) would never have wanted to
interrupt his golden singing line in that way, but he had his own
marvelous strange notions. After a beautiful performance of the B
flat Partita, he extends the beauties of the slow movements of the
D major to the extent that the Allemande lasts more than a quarter
of an hour. But what a quarter-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Kozinn
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldberg'' Variations (BWV 988).
</P>
<P>
   Something about the ``Goldberg'' Variations brings out
musicians' inventiveness and eccentricity. And it is not only
pianists and harpsichordists who are drawn to this journey through
30 magnificently diverse variations on a graceful aria; although
the present survey covers recordings on those instruments only,
transcriptions for guitar, organ, string trio, orchestra and brass
quintet are available.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, quite a few favorite harpsichord versions have gone
out of print. But Kenneth Gilbert's supremely rational 1986
recording (Harmonia Mundi France HMX 2951240), recently reissued as
part of Harmonia Mundi's Bach Edition, has several appealing
qualities, among them an interesting approach to the perennial
question of how to handle the repeats.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert takes some but not all of them, his decision based on
the form each variation takes. Canons are repeated, so listeners
can focus on different voices with each pass, although he tends not
to emphasize the voices very differently the second time.
Variations for which Bach supplied alternative endings are repeated
as well, so none of Bach's notes are left out.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert does not go wild in matters of registration. For a
lesson in how tastes and techniques have changed, compare his
account with the aggressively colorized versions by Wanda Landowska
(from 1933 on EMI) and Karl Richter (from 1958 on Teldec), both
still available.
</P>
<P>
   Pianists have long found the ``Goldberg'' Variations a canvas on
which to paint richly hued self-portraits in more or less Bachian
garb. Surely the champion here is Glenn Gould, whose 1955 recording
on piano (Sony Classical SMK 52594) is classic Gould and, in its
way, classic modern Bach. Gould liked extremes and provocations,
and they abound in this brisk reading. A typical few moments are in
the contrasting Variations Nos. 26 and 27. The first is played in a
whisper and fades away; its successor is brash and torrential.
There are also, of course, the humming and singing. If you're new
to Gould, learn to ignore them; it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the early-music movement made pianists shy about
Bach, but since the mid-1980s they have returned to the
``Goldberg'' Variations with a vengeance. Andrew Rangell recorded
the work in 1991 (Dorian DOR-90138) and Sergey Schepkin in 1995
(Ongaku 107) in versions that should not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Schepkin's performance has an electrifying energy, but it is
most striking for the florid ornamentation the pianist applies at
every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a picture of textural clarity, a quality it shares
with Rangell's account. Here the strands of counterpoint sing with
extraordinary transparency; you will hear relationships never
apparent before.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest of her periodic examinations of the ``Goldberg''
Variations, also on piano, Rosalyn Tureck takes all the repeats and
plays at remarkably leisurely tempos. Her recording (Deutsche
Grammophon 459 599-2, two CDs) takes the prize for figurative bells
and whistles. If you play it on your CD-ROM drive, you can follow
the score (in black-and-white or with individual voices color
coded) or read a variation-by-variation analysis and an illustrated
biography of Bach.
</P>
<P>
   James R. Oestreich
</P>
<P>
   English Suites (BWV 806-11), French Suites (BWV 812-17).
</P>
<P>
   The English Suites, hardly less French in idiomatic gesture than
the French Suites, pose the greater challenge for performers, in
their length and density. Whether despite that reason or because of
it, they are represented in slightly greater diversity among
current recordings.
</P>
<P>
   One particularly happy venture in the English Suites is Murray
Perahia's recording for Sony Classical (SK 60276/7, two CDs). To
this pianist's virtues in more standard repertory _ a wonderful
suppleness, freedom and fluidity _ are added the curiosity of a
relative outsider and a fresh sense of adventure in ornamentation
and such matters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other recommendations for the English set extend with more or
less equal force to the French Suites as well. The pianist Andras
Schiff, who performs both sets at Alice Tully Hall next week, has
recorded both for Decca/London (English Suites, 421 640-2; French
Suites, 433 313-2; two CDs each). Schiff quite simply lives and
breathes Bach, and the nimblest fingers this side of Glenn Gould's
allow him to avoid the sustaining pedal, a practice that in his
case paradoxically yields more variety rather than less.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff is also deft at finding humor in Bach's writing (as
opposed to creating it, as Gould so often seems to do). This
attribute, perhaps rarer among harpsichordists than pianists, is
nevertheless notably shared by the splendid New York harpsichordist
Bradley Brookshire, who in 1997 gave the finest performance of the
French Suites in recent memory, which so far has no counterpart on
records: a worthy project for some label in the Bach year.
</P>
<P>
   The maniacally virtuosic Gould, meanwhile, makes essential
listening on Sony Classical (English Suites, SM2K 52606/7; French
Suites, SM2K 52609/10; two CDs each) despite his infuriating
vagaries and mannerisms. Even at his most outrageous, he turns up
unexpected features in the music and shows the way to piquant
interpretive possibilities that one might enjoy if applied with
greater restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on piano, listeners on a tight budget might well, as
so often, turn to Naxos, for performances of both sets by Wolfgang
Rubsam that occasionally transcend the acceptable (English Suites,
8.553012/3; French Suites, 8.550709/10; two CDs each).
</P>
<P>
   It is remarkable how decisively excellent and characterful
performances of Bach on the piano in recent decades have settled
the once contentious issue as to whether that instrument should
continue to be used in Bach at all. Who would surrender Gould,
Schiff or Perahia?
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of us Bachians nourish a special fondness for the
prickly, colorful sonorities of the harpsichord, and the good word
here (for those who continue to find Gustav Leonhardt's readings a
bit sobersided) is in the two big Bach editions just appearing.
Kenneth Gilbert's fine recordings of both sets of suites (as well
as the Partitas) are available in a six-CD package in Harmonia
Mundi France's Bach Edition (HMX 2908078/83). Alan Curtis' somewhat
livelier versions of the suites are more inaccessibly buried at the
moment in the 153 CDs of Teldec's Bach 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Tommasini
</P>
<P>
   Miscellaneous keyboard works.
</P>
<P>
   Almost anyone who ever took piano lessons as a child has played
at least a couple of Bach's 15 Two-Part Inventions. Bach composed
these short works as study pieces for his children, and they have
been used by youngsters ever since. With just two lines of music to
execute, one by each hand, the inventions allow elementary pianists
to develop finger independence and learn to hear two voices at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Though staples of children's recitals, the pieces are seldom
performed by professionals. Happily, Peter Serkin recorded them in
1997 (RCA Victor 09026-68594-2). With his exquisite pianism and
sense of adventure, he reveals just how musically inventive these
inventions are. They are paired on this disc with fine accounts of
the 15 Sinfonias, or Three-Part Inventions, often used as teaching
works for more advanced students: here two hands must play three
independent lines. This rewarding program also includes four
seldom-heard duets from the ``Clavierubung.''
</P>
<P>
   If you doubt that Bach's keyboard music can be terrifying,
listen to the historic 1935 recording of his stormy Chromatic
Fantasy and Fugue by the harpsichordist Wanda Landowska (EMI
Classics CDH 7 61008 2, two CDs). Landowska took a bold,
rhythmically free approach to Bach, but this work especially
invited it. She plays the grimly rhapsodic fantasy as if it were
some harmonically experimental late piano work by Liszt. Her
intrepid march through the fugue, with the final statement of the
theme in thick bass octaves, is positively Horowitzian. The
two-disc set includes her famous accounts of the ``Italian
Concerto'' and the ``Goldberg'' Variations.
</P>
<P>
   The pianist Andras Schiff offers quite a different approach to
the work on a recording from 1994 (Hungaroton HCD 11690). He also
captures the music's ominous quality and shifting moods, but his
performance is bracingly lucid and fleet. Whereas Landowska plays
the final moments of the fantasy as a weighty, inexorable descent
to the depths of chromatic abyss, Schiff plays them with affecting
poignancy, as if all the energy had been beaten out of the music
and the only consolation were the affirming fugue that follows.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other works on Schiff's disc is a lively account of
the popular Toccata in D. For a more provocative take on that work,
along with the other six Bach toccatas, try Glenn Gould's set,
recorded between 1963 and 1979 (Sony's Classical SM2K 52612, two
CD's), in Glenn Gould Edition.
</P>
<P>
   Some listeners find Gould's Bach eccentric; others think it
supreme. Either way it is impossible to resist. Gould's alert ear,
startling imagination, rhythmic sparkle and ability to project
contrapuntal intricacies with uncanny clarity combine impressively
in these riveting performances.
</P>
<P>
   Another recording in the Gould Edition offers the pianist in
vibrant interpretations of the Chromatic Fantasy and Fugue, the
``Italian Concerto'' and, most notably, several seldom-heard works,
including three fantasies, two fugues on themes by Albinoni, and
the ``Aria Variata Alla Maniera Italiana,'' a theme with 10
variations (Sony Classical SMK 52620). No, the ``Goldberg''
Variations are not Bach's only keyboard work in this genre,
something I have never forgotten since I flubbed a question about
it on my doctoral oral exam.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BACH BY THE BOX FOR THOSE WITH THE SHELF SPACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JAMES R. OESTREICH &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The first thundering volleys in the record wars of the Bach year
have been fired by Teldec, which has released Bach _ all of Bach _
on 153 CDs, and Harmonia Mundi France, which is releasing some half
of Bach, evidently, on 81 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   A full review of this largess will take time, obviously: perhaps
the rest of a lifetime. But several things can be noted at the
outset. In contrast to the Harmonia Mundi project, appearing in
small packages ranging from single CDs to a 12-CD set, the Teldec
load was dumped in a single box; make that suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding on the rage (among producers if not necessarily
consumers) for monster coffee-table packages, this box might itself
serve as a coffee table. And in a manner not calculated to appeal
to serious collectors, with CDs already spilling off their shelves,
it holds mostly air; repackaged sensibly in soft plastic sleeves,
the CDs and booklets shrink down to fit into less than two shoe
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   There are treasures galore, starting with the already historic
complete series of sacred cantatas led by Nikolaus Harnoncourt and
Gustav Leonhardt in the 1970s and '80s. (Those who purchased them
in an earlier coffee-table edition from Teldec can buy a ``lite''
version of Bach 2000, without those cantatas, for $850 rather than
the full $1,250.)
</P>
<P>
   As with those versions, most of the recordings are reissues.
There are also bonuses: in addition to comprehensive booklets, an
entire book, Wolfgang Sandberger's ``Bach 2000: 24 Inventions on
Johann Sebastian Bach,'' retailing up-to-date information and
theories on Bach, particularly where they tend to debunk cherished
myths, and a CD illustrating performance practice in Bach's ``St.
Matthew Passion'' through much of the century.
</P>
<P>
   That disc offers 10 minutes or so of excerpts (around and
including the soprano aria ``Aus Liebe will mein Heiland sterben'')
from recordings conducted by Willem Mengelberg in 1939, Wilhelm
Furtwangler in 1954, Karl Richter in 1958, Georg Solti in 1987, Ton
Koopman in 1992 and Christoph Spering (using Mendelssohn's
arrangement) in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the set's thoroughness and Bach's propensity to reuse
choice material, considerable light is also cast on recent and
current varieties of period practice. The 11-disc volume devoted to
secular cantatas, for example, includes two versions of what is
basically the same work musically: the Cantata No. 207
(``Vereinigte Zweitracht der Wechselnden Saiten,'' or ``Resolved
Discord of the Vibrating Strings''), conducted by the firebrand
Reinhard Goebel from Cologne, and the Cantata No. 207a (``Auf,
Schmetternde Toene der Muntern Trompeten,'' or ``Come, Blithesome
Trumpets' Blare''), led by the altogether mellower Koopman from
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Bachians of unlimited means can throw many more close
comparisons of period performances into the mix with the Harmonia
Mundi sets. Especially prominent among the performers here is the
fine Belgian conductor Philippe Herreweghe. Another Belgian, Rene
Jacobs, proves no less revelatory in a disc of secular cantatas.
</P>
<P>
   Again, most of the material is repackaged from earlier releases.
But instead of reissuing Herreweghe's first version of the ``St.
Matthew Passion,'' Harmonia Mundi has rerecorded the work with him,
and with the English tenor Ian Bostridge as the Evangelist, a role
in which he will undoubtedly have much to say in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Word of a set of historical Bach performances from EMI has
preceded its arrival in this office. And more Bach _ in amounts and
varieties hardly to be imagined, with the predictable already so
far surpassed _ is bound to come.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: insatiable Bachians will not be able to
afford another Bach year anytime soon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
