<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-TITANS-FISHER-HNS     01-27 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-FISHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TITANS HEAD COACH FOUND SOMETHING USEFUL FROM HIS NFL COACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - From every man he has worked for in his coaching
assignments over the past 14 years and in his five preceding years
as an NFL player, Jeff Fisher has taken something with him.
</P>
<P>
   From Mike Ditka: ferocity, passion and the ability to chew gum
and coach at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   From Buddy Ryan: a defensive scheme based on constant pressure
and attack.
</P>
<P>
   From John Robinson: how to look and act like a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   From George Seifert: the art of preparation and the expectation
of victory.
</P>
<P>
   From Jack Pardee: the head coaching job after Pardee was fired
10 games into the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the experience of going through a number of
organizations,'' Fisher said. ``You're going to take a little from
each organization. I can't say I'm a Buddy Ryan disciple. There's
something to be said for being yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line, the 41-year-old Fisher learned how to
remain calm and focused while the building was collapsing around
him. Make no mistake - the Houston Oilers could have been reduced
to rubble as they made their prolonged and painful transition into
the Tennessee Titans, a four-year process that began in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Fisher was the guy with the hard hat and pickax,
ready to dig out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pretty much held the ship together and kept it from
sinking,'' Tennessee linebacker Terry Killens said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason Floyd Reese is beaming these days, and it's not
all because the Titans made the Super Bowl in their 40th year of
existence. Reese, the club's vice president and general manager,
hired Fisher away from the San Francisco 49ers in 1994 as defensive
coordinator and promoted him to head coach later that season when
he fired Pardee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his youth and relative inexperience - or maybe because
of it - Fisher kept the team competitive during its last two
apathetic years in Houston and its first two years in Tennessee.
The Titans were 8-8 for three straight seasons before this year's
breakthrough 13-3 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get thrown into a situation like we were, you have to
be a certain type of personality to survive,'' Reese said. ``I've
coached with 25 guys who would have had strokes in the last three
years. He's level-headed. He's not going to get thrown out of whack
if the plane is two minutes late. He's able to adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   That describes, or at least used to, Fisher's opposite number in
Super Bowl XXXIV, Rams coach Dick Vermeil. While the term
``burnout'' can be traced to Vermeil's Philadelphia tenure, Fisher
is slow to rile. If you told him his pants were on fire he'd make a
note to fetch the extinguisher at his earliest convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's something of the grinder in Fisher, who went to
USC and played in the same defensive backfield as Ronnie Lott. He
didn't realize how much the job had consumed him until he spent
some time with his family during Tennessee's bye week this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my kids to read at least 15 minutes a night,'' Fisher
said. ``I took advantage of a rare night at home and I went up to
read with my youngest son (Trent, 7). I went downstairs and told my
wife, Juli, 'Trent can read.' She said, ``Yeah, he's been reading
for two years now. Where have you been?''' Moving from Houston to
Memphis to Nashville, that's where, trying to build a team for the
future without having it fall apart in the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough to win in the NFL with a level playing field,
and we weren't there,'' Fisher said. ``The types of things we went
through helped us get to where we are today. We are a strong team
mentally. If we didn't go through that, there's no telling where
we'd be.''
</P>
<P>
   Drafting on consecutive years Steve McNair, Eddie George, Kenny
Holmes, Kevin Dyson (who caught the lateral on the kickoff return
for a touchdown against Buffalo) and Jevon Kearse provided a solid
foundation for the Titans as they finally settled into their new
home at Adelphia Coliseum in the Music City.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had a tougher job in the league the last three years
than he did,'' tackle Brad Hopkins said. ``For Jeff to keep the
team together, to keep us focused to win eight games, is a great
thing to me. When he took over we were in a seven-game losing
streak. He's done a great job of maintaining his focus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
