<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8383 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CALDWELL-part1-NYTSF &LR;      01-27 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALDWELL-part1-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CALDWELL JOURNALS: HERE COMES THE BOLL WEEVIL 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: For Black History month, which begins on
Monday, Feb. 1, The New York times Syndicate is offering a
five-part feature, ``The Caldwell Journals,'' an account of major
moments in the civil-rights movement of the 1960s by Earl Caldwell,
the nationally acclaimed black journalist whose early career was
shaped by that dynamic era. Caldwell, a former New York Times
reporter, was witness to some of the most important events of the
last 40 years. He covered the riots that swept many American cities
during the summer of 1967. In 1995, the National Association of
Black Journalists presented Caldwell with its President's Award,
saying his record of professional achievement made him ``one of the
most important journalists in the last 50 years.'' Caldwell is
currently a writer-in-residence at the Robert C. Maynard Institute
for Journalism Education in Oakland, Calif., and is writing ``The
Caldwell Journals'' for the institute's Web site. For purchase
information _ on an individual part or the entire package _ contact
New York Times Syndicate Sales Representative DEBRA WEYDERT by
phone, 732-390-4480, or fax, 732-390-4697.)
</P>
<P>
   (PLEASE NOTE: All five parts have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle and ``a'' general news category codes.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EARL CALDWELL &QL; 
 &UR; (Worldwide rights) &QL; 
 &UR; c.2000 the Robert C. Maynard Institute for Journalism Education &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   PRELUDE TO PART ONE: In August 1963, tensions between blacks and
whites in many cities across the United States were on the rise.
Crowds converged on the nation's capital for the historic March on
Washington. Earl Caldwell, then a reporter for the Lancaster
Intelligencer-Journal, joined his parents in the living room of
their home in central Pennsylvania to watch Martin Luther King Jr.
deliver what many call his finest speech. Ten days later, a bomb
exploded during Sunday services at a black church in Birmingham,
Ala., killing four girls. Across urban America, black populations
became restless, and newspaper editors began searching for
reporters who could get inside the ``ghettos'' to gather stories
from those black communities. The Democrat and Chronicle in
Rochester, N.Y., began to recruit Caldwell aggressively. In the
fall of 1963, he accepted the job. Here, Caldwell recounts his
first assignment for the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   The story was boxed across the top of the front page of the
Sunday edition. It was even above the masthead. Of all the stories
I had ever written, nothing came close to this, my first story as a
reporter at the Democrat and Chronicle in Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the story herald my arrival, but there was also a
photograph of me, which was a way of letting readers know that for
the first time the newspaper had a reporter who was black.
</P>
<P>
   I'd arrived in town expecting the newspaper to make good on a
promise. Back when they were wooing me, I was told that if I
accepted the job, they would have an apartment waiting in a luxury
building not far from the newspaper. When I got to town and
mentioned all of this, I got a blank stare. Nobody knew what I was
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Dick Dougherty came up with his idea. He was the city
editor, and on my first day at the D&AMP;C, he told me that of all the
complaints that he was getting from blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the housing here is really segregated,'' he said. ``I
don't know if that's true or not. You have to find an apartment. We
don't need to phony up anything. We can use your experience to tell
a true story of what the situation really is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you do it?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty was a tall, thin guy whose hair was white even though
he didn't look to be a day past 35. His style was low key but very
persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   I had never reported and written a story about race, and what
Dougherty was suggesting caught me off-guard. But I was just
starting out on a new job; there was no way I was going to say no
to my city editor.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty wanted two reporters on the story _ one white and one
black. The plan was for each of us to try separately to rent the
same apartment. The white reporter was Bill Vogler. He was a
veteran on the staff at the D&AMP;C and he liked the idea. The two of
us got newspapers and circled apartments in my price range. Then we
got started.
</P>
<P>
   After we had visited about five or six apartments, Vogler asked
me, ``Are you sure you're actually going into these places?''
</P>
<P>
   He did not understand. I would just reach the door and promptly
be told, ``The apartment has already been rented.'' Right after I
was told that no apartment was available, Vogler would visit the
same place and be invited inside. He'd get a whole spiel on how
great the apartment was, why he'd like it and what the neighborhood
had to offer.
</P>
<P>
   My experience was so different that at times it would be
downright embarrassing. One building had a big sign on the lawn,
Apartment for Rent. I was heading up the sidewalk when a window on
the second floor opened. A woman leaned out and hollered: ``If
you're coming for the apartment, forget it. It's already rented.''
</P>
<P>
   Once I explained all this to Vogler, we kept going. We visited
apartment after apartment. It was always the same: no to me, yes to
him. I just kept making notes of everything that happened. At the
typewriter, I got my chance to tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the story was published, blacks began showing up
in the newsroom ``to meet Earl Caldwell.'' Some would barge right
past the receptionist.
</P>
<P>
   These were not ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Some people called these visitors troublemakers. They called
themselves activists, which meant they were in the forefront of
stoking, shaping and channeling the anger they said was growing in
Rochester's two black communities, the Third and Seventh wards.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper itself was a target of their anger. They said they
never saw reporters in their neighborhoods ``except when there's
trouble'' and accused the newspaper of not covering the important
issues in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   They looked to me to change that. They said that they expected
to see me in their communities, to tell the stories that were not
being told. The irony was that in a sense, my editor and the
activists were saying the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find out what the facts are,'' Dougherty had
challenged me. ``We expect you to tell the story,'' the activists
said, inviting me to the ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   I was being handed what every reporter wants: a big and
important story.
</P>
<P>
   The front-page story of my experience in hunting an apartment
had given me the kind of notoriety that a reporter new in town
could only dream of. The reaction was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Once the story was published, so many whites called to offer an
apartment that I had to write another piece just to tell that
story. One very nice woman, also white, did rent me a place not far
from the office.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I had settled in, black folks still hung a nickname
on me. They called me boll weevil. The name came from the title of
a popular song, and when they'd see me, they'd say, with a lot of
laughter, ``Here comes boll weevil. He's still looking for a
home.'''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: HARLEM, THE COLONY CONVERGES
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Earl Caldwell is a writer-in-residence at the Robert C.
Maynard Institute for Journalism Education in Oakland, Calif.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
