<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8394 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-BEHOLDER-SPI &LR;      01-27 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEHOLDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUNNING VISUALS THE ONLY BEAUTY IN DREADFUL `EYE OF THE
BEHOLDER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to believe this moronic thriller was written and
directed by the same guy who gave us that camp outback classic,
``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, Stephan Elliott also gave us the egregious ``Welcome
to Woop Woop,'' which pretty much went straight to the video
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eye of the Beholder'' wastes a nifty cast in an abysmal,
incoherent story. Ashley Judd, Ewan McGregor and even the French
Canadian legend Genevieve Bujold, who rarely makes movies and is
reportedly very selective about her choices, opted to take a chance
with this one.
</P>
<P>
   So you have to wonder just what happened. Did a third of the
movie end up on the editing room floor?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is it can't make up its mind what it wants
to be. Is it a stalker movie, a high-tech detective film or a
black-widow murder mystery? In a way, it's all three.
</P>
<P>
   So many inane things occur _ coupled with plot twists and
characters that spring out of the blue _ that we ultimately haven't
a clue as to who is who, or what their motivations are or their
relationships to each other.
</P>
<P>
   The press notes tell us the film is a ``surrealistic thriller
that takes a visceral journey deep into the eerie, seductive
recesses of the obsessive psyche.'' Well, they're terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eye of the Beholder'' never delves deeper than its noirish
surface and McGregor, who plays surveillance expert Eye, and Judd,
who is his beautiful and elusive target, Joanna, have to to keep
running from city to city just to get to the end of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   But their labors take them nowhere and, by the absurd finale, we
know little more about these misguided, sad souls than we did in
the first five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The film may catch the eye of audiences drawn by its fine cast,
but they'll be sorely disappointed once they discover this is a
perfect example of form without content.
</P>
<P>
   The form includes visuals that are stunningly gothic and
stylish, and costumes designed by the Oscar-winning Lizzy Gardner
(she collaborated with Elliott on ``Priscilla'' and wore the
revealing American Express card dress to the awards).
</P>
<P>
   As for content, Elliott leaves the audience in the lurch by
blatantly rejecting narrative cohesiveness and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Eye of the Beholder. Directed and written by Stephan Elliott.
Cast: Ewan McGregor, Ashley Judd, k.d. lang, Patrick Bergin,
Genevieve Bujold. Destination Films. 105 minutes. Rated R for
nudity, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
