<HEADER>
A8395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      01-27 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GAY BASHING TO GAY MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The notion of an hourlong drama that traces the experience of
homosexuals in America from the 1950s to the present is not
altogether promising. It invites a programmed account that goes
from harsh crackdowns to resistance, from closet practices to
comings out, from sexual shakiness to liberation. At its best
``Common Ground,'' Saturday night's ``Showtime'' production,
manages to mitigate the conventions by focusing on individuals
caught between their perplexities and society's injunctions.
</P>
<P>
   At its worst, the three-parter begins with Paula Vogel's play,
``A Friend of Dorothy's,'' about a young woman who returns to
Homer, Conn., after receiving a dishonorable discharge from the
Navy for sexual deviance. The lightweight but heavy-handed script
(``I will not have filth and perversions in my home,'' announces
Dorothy's mother) is not helped by an incessantly wide-eyed
performance by Brittany Murphy and Donna Deitch's blunt direction.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Dorothy comes down with a crush on a male sailor (Jason
Priestley), who reveals, ``I'm homosexual'' and introduces her to a
gay bar, which supplies more romance than rough trade. The hopeful
ending finds Dorothy, still searching, on a bus to Greenwich
Village, where sexual identities are known to abound. So much for
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Roberts,'' Terrence McNally's more polished contribution,
carries life in Homer to the 1970s and the puzzlement of Toby
Anderson (Jonathan Taylor Thomas), a high school senior, scholar,
swimmer and pianist, who keeps being taunted and beaten up by his
classmates when they discern that he isn't like them.
</P>
<P>
   The play draws its strength from Toby's relationship with the
title character, a French teacher (Steven Weber), who is having
trouble finding the courage to emerge from his own closet. When
Toby reaches out for some sort of advice or consolation, Roberts
ducks: ``I'm sorry I'm not what you think I am.'' Their effort,
finally, to help one another reach honest understanding is
touching, if a touch predictable. ``I let you down, and I let
myself down,'' Roberts confesses.
</P>
<P>
   The third play, ``Andy and Amos,'' by Harvey Fierstein is the
slightest effort but the most successful, owing to some smart
Fierstein dialogue and his turn as a gay florist hired this year to
provide the floral arrangements for the marriage ceremony of Amos
(James Le Gros) and Andy (Andrew Airlie). The occasion provides
Homer with a cause celebre in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   At the work's heart is an affectionate conversation between Amos
and his father (Ed Asner), who sports a World War II uniform that,
remarkably, still fits despite what the years must have added to
his waist. Dad's boosterism prompts him to show solidarity with
some protesting veterans and a contingent of offended Roman
Catholics. But his better nature and his love for his son prevail
as he helps the younger man overcome his own misgivings about the
ceremony. Dad's point is simply that homosexuals as well as
heterosexuals are entitled to ``the wedding jitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The hour ends with a sort of commercial from the narrator: ``We
owe our lives to the generation of gays and lesbians who struggled
before us.'' All right, but as Dad says, ``Enough lecturing
already.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COMMON GROUND'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. (ET) Saturday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Donna Deitch; written by Paula Vogel, Terrence
McNally and Harvey Fierstein; A.D. Oppenheim and Brian Kerwin,
executive producers; director of photography, Jacek Laskus;
production designer, Doug McCullough; edited by Robin Katz;
costumes by Antoinette Messam; music by Frederic Talgorn; sets by
Garth Brunt. A production of Winsome Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   With: Edward Asner (Ira), Beau Bridges (Father Leon), Harvey
Fierstein (Don), Margot Kidder (Mrs. Nelson), James Le Gros (Amos),
Brittany Murphy (Dorothy Nelson), Jason Priestley (Billy Temple),
Jonathan Taylor Thomas (Tobias), Steven Weber (Gil Roberts), Joanne
Vannicola (Max) and Andrew Airlie (Andy).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
