<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COMMON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COMMON GROUND' DELIVERS WORTHWHILE LESSONS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A high school senior, gifted in athletics, confronts the
realization that he might be ``playing for the other team.'' Beaten
and brutalized by his teammates for his sexual orientation, he asks
a gay teacher: ``Do people ever stop hating you?''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, ashamed of his own failure to offer the boy support
and sympathy, replies: ``I don't think some of them can.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the intended message of ``Common Ground,'' a
collection of three short films airing Saturday on Showtime premium
cable. But, more than any other lines in the three screenplays,
they lend sharp focus to why a project such as ``Common Ground'' is
worthwhile and why Showtime deserves a bouquet for green-lighting
it.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Paula Vogel (``How I Learned To Drive''), Terrence
McNally (``Kiss of the Spiderwoman'') and Harvey Fierstein (``Torch
Song Trilogy''), the films go together like mustard, onions and a
hot dog on the Fourth of July. And it's no accident that each takes
place in fictional Homer, Conn., the first in 1954, the next in
1974, the last in 2000. Homer is the sort of safe haven where
All-American values are always in stock at the corner store. Eric
Stoltz, as narrator Johnny Burroughs, provides the continuous
thread, observing events in Homer through the eyes of a child, then
a young father, and finally a middle-age man.
</P>
<P>
   What Johnny sees as keeper of the town commons, raiser of the
town flag, isn't always pretty, and at one point he is moved to
lament, ``Small town, smaller minds.'' But Homer's odyssey through
the second half of the 20th century isn't completely discouraging.
Attitudes do change. They just change more slowly than the
stoplight at the corner of Intolerance and Bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   The first film, Vogel's ``A Friend of Dorothy,'' centers on a
young woman dishonorably discharged from the Navy for suspected
homosexual activity. Brittany Murphy gracefully plays Dorothy
Nelson, someone so naive that she knows nothing of lesbianism until
warned against it by her commanding officer (Mimi Rogers), and
nothing of the closed-mindedness that awaits her back home in
Homer. Even her mother (Margot Kidder) declares, ``I will not have
filth and perversion in my home'' as she switches on TV coverage of
the McCarthy hearings, and Dorothy realizes she must find solace
and support elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Roberts,'' the second and most powerful of the films,
introduces Toby Anderson and his French teacher, Gil Roberts, who
pronounces his surname ``ro-BAIR'' because, well, he's the French
teacher and also because an alternate identity makes life seem less
threatening to a closeted gay man. In little more than half an
hour, Steven Weber, as the teacher, and Jonathan Taylor Thomas, as
the student, create a tension so dramatic, so elastic, that one
ponders the what-ifs had McNally written ``Mr. Roberts'' as a
full-length film.
</P>
<P>
   The preachiest of the films is Fierstein's ``Andy &AMP; Amos,'' a
flamboyant salute to present-day acceptance of gay couples, even by
stubborn and confused parents like Amos' dad, Ira (Edward Asner).
Ira doesn't like the idea of Amos (James Le Gros) marrying his
longtime partner, Andy (Andrew Airlie), and he even helps organize
a protest of the ceremony by the town's macho military veterans.
But when Amos experiences wedding-day jitters, Ira realizes his son
isn't so different after all.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons of ``Common Ground'' will be obvious to many, but
instructive to anyone who thinks devotion to a set of values is
immutable. With elegance, power and the sort of humor often missing
from such message films, ``Common Ground'' is a fertile place to
plant the seeds of change.
</P>
<P>
   Common Ground. A collection of three short films dealing with
attitudes toward homosexuality in small-town America. Starring
Edward Asner, Beau Bridges, Harvey Fierstein, Brian Kerwin, Margot
Kidder, Dan Lauria, James Le Gros, Brittany Murphy, Jason
Priestley, Mimi Rogers, Helen Shaver, Eric Stoltz, Jonathan Taylor
Thomas and Steven Weber. Saturday night on Showtime; repeating
Monday and Feb. 10. Parental guideline rating: TV-MA.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1725EST &QL; 
