<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-FUNDRAISING-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN DEMOCRATS IN HESSE DISCLOSE MORE OVERSEAS ACCOUNTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The Christian Democratic Union in the state of Hesse
said Thursday that it illegally transferred $10 million to overseas
accounts, more than double the amount it had previously disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Manfred Kanther, a former interior minister
and party leader in the state, said only $4.2 million had been
moved into accounts in Switzerland and Liechtenstein, where shrewd
investment had increased the sum to more than $7 million. He later
resigned his seat in the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But Roland Koch, the Christian Democratic premier in the state
of Hesse, said Thursday that a new audit showed the money
transferred was far larger than Kanther had claimed. ``This has got
to be the right figure,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily revelations of illicit financial dealings by the
opposition Christian Democrats have generated a mood of deep
political unease in Germany, exacerbated by the refusal of former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl to heed the law and reveal what he knows
about the sources of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Hesse, home to Germany's financial capital, Frankfurt, has
emerged as the place where most money of uncertain origin was
secretly put to use by the party. Koch, who was elected premier
last year, painted a picture Thursday of a covert system eventually
involving more than $16.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The seed of this hidden treasure, whose origin remains unknown,
was the $10 million disclosed Thursday. This sum, whose origin
remains mysterious, was transferred in 1983 from accounts at
Metalbank in Frankfurt run by the longtime treasurer of the party
in Hesse, Prince Casimir Prinz of Sayn-Wittgenstein. It went to
accounts in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   A small part of the money _ less than $1 million _ quickly
returned to Christian Democratic accounts in Germany. The rest,
with capital gains from investment, was eventually used to
establish a foundation named ``Zaunkonig'' (or ``Wren'') in
Liechtenstein, secretly controlled by the party.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Schnee, a spokesman for the Hesse Christian Democrats,
said that $8.8 million remained on the foundation's accounts. He
added that a recent inspection of the foundation's books revealed
that, through the years, a further $7.5 million had been moved back
into Germany, generally disguised as ``bequests.''
</P>
<P>
   These two figures, totaling $16.3 million, are the result of the
initial $10 million transfer from Frankfurt to Switzerland. ``It's
a lot of money, and we still don't know what may pop up in the next
two days,'' Schnee said.
</P>
<P>
   The party's investigation in Hesse is now focused on discovering
where the $10 million came from and ensuring that no more hidden
money surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Under German law, the party appears to have committed several
crimes: misrepresenting the source of party contributions as
``bequests,'' placing undeclared sums in overseas accounts, evading
tax on capital gains there, and failing to identify the source of
the $10 million in the original account at Metalbank.
</P>
<P>
   An audit last week of the federal accounts of the Christian
Democratic Union revealed about $6.3 million in illicit
contributions under Kohl. In all, with the $16.3 million in
unexplained money in Hesse, the Christian Democrats are grappling
with a system that generated more than $21.5 million that has not
been properly accounted for.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A further mystery surrounds the money. Of the $7.5 million taken
from the Liechtenstein foundation and transferred back into
Germany, only about $5.2 million turned up on the accounts of the
Christian Democratic party. The rest has apparently been stolen or
lost.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of these illicit dealings led the Social Democratic
party of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder to seek the annulment of
Koch's election last year. But that attempt was narrowly rebuffed
this week by the Hesse legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has admitted to taking more than $1 million in secret
payments between 1993 and 1998. But he continues to insist that he
will not identify ``donors'' to whom he promised anonymity,
flouting a law that says the source of any party contribution of
over $10,500 must be revealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
