<HEADER>
A8410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EYE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     01-27 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EYE OF THE BEHOLDER':   SHE'S A REAL KILLER, AND HE'S SMITTEN
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only question worth asking about Stephan Elliott's surreal
thriller ``Eye of the Beholder,'' is whether Ashley Judd, coming
off the success of the surprise hit ``Double Jeopardy'' can draw
enough unsuspecting patrons into theaters for this impenetrable
mess of a movie to turn a profit. Ms. Judd, who was the scowling
embodiment of female vengeance in ``Double Jeopardy,'' has a
vaguely similar role in ``Eye of the Beholder.'' Here she is Joanna
Eris, a glowering, peripatetic psycho killer who changes wigs and
aliases every few minutes while cutting a deadly swath from New
York to San Francisco to Alaska with many boring stops in between.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Joanna becomes the obsessional love object of a
British intelligence agent and surveillance expert known simply as
the Eye (Ewan McGregor). The Eye, who is more than a little nuts
himself, chooses the oddest moment to fall in love. Assigned to spy
on Joanna, who may be blackmailing the son of a British government
official, he is busily filming one of their kinky assignations when
he sees her pull a knife, lunge at her blindfolded partner from
behind and repeatedly stab him in a frenzy of blood lust. From that
instant, he is hopelessly smitten. Who wouldn't be?
</P>
<P>
   As the Eye follows Joanna from city to city, always staying in
the same hotel and putting his ear to the bathroom tile to discern
her stirrings in her bubble bath beyond the wall, the Eye is
accompanied by the accusing spirit of his young daughter Lucy
(Ann-Marie Brown). Although the Eye hasn't seen Lucy in years, he
hallucinates her presence in airports and train stations where she
is always signaling for his attention. In a hotel room he is joined
by two Lucys, one playing jump-rope on the bed, the other yelling
nonsense rhymes.
</P>
<P>
   Flashbacks reveal the Eye and Joanna to share a tormented
father-daughter link. When Joanna was 9, her adored but no-account
father abandoned her on Christmas Day. The Eye's wife and daughter
likewise abandoned him when his work took over his life, and now he
is consumed with guilt and loneliness. Or so we must deduce,
McGregor's performance being so flat and devoid of feeling that his
character emerges as less than a zero.
</P>
<P>
   You can see what the director is trying to get at in this clumsy
screen adaptation of Marc Behm's 1980 noir novel. Especially in a
scene where the Eye hides out in a San Francisco bell tower, the
movie wants to be a souped-up, serial-killing ``Vertigo,'' with a
big dash of ``Obsession'' thrown in. But Elliott, who made his
reputation with ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the
Desert'' and followed it with the chaotic black comedy ``Welcome to
Woop Woop,'' hasn't the temperament for noir movies.
</P>
<P>
   He has no idea of how to establish a mood of menace or to use a
setting to evoke an emotional landscape. Everything from the
movie's sudden abrasive intrusions of fake thunder and lightning to
Lucy's jarring appearances in the Eye's life is a garish surface
effect. Instead of Bernard Herrmann's fractured Wagnerian
orchestrations for Alfred Hitchcock, the score for ``Eye of the
Beholder'' pounds us with the usual electronic cliches. The voice
of Chrissie Hynde whining ``I Wish You Love,'' which becomes a
recurrent refrain, is more an annoyance than a haunting theme.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Judd, at least, emerges from this fiasco with her dignity
intact. Her role may make no psychological sense, but as she acts
out Joanna's crazy personality changes, from cunning femme fatale
to a gender-reversed Norman Bates, she is clearly giving her all to
an unsalvageable enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eye of the Beholder'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has scenes of gory
violence and some nudity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EYE OF THE BEHOLDER'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Stephan Elliott; based on the novel by
Marc Behm; director of photography, Guy Dufaux; edited by Sue
Blainey; music by Marius de Vries; production designer,
Jean-Baptiste Tard; produced by Nicolas Clermont and Tony Smith;
released by Destination Films. Running time: 102 minutes. This film
is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ewan McGregor (the Eye), Ashley Judd (Joanna), Ann-Marie
Brown (Lucy), Patrick Bergin (Alex), K.D. Lang (Hilary), Jason
Priestley (Gary) and Genevieve Bujold (Dr. Brault).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
