<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     01-27 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN GLOBES AS CRYSTAL BALLS 
IVY LEAGUE INTRIGUE 
`SCREAM' DYING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Producers, studio executives and agents agree that
in a town of often odd events, the Golden Globes ceremony ranks
quite high as one of the oddest.
</P>
<P>
   The annual nationally televised award show on NBC, presented
last Sunday, is often seen as a harbinger of the Academy Awards.
But the track record of the Hollywood Foreign Press Association,
which gives the awards, is mixed. And the organization itself, with
only 82 voting members, some of them freelance writers with only
vague journalistic connections, is treated with a shrug and a
certain humor by the Hollywood elite.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, though, Hollywood treats the Golden Globes
seriously, sort of. ``They are important because they are seen as a
bellwether for the Academy Awards,'' said Terry Press, in charge of
marketing at DreamWorks.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Press was speaking, perhaps, with a bit of wishful thinking.
The DreamWorks film ``American Beauty,'' starring Kevin Spacey and
Annette Bening , took home three of the top awards at the Golden
Globes ceremony. The awards were for the best drama, for the
director, Sam Mendes, and the screenwriter, Alan Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Even though only four of the 13 Golden Globe winners went on to
win Academy Awards last year and even though the organization
itself is a bit offbeat _ ``Feed them, and they will come,'' said
one studio publicity agent about the Foreign Press Association _ a
triumph at the Globes is an important ingredient as the Oscar
season moves into high gear. (The nominations for the 72nd annual
Academy Awards will be announced on Feb. 15, and Oscars will be
presented on March 26.)
</P>
<P>
   One day after winning best picture in the drama category for
``American Beauty,'' DreamWorks announced that it was re-releasing
the movie at 750 theaters around the nation. At the same time
DreamWorks made plans to promote the film, which is now, at least
for the moment, the front-runner in the best film category.
Potential rivals include ``The Insider,'' ``The Talented Mr.
Ripley'' and ``Being John Malkovich.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Press said the notion of being seen as a front-runner
appalled her and the company. Last year DreamWorks was seen for
months as the front-runner for Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' But after a savvy and high-priced marketing campaign by
Miramax, its ``Shakespeare in Love'' won the Oscar for best
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We presume nothing now,'' said Ms. Press. ``We're grateful to
have won the Golden Globes. But I'm not going to repeat the sins of
last year. We've been there. We've been front-runner before. This
is our second time around with this. It didn't work out last year
and we're not counting on anything this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, Ms. Press said that DreamWorks got caught up in the
competition with Miramax last year and may have overspent on the
Academy Award campaign on trade paper and newspaper advertisements.
This year, she said, that will not happen. ``We'll have a presence,
but a restrained and tasteful presence,'' Ms. Press insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Hollywood Foreign Press Association, which earns
substantial sums from its telecast, is struggling to gain
credibility. Years ago gifts and free trips from studios were
commonplace. Last month though, Sharon Stone, who was up for an
acting award for ``The Muse,'' sent watches worth $295 to $395 to
the 82 members of the association. Helmut Voss, the president of
the group, returned them. ``We were touched by her generosity, but
this is definitely a no-no for a group like ours to protect the
integrity of the awards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stone failed to pick up a Golden Globe this year. But
another actress, Angelina Jolie, who won a supporting actress award
for ``Girl Interrupted,'' thanked the Hollywood Foreign Press and
said: ``You guys are so kind to me. Like I must be paying you or
something!''
</P>
<P>
   Ivy League Intrigue
</P>
<P>
   John Pogue, Yale, class of '87, joined a secret society in his
senior year. ``I can't tell you which one,'' said Pogue. Rob Cohen,
Harvard, '71, never joined one of the school's private eating
clubs. ``A guy with the name of Cohen didn't get invited to join
too often back then,'' said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Using their experience and knowledge of the Ivy League elite,
the two men have created a thriller, ``The Skulls,'' about an
overachieving and poor New Haven townie who joins an elitist secret
society called the Skulls, which has members including lawmakers,
business executives and top government officials. The film _
written by Pogue and directed by Cohen _ opens on April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie is fiction _ there is a suicide and assorted
mayhem _ ``The Skulls'' was created to use the secret Ivy League
bastions of privilege as a backdrop for a drama about corruption.
Cohen, who previously directed ``The Rat Pack'' for HBO, said he
became interested years ago in Skull and Bones at Yale as well as
other clubs while researching a project about the Central
Intelligence Agency. Cohen said that many CIA directors and top
officials _ as well as Supreme Court justices, chief executives at
Fortune 500 companies and diplomats _ were members of Skull and
Bones and played a significant role in shaping American society,
especially since the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys were classmates and soul mates,'' said Cohen.
``They linked up in their college years, and stayed in a very tight
web throughout their lives to create American society in their own
image.''
</P>
<P>
   (President Bush was a member of Skull and Bones, and so was his
son George W. Bush, the Texas governor and Republican presidential
candidate.)
</P>
<P>
   Pogue, who wrote ``U.S. Marshalls,'' said he became aware of the
secret ways of Skull and Bones in his freshman year at Yale when he
visited one of his advisers, a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some problems I wanted to talk about,'' Pogue said. ``I
noticed that he had a gold pin inadvertently sticking out beneath
his shirt, and I said, quite innocently, `Are you in Skull and
Bones?' He turned away very cold. He said, `We'll have to talk
about your problems later.' He left the room. Clearly his
allegiance to his secret society was more important than his job
helping freshmen out. It sort of irritated me.''
</P>
<P>
   But why did Pogue himself join a secret society in his senior
year. ``It was a curiosity mixed with a strong desire to see who
was in them,'' he said. ``I wanted to know what went on inside
those stone temples that were all over the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stereotype to say they were all Boston Brahmin, all
from Phillips Academy. They take them from every race and color.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pogue's depiction of the secret clubs in the movie was
hardly positive. ``Maybe it was hypocritical, on my part, to
join,'' Pogue said. ``In retrospect, it probably was. I was just
intrigued.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `Scream' Dying
</P>
<P>
   The violent, witty and weird ``Scream'' trilogy is drawing to a
close, and Wes Craven, the horrormeister and director of all three
films, insisted he was happy. ``We always said it would be a
trilogy,'' said Craven, whose new film, ``Scream 3,'' opens on Feb.
4. ``The trilogy completes our theme: Real life is reflected in
movies and movies reflect real life.''
</P>
<P>
   The two earlier movies, with their teen-age and 20-something
audiences, have taken in more than $100 million each at the box
office. These are probably the most lucrative films ever made by
Miramax, which usually releases arty films. (Miramax created a
separate unit, Dimension Films, to release movies like ``Scream.'')
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the success of the series so far is based on its
shrewd casting of popular actors mostly from television shows who
appeal to the teen crowd. While previous horror films were often
made up of unknown young actors as well as older ones, the third
``Scream'' reunites Craven with David Arquette, Neve Campbell and
Courteney Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horror films until recently would be populated by first-time
actors and actresses and maybe an older star for the European
market,'' Craven said. ``You could always get Telly Savalas.''
</P>
<P>
   In the newest ``Scream,'' the lines are blurred between fiction
and a vague sense of reality. The film takes place during a
Hollywood production of ``Stab 3, Return to Woodsboro,'' a thriller
that asks questions about the murderous events that took place in
the town that was the setting of the earlier films.
</P>
<P>
   Why the success of the ``Scream'' films? ``They're actually very
contemporary films,'' Craven said. ``There's the sense in these
movies that we need to look no further than the people we know in
looking for the real villain. In most horror films, you have
supernatural mysterious figures like Jason or Freddy. In the case
of `Scream,' the villains are real people, well-known to the
victims, their contemporaries. It makes them somehow more
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The films also have a quick wit about popular culture,'' he
said. ``The names of famous people and famous movies are used. It's
closer to our own reality than the fabricated reality of making up
the names of movies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
