u e BC-NAIPAUL-BOOK-REVIEW-N     01-27 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAIPAUL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BETWEEN FATHER AND SON': HOW NAIPAUL'S BITTERSWEET NOVEL GOT THAT
WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most collections of a writer's youthful correspondence,
this volume of letters between V.S. Naipaul, then a college student
on scholarship at Oxford, and his family back home in Trinidad
draws a telling portrait of the artist as a young man. At the same
time, the book provides a fascinating map to the autobiographical
underpinnings of what is arguably Naipaul's finest novel, ``A House
for Mr. Biswas'' (1961), which created a bittersweet fictional
portrait of his father, a struggling Trinidadian journalist trying
to support his large family while holding onto his own dreams.
</P>
<P>
   That novel closed with the aging, ailing hero worrying about his
precocious son in England. ``Anand's letters, at first rare, became
more and more frequent,'' Naipaul wrote in ``Mr. Biswas.'' ``They
were gloomy, self-pitying; then they were tinged with a hysteria
which Mr. Biswas immediately understood. He wrote Anand long
humorous letters; he wrote about the garden; he gave religious
advice; at great expense he sent by air mail a book called
`Outwitting Our Nerves' by two American women psychologists.
Anand's letters grew rare again. There was nothing Mr. Biswas could
do but wait.'' The world had opened for his son, he realizes, while
for him now, ``there was nothing to wait for. Except the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   As this volume of letters reveals, that passage from ``Mr.
Biswas'' perfectly captures the relationship that existed between
Naipaul and his father in the early 1950s: the father, increasingly
burdened with financial woes and failing health, transferring his
own dreams of literary success to his talented son; the son, torn
between self-absorption and familial concern, writing home out of
duty, need and affection.
</P>
<P>
   Although we see spasms of self-doubt on the part of the young
Naipaul, he already evinces, in these letters, many of the traits
that would later make him so controversial as a writer: an
impatient elitism (``people outside are perhaps even stupider than
Oxford people, and incredibly coarser'') and a judgmental
dismissiveness: Austen's ``Emma'' is written off as ``mere
gossip,'' Conrad's ``Lord Jim'' as ``dull,'' and Tolstoy's ``Anna
Karenina'' as ``tedious.'' ``A friend told me the other day that
people don't like me,'' he writes his older sister Kamla, ``because
I made them feel that I knew they were fools.''
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier letters, dating from Naipaul's arrival in 1950 at
Oxford, his father tends to be the one dispensing advice: he warns
his son not to give in to depression and exhorts him to be sincere
in his writing. ``What do you think literature boils down to?'' he
asks. ``To writing from the belly rather than from the cheek. Most
people write from the cheek. If the semi-illiterate criminal wrote
a long letter ordinarily to his sweetheart, it would be what most
letters of such people generally are. If the criminal wrote this
letter last thing before his execution, it would be literature; it
would be poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   As time passes and Naipaul settles into his studies, however, it
becomes clear that his relationship with his father has begun to
change. For a time they write to each other as colleagues, as two
writers, grappling with the frustrations of their craft, each
encouraging the other to persevere.
</P>
<P>
   While Naipaul's ambition is all too apparent _ he is already
working on a novel, even as he crams for exams _ his father grows
increasingly weary, ``hemmed in by hard, unescapable facts'' and
the demands of supporting a wife and seven children on a salary of
$165 a month. His requests for help in getting his stories
published in England sound more and more plaintive, and in 1952 he
effectively passes the literary torch to his son, pledging to
support him after his graduation from Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to have that chance which I have never had,'' he
writes, ``somebody to support me and mine while I write. Two or
three years of this should be enough. If by then you have not
arrived, then it will be time enough for you to see about getting a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Naipaul, on his part, increasingly identifies with his father.
``As I grow older,'' he writes his sister Kamla, ``I find myself
doing things that remind me of Pa, more and more. The way I smoke;
the way I sit; the way I stroke my unshaved chin; the way in which
I sometimes sit bolt upright; the way in which I spend money
romantically and foolishly. I am afraid Pa won't like this. For he
will presently have no secrets from me. The more I learn about
myself, the more I learn about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming a successful writer was, for Naipaul, a way of paying
homage to his father and his father's dreams, and it was also a way
for him to escape his provincial past. Though the most lyrical
passages in Naipaul's otherwise flatly written letters attest to
his nostalgia for home (``I long for the nights that fall blackly,
suddenly, without warning,'' he writes his father. ``I long for a
violent shower of rain at night''), he remains contemptuous of
Trinidad as one of those countries he would later describe as
``half-made'' societies ``doomed to remain half-made.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I shall die if I had to spend the rest of my life in
Trinidad,'' he writes his mother. ``The place is too small, the
values are all wrong, and the people are petty. Besides, there is
really very little for me to do there.'' Despite promises to visit
his family, he will not return home for six years, by which time he
has sold two books, ``The Mystic Masseur'' and ``Miguel Street,''
and launched himself on a successful literary career. By then his
father, like Mr. Biswas, is dead from heart problems at the age of
47.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BETWEEN FATHER AND SON: Family Letters: V.S. Naipaul'
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Gillon Aitken
</P>
<P>
   297 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
