<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEASE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BIG TEASE': HOLLYWOOD MOCKUMENTARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nuclear missiles could be zooming in all directions and
earthquakes and plagues devastating the planet, but as everybody
(especially in Hollywood) knows, there's nothing worse than a bad
hair day. Joan Rivers would understand. Beyond cosmetic surgery and
selecting the right dress, a woman's choice of hair color and style
can spell the crowning difference between being deemed a lady or a
tramp while making that perilous journey down the red carpet into
the awards show ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of awards, forget the Oscars and the Golden Globes!
The only Hollywood competition that really matters is the World
Freestyle Hairdressing Championship. Never heard of it? Well, ``The
Big Tease,'' a campy, moderately amusing new comedy, will take you
behind the scenes at this ultraexclusive event in which the world's
leading hair stylists battle tooth and nail, comb and curler, for
the Platinum Scissors Award, a priceless pair of gleaming shears
once possessed by Czar Nicholas II of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   And wait till you see their creations! More than mere hairdos,
they resemble elaborate window displays teetering precariously atop
plumes that have been teased, sprayed, glued and lacquered into
unsinkable vessels bearing enough tchotchkes to fill an F.A.O.
Schwarz window at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks: If you have overdosed on the preening
narcissism and nutty hyperbole of recent Hollywood awards
ceremonies and their surrounding hoopla, this funny but ramshackle
movie might be the purgative you need. A mock documentary directed
by Kevin Allen, ``The Big Tease'' follows Crawford Mackenzie (Craig
Ferguson), an indefatigably cheerful hairdresser from Glasgow,
Scotland, all the way to Los Angeles, where he arrives under the
mistaken impression that he is an official contestant.
</P>
<P>
   Although continually patronized and humiliated, with doors
slammed in his face and receivers clicking in his ear, Crawford,
with his can-do spirit and boundless enthusiasm, eventually melts
the hearts of the officious Hollywood handlers who stand in his way
and whom the movie assesses with a cheerfully withering eye.
</P>
<P>
   One of the movie's chief sources of humor is its extreme case of
tunnel vision, which mirrors that of its main character. ``The Big
Tease,'' which is being smartly promoted by Warner Brothers as
``Rocky in Curlers,'' never questions Crawford's values, which are
finally as dubious as those of the snooty entertainment
professionals he charms. Its other biggest asset is Ferguson, the
popular Scottish comedian who plays Drew Carey's boss on television
(Carey puts in a cameo appearance) and who wrote the screenplay
with Sacha Gervasi. Ferguson's Crawford is an original: a
blustering party-loving bloke who is gay but sleeps with a woman
when the occasion demands, although afterward she wonders why he
kept murmuring the name Gareth (his Glasgow boyfriend) during
lovemaking.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner has Crawford's plane touched down than the procession
of Hollywood caricatures begins. There's a goonish limo driver and
self-described ``player'' peddling a screenplay about aliens and
basketball. There's the hotel clerk impressed by Crawford's
Scottish accent who blurts, ``I love the Beatles,'' and the nutty
hotel manager who lectures Crawford about his ``fiscal
responsibility'' when it turns out the competition isn't paying for
his fancy hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford makes some headway by trading on a distant connection
with his fellow Scot Sean Connery, whose publicist, Candy Harper
(Frances Fisher), he wins over by giving her an in-office follicle
makeover. Eternally grateful for the restoration of her
self-esteem, Candy begins pulling strings and opening doors. Ms.
Fisher makes this obnoxious powermonger _ the kind of person who
boasts, ``This is MY town'' _ into someone almost lovable.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking on the outskirts of the movie, which increasingly
forgets to act like a mockumentary, is the dour filmmaker (Chris
Langham) whose movie about Crawford for British television is a big
change of pace from his usual fare, which normally deals with
issues like poverty in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Big Tease'' sustains an antic mood, it is crudely
edited (most of an extended disco sequence seems to have landed on
the cutting-room floor), and its closest thing to a villain, a
hulking Scandinavian hairdresser named Stig (David Rasche) who is
Crawford's rival for the Platinum Scissors, doesn't work as a
character. Still, ``The Big Tease'' is diverting. As it rubs our
noses in our own fascination with vanity and the silliest values in
life, it's charming enough to make us like it.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE BIG TEASE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kevin Allen; written by Sacha Gervasi and Craig
Ferguson; director of photography, Seamus McGarvey; edited by Chris
Peppe; music by Mark Thomas; production designer, Joseph Hodges;
produced by Philip Rose; released by Warner Brothers. Running time:
88 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Craig Ferguson (Crawford Mackenzie), Frances Fisher
(Candy), Mary McCormack (Monique), David Rasche (Stig) and Chris
Langham (BBC Interviewer).
</P>
<P>
   This movie is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It has sexual situations and off-color humor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
