<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8437 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOON-THEATER-REVIEW-N     01-27 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEAHOUSE OF THE AUGUST MOON': FAULTY PRODUCTION IS STILL WORTH
SEEING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Teahouse of the August Moon,'' set in 1946, is about a
poor American Army slob who has never been able to do any job
right. His latest assignment is to Americanize a small village on
occupied Okinawa, but he is talked into building a teahouse instead
of a schoolhouse and into selling particularly potent sweet-potato
brandy for profit. He is the one who ends up being taught _ that
there may be something superior about a culture that makes a daily
ritual of sitting in the pine grove, sipping tea and watching the
sunset.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, he declares that he has taken ``a step backward in
the right direction.'' (In 1953, when John Patrick's play was first
staged on Broadway, this was, believe it or not, high transcultural
praise.)
</P>
<P>
   Take that and the fact that the movie version is notorious
because Marlon Brando was cast as the Asian interpreter, and you
can see why the Pan Asian Repertory Theater wanted to revive this
work. Unfortunately, the production is a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Abuba, who is Asian-American, does a fine job as the
interpreter, Sakini. Scott Klavan is lovable and funny as Fisby,
the pushover American captain. John Daggett as Captain McLean, the
psychiatrist who would rather be reading seed catalogs, has a
couple of nice moments. But a few cast members are absolutely
wooden, letting Tony-winning, Pulitzer Prize-winning jokes die on
the vine. A goat puppet, playing the role of a live goat, gets some
of the most heartfelt laughs, and it's not THAT cute.
</P>
<P>
   But even a faulty production of ``The Teahouse of the August
Moon'' is almost worth seeing, just for the play's juxtaposition of
ahead-of-its-time awareness and cultural stereotyping. (All the
Okinawan characters speak without verbs: ``Pornography question of
geography.'') Colonel Purdy (Peter Von Berg) says things like
``You'll find these people lack the capacity for sustained
endeavor,'' and when Fisby volunteers to study the local dialect,
Purdy dismisses that idea in the blink of an eye. ``No need,'' he
says. ``We won the war.'' But the colonel has always been the
villain, and he is proved wrong at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning the play seems to show Okinawans as fatuous
manipulators and Americans as blithering idiots, but the humanity
on both sides soon shines through. Fisby learns that geishas are
not prostitutes, and he learns to be happy working in a bathrobe,
which is as close as he can come to a kimono. His final
realization, to the horror of his superiors, is that by making all
the villagers members of the brewing cooperative, he has actually
brought communism to Okinawa. That observation was left out of the
1956 movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Teahouse of the August Moon'' is directed by Ron Nakahara,
with attractive, inventive sets by Robert Klingelhoefer. It
continues at Playhouse 91 through Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TEAHOUSE OF THE AUGUST MOON'
</P>
<P>
   By John Patrick, adapted from the novel by Vern Sneider;
directed by Ron Nakahara. Lighting by Jeffrey Cady; sound by Peter
Griggs; sets by Robert Klingelhoefer; costumes by Terry Leong.
Presented by the Pan Asian Repertory Theater, Tisa Chang, artistic
and producing director. At Playhouse 91. Through Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ernest Abuba (Sakini), Kevin Bergen (Sergeant Gregovich),
Peter Von Berg (Col. Wainwright Purdy III), Scott Klavan (Captain
Fisby), Carol Honda (Old Woman/Miss Higa-Jiga), Ako (Old Woman's
Daughter/Lotus Blossom), Tran T. Thuc Hanh (Child/Mrs. Keora), Tom
Matsusaka (Ancient Man/Mr. Oshira), John Baray (Mr. Hokaida), David
Kimo Ige (Mr. Omura), Paul Keoni Chun (Mr. Sumata), J.B Barricklo
(Mr. Seiko) and John Daggett (Captain McLean). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
