<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SANTITOS-FILM-REVIEW-     01-27 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTITOS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SANTITOS': WHY A YOUNG WIDOW WENT NOBLY INTO BROTHELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things are not dull at Padre Salvador's confessional, especially
after Esperanza Diaz, a lovely young widow, starts dropping by so
often. By the middle of ``Santitos,'' a disarmingly endearing film
from Mexico, Esperanza is confessing about her activities at more
than one brothel.
</P>
<P>
   The padre (Fernando Torre Lapham) would rather be back in his
room watching his favorite telenovela, but the male parishioners,
who stand impolitely close to the confessional, are fascinated.
</P>
<P>
   It all started when Esperanza (Dolores Heredia) saw St. Jude
through the dirty window of her oven. (``Thank God I ran out of
Easy Off &UR; , &LR; '' she tells the priest.) The saint spoke to her,
informing her that Blanca, her 12-year-old daughter, was not dead
after all and could be found in ``La Casa Rosa'' (the pink house).
</P>
<P>
   Esperanza, who lives with another widow (Ana Bertha Espin), is
beside herself with joy. Her daughter's recent death had been
suspicious anyway. Blanca (Maya Zapata) had gone into the hospital
just to have her tonsils out. But she suddenly died of ``an unknown
virus,'' the doctor said, which was why the coffin had to be
sealed. So Esperanza never saw her daughter's body.
</P>
<P>
   After St. Jude starts appearing, Esperanza will stop at nothing
to find out the truth. This leads her to the hospital (where she
learns that Blanca's doctor disappeared right after the girl's
supposed death), to the cemetery (where, denied an exhumation
order, she goes grave digging in the middle of the night) and to a
cleaning job at a local brothel (because she has been told that
young girls are sometimes kidnapped and sold into prostitution).
</P>
<P>
   When she hears about a house of ill repute called La Casa Rosa
in Tijuana, Esperanza is on her way to new adventures. They will
involve prostitution on her part, a French provincial waterbed, a
secret room, a rich client from California, a gray-haired madam who
has the look of a ladylike drag queen (understandably, since she is
played by Roberto Cobo), an illegal border crossing and a wrestler
called the Angel of Justice, who doesn't like to take off his mask.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the story goes astray, and the last half-hour or so
is disappointingly banal, but it makes a nice recovery at the very
end.
</P>
<P>
   The charm of ``Santitos,'' which was shown at last year's
Sundance Film Festival, is its knowing but joyous life-affirming
tone. Both the director, Alejandro Springall, and the screenwriter,
Maria Amparo Escandon, have done well by Ms. Escandon's novel, on
which the film is based.
</P>
<P>
   But a great deal of credit should also go to Ms. Heredia, a
Mexican actress who lives in Switzerland, for making Esperanza's
common-sense faith and bright innocence believable, and admirable,
from beginning to end.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SANTITOS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alejandro Springall; written (in Spanish, with
English subtitles) by Maria Amparo Escandon; director of
photography, Xavier Perez Grobet; edited by Carol Dysinger; music
by Carlo Nicolau and Rosino Serrano; produced by Springall and
Claudia Florescano; released by Latin Universe. Running time: 90
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With: Dolores Heredia (Esperanza), Fernando Torre Lapham (Padre
Salvador), Juan Duarte (Fidencio), Ana Bertha Espin (Soledad), Maya
Zapata (Blanca), Roberto Cobo (Dona Trini) and Georgina Tabora
(Hospital Receptionist). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Santitos' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It includes profanity, sexual situations, partial
nudity and a brawl at a wrestling match. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
