<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      01-27 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, January 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A batch of wintry precipitation, mainly in the form of ice
pellets, moved across northern Texas on Thursday morning as a
potent jet stream disturbance approached from eastern New Mexico.
Snow fell in Oklahoma and Arkansas, where a deep layer of cold air
prevailed above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, broken areas of light to moderate wintry precipitation
will affect an area ranging from the lower Mississippi and
Tennessee valleys to the southern Appalachians as the disturbance
lifts northeast and gradually weakens. However, a narrow swath of
locally heavy snow could affect the Tennessee Valley, where a
surface trough of low pressure reaching north from the Gulf of
Mexico enhances the lifting of moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Patches of light to moderate snow will develop over the lower
Ohio Valley, but its northeastward advance will be checked by a
robust high pressure system over the upper Ohio Valley. Meanwhile,
showers will spread toward Florida from southern Mississippi as a
low pressure system grinds eastward. Rainfalls of an inch are
possible near the Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous combinations of Arctic air and strong winds will
prevail across New England, which will stay in the windy, frigid
wake of a low pressure system over the Canadian Maritimes. Wind and
Arctic chill will ease Saturday as the weakening low heads toward
the Labrador Sea.
</P>
<P>
   A swath of accumulating snows will blanket parts of the Missouri
Valley as an upper-level low lifts moist air drawn northwestward
from the Tennessee Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snow Legacy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the snow cover left by this week's storm can have
important effects on temperature. Newly fallen snow reflects up to
90 percent of the energy from the sun, resulting in daytime
temperatures a few degrees colder than when the ground is bare. On
a clear and calm night, the snow aids in the process that radiates
energy away from the earth, allowing temperatures to fall more
sharply. This weekend, the snow cover in valleys near the southern
Appalachians will help keep the air near the ground chilled,
heightening the risk of an ice storm as moisture arrives from the
south. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8449 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOXER-HNS &LR;      01-27 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOXER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOXER VOWS TO FIGHT U.S. CITIZENSHIP FOR CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND and MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Barbara Boxer pledged Thursday to block any
legislation to grant U.S. citizenship to Elian Gonzalez, saying
efforts to keep the Cuban boy in this country amount to ``child
abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, D-Calif., said in an interview that ``it's just
horrible'' that the 6-year-old boy ``has been made a political
pawn'' in American-Cuban relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service has ordered the
American relatives of Gonzalez to return the boy to his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, in Cuba. Elian Gonzalez, who was 5 at the
time, was found clinging to an inner tube off the coast of Florida
on Nov. 25 after the boat carrying him to the United States
capsized, killing his mother, her boyfriend and nine other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing to this child is causing him to suffer
another loss on top of this incredible loss of watching his mother
die before his very eyes,'' Boxer said. ``Now as a result of U.S.
action we're going to say he's going to lose his father? This is
child abuse in my opinion. This is not right. This is untenable. If
you really believe in family values you wouldn't do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said the boy should be back in Cuba with his father as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's young enough that after time this memory will be
put into some kind of perspective,'' she said. ``The longer this
goes on, the more traumatic this will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Thursday, Attorney General Janet Reno said she
continued to be willing to work with the family to reach a
compromise, but the government's decision to return the boy to Cuba
would not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that we recognize that what is at stake
here is a bond between a parent and his child, and that in almost
every legal system I know, certainly in ours, (that bond) is
something that is interrupted only in extreme circumstances,'' she
said at her weekly new conference.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reno declined to say whether the Justice Department
would fight the citizenship legislation, she made clear her
opposition to any such action by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If American children ended up abroad, and American parents
wanted them returned, and a foreign country made them a citizen so
they did not return, I don't think people in the United States
would be very happy about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., is pushing legislation to grant
citizenship to the boy, but Boxer said she doubts there is enough
support in the Senate to approve the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's unclear whether he'll bring this to the
floor,'' said Boxer, who vowed to filibuster the citizenship bill
if there were a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, who has one grandchild, said she empathizes with
Gonzalez's grandmothers, Raquel Rodriguez and Mariela Quintana, who
returned to Capitol Hill Thursday with a tearful plea to have their
grandson returned to Cuba. Boxer said she met with the women on
Tuesday and got ``a strong feeling that this is from their heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and Quintana spent Thursday pressing their case with
lawmakers on Capitol Hill while at the same time, American
relatives of the boy urged Congress to approve the citizenship
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters through a translator in a hallway,
Quintana said she and Rodriguez ``have been suffering a lot'' since
they met with their grandson on Wednesday in Miami. ``Our grandson
is a whole different boy. He has changed completely. They are doing
something to him that has changed the child,'' Quintana said.
</P>
<P>
   Quintana said her grandson was very shy at first but ``became
more interested'' after they showed him photos of his friends and
family in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to save this child as soon as possible to bring him
back to his family and father in Cuba,'' Quintana said, adding that
is the only way he will ``recover and be the happy boy he was
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintana added that when the grandmothers told the boy they want
to bring him back home, ``he nodded his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said the grandmothers ``are under tremendous stress and
strain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that this isn't doing any good for the
anti-Castro cause,'' Boxer said. ``They're looking as if they'll do
anything for politics and ideology. You have to put a little boy's
health and safety before politics. They ought to take their stand
on other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington has no formal diplomatic ties with the Cuban
government of Fidel Castro. Gonzalez's relatives in Florida are
fighting to prevent his return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
