<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLY-DOTCOM-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES CALL ATTENTION TO ALL RELIGIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Clarifies in fourth from last graf that Max Waldman was Steve's
grandfather.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking old-time religion (or New Age spirituality) on line can
be a hellish business of sifting through myriad sites as diverse as
the homepage of a Minnesota-based sect that practices ``spiritual
dreaming'' and the official Web site of the Holy See. With Yahoo
listing almost 7,500 Christian sites alone, cyberspace promises as
much daunting journey as heaven-sent opportunity for believers and
searchers alike.
</P>
<P>
   Now, striding boldly into this on-line chaos comes
Beliefnet.com, thought to be the first Web site to attempt to
encompass all of the world's principal religions and belief
systems. Launched this month by two journalists with strong roots
in traditional print media, Beliefnet targets a multifaith audience
with a slickly packaged magazine-style mix of news and advice and
inspirational writing from a panoply of religious perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that Beliefnet will be a place where adults and
children alike can find answers to some of life's stickiest
questions,'' says co-founder Steven Waldman, former editor of US
News &AMP; World Report, ``or at least find other people similiarly
baffled, curious, or in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Beliefnet has attracted more than $5 million of start-up capital
and a Who's Who of regular writers, ranging from liberal Catholic
sociologist and novelist Rev. Andrew Greeley to Harvard theologian
Harvey Cox, from conservative Catholic Tom Bethell of American
Spectator magazine to rabbinical writer Joseph Telushkin, from
American Buddhist lama Surya Das of Cambridge to National Public
Radio correspondent and Wicca priestess Margot Adler.
</P>
<P>
   Based in New York, it's the brainchild of Waldman, 37, and
Robert Nylen, 55, founding publisher of the former New England
Monthly, who shuttles between a Manhattan apartment and his home in
Ashfield.
</P>
<P>
   While providing a site for all those ``sticky'' questions, they
also devoutly hope to make money in the process. In an on-line
world where most religion sites are ``dot.org,'' not ``dot.com,''
Beliefnet is a for-profit venture. An estimated 25 million
Americans regularly peruse the Internet for religious information,
and Waldman and Nylen want to tap that potential market with an
e-commerce component scheduled to go on line in the spring. They
expect to sell and advertise inspirational books, tapes, videos,
and CDs as well as holistic health products and trips with a
religious theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate doing tens of millions dollars in business
within five years,'' says Nylen.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's sound prediction or fervent prayer, of course,
remains to be seen. There are several large Christian commercial
Web sites such as iChristian and Crosswalk but none that targets as
broad an interfaith market as Beliefnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very well-designed site and they seem to have
leap-frogged over what else is out there. I've never heard of
another aggregator who cuts across all these differrent sectors and
is a portal for all religions,'' says Jill Frankle, director of
retail research at Gomez Advisors of Lincoln, Mass., an e-commerce
analysis firm. ``Getting visitors is the key and having leading
religion writers and columnists should attract strong participation
from religious communities. Then, e-commerce can be layered on top
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beliefnet's menu offers a virtual smorgasbord of spiritual
concepts and religious practices whose strength _ and weakness _ is
its one-stop shopping approach to matters of the soul. It's an
equal-opportunity portal where major and minor religions get equal
access.
</P>
<P>
   It offers everything from tips on the best way to say grace in a
restaurant (bowed head and silent prayer) and weekly Torah
commentaries to advice about what to give a newlywed pagan couple
(matching goblets, hanging crystals, and a broom made of birch or
cinnamon to put over the door). It aims to be both intellectual and
interactive, with articles on such topics as the growing shortage
of Roman Catholic priests and electronic ``prayer circles''
soliciting prayers on behalf of individuals in need. It includes a
daily quotation excerpted from the writings of the Dalai Lama and
an ``Ask the Lama'' column in which Surya Das addresses such basic
questions about Buddhism as ``Can Buddhists eat meat?'' (Yes,
although many don't.)
</P>
<P>
   Its ``browse religions'' link leads to the home pages of 32
religions from Bahai and Buddhism to Unitarian-Universalist and
Zoroastrianism and includes Christianity (Catholic, Eastern
Orthodox, Mormon, and Protestant), Judaism and Islam as well as
Jainism, Shinto, and Scientology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other sites may have chat rooms, but I'll have a chant room,''
quips Surya Das, an on-line veteran who has had his own Web site
for more than five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new media, and I was hesitant at first,''
acknowledges Cox, a Baptist minister. ``But my students are always
showing me things that they've pulled off the Net, and obviously
that's what more and more people are looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Waldman sees it, this opportunity for spiritual
comparison shopping makes Beliefnet a religious site uniquely
attuned to its times. About 60 percent of Americans now marry
outside their faith or denomination, he says, and people are
increasingly exposed to _ and often intrigued by _ belief systems
other than the ones of their childhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Waldman himself is a product of these times. He describes
himself as ``a standard-issue American Reform Jew raised to know
more about Jewish culture than Jewish theology.'' He's married to a
Presbyterian woman who, he says, agreed to raise their children as
Jews who are aware of their mother's faith. A few nights a week, he
says, they sing their children the Sh'ma, the core prayer of Jewish
belief, ``sometimes before and sometimes after the Lord's Prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Beliefnet's goal is to encourage tolerance and a wide-ranging,
faith-based conversation about some of the vexing issues of modern
life. The danger is that by assembling so many religious
perspectives in one place it will promote a superficial,
pick-and-choose approach to belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization provides us with the double challenge of getting
along together and also affirming and projecting our own identity,
and the Internet is a tremendous resource to do that,'' says the
Rev. Theodor Stylianopoulos, who teaches at the Eastern Orthodox
Hellenic College in Brookline, Mass. and writes a column for
Beliefnet. ``In our pluralistic, post-modern world, religion has to
go to the marketplace, but I would be concerned about the site if
it suggests a mingling of religions and a loss of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Waldman anticipates such concerns in a preemptive
article he wrote for the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion rubs our faces in certain uncomfortable principles
(like those underlying the Ten Commandments) even when it might be
more convenient to ignore them,'' he writes. ``The Internet, on the
other hand . . . will make shopping for principles a little too
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as the telephone can be misused to harass and bedevil, so
can the Internet end up either eroding or enhancing religion. It's
our choice.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Nylen did not set out to launch an Internet company. With
backgrounds in publishing, the original idea was to start a
magazine with a strong Web presence. But after some research they
concluded that a Web site was far more likely to attract investors
and viewers _ as well as make more money _ than a print venture.
And, Waldman says, the interactive nature of the Internet makes it
responsive to the natural rhythms of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional media don't cover the most important events in
most peoples lives, like the births of children or deaths in the
family,'' he says. ``An interactive media can let people create a
community and cover themselves and their own life passages.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's ``Milestones'' page chronicles those passages. Its
early postings come from the 35 staff members and their families
and friends. In the memorial he posted to his grandfather, Max,
Waldman writes, ``All his life he worked hard, often exhausted
himself to support his family and see that his only son could go on
to better things.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Stone, a Methodist minister who teaches evangelism at
Boston University's School of Theology, regularly surfs religious
Web sites. So far _ and for the most part _ he likes what he sees
on Beliefnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at the breadth and the attractive format,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could become a kind of religious deli where people select
what they want from here and there,'' he cautions, ``but a better
understanding of other people's traditions and unique contributions
is healthy. The world's problems are too great to be solved by any
one group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
