<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS COMES AGAIN FOR AGASSI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ Christmas came a little late, but Andre Agassi
didn't mind. As long as he had Pete Sampras gift-wrapped _ or was
it rapped? _ he could stand the wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a little late, but it's here,'' he says, acknowledging
that Christmas Eve and Christmas Day had been largely devoted to
running up and down the steep hill in Las Vegas that he and his
gargantuan trainer, Gil Reyes, call ``Magic Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had tears in my eyes, Andre was working so hard to get ready
for this,'' Reyes says. Reyes's tears reappeared as Agassi
propelled one last high-kicking serve to Sampras's vulnerable
backhand, certifying that the hard labor had paid off in another
long-distance run, five fantastic sets, 6-4, 3-6, 6-7 (0-7), 7-6
(7-5), 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Only 22 minutes before that, Agassi had hung from the high wire
by his pigeon toes, so close to falling to defeat that all Sampras
had to do was give him a last nudge. But Agassi resisted any last
rites, righted himself in a triumph of fine-tuned will and
physique, and now the glitter-domed little guy, the reformed
wastrel of a monster talent, is in the final of the Australian Open
for a second time. He beat Sampras for the title in 1995, and is
the first guy to qualify for four consecutive major championship
bouts since Rod Laver did so while making his 1969 Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   For almost three hours, the shotmaking brilliance of the
universe's two best players, a smorgasbord of acrobatics and daring
strokes, may have constituted the finest match seen in the
12-year-old amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another of our epics,'' says Sampras, winner of four of their
previous five encounters, and still ahead, 17-12. He shrugs and
shakes his head. ``I got a little down after I came so close to
winning in four. How did I let it happen? I'll be asking myself
that for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament isn't over. It just seems that way, as though it
were the proper final, hyped for nearly two weeks, since the draw
pointed to a semifinal collision between No. 1 Agassi and the
dispossessed ruler, No. 3 Sampras. They lived up to the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the pounding in Reyes's body shop, or the good karma of
Agassi's love affair with a fairly resolute champion herself,
Steffi Graf, or the overdue decision to ante every last ounce of
himself on the table that has made this Vegas venturer the highest
roller in his game? Probably all of that as well as the faith of
coach Brad Gilbert when Agassi fell so low in the rankings that he
needed a miner's helmet a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes coddles Agassi like a jailer overseeing a guy on a chain
gang breaking rocks. And ``Rock,'' as the recent champion of France
and the United States is called in his camp, was positively
Gibraltarian in breaking down Sampras, his rival since childhood,
in their 29th professional clash.
</P>
<P>
   You could almost hear Reyes singing ``Jingle Bells'' as he and
Graf and Gilbert went into a three-way hug while their man blew
kisses at them and bowed north, south, east, west to the
thundering, exhilarated full house of 15,000 in Rod Laver Arena.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of jingle and tingle left in Agassi after the
fourth set. However, Sampras, twice two points from victory,
couldn't grasp it with his smooth, effortless strokes and faded
beneath the relentless staccato of Agassi's whippy uppercuts.
</P>
<P>
   Melbourne lost summer somewhere during the last week. You would
have believed that a late white Christmas might appear as toothy
gusts took the wind chill down into the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cold,'' says Agassi, who played hot. ``Sometimes all I
was moving was my head, watching Pete's serves go by. But you have
to get yourself in a frame of mind not to be bothered. He can serve
you right out of here _ he almost did.'' Sampras's high-velocity
zingers, up to 125 m.p.h., were zephyrs as chilling to Agassi as
the natural breezes.
</P>
<P>
   Though Agassi is the returner supreme, Sampras knocked a
career-high 37 aces past him _ 17 in the fourth set, but down to
two in the fifth _ plus 46 service winners. But Agassi was serving
cleverly, moving the ball astutely, damaging Sampras with his
kicker and coming up with 13 aces and 17 service winners on less
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Agassi says, ``that when the match looked close
to the end in the fourth-set tie-breaker, it was actually close to
beginning for me. That's what got Pete. One second he's two points
away, and a couple of minutes later, he's lost his serve (for only
the second time) and is down, 2-0, in the fifth. That was a huge
momentum change.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I had to do was not make mistakes. Make him earn it in
the fourth set-breaker. I was a spectator (7-0) in the first
tie-breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras slashed a forehand for a mini-break to 4-3, but Agassi
snatched it back to 4-4. Then Sampras hooked his 35th ace, an
astounding 120 m.p.h. second ball to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept raising the stakes,'' Agassi says. ``I'm two points
from gone, so I have to make no mistakes, make sure on my serve.''
Which he did with a pair of service winners to 5-5 and 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   A toenail-painting backhand return that set up a backhand passer
suddenly punctured Sampras for the set. Agassi gave forth a leonine
growl that could be heard above the raging crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would have suspected that Sampras, 8-0 in five-set
matches here, was through. Nevertheless, he was, collapsed by
Agassi's controlled abstinence from blunders: a mere 19 unforced
errors to Sampras's 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're pushed to the limit, and then dig for some more .
. . well, that's where I am now,'' Agassi says, smiling. He still
has either the defending champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov or the pesky
Swede Magnus Norman to contend with for first prize Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But he had survived the evening's bombing _ by Sampras and a
flock of seagulls. ``I didn't mind them flying over, but then they
decided to drop me a few presents.'' Sampras fans, maybe. After
taking a towel from a ball boy and mopping up the deposits, Agassi
continued to mop up Sampras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
