<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLARE-UP AT `FEVER'  
 POPULAR FARE, NO FUSS 
WITTY AND WITCHY 
ACTION ON THE BOARD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actors Equity, the union of actors and stage managers, was
investigating an increasingly tense backstage scene at ``Saturday
Night Fever'' this week, a situation apparently triggered by a
dismissal of the stage manager. That move has sparked bad blood
between some in the cast and management, as well as the resignation
of three assistant stage managers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   What set off the dispute seems surprisingly minor. In
mid-December, the musical's cast sent a letter to Robert Stigwood,
the show's lead producer, about the quality of the souvenir
program. Among the complaints were several captions in which cast
members' names had been omitted and several images that were
described as poorly reproduced. These oversights and others, the
letter pointed out, violated the Equity contract and should be
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cast signed the letter, as did Perry Cline, the
production stage manager. The letter was delivered to Stigwood at
Barton Manor, his estate on the Isle of Wight in England, around
Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent back to the cast and posted on the call board,
Stigwood said he thought the criticism was misdirected as well as
poorly timed. (His return letter stated: ``I much rather would have
heard Happy Christmas.'')
</P>
<P>
   Company members said that they thought that was the end of the
issue until early this month, when word leaked out that Cline had
been dismissed. This action infuriated some cast members, who
called the move a clear retaliation against Cline. ``He signed it,
so he got fired,'' said one cast member. ``They believed he
co-wrote it or wrote it, which wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Manny Kladitis, the show's associate producer and general
manager, disputed this account, saying that Cline's departure was a
``mutual decision'' and that there was no connection between the
letter and the decision to change stage managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage manager is not being dismissed because of the
letter,'' Kladitis said. ``I think everybody's misunderstanding
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Eisenberg, the union's executive director, said Thursday
that the union was investigating the situation and would be meeting
with the company Friday. In general, cases of this sort result in
severance packages for the fired individuals but rarely
reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through a spokesman, Stigwood said Thursday that
Cline's dismissal did not have to do with his signing of the letter
and added that disputes between cast and management were
commonplace in Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fever,'' which opened in October at the Minskoff Theater, was
the second-highest grossing show on Broadway last week.
</P>
<P>
   Cline, a respected stage manager with a dozen Broadway shows to
his credit, is still on the show but is expected to leave next
month. He did not return calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, cast members said the incident has soured
relations between the company and the show's management. ``It's
horrible,'' one cast member said of the mood backstage. ``Everyone
thinks it's completely unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Kladitis, however, said the discontent was news to him. ``No one
in the company has discussed this with me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Popular Fare, No Fuss
</P>
<P>
   It may not have the name recognition of ``The Vagina
Monologues'' or the name deconstruction of ``Fuddy Meers,'' but
``Dinner With Friends'' has quietly become one of off-Broadway's
more solid hits.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, the Donald Margulies comedy, at the Variety
Arts Theater in the East Village, has been regularly selling more
than $100,000 in tickets a week, and during the first week this
month, the figure topped $175,000. All of which has led to an
advance of about $300,000, an enviable figure for a 499-seat
theater.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which opened on Nov. 4, is about the repercussions on
the lives of two couples when one of those couples splits up. It
received favorable reviews but has maintained a relatively low
profile, with no marquee stars but strong word of mouth. Producers,
who invested $660,000 in the production, said Thursday that they
expected to recoup their investment by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Witty and Witchy
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Edward Hibbert earned good reviews at the Long
Wharf Theater in New Haven for doing a role that few actors tackle,
that of Lady Bracknell, the bon-mot-tossing matron at the heart of
Oscar Wilde's ``Importance of Being Earnest.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hibbert is back as a missus. Beginning April 1, he will be
appearing as Tartagliona, the witchy grandmother in ``The Green
Bird,'' Carlo Gozzi's 18th-century Italian fable at the Cort
Theater. He joins a cast that includes Kristine Nielsen, Derek
Smith and Andrew Weems.
</P>
<P>
   Action on the Board
</P>
<P>
   Last fall didn't work out exactly as Illeana Douglas thought it
might. After all, it was only a few months ago that the actress was
starring in ``Action,'' easily the most hyped television show of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Critics raved about her performance as Wendy, a wisened
streetwalker, but audiences didn't take to the show. It was
canceled last month.
</P>
<P>
   While the end of ``Action'' was sad for Ms. Douglas, it has
opened up a chance to do something she hadn't tried in years.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Feb. 18, Ms. Douglas will be heading an impressive
cast in ``The Moment When,'' a new play by James Lapine at
Playwrights Horizons. Rehearsals begin Friday, with a company that
includes Estelle Parsons, Kieran Culkin, Mark Ruffalo, and Arija
Bareikis.
</P>
<P>
   Known for her film work, Ms. Douglas trained and worked the
trenches of the New York theater world. She studied at the
Neighborhood Playhouse in the mid- 1980s, worked with the Naked
Angels theater company and performed ``very off-off Broadway.''
After directing three short films and playing smaller roles in
handful of films, she broke through in 1995 in ``To Die For,''
playing opposite a villainous Nicole Kidman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was making a joke yesterday that every theater I worked at
no longer exists,'' she said. ``I'm hoping for better luck this
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
