<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV01-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR YEARS AND NOTHING FOR JANE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tues., Feb. 1)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy news comes from Los Angeles where Sukie Miller has become
the proud possessor of a new kidney, courtesy of her second cousin
Cynthia. Recuperation has begun and the e-mail reports are all
upbeat. The friends are relieved and celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   But sad news comes from Sebastopol, Calif., where Jane Flood has
died waiting for a liver transplant. She'd been on the waiting list
for almost four years and watched others in her hepatitis C support
group get their livers, but Jane's blood type was harder to match.
</P>
<P>
   But damn, four years?
</P>
<P>
   We all know about the life-giving promise of organ transplants.
A person can have a vital organ stop on them but then get a new
one. Those kinds of miracles happen all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Sukie will probably go on to write another book, travel the
world, give workshops. Jane would have returned to teaching,
written more poems, gone hiking along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone gets her miracle and that's our fault because as a
society we're too busy, complacent or scared to donate. There's an
ongoing organ shortage in the United States. Yet it costs no time
or money to be a donor. You fill out a form, put a little sticker
on your driver's license and tell your family that you want your
organs to be available to someone else when you die. And then you
go on living.
</P>
<P>
   When you die you leave behind a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Sukie got her kidney from a living donor, which is possible with
kidneys. But many people also die waiting for kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   Jane had to wait for someone with the right blood type, a
healthy liver and a donor card to die in Northern California.
Friends say she never stopped believing that would happen.
Hospitalized with an infection, she told friends the day before she
died she needed to get stronger so she could get her liver.
</P>
<P>
   There's really no reason not to agree to be a donor. Most
religions don't seem to have a problem with it. Some people seem to
worry that if they're a known donor and are critically injured some
ghoul in the ER is going to snatch their liver or other valuable
parts rather than patch them up. But that doesn't seem to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Jane used to say that people resist becoming a donor because
they don't like to think about their own deaths.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of things can happen between now and death which might
have us hope that someone else had been more generous than
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   These things kind of creep up on people. This time last year
Sukie hadn't a clue her kidneys were in bad shape. A routine blood
test last spring showed she had advanced kidney disease and her
doctor said she better start thinking dialysis or transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Jane believed she was likely infected with hepatitis C 30 years
ago, but it only hit her so she knew it five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So, something could be cooking in our bodies right now that
someday will eat away at one of our organs. One of the replaceable
ones. We may be waiting to be transplanted long before we're doing
the donating.
</P>
<P>
   Jane's friend Betty Nudelman, who had a successful liver
transplant years ago, is pretty angry about losing Jane. She thinks
it ought to be policy that no one gets a replacement organ unless
they themselves have signed a donor card.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't the drug companies that make money on the very
expensive immunosuppressive drugs that every transplant patient
takes for life sponsor public service campaigns?
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be great if organ donation became the American thing
to do, so popular and widely presumed that only people who felt
otherwise needed to carry cards?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a great way to start out the century. Create a legacy and
get your karma aligned at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
