<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8462 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BLACKGIRL30-COX     01-27 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BLACKGIRL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seeking the artist within in the City of Light
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By Valerie Boyd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shay Youngblood's second novel is as stimulating as a stroll
down the Champs Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia-born author's first novel, 1997's ``Soul Kiss,'' was
an exquisite and erotic story of a girl's sexual and sensual coming
of age. Full of the same lush language, ``Black Girl in Paris'' is
also a coming-of-age story, but it explores a different kind of
maturation _ that of an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Walking in the footsteps of iconic figures such as Josephine
Baker, Langston Hughes and James Baldwin, 26-year-old Eden arrives
in Paris in 1986 with two years' worth of nearly forgotten college
French in her head and a few dollars pressed into the soles of her
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to be a writer and, like others before her, believes
Paris will teach her how: ``I was making a map of the world. In
ancient times maps were made to help people find food, water, and
the way back home,'' Youngblood writes in Eden's diarylike,
intimate voice. ``I needed a map to help me find love and language,
and since one didn't exist, I'd have to invent one following the
trails and signs left by other travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Paris that Eden finds, however, is not quite the Paris of
Baldwin's youth, nor the city of her dreams. It is a potential
paradise tarnished by terrorism. Within a few days of her arrival,
four explosions kill several people and wound hundreds. But she is
undaunted. Born in Birmingham, she is no stranger to terrorism:
``During that time the city was nicknamed Bombingham. When the four
little girls were killed by a segregationist's bomb at church one
Sunday morning in 1963, I had just started to write my name,'' she
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   What frightens the grown-up Eden more than terrorists' bombs is
the prospect of poverty driving her home before she can meet
Baldwin, the legendary African-American essayist, novelist and
playwright rumored to be living in France. (Youngblood's research
is accurate: Baldwin spent his final years in France, before his
death in December 1987.) To avoid this fate, she does stints as an
au pair, an artist's model, a poet's helper and, occasionally, a
thief pilfering a meal. She even spends a night as a blues singer,
urged on by her white, jazz-playing boyfriend:
</P>
<P>
   ``Music drifted above the smoke and laughter and loud talk in
the tiny bar. A dozen tables were heavy with elbows, strong
cigarettes, and booze,'' Eden tells us in you-are-there detail.
``My short, natural hair was hidden under a straight black wig with
bangs. The fragrant white flower tucked behind my left ear.
Red-painted lips, gold dust at the corners of my eyes, pearls of
sweat on the tip of my nose. I hoped the makeup hid my fear. My
legs atop the silver high heels suddenly felt weak, but then I took
a deep breath and closed my eyes. I was back in Georgia in a small
roadside juke joint. I opened my mouth again, and Billie Holiday
came out. ... I was crying when the music stopped. The audience was
wild with appreciation, clapping, whistling, and cheering. I closed
my eyes and clicked my heels together, part of me wishing I was
home.''
</P>
<P>
   This nod to ``The Wizard of Oz'' (or its African-American
update, ``The Wiz'') is not accidental. Eden's search is much like
Dorothy's: She is looking for her personal wizard, her very own
muse embodied as Baldwin _ and she must find him to know that what
she's truly looking for is already within.
</P>
<P>
   In a not-always-linear narrative that includes a few recipes and
primer-type lists (``How to Look at Art,'' ``How to Be an Au
Pair''), Youngblood introduces several supporting characters who
serve as Eden's guides in her search for Baldwin _ and in her
deeper quest for the writer within. These characters and the
episodic structure of the novel are among the novel's few
weaknesses _ yet, ultimately, among its many strengths. On one
hand, a reader might wish for Eden to slow down as she moves
through other characters' lives, to let Youngblood apply her
considerable character-development skills to making these
supporting players more memorable.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Youngblood seems to say, who cares about
them? She wants you to focus on Eden, whose quest for the artist
within is her most important _ and most daring _ adventure. And
it's a testament to Youngblood's talent that Eden's inner adventure
is as riveting as any exploit in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Black Girl in Paris. By Shay Youngblood. Riverhead Books.
$23.95. 224 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A different kind of coming-of-age tale.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Boyd, an editor at The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, is
working on a biography of Zora Neale Hurston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
