<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8463 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MIKELEIGH28-COX     01-27 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIKELEIGH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director takes fresh look at Gilbert and Sullivan
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last thing that would likely pop into moviegoers' minds
while watching ``Topsy-Turvy,'' English director Mike Leigh's new,
opulent costume tale of comic opera legends Gilbert and Sullivan,
is a vision from ``Naked.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``Topsy-Turvy,'' was recently named best picture of
the year by the New York Film Critics Circle, is an ornate
depiction of 19th-century artistic whimsy that includes a detailed,
highbrow staging of ``The Mikado.'' The decidedly seedier
``Naked,'' which Leigh directed to critical acclaim in 1993, kicks
off with its brilliant and deeply disturbed modern-day main
character raping a crying woman in a damp, dark alley.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something about ``Topsy-Turvy'' that establishes a
twisted connection not only to ``Naked,'' but to ``Secrets &AMP; Lies''
and just about every other Leigh film. They are each unrelenting in
the precision with which they hone in on the intelligence, quirks,
motivations, oppressions, infatuations and psychological damage
inherent in their main characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I wanted to do _ to deal with Gilbert and Sullivan
in that way,'' says Leigh, 56. ``The only real separation is the
culture (all those characters) are in. You really don't have to
scrape away more than the finished surface of `Topsy-Turvy' and
it's a Mike Leigh film.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Leigh is in New York, recovering from jet lag. He's
flown from England to accept the New York critics award for
``Topsy-Turvy'' and work in a visit with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, all I did was watch a bit of TV and drink from the
mini-bar,'' he says. ``That's what we call getting over jet lag.
Tonight I'll have dinner with friends at their house in Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he know what they'll cook?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. But they're good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking by telephone, Leigh discussed not only why he decided to
make a two-hour-and-39-minute film about W.S. Gilbert and Arthur
Sullivan, but how he first became interested in movies and the
genesis of the unique process he uses to develop his art.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's kind of surprising to see you tackle a subject like
Gilbert and Sullivan. Why pick them?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wanted to do a period film in the same way I approach a
modern story. And a film about us: people who do popular
entertainment seriously. I was attracted by the idea of taking what
would seem kind of a chocolate-box subject and subverting it and
taking it seriously as a real working world. And I grew up in
Manchester in the '40s and '50s, and it maintains this Victorian
look and feel. The houses, the schools and the culture that just
hangs in the air. So, in effect, I grew up with Gilbert and
Sullivan. They've always been there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How true is your film to what happened in their relationship
and the first staging of ``Mikado''?
</P>
<P>
   A: In broad terms, the general narrative is accurate. Gilbert
did originally cut that famous song in the dress rehearsal, and the
chorus did go to him in a posse. But what they actually said (we
don't know).
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert had already thought of ``Mikado'' before he went to the
Japanese exposition. There are all kinds of small details that are
not true. What I was concerned about was that these two creative
forces got stuck. Their partnership was jeopardized. We also went
to great lengths to tackle the language. That to me had to be
accurate. I had my researcher forever with me with a trolley of
literature.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were you concerned much about the length of the film?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was supposed to be shorter. Films are normally expected to
be shorter. It seems to me that this movie is what it should be.
There were a few battles about it. It just takes all that time to
deal with what we were trying to get across. I don't think people
will ultimately think it's too long. If I thought it was tedious, I
would have hacked it to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This film has a rather unique presentation of the inventions
of the time: the telephone, the first fountain pen. I can't think
of another film that introduces inventions in such a way that they
are integral parts in revealing the characters' personalities.
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't either. That period was so rich in that sense.
Because of the way I'm able to explore these things and actors and
action, if you put it in a three-dimensional way, you come up with
those moments.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did you first get interested in movies?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the '40s and '50s when I was growing up, I went to the
movies as much as I possibly could. There were tiny cinemas in
Manchester. All showed two films. I saw loads and loads of films
that were American and British. None in foreign languages. Then in
the '60s, I was exposed to more world cinema: Renoir, Kurasawa and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What films did you use as inspiration for ``Topsy-Turvy''?
</P>
<P>
   A: There were obviously films and things lurking in the back of
my mind. ``Les Enfants du Paradis.'' Jean Renoir. We also looked at
a load of period films and a huge amount of historic footage shot
in 1896 through 1901. It was still very useful. Another film that
we did look at was 1953's very British ``The Story of Gilbert and
Sullivan.'' Obviously, that was a film this film attempts not to be
like.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read about the life drawing class where you had this
flash that formed how you work _ the months-long rehearsals, the
preliminary collaborations, all of it leading to a script and
shooting. What happened in that life drawing class that led to the
flash of inspiration?
</P>
<P>
   A: It wasn't one particular thing. What I experienced as an art
student was that I became aware of something I hadn't experienced
before. What we experienced (in that class) was looking at the real
world. In an English drama school, you didn't look at the real
world. It didn't relate to the street but regurgitated plays and
didn't actually deal with who are these people and what are they
about. ... It was a revelation in the kind of liberating thing it
was to be an art student. There we were asked to investigate and
deal with realities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How intense were the ``Topsy-Turvy'' rehearsals?
</P>
<P>
   A: We had five weeks to do all the things in the theater, in a
heat wave. All these people were wearing terribly hot kimonos and
wigs and makeup and things. I have to say, though, those are merely
the ordinary stuff of filmmaking. The preparation, rehearsing for
seven months, all the rehearsals and improvisations and working
with historical background. All of that was what was difficult and
hard. And not really traumatic were the contemporary films that I
normally do. We can take it for granted we know about the world
we're in. The minute you're in the late 19th century, no matter how
recent it seems, you have to have really researched it. Every
detail of the time period is this huge worm you have to get your
head around.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
