<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SUNDANCE30-COX     01-27 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cell phone ultimate Sundance star
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ There he is. You can spot him just to the
right of the trees at the top of the slope, gliding on what must be
perfectly waxed skis atop powdery snow. He's the impeccable icon of
an entertainment industry gone perfectly out of whack: slicked-back
dark hair, black wraparound sunglasses, white turtleneck and one
hand cupping a cell phone to his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Call it frozen hydrophoning. It's what Hollywood does here every
year at the Sundance Film Festival. And every year, they say, it
just gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   Walk down Main Street on the way to a screening, make a call.
Nestle into a seat before the theater goes dark, make a call. Ride
the shuttle bus. Between bites at a sushi bar. Up in the lift, skis
dangling, en route to the highest slopes. That's three more calls.
</P>
<P>
   What's so important? Just listen to a few of the one-sided
conversations overheard on the street: ``There's all these cameras.
It's getting wild here.'' ``He's one of the big shots at BMI. He
told me to call him.'' ``Redford and I are good friends. We're like
brother and sister. It's great.'' ``Whatever, baby.'' ``That movie.
There was no way anybody was going to get into it. I just stayed on
the shuttle and kept going.'' ``James Spader called.'' Of course he
did.
</P>
<P>
   With so much cell-phoning here ``it reaches the point it's no
longer unusual,'' says Chuck Collins of Kennesaw's Digital
Projection Inc., who's here to set up equipment for the festival's
first major foray into projecting digital films on theater screens.
And he should know. He has a cell phone and a Motorola hand-held
radio to use while here. Which is what he's doing. Over and over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Redford's annual 10-day celebration of independent
movies, which ends today in this small, century-old silver mining
town nestled in the snow-dusted valley of Utah's Wasatch Range, is
many things. A celeb-filled frenzy (among this year's glitterati:
Ben Affleck, John Sayles, Heather Graham, Julianna Margulies, Danny
DeVito, Oliver Stone and Ethan Hawke). A movie lover's paradise of
112 films (the most persistent fan can watch six or more movies a
day). A nonstop movie industry networking party. And a sea of
wandering individuals _ at least 15,000 _ clad in enough black
leather to reupholster every den sofa in Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   Some who come here to see movies and people-watch strike
celebrity gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went skiing and saw Stanley Tucci on the slopes,'' says
George Nakos, 41, of Atlanta, an investment banker, vacationing
here with friend Michael Randman, 44, of Birmingham, a former
junior agent for the William Morris Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're movie buffs,'' Nakos says. They sat near Jodie Foster at
the first-night film, Tucci's ``Joe Gould's Secret.'' (Nakos'
verdict: ``It was no `Big Night.''') Also in the theater were
Redford and ``Gould'' star Ian Holm.
</P>
<P>
   The previous night Nakos and Randman ventured into Grappa, a
local upscale restaurant featuring a 2000 Sundance Film Festival
prix fixe menu. For $60 each they could dine on such dishes as
grape and Gorgonzola salad, wild mushroom soup and baked salmon
encrusted with horseradish and bread crumbs atop homemade
fettuccine. At a nearby table sat R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe, who
produced ``Spring Forward,'' one of 16 films in the festival's
noncompetitive American Spectrum category.
</P>
<P>
   With each day bringing more than 50 screenings of independent
movies, documentaries and shorts, the Sundance Film Festival is the
be-all, but not the end-all, of what's going on here.
</P>
<P>
   Several renegade mini-festivals have popped up in small pockets
throughout town. There's Slamdance (started in 1995 by four
filmmakers whose works were rejected by Sundance), No Dance,
SlamDunk, LapDance, Digi-
</P>
<P>
   Dance, Dances With Films and Son of Sam Dance. The latter
consists of a Toyota van roaming the town and screening films from
a projector atop its roof.
</P>
<P>
   You want independent? The No Dance crowd shuns publicists (or,
rather, often can't afford them) and pushes its own movies.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker Kaleo Quenzer, 27, of Memphis has perched himself on
Main Street with a cardboard sign that reads, ``Will work for
distribution.'' He's promoting the $20,000 ``Central Garden,'' the
movie he wrote and directed and submitted to No Dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this to make people laugh and to get attention,''
Quenzer says. ``We're real low-budget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke. It's just so busy,'' says Miranda Price, 20, of
Salt Lake City, who commutes the 40-minute drive here to run the
Starbucks espresso machine on Main Street for a continuous line of
customers from 7 a.m. to 9:30 p.m. weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my third year, and it gets busier every year,'' she
says, whipping up another tall latte. ``The Sundance crowd is so
uptight. They're not as friendly. We're just so laid-back here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the tips?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they're very fair,'' she says. ``In that way, they're very
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
