<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPER-MATTHEWS-NY     01-27 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-MATTHEWS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 XXXIV ISN'T OLD FOR HIM: MATTHEWS REACHES SUPER BOWL IN HIS 17th(bl) 
 By DOUG FERNANDES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tennessee's Bruce Matthews is so old ...
</P>
<P>
   How old is he?
</P>
<P>
   He's so old that he played at the University of Southern
California with his current head coach, Jeff Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have much to say my freshman year,'' Matthews said.
``He always seemed a studious guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He's so old that Titan rookie guard Zach Piller was 7 years old
when Matthews went through his first training camp with the
then-Houston Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even really imagine that,'' Piller said.
</P>
<P>
   He's so old that he once blocked for Earl Campbell and knows, at
38, that Father Time is closing in on the tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that the end is very near for me,'' Matthews
said. ``But I guess I'm too selfish to set a date.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be Monday, the day after he makes the first Super Bowl
appearance of his glorious 17-year career. He signed a four-year
deal with the Titans in the off-season. Matthews will be 41 if he
fulfills the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing. In a league where the average career lasts four years,
Matthews is a 6-foot-5, 305-pound anomaly. He's as reliable as the
sun. He's never missed a game because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   He shines brightly too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt I understand the only reason I'm here is
because God just blessed me with this body and the desire to play
this game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Health and desire aside, a player doesn't play 17 seasons
without a large dose of skill. This season, Matthews earned his
12th Pro Bowl berth.
</P>
<P>
   In his time with the Oilers/Titans, he has played at least one
season at each of the five offensive line positions. Matthews has
been named to eight Pro Bowls at guard, four at center.
</P>
<P>
   This season he shattered ex-Ram Jackie Slater's record for most
games played by an offensive lineman in NFL history (259.) He's
played in 200 consecutive games, the longest current streak in the
league. He's protected 14 different quarterbacks, opened holes for
24 different running backs.
</P>
<P>
   But mere numbers don't reflect the true value of Matthews.
That's best expressed by the people who have witnessed his
exemplary performances over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you say?'' said Titans general manager Floyd Reese.
``I don't know what to say. Every year I try to think of something
that can describe what he's done. I can't. He just plays, plays at
the top level, comes back every year and does it again. That's
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an icon around here,'' fullback Lorenzo Neal said. ``So,
no, I can't describe what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews' 20-something teammates have the same problem. Many
can't believe what he's done. Or whom he's done it with.
</P>
<P>
   ``They read the press guide,'' Matthews said, ``and they come up
to me and their jaws are hanging and it's like, `You played with
coach Fisher?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, so what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He played?''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher believes he knows why Matthews remains a powerful force
along the Titans' offensive line, able to control defensive linemen
15 years his junior. Love of the game aside, Fisher said it's
Matthews knowing exactly what he's doing every moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very instinctive,'' Fisher said. ``He never puts himself
in an awkward position where he's risking injury. He understands
what's going on around him and he sees things very well.''
</P>
<P>
   He's soaking it all in this week. Matthews knows better than
most that reaching the Super Bowl is anything but a birthright. He
always believed an appearance in the NFL's biggest game wasn't
needed to validate his career.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after witnessing the significance placed on the game,
he knows his career wouldn't have been complete without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess without being here I wouldn't have realized what a
great loss it would have been if I had never been here,'' Matthews
said. ``There would have been a void in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was one of the first people to congratulate him
because I feel for him,'' wide receiver Kevin Dyson said. ``I told
him, `I don't know if I could have waited 17 years.' I'm happy for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   So is his brother, Clay Matthews. It appears longevity is part
of the family makeup. Clay played 19 years at linebacker in the
NFL. As you might expect, the two brothers were competitive growing
up.
</P>
<P>
   One game could have ended both of their dreams' of reaching the
NFL. It was a dangerous version of baseball with a 2-by-4 and a
dart. One Matthews brother swung the board, the other threw the
dart. A hit was recorded when the hitter got the dart to stick in
the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the first beanball,'' Bruce said, ``and that game was
retired by our parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce's dad, Clay Sr., was a wrestler at Georgia Tech and is in
the school's athletic Hall of Fame. He convinced Bruce to wrestle
in high school, saying it would help him on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the ninth and 10th grade, we used to get on the
living room floor,'' he said. ``He inflicted more injuries on me
than anyone on the wrestling team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Matthews knows the reason he's in Atlanta. For some time,
he didn't quite believe his Titans, which he calls an ordinary team
performing extraordinary things, belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took awhile to think, `Hey, we're a Super Bowl team,''' he
said. ``But now that we're here, it's like, `Why not? Let's go out
and win this thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Fernandes writes for The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald Tribune,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
