<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SAFRICAN-AGENTS30-COX     01-27 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICAN-AGENTS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts' suggestions for South Africa
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   South Africa, here we come.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Monday, Delta Air Lines and South African Airways will
offer nonstop, code-shared service from Hartsfield International
Airport to Johannesburg, with alternating daily service to Cape
Town.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, South African Airways had teamed with American
Airlines for flights out of Miami and New York. Monday, Delta takes
over for American and the Miami service will be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The move is designed to make the flights much more accessible _
Delta is the world's most-flown airline, connecting to 365 cities
in 60 countries. South African and Delta are offering an
introductory deal of $747 round trip to Cape Town and Johannesburg
for departures through March. You must stay from three to 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's easier for Atlantans, and indeed most other
Americans, to travel to South Africa, what do you do when you get
there? We asked two local experts _ travel agents who specialize in
excursions to southern Africa _ to suggest the best trips for
animal lovers, sightseers, newlyweds, senior citizens and families.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Udwin, a native of Zimbabwe, runs the north Atlanta agency
Mushinda (a Shona term meaning ``personal attendant to the king'')
with her husband, Leon. Robert Goolsby is the co-founder of the
Sandy Springs agency S. A. Adventures. Here are their suggestions
(prices converted from South African rands to U.S. dollars):
</P>
<P>
   GAME
</P>
<P>
   VIEWING
</P>
<P>
   Udwin: Kruger National Park is popular, but I prefer to send my
clients to more secluded camps such as Phinda, which is on a
private game reserve in Zululand on the Indian Ocean. There are
regular leopard sightings, and the ecosystem in this region allows
for a vastly different game-viewing experience. Phinda has
beautifully decorated bungalows with private showers, toilets and
baths. There's even a little swimming pool. One day we came back
from a game drive and there was a hippo in the pool. We didn't go
swimming that day. (Cost: $300-$350 a day.)
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby: Kruger National Park is far and away the best-known of
the 16 national parks in South Africa. It's about the size of
Massachusetts and is home to great numbers of amphibians, reptiles
and birds as well as 147 species of mammals, including the big
five: elephants, rhinos, cape buffaloes, lions and leopards.
Accommodations in the park range from tents to luxury guest houses.
(Cost for a three-day stay: about $647.)
</P>
<P>
   SIGHTSEEING
</P>
<P>
   Udwin: Cape Town, which is without a doubt one of the most
beautiful cities in the world, is definitely worth a visit. From
here, private guides may take you on a day trip to the wine
district, about 45 minutes outside the city. The stately Cape Dutch
estates are magnificent. Another guided excursion takes visitors
along the awesome coastline to Cape Point. From here you can see
the confluence of the Atlantic and Indian oceans. (Guided tours are
about $100.)
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby: No visit to Cape Town would be complete without a cable
car ride to the top of Table Mountain, which rises out of the
center of the city. The cable car rotates around a spindle, so you
don't have to fight to get a good view. From the top, you can see
all of Cape Town and the tip of Cape Point. To add a bit of poetry,
when the clouds come down, the locals say that the mountain has its
tablecloth. (Cable car rides are about $10.)
</P>
<P>
   NEWLYWEDS
</P>
<P>
   Udwin: Honeymooners usually want to experience all Africa has to
offer and still have their romance and privacy. The staff at many
lodges and camps in the region goes out of its way to ensure that
this is a trip of a lifetime. For example, at Barker's Lodge in
Zimbabwe, my clients walked into their cottage to find rose petals
strewn from the door to the bed with a bottle of champagne nestled
among the pillows. (Barker's rates are about $100 a day.)
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby: One of the big attractions for honeymooners in Cape
Town is the Kirstenbosch National Botanical Gardens on the eastern
slope of Table Mountain. More than 6,000 species of plants are
here, including hundreds of varieties of protea, a flower
indigenous to South Africa. The protea blossoms range from the size
of your thumb to big enough to hold in both hands. (Entrance fee:
about $1.75.)
</P>
<P>
   SENIOR CITIZENS
</P>
<P>
   Udwin: A South African safari is the ideal vacation for anyone
who can ride in a Land Rover. Unlike in east Africa, all safaris
are in open vehicles (no sides), which afford a 360-degree
panorama. Whether traveling on their own or in large groups, all
our clients are met and escorted. Most camps cater to the dietary
requirements of the individual. Also, while it's a necessity to
take anti-malaria medication, no shots or other inoculations are
required. ($300-$350 a day.)
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby: A three-day tour from Cape Town to Pretoria on Rovos
Rail, a vintage train, has wide appeal for senior citizens. Many of
them remember trains like this from their childhood _ the dining
car was built in the 1920s. When you're inside the train, it's
elegant like the Orient Express except each cabin has its own
bathroom. The easy tour pace includes a stop at the diamond mines
in Kimberly. ($1,135 per person).
</P>
<P>
   FAMILIES
</P>
<P>
   Udwin: We first took our children on safari when they were 7 and
10. Not once did they moan or ask for TV. They were absolutely
enthralled, as were we all. Many of the camps will not accept
children under 12. For those that do not, we have alternatives such
as setting up private tented camps. For more of a resort
atmosphere, I recommend the Palace of the Lost City. This
fantastical hotel was built to resemble an ancient African palace.
No expense has been spared and the results are breathtaking. It is
part of a huge entertainment and resort complex in the middle of
the dry bushveld. ($350 a night for standard room to $3,500 a night
for full-service suite.)
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby: Our Makutsi Safari Farm package offers a complete tour
of South Africa. On the farm, which lies between the Drakensberg
Mountains and Kruger National Park, you can see jackals, antelopes,
giraffes, crocodiles and rhinos. But besides game viewing, the tour
visits tribal villages, a cheetah farm and natural sights such as
God's Window, the cliff seen in the movie ``The Gods Must Be
Crazy.'' The cost for seven days and six nights includes airfare
and works out to be fairly inexpensive for families. ($1,587 per
person.)
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   WHEN TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Game viewing in South Africa is best in May and June, says Judy
Udwin. ``That is their winter, and it's a dry season. The animals
are looking for water, so they come out to the watering holes.''
However, Udwin notes, Cape Town can be cold and rainy then, so for
touring the city and relaxing on such beaches as Muizenberg and
Simonstown, she suggests going during the summer _ December through
March.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mushinda, 404-843-0046.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  S.A. Adventures, 404-851-9744.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Delta Air Lines international reservations, 1-800-241-4141 or
</P>
<P>
   www.delta-air.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  South African Tourism Board, 1-800-782-9772 or www.satour.org.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
