<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8473 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS30-COX     01-27 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Sanctuary' bears stark witness to unthinkable dark era
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The noose abruptly tightens and the neck snaps, tilting
uselessly to one side. Its oxygen cut off, the heart goes into the
frantic arrhythmia called fibrillation, and within seconds is
still. The bowels loosen.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd erupts in frenzied satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   On the shoulders of parents, children consume it all, a
whoop-it-up, public spectacle often accompanied by a barbecue
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   One 9-year-old, his appetite whetted, wanted more. ``I have seen
a man hanged,'' he told his mother; ``now I wish I could see one
burned.''
</P>
<P>
   At a particular time in the history of this country _ in the
late 19th century and well into the 20th _ he would have had
opportunity aplenty. Two or three people were lynched or burned at
a stake every week, most of them in the South, most of them black.
</P>
<P>
   The facts themselves are well-known, at least among scholars and
anyone who cares to look into the matter. What freezes the
attention is the sight of it: human beings dangling from trees,
lamp poles and bridges, while a crowd gazes at the contorted forms
in glassy-eyed glee.
</P>
<P>
   Few people today have ever seen such a sight; few people, at one
time, had never seen it.
</P>
<P>
   To see it in photographic retrospective is to look not so much
at the dead as the living _ those who thrilled to see someone
stripped bare, bullwhipped and put to death in whatever macabre
manner suited the audience. The dead are only mutilated corpses
that have to be disposed of.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who opens ``Without Sanctuary: Lynching Photography
in America,'' an extraordinarily impressive documentary of American
vengeance and barbarism, agonizing death induces a sucking in of
breath, only to be followed by somber contemplation of the pleasure
it brought spectators _ ``lingering in the woods, circling after
the kill,'' as James Allen writes.
</P>
<P>
   Americans don't like to know the dark side of their history;
some would deny there ever was a dark side. But it is there, and
the period photos that Allen, an Atlanta antiques dealer, collected
are the palpable proof. Lynching was not an aberration but a way of
life supported in pulpits, in the offices of governors, on the
editorial pages of leading newspapers. If it was not exclusively a
Southern way of life, nowhere did it flourish as in the South. And
if it was not directed exclusively at African-Americans, they were
disproportionately its victims. As one black man said, ``We always
in season.''
</P>
<P>
   Shame for sale
</P>
<P>
   Allen calls himself a picker, a collector of quotidian odds and
ends. He searches out the yellowed scraps of news and salutation
that end up in the bottom of a drawer _ postcards, for example _
and sells them to people for whom such refuse has curious value.
``In America,'' he writes in an eloquent afterword, ``everything is
for sale, even a national shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, another dealer called Allen to say he had
come across, in an old roll-top desk in Macon, something that might
interest him. ``Until I came upon a postcard of a lynching,'' Allen
writes, ``postcards seemed trivial to msshapen Rubber-maid products
might seem now.''
</P>
<P>
   The postcard was a photograph of Leo Frank, the Jewish factory
worker accused of murdering a young woman and hanged by a mob in
Marietta in 1915. Soon afterward, Allen came upon another such
postcard, this one of a young black girl dangling from a tree. Now
he was interested, and he began calling other dealers and even set
up a Web site (www.willbuy.com). With the financial help of his
friend John Spencer Littlefield, he paid as little as $15 and as
much as $30,000 for postcards and other records that today are on
deposit in the special collections department at the Robert W.
Woodruff Library at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Sanctuary'' reproduces 98 images from the
Allen/Littlefield Collection, along with a foreword by U.S. Rep.
John Lewis (D-Ga.), Allen's afterword and essays by the Pulitzer
Prize-winning historian Leon Litwack and Hilton Als, a writer for
The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   All of these are, in their different ways, powerful responses to
what can be seen with the eye. But it is the pictures that speak
most powerfully.
</P>
<P>
   When the townsfolk found the right tree for John Richards, they
left his shirt on but pulled his trousers below his crotch. It was
1916, in Goldsboro, N.C. Richards' hands are tied behind his back
and his muscular black butt is hard against the bark. From the
bottom of his trousers, his toes _ once the stubby toes of an
infant _ protrude. His executioners have his pine coffin open and
ready. Their faces wear grins of satisfied competence, a signal
from which bystanders take heart.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Frank Embree, were not dispatched with such swift
mercy. Unclothed and handcuffed, Embree was stood before the
citizenry of Fayette, Mo., in 1899, the skin on his legs and back
blistered and ripped open from repeated whip lashes. A camera
catches him eye-to-eye. His expression is without hope but also
without pity. Two images later, Frank Embree hangs from a tree, the
same eyes open but lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   Grim as these pictures are, the events they document once were
spectator events.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a Sunday afternoon, April 23, 1899,'' Litwack writes,
``more than 2,000 white Georgians, some of them arriving from
Atlanta on a special excursion train, assembled near the town of
Newnan to witness the execution of Sam Hose, a black Georgian.''
</P>
<P>
   Hose was chained and slathered with oil. Wood soaked in kerosene
was stacked around him. Before the torch was applied, fingers, ears
and genitals were cut off _ souvenirs of the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Captured on film
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, lynchings and public burnings became
something to which people brought their cameras, still a
comparatively new gadget for most Americans. The open use of
cameras testified to an interest in memorializing the occasion.
``Not only did photographers capture the execution itself,''
Litwack writes, ``but also the carnival-like atmosphere and the
expectant mood of the crowd, as in the lynching of Thomas Brooks in
Fayette County, Tenn., in 1915.'' Litwack quotes a contemporary
report:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of kodaks clicked all morning at the scene of the
lynching. People in automobiles and carriages came from miles
around to view the corpse dangling from the end of a rope. ...
Picture card photographers installed a portable printing plant at
the bridge and reaped a harvest in selling postcards showing a
photograph of the lynched Negro. Women and children were there by
the score. At a number of country schools the day's routine was
delayed until boy and girl pupils could get back from viewing the
lynched man.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1890s, Litwack writes, 139 people were lynched each year.
Others were burned alive. Three-quarters of the victims were black.
The number of lynchings and burnings declined in the next decade,
``but the percentage of black victims rose to 90 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, there is something predictable to the eye in seeing
the stripped figure, brown shoulders sloped, arms bound in cuffs.
But in an odd way there is something ghostlike about seeing a
victim such as John Holmes, a white man hanged in San Jose, Calif.,
as late as 1933. He hangs naked 3 or 4 feet over the bowler hats of
spectators, pale as putty, almost like a rag doll that had never
breathed.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is what one takes away from ``Without
Sanctuary'': the extinguishing of life, and the enjoyment in doing
so. So exuberant is that enjoyment that on occasion it denied life
even to the unborn. In Valdosta in 1918, Mary Turner, eight months
pregnant, was hanged upside down from a tree for what The
Associated Press called ``unwise remarks'' about the execution of
her husband.
</P>
<P>
   In their ``indignant mood,'' the AP reported, the people ``took
exception to her remarks, as well as to her attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   As she hanged by her ankles, someone ripped her belly open with
a knife used for splitting hogs. Her infant fell from her womb and
cried briefly.
</P>
<P>
   A man ended its cries with his heel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Without Sanctuary: Lynching Photography in America. Text by
James Allen, Hilton Als, U.S. Rep. John Lewis and Leon F. Litwack.
Twin Palms Publishers. $60. 209 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
