<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SPOLETO30-COX     01-27 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old head: Spoleto exercises esoteric lineup in `spa for the
mind'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verdi's ``Aida'' will be there _ as a marionette show. Sweden's
Cullberg Ballet will be there _ with a darkly beautiful,
controversial ``Swan Lake.'' ``Mother Courage'' will be there _
with a diminutive actress in the monumental Brecht role. And Joel
Shapiro's angular sculptures will be there _ dancing across the
18th-century gardens of Middleton Place.
</P>
<P>
   In what looks like one of its more esoteric lineups in recent
memory, Spoleto Festival USA has announced the $6.2 million event
planned for May 26-June 11 in the historic city of Charleston, S.C.
The 17 days of opera, dance, theater, music and visual arts will
showcase new productions of Verdi's ``Luisa Miller'' and jazz
composer Diedre Murray's ``Running Man''; modern dance by Susan
Marshall and Bill T. Jones; and a bigger-than-usual jazz roster,
including Chick Corea and Gary Burton, pianist Fred Hersch and
vocalist Dianne Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best metaphor is that it's going to be like a spa for the
mind,'' says general director Nigel Redden. ``You end up doing a
whole bunch of exercises ... and it's sort of wonderful finding
these muscles that one had forgotten existed.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, opera _ and the chamber music series led by
impresario Charles Wadsworth _ will be major draws.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``Luisa Miller,'' Spoleto is importing a Welsh National
Opera production of Gluck's ``Iphigenie en Tauride,'' to be
directed by Spoleto opera and orchestra leader Steven Sloane, who
recently announced that he won't be renewing his contract beyond
the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Redden says the jazz opera ``Running Man,'' about a young boy
who has lost his way in life, is ``a story that you feel that you
read about in the newspaper all the time.'' Rounding out the opera
program is ``The Silver River,'' based on the ancient Chinese
legend about the creation of night and day. It was composed by
Bright Sheng, with libretto by Tony Award winner David Henry Hwang
(``M. Butterfly'').
</P>
<P>
   If, as in Redden's words, the Spoleto experience is like
``walking a tightrope,'' then this year it is even more so.
``Filao,'' by the French company Les Colporteurs, employs trapeze
artists, dancers and musicians in a surreal circus adaptation of
the Italo Calvino novel ``The Baron in the Trees,'' about a young
man who refuses to come down from his perch in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the nouvelle cirque (``new circus'') is anything like
the popular Cirque du Soleil, Redden says: ``If Cirque du Soleil is
Broadway, then this is off-Broadway. It doesn't have the glitz of
Cirque du Soleil, and people shouldn't expect that kind of smoke
and lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he says, Cullberg Ballet's ``Swan Lake'' is nothing
like Matthew Bourne's theatrical, mostly male version that played
Broadway last year. Though wildly contemporary, with emaciated
figures wearing stockings over their heads, the Cullberg telling is
faithful in spirit to the Petipa original. It is about dance. But
Redden warns: ``You have to come to it with an open mind. You can't
come expecting the `Swan Lake' you saw at American Ballet Theatre
several years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Aida'' puppet show is by Italy's Compagnia Carlo Colla e
Figli, which will also be doing Jules Verne's ``Around the World in
80 Days,'' with 300 puppets and some of the original music and sets
from the company's 1896 production.
</P>
<P>
   This season's only straight theater production will be ``Mother
Courage and Her Children,'' from London's Shared Experience
Theatre. Playing the title role will be Kathryn Hunter, whose
outsized mannerisms (and cigarette holder) mesmerized Spoleto-goers
who saw Theatre de Complicite's ``The Visit'' in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The singer Kurt Elling will open the jazz series at the Cistern,
and guitarist Bill Frisell will bring his fusion sound to the
Cistern and Kiawah Island Resort. Corea will be jamming with
vibraphonist and old pal Burton before breaking out into a set with
his new six-piece acoustic band, Origin. Hersch will wear two hats,
performing a solo piano concert and accompanying one piece on the
Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane Dance Company program.
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto Festival USA
</P>
<P>
   May 26-June 11. Charleston, S.C. $15-$85. Single tickets go on
sale Monday at 1-877-386-7765 or www.spoletousa
</P>
<P>
   .org.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
