A8476 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-PICKPOCKET-TIPS30-COX     01-27 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICKPOCKET-TIPS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to reduce odds you'll become a target
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, at least I'm not alone. Pickpocketing is the one of the
most common complaints American travelers report to U.S. embassies
and consulates abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clark Howard, Atlanta's consumer and travel authority, has
been victimized. While he hasn't been pickpocketed, his rental cars
have been broken into twice _ once, in Amsterdam, when he unwisely
left a camera in plain view through a soon-to-be-smashed
windshield. Both his sister-in-law and father-in-law have been
pickpocketed. The latter was hit at the Colosseum in Rome, just
like me.
</P>
<P>
   So it can happen to anyone. The trick is reducing the odds.
Here's a checklist of precautions from Howard and from a useful
State Department publication called ``A Safe Trip Abroad'' (which
can be viewed on the Bureau of Consular Affairs Web site:
travel.state.gov _ click ``travel publications''):
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lighten your wallet and pocketbook before leaving. Carry no
more cash or credit cards than you'll need.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make two photocopies of passports, airline tickets, driver's
licenses and credit and ID cards. Write down the phone numbers to
report theft. Leave one photocopy at home with family or friends.
Pack the other in a place separate from your other valuables.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't carry any irreplaceable objects. A friend of mine was
heartbroken when some of her one-of-a-kind jewelry was stolen from
her hotel room in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Split up your cards and cash and carry them in different
places. Howard divides his between a front pants pocket and a body
wallet; ``I try not to reveal my main source of money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beware of pickpocket MOs: people who jostle you, spill food on
you, ask you for directions or time. Sad to say, but beggars _
particularly beggars with babies _ figure in a lot of incidents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Know where you are. Poor countries, large cities and tourist
sites like the Colosseum seem to attract more pickpockets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wear the strap of your pocketbook or camera bag across your
chest, bandolier-style. Carry it away from the curb, where drive-by
purse snatchers can't get at it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't carry your wallet in an outside pocket or fanny pack.
Some people put their money in body wallets worn inside their
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   This last one was my big mistake. My pocket was deep and zipped
shut, but because it was on the outside of my windbreaker, I was
vulnerable. Never underestimate the skill of professional
pickpockets.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
