<SLUG> BC-TREK-VIN-DIESEL-IN-PITCH-BLACK-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTO THE DARK WITH VIN DIESEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Vin Diesel
in a scene from ``Pitch Black.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Vin Diesel is a creature of the night.
 &HT;    ``I love the nightlife, I love to boogie,'' he says, crooning a
classic disco tune, horribly off-key. ``Really, I am a night
person.''
 &HT;    It's virtual typecasting, then, that the imposing actor co-stars
in the new sci-fi adventure ``Pitch Black'' _ written and directed
by ``The Arrival's'' David Twohy and opening Feb. 18 _ as Riddick,
a convicted murderer with shimmering, surgically enhanced eyes that
enable him to see in the dark.
 &HT;    That ability proves useful when Riddick and a group of space
travelers crash-land on a desolate planet whose three blazing suns
swiftly set, giving way to nightfall and the onslaught of ravenous,
flesh-eating flying creatures.
 &HT;    Nearly as dangerous are Riddick's volatile relationships with
his fellow survivors: Johns (Cole Hauser) is the lawman
transporting Riddick to prison, while Fry (Radha Mitchell) is the
pilot who crashed the ship but now leads the group. Imam (Keith
David) is a Muslim whose faith is put to the test by the crisis,
and Jack (Rhiana Griffith) is a teen with a secret. ``Farscape''
star Claudia Black plays Shazza, a plucky geologist, with Lewis
Fitz-Gerald as Paris, a selfish antique dealer.
 &HT;    ``It's almost impossible not to retrace some of the steps taken
by other sci-fi films, but we wanted to make `Pitch Black' as
original as possible,'' Diesel says. ``We did that through the
characters.
 &HT;    ``Riddick, specifically, is going on a journey to explore his
humanity,'' the actor adds. ``He comes off at first as a villain,
as beastlike and nefarious, but later we discover he may have more
humanity than some of the characters to whom we've attributed
heroic qualities.
 &HT;    ``That's fascinating.''
 &HT;    Sitting in a suite room at Manhattan's Regency Hotel, Diesel is
dressed head to toe in black. He's got muscles on top of muscles
and speaks in a voice as deep as the Atlantic Ocean. Muggers would
flee from this guy.
 &HT;    That physicality, however, bolsters Diesel's performance and the
film. The actor handled most of his own stunts, which meant
tussling with both Hauser and the monsters.
 &HT;    ``Cole and I worked very hard with the stunt coordinators,'' the
former bouncer says. ``In rehearsals and then every week during
production, we allocated time to making sure that those scenes came
off.
 &HT;    ``These guys wouldn't just walk in and start pummeling each
other,'' he adds. ``They are masters at what they do, and they
fight in a cobralike way, with striking movements.
 &HT;    ``Fighting the creature was a little more difficult,'' Diesel
says. ``There was a contraption created that was part puppet and
part animatronics. It took several people to work it. I'd hold each
arm and push the thing.
 &HT;    ``After an hour of takes my arms got tired,'' he adds. ``I got
scrapes. But it looks good.''
 &HT;    For those who can't get enough of Riddick or ``Pitch Black,''
there's ``Into Pitch Black,'' a Sci-Fi Channel special that will
debut on Feb. 20. The inventive, hour-long companion piece centers
on the government's search for Riddick following the crash, and
includes original footage, scenes from ``Pitch Black'' and Diesel
reprising his role as Riddick.
 &HT;    Diesel may not yet be a household name, but in millions of homes
he's already a household voice: The actor, whose credits include
``Strays'' _ which he also wrote, produced and directed _ and
``Saving Private Ryan,'' put the words in the mouth of the title
alien robot in ``The Iron Giant.''
 &HT;    That superb animated feature got lost in the shuffle upon its
release last summer. However, it's finding a sizable audience in
home video.
 &HT;    ``I was very proud to be a part of `The Iron Giant,''' Diesel
says. ``My mother said, `If you never do anything again, I'll
always be proud of you for being the Iron Giant.'
 &HT;    ``It was a very different experience,'' he says. ``We had to
dissect little things that in live-action films you overlook. A
`Hmmm' was something you did 20,000 times, 1,000 different ways.
Then I had to do the guttural sounds, which were deeper than my
voice. I had to perfect that, then keep doing it.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't able to talk for two hours after each session.''
 &HT;    That's not to say there weren't similarities between the Iron
Giant and Riddick.
 &HT;    ``They are both perceived as the villain, as the enemy,'' Diesel
says. ``In the case of the Iron Giant, it's all in the way he's
treated.''
 &HT;    ``The Iron Giant'' actually carries a spiritual message, the
actor believes.
 &HT;    ``It preaches that the soul doesn't die,'' he says. ``That's
what I believe, and I thought it was beautifully done in the film.
It was done without being as didactic as some of the Walt Disney
films, but it was effective. It's a message you want kids to hear.
 &HT;    ```South Park' and `Inspector Gadget' are cool,'' he admits.
``They're entertaining, but there's something about quality films
that have heart, with a substantial message, that just make the
world a better place.''
 &HT;    Diesel catches himself and smiles.
 &HT;    ``As idealistic as that sounds, there's something to be said
about that in a world with no boundaries, where the envelope is
pushed wide open,'' he says. ``Films like `The Iron Giant' come in
handy.
 &HT;    ``You feel good when `The Iron Giant' is your kid's favorite
film.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
