</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-FUNDRAISING (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
party was fined and placed under criminal investigation Thursday
after the state comptroller issued a blistering account of its
alleged violations of campaign finance laws during the 1999
elections. The comptroller, Eliezer Goldberg, did not implicate
Barak personally but he held him accountable for what he described
as a ``trampling of the law'' by his One Israel party. Barak's
associates circumvented strict campaign finance restrictions
systematically, channeling illegal contributions into a host of
non-profit organizations, the comptroller said. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PRISONS (Paris) _ While working at La Sante prison in
Paris, Dr. Veronique Vasseur met inmates so deranged or depressed
that they had swallowed rat poison, forks or drain cleaner. Skin
diseases were rampant because showers were only available twice a
week, though temperatures sometimes soared to more than 100 degrees
in cramped cells holding four prisoners each. Some of the weaker
inmates had been turned into slaves by their cellmates. Moreover,
nearly half of the France's 55,000 prisoners have never been
convicted, because the law here allows investigating magistrates to
put suspects in jail indefinitely without trial or bail. Dr.
Vasseur's account of her work at La Sante over the last seven years
has just hit the bookstands, and it has caused an uproar here. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WORKFARE (New York) _ New York City is placing some of its
workfare recipients in rather unusual jobs. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   MULLIGAN-DAMAGE (Undated) _ A New Jersey appeals court rules
that a golfer who takes a second tee shot without warning his
partners, and then injures someone with that shot, may be sued for
his errant swing. The opinion breaks with precedent in sports
liability cases, saying that hitting a ``mulligan'' could be
considered a recklessly dangerous act. By Neil MacFarquhar.
</P>
