<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, January 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A batch of wintry precipitation, mainly in the form of ice
pellets, moved across northern Texas on Thursday morning as a
potent jet stream disturbance approached from eastern New Mexico.
Snow fell in Oklahoma and Arkansas, where a deep layer of cold air
prevailed above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, broken areas of light to moderate wintry precipitation
will affect an area ranging from the lower Mississippi and
Tennessee valleys to the southern Appalachians as the disturbance
lifts northeast and gradually weakens. However, a narrow swath of
locally heavy snow could affect the Tennessee Valley, where a
surface trough of low pressure reaching north from the Gulf of
Mexico enhances the lifting of moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Patches of light to moderate snow will develop over the lower
Ohio Valley, but its northeastward advance will be checked by a
robust high pressure system over the upper Ohio Valley. Meanwhile,
showers will spread toward Florida from southern Mississippi as a
low pressure system grinds eastward. Rainfalls of an inch are
possible near the Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous combinations of Arctic air and strong winds will
prevail across New England, which will stay in the windy, frigid
wake of a low pressure system over the Canadian Maritimes. Wind and
Arctic chill will ease Saturday as the weakening low heads toward
the Labrador Sea.
</P>
<P>
   A swath of accumulating snows will blanket parts of the Missouri
Valley as an upper-level low lifts moist air drawn northwestward
from the Tennessee Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snow Legacy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the snow cover left by this week's storm can have
important effects on tempe across broken glass to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bush comes off as a man who wants it, but not at any price,
and sometimes not as much as he wants to wake up in his own bed at
the Governor's mansion in Austin, Tex., wander downstairs to make a
pot of coffee, let out the pets, fetch the newspaper and get back
under the covers with Mrs. Bush to read it.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, just maybe, that is one of the reasons why many
Ameri- cans like him, a possibility of which Mr. Bush is
undoubtedly aware.
</P>
<P>
   (NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mr. Bush is happy to sepa- rate himself from both Mr.
Gore and President Clinton, and has been more aggressive about it
lately.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a new line appeared in his speeches, and that does
not hap- pen too often. To rally Republican voters in Iowa, Mr.
Bush began talk- ing about what this election really means.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of the end of the Clinton era,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a freighted statement, be- cause one of the signals it
sent to Republican voters was that if they wanted the White House
back, as they surely did, it was time to unite around the front
runner and send him into the general election as un- scathed and
unbowed as possible.
</P>
<P>
   It also made a tacit claim to mo- rality at the same time that
Mr. Bush was facing questions about abortion and giving answers
that might not be wholly satisfying reli- gious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   In Mr. Bush's victory speech after the Iowa caucuses on Monday
night, he went a step further, not only re- ferring to the Clinton
era but also appealing to Americans ``weary of scandals and
alibis.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in Concord, some- one in the audience played into
his hands, asking Mr. Bush how he would handle the baggage of Mr.
Clinton's behavior if he were in Mr. Gore's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have been in his posi- tion,'' Mr. Bush said. ``I
wouldn't have accepted the vice presidency under Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, when he was asked a simi- lar question by a reporter, Mr.
Bush said of Mr. Gore: ``I don't think he can figure out how to
handle his relationship with the president. He distances, he
doesn't distance. He distances, he doesn't distance.''
</P>
<P>
   (NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU)
</P>
<P>
   In the semiotics of political cam- paigns, perhaps nothing is as
reveal- ing as the music that plays at a candidate's events. Mr.
Bush's aides have assembled an entire sound-H track, which made its
debut last week, and the song list is almost a synopsis of Mr.
Bush's persona and strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Bamba'' is on it, with Spanish lyrics that evoke both Mr.
Bush's ability to speak the language and his outreach to
Hispanic-American vot- ers.
</P>
<P>
   The singer John Fogerty's ``Cen- terfield'' is on it, a reminder
that Mr. Bush loves baseball, was once the managing general partner
of the Texas Rangers and is ``ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of country and western, for that down-home,
folksy feel. There is a bit of mild disco, just to show that Mr.
Bush can groove.
</P>
<P>
   Van Morrison's ``Bright Side of the Road'' telegraphs Mr. Bush's
optimism, while Tom Petty's ``I Won't Back Down'' claims a certain
degree of tenacity, his homesickness notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   And Sting's ``A Brand New Day'' promises precisely that. Never
mind that the song is more romantically than politically inclined.
</P>
<P>
   After a miscue several weeks go, when ``Cat's Cradle,'' about a
son who grows up to be like his aloof father, played at several
campaign appearances, all the lyrics were carefully vetted this
time around.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why one aide's sugges- tion, Sheryl Crow's ``A
Change Would Do You Good,'' did not make the cut. Upon closer
examination, a vigilant member of the Bush staff realized that the
song included a reference to, um, self-gratification.
</P>
</TEXT>
