<HEADER>
A8489 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES27-COX     01-27 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southerner's book gets Big Apple buzz
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It pays to have friends in high places. When Tuscaloosa, Ala.,
native Helen Ellis took a job as secretary to Chanel Inc. chairman
Alain Wertheimer in New York, she persuaded her boss to give her
Fridays off to work on her novel. Then, once ``Eating the Cheshire
Cat'' (Scribner, $23) was sold, Wertheimer asked Chanel president
Arie L. Kopelman to play publicist and send the book to editors at
10 fashion magazines. Anna Wintour of Vogue liked the story of
wacky Southern belles and their obsession with beauty so much, she
plugged it in a recent issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chanel has been great to work for,'' Ellis, 29, said in a
telephone interview while on a ``maternity leave'' to promote the
book. While some reviewers have referred to the novel as a social
satire, Ellis laughs and says that was never her intention. ``I
just wrote about the people I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, she has an interesting set of friends.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Alabama, the novel is a twisted tale of three teen girls
and their domineering mothers, all overly concerned about status
and beauty. One mother is so bothered by her daughter's genetically
deformed fingers that she gets the teenager drunk, smashes them,
and takes her to the hospital to get them reset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to exaggerate much,'' Ellis said. ``One of my
friends does have that recessive trait, with her fingers bent, but
her mother never did that to her.''
</P>
<P>
   As for reports that the South has become less gothic and more
homogenized, Ellis says there are still a lot of Flannery O'Connor
characters around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a brunch when I was back home, and I heard stories
about murders, decapitations, poisoned dogs and other horrific
tales all while we were eating our French toast. So things haven't
changed that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis will sign her book at 7 tonight at Chapter 11 bookstore at
Peachtree Battle Shopping Center, 2345-A Peachtree Road N.E.,
404-237-7199.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From page to screen: There are a number of literary works
playing in theaters _ from ``Angela's Ashes'' to ``The Talented Mr.
Ripley'' and ``The End of the Affair'' _ and more are on the way.
Book magazine reports that Bette Midler will produce ``Divine
Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood'' by Rebecca Wells and
``Neurotica'' by Sue Margolis; Matt Damon will star in Cormac
McCarthy's ``All the Pretty Horses''; James Cameron is at work on
Anne Rice's ``The Mummy''; and Barry Sonnenfeld is planning an
adaptation of Don DeLillo's ``White Noise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
