<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-N.H.-HNS &LR;      01-27 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-N.H.-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRADLEY ACCUSES GORE OF MISLEADING VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATHAM, N.H. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley, spying opportunity in
the fast-moving New Hampshire primary campaign, repeatedly accused
Vice President Al Gore Thursday of misrepresenting his detailed
policy proposals in the hard-fought contest for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The former New Jersey senator carried his complaint from an
outdoor rally in the state capital of Concord to communities along
the populous Atlantic seacoast, charging that Gore has relied upon
``misrepresentation and misleading statements'' in his effort to
stem Bradley's insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you trust a person to tell the truth if he was the
president of the United States if you don't care enough about the
people to tell the truth in the campaign?'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley echoed a complaint that he first voiced during a
televised debate with Gore on Wednesday night, as supporters urged
a more fiery challenge to the rebounding campaign of the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been running a negative campaign, misrepresenting,
misleading and so forth,'' Bradley told employees of the Timberland
Co. in Stratham. ``After absorbing months of misleading statements
and misrepresentations, last night I decided it was my turn to
throw a little elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's comments recalled his vaunted days as a professional
basketball player with the New York Knicks. He added: ``One week
before the election I thought it was important for (voters) to
consider the comments that have been made by Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign released a detailed list of alleged
misrepresentations that included claims that the vice president has
distorted Bradley's health care overhaul. The campaign issued a
list citing seven instances in the last debate when Gore misstated
Bradley's record on campaign finance reform, Chechnya, welfare
reform, nursing home standards, Medicaid, Medicare and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's spokesman, Eric Hauser, said that the accusations
target Gore alone and are not designed to paint the vice president
with questions about character and truthfulness that have dogged
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore left the campaign trail in New Hampshire on Thursday to
return to Washington to sit as president of the Senate during the
president's State of the Union address. The primary election is
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public is yearning desperately for a fresh start
and more trust,'' Hauser said. ``Our opposition is Vice President
Gore. But Bill Bradley has talked about the importance about trust
in national leadership for 15 years _ long before anybody outside
of Arkansas had heard of Bill Clinton and long before anybody
outside of Tennessee had heard of Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, faced with latest public opinion polls showing him
starting to fall behind Gore, appealed directly for support. ``I
need you. I need your help. This is a very close primary election
next Tuesday. It could go either way.''
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/USA Today survey published Thursday that took into account
Gore's victory in Iowa on Monday night, showed Gore leading Bradley
53 percent to 44 percent. That represented a five percentage point
jump for Gore from Sunday. The survey had a margin of error of five
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   John Fitzgerald, a Timberland employee for seven years who lives
in Stratham, said he was pleased with the ``leadership skills''
that Bradley displayed during remarks to several hundred workers of
the footwear company that employs 5,200 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked what I heard,'' Fitzgerald, 37, said. But he added
that the debate between Bradley and Gore left him disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both in attack mode,'' Fitzgerald said. ``That
displeased me. I wanted to hear more specifics about what they
would do as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Kinson, 41, of Bow, heard Bradley at the Concord rally.
``What he said is what I wanted to hear but I've got to do more
research. I'll make up my mind by Tuesday,'' said Kinson, who said
she was a registered independent who planned to vote in the
Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Kinson said she was drawn to Gore, as well, because of his
experience in international affairs. ``One of the things that I
have a little bit of uncertainty about is that I feel that Gore has
more experience internationally so for me there's the experience
issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bradley added what aides described as a more impromptu approach
to his campaign, diverting his two-bus motorcade for a quick
meet-and-greet stop at a Dunkin' Donuts and a subsequent stint as a
grocery bagger at a supermarket at Straw's Plaza in Newmarket. He
listened attentively and promised to help small family farmers
after Lisa Aragones, of Newmarket, intercepted him in the plaza
parking lot to ask for government to ``give us a little hand'' to
help small family farms withstand the pressures for commercial or
residential development.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also raided one of Gore's most reliable constituencies,
garnering the endorsement of two prominent environmentalists on the
banks of the Great Bay Estuary in Stratham.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Klein, who donated land for the Heron Point Sanctuary after
fishing Great Bay Estuary for 30 years, said some fishermen shared
Bradley's complaints about Gore. ``Some call it
`misrepresentation.''' Klein said. ``We fisherman call it just
plain old B.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bogen, of New Hampshire's Clean Water Action public
interest organization, said he was endorsing Bradley because the
18-year Senate veteran would fight to close loopholes in the Clean
Air Act that allow older fissile fuel power plants to continue to
emit greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, taking in the picturesque landscape with the
ice-and-snow covered bay as his backdrop, cited the winter majesty
of the setting. ``When you're here even in the deep part of the
winter, the stillness about this place with the wind in the trees,
that allows you to know that there is something very special. It's
a gift given to all people for all time.''
</P>
