<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KOREAN-CERAMICS-ART-2     01-27 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-CERAMICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN CERAMICS, INSPIRED BY HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Korean Ceramics From the Museum of Oriental
Ceramics, Osaka'' is not, as Yogi Berra might have said, a case of
deja vu all over again. More than 35 of the 48 pieces in this
serenely beautiful show were part of a larger exhibition of
ceramics from the same museum that traveled to Chicago, San
Francisco and the Met in 1992. But it scarcely matters. The
recidivists, like the first-timers, constitute the masterworks of
the Osaka museum's extensive Korean holdings. They account rather
fully for the innovations and high points of Korea's ceramic art,
which occurred with impressive regularity throughout the Koryo
(918-1392) and Choson (1392-1910) dynasties. In addition, seeing
them cloistered in the Met's intimate yet spare, white-on-white
Korean arts gallery, which opened in 1997, is an exceptional
viewing experience.
</P>
<P>
   The objects deserve it. Ceramics are generally considered
Korea's greatest artistic legacy, and have been long appreciated in
the West. But they tend to be overshadowed in most major American
museums by Japanese, and especially Chinese, art. This is certainly
the case at the Met, which seems to be taking advantage of all the
outside loans it can broker to broaden public understanding of
Korean art and contextualize its own holdings. After this
exhibition closes in June, the Gallery of Korean Arts, as it is
formally known, will feature a selection of ceramics on long-term
loan from the Osaka museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Met is right to persist. China, Korea and Japan are linked
geographically, historically and culturally, and while China
exerted the greater influence on its neighbors, the flow was far
from one-directional. Korea sometimes served as a cultural conduit
between the other two, channeling Buddhism from China to Japan in
the sixth century, for example. And where the prestigious,
competitive art of ceramics was concerned, there was a lot of give
and take. Emulating the Chinese, the Koreans equaled them, first on
Chinese terms and then on their own.
</P>
<P>
   During the Koryo period, Koreans took the pale, jade-colored
celadon glaze, which the Chinese began using in very rudimentary
form as early as the Shang dynasty around 1600 B.C., to new levels
of perfection. The Koreans' celadons, the most admired of which was
a kingfisher color, were exquisite in tone and translucence, a
result of a single layer of glaze. To this was often added
intricate inlaid decoration, an entirely Korean invention. By the
12th century, the Chinese considered Korean celadon ``first under
heaven'' and more valuable than gold.
</P>
<P>
   During the early Choson dynasty, the other side of the Korean
sensibility _ a penchant for roughness, asymmetry and the
unexpected that is most visible in Korean punchong ware of the 15th
and 16th centuries _ exerted a profound influence on Japanese
ceramics. This was especially the case in the 1500s after the
introduction of the tea ceremony; the small, rough utilitarian
bowls produced by both government and rural kilns in Korea suddenly
dovetailed with Japan's new ceremonial needs.
</P>
<P>
   It is sometimes hypothesized that the high demand for these
bowls prompted Emperor Hideyoshi's invasions of Korea in 1592 and
1597. In any event, he forcibly transplanted a great number of
Korean potters to Japan, which heralded the demise of punchong in
Korea, stimulated Japanese stoneware and kiln construction and
accelerated the development of porcelain. In 1639 the Japanese
established kilns in southeastern Korean villages. There the two
cultures effectively merged, with Korean potters producing wares
according to Japanese specifications for nearly 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   And a later twist of influence: In early 20th-century Japan,
renewed interest in 16th- and 17th-century Korean ceramics helped
ignite the Mingei (folk art) movement led by the critic and
philosopher Soetsu Yanagi. Yanagi's ideas, in turn, were embraced
and spread beyond Japan by influential 20th-century potters like
Shoji Hamada and Bernard Leach, which brings the influence, at
least indirectly, up to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The history of ceramics is as complex in its
cross-fertilizations as any in the history of art, especially in
eastern Asia, where conventions borrowed from bronze vessels and
lacquerware must be factored in. No New York museum makes this
clearer than the Met.
</P>
<P>
   On your way to the Korean show, peruse the long stretch of
vitrines at the top of the grand staircase. On display are clusters
of sometimes nearly identical blue-and-white and polychrome
porcelains that track the furious stylistic back-and-forth between
Asia and Europe that started heating up in the 17th century. (Until
this assortment was installed two years ago, the Met's ceramics
tended to maintain their national divisions.)
</P>
<P>
   You will also sharpen your appreciation of the show if you
approach it by taking the long way around the Great Hall's balcony.
You will be walking backward through the history of Chinese
ceramics, past the often highly decorated porcelains of the Ming
and Qing dynasties, which are roughly contemporary with the
Choson-dynasty Korean pieces in the show. There's a hothouse
complexity to many of these works that doesn't subside until you
reach the ceramics from the Five Dynasties period, the Tang dynasty
and the Song dynasties, whose integrated shapes and subdued
decorations crucially influenced 9th- and 10th-century Koryo
potters. Finally, just outside the entrance to the exhibition you
are reminded of the greatness and longevity of Chinese ceramics by
an imposing display of large Neolithic earthenware jars, one of the
signal points of origin of the world's ceramic arts.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to enter the Korean show with all this history
buzzing in your head, but it won't buzz for long. Rugged or
refined, the Korean objects aren't quite like anything you've seen
along the way. They cast a spell that is all their own, one that is
grounded in simplicity and directness and a continual sense of the
hand.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
