<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: We're mad and not going to take it any more
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, declaring he'd ``had it,'' said today he'll stick
with the more confrontational stance he took against Al Gore in the
final debate before the New Hampshire presidential primary, Cox's
Ken Foskett reports. In the debate, Wednesday night, Bradley
accused Gore of campaign dishonesty and flip-flops on abortion.
Gore responded that Bradley was responsible for dragging the
campaign into the mud. Even afterward, in the press room, he
wouldn't back down: ``I think Al will have to go a long way to
demonstrate that what he said tonight was true and that he has not
lied in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   I'M MORE PRO-CHOICE; NO, I AM
</P>
<P>
   Feminist Gloria Steinem couldn't have it any better in the
Democratic presidential race. She says she's happy to see the two
major Democratic candidates debating over who is more pro-choice,
because, she says, ``It proves two facts: First, the huge majority
of Americans believe that the abortion decision should be made by a
woman and her doctor. Second, the Republican presidential
nomination is in the hands of anti-choice extremists who don't
represent the majority of even their own party.'' By the way,
Steinem's for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   TIPTOEING THROUGH THE ABORTION MINEFIELD
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and John McCain tiptoed around the abortion issue
today, with Bush saying that ``good people can disagree on that
issue'' and McCain calling questions about how his family would
handle an unplanned pregnancy ``painful.''
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN AMMO
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer was campaigning today on a different target _ what he
called the growing threat to Second Amendment rights facing Granite
Staters. He toured a small business in Manchester, N.H., that
produces custom leather firearms products and discussed the growing
threat to gun owners' Second Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   IT COULD BE OVER BY THEN, ANYWAY
</P>
<P>
   The South Caroling Democratic Party canceled its March 9
presidential primary today and instead will hold caucuses that day.
The state reported today that the GOP will still hold its primary
on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   CHANCE OF A LIFETIME
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley and Gary Bauer are the first presidential
candidates to commit to Lifetime cable channel's town hall meeting
to be taped Saturday in Bedford, N.H. CBS News correspondent Sharyl
Attkisson will host the one-hour original special, ``Who Wants to
Be Our President?'' All candidates of both parties have been
invited to address issues of importance to women. The program will
air Sunday at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   KEMP ON BOARD AS BUSH BACKER
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush picked up the endorsement today from Jack Kemp,
the former housing secretary and congressman, and losing vice
presidential candidate in 1996. Most of the Republican
establishment already has endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   HARD TO COME FROM BEHIND
</P>
<P>
   Iowa and New Hampshire are just two small states, really, but
the voters there love winners and front-runners have always been
tough to beat. A trailing candidate hasn't knocked off a
front-runner of either party since George McGovern lost in Iowa and
New Hampshire but defeated Edmund Muskie for the Democratic
nomination in 1972. Democrat Gary Hart in 1984 and Republican Pat
Buchanan in 1996 defeated front-runners in New Hampshire, but still
failed to win their party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   POPULAR TARGET TO SHOOT AT
</P>
<P>
   During the GOP debate, all five candidates agreed that President
Clinton ``committed a felony in the Monica Lewinsky case and should
have been removed from office. Gary Bauer faulted Clinton for
discussing the crisis in Bosnia on the telephone with a member of
Congress ``while in the middle of a disgusting act.'' Alan Keyes
added that Congress ``lacked the guts'' to remove the president
from office.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE REMEMBERS HOW IT WAS
</P>
<P>
   A moderate GOP group is on the air with another ad slamming
Steve Forbes for attacks on front-runner George W. Bush. The
Republican Leadership Council cites a letter from Bob Dole
complaining that Forbes' attacks on him in 1996 helped Democrats
win that November. The TV spot quotes Dole: ``I emerged the
Republican nominee, battered, bruised and broke, and a much easier
target for the negative Clinton-Gore fall campaign. I speak up now
only because it could be happening again.'' The TV ad closes with:
``Mr. Forbes: Stop the negative ads. Don't help the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   NO NEED TO PARDON HIS FRENCH
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes didn't miss a beat in New Hampshire when a couple of
questions came at him _ in French. Marcel Calfat of Radio-Canada
had read that Keyes could speak French and wanted to check it out.
So Calfat asked Keyes about NAFTA. In French, Keyes said he isn't
opposed to it in principle, but that it may need to be
re-evaluated. And he answered another in French about his message:
``The message is very simple. I represent moral priorities.'' How
well did Keyes do? ``A lot more articulate, in fact, than some
Canadian politicians,'' Calfat said _ in English.
</P>
<P>
   BRINGING IN THE BIG GUNS
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is listing two prominent Democrats among his foreign
policy advisers: Zbigniew Brzezinski, the national security adviser
under President Carter, and James Woolsey, a CIA director under
President Clinton. Also on a list of advisers released Wednesday
were Republicans like Henry Kissinger, Jeane Kirkpatrick, Robert
McFarlane and Lawrence Eagleburger.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU'RE GONNA BE A HAWK, BE A STRONG HAWK
</P>
<P>
   On his first full day of campaigning in New Hampshire, Steve
Forbes appeared at a defense contractor in Nashua and called for
increased military spending. ``A cheap hawk is a dead hawk,'' he
said, adding: ``The U.S. is the only superpower. If our country
gets in trouble, then the rest of the world gets in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A CLOSE PLAY AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   Even in his home state, John McCain of Arizona is found to be in
a tight race with George W. Bush. A recent Arizona State University
poll determined that Republicans who voted in the past two
presidential primaries support McCain over Bush, 37 percent to 30
percent (4 percentage point margin of error). All the other
Republicans were in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OF BOTH WORLDS
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Republicans weren't the largest group of voters
watching Wednesday's double-barreled debates. Nor were Democrats.
Independents are the big bloc in this state's politics, and they
were getting a rare chance to size up both presidential fields at
once. ``It's one-stop shopping,'' said Terry Blair of Manchester,
one of 274,000 registered independents. New Hampshire independents
outnumber the state's 265,000 Republicans and 194,000 Democrats,
and they can vote in either primary Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   POWER RUN UP THE MIDDLE
</P>
<P>
   Ending weeks of speculation, former Nebraska football coach Tom
Osborne, who led the Cornhuskers to three national championships,
announced today he's running for Congress. Osborne, a Republican,
said he started contemplating a campaign when Republican Rep. Bill
Barrett announced in October that he was retiring at the end of his
fifth term. ``I don't think this is an ego trip,'' Osborne said at
a news conference with his family. ``It would be a lot easier to go
fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE ENCOUNTERS OF A NEW HAMPSHIRE KIND
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan buddy talk enlivened the second encounter in three
days between George W. Bush and a Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey,
campaigning for Bill Bradley. ``I'm stalking him,'' Kerrey cracked
after bumping into Bush on Wednesday at the Puritan Backroom
Restaurant and Lounge, a blue-plate diner
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, killer,'' said the Texas governor, shaking Kerrey's hand.
Kerrey complimented Bush on his Iowa State University address on
Monday, when they last met. The Puritan is a popular stop: Al Gore
and Gary Bauer ran into each other there several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   SORT OF LIKE THE DO DAH PARADE
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proposals were familiar _ a flat tax, universal
health care, getting rid of pork-barrel legislation, a ban on
late-term abortions. But the names at this debate didn't ring many
bells. If fact, probably no bells at all. The New Hampshire
Historical Society held a forum in Concord for candidates on the
ballot who weren't invited to Wednesday night's nationally
televised debates. Eight presidential hopefuls _ people like
Heather Harder of Crown Point, Ind., and Vermin Supreme (his legal
name) of Baltimore _ shelled out $1,000 apiece to get a brief time
in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and wire reports
</P>
