<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KOREAN-CERAMICS-ART-2     01-27 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-CERAMICS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the hand. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The objects include tall-necked bottles, bowls, ewers, jars of
different sizes and shapes, water-droppers and brush holders dating
from the early 12th to the early 19th centuries. They are arranged
in chronological order in vitrines that line three walls of the
gallery, regularly spaced, each isolated on a separate mat. This
means that one can take in an impressive seven-century span of
aesthetic development with a turn of the head and then proceed
object by delectable object.
</P>
<P>
   Along the first wall one encounters the pale, understated Koryo
celadons from the 12th century, their golden age. The few blades of
grass incised on a tall-necked ceremonial bottle called a kundika
are so subtle you almost miss them. (A nearly identical
10th-century kundika, in bronze, can be found in the vitrines along
the gallery's fourth wall, which present works from the Met's
collection.)
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is a small celadon plaque whose sparse images of bamboo
and waterbirds seem to have been painted with the tiniest of
brushes. The motifs exemplify the inlay technique, invented in the
early 12th century, in which delicately incised motifs were
infilled with a glazelike paste of black or white, biscuit-fired
and then fired a second time with the celadon glaze. Its relatively
more boisterous neighbor is a rare example of reverse inlay, the
result being a delicately inflected white background against which
a little celadon boy climbs a large celadon vine, like Jack on his
beanstalk.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this wall, a display of five small bowls
illustrates the level of refinement that Korean potters, unburdened
by the large production quotas of their Chinese counterparts,
frequently achieved. In the case of one celadon bowl, this allowed
for the superfine veins on the leaves of a raised floral design;
the mold that formed this design had to last a much shorter time.
In another bowl, the potter returned to the inlaid image of a white
waterbird to incise individual feathers on its wings.
</P>
<P>
   With the decline of the increasingly corrupt Koryo dynasty, its
celadon declined as well, but its coarseness would eventually yield
the wonderful, strikingly modern looseness of punchong ware, the
highest of the high points of the Choson dynasty, which takes up
most of the show's second wall.
</P>
<P>
   Here, celadon green gives way to the light gray punchong glaze.
The punchong potters continued to inlay, but into stamped, almost
textilelike fields of pattern and irregularly repeated motifs
instead of the refined incisions of the Koryo period. They favored
underglaze painting, usually with iron oxide, and, sometimes, a
subtly angular drawing style, as evidenced by the curling vines and
sleeping duck on a tall Choson jar at the center of this wall. The
punchong potters used white slip, or clay dissolved in water,
liberally, brushing it on and then simply incising schematic plant
motifs into it with a boldness that brings to mind Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   They also produced asymmetrical hand-built pieces like the two
extraordinary ritual vessels here. One of these, a boxy volume in a
brown clay whose stepped legs echo Chinese bronzes, is decorated
with a roughly incised labyrinth of lines that has been inlaid with
white and then spattered with thick white slip. The timeless
quality that often makes ceramic objects so appealing abounds in
this exhibition; it is unusually present in this object, which
could be Neolithic, medieval or modern.
</P>
<P>
   To distance themselves from the Koryo dynasty, the Choson
emperors and elite turned to Neo-Confucianism, which may account
for the austere, virtually undecorated surfaces of three stunning
all-white porcelain jars that complete the show's middle wall. One
is round, almost bubblelike, with a glaze of golden cream. Another,
made by joining two thrown bowls together, is tall, slightly
elliptical and pure white. And between them is a shorter
eight-sided jar, cherished for its signs of use and aging; around
its foot, the jar's warmly yellow clay has worn through the glaze,
each patch serendipitously accented by an indolently curving crack.
</P>
<P>
   Along the show's final wall, things turn subtly diverse,
reflecting the loosening of Neo-Confucian strictures in the 17th
and 18th centuries. This resulted in a broader range of shapes, a
freer use of both Chinese and Korean decorative motifs and the
increased use of cobalt-blue underglaze painting as well as
occasional attempts at the more fugitive copper-red underglaze. In
one round jar, a quickly drawn heron and pine are vividly red. But
more engaging is a taller jar where copper-red depictions of lotus
blossoms faded to a gorgeous range of pale browns and lavenders.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing national motif here is a Korean tiger, rendered
in iron-oxide with irresistible calligraphic flair on a
rough-surfaced jar at the center of the gallery. Wide-eyed, almost
comic, he prances forth from a swirl of fungal clouds.
</P>
<P>
   A turn back toward a Chinese aesthetic is evident along the
show's last wall, where nearly every piece uses the cobalt-blue
underglaze painting. But even so, most retain a distinctive Korean
sturdiness and plainness that is quite unlike the blue-and-white
Chinese porcelains on the balcony. The blue decorations are always
discreet, always subsidiary to the expanses of luminous white, and
they never interfere with the assertive shapes of the jars. In
addition, the pieces continue to be animated by slight
irregularities of profile, lip and surface.
</P>
<P>
   Having met the Chinese standards of perfection with their Koryo
celadons, Korean potters of the Choson period defined a new, more
natural and ineffably human kind of perfection, one that is
instantly recognizable today.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``Korean Ceramics From the Museum of Oriental Ceramics, Osaka''
is at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street,
New York, (212) 879-5500, through June 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
