<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush seeking McCain-Gore linkage
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. - Gov. George W. Bush, honing in on the Republican
he has to beat here next Tuesday and the Democrat he might face in
November, worked to link John McCain and Al Gore to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, running behind McCain in polls here, on Thursday accused
the Arizona senator of playing ``me-tooism'' with Clinton on taxes
and education. And Bush said Vice President Gore can't seem to
figure out if he is on Clinton's team or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he can figure out how to handle his relationship
with the president,'' Bush said after a breakfast speech to the
Nashua Chamber of Commerce. ``He distances. He doesn't distance. He
distances. He doesn't distance. I think that is going to send
confusing signals to the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who picked up the endorsement of 1996 GOP vice
presidential nominee Jack Kemp here on Thursday, campaigned in
Nashua, Jaffrey and Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Bush remains confident he can score a come-from-behind win over
McCain here on Tuesday. Current polls show McCain with a slight
edge over Bush, who won the Iowa caucuses on Monday. McCain did not
compete there. Publisher Steve Forbes, the Iowa runner-up, is in
third place in the New Hampshire GOP polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Thursday attacks on McCain were sparked by the Arizona
senator's comments on taxes during a Wednesday night debate.
McCain, like Clinton, backs a smaller tax-cut plan than the
five-year, $483-billion package pushed by Bush. McCain prefers a
smaller plan in order to reserve more money for debt reduction, as
does Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe President Clinton's looks too much like mine,''
McCain said during the debate when the similarity was noted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush immediately seized on the comment on the campaign trail,
calling it ``one of the telling points of the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to nominate somebody who will be able to debate
the Democrat nominee on key issues, not mimic them,'' Bush said
here.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp joined in by charging that McCain ``is obsessed with debt
reduction and seems to be defending . . . the Clinton tax code.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, on board his campaign bus in Portsmouth, retaliated in
kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps spinning like Bill Clinton,'' he said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman via e-mail at
kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
