<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8504 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-FUNDRAISING-AR     01-27 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-FUNDRAISING-ART-2TAKES(1060)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK'S PARTY FINED AND PLACED UNDER INVESTIGATION OVER CAMPAIGN
FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's party was fined and
placed under criminal investigation Thursday after the state
comptroller issued a blistering account of what he called
violations of campaign finance laws during the 1999 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller, Eliezer Goldberg, did not implicate Barak
personally but held him accountable for what he described as a
``trampling of the law'' by his One Israel party. Barak's
associates systematically circumvented strict campaign finance
restrictions by channeling illegal contributions into a host of
nonprofit organizations, the comptroller said. The party was fined
$3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a reserve general who ran his political campaign like a
military operation, said that he welcomed the investigation as a
spur to clarify an unclear campaign funding law. He said he had
advised his associates to operate legally and knew nothing about
the operations of the nonprofit associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not deal with raising money,'' he said. ``I was not
updated on the details and I was not involved specifically in any
of the activities described in the comptroller's report.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a former Supreme Court judge, said he had found no
evidence to contradict Barak's assertion that he was ignorant of
the ``particulars.'' But the comptroller charged that the
``extensive scope'' of the illegal activity should have ``lit a red
warning light for the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Claiming not to know is simply untenable,'' he said in a radio
interview, adding that it was Barak's responsibility to supervise
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One Israel campaign's overall budget was about $22 million; the
allegations involve the funneling of about $1.2 million in illegal
money to the nonprofit organizations, which then directly or
indirectly supported the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising affair has erupted at a delicate moment for
Barak. He is encountering frustrations in his ambitious peacemaking
initiatives with the Palestinians and the Syrians, and he faces an
impatient public waiting for him to make good on his campaign
promises of peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of illegal behavior on his behalf clash with the
image that Barak presents as a straightforward, old-fashioned man
of his word. And it makes it harder for him to declare himself
above the political fray that has dragged so many into scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police are already juggling the criminal probes of
several political leaders. Among those under investigation are
President Ezer Weizman, who has been accused of improperly
accepting substantial cash gifts from a French executive, and
former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, on allegations of bribery
and theft of gifts to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is yet another investigation placed on the shoulder of
the police,'' Police Chief Yehuda Wilk said, sighing. ``And in the
slew of investigations, it becomes a a logistical issue who will
investigate what, when and how.''
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller report was released Thursday as a rare snowfall
began blanketing the turbulent Holy City in an otherworldly quiet.
Over the airwaves, the political storm broke the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud Party, blasted the
prime minister for breaking his election promise to be trustworthy.
``I hereby declare that the prime minister knew about the existence
of the apparatus and the system'' used to obtain illegal donations,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Benizri, a Cabinet minister from the Shas political
party, whose former leader Aryeh Deri, is appealing his conviction
on corruption charges, said, ``After this, the Deri appeal should
go to small claims court!''
</P>
<P>
   One Israel is a reconstituted version of Barak's Labor Party,
which is heavily indebted and will face the financial penalty with
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller also found similar violations on a far lesser
scale by four other parties, and criminal investigations into their
activities were also opened. The parties were: the opposition Likud
Party, the Center Party, the United Torah Judaism faction, and the
Russian immigrants' Yisrael Beteinu.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after the report was issued, Barak noted that other
parties were criticized, too. And he suggested that the problems
lay in the campaign financing laws themselves, and with the murky
way they have been interpreted since the country switched in 1996
to a direct election system for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself am convinced that there is a need for corrections to
the campaign finance law in order to make the picture clear so that
no list, candidate or public body of any kind will find itself
uncertain as to how to act,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Israel's strict campaign financing law, political parties
receive state funding for their campaigns based on the number of
Parliament seats they eventually win. Individual citizens are
limited to contributions of about $400 each and corporations and
foreigners cannot give at all.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion arose after the 1996 election because the system
changed but the law didn't. Starting in 1996, the parties'
candidates for Parliament and for prime minister were elected on
separate ballots. The law made no specific mention of restrictions
on the candidates themselves, just their parties.
</P>
<P>
   The state comptroller then, Miriam Ben-Porat, felt that the law
could be applied to the candidates by inference. And she fined the
Likud Party some $600,000 for improperly using nonprofit
organizations in Netanyahu's successful 1996 campaign. One
organization stood out: ``Netanyahu is Good for the Jews,'' which
was backed by Joseph Gutnick, a wealthy Australian who belongs to
the ultra-Orthodox Chabad, or Lubavitch, movement.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's Labor Party urged the attorney general, Elyakim
Rubinstein, to prosecute. But Rubinstein said the law as written
applied only to parties and not to candidates, and could not be
``widened by inference.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's critics say that his advisers deliberately took
advantage of this loophole, as decreed by the attorney general in a
private letter, to plot campaign fund-raising strategy based on the
``Gutnick precedent.'' They created nonprofit organizations to
assist the campaign and enlisted existing ones, as described by the
comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Barak said he would petition the Supreme Court
to clarify if the law indeed applied to candidates as well as to
parties.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein said his investigation would go beyond the campaign
law violations to look at alleged ``violations of the penal law,
false registration, fraud and breach of trust in a corporation, and
acceptance of an object by fraudulent means.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's campaign relied on costly U.S. consultants from the
Democratic Party who had worked for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, the comptroller singled out the activities of Tal
Zilberstein, Barak's campaign manager, and Yitzhak Herzog, Barak's
cabinet secretary, an attorney and son of the late Chaim Herzog, a
former Israeli president and ambassador to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report, for instance, said that Herzog had funneled
donations into the campaign from the estate of a dovish Swiss Jew,
Octave Botner.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog had served as a trustee for Botner's charitable accounts
in Israel before his death, the comptroller said. Afterwards,
Herzog handled the estate's Camilla Fund, which was intended to
ease poverty and promote education in Israel, the comptroller said.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog, who told the comptroller he had personal discretion to
disburse the money according to general instructions, directed
about $105,000 from the Camilla Fund to the campaign, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the Camilla fund set up several nonprofit
organizations, including one nominally for the ``promotion of taxi
drivers in Israel,'' which provided posters and put on rallies for
the campaign, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
