<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8507 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ROBERT-SHAW-MUSIC-2TA     01-27 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERT-SHAW-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINAL PIECES OF A MAESTRO'S LEGACY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would somehow have been both fitting and a bit grotesque if
Robert Shaw, the great choral conductor who died just over a year
ago at 82, had left behind a recording of a Requiem, to be released
after his own death. And he missed doing so only by weeks.
</P>
<P>
   His last recording, made in late 1998 and recently released by
Telarc, was of Dvorak's Stabat Mater, an expansive setting of a
traditional text of the Roman Catholic Church, reflecting on the
sorrows of the Virgin Mary at the cross of Jesus. ``When my body
shall die,'' runs the last verse, ``Grant that my soul be given/The
glory of Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was also to have recorded Brahms' ``German Requiem'' in a
new English adaptation of his own last February with the Mormon
Tabernacle Choir. The project was carried through by Craig Jessop,
a Shaw disciple and then the choir's associate director, now its
director. Telarc has just released that recording as well.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, RCA Victor has reissued Shaw's 1960 recording of
Bach's Mass in B minor with the Robert Shaw Chorale, a reminder of
the extraordinary scope of the maestro's career.
</P>
<P>
   It was Shaw's good fortune, and his admirers', that he was able
to remain not only active, apart from a series of late
cancellations, but also mentally engaged until his death. The
Dvorak, in fact, was a work new to his vast repertory. He also
retained his quick, robust and often self-deprecating humor to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   When, in a National Public Radio interview included with the
recording (Telarc 2CD-80506; two CDs), Martin Goldsmith asks why
Shaw didn't come to the Stabat Mater sooner in a career of more
than 60 years, the conductor shoots back: ``I can think of a couple
of reasons, Martin. The first is ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   This is indeed a rewarding piece, as new listeners will come to
realize in some particularly lilting inner movements. The opening
movements, dark, halting and spare, may yield up their restrained
beauties only with added familiarity and a thorough immersion in
the sound world.
</P>
<P>
   The piece is not so rarely heard as Shaw suggests in the
interview. (If you want a real rarity, try the Dvorak Requiem.) It
has been especially well and idiomatically tended to both in
concert and on records by native Czechs. But for sheer tonal beauty
and refinement, few versions rival this Shaw account, with the
Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and Chorus, in typically polished and
wide-ranging sound from Telarc.
</P>
<P>
   The vocal soloists _ Christine Goerke, Marietta Simpson,
Stanford Olsen and Nathan Berg _ are generally fine, and the
occasional operatic touch tending toward Verdi in no way
contradicts the nature of the writing.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Woods, the president of Telarc and the producer of this
recording, reports in the booklet that the sessions, on Oct. 31 and
Nov. 1, 1998, were extraordinarily mellow and free of problems. He
prints Shaw's own review of the sessions, addressed to the chorus
in doggerel matching the cadence and rhyming pattern of the Stabat
Mater poem: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Stabat pater fortunatus
</P>
<P>
   Happy as a hippopatus
</P>
<P>
   Up to here in muck and mire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hearing sounds beyond believing,
</P>
<P>
   Angel voices Halloweaving,
</P>
<P>
   Quel orchestrand WHAT A CHOIR!(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herewith an amen.
</P>
<P>
   The other works represented in this batch of recordings were
Shaw perennials. He conducted the B minor Mass in his last New York
appearance, in April 1998, with the Orchestra of St. Luke's and the
Atlanta Symphony Orchestra Chamber Chorus at Carnegie Hall. He
conducted the ``German Requiem'' (in German) with essentially the
same forces in April 1997 at Carnegie.
</P>
<P>
   The Englishing of the ``German Requiem'' may strike some as
wrongheaded. To a listener who first learned the work in English,
from a 1963 Musical Heritage Society recording by Edward Gilday and
the Handel and Haydn Society of Boston, it seems anything but.
Indeed, to these ears, certain of the English lines complement the
musical contours with a poetic force and eloquence at least equal
to the German.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For one example, ``How lovely is thy dwelling place, O Lord of
Hosts,'' the first line of the slowly, softly soaring fourth
movement, rings as true as ``Wie lieblich sind deine Wohnungen,
Herr Zebaoth,'' and is happily unchanged from the earlier
recording.
</P>
<P>
   Much is similar in the two translations, in fact, for both the
Shaw adaptation and the unattributed Boston text (virtually
identical to R.H. Benzon's translation for the music publisher C.F.
Peters, as printed in the Eulenburg score) draw heavily on the King
James Version of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time in the past 50 years that I have considered making
an English version of the `German Requiem,' I have concluded that a
`translation' would not work grammatically, aesthetically,
quasi-liturgically, philosophically or `spiritually,''' Shaw
writes, explaining his reliance on King James. ``A version in
English would need roots in language as deep as those in music, and
as exalted in beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessop leads the Mormon Tabernacle Choir and the Utah Symphony
in a heartfelt rendition of the work (Telarc CD-80501; CD). (
Jessop's father, Telarc's notes reveal, died two days after Shaw,
less than three weeks before the sessions.)
</P>
<P>
   The choir, though 320 strong, almost everywhere avoids
woolliness and conveys the text clearly, with the usual help from
Telarc. Janice Chandler and Nathan Gunn are admirable in the vocal
solos.
</P>
<P>
   The Brahms project is only one indication that Shaw, a son of a
preacher, with a strong evangelical streak of his own, never
relented in his strenuous commitment to the texts as well as the
music of great spiritual works. Another proof was a Shaw
performance of Bach's ``St. Matthew Passion'' in 1996 at Carnegie
Hall, again in Shaw's own English translation. He never recorded
that work, whether in German or English: perhaps the saddest gap in
his discography.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded the B minor Mass several times (three, he says in
the NPR interview, sounding unsure himself). The resurrection of
the 1960 version (RCA Victor 09026-63529-2; CD) will be of interest
primarily to specialists. For its time, Shaw's account is often
lean and lithe. As a performance note from the original release
indicates, he was alert to the nascent early-music movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Bach's custom,'' he writes, ``we have assigned to
soloists, as concertists, those sections of the choral movements
wherein instruments do not double voices, or where a choral sound
might obscure instrumental detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was wading into deep waters here. But whether honoring
Bach's custom, a notion that became increasing problematic in later
decades, or his own instinct, Shaw carried this practice right down
to that New York performance in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There are wonderfully lucid moments here, as when the tenors
shift into cantus firmus mode in the ``Confiteor,'' a piquant
compositional gesture brought to the fore with superb choral
balance and subtle emphasis. Still, a certain heaviness persists in
tempos and rhetorical touches. Some movements end with outsize
ritardandos; the Credo slows to a virtual halt at Jesus' burial.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the work of the Robert Shaw Chorale and
Orchestra is mostly excellent. The vocal solos _ by Saramae Endich,
Adele Addison, Florence Kopleff, Mallory Walker and Ara Berberian _
are more uneven. Although it is wonderful to have this document
back, nonspecialist listeners will almost certainly prefer the
latest Shaw B minor, on Telarc: livelier, by current standards, and
more cleanly reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with this wealth of Masses more or less sorted out, there
is nothing left for any of us, specialists and general listeners
alike, to do but dream of the ``St. Matthew Passion'' that got
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0128-COX     01-27 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SWIRL OF EVENTS, EMOTIONS FOLLOWING ELIAN'S MEETING WITH
GRANDMOTHERS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With ELIAN-CONGRESS-0128.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ Far from helping settle the case, the
dramatic reunion of 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez with his
grandmothers triggered a new round of angry rhetoric and charges
Thursday, as well as an apparent rift between two key U.S. players
in the on-going saga.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic about-face, the nun who hosted the long-sought
reunion Wednesday at her Miami Beach home said that while she went
into the meeting feeling Elian should go back to Cuba, the fear and
apparent manipulation she saw coming from the Cuban government
convinced her to change her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I experienced yesterday about tangible fear gives me real
concern about the future of the child,'' Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin
said on NBC's Today program. ``When I look at the real fear I say
he would grow to greater freedom of manhood here.''
</P>
<P>
   Her opinions on the case are important because she is a personal
friend of U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, a Miami native who has
ultimate authority over the boy and who supports returning him to
Cuba. O'Laughlin, president of Miami's Barry University, is a
widely respected advocate for children and immigrants known in
South Florida for her compassion.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as the U.S. Justice Department filed a
300-page motion to dismiss a lawsuit by Elian's Miami relatives
aimed at keeping the boy here, and as Elian's grandmothers and
Miami family lobbied Congress over bills that would make him a U.S.
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cuba's government reacted angrily to the family
reunion, calling the treatment of the grandmothers ``inhumane and
despotic,'' and saying they were subjected to ``deceits, lies,
tricks, betrayals and humiliations.''
</P>
<P>
   Also emerging Thursday were comments from Elian's father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, who said the boy's Miami relatives assured him in
private telephone conversations that they would bring Elian back to
Cuba, only to change their stories in television interviews because
of pressure from Miami's Cuban exile community.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami family also pressured the boy, interrupted his
telephone conversations with his Cuban family and offered millions
to the Cuban relatives if they would move to the United States,
Gonzalez told a U.S. immigration official in an interview included
in the federal court papers filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we call and Elian starts saying, 'Grandma I want to be
with you' or 'Daddy I want to go with you,' they immediately make
him cry, or give him a candy or start tapping on the lines saying
that the lines are getting bad and hang up,'' Gonzalez said. ``In
the background, you can hear them telling Elian to say he wants to
stay in the United States. It's abusive what they are doing to
Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   In other conversations, Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzales,
offered Juan Gonzalez $2 million and Elian $4 million if the Cuban
family would move to the United States, saying the money would come
from an unidentified church, Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez denied the charges in an interview on CNN
International Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did that,'' he said, when asked about promising to
take the boy to Cuba. As for offering Juan Gonzalez money, he said
``we never offered anything to him ... If I had $2 million, I
wouldn't be sitting here.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments were yet more evidence that the two-month-old
saga is likely to drag on for weeks or months, and that the child
is being tugged from both sides in a politicized family feud with
no easy solutions.
</P>
<P>
   As for Elian, he stayed home Thursday from the private school he
is attending in Miami's Little Havana. In an interview with a
Spanish-language radio program Wednesday, the boy said he was going
to be made a U.S. citizen Thursday, an apparent reference to
activities underway in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Those bills, however, seemed to be losing steam Thursday, even
as both sides of the family lobbied hard for Congressional support.
House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said he would refer the
matter to committee instead of allowing it to come up for an
immediate floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   That means any action will likely be delayed for weeks. Hastert
said there was a growing sense on Capitol Hill that the matter
should be resolved in the courts before Congress considers it.
</P>
<P>
   But action in court will be several weeks away. U.S. District
Judge William Hoeveler met with attorneys in the case briefly
Thursday and gave the Miami family until Feb. 24 to respond to the
government's motion to dismiss the case. A full hearing on the
motions will not come until after March 6, Hoeveler said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the flurry of events, Sister O'Laughlin's dramatic about-face
seemed one of the most intriguing, mainly because she was chosen by
Reno and other federal officials to host the meeting because of her
reputation for integrity and fairness.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said she was struck during the reunion by the
mistrust and fear on both sides, and had to show the separate
branches of the family around her mansion _ donated by a
philanthropist _ to assure them there were no trap doors and
unlocked entrances where kidnappers might be lurking.
</P>
<P>
   But while Elian's Miami relatives quickly relaxed, the
grandmothers remained fearful even as they left after the two-hour
meeting, O'Laughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there are people with political agendas that take
the child as a pawn, and perhaps the grandmothers also,'' she said,
a clear slap at the Cuban government. ``I think I am a wiser woman
today, and I understand how blessed we are to understand what it is
to be free and not full of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what impact O'Laughlin's comments would have on
her friend Reno, or on the controversy swirling around the boy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said she would tell Reno ``the truth as I experienced
it. I don't represent pro-Castro, anti-Castro or INS. I only have
the sense that I felt when I blessed that boy when he was leaving
here.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Reno appeared critical of the Miami relatives in
comments at her weekly press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the family parading the boy around before television
cameras, Reno said that while she wouldn't comment on Elian's case,
she believes that if something similar happened to her own
great-nephew, who is about Elian's age, ``I sure wouldn't like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In another development, the National Council of Churches, a
Protestant group that arranged the grandmothers' trip to the United
States and has lobbied to return Elian to Cuba, announced it was
withdrawing from the case and turning it over to the Cuban
Interests Section in Washington. The group, which has drawn heavy
fire from Cuban exiles in Miami, feels the case has become too
entangled in politics, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers, meanwhile, told interviewers in Washington
they were disturbed by how much their grandson has changed since
they last saw him two months ago, just prior to the ill-fated boat
ride from Cuba on which his mother drowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has changed completely,'' said Mariela Quintana, Elian's
paternal grandmother. ``I have to save the child as soon as
possible, to bring him back to his father and his family in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox News Service Writer Larry Lipman contributed to this
report.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
