<HEADER>
A8514 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV03-     01-27 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING UP AN OLD GRUDGE FOR GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Feb. 3.)  
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I heard about this New Year's party where people sat around and
gave up their grudges. They had a whole night of it, naming names,
telling stories, recounting big and little offenses against them.
</P>
<P>
   The part where they shared the little details sounded almost
like therapy. There's something deliciously righteous about
explaining an old grudge. You can relish the torment of a certain
slight, a major snub and show your wounds. You can be dramatic and
justifiably outraged, which is one reason we hold onto our grudges.
Plus you can always get sympathy that you were right and the other
was wrong, and besides, you are too wonderful a person to ever be
treated that way.
</P>
<P>
   At a Grudge Night, the target of the grudge would not be there
to defend herself or himself. In most cases the object of your
resentment probably wouldn't know what you're talking about anyhow
because grudges seldom break into open conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom are they even mutual. You're walking around with this big
bag of malevolent thoughts that gets heavier as the years go by,
and the other person is acting as if he or she doesn't know and
doesn't care. This only deepens your end of the grudge.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the grudge-holder doesn't even remember the original
reason for it, which is probably why it's a good idea to review
your grudges now and again.
</P>
<P>
   But the purpose of the Grudge Night, as I understand it, is not
to keep the grudge alive but to bid it goodbye. Push it out the
door to shiver alone on the back steps. The people at the grudge
party said they felt so much better after they promised to stop
grudging. I wondered if that meant you had to then go beyond, like
inviting the begrudged out for coffee or sending them a Valentine's
note saying all is forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Oh no, they said. You don't have to end up liking the person.
You might relax enough to make eye contact after all these years,
but they still did you wrong. In fact, they could again, so it
might be prudent to not let your guard down all the way.
</P>
<P>
   But why give someone else so much power in your life that when
their name is mentioned your neck veins stick out and your face
becomes hard with a look that says, ``I could tell you stories.''
</P>
<P>
   I learned of a grudge against me that is more than 35 years old
when I talked to a woman I first met in grade school. In recent
years we became reacquainted by phone, and one day she admitted
that she was still a little peeved at me.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because, she said, when I was in ninth-grade or something,
I turned into ``such a goody two-shoes.'' She couldn't remember
what I had done to her to make her think that, but she had clearly
resented me, or that loathsome part of my character, for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   I laughed it off, even though I could have turned her slur into
a reverse grudge, but instead sought reassurance from a close
friend who knows my dark side and promised no one would ever think
of me as that today.
</P>
<P>
   I started thinking about people from college, former bosses,
certain family members who have made me seethe. At first I thought
I might be able to come up with two or three really good grudges,
but pretty soon I had a long list.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how far back you can remember those old wounds,
better than you can remember who brought you heart-shaped candies
and complimented you on your spelling. A grudge doesn't even have
to be real. It can be imagined but fed for so long that you finally
believe it. You hear about divided families, where one sibling
won't speak to the other because of a slight she doesn't want to
talk about and then finally it comes out that it was their cousin
Donny who really made off with grandma's crystal.
</P>
<P>
   You can have a grudge against institutions like the Catholic
Church or the DMV or a fashion industry that encourages control-top
pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   The mini-grudges, the ones that don't require therapy or
mediation, are another reminder of how all of life is junior high.
You told him first. You invited her instead of me. The teacher
likes you better.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with holding on to grudges is that they eventually
overwhelm the good memories. And they can become deadly in their
own way. Allowed to fester, the grudge you hold can be turned on
you and then there's war in the Balkans again.
</P>
<P>
   What a notion, to clear your mind of old baggage instead of
leaving it in the middle of the room to trip over. I'm thinking of
trying it out. But I am no goody two-shoes.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
