<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GUARD UNIT TO BE DEPLOYED IN BOSNIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Mounting its first massive deployment since
1961, a Texas Army National Guard unit Thursday was making final
preparations for a nine-month peacekeeping assignment in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the deployment, ordered by President Clinton, is
a routine rotation of U.S. troops in Bosnia's American sector,
though the lengthy tour of duty is a reflection of changing times
for Guard members, who used to be known as ``weekend warriors.''
</P>
<P>
   About 700 members of the 49th Armored Division, which is based
in Austin but draws on units throughout the state, will begin
departing for Bosnia from Fort Hood on Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   A patriotic sendoff, led by Army officials and Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry, is scheduled from 2 p.m. to 4 p.m. Feb. 7 at Austin's City
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the soldiers get up to Fort Hood, we'll have the
good-byes over with, and they can do the final touch-ups on the
training. There are still a few people who have to qualify with
certain weapons,'' said Guard spokesman Lt. Col. John Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not see their families again for 270 days,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such extended stays have grown common since Desert Storm in
1990, when 166,000 National Guard members were utilized, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very clear signal what the American military was
going to look like from then on,'' Stanford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said that we were going to use the National Guard
and reserve. We started doing that in Desert Storm and we haven't
stopped,'' Stanford said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no sudden crisis in Bosnia, he said. In fact, it's been
relatively tranquil there for the past two years, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Guard members will be assigned to the U.S.
headquarters in Tuzla of ``Stabilization Force 7,'' and will take
over command from an Army division based in New York. The most
dangerous assignments, such as patrolling in tanks and Bradley
fighting vehicles, will be handled by an Army Cavalry regiment from
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Texas Guard members are male because of the legal
prohibition against females in combat roles, but women will be
handling helicopter operations, communications and other tasks,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the private-sector jobs that the Guard members will
leave behind must be waiting for them when they return. Those with
serious personal or business conflicts weren't required to go
because there were more than enough volunteers to fill the 700
slots, Stanford added.
</P>
<P>
   In its only other full deployment, the 49th Armored Division
spent 11 months at Fort Polk, La., in 1961 due to the Cuban missile
crisis and Berlin Wall tensions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
