<HEADER>
A8518 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-WINE-SALES-NYTR     01-27 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-WINE-SALES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER-END WINES LEAD A VINTAGE YEAR FOR CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
 (mk) 
 By TED APPEL   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California wineries enjoyed their best year
ever in 1999, ringing up a record $5.4 billion in sales as a strong
economy and the arrival of a new millennium inspired consumers to
celebrate with a hearty twist of the corkscrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this market as the finest we have ever had in
California,'' analyst Jon Fredrikson told a crowd of 3,000 wine
industry leaders Wednesday at the annual Unified Wine &AMP; Grape
Symposium.
</P>
<P>
   Not for every winery, however. Consumers increasingly are
turning their noses up at cheap wines, which still account for the
vast majority of production by California's diverse wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments of ``everyday wines,'' priced under $7 a bottle, grew
an anemic 1 percent last year, Fredrikson said. These low-priced
wines account for 75 percent of the state's wine production but
generate less than half of the industry's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments of premium wines, priced at $7 a bottle and higher,
jumped 13 percent last year as consumers' tastes continue to move
upward to wines of higher quality. Though they produce just 25
percent of the state's wine, premium wineries have become a cash
cow that generate 54 percent of the industry's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high end of the market is going crazy. Unfortunately, the
low end of the market is not doing well,'' Fredrikson said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, wine shipments from California increased 3 percent in
1999 to a record 442 million gallons, or 184 million cases. But in
a sign of premium wineries' growing economic power, winery revenues
rose three times as fast, jumping almost 9 percent to $5.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in premium wine sales is a direct result of the surging
U.S. economy, Fredrikson said. ``We're riding this tremendous
increase in disposable incomes. Let's hope it continues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sparkling wine sales enjoyed a resurgence in 1999 as consumers
stocked up on bubbly for millennium parties, ending a 15-year
decline in champagne sales. Sales of California and imported
sparkling wine jumped 25 percent last year, reaching 15 million
cases, Fredrikson said.
</P>
<P>
   Wine sales also were fueled last year by the release of the
giant 1997 vintage, the largest grape crop in state history. The
bumper harvest alleviated a three-year shortage of California wine
that pushed prices up sharply. Prices for premium wines have not
yet fallen significantly, however, because two subsequent smaller
crops postponed a much-anticipated glut of wine in California.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, premium vintners enjoyed the best of both worlds in
1999: High prices and ample supply.
</P>
<P>
   Varietal wine prices on the bulk market are generally steady in
most parts of California and rising in Napa and Sonoma counties,
said Richard De Los Reyes, a broker with Joseph W. Ciatti Co., a
Mill Valley bulk wine brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Wine and grape prices may fall this year as new vineyards
planted across the state come into production, said Barry Bedwell,
president of Allied Grape Growers, a Fresno trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Bedwell placed the odds of a record-breaking harvest this year
at 60 percent. California is overdue for another bumper crop, and
another 40,000 acres of vineyards will begin producing grapes this
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bedwell warned that Mother Nature could prolong the
shortage of premium wine. A lack of rain could hurt the 2000 grape
crop and increase the threat of frost damage if the grapevines
break into buds early. At the same time, growers are increasingly
worried about the spread of Pierce's disease, a deadly and
incurable bacterium carried by insects.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the giant 1997 crop has resupplied California wineries
and allowed them to staunch the flow of imported wines into the
United States. Wineries imported just 4.8 million gallons of bulk
wine from overseas last year, down from 8 million gallons in 1998
and 20.3 million gallons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tougher and tougher for imports to get the growth they
had,'' Fredrikson said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, U.S. wineries experienced a slowdown in
exports last year. Exports of U.S. wines grew just 4 percent in
1999 to 18.4 million cases, ending five years of double-digit
growth. Fredrikson called the slowdown ``a danger sign,'' reminding
vintners that foreign markets will become increasingly important if
there is a glut of wine in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times regional newspaper group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
