<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8520 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-UMASS-TUITION-BOS &LR;      01-27 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UMASS-TUITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS TUITION TO REMAIN LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The cost of attending the University of Massachusetts
will remain at current levels next year, giving what was in recent
memory one of the nation's most expensive public systems its fifth
straight year of tuition cuts or freezes.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze, which will make tuition and fees on the four
undergraduate campuses an average of $4,680 per year, are all the
more striking in contrast to national trends.
</P>
<P>
   Although California recently announced a tuition freeze for next
fall, no other state has so consistently cut its tuition. In fact,
average tuition has been rising at twice the rate of inflation, or
about 4 percent, at private and public colleges nationwide,
according to the College Board. Average student charges at UMass
will have dropped $289, or 5.8 percent, between 1995-96 and
2000-2001. Inflation during that time is expected to be about 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have steadily worked against any increases in
UMass tuition or fees _ which together make up total mandatory
charges _ for several years, trying to roll back the huge increases
of the late 1980s and early 90s. In those years, many students were
squeezed out of the state university, as state funding declined 22
percent, and tuition more than doubled. By 1994, the tail end of
the state fiscal crisis, UMass was the fourth most expensive public
university in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the trustees requested a slight increase,
Governor Cellucci threatened to withhold state funding if they did
not agree to cut overall charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an era in which many students and many families
fear that top-quality higher education is simply beyond their
means,'' UMass president William M. Bulger said. ``The good news is
that this isn't the case....a student who enters the University of
Massachusetts this fall will be paying less than a brother or
sister who enrolled in 1995 and has already graduated.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's board of higher education has final say over UMass
charges, but a dispute like last year's is not expected. Under the
package approved, undergraduate tuition and fees will be as follows
for the individual campuses: Amherst, $5,212; Boston, $4,222;
Dartmouth, $4,129; Lowell, $4,255.
</P>
<P>
   Graduate rates will be as follows: Amherst, $5,642; Boston,
$5,110; Dartmouth, $4,959; Lowell, $4,984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
