<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANDEIS-GIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA COUPLE GIVE $20 MILLION TO BRANDEIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Florida couple well-known for making gifts of their wealth has
given Brandeis University the largest single donation in its
history, school officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Carl and Ruth Shapiro, one-time Bostonians now living in Palm
Beach, have donated $20 million to the Waltham, Mass. university to
build a new student center.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the Shapiros studied at Brandeis, but school
officials said the gift, one of many the couple has given to the
liberal arts college, derives from their long interest in
bolstering Brandeis.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of wealthy Jews seeking a US university that
didn't use quotas to limit the number of Jews or other groups,
Brandeis opened in 1948 with 107 students. Today, more than 4,200
undergraduates and graduates study at Brandeis, about 60 percent of
them Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shapiros' gift is important because the existing student
center is too small for the current number of students,'' said
Dennis Nealon, a Brandeis spokesman. ``It's filling a critical
need.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shapiros have already left their mark on Brandeis, with
money for a new admissions building, a library, and professorships.
</P>
<P>
   They have also left a mark on Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, the couple gave $6 million to help pay for medical
education and research at an institute established jointly by
Harvard Medical School and Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center,
now called the Carl J. Shapiro Institute for Education and
Research. The Shapiros have also given to The Museum of Fine Arts,
where a gallery is named after them.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Shapiro, the founder and former chairman of Kay Windsor
Inc., a New Bedford, Mass. company that manufactured and imported
knitted apparel, served on Brandeis' Board of Trustees until 1988.
His daughter, Rhonda Zinner, now serves on the board.
</P>
<P>
   The Shapiros' latest gift will go to building a student center
that in 2001 will house a computer library, theater, bookstore,
cafe, and student clubs and offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Carl and Ruth Shapiro Student Center will transform the
campus,'' said Brandeis president Jehuda Reinharz. ``It will be the
signature building and the heart of student life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1905EST &QL; 
