<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-VIEQUES-NEGOTIATIONS-     01-27 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-NEGOTIATIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PUERTO RICANS, WHITE HOUSE MEET OVER VIEQUES RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHNGTON _ In an attempt to resolve a simmering dispute,
Puerto Rican officials met Thursday with White House and Defense
Department representatives over the fate of a controversial U.S.
Navy bombing range but failed to reach agreement about the future
of the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was part of an open dialog that has been ongoing since
last year,'' one administration official said of the high-level
meetings that included Angel Morey, the secretary of state for the
U.S. Commonwealth of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official said that additional meetings will
take place over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican officials want the bombing range on the small
island of Vieques permanently closed, asserting that the facility
has been a health hazard and economic drain for the island's 9,000
residents. The Navy, meanwhile has argued that the range is needed
to help train its crews and Marines for amphibious combat.
</P>
<P>
   As the meeting was getting under way Thursday, Sila Calderon,
the mayor of San Juan, blasted the Navy for its ``appalling'' and
``shameful'' treatment of the island's residents.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the widespread public support from Puerto Ricans at
home and abroad, Calderon said that the Puerto Rican officials were
pressing the Clinton administration for a permanent end to the
Navy's presence on the island, 900 acres of which the Navy has used
as a bombing range for nearly 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean facility is the only location in the eastern
United States where the Navy and Marines practice combined
amphibious landings, aerial attacks and naval gunfire support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puerto Ricans across all social, religious and political lines
have formed an unprecedented consensus and have determined that the
bombing must end and the land occupied by the Navy must be returned
to the people of Vieques,'' Calderon said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Calderon, who is a member of Puerto Rican Gov. Pedro Rossello's
task force on the future of Vieques, said Puerto Rican negotiators
were seeking from the White House a specific timetable for the Navy
withdrawal from the base; details on how that Navy would clean up
the range, which is littered with fragments of exploded ordnance;
and guarantees that any Navy withdrawal cannot be revered by a
future administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy has resisted an outright closure. Instead, the
service has proposed that the issue be put forward as a referendum
to residents of Vieques. Under the Navy proposal, the residents
would have a choice: allow the Navy and Marine Corps to resume
training with live ammunition and get $40 million in community aid
as a sweetener; or close the base within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello has rejected the Navy offer. However, Calderon left
open the possibility that Puerto Rico might still reach a
compromise with the White House and Navy. She said that some sort
of referendum was possible ``if it's put together in a way that's
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But Calderon stressed that Puerto Ricans were unwavering in
their sentiment about bombing. ``There can be no more exercises
with ammunitions of any kind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House imposed a moratorium on live-fire exercises at
the Vieques range after a civilian employee of the Navy was killed
last year in a bombing accident. The moratorium expires on March 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
