<SLUG> BC-SINAI-BEDOUIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESORT, BEDOIN CLASH IN THE SINAI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the sands of Egypt's Sinai Peninsula, the Bedouin tribes
don't settle their conflicts in a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   They work it out man-to-man, tribe-to-tribe, according to the
desert code of honor. And often that means violence.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Roger H. Rotondi Jr., 39, the Massachusetts-born
scion of a prominent Bay State political family, found out that
this ancient tribal culture still is very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   Rotondi, the grandson of three-term Massachusetts governor John
Volpe, says he ended up fleeing for his life from a tourist hotel
he owns in Egypt's Red Sea resort town of Dahab.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here, I had some romantic notions about the
Bedouin and about living here,'' said Rotondi, speaking Wednesday
on a mobile telephone after having fled to another town nearly 200
miles away. ``But I've learned my lesson. This was just pure
barbarity.''
</P>
<P>
   The story began four years ago when Rotondi invested in a resort
that specialized in diving excursions along the Red Sea's magical
coral reefs. In a play on ``Club Med'' and Red Sea, it was named
``Club Red.''
</P>
<P>
   He signed a management contract with a Bedouin tribal family
headed by Nasser Hamid and leased land and some cottages in
exchange for a percentage of the profits. Recently, however, the
relationship soured _ Rotondi would not go into the details _ and
Hamid began threatening Rotondi and his staff, the American said,
pressuring Rotondi to leave the resort.
</P>
<P>
   It came to a head Monday in a confrontation on the Gulf of
Aqaba, he said, in a scene that sounded straight out of the
Hollywood classic ``Lawrence of Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   At high noon, the resort was surrounded by about 50 members of
the Bedouin clan dressed in traditional Bedouin ``jalibiyas'' and
``kaffiyehs'' (robes and head scarves) and armed with sticks,
stones, and broken bottles, he said. They took over the hotel,
threatened the staff, and threw his desk and papers out of his
office while startled guests watched.
</P>
<P>
   Rotondi said he and the staff were attacked, and two employees
were hospitalized with serious facial cuts and bruises. The Bedouin
then occupied the management offices and cut the phone lines and
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Rotondi claimed local police came with the tribe and did nothing
to stop the attack. When he sought help from more senior police
officials, he said, he was met with a shrug of the shoulders and a
sense that Bedouin law prevented them from acting. Instead, the
Egyptians pushed him to try and work out a ``sulha,'' or truce,
with the Bedouin ``sheikh,'' an ancestral leader with wide
authority over the families of the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Rotondi said he has master's degree from the Fletcher School of
Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, but it didn't really come in
handy in this conflict. Fearing for their lives, Rotondi and his
staff holed up in the hotel for most of two days before escaping
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not some quaint, traditional Bedouin,'' Rotondi said
of Hamid. ``This is a powerful local guy who uses violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy rides a 1999 Mercedes, not a camel,'' he said, adding
that Hamid travels with an entourage that includes his attorney as
well as menacing toughs from his extended family.
</P>
<P>
   There was no answer Thursday on the phone at the resort. Hamid
could not be reached. David Ballard, the US Embassy spokesman in
Cairo, said the embassy had been contacted by Rotondi and it was
assisting him, but Ballard said he could not comment on the
specifics of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Three days ago, Rotondi wrote a letter to Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, his government's tourism minister, and other senior
Egyptian officials seeking assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared for myself and my partners and colleagues. We are
alone. The biggest Bedouin family in the area and the police are
against us,'' he wrote, in a letter in which he mentions his
grandfather's political career, his past work for the United
Nations, and his education.
</P>
<P>
   Rotondi's grandfather on his mother's side, John Volpe, was a
construction industry magnate who became a fixture in Massachusetts
Republican politics. He was elected governor in 1960 and later
served two more terms. He was named US Secretary of Transportation
in the Nixon White House and later appointed ambassador to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Rotondi said that after graduating from the Fletcher Shool at
Tufts University, he went to the Middle East to work with a United
Nations agency assisting Palestinians in the West Bank. He often
took the roughly six-hour drive to the Red Sea resorts in Dahab for
vacation, and fell in love with the place.
</P>
<P>
   It is an internationally known destination for deep sea divers
who prize the unique reefs where the Gulf of Aqaba meets the Red
Sea. It has five-star resorts as well as many small camps
frequented by a young crowd of tie-dye-wearing Americans and
Europeans drawn by the place's reputation for readily available
hashish.
</P>
<P>
   The tourist community rubs elbows with the camps of local
Bedouin, many of whom still live a nomadic existence herding camels
and goats in the desert expanse. Bedouin hospitality is legendary,
and guests are eagerly invited into their tents for tiny cups of
bitter coffee. But they are also not to be crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have my own experience of investing in a local
economy,'' he says. ``And it's turned out to be quite an
experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
