<SLUG> BC-THAILAND-MYANMAR-ART-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYANMAR TROOPS SAID TO SEIZE BASE OF REBELS WHO TOOK THAI
HOSTAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ The small jungle base of God's Army, the
Burmese rebel band that took hundreds of people hostage at a Thai
hospital this week, was overrun by the army of Myanmar on Thursday,
Thai officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dissidents living outside Myanmar, formerly known as Burma, said
the base was captured early Thursday morning. They said that 50
people had been captured but that the fate of the twin 12-year-old
boys said to lead the group, Johnny and Luther Htoo, was not
immediately known.
</P>
<P>
   Ten gunmen from the group, which is made up of ethnic Karen
separatist fighters, were killed Tuesday after taking hundreds of
people hostage for 22 hours in a hospital in the Thai border town
of Ratchaburi.
</P>
<P>
   Thai human rights groups are demanding an investigation into
reports that the gunmen were summarily executed by security forces
who raided the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Thai newspapers quoted unidentified commandos as acknowledging
that they had shot some of the gunmen in the head even when they
were not acting aggressively. They said they had done this in the
heat of a fast-moving pre-dawn attack to protect their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamentalist Christian band of no more than 200 fighters
had been under intense attack at their hideout inside Myanmar for
the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen who took over the hospital had sought to stop
Thailand from adding its own artillery attacks, which the Thais
said were intended to prevent them from fleeing across the border.
</P>
<P>
   A Thai intelligence officer told The Associated Press that about
100 of the fighters fled their camp Thursday, with the twin boys
leading one of two groups.
</P>
<P>
   God's Army is a splinter group from the main Karen separatist
group, the Karen National Union, which is one of several ethnic
insurgencies that continue to battle the government despite a
series of peace agreements during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Karen National Union issued a statement Thursday saying that
its longtime leader, Bo Mya, 73, had been removed from command. It
said the decision had been made at a previously scheduled
leadership meeting and had nothing to do with the actions of the
God's Army group.
</P>
<P>
   The larger insurgency claims to have 12,000 fighters along the
1,000-mile border between Thailand and Myanmar. Independent
estimates put the number closer to 3,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the wake of the takeover, police in Ratchaburi said
unidentified callers had made bomb threats against another local
hospital as well as a school and a department store.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said schoolchildren and shoppers had gone out into the
streets as the buildings were searched.
</P>
<P>
   If the Htoo twins are still alive and at liberty, it was not
clear Thursday what their ragtag insurgency might have the strength
to do next. It has little support among other insurgencies or
Burmese dissidents, who depend on Thailand for sanctuary along the
border. The Karen National Union joined a virtually unanimous
condemnation by Burmese dissident groups of the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Already driven to the desperate move of taking over a hospital,
the small, poorly trained band was apparently divided and on the
run Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even the larger insurgencies have been on the defensive for
several years. In the early 1990s the Karen fighters lost all their
main bases and now no longer control any significant population
centers.
</P>
<P>
   After the hospital takeover, Thai public sentiment has turned
strongly against the rebel groups and the 100,000 refugees taking
shelter in camps just inside Thailand.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
