<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-EYE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      01-27 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EYE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUDICROUS SCRIPT LEADS TO A BLACK `EYE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Saturday, Jan. 29. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
 
 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Eye of the Beholder'' raises a number of interesting
questions, including: Are bathrooms on trains really hermetically
sealed? Can one be charged with leaving the scene of a crime if one
didn't see it happen and had nothing to do with it? If this is
America, why do so many people have European accents and the
buildings all look 200 years old? Unfortunately, these aren't the
sorts of things you should be stopping to question in a slickly
made thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Ewan McGregor (young Obi-Wan Kenobi in ``The Phantom Menace'')
and Ashley Judd (``Double Jeopardy'') star in this convoluted tale
of an intelligence agent hired to track a killer, for whom he
quickly develops an obsession. McGregor's character, known as The
Eye, follows Judd's Joanna Eris, a woman of many identities, on a
killing spree across America. Rather than turning her in, he
decides he must protect and marry her.
</P>
<P>
   Problem No. 1 is that McGregor is simply too young for the role.
The Eye is apparently driven by the loss of his daughter; it's not
entirely clear, but it seems his wife took the child with her and
left the secret agent man because he was too focused on his work
(something one would think a woman would expect, entering into a
union with such a man). The Eye's obsession with Joanna is
supposedly triggered by her similarity to his daughter _ who, when
we see her in fantasy sequences, is about 20 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   The other major problem is the script's many cliches
masquerading as stylistic touches. There are occasional fun twists
_ making singer k.d. lang The Eye's agency contact, and emphasizing
The Eye's role as a low-rent James Bond with cell phones that stop
working and communicators that resemble old TV sets _ but not
enough. A motif of the American flag seems a rather desperate
attempt to make Montreal look like America, and poor Genevieve
Bujold is stuck in the silly role of a tough older woman who taught
(and probably did a lot more than that with) Eris in a juvenile
detention facility years prior to the story's setting.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bergen has a small part as a wealthy blind man whom Eris
seems to genuinely fall in love with, because, as she tells him,
``You can't see who I really am.'' Ex-``90210'' star Jason
Priestley does a nice turn as a Brad Pitt-in-``Fight Club''-like,
bleached-blond psychopath.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Beholder'' just has too many ludicrous moments to remain
compelling to the viewer. Marketed as a sexy, stylish romp with two
attractive young stars, the film doesn't even deliver on that
score. Though we see Judd in a couple of sexy lingerie ensembles,
there's really no sex or chemistry ... and she's not even shot in a
flattering light. Even when she's supposed to be attracting
unwitting men like bees to honey, she appears somewhat haggard. She
is well-dressed, though: Valentino is credited with supplying her
wardrobe, lingerie and eyewear. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Eye of the Beholder'' (R; some strong violence,
sexuality, language and brief drug content). &QL; 
The stars: Ewan McGregor, Ashley Judd. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Stephan Elliott.
Produced by Nicolas Clermont and Tony Smith. Released by
Destination Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 50 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
