<HEADER>
A8541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      01-27 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST TREASURY PRICES FALL ON EXPECTATION OF HIGHER RATES  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury bond prices, with the exception of the
30-year bond, were lower Thursday after the December durable goods
report showed that factory orders had their largest increase in
five months.
</P>
<P>
   The report reinforced market expectations that the Federal
Reserve would increase short-term interest rates in the coming
months to slow economic expansion and keep inflation from
accelerating _ thus hurting fixed-income investments.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the long bond was up 22/32, to 94 28/32,
as the yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.52
percent, from 6.57 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With shorter maturities down in price Thursday, the long
maturity managed to hang onto the gains made over the last four
days. The long bond was benefiting from optimism among market
participants that the central bank would remain vigilant about
inflation. It was also helped by the dwindling supply of
longer-term securities, after the Treasury cut its sales. The
Treasury will buy back some longer-term debt later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yields of shorter maturities, the most vulnerable of the
Treasuries to expectations that the Federal Reserve will raise
rates, gained after the report showed that durable goods orders
surged 4.1 percent last month. Orders gained 1 percent in November.
Analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News had expected a 1 percent gain
for December.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries were restrained by initial jobless claims of 266,000
last week, which were fewer than the 277,000 expected by
economists, a result that hinted at inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said that bond market participants overwhelmingly expect monetary
policy to be tightened by another 25 basis points at a
policy-setting meeting on Tuesday ``as the Fed continues on its
pre-emptive anti-inflationary course in the face of what it
considers to be excessively strong economic growth amid extremely
low employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other reports are scheduled to be released Friday: the
Employment Cost Index (ECI) for December, and the initial estimates
of real gross domestic product growth and the gross domestic
product price index for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wage pressures have been rather modest up to this point,''
Fine said, ``but part of the reason is that we are currently in a
demand-pull inflation environment as opposed to a cost-pull
situation, which means that wage upticks are likely to lag, rather
than lead, overall increases in inflation. As a result many market
participants will tend to put more emphasis on the expected
continued strength in the broadest measure of economic growth and
its price component, although the ECI will hardly be overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy is expected to show a 5.2 percent annual growth rate
in the final three months of 1999, according to some economists,
who also expect the Employment Cost Index, which measures wages,
salaries and benefits, to show an increase of 0.9 percent in the
fourth quarter of 1999, from 0.8 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the inversion in the Treasury yield curve has become
more pronounced, as the 30-year bond continues to gain relative to
the rest of the maturities as a result of the Treasury's announced
buyback program and the anticipated reduction in supply in the
longer maturities in the Treasury market.
</P>
<P>
   After having its worst year on record in 1999, the long bond has
earned investors 2.4 percent in the last week alone, including
reinvested interest payments. Last year it fell almost 13 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
