<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK'S PARTY UNDER INVESTIGATION OVER CAMPAIGN FINANCING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a scandal that could weaken Prime Minister Ehud
Barak at a critical juncture in the Middle East peace process,
Israel's attorney general opened a criminal investigation Thursday
into the campaign finance practices used by Barak's political party
during last year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The probe came in response to a report released by State
Comptroller Eliezer Goldberg that accused Barak's One Israel Party
of setting up nonprofit organizations to receive large
contributions, which he said violated Israel's campaign-finance
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that in the weeks leading up to last May's
general election, 12 of Israel's 15 political parties had broken
laws limiting the amount of money that an individual can donate.
But it singled out Barak's party as the worst offender and held the
prime minister responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Barak defeated Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of the Likud
party in the election, and Barak's coalition formed a parliamentary
government in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I determined clearly that the law was broken,'' said Goldberg
in presenting the report to Israel's Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Barak denied knowledge of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know most of the non-profit organizations,'' he said
at a hastily called press conference. ``I wasn't involved in fund
raising, and I wasn't kept up to speed about the activities
described in the report.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Israel's campaign-finance laws were vague but added that
he did not have any problem with an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the probe could undermine Barak's ability to move ahead
on an ambitious peacemaking agenda with the Palestinians and the
Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians broke off peace talks last month and have refused to
set a date for a resumption, and the Palestinians have criticized
the Israelis for what they term a lack of attention to negotiations
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has has set his sights on achieving a peace deal with
Syria by July, and he has expressed hopes to negotiate an outline
of a final peace treaty with the Palestinians by Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein said it was too early to
know whether Barak would be questioned about the contributions, but
he added, ``Every relevant person will be investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Goldberg, the state comptroller, blamed Barak for
failing in what he implied was Barak's duty to stop campaign
financing abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough for the prime ministerial candidate to direct
his people to work within the framework of the law,'' Goldberg
wrote. ``Rather, he must concern himself with activity in the field
to ensure his directives are carried out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The wide-ranging spectrum of activity should have
lit a red warning light for (Barak) and motivated him to check that
the campaign for which he was responsible was run according to
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The One Israel Party raised $1.3 million through nonprofit
organizations, according to the report, and has already been fined
$3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Several other parties that violated campaign-finance laws also
received fines, and four of them _ the opposition Likud Party, a
Russian immigrant party called Israel Beitenu, the Center Party and
the ultra-Orthodox United Torah Judaism party _ were also put under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Likud leader Ariel Sharon, glossing over the investigation of
his own party, accused Barak of ``buying his office'' and of
personal involvement in the fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   Limor Livnat, a Likud member of Parliament, mocked Barak for
maintaining that he had no knowledge of his campaign finance
practices and said she doubted he could run the country if he
couldn't properly oversee his own election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a prime minister is even more difficult than being a
candidate,`` Livnat said. ``How can he deal with all these
important issues that Israelis facing (if he can't run his
campaign)?''
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller's report said the One Israel Party had received
contributions from, among others, a Swiss millionaire and a
Canadian charity. It said the money was used by the prime
minister's associates, including his brother-in-law, Doron Cohen,
to cover such expenses as polling voters, printing campaign
materials and recruiting volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Likud officials alleged that some of the money was channeled
through companies set up in Panama, Bermuda and the United States
to avoid detection. Goldberg said that his investigation extended
beyond Israel's borders, but he refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The probe into One Israel comes on the heels of a high-profile
political scandal involving Israeli President Ezer Weizman, accused
of possible tax evasion and failing to report millions of dollars
in cash gifts from a French millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman has admitted accepting hundreds of thousands of dollars
from Edouard Sarousi between 1988 and 1993, the year he became
president, but has denied that the money was a bribe. Despite the
police investigation, Weizman has refused to leave office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
