<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY BURIED THE HATCHET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peace at last for our own little version of ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him up and told him it was Darth Vader calling, and
Bob laughed,'' Bill Parcells said of the first step toward ending
his long-running feud with Patriots owner Bob Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hatchets have been buried,'' said Parcells. ``The border
war is over. In fact, when I called Bob that first night (Tuesday),
I told him I thought it was time to end the border war. He agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better about our relationship right now than I have. I
know from my part there's a good feeling about him, and I think
it's the same way with Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Darth Vader?
</P>
<P>
   That's the nickname the assistant coaches on Pete Carroll's
staff gave Parcells because of the fear/contempt with which he was
held at Foxboro. They kiddingly referred to the Jets as the Evil
Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was amused when he learned of the Darth Vader label,
and used it to open his first conversation with Kraft in nearly
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells decided to reach out to Kraft after Bill Belichick's
bid to gain a temporary restraining order against the Jets, freeing
him to negotiate with other teams, was denied by a federal judge
Tuesday. ``I didn't want to see him out of football, and knowing
that Bob liked him, I thought that Bob didn't want that either,''
Parcells said. ``So I made the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the first 30 minutes mending fences, and then
we talked about Belichick. Bob said he still had interest, but
would like to get something done fast, because if we couldn't, he
had to move on and get something done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a few good laughs about some of the things that
happened. I told him that I'd wished things had turned out
differently when I left New England, and I think he felt the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed (compensation) ideas. I told him what I wanted
and he didn't want to do that, so we both agreed to think about it.
The next day, Bob didn't call so I thought it was over, that we
couldn't make a deal. But Bob called back late that night
(Wednesday), and we made the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots gave up their No. 1 pick in this year's draft (16th
overall), a fourth-round choice in 2001, and a seventh-rounder in
2002. New England received the Jets' No. 5 pick in 2001, a
seventh-round pick in 2002 _ and Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the situation was reversed, I would have done the same
thing,'' Parcells said. ``Belichick is a good man. He'll do a good
job up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday morning I spoke with Belichick twice on the phone. I
told him what was happening. I told him I didn't want to see him
out of football, and he said he appreciated that. We talked again
after the trade was passed by the league, and I wished him well and
told him to go up there and show what he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells also said, ``I want to feel good about going back to
New England and be able to sit in that stadium and watch a game. I
loved my time in New England. I left a lot of my blood there. We
were getting very close to doing some special things when I left
there. I wish now it could've ended differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was asked if he thought he'd ever be invited to Kraft's
luxury box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I wanted to, I think I might,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The finalization of the deal took some time because of its
unusual features, a coach being exchanged for draft picks. Kraft
and Parcells first put together a letter of agreement to release
Belichick from his Jets contract that had to be approved by NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Then Andy Wasnyczuk, representing New England, and Mike
Tannenbaum of the Jets, each team's salary cap expert, put in
writing the compensation agreement Kraft and Parcells had reached.
Parcells said he pressed for a No. 1 pick because he didn't have
room under the salary cap to sign veterans.
</P>
<P>
   When that was done, Belichick was on his way to Foxboro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
