<SLUG> BC-MA-CLEAN-AIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TAKES CLEAN-AIR CASE TO SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Opening a new front in a high-stakes legal battle over
the nation's air-pollution problem, Massachusetts Attorney General
Tom Reilly appealed Thursday directly to the US Supreme Court to
clear the way for tough new federal limits on smog and soot to take
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington last year overturned
the proposed health standards _ generally opposed by Midwestern and
Southern states, but supported in the Northeast _ finding that the
EPA had exceeded its authority to limit pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But Reilly, working with New Jersey Attorney General John J.
Farmer, filed an unusual petition at the Supreme Court to reinstate
the smog and soot limits, claiming they would save 15,000 lives a
year and ease breathing problems for 1.5 million. The American Lung
Association made a similar appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an urgent need to implement these stringent federal
clean air standards for Massachusetts residents, especially
children,'' Reilly said. ``We urge the Supreme Court to review the
lower court's decision on this important public health issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court rejects the vast majority of petitions to
overturn lower court decisions, but Reilly's office said the
gravity of the health issues and the narrow technical nature of the
lower court decision made them confident the Supreme Court would at
least hear their case.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has been trying for years to adopt stricter limits on
the key ingredient in smog, ozone, as well as fine particles of
soot that can deeply penetrate lung tissues. But Midwestern and
Southern states, allied with a wide array of industries, have
opposed the standards, arguing they weren't based on sound science
and would be too expensive to implement.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Court of Appeals rejected the new standards last May,
EPA Administrator Carol Browner has looked for other ways to attack
the problem such as ordering 392 high-polluting power plants and
industrial facilities to reduce emissions. However, Massachusetts
officials said tougher national standards would be more effective
at reducing Midwestern air pollution that travels on the wind to
this region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sick of breathing the Midwest's secondhand smoke,''
said Environmental Affairs Secretary Robert Durand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
