<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HE PURSUES THE WHITE HOUSE, BUSH PINES FOR THE GOVERNOR'S
MANSION  
 MORE DEGREES OF SEPARATION 
WORDS COUNT IN A CAMPAIGN _ EVEN IN SONG
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, N.H. _ Anyone who attended George W. Bush's campaign
events over the last few days heard a number of familiar themes,
from tax cuts to defense spending, education to tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   But he or she perhaps picked up on something less predictable as
well: Bush is homesick.
</P>
<P>
   During a speech on Tuesday night, the Texas governor lapsed into
a reverie about the morning rituals he misses and how long it had
been since he visited the swath of land in Texas where he and his
wife, Laura, are building a ranch.
</P>
<P>
   At other times he talked about his cats. He pined for his dog.
</P>
<P>
   He was off his game on Tuesday, and again on Wednesday, and
again Thursday. He sniffled through speeches. At one point,
characterizing the relationship between the United States and
Israel, Bush mused, ``They're our buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, visiting an elementary school in Nashua that was
celebrating what it called Perseverance Month, he told the gathered
schoolchildren: ``This is Preservation Month. I appreciate
preservation. This is what you do when you run for president.
You've got to preserve.''
</P>
<P>
   And the most difficult part of that endeavor, he said, was being
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   It all made for an interesting contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore comes off as one of the most ardent,
ambitious aspirants to the Oval Office in quite some time, a man
who would crawl across broken glass to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Bush comes off as a man who wants it, but not at any price, and
sometimes not as much as he wants to wake up in his own bed at the
governor's mansion in Austin, Texas, wander downstairs to make a
pot of coffee, let out the pets, and fetch the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, just maybe, that is one of the reasons why many
Americans like him.
</P>
<P>
   More Degrees of Separation
</P>
<P>
   Bush is happy to separate himself from both Gore and President
Clinton, and has been more aggressive about it lately.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a new line appeared in his speeches, and that does
not happen too often. To rally Republican voters in Iowa, Bush
began talking about what this election really means.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of the end of the Clinton era,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a freighted statement, because one of the signals it sent
to Republican voters was that if they wanted the White House back,
as they surely did, it was time to unite around the front-runner
and send him into the general election as unscathed and unbowed as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   It also made a tacit claim to morality at the same time that
Bush was facing questions about abortion and giving answers that
might not be wholly satisfying to religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's victory speech after the Iowa caucuses on Monday
night, he went a step further, not only referring to the Clinton
era but also appealing to Americans ``weary of scandals and
alibis.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in Concord, someone in the audience played into
his hands, asking Bush how he would handle the baggage of Clinton's
behavior if he were in Gore's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have been in his position,'' Bush said. ``I
wouldn't have accepted the vice presidency under Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, when he was asked a similar question by a reporter,
Bush said of Gore: ``I don't think he can figure out how to handle
his relationship with the president. He distances, he doesn't
distance. He distances, he doesn't distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Words Count In a Campaign _ Even in Song
</P>
<P>
   In the semiotics of political campaigns, perhaps nothing is as
revealing as the music that plays at a candidate's events. Bush's
aides have assembled an entire soundtrack, which made its debut
last week, and the song list is almost a synopsis of Bush's persona
and strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Bamba'' is on it, with Spanish lyrics that evoke both
Bush's ability to speak the language and his outreach to
Hispanic-American voters.
</P>
<P>
   The singer John Fogerty's ``Centerfield'' is on it, a reminder
that Bush loves baseball, was once the managing general partner of
the Texas Rangers and is ``ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of country and western, for that down-home,
folksy feel. There is a bit of mild disco, just to show that Bush
can groove.
</P>
<P>
   Van Morrison's ``Bright Side of the Road'' telegraphs Bush's
optimism, while Tom Petty's ``I Won't Back Down'' claims a certain
degree of tenacity, his homesickness notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   And Sting's ``A Brand New Day'' promises precisely that. Never
mind that the song is more romantically than politically inclined.
</P>
<P>
   After a miscue several weeks go, when ``Cat's Cradle,'' about a
son who grows up to be like his aloof father, played at several
campaign appearances, all the lyrics were carefully vetted this
time around.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why one aide's suggestion, Sheryl Crow's ``A Change
Would Do You Good,'' did not make the cut. Upon closer examination,
a vigilant member of the Bush staff realized that the song included
a reference to, um, self-gratification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
