<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO WATCH IF FOOTBALL ISN'T YOUR BAG
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Sunday, Jan. 30 _ today is Sunday in this
story. All times PST) 
 
 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's more deadly for a TV programmer than having to go up
against ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''? Having to schedule
something opposite the Super Bowl, which regularly attracts more
than 60 percent of the total viewing audience.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with those kinds of numbers, networks that compete with
ABC _ which airs the Super Bowl this year _ have two choices. They
can throw up their hands, or put on counter-programming.
</P>
<P>
   That means lots of chick flicks, reruns and goofy stunts. If you
want to see women being clairvoyant (``The Butcher's Wife''), going
crazy (``Frances''), nearly drowning (``Titanic'') or just being
bitchy (``Jezebel''), today's your day. Ditto if you've been pining
for the return of the short-lived ``Brady Bunch'' spin-off ``The
Brady Brides.''
</P>
<P>
   In the stunts department, MTV continues its tradition of
claymation tastelessness with back-to-back episodes of ``Celebrity
Deathmatch'' _ including a stop-motion face-off between Joe Namath
and O.J. Simpson _ and Cartoon Network delivers its now-traditional
cartoon marathon (this year, Road Runner vs. Wile E. Coyote) with
``color commentary'' by John Madden and Pat Summerall.
</P>
<P>
   And in possibly the ultimate combination of chick viewing,
reruns and stunts, CBS airs a 2 1/2-hour marathon of ``Martha
Stewart Living.'' How come guys get to prove their manhood by
sitting around in their undershirts eating chips, while the gals
feel compelled to create elaborate centerpieces out of birch twigs,
French ribbon and wildflowers?
</P>
<P>
   Following are details of some of these TV highlights. Nothing
here for you? Well, there's always a football game on ABC. The
pregame show starts at 3:15 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central: An ``Absolutely Fabulous'' marathon. Joanna
Lumley and Jennifer Saunders are the two unlikable stars of this
outrageous British sitcom that ran in the '90s. (until 7:30 p.m.) 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoon Network: ``Road Runner vs. Coyote: Big Game XXVIII.''
Warner Bros. cartoon marathon, with some sly extras, including a
``pregame show'' hosted by HBO's Len Dawson, Nick Buonoconti, Jerry
Glanville and Cris Collinsworth. (until 5 p.m.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MTV: ``Celebrity Deathmatch'' marathon begins (until 6 p.m.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Family Channel: ``The Brady Brides'' marathon starts with
``The Brady Girls Get Married.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sci-Fi Channel: ``The Butcher's Wife,'' 1991 movie starring
Demi Moore and Jeff Daniels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FX: ``The Accused,'' 1988 movie starring Jodie Foster and Kelly
McGillis.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime: ``Frances,'' 1982 movie starring Jessica Lange and Sam
Shepard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CBS: ``Martha Stewart Living'' marathon begins (until 5:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Cinemax: ``Titanic,'' 1997 movie starring Leonardo DiCaprio and
Kate Winslet.
</P>
<P>
   HBO: ``Dead Poets Society,'' 1989 movie starring Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Classic Movies: ``Jezebel,'' 1938 movie starring Bette
Davis and Henry Fonda. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !folo!4:30 p.m.
</P>
