<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8563 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-HUMMER28-COX     01-27 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vermeil a champ in the crying game
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLABTA _It can happen almost any time. A quarterback wrecks his
knee, a big game is won, a sentimental notion flutters across his
frontal lobe, heck, a bird sings or a baby coos _ and Dick Vermeil
springs a leak.
</P>
<P>
   Did Vince Lombardi cry? Or Knute Rockne? Don Shula was granite
from the chin up.
</P>
<P>
   But Vermeil is a different kind of coach, and you can read that
in the tracks of his tears.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose Sunday, the St. Louis Waterworks probably will be
open. He hasn't been afraid to cry to date; no reason he'll hold
back come the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been an emotional person, regardless of whether it
applies to football or not,'' the Rams' sensitive guy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just me. Sometimes I've evaluated that as a weakness.
It's embarrassing sometimes. I can't help myself sometimes. I have
prepared myself emotionally and mentally not to do it, and I still
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   All healthy, a resident expert says. ``He seems like a man who
is confident and sure of who he is,'' said Carole Kant, assistant
professor in Emory's Department of Psychiatry and Behavioral
Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crying used to be thought of as the woman's privilege,'' Kant
said, ``But as we are becoming more astute, we are becoming more
accepting of a man's ability to show emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Let it out, guys. If the NFL sack leader can get misty, who are
we to stay all stoic? ``I'm a crier. I watch `Forrest Gump' or
`Green Mile' and its, `Waaaa!''' Rams defensive end Kevin Carter
said.
</P>
<P>
   His buddy on the line teetered on the brink. ``I got choked up
last week at the thought of going to the Super Bowl, but it was
very brief,'' Grant Wistrom said. A couple of more years with
Vermeil, and he'll loosen up. The coach could make Barbara Walters
cry.
</P>
<P>
   Possessing no lame ducts, Vermeil is football's undisputed
champion of the constricted throat and dewy eyes. Although, this
week, he has held tight rein on the impulse. I had considered
trying to prompt an outburst, asking something like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, what did you think about the ending to `Old Yeller?'''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Dick, any thoughts on motherhood?'' But football questions
kept getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, he'll show the soft side in a victory speech, or
during a team meeting or reading some syrupy note from a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, it was very difficult for the players to get used
to,'' Rams cornerback Todd Lyght said. ``I remember we had the
first team meeting, and he was talking about some of his past
players and the emotional ties he had to them. When he got
emotional, guys were a little bit disturbed, because they didn't
know how to react. But after you get to know Dick as a person, you
get to know he's like that, and you just let it go.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times when he starts getting choked up, guys
will be like, ``Hold on, coach, don't let it go.' Teasing him a
little bit. So, he gives it his best effort not to let it bother
him too much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just talking about a guy who's really passionate about
people,'' linebacker Todd Collins said. ``It's a shame people make
a big deal out of it. It shouldn't have to be an odd thing. We live
in such a cynical world that people take that as a sign of
weakness. I think it's a sign of strength.'' ``I don't see it as
any sign other than that's who I am,'' Vermeil said. ``That's just
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Any eminent Emory psychiatrist will tell you that a little
crying can be good for you. There is one other benefit that might
persuade even the most leathery tough guy to give the sensitive man
thing a try.
</P>
<P>
   Kant said, ``That's the kind of man women like.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
