<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8564 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-MCCAIN-SPI &LR;      01-27 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S FREEWHEELING CAMPAIGN STRIKES A CHORD IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDONDERRY, N.H. _ Rolling down the highway aboard his bus, the
``Straight Talk Express,'' Sen. John McCain is on his way to yet
another town meeting, 104 so far in New Hampshire and counting.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sits with his wife, Cindy, telling jokes about his
``second or third grade'' proficiency at the computer and arguing
that George W. Bush's tax cut plan ``doesn't provide one penny'' to
pay down the national debt. He makes a gutteral exploding bomb
sound when asked to describe the reaction last summer when House
Republicans took a $793 billion tax cut proposal to the American
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs won't eat it,'' McCain said, likening the tax plan to a
much-promoted pet food that gathers dust on grocery store shelves.
McCain doesn't mention that he cast a reluctant vote for the tax
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The former Navy pilot and Vietnam POW has brought a breezy,
wing-it style to the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And here on the snow-packed streets of New Hampshire, his
``Straight Talk Express'' is threatening to run Bush off the easy
road to the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show McCain with a lead over the Texas governor, but
McCain shrugs it off. ``Whether it's enough, whether it'll last, I
don't know,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   In this retail phase of the presidential race, thousands of New
Hampshire voters get to meet, question and take the measure of the
candidates. They are showing up in crowds of 400 to 500 to hear
McCain. In the old Navy phrase, many like the cut of his jib.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made his own way, not like that whippersnapper (Bush),''
said Bill Fellows, a cab driver. ``Even in his family, he had to
work his way up. He proved himself.'' (McCain is the son and
grandson of Navy admirals.) An independent who once backed Bill
Clinton, Fellows plans to vote for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's town meetings have a breezy spontaniety lacking in an
era of sound bites and bland stump speeches. Audiences do not get
canned answers. The candidate often disagrees with questioners. The
questioners are invited to speak their minds.
</P>
<P>
   As freezing rain fell outside, putting an icy layer atop the
day's snowfall, a Londonderry retiree named Bob Kaszynski
reflected: ``People really struggled to get here. And I don't hear
anybody saying, `I wish this was over, I want to watch the
ballgame'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the framers of the Constitution intend the separation of
God and the state?'' a pipe organ builder named James Stewart asked
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they did,'' the Arizona senator replied.
</P>
<P>
   He added that America's founders intended that Judeo-Christian
values play an integral part in how the government functioned, and
noted that the Senate begins each day's business with a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   There followed a typical shaft of McCain wit. ``It's very hard
to do the Lord's work in the city of Satan,'' he pointed out,
referring to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   McCain concluded by saying that he would never force anyone to
say a prayer, or put anyone unwillingly in a room where prayers
were being said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart disagreed with McCain but was impressed at the
completeness of his answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to choose between this man, who impresses me greatly,
and Alan Keyes whose position on God in the nation I agree with.
I'm not sure,'' he said. Keyes is a former diplomat and radio host
running on a platform of restoring morality in America.
</P>
<P>
   Frontrunners Bush and McCain present a contrast in themes and
styles. The Texas governor gives the impression that every word he
speaks has been carefully vetted, such as an oft-stated promise to
``rally the armies of compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is sounding themes usually heard from a candidate who
has wrapped up his party's nomination. ``I will be a uniter, not a
divider,'' he tells audiences.
</P>
<P>
   In a jab at President Clinton, Bush promises that once
inaugurated he will ``uphold the honor and dignity of the office to
which I have been elected.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Straight Talk Express, by contrast, the conversation
swings around to who in a McCain administration would be
responsible for firing underperforming officials. ``Cindy,''' joked
McCain. ``She's a snake.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush takes a limited number of questions, trying to keep
attention on his theme of the day. McCain talks freely and for
hours on his bus. GOP consultant Mike Murphy carries a kazoo, which
he threatens to sound if anybody asks the same ``gotcha question''
seven times in a row.
</P>
<P>
   There also are serious differences, $200 billion worth of them,
between the GOP frontrunners. Bush promises that a $483 billion
across-the-board tax cut will be the centerpiece of his presidency.
He jabs at McCain with TV ads about ``Washington, D.C.,
politicians'' who want to keep the money in the capital and spend
it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain would use the federal budget surplus differently. About
$260 billion would go to a tax cut targeted to the middle class.
``I want to move the 15 percent tax bracket up to $70,000 a year; I
want to eliminate the marriage penalty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under McCain's plan, a big chunk of the federal surplus would be
used to guarantee the longterm viability of Medicare and Social
Security. McCain would also rapidly pay down the national debt.
McCain also is talking about areas of federal responsibility that
have been neglected, such as the $6 billion repair backlog in
America's national parks.
</P>
<P>
   McCain remains proudly conservative. ``I support overturning Roe
v. Wade,'' he said, referring to the 1973 Supreme Court ruling that
legalized abortion. McCain would permit abortion in cases of rape,
incest or threat to the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Although he proclaims Teddy Roosevelt a hero, and helped write
two Arizona wilderness bills, McCain takes strong exception to
Clinton's recent proclamation of two new national monuments in
Arizona. Nor does he like how the Clinton administration is moving
to protect 50 million acres of roadless, undeveloped national
forest land.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a conservative, I believe in consultation with local
people,'' he said. ``If you want to rule by edict, fine, but that's
not the way government should work. What he (Clinton) did was
alienate large numbers of citizens who live, work and recreate (in
the monuments). We would have put a lot of that land into
preservation status. We were working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also pounding at the need for campaign finance reform
and special interests. He has managed to make the issue resonate
among voters by delivering a litany of special interest efforts in
Washington, D.C., including some from members of his own party. A
few are sweethearts of Senate Majority leader Trent Lott. Last
year, McCain also mentioned Washington Sen. Slade Gorton's
amendment on behalf of a proposed gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign themes are being heard elsewhere. McCain
opposes any tax on Internet commerce; Bush has come out for
extending the moratorium now in place. Speaking last week on
``Larry King Live,'' Bush talked of Americans devoting themselves
to ``causes greater than their own self-interest.'' The phrase is a
mainstay of McCain's stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of cases where he (Bush) has taken a position
similar to mine, but I attribute it to enlightenment rather than
mimicry,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond New Hampshire, McCain remains an underdog. Bush is
massively funded and organized. And Republicans have a reputation
as royalists when it comes to picking nominees. No insurgent
candidate has gained the nomination since another outspoken
Arizonan, Barry Goldwater, in 1964. Hence, McCain must put together
a string of victories starting in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   McCain makes light of the daunting challenge, noting that
Arizona had produced Goldwater as well as Democrats Morris Udall
and Bruce Babbitt _ all admired but unsuccessful presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona may be the one state in the nation where mothers can't
tell their children that they may grow up to be president of the
United States,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Joel Connelly
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8160
</P>
<P>
   or joelconnelly &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
