<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-NFC-PASS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Making the grade: It'll be pass or fail
</P>
<P>
   By Curtis Bunn
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Isaac Bruce smiled, which was an accomplishment in
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there were always boos,'' he said. ``I thought
they were saying, `Bruuuce.'''
</P>
<P>
   Usually stoic, Bruce amused himself with that line and flashed a
grin, however brief. He was referring to the old days in St. Louis
when the disgruntled fans let the Rams know their displeasure. He
was about the only thing the franchise had going for it then, an
outstanding receiver with not enough help to elevate the team from
the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Those boos certainly are ``Bruuuuce!'' now. He remains the
biggest passing threat on what has become a potent Rams offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce maintains the look of a prize fighters right before
the opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``People misinterpret me,'' he said. ``They say I don't smile. I
smile a lot. They say I always look mean and that I'm hard to
approach. But how would you know unless you approach me? The reason
I'm quiet is that I like to see what a person is about before I
start opening up. I withhold. And I watch. The least said is the
best said.''
</P>
<P>
   When he does speak, people listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn from Isaac every day,'' young receiver Az-Zahir
Hakim said. ``You know what he's saying is beneficial because he's
done it at a high level in this league. You respect him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And day in and and day out, he comes to play,'' Hakim said.
``You see how he handles himself on the field, and it's carried
over to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce, chosen for the Pro Bowl, carried the Rams' passing
offense with 77 receptions for 1,165 yards and 12 touchdowns in the
regular season. In the two playoff games that pushed the Rams to
the Georgia Dome, Bruce had seven catches for 155 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous receiver in every aspect,'' Tampa Bay
Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy said. ``He has the speed to get deep
and he runs so well after the catch. He's a complete player.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his demeanor, Bruce is excited about how far the Rams
have come. He had been the shining light of a franchise going
nowhere. Now, he has ample assistance in a passing game that
produced record numbers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many weapons, I'm like a kid in a candy store,''
Bruce said. ``We can beat you from anywhere on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bruce is not the choice for Kurt Warner, the quarterback also
has Torry Holt, who had 52 catches for 788 yards and six touchdowns
in the regular season. ``We feed off each other,'' Holt said. ``The
way we see it, you can't possibly cover all of us. Somebody's going
to be open.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes Hakim, the fifth receiver on passing downs who
found his way to the end zone eight times. ``Attack, attack,
attack,'' Hakim said. ``We feel like we can get open against
anybody because we have an aggressive approach. We have the speed
to beat you deep and we're willing to go underneath. So what do you
give up?''
</P>
<P>
   A lot. If Warner gets pressure and has to give up the ball in
the flat, he has running back Marshall Faulk. Faulk led the team in
regular-season receptions with 87 for 1,048 yards. That total also
was the most by an NFL back. ``I'm used as a receiver as much as a
runner,'' Faulk said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce said: ``The defense is well aware of what we have done,
and their main thing is to take away the long ball. ``I didn't know
if we'd get to this point,'' he said. ``I had my doubts. When
you're 4-12, 3-13, you don't see much light. But we've kind of just
been holding our serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
