<HEADER>
A8566 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-SAFETYSIDE-     01-27 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-SAFETYSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old players didn't want helmets
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day back in 1912, the same year a touchdown was increased
from five points to six, somebody showed legendary football coach
Glenn ``Pop'' Warner the latest contraption.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether it was called a head harness or a helmet,
but this much is certain: Warner hated the thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing without helmets gives players more confidence, saves
their heads from many hard jolts, and keeps their ears from
becoming torn or sore,'' he said. ``I do not encourage their use.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner believed that headgear gave players a sense of
invincibility that caused them leading with their heads while
tackling, increasing the risk of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was able to prevent the helmet from becoming standard,
but not so long ago it was in danger of going extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, at least 18 companies were manufacturing
helmets.
</P>
<P>
   But a rash of liability lawsuits in the 1970s and a paralyzing
injury to former Detroit Lion Mike Utley put the maker of his
helmet, ATI, out of business in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   By a few years ago, just two companies made NFL helmets _
Riddell, of Chicago, and Athletic Helmet Inc., a division of the
Schutt Sports Group, of Litchfield, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   No protective gear was enough in 1974 to prevent the Texas
Supreme Court from ordering Rawlings to pay $1.5 million in damages
to a former Texas high school player injured in practice while
wearing a Rawlings helmet.
</P>
<P>
   By 1979, at least 13 trials had involved helmet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings, maker of the helmet that Hall of Fame quarterback
Terry Bradshaw wore while playing for the Steelers, and others,
including Wilson and Spalding, got out of the business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Dick Kazmaier, who won the Heisman Trophy while playing
at Princeton in 1951, bought Bike from Colgate-Palmolive, but he
soon sold the helmet company to Schutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very economic business when you have to have 45
percent to potentially 85 percent of sales just to pay insurance
costs,'' Kazmaier said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If each (helmet manufacturer) lost a major product liability
in the same year, it come mean the end of helmet manufacturing. And
football,'' said Julie Nimmons, president of Schutt. ``We have to
stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The bleeding has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, doctors became more willing to testify that helmets
were good at their designed purpose _ protecting skulls.
</P>
<P>
   Warning labels on helmets have for several years made it clear
that wearing one doesn't make a player immune from injury.
</P>
<P>
   Juries began taking a middle ground in cases against helmet
makers, less frequently finding for plaintiffs. Also, coaches have
done a better job at all levels of teaching players not to lead
with their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Bike Athletic Co., based in Stroudsburg, Pa., has gotten back
into the business with an ultra-light model worn by a handful of
NFL players, including Darren Woodson of the Cowboys and Trace
Armstrong of the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward comfort is likely to continue, as different
foams are tried inside shoulder pads, and the air bladders in
helmets are adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they're trying to make things lighter and more
comfortable,'' Falcons equipment manager Brian Boigne said.
``Ventilation is a big thing. Shoulder pads, you can almost say the
same thing.'' Helmets could change in the way the equipment works.
</P>
<P>
   Visors have become more common inside face masks, to prevent
finger pokes, and players have experimented with foam-rubber caps
on top of helmets.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think that air-bag technology could make its way
into headgear, or even shoulder pads, and some have predicted that
helmets will one day fit into a housing on shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   `` Everything now is air-management,'' Boigner said. ``I feel
that it's like trying to re-invent the wheel, if you're trying to
change the look.''
</P>
<P>
   What would Pop think now?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
