<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8567 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-SAFETY-COX     01-27 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-SAFETY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Have players outgrown safety?
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be easy to assume that professional football is more
dangerous than ever. Just look at the NFL's list of devastating
injuries this season and couple it with what seems like an endless
list of smaller injuries every week.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that the collisions get more violent as the size
of the players and the speed of the game increase.
</P>
<P>
   And the equipment that players wear isn't evolving as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the evidence does not support the notion that the
NFL has more injuries _ even if the players are much, much bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Bishop, the Falcons' team orthopedist, said the fuss
about bigger and faster players causing more injuries doesn't make
common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the guys are bigger and faster, but they're all bigger
and faster,'' Bishop said. ``It's not just the guys hitting; the
guys getting hit are bigger and faster, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Chargers offensive tackle Ron Mix, a Hall of Famer who
weighed about 260 pounds when he played in the 1960s, can hardly
believe the size of the modern-day player. Just a handful of
offensive linemen weigh less than 300 pounds. Offensive tackles
average about 320.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever seen an evolution with such a gigantic leap in
the shape of a person?'' Mix asked an interview with the San Diego
Union-Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a 20-year period, you just don't have that kind of
evolutionary leap, where suddenly the human race has gotten bigger.
Well, it hasn't. It is only a segment of the human race: the
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who doubt the effects of increased size and speed on
injury rates, face sizable evidence.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the list of big-name players who missed most of
the season: Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde, Falcons running back
Jamal Anderson, Broncos running back Terrell Davis, 49ers
quarterback Steve Young, Cowboys wide receiver Michael Irvin and
Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, Falcons and Broncos were three of the last four teams
left standing at the end of the 1998 season. None of them had
winning records in 1999, and they all had many more significant
injuries than the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, on Sunday, the Tennessee Titans lost free safety
Marcus Robertson to a broken leg. Titans wide receiver Yancy
Thigpen is doubtful because of a fractured foot.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Falcons who had postseason surgery is impressive:
cornerback Ray Buchanan (debris/left shoulder); linebacker Henri
Crockett (debris/left knee); running back Gary Downs
(screw/surgically repaired right knee); defensive tackle Travis
Hall (debris/right shoulder); running back Byron Hanspard (debris,
scar tissue/surgically repaired left knee); tackle Jose Portilla
(debris/right shoulder); tackle Ephraim Salaam (torn
cartilage/right knee); linebacker Craig Sauer (debris/right knee)
and linebacker Jessie Tuggle (debris/left shoulder)
</P>
<P>
   ``Players are getting faster, stronger, bigger, so you're going
to get bigger collisions,'' said Steve Young, who suffered a
concussion early in the season. ``But I don't know that that's
going to correlate to significant changes in (the number of)
injuries.'' Other than concussions, protective football equipment
is not designed to prevent the types of injuries that sidelined
many of the big-name players.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Davis tore knee ligaments, Anderson without
contact. Testaverde tore an Achilles tendon without being hit.
Irvin suffered an injury to his spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for seven years, and I really don't think
(injuries have increased),'' Bishop said. ``I don't have numbers in
front of me, but . . . helmets and shoulder pads protect from
direct blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have nothing to do with quad pulls. Your knee injuries,
quad pulls, ankle turns and things like that have nothing to do
with protective equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who think that the game is getting more dangerous would
have a hard time debating a recent Los Angeles Times survey showing
that NFL players missed considerably less playing time this season
than last because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 season, 364 injured NFL players missed 1,061 games,
a decrease from 398 players sidelined for 1,340 games. In 1997, 335
players missed 937 games. Only in the last 20 years or so has the
NFL made it mandatory that teams keep up-to-the-day injury reports.
Part of the reason was to reduce the amount of ``inside
information'' that bettors could use to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole bunch of what's now classified as injuries
that we didn't worry about when I played (at SMU in the 1960s),''
Falcons general manager Harold Richardson said. ``If we pulled a
groin, heck, we kept playing. There's a lot more reporting of
injuries today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said, ``They didn't keep injury records back in the `50s,
so it's hard to make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Players weren't necessarily tougher in the old days, despite
such defensive starts as Ray Nitschke and Dick Butkus.
</P>
<P>
   But today, doctors and trainers realize that injuries are more
likely to linger, and affect performance longer, if they're not
given time _ and treatment _ to heal.
</P>
<P>
   And protective equipment has done a pretty good job of keeping
pace with the increased size and speed of the game and its players.
</P>
<P>
   According to the L.A. Times survey, damage to knees, ankles,
hamstrings and shoulders have ranked as the four most common
injuries each season since 1997, with twice as many injuries to
knees as ankles.
</P>
<P>
   But Rams defensive tackle Ray Agnew, a 10-year veteran, says he
doesn't see a big difference in injury rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has always been violent,'' Agnew said. ``I don't see
much difference, at least nothing that you could base on science. I
don't think shoulder pads and helmets are lagging behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of concussions doubled this season, from five in both
1997 and 1998 to 11 in 1999. But it might not be the players or the
helmets that are responsible.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of concussions seem to result, not from
direct contact from one players equipment to another's helmet, but
from helmets pounding into artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial surfaces, especially the one in Veterans Stadium
where Irvin was injured, can be very hard.
</P>
<P>
   As for the knees and ankles, human joints haven't been evolving
with the size of the players' bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Some training methods can strengthen the area around joints to
reduce the likelihood of injuries, but only to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size and speed of players is definitely increasing, and
they're staying in shape year round, which helps that,'' said Fox
analyst Jackie Slater, who played tackle for the Rams 1976-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that works both ways,'' Slater said. ``The fact the
offseason workout programs are there means guys are better
conditioned to withstand many injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
