<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFCFEATURE-     01-27 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFCFEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titan's owner still walks tall in Texas
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yes, these are happy days for Tennessee Titans owner
Bud Adams. Heck, things are going so well, he hasn't moved his team
anywhere all week.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, Bud Adams insists that the people of Houston do not
liken him to a cockroach for moving the Oilers to Tennessee,
slapping some almost-Columbia blue on their shoulders and calling
them the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   It probably is more wishful thinking by Adams than fact. But the
owner, whose non-football business remains based in Houston, says,
``I'm not afraid to walk around anywhere in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams' transplanted team, which could never get past an AFC
title game in Houston, finally made it to Super Bowl XXXIV. When
the Oilers were a lame-duck franchise in Houston, after the
announcement of plans to leave for Tennessee, Astrodome crowds
steadily dwindled. Those were not days when Adams did a whole lot
of walking around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say this -- we had great support in Houston,'' Adams
said. ``I can't complain about the support we had in Houston. It
was a good football town, and I'd like to see them get a franchise
(which is happening in 2002). . . . I tried to get a new stadium
built down there. We just never could get it done. If I'd have
stayed, I think I'd still be working on getting a new stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams rambled for 50 minutes Thursday at the news conference at
the Hyatt Regency. He was just in town from Houston and bundled up
in overcoat and scarf.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this excitement,'' he said, ``I must have picked up one of
those Houston viruses, and you know what that's like.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams noted that:
</P>
<P>
   _ He wants to sign head coach Jeff Fisherto a contract extension
as soon after the Super Bowl as possible. Fisher has a year left on
his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have it right here, the new contract,'' Adams said,
kiddingly, reaching into his coat pocket. ``If I could just get him
to sign, I'd feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning serious, Adams added, ``I don't think it's the proper
time to do it, when we're going down to the wire for the final
playoff game, but I don't want him to go into his last year without
a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although he referred to Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones as
``a very smart guy who understands the game better than most owners
do,'' he was critical of the Cowboys' independent sponsorship
deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the ambush marketing he's done,'' Adams said.
``We're all partners in this, and you're only as good as your other
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   _ After Adams sued the city of Houston and the Astrodome and
eventually was given the right to move, he called the mayor of
Nashville, Phil Bredesen, and said, ``I'm Bud Adams, the owner of
the Houston Oilers, and I'll move my team down there if you'll
build a stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said the mayor replied, ``This isn't Bud Adams, and I'd
appreciate it if you wouldn't pull these pranks on me,'' and hung
up on him.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said Mayor Bredesen called back 30 minutes later,
apologized and said, ``Yes, we are interested in talking to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
