<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8569 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-BRADLEY28-C     01-27 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-BRADLEY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Snow place like here for chaos on thin ice
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Look, we're sorry. You think we planned this? We hate
winter. Absence of winter is why we all moved here. First thing we
imports do when we cross the state line is throw away our ice
scrapers.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody got an extra ice scraper?
</P>
<P>
   Look, we're sorry. Ordinarily we get one dusting every three
years, and we freak out then. Now we're about to get two wintry
mixes in a week, which means we've all turned into bigger freaks
than Jevon Kearse. Four inches of snow? Better cancel the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   We're buying enough supplies to last through Y3K. On Wednesday
night, one of our weather guys said to prepare for four days
inside. Four days? We can't do four minutes. We're outdoor people,
if you count being gridlocked inside an SUV on the Downtown
Connector as being outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you're not happy because you brought your golf clubs and
are using your 9-iron as a clothes hanger. Think we're happy? At
least you tourists are in your nice downtown hotels equipped with
coffee shops and backup generators. We're in our hilly subdivisions
with the trees just waiting to fall over the driveways and the
power waiting to cut off. We wish this wasn't happening Super Bowl
week. We wish this wouldn't happen any week.
</P>
<P>
   You're downtown. Worst case scenario, you can slog to the Dome.
We have to drive. Only we can't drive in snow. We can't drive in
rain. We can't drive, period. Our idea of winter automotive safety
is to slow down to 95 on the Perimeter and maybe close the sunroof.
</P>
<P>
   We're hopeless. All of us who came from up North and who knew
how to drive when it's slippery have forgotten. We left the
steer-in-the-direction-of-the-skid lesson at the border along with
the ice scraper. Put cinder blocks in the trunk? There's no room.
The tennis rackets and water skis take up all the space.
</P>
<P>
   Look, we're sorry. We know we're getting hammered in the
national media for the crummy weather, and we're hypersensitive
about what the national media thinks. Tom Wolfe wrote a sneering
book about Atlanta, and we all spent six months in group therapy to
restore our self-esteem. Just when we thought we were feeling
better, along comes John Rocker. Now this. It's enough to make us
cast envious glances at Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Look, we're sorry. You think we planned this?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we did.
</P>
<P>
   It's said that this week's weather will doom our chances to
stage another Super Bowl. We don't care. Super Bowls are $100
million a dozen. Our eyes are on a bigger prize. Remember how we
got ripped worldwide for the way we handled our Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   We want to try again.
</P>
<P>
   We want the Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   This week is our audition. We didn't advertise it, but we've
been scheming all along. See the facilities already in place? Stone
Mountain can be our ski jump. Spaghetti Junction looks like a
bobsled run. Lake Lanier makes for a lovely skating rink. We hope
our good pals in the IOC will be duly impressed and grant us a
Winter Olympiad. And we hope they won't take it the wrong way when
we start firing snowballs at the most exceptional Mr. Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as we've come to think of him, ol' Frosty.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
