<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ARTS-ATLANTA30-COX     01-27 1710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-ATLANTA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking a job in Houston, the former High Museum director says
companies must boost bucks for Atlanta to keep pace
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ned Rifkin says he wasn't job hunting when Houston's
Menil Collection and Foundation came calling. In fact, the recently
divorced director of the High Museum of Art had just bought a house
not far from the home of his ex-wife and 17-year-old son, Amos. (An
older son, Moses, is off at Brown University.)
</P>
<P>
   But Rifkin, a curator at heart, couldn't pass up the offer to
run one of America's most extraordinary private collections,
located in what he calls a ``magical, unique'' setting, a placid
artistic enclave known, apart from its collection, for its
buildings designed by Renzo Piano and Philip Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Rifkin, 50, left the High on Dec. 31. A ``For Sale'' sign sits
on his front lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the house one recent morning, sitting beneath a
contemplative photograph of John Lennon and George Harrison taken
during the Beatles' Hamburg days, Rifkin talked about the Atlanta
arts scene, his days at the High and the city's potential,
specifically when it comes to arts and culture.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy is worth highlighting. During the 1990s, museum
membership rose from 13,500 to 40,000. Since arriving in 1991, his
tenure has included the Olympic ``Rings'' show and blockbuster
exhibits of impressionism, Matisse, Picasso and Norman Rockwell. He
was integral in getting Piano involved in designing an expansion
for the museum, which evolved into the Italian architect being
recruited to design a master plan for the Woodruff Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   But a litany of his achievements, he stressed, wasn't the point
of this meeting. Speaking out was.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What did you want to say about the arts and the city before
leaving town?
</P>
<P>
   A: I felt that I had an obligation to my peers, friends and
leaders of other cultural institutions to send a message to the
larger community about what it's going to take to really bring
Atlanta to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's it going to take?
</P>
<P>
   A: Atlanta needs to raise the bar in corporate giving. That is
what separates the great cultural cities from the next level down.
You look at Chicago, some company like Sara Lee, and they're not
shy of giving a million dollars in support of a major impressionist
show at the Art Institute. In most major cities, with a major
exhibition that costs millions of dollars to present, there is a
sponsorship level of $1 million or more. I am concerned that the
level of corporate giving within Atlanta is considerably lower than
comparable sponsorships in Chicago, New York, L.A. and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What was fund-raising like here?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'm not saying we weren't successful. I'd say relative to
where we started, the fund-raising really took off. But it is the
corporate community that needs to reinvest much of their resources
back into the cultural community for this to happen. If Atlanta is
going to take off and go to the next level, those enlightened
leaders of businesses are going to have to double and triple their
efforts to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give an example of Atlanta businesses not stepping
up?
</P>
<P>
   A: When we had this Picasso show a couple years ago, we had 13
sponsors and thanked them all. The minimum gift was $50,000, I
believe. I seem to recall that the largest was $150,000. To get to
the needed $1.5 million that we had budgeted, it meant that we had
to work extremely hard to identify these 13 sponsors. But there
should have been somebody, one corporate community leader, who
said, ``This is mine. I want this. And I'm going to give a million
dollars, and you raise the other half-million.'' That's what I'm
talking about. It may sound like sour grapes, but the truth is,
somebody has got to say it when the emperor's only half-clad.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When you asked for larger donations, what was the reaction?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, actually, in the case of one major, major corporation,
I got no response. I never even was told ``no.'' And that's the
level at which the dialogues ... exist or don't exist. There is a
sense (in the corporate world) that these (arts) organizations are
sort of needy and always asking for money. ``Why are they always
asking?'' Well, we're always asking because we're always providing.
It's not like we're pests. In fact, what we are is providers. And
we're nurturers. And we're offering wonderfully rich, powerfully
compelling experiences of art in all forms. And I say art, and I
include the zoo and the botanical garden. These aren't add-ons;
these are essentials.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about individual giving?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have something at the museum we started in 1991 called the
Director's Circle, the people at the highest level of annual
individual giving. When I got here, before that was created, there
were eight people, I believe, giving $5,000 a year, which is a
substantial amount of money _ I'm not in any way trying to
castigate them for giving that much. But they weren't asked for
more. We ratcheted it up to ask for $10,000 a year. We now have
over 100 members of the Director's Circle, some of them giving
$40,000 to $50,000 a year annually. That's a major gift. And that,
to me, is
</P>
<P>
   paradigmatic of the individual support that does exist in this
community for things that are exciting and enlivening and vital in
terms of our culture, at least in terms of visual arts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the financial status of the High now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I know that the museum is in a substantially better position
than it was when I arrived on Aug. 1, 1991. It does have hopes and
aspirations to expand. I believe that the challenge before the
museum will be not just individual support, but also how and when
the corporations understand that this is also going to accrue to
the entire community, to have more than twice as large an
institution that can service many more people comfortably in a
building that is going to be designed for that purpose. We now
bring hundreds of thousands of people to the fourth floor in an
elevator designed to carry, I believe, 14 people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What would you call the high points of your tenure here?
</P>
<P>
   A: There have been many. Certainly ``Rings'' (the Cultural
Olympiad exhibit that brought in masterworks from around the
world). That experience stays with me. Seeing non-art lovers come
to the museum and be visibly moved to tears.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Low points?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first two years were really challenging and difficult.
Feeling the burden of responsibility of an institution that had
acquired significant debt. It was daunting, really daunting. Having
to fire people. Letting people go is a very grown-up thing you're
not trained for in art history.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think about the structure of the Woodruff Arts
Center and its four divisions (the High, the Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra, the Alliance Theatre, the Atlanta College of Art)?
</P>
<P>
   A: There have been times when the partnership has been
extraordinarily right in terms of spirit, and times when it
misfunctioned. I don't think any of the business people sitting on
the (Woodruff) board would want to run their businesses the way
they were run when they were originally founded. To revisit the
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff's governance periodically and look at internal
operations on a regular basis is just good business. And that's
consistent with things I've said to them as a group.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would some Woodruff divisions be better off not being part of
the center?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think a study would have to be done. Certain divisions
could manage independently, others could not. But only if the
Woodruff Foundation would support them to some degree. That's a
tremendous reserve of wealth, and without its direct support, it
would be very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you feel about the cultural tourism initiative
sponsored by the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's been very effective for the museum. The smaller
organizations probably feel they don't get out of it what they
need. They're trying to create a cultural consciousness in a
regional way, to get people to come to Atlanta. Art exhibits are
uniquely qualified to do that, more so than a concert. The pandas
(at Zoo Atlanta) are something comparable. But museums have proven
it can happen. And that's a second good reason for corporations to
make an investment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you feel about your new home, Houston?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a major cultural center. It's got a great opera. Great
ballet. It's a thriving, culturally ambitious city.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will you miss about Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: The people, friends, the kindness. There's a benevolence in
Atlanta that's foreign to a lot of cities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you'll still be working with the High on the Elton John
photo show this fall. Talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm curating the show, and I'll be here for the festivities.
It's a real pleasure; my background is curatorial, and it will be
nice to exit the High as a curator. The show will be a real
revelation to people. This is a very thoughtful and very important
collection of photography that very few people have ever seen. It's
going to keep me connected to the High in a way that's poignant and
meaningful to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think when you hear Atlanta call itself an
``international city''?
</P>
<P>
   A: This moniker is one of those buzzy concepts that sounds more
meaningful than it might truly be. Atlanta has enormous ambitions,
and I say that's great. The problems set in when people become
satisfied with the language and the concepts but perhaps do not
even know what the reality looks like. Paris is an international
city. New York is the most international of all American cities.
(Atlanta) will become one only when its art and cultural life
approaches that of these cities. While it is unlikely this will
occur during our lifetimes, it is imaginable that Atlanta will be
taken more seriously over the years ahead by the international
cultural community if, and only if, it is able to sustain the
growth and development of its cultural resources. In my opinion,
this will only happen with powerful and enlightened leadership in
the corporate sector.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
