   By Joel Connelly. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-VICTIM (Seattle) _ Jeanne Sather has learned a lot about
possible side effects since she was first diagnosed with cancer 17
months ago. She's learned about nausea, headaches, hair loss, the
usual things that go with cancer treatment. And she's learned about
some things you don't always hear about: Getting fired. Call them
the unwritten side effects, the collateral damage of serious
illness that no one mentions _ friends who disappear because your
mortality reminds them of their own. Jobs that vanish without
explanation. These are the side effects you don't prepare for
because you don't see them coming.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
