<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TLC-FUTURE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Starting all over again': It's smooth sailing for TLC as often
stormy trio rolls in for hometown tour stop
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand.
</P>
<P>
   Left-Eye means every word she's been screeching.
</P>
<P>
   She still insists that she's the creative force in TLC, the
best-selling female group of any genre in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge still stands for fellow members Tionne ``T-Boz''
Watkins and Rozonda ``Chilli'' Thomas to record solo albums and let
sales determine who has the most talent.
</P>
<P>
   And Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes only has exclamation points to add
to the statement she made last February when the Atlanta pop trio's
``Fanmail'' album was released: ``I'm not really feeling TLC.''
</P>
<P>
   But things, they all say, are better between them.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta gets to bask in this rare moment, as TLC, that spiciest
of girl groups, brings its ``Fanmail'' tour to Philips Arena on
Saturday, after 30 dates on the road. Despite the ebb and flow of
its troubles, TLC's touch is still undeniable. As the three
approach this concert, everyone is talking about their past, their
future and their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a group like TLC, who has broken records saleswise
_ had insurmountable sales in fact _ but you don't simply see a
female singing group,'' says Asondra Hunter, the new editor in
chief of Honey, a burgeoning women's lifestyle magazine. ``What you
have is a group that young white girls in the suburbs want to be.
There's the black girls in the city who are TLC. They just don't
know how to sing. And then you have the guys who want to date girls
like TLC.''
</P>
<P>
   Then and now
</P>
<P>
   Quoting inspirational author Iyanla Vanzant and responding
playfully to inquiries about the status of the group, as if asked
in a foreign language _ ``Huh? Us, mad? _ TLC is the oft-changing
face of harmony. It's almost as if this is 1992, when the threesome
released its multimillion-selling debut, ``Ooooooohhh ... On the
TLC Tip,'' and the most talked-about thing they did was wear
condoms on their clothing to promote safe sex. No chatter about
discord then.
</P>
<P>
   But the calendar says 2000, and we're backstage at the Rose
Garden in Portland, Ore., where Lopes is rushing her assistants to
complete her elongated hair and magazine cover makeup so she can do
a photo op with Mayor Vera Katz. Quite a change from the start of
the ``Fanmail'' tour in October, when Lopes not only refused to do
meet-and-greets, but spoke to no one as she moved from dressing
room to stage in the midst of an entourage.
</P>
<P>
   This second leg of this national tour has done much better
saleswise than the first. In October and November, stops in markets
as small as Dayton, Ohio, and Greenville, S.C., drew crowds that
filled only half to 75 percent of the venues. But with a new
opening lineup and new promotional help _ from MTV, cosmetics
retailer Sephora and TLC's Atlanta-based record company, LaFace
Records, the tour has come close to, if not selling out, recent
dates in Oakland, Calif., Seattle and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to seven Grammy nominations this month _ including
record, song and album of the year _ and Lopes says, ``It feels
like a renewal right now. Like we're starting all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it was only a month ago that rumormongers were
whispering that this, TLC's first headlining tour, could be its
last. The group's record is spotty. It took TLC five years to get
back into the studio to record ``Fanmail,'' a span that included
one $1.3 million house burning down (Left-Eye was convicted of
arson), one life-threatening bout with sickle cell anemia (T-Boz),
one baby boy (Chilli) and one bankruptcy filing (all three).
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, 29, was wondering aloud recently about how much more
the group could take: ``TLC is like the never-ending soap opera,''
she sighed during the December press storm that Lopes helped kick
up in the magazines Entertainment Weekly and Sister 2 Sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want it to end,'' she says. ``But everything you
read, everything you hear, even some of the things you feel deep
down make it seem like it's headed off the cliff. At full speed.''
</P>
<P>
   But they finished the first leg of the ``Fanmail'' tour by
Thanksgiving. Watkins, who toured against doctors' advice, took
time to recuperate in her Dunwoody home. Thomas, 28, took to her
Stone Mountain kitchen, where she baked sweet potato pies with son
Tron, 2. And Lopes, 28, who also lives in Stone Mountain, took off
to the Honduras, a favorite getaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we got back (Jan. 3), everybody was past all of
the headlines and `TLC Breaking Up' and all that we were venting
back then,'' Lopes says. ``We're looking forward.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means though, depends on whom you ask.
</P>
<P>
   The future
</P>
<P>
   The group's focus isn't on a follow-up to ``Fanmail.'' Or on any
post-tour activities as TLC. Lopes has her sights on a solo
project, a casual clothing line due in stores this August, and
television, where she debuted in fall 1998 as a host on the MTV
talent show ``The Cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, appearing in print ads for leather goods retailer Coach,
continues to receive movie scripts. She's looking for one she can
be funny in. ``Let me act a fool!'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And Watkins is working on a script that she and TLC producer
Dallas Austin have come up with about the group's start in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``TLC is already like the best movie, because they always have
drama,'' offers Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid, LaFace co-president. (TLC
still has a contract for three more albums with the label.)
</P>
<P>
   Says Thomas: ``Even with all the drama we as a group and
individuals go through, we know that when we get together _ no
matter how long we are apart _ magic happens.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why many in and around the music industry believe TLC
will continue.
</P>
<P>
   TLC appeal
</P>
<P>
   TLC has exemplified ``girl power'' before, during and after the
Spice Girls reign, says multi-million-selling teen vocalist
Christina Aguilera (``Genie in a Bottle''), an opening act on this
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal is in the marketing and the imaging,'' adds Honey
magazine's Hunter. ``They are very cutting edge. You see them at
award shows and people look to see what they have on, and are like:
`I want to wear that outfit. I want to wear my hair that way.' And
it's not necessarily mimicking, it's just taking ideas. Feeling
inspired to express your own individuality. The singing and
production are there, but that's almost like a given when you've
got Babyface and Dallas Austin with you on every album.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, we love TLC because we always love someone we
can live life wildly and vicariously through, be it the growth and
changes T-Boz wrote about in her book (``Thoughts''). Left-Eye
conquering substance abuse. Or Chilli raising a child as a single
parent. They've overcome a lot of things in their lives and that
strength is very attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kayla Charping, a Greenville 12-year-old, doesn't articulate
TLC's appeal quite that way. But as she walks to the seat of her
first concert ever, she knows exactly what she likes about them.
``They look cool, they sing cool, and I think they'd be cool to be
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beyond every girl group that comes out every day,''
offered David Roncinski, 22, on his feet for most of the show.
``You know them and their music. And I like them. I hope they never
stop doing what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no chance of that, right, Lisa?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, things are cool,'' Lopes says with a suspicious giggle.
</P>
<P>
   Um, Lisa?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to keep the suspense,'' she says, smirking. ``We need
that kind of attention. Even though the fire was a terrible thing,
we needed that. That helped us sell a couple of million records.
And that's good. We like the hype that controversy and drama
generate.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Don't misunderstand this moment of calm as
anything other than a moment.
</P>
<P>
   IN CONCERT
</P>
<P>
   TLC
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m. Saturday. Christina Aguilera, Blaque and Vega open.
$45.50. Philips Arena, 1 Philips Drive N.W. 404-249-6400
(Ticketmaster).
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
