r e BC-TLC-TIMELINE28-COX     01-27 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TLC-TIMELINE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TLC: The highs and lows
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  1991: TLC is formed when R&AMP;B recording artist Pebbles
(``Mercedes Boy'') puts her backup dancer, Rozonda ``Chilli''
Thomas, together with Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins and Lisa
``Left-Eye'' Lopes. Watkins and Lopes were already in a trio called
Second Nature.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1992: ``Ooooooohhh ... On the TLC Tip'' is released with the
hits ``Ain't 2 Proud 2 Beg'' and ``Baby, Baby, Baby,'' eventually
selling more than 4 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 9, 1994: After a fight between Lopes and former Atlanta
Falcon Andre Rison, Lopes places sneakers in a bathtub and sets
fire to them, burning down the $1.3 million Alpharetta, Ga., home
the couple shared. She later pleaded guilty to one count of
first-degree arson, and was ordered to spend several months in a
halfway house, pay a $10,000 fine and complete counseling for
alcoholism and battered women. She was also given five years'
probation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  November 1994: ``CrazySexyCool'' is released with Atlanta
producers Dallas Austin (``Creep'') and Jermaine Dupri (``Kick Your
Game'') recording with the group again. But its biggest single,
``Waterfalls,'' is from new Atlanta producers Organized Noize. The
album goes on to sell more than 11 million copies, making TLC the
best-selling female group in the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 1995: TLC files for bankruptcy protection citing $1
million in assets and $3.5 million in debts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  November 1996: TLC settles with its creditors in an agreement
approved by a bankruptcy judge. A confidentiality clause bars the
parties from disclosing the financial details, but TLC signs a new
contract with Atlanta-based LaFace Records. Former manager and
producer Pebbles, who owns the TLC name, is paid more than $1
million, she says. Lopes agrees to pay $527,000 to Lloyd's of
London, which insured the house she admitted torching.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  February 1999: ``Fanmail'' is released and debuts at the top
of Billboard's pop and R&AMP;B charts with help from its first single,
``No Scrubs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 22, 1999: TLC starts its first tour as headliners in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  November 1999: The Recording Industry Association of America
names ``CrazySexyCool'' the best-selling hip-hop album of the 20th
century, though, strangely enough, none of the songs is composed
mostly of rap.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jan. 4, 2000: The two-time Grammy winners receive seven 1999
Grammy nominations _ record of the year and R&AMP;B performance by a
duo/group with vocal for ``No Scrubs''; album of the year and R&AMP;B
album for ``Fanmail''; song of the year, pop performance by
duo/group with vocals and short form music video for ``Unpretty.''
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
