A8576 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TLC-CRITICS28-COX     01-27 0215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TLC-CRITICS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What the critics are saying
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although TLC isn't even a decade old and has put out only three
albums, its 90-minute ``Fanmail'' concert feels like a
greatest-hits show. Here's what reviewers across the country are
saying:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The high point: Chilli, mother of a 2-year-old, has a
chiseled body and sincere smile. Most pathetic moment: Left-Eye,
whom the audience adored, dropping the balls she was juggling.''
</P>
<P>
   _Toronto Star, in October
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Strutting and singing their way through a truckload of hits
in front of a backdrop straight out of a cyber-fantasy, they
displayed versatility, edginess and theatrical flair that the
average female group can't touch.''
</P>
<P>
   _USA Today, in November
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A thoroughly 21st-century pop concert, with all the
razzle-dazzle and sense of fun you'd expect from a group whose
kinetic videos are as memorable as its records.''
</P>
<P>
   _Los Angeles Times, Jan. 10
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Onstage TLC was revealed as a studio concoction; it makes
Janet Jackson sound like a coloratura.''
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Times on Monday
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
