<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8577 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WINTER-SEAST-COX     01-27 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-SEAST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deep South in a deep freeze
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When stores run out of canned meat, zoo animals get blankets and
people snow ski on beaches, you know the Deep South is in a Deep
Freeze.
</P>
<P>
   The South's second winter storm in less than a week blew through
northern parts of Mississippi, Louisiana, Arkansas and western
Tennessee Thursday with a mix of snow, ice and sleet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, forecasters predict, the snow and ice will glaze more of
the South from Birmingham to metro Atlanta as the system barrels
east. Thousands in Alabama, Georgia and North Carolina face the
fresh front still without power, knocked out by snow and ice
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of the Mississippi Delta, Greenville accumulated a
half foot of snow by Thursday evening. New Mississippi Gov. Ronnie
Musgrove placed the National Guard on alert. The Legislature shut
down for a long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any measurable snow in the last four or five
years,'' said Capt. Doyle Barrett of the Washington County
Sheriff's Department near Greenville. ``We're working one wreck
behind the other.''
</P>
<P>
   A disheveled Dixie bundled up for this latest blast.
</P>
<P>
   For two days at Lucky's Supermarket on Sand Mountain in
northeastern Alabama, Vienna sausage sales have nearly doubled,
said grocer Diaz Frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's convenient. You can pop it open and you don't even have
to heat it,'' Frost said during in a telephone interview Thursday.
Among other nicknames, locals have called the 50-year-old
storeowner ``Defrost.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of running to the Bi-Lo, Food World or Winn Dixie, loyal
customers have come to Diaz's 12,000-square-foot store in Henagar
and bought up his ration of lamp oil and bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll worry about myself after I've taken care of everybody
else,'' said Frost, who woke up Thursday with no water at his
house.
</P>
<P>
   When the storm grips Alabama, officials estimate as many as
2,000 people near Sand Mountain who lost electricity in weekend ice
storms still may be without power. Weather forecasters warn that
severe icing could kill electricity in Montgomery and Auburn and
turn roads into bobsled runs.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman authorized state offices to close
today if roadways are too hazardous. ``We could be downright
paralyzed,'' said Brian Peters, who coordinates weather service
warnings in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The same storm system that dropped more than 9 inches of snow in
Oklahoma and Texas Thursday could coat Birmingham with up to 6
inches of snow today. Trucks in Birmingham are loaded with 400 tons
of sand. They're ready to de-ice slickened roads such as
``malfunction-junction,'' the I-20 ramp near the
Birmingham-Jefferson County Civic Center and the Sheraton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Orangutans Oliver and Chelli _ among the 800 animals at the
Birmingham zoo _ broke in blue blankets donated to them Thursday.
``This is the first time we've done it, so they're dragging them
around,'' said zoo marketer Patty Pendleton. The zoo made sure heat
lamps and heating pads for their tortoises were working.
</P>
<P>
   To the probable delight of University of Alabama sports fans,
seven zoo alligators swam under the iced-over tops of their zoo
pond. ``They come up every now and again and poke their heads
through,'' Pendleton said. The gator habitat is sponsored by a
local University of Florida booster club.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday in South Carolina, temperatures reached just into the
upper 30s at Myrtle Beach. By this evening, a mix of frozen
precipitation may hit the coast.
</P>
<P>
   The beach had 4 inches of snow on Tuesday. Cross-country snow
skiers swooshed across places normally populated by snowbirds
craving Southern sunshine. Snowmen popped up everywhere, and a
local television station aired the best ones on its nightly
newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of unique,'' Sunset Inn owner James Dean _ and
former Pittsburgh resident _ said by telephone Thursday. ``At
first, it was real nostalgic. After three hours, we were tired of
it.'' The former accountant moved to Myrtle Beach 10 years ago to
escape cold, miserable business trips from Pittsburgh to
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, Raleigh-Durham International Airport opened
its longest runway at 4 p.m. Thursday. The first plane to depart
was an Atlanta-bound AirTran 717 that became airborne at 4:06 p.m.
Delta and U.S. Airways also began flying Thursday. Thousands of
travelers have been stranded at the airport since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After clearing 20.3 inches of snow _ the most from a single
storm since 1927 _ Raleigh airport crews Thursday discovered a
3-inch layer of ice, which took all day to scrape off with heavy
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But with just one runway open, today ``will be sporadic at
best,'' airport spokesman Mike Blanton said. Midway, which holds
nearly one-quarter of Raleigh-Durham's air market, plans to restart
its operations there today. American Airlines, however, hampered by
snowstorms in Dallas, has canceled flights to and from Raleigh
today, Blanton said. The prospect of ice and sleet this weekend
will more than frost the spirit of passengers and airport
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Not many trees are left standing in Erect, one of several rural
communities in central North Carolina covered by record snowfalls
of nearly 2 feet Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Snow collapsed the roof of Lynn Deaton's chicken house. The cold
froze Bill Caviness's tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``About everybody has had enough,'' June Cox, 78, said Thursday.
He reached back to 1927, when he was 6, to remember snow as deep as
this week's surprise blizzard. He measured 14 inches in the yard of
his Erect home_10 inches less than surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   In Asheboro, the American Red Cross set up an emergency shelter
in First Baptist Church. Wednesday night, 13 people sought safety
from the cold. Pastor John Rogers said the shelter would remain
open through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Bowman, a 36-year-old shelter resident, woke up Tuesday
morning at home ``so cold I like to froze.''
</P>
<P>
   He called 911, and a sheriff's deputy transported him to First
Baptist Church, where he keeps track of forecasts for more snow on
a TV in the dining hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it turns and goes away,'' Bowman said. ``I've had
enough winter and enough snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service writers Chris Burritt and Anne Rochell
Konigsmark contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
