<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's done. So now what?
</P>
<P>
   That is what Robert Redford once had to ask himself in the
movies when he was unexpectedly transformed from The Candidate to
The Senator and had no idea what to do once the election was over
and it was time to stop running and start doing the job he'd been
hired for.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bill Belichick finds himself in the same position, and so
does Bob Kraft. They made the deal. They gave up the No. 1 pick
Kraft said he never would surrender to the hated Jets and the
fourth- and seventh-round choices in 2001 in exchange for a
face-saving fifth in 2001 and seventh in 2002 that will be heading
up the New Jersey Turnpike to New England, probably to no good end.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft paid the ransom you knew he would and got what he wanted
all along, despite running that dog and pony show of interviewing
non-candidates for jobs that were already filled. Got what he
wanted, so now what do they do?
</P>
<P>
   For Kraft, the job is simpler than it is for Belichick. He sits
and waits. He watches. He puts on a prayer shawl and hits his knees
from time to time. He does all he can to help Bill Belichick
succeed, but he thought he was doing the same thing for Pete
Carroll and failed miserably in almost every way possible, turning
an above-average team into a mediocre one with thin talent because
of three years of stubbornness.
</P>
<P>
   Now Belichick must cope with the mess Kraft, Carroll, and Bobby
Grier created. He must come in and transform a team of
underachievers who think they are more talented than they are into
something bigger than themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He must come into a team that has had two straight lousy drafts,
now has no No. 1 pick this year, is $10 million over the salary cap
with nearly a half-dozen starting players eligible for free agency
next month, and rebuild it while competing against the Colts,
Dolphins, Bills, and most of all the Jets without sliding backward
even for a year.
</P>
<P>
   How Belichick will do this is his problem, and so is how well he
handles the pressures that will mount from it because when your new
employer pays a ransom to free you _ as the Jets did four years ago
to extricate Bill Parcells from a Patriots contract _ there is no
grace period. There is no slow improvement from, say, 1-15 to 7-9
to 12-4 as there was for Parcells in both Foxborough and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   For Bill Belichick, there must be rebuilding without losing.
There must be winning now, winning in a difficult circumstance
because for that to happen he has to transform a moribund offense
soon to be under the leadership of Charlie Weis and alter an
attitude that allows someone such as Shawn Jefferson to guarantee a
division title if Belichick arrived when he would have been wiser
to have just worried about winning a game or two.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final half of the year, that was the Patriots' problem.
Not winning division titles. Winning a game. Winning two games in a
row was impossible in the final two months under Carroll. The fact
that Jefferson could so assuredly promise a division title if
Belichick was hired was not an endorsement of his coaching
abilities, it was symptomatic of the skewered expectations he
faces.
</P>
<P>
   They do not know who they are in New England any more. They
haven't known since Bill Parcells left. Somebody has to teach them
that before anything else will change. That job will fall to
Belichick and it will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Now Parcells's evil twin, his young offspring, his alter ego,
has come to try and teach them who they are. If he is to be
successful, the first thing Belichick has to make clear to
Jefferson and Kraft and everyone else in New England is that what
he learned from Parcells years ago still holds true.
</P>
<P>
   You are what you are, Parcells always cautioned. If you're 8-8
and out of the playoffs and on a three-year skid, hiring Belichick
won't make you a division champion. You've got problems that cannot
be solved by one coach or by simple changes.
</P>
<P>
   Today Bill Belichick is the new head coach of a team that
finished last in the division. He is not the new head coach of a
division champion or of a team that has any right to be
guaranteeing such things because of his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   If Belichick can get that point across when he first meets with
his new team, the rest of his job will be easier.
</P>
<P>
   Not easy mind you, but easier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
