<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d BC-SUPERBOWL-DIPS28-COX     01-27 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-DIPS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will your snacks win Most Valuable Party Food?
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A Super Bowl party without dips is
simply second-string. Dips and beer and a football game are a team,
no question.
</P>
<P>
   Hot or cold, savory or sweet, dips are a snap to put together.
</P>
<P>
   They are made from the most adaptable and forgiving of recipes,
too, so if you find a basic one you like, you can change it to fit
the tastes of your crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Update some of your old ones. Still
</P>
<P>
   serving that tired onion-soup dip? Use
</P>
<P>
   a head of roasted garlic instead. Guacamole a bit ho-hum? Try
broccomole _ the name alone
</P>
<P>
   should elicit laughs. The surprise
</P>
<P>
   is, it's tasty!
</P>
<P>
   We've got a few more dip tricks
</P>
<P>
   and new dips in our playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Give them a try to win over your
</P>
<P>
   party team.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAYERS
</P>
<P>
   Chips and raw fruits and veggies are the norm for dipping, but
try these other dip-sters:
</P>
<P>
   _ Flatbreads or bagel chips, flavored or plain
</P>
<P>
   _ Soft pretzels (buy them frozen, or make your own out of bread
dough)
</P>
<P>
   _ Homemade sweet potato chips
</P>
<P>
   _ Ice cream cones, especially for sweet fruit dips
</P>
<P>
   _ Pizza crust wedges
</P>
<P>
   _ Shredded wheat biscuits
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiny doughnuts, in a sweet dip
</P>
<P>
   _ Dried fruit chips, such as banana and plaintain rounds
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAYING FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Glass bowls are nice, but consider serving from these
``natural'' containers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hollowed-out coconut shells, papaya or melon shells for fruit
dips
</P>
<P>
   _ Hollowed-out cabbages, green and red peppers, giant mushroom
caps or ``bloomed'' onions
</P>
<P>
   _ Round or rectangular bread loaves
</P>
<P>
   _ Giant tortilla shells. Make your own by overlapping several
small corn tortillas in a deep-frying basket or metal colander;
lower into hot oil and fry until crisp. Set aside, upside-down, to
cool and drain. Support it in a bowl for best results.
</P>
<P>
   THE RULES
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep hot dips hot, and cold dips cold. Use a punch bowl filled
with ice in which to nestle a smaller bowl or bowls of dips to keep
them at safe temperatures. Keep hot dips in a crockpot or over a
low burner, especially those containing seafood or meat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide a spoon or small canape knives in each dip to
discourage the ``direct dippers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Clearly label dips if you have anyone attending who has food
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hot pepper dips are great if you can handle the heat. Many
diners can't, so make some of the dip without the hot peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
