<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-CONGRESS-0128-C     01-27 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CONGRESS-0128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS COOLS TO CITIZENSHIP BILLS FOR ELIAN AS GRANDMOTHERS,
RELATIVES CONTINUE LOBBYING
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0128.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN and SUE SCHULTZ 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional enthusiasm for getting involved in
the family fight over the fate of 6-year-old Cuban refugee Elian
Gonzalez appeared to cool Thursday, even as relatives on both sides
of the issue lobbied sympathetic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert emerged from a meeting with fellow
GOP House members Thursday and said ``there's a difference of
opinion'' over how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who supports a bill to grant Elian U.S. citizenship in
a bid to force the case into a Florida custody court, said he would
not rush the bill to the floor but would require it to go through
the often-interminable committee process.
</P>
<P>
   On some issues, ``politicians need to step back,'' Hastert told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the immigration
subcommittee of the House Judiciary Committee, has expressed
reservations about the bill. Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, the
senior Democrat on that panel, is one of its most outspoken foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am personally appalled. This is not a political matter, this
is a family matter,'' Jackson-Lee said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., a co-sponsor of the
citizenship bill who once vowed to rush it to the Senate floor this
week, is now undecided about a timetable, said his spokesman, John
Czwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know right now. There is still a lot of talking
going on. He's taking the temperature of members,'' Czwartacki
said, adding that it could still come up sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the boy from Cuba has blurred political lines with
some of Congress' most conservative members, such as Rep. Steve
Largent, R-Okla., joining forces with some of its most liberal,
such as Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., in saying Elian belongs with
his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some of the most liberal members, including Rep.
Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I. and Rep. Peter Deutsch, D-Fla., are
supporting a bill to grant Elian temporary residency status which
would thwart efforts to return him quickly.
</P>
<P>
   With lawmakers assembling in the capital for Thursday night's
State of the Union message, two groups of Elian's relatives prowled
congressional hallways meeting with sympathetic legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives told lawmakers that the child was upset
by his meeting with his grandmothers in Miami on Wednesday and that
he feared being forced to return to Cuba. But his grandmothers said
the boy expressed the desire to go back and worried that he was
being harmed by remaining in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers complained to the members of the Congressional
Black Caucus about a lack of privacy at the meeting with their
grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Raquel Rodriguez, Elian's maternal grandmother, said she wanted
the meeting to be a normal visit, but when they arrived, ``there
was a lot of press and people with posters shouting at us.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the grandmothers, Rep. Mel Watt, D-N.C., said
``justice would be sending the child back to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers, showing signs of exhaustion after their
whirlwind visit which has taken them to New York, and twice to
Washington and Miami during the past week, are expected to meet
Friday with Rangel and Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., the
third-highest ranking Democrat in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile a group of Elian's Miami relatives and survivors of
the shipwreck that ultimately killed 11 refugees including Elian's
mother _ met with lawmakers sympathetic to allowing him to remain
in the United States pending a court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Among those was Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., who was particularly
interested in learning about the wishes of Elian's mother just
before she died. Survivors Nivaldo Fernandez and Arriane Horta told
Graham her wish was that Elian touch American soil, where he would
be safe from being forced to return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez rolled up his pants leg to show Graham the deep bites
he suffered from fish while in the water for three days after the
shipwreck. Donato Dalrymple, one of the fishermen who rescued Elian
on Thanksgiving Day, told Graham the boy ``looked like a flower,''
when plucked from the water.
</P>
<P>
   Graham asked about Elian's reaction to his meeting with his
grandmothers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez, the 21-year-old cousin who has been
Elian's primary caregiver, told Graham that he rushed into her arms
after the meeting and asked to ``go home.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Georgina Cid, another cousin, said the group
felt ``very positive'' from the meetings with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story
</P>
<P>
   (LarryL(at)coxnews.com and SueS(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
