<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-FORBES-PRIMARY-BOS &LR;      01-27 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES TRIES TO SHRUG OFF KEMP ENDORSEMENT OF BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ This was going to be Steve Forbes' moment
four years ago. He was on the cover of Time and Newsweek, he was on
the verge of being endorsed by Jack Kemp and he was the talk of New
Hampshire _ but still he plummeted into fourth-place in the New
Hampshire primary and, before the first day of spring, had dropped
out of the nomination race.
</P>
<P>
   Now Forbes again is seeking his moment, but it is one filled
with wild uncertainty and worrisome trends. Forbes' political hero,
Kemp, endorsed his political rival, George W. Bush, Thursday.
Forbes complained he was ignored in Wednesday's Republican debate
focus on Bush and Senator John McCain, who are tied at the top of
the polls. The latest Boston Globe poll shows the millionaire
Forbes is in danger of another fourth-place finish, with Alan Keyes
running stronger in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as his campaign bus idled in the parking lot of a
Manchester restaurant, Forbes insisted in an interview with Boston
Globe reporters that his campaign was catching on. Asked about
Kemp, he issued a curt dismissal of his longtime close friend,
saying the one-time NFL quarterback and ex-congressman ``is part of
the political establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, Jack was on the cutting edge of tax cuts and
junking the tax code,'' Forbes said. ``Obviously he has gone back
on that. The establishment is rallying around Bush; they know now
that Bush is in danger. I think we will see more and more evidence
that the establishment has met its match in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his tough talk, it was clearly a painful day for Forbes,
who in 1995 spent months urging Kemp to run for president. When
Kemp decided not to run, Forbes decided to run himself, carrying
the supply-side banner for the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, appearing with Bush in Nashua, called Forbes an
``outstanding human being'' who was best qualified to be Treasury
Secretary, not president. ``I really believe Governor Bush is the
one that can inspire the Congress, inspire the nation and win a
mandate for bringing down the tax rates,'' Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' campaign manager, Bill Dal Col, said Kemp made the
endorsement partly because his son-in-law, Scott Andrews, is a
business partner of Bush's brother, Marvin Bush. ``That is a big
part of the reason,'' Dal Col said. ``It is sure not philosophy or
ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer confirmed the relationship but said
the endorsement was purely ``ideological.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Forbes touted his endorsement of the Manchester
Union-Leader, which he called more powerful than ``50 Jack Kemps''
and prepared to dig once again into his personal wealth to finance
a new advertising campaign. There is good reason to think he could
heavily influence the outcome of the primary, whether he falters or
not. Forbes said that his strategy will rely on taking
anti-abortion voters away from Keyes and Bush, and drawing away
anti-tax voters from McCain and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This is markedly different from Forbes' last presidential run.
In 1996, Forbes rarely mentioned abortion in speeches and usually
talked about the subject only if asked. This time around, Forbes is
running a graphic anti-abortion ad that shows a sonogram of a
fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who has five daughters, was asked in the interview what
would he do if one of them became pregnant while a minor _ the same
question posed to John McCain Wednesday. Forbes responded that if
his daughter was under 18 years and a minor under the law, ``we
will have that child brought to term.'' If his daughter was over
18, ``You're an adult. We would urge her to bring the baby to
term.''
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma for Forbes is that what worked well for him in Iowa
may be a hindrance in New Hampshire. He collected 31 percent of the
caucus vote with a heavy appeal to religious conservatives and a
strong anti-abortion pitch. But in New Hampshire, the Christian
Coalition has little influence and polls show that most voters
favor abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Forbes has reason to hope for a surprise. In Iowa, he was
at 20 percent in the polls on Sunday, but got 31 percent on Monday
as many Iowans embraced his claim that he is the ``conservative
alternative'' to Bush with the money to last through a long primary
fight. And, on economics at least, the anti-tax state of New
Hampshire should provide a receptive audience for Forbes' flat-tax
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes may be being hurt by a lasting image of the 1996
primary _ a series of devastating ``attack'' ads that Forbes ran
against Bob Dole, which helped Patrick Buchanan emerge from the
pack to win the primary. Dole is now featured in an ad sponsored by
the moderate Republican Leadership Council in which he says that
Forbes' attack ads left him ``bruised and broke'' as he headed
toward the general election. Voters are being reminded of a darker
side of Forbes' image, and his four-year-old ads have been turned
against him.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes campaign is not nearly as negative as four years ago.
In one ad that might be considered an attack, he accuses Bush of
reneging on a no-tax pledge. But most of Forbes' ads have focused
on his issues and beliefs. In recent days, Forbes has begun running
anti-abortion ads, primarily a pre-emptive effort to prevent
supporters from drifting to Keyes or Gary Bauer, who have abortion
their top issue.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how enthusiastically Forbes' message is being
received. So far in New Hampshire, Forbes' crowds have been smaller
and more subdued than those in Iowa. In part, that may reflect a
strategy that is emphasizing radio and television appearances above
in-the-flesh campaigning; since returning from Iowa, Forbes has
been averaging only about two public appearances a day.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the lunch crowd at the Puritan Backroom
Restaurant in Manchester seemed underwhelmed as Forbes visited
their tables, making awkward small talk and asking for votes.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Pawloski, a Manchester retiree who has been a Republican
all his life said he liked some things about Forbes _ but not the
flat tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself don't see how a flat tax is going to work,'' Pawloski
said over lunch at the Backroom restaurant. ``It's going to know
the stuffing out of the working man.'' Pawloski, who said he is
supporting Bush, added that Forbes is ``funny-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   But his wife, Susan, disagreed.``He's a handsome man,'' she
said. ``He looks much better in person that he does on TV. He's got
a nice suit on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe reporter Anne Kornblut, traveling with Bush, contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
