r f BC-COKE-STOCK28-COX     01-27 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke raises doubts, and the stock falls
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thou shalt not surprise Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Coca-Cola shareholders are discovering in the wake
of what normally would have been favorable news for investors: a
respected company's management taking stern measures to correct its
problems.
</P>
<P>
   While two days isn't a trend, Coca-Cola's share price has taken
a big hit, falling almost 10 percent _ including nearly 6 percent
Thursday _ since Chairman-elect Doug Daft and other top executives
announced a massive restructuring of the world's best-known, but
recently troubled, company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the market saying we don't like Coca-Cola and we
don't like what they're doing, but it is saying we think its shares
are too pricey and we're going to wait this one out on the
sidelines for awhile,'' said Alfred Goldman, strategist for A.G.
Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, some analysts have been supportive of the company.
Four reiterated positive ratings on Coca-Cola shares on Wednesday
and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Goldman of Banc of America Securities, Marc Greenberg
at PaineWebber and Douglas M. Lane of Merrill Lynch reiterated
``buy'' ratings, and Christopher Wilkens of Deutsche Banc Alex.
Brown awarded a ``market perform'' rating, meaning he thinks the
stock will do at least as well as the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock
index.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, none of that cut any ice with the market. The
stock, which that fell $2.81 1/4 on Wednesday, dropped another
$3.56 1/4 to $59.50 on Thursday. Trading volume was heavy again,
with almost 8.8 million shares trading hands. That's almost the
double average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and money managers cite three reasons in particular why
the stock price has fallen and is likely to fall further:
</P>
<P>
   _ The layoff of 21 percent of its global work force was much
bigger than expected. As the week began, Wall Street speculated
that about 4,000 would lose their jobs. Coca-Cola instead announced
layoffs totaling 6,200.
</P>
<P>
   _ The inventory buildup of syrup _ the product Coca-Cola sells
to its bottlers who make the drinks _ was excessive in key markets
such as Japan, Germany and Eastern Europe. This will curb syrup
shipments in the first half of 2000. As a result, the company
trimmed its per-share earnings outlook for that period by 11 cents
to 13 cents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some analysts have protested that the company's goals for
profit and sales growth announced on Wednesday by Daft are too high
to be attainable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another reason offered by Goldman is what he called an
excessively high price multiple for Coca-Cola shares, a situation
he said leaves no margin for error in dealing with problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even at $59.50, the stock is still trading at about 45 times
earnings. That's a reflection of investor demand for the company's
stock. But analysts also say that the company's earnings
historically justify multiples of about half that.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the share price spiked upward by almost 20 percent in the
first three weeks of January, before this week's announcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is saying the company's solutions (announced by
Daft) are probably going to work, but when the shares are selling
at 45 times earnings, the outlook is pretty uncertain,'' said
Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some analysts believe the market hasn't had
time to hear all the details of Coca-Cola's recovery strategy. That
should become clearer today , when Daft and other top company
executives meet in New York with analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the market has been impressed with some of the opening
scenes of the Daft era,'' said Mark Godfrey, a senior analyst with
the Invesco Equity Income Fund. ``He has moved more quickly than
the market thought he would. It is obvious that he is hitting the
ground running and has a lot of ideas about where the company
should go.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Godfrey, the company's executives ``are setting
themselves up for good growth in the second half of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company's plan to cut bottler syrup inventories from
a 45-days' supply to 34 days will free up considerable cash for the
bottlers to use in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke is trying to work with its bottlers to help lower their
working capital needs. You don't need that much inventory in the
back room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in Coca-Cola's stocks continues a pattern of the last
year, during which the shares have reflected the company's many
problems with volatile swings.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest decline, from a May high of $70.50 to an October low
of $47.56 1/4, tracked the company's problems with the
health-related product recalls in Belgium and France, and the
subsequent impact on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Then the shares dropped 14 percent Dec. 6-7 when Chairman and
Chief Executive Douglas Ivester stunned the market by announcing he
would retire early this year after only 25 months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The shares traded within about an $8 range until the end of
1999, from which the price took its sharp upward spike to this
year's high of $66.87 1/2 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   How long will it take for the shares to get back to Tuesday's
close of $65.87 1/2? If history is any guide, it could take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 27, 1992, IBM announced a $3 billion charge against
earnings and job cuts of 20,000 in its restructuring. The share
price fell about 30 percent over the next two weeks. It was another
year and 10 months before the share price got back where it was
before that announcement. &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
