<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINO-MUSEUM28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exhibit will showcase casts of largest skeletons ever found
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Fernbank Museum of Natural History announced plans
Thursday to open a $1.25 million exhibit later this year featuring
casts of the two largest dinosaur skeletons ever found. One of the
dinosaurs weighed 100 tons.
</P>
<P>
   The casts are being made now in Argentina, where fossils of the
two giant dinosaurs were excavated in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   One cast is of the bones of a female Argentinosaurus, a 100-ton
plant eater; the other, a male Giganotosaurus, a 10-ton meat-eater,
said Susan Neugent, president and chief executive officer of the
Fernbank Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The casts will be assembled here, and the model of the smaller
male will go on display in the museum's Great Hall in June, she
said. It'll take a little longer to put the huge female together,
but it should go on display by December.
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs, unique to Argentina, became extinct about 85
million years ago, almost 20 million years before the last of the
dinosaurs died out, said Richard A. Hengst, a Purdue University
paleophysiologist working with Fernbank on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fossilized bones of the Argentinosaurus are on
display in the Museum Municipal de Carman Funes in Plaza Huincul, a
town in Argentina's Patagonia region.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time a cast of the Argen-
</P>
<P>
   tinosaurus has been made, Neugent said. Because the fossils of
the Argentinosaurus have never been fully put together, no one has
ever seen what a complete skeleton looks like.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are super-saurs,'' Neugent laughed, ``as in Super Bowl.
They're going to be great, breathtaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fernbank display will depict the meat-eating Giganotosaurus
trying to get its claws on about 20 eggs of the much-bigger female
dinosaur, she said. The display also will include a cast of a
flying dinosaur called a Pterasaur, also unique to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of all this will be unlike anything ever done
before,'' said Neugent. ``These dinosaurs are so huge. If I were to
stand up beside a single vertebrae, it would come up to my ears.''
Neugent stands about 5 feet, 7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The male dinosaur, Hengst said, was ``much bigger than a T. rex,
had a bigger head and a much larger bite. It's a longer animal
overall by 5 feet than the biggest T. rex known to this point. But
it's more lightly built, and its legs seem to be a little lighter.
I think it was probably a faster animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the male was a shrimp compared to the female. The
Argentinosaurus female was 120 feet long, and the male
Giganotosaurus 47 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen dinosaurs all over the world, and I've never seen
one anything as big as this,'' Hengst said, referring to the
Argentinosaurus. ``It's absolutely stunning to stand next to one of
those vertebrae, especially when you've looked at as many as I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
