<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CRADLE28-COX     01-27 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CRADLE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tale of battle for free expression crackles with energy, good
intentions
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Presented as ``a (mostly) true story,'' ``Cradle
Will Rock'' raucously explores a little-known chapter of American
history in which U.S. soldiers closed down a stage play directed by
Orson Welles on the eve of its opening.
</P>
<P>
   The government action came at the height of the Great
Depression, when American workers began turning to unions. Marc
Blitzstein's pro-labor musical, ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' was
banned because of growing fear of communism in America.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Robbins' film account wears its politics on its sleeve,
pitting artists against their wealthy patrons in a battle over free
expression. It's a war that's still being waged today, as evidenced
by the Brookyn Museum of Art's controversial ``Sensation'' exhibit,
which Mayor Rudolph Guiliani attempted to shut down by withholding
the museum's funding.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its didactic tone, the complex and poignant comedy is
one of the year's most entertaining films. The National Board of
Review named it one of the 10 best films of 1999 and honored
writer-director-producer Robbins (``Dead Man Walking'') for Special
Achievement in Filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in the boisterous style of 1930s motion pictures,
``Cradle Will Rock'' is set amid New York City's art and theater
world, where fictional characters intermingle with larger-than-life
historical figures such as Nelson Rockefeller, William Randolph
Hearst and Welles.
</P>
<P>
   They are portrayed by a stellar ensemble cast that includes Hank
Azaria, Ruben Blades, Joan Cusack, John Cusack, Cary Elwes, Angus
Macfadyen, Bill Murray, Vanessa Redgrave, Susan Sarandon, John
Turturro and Emily Watson.
</P>
<P>
   The head-swimming array of characters and stories is unwieldy at
times, particularly as the film builds to its feverish climax, but
Robbins pulls it together with an assured hand.
</P>
<P>
   His exhaustively researched screenplay is tragic, funny and
uplifting.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins sets the political scene with newsreel footage from the
era, which we view from behind a movie theater screen, where
aspiring actress Olive Stanton (Watson) sleeps. The camera follows
the homeless waif in one continuous tracking shot as she is chased
out into the street, introducing several key characters before
taking us through a third-floor apartment window, where Blitzstein
(Azaria) composes at his piano.
</P>
<P>
   The passionate, 22-year-old Welles (Macfadyen) mounts a
production of ``The Cradle Will Rock'' with his Federal Theater
company, which includes combative producer John Houseman (Elwes)
and Italian immigrant actor Aldo Silvano (Turturro).
</P>
<P>
   Headed by Hallie Flanagan (Cherry Jones), the Federal Theater is
a Works Progress Administration project that brings lost-cost
theater to millions of Americans while providing work for
unemployed actors. A congressional committee in Washington conducts
hearings over the supposed ``un-American'' themes of Federal
Theater plays.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to testify are Hazel Huffman (Joan Cusack), a lowly WPA
clerk concerned about content, and Tommy Crickshaw (Murray), a
boozy ventriloquist embittered about the decline of vaudeville.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzstein's musical becomes a political powder keg.
</P>
<P>
   Paralleling the struggle of Welles' theater group is the
conflict between Rockefeller (John Cusack) and Mexican artist Diego
Rivera (Blades), whose class-conscious mural for Rockefeller Center
affronts the tycoon's aesthetic taste. Mediating their dispute is
Margherita Sarfatti (Sarandon), a fascist sympathizer and former
mistress of Mussolini.
</P>
<P>
   The stylish, tightly woven tapestry features marvelous
performances and many wonderful scenes. John Cusack, Macfadyen,
Elwes and Murray give especially sharp turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists are whores like the rest of us,'' says publishing
magnate Hearst (John Carpenter), wearing a powdered wig at a
costume ball, as Robbins juxtaposes the decadent rich against the
embattled painter and performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cradle Will Rock'' portrays them as quite the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
