</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE SECTION FRONT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-ECONOMY (Undated) _ Gone is the vision of America as an
economically weak giant. With the economy growing since 1995 at an
average annual rate of 4.2 percent, unemployment has fallen to a
30-year low of 4.1 percent, and consumer prices have risen less
than 3 percent a year. Even as its global rivals have faltered, the
United States has turned out to be capable of more growth and less
inflation than almost anyone had anticipated. By Louis Uchitelle.
WITH GRAPHIC and PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
