<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BRADLEY-28GORE-COX     01-27 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-28GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No more Mr. Nice Guy in Bradley-Gore race
 &HT;    By Ken Fosket and Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ Democrat Bill Bradley dumped the laid-back
style that has characterized his insurgent campaign for president
Thursday and lashed out at ``months of misleading statements'' from
rival Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And for Gore's part, he learned a hard lesson of what happens
when you portray yourself as a ``fighter'' in politics: Your
opponent, even one who professes to disdain bare-knuckle brawls,
might hit back.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, pounding away at the chord he struck during Wednesday
night's debate, told crowds of New Hampshire voters that Gore
couldn't be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't trust the people to tell them the truth in the
campaign, how can the people trust that you are going to tell them
the truth when you are president of the United States?'' Bradley
asked a crowd of supporters in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at Timberland Co., the boot and clothing maker, Bradley
turned to a basketball metaphor to explain his new line of attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been negative, has been misleading,'' Bradley
said. ``Last night, I decided it was my turn, and I threw a little
elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Washington for President Clinton's final
State of the Union address, Gore gave an interview on New Hampshire
Public Radio and toured a software company in Manchester, touting
the Clinton administration's record on the economy. Then he turned
his attention to Bradley's continuing accusations and said, ``I
don't quite understand how someone can condemn so-called negative
attacks while in the next breath launch real negative attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said Bradley's new aggressive style
of campaigning was ``an act of desperation'' and ``a crass
political decision by someone who is supposed to be apolitical.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Berman, Bradley's campaign chairman, said Bradley's
frustration with Gore's assaults on his health care proposals and
domestic agenda had been building for some time. But Berman said
Bradley waited until Wednesday's debate to confront Gore ``face to
face.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Bradley's new assertiveness can
translate into a win for him in Tuesday's New Hampshire primary.
Some analysts believed Bradley's criticisms in the debate fell
flat. But raising questions about Gore's trustworthiness might be
more effective, said Dartmouth political scientist Richard Winters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to the issue of Gore as the professional politician,''
Winters said. During the public radio interview, a caller
criticized Gore's record on abortion in terms similar to those used
by Bradley in their debate Wednesday night. She noted that Gore, as
a congressman in the early 1980s, had not supported federal funding
for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always supported Roe v. Wade,'' Gore insisted,
referring to the Supreme Court decision that legalized abortion. He
acknowledged, however, that early in his career he did not support
federal funding of abortions. ``But over the years, I've come to
the view that federal funding ought to be available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The more-assertive rhetoric by Bradley also translated into a
more assertive campaign style on the road Thursday. He staged
several impromptu stops between his scheduled events. Seeking to
counter the perception that Bradley might be finished if he fails
to win Tuesday, his aides announced Bradley will appear in
Hartford, Conn., and Brooklyn, N.Y., the day after the primary.
Both states are central to Bradley's strategy for winning the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
