<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ABERNATHY28-COX     01-27 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABERNATHY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abernathy awaits sentence in scheme to pocket taxpayer's money
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former State Sen. Ralph David Abernathy III says he
has turned his life over to God. But his immediate future rests in
the hands of Fulton County Superior Court Judge L.A. McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell is scheduled to sentence the son and namesake of
Atlanta's famed civil rights leader today. A jury found Abernathy
guilty last month of a scheme to pocket taxpayer funds. Although
his first trial ended in a mistrial, he was convicted by the second
jury on 18 counts _ five of theft by taking involving $5,700, five
of false swearing, five of violating his oath of office, two of
forgery and one count of influencing a witness. A decision to
appeal is being weighed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thurbert Baker has indicated that his office
will seek incarceration. Abernathy's lawyer, Theodore Lackland,
plans to ask the judge to spare his client prison time. ``We may
well make an argument that perhaps incarceration is not
appropriate,'' Lackland said.
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy, who is free on $25,000 bond, is preaching part-time
at West Hunter Street Baptist Street, where his father was pastor
for many years. He also owns a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith in God hasn't wavered,'' said Abernathy, who was
unable to seek Senate re-election because his check for the
election qualifying bounced. ``I'm looking forward to whatever
happens in the future. I'm still doing my business and studying to
become an ordained minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy will learn today whether his business and studies will
be interrupted. It may be fortunate for him that he is being
sentenced in a state court, instead of in federal court, where
judges have less discretion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the potential maximum sentence is significantly higher
in state court _ Abernathy faces up to 150 years _ state sentences
vary more widely than federal ones. Legal experts say he won't
serve anything close to the maximum _ if he even sees the inside of
a jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things that all judges look at,'' said criminal
defense attorney Jerry Froelich. ``They look at the good that an
official has done. They look at ... whether there was minor or
large harm to community; if it was a minuscule amount of money,''
said Froelich, who defended businessman Mack Wilburn in the
Hartsfield International Airport kickbacks trial. Wilburn was
acquitted in the federal case that sent former Atlanta City
Councilman D.L. ``Buddy'' Fowlkes, former Airport Commissioner Ira
Jackson and businessman Dan Paradies to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was found guilty on 83 counts of mail fraud in
connection with a scheme through which he received more than $1
million in illegal payments; 43 counts of accepting bribes; and
four counts of tax evasion. He was sentenced to 42 months in
federal prison. For one count of accepting a bribe and three counts
of tax evasion, Fowlkes got 41 months.
</P>
<P>
   Paradies, who owned an airport gift shop, was convicted on 83
counts of mail fraud and one count of conspiracy for his role in a
scheme to bribe as many as five members of the Atlanta City
Council. He was sentenced to 33 months.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta attorney Larry Thompson, who defended Paradies in the
airport case, said judges tend to weigh practical aspects such as
the nature of the offense and whether there were aggravating
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In Abernathy's case, there were no serious aggravating aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Also, judges tend to take into consideration the public scrutiny
and notoriety brought to bear in cases involving public officials,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that would probably count toward a sentence that would not
be a severe sentence,'' said Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   William Boone, associate professor of political science at Clark
Atlanta University, agrees. ``I think most folks probably would
argue that ... he was judged guilty and that would suffice. Jail
time is probably not necessary,'' Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, society wants a system of justice that is stable and
even-handed, Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you're really trying to do in this instance is send a
message to a certain population that this kind of behavior won't be
tolerated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tyrone Brooks (D-Atlanta), an Abernathy family friend, said
he is amazed the case went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't understand why the attorney general would want
to prosecute such a case of low value in terms of money. You're
talking about a conviction based on $5,000 over a 10-year period.
I've looked at all the evidence the state brought to trial and,
from my knowledge, I'm convinced he's innocent. I'm convinced he's
not stolen a penny,'' said Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks thinks it would be unfair for Abernathy to serve prison
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the Legislature over 10 years and I've seen $10
million dollars stolen and embezzled, and people get probation,''
said Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
