<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8607 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-LOCKHEED28-COX     01-27 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lockheed Martin Corp.'s latest restructuring includes
mixed news for its Marietta, Ga., plant.
</P>
<P>
   The ailing defense giant said Thursday it will consolidate
management of all aircraft business in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That will eliminate a division headquarters and another 830 or
so jobs at the Marietta plant, which is already undergoing a
2,000-job cutback announced last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan leaves the plant's assembly lines and other
programs intact, for now quelling speculation that the entire
facility might be closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means more layoffs, but that beats a shutdown,'' said
Richard Aboulafia, an aviation consultant at Teal Group in
Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the Aeronautical Systems division based in
Marietta will be folded into a new Lockheed Martin Aeronautics Co.
based at Lockheed Martin's Fort Worth plant.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the new unit will manage operations at all three of
the company's primary aircraft facilities in Fort Worth, Marietta
and Palmdale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``No decision has been made on changes in any assembly work
right now,'' said Sam Grizzle, a spokesman at the Marietta plant.
``The company is still evaluating a variety of approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed Martin, the nation's biggest
defense contractor, has been beset by troubles in various programs
and the slowdown in defense spending. Analysts also blame poor
management for the slide, which has depressed profits and cut
Lockheed Martin's stock price by more than half since last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year the company disclosed it would consider shedding
or reorganizing core assets, including aircraft plants, as part of
its turnaround effort.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft management consolidation announced Thursday will
result in about 2,500 job cuts, to be spread equally among Fort
Worth, Marietta and Palmdale, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The new, streamlined Fort Worth unit will be led by Dain
Hancock, a corporate executive vice president in Bethesda. All
positions below him have yet to be filled, leaving the fate of the
Marietta top management team unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be making a final disposition on job changes for 30
days,'' Lockheed Martin spokesman Jim Fetig said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin said it expects the consolidation to generate
$175 million in annual savings. It said the savings will come from
a leaner management structure and centralized administrative
functions. It also said certain ``engineering, production
operations and material management'' functions will be
consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   But details of the job cuts in Marietta are still being worked
out, Grizzle said. The cuts will take place over the next 18
months, with most finished by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of short-term impact, the job loss is not that
significant, but what you have to worry about is the quality of
jobs and when the top management goes, there is less incentive to
maintain the local operation here,'' said Roger Tutterow, an
economist at Kennesaw State University.
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia said Lockheed's plan strikes a balance between shaking
up the status quo and preserving the company's basic capabilities.
The aviation analyst said the current setup, in which separate
business units at Marietta, Fort Worth and Palmdale answer to
corporate headquarters, contributed to poor strategic oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had developed into a rather feudal organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth plant, where Lockheed Martin makes the F-16
fighter and a portion of the F-22 fighter, was a logical choice as
the new management base, Aboulafia added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most commercially focused of the plants and also the
most successful at cost-cutting,'' he said. In addition, the plant
is expected to head up Lockheed Martin's work on the Joint Strike
Fighter if it wins a competition to build the planned multi-service
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia also contends keeping the Marietta plant's assembly
lines open is wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get rid of Marietta as a plant, you're cutting muscle
and bone,'' he said. ``If there's any kind of upturn in the defense
market they're going to need the capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Marietta's main product is the C-130J cargo plane, which has
suffered from development delays and poor initial sales. But the
outlook seems to be improving. In the past two months the company
bagged a handful of new foreign orders and persuaded the Air Force
to accelerate its future purchase plans.
</P>
<P>
   The plant also does final assembly and testing on the F-22
fighter program, which survived a funding dogfight in Congress last
year and could face more attacks in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace analyst Paul Nisbet, of JSA Research, contends
Lockheed Martin would save more money in the long run by moving
those programs to Fort Worth and abandoning Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would make sense economically, but not politically,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Georgia has lost clout on defense matters since the
departures of former Sen. Sam Nunn and House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
Nisbet believes Lockheed Martin is reluctant to narrow its base of
political support by closing plants. Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), whose
district includes the Marietta plant, called Thursday's
announcement ``disappointing to all of us who have worked hard to
represent the workers of Lockheed's Marietta plant.'' But, he
added, ``our top goal of assuring the plant's survival has been
achieved for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing the Georgia delegation can do is stay focused
on the goal of ensuring adequate funding for the F-22 and C-130J
programs,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell said: ``I have been reassured that the F-22
and C-130J production lines in Marietta will not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this decision is best for business,'' the Georgia
Republican added, arguing the cost of shutting down the Marietta
plant and moving its operations to Fort Worth is prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, House Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Illinois) is
scheduled to tour the Marietta plant and the F-22 assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's restructuring includes a management
consolidation of its space systems business in Denver. That move,
which will result in another 300 to 400 job cuts and projected
annual savings of up to $40 million, has no direct impact on the
Marietta plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``These actions are the direct result of our continuing drive to
improve our customer focus, flatten our management structure and
enhance our financial performance,'' said Lockheed Martin Chairman
Vance Coffman.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr of the Cox News Service Washington Bureau
contributed to this report
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
