<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN-A     01-27 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN-ART-375(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL SUPER BOWL'S DOT-COM ADVERTISERS BE ABLE TO DISTINGUSH
THEMSELVES? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT20,21 are sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether or not Super Bowl XXXIV is remembered for the game that
the St. Louis Rams and the Tennessee Titans play on Sunday, it will
certainly enter the annals of advertising as Dot-Com Bowl I.
</P>
<P>
   But will consumers recall the commercial assault as a dot-comedy
of errors or as a turning point for dot-coms on the road to
respectability? That's the $135 million question _ the approximate
cost of all the commercials to run during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the 30-plus companies spending record sums to buy
commercial time during the game to generate attention and awareness
will be Web sites and electronic commerce entrepreneurs with
unfamiliar names like Computer.com, Epidemic.com, Healtheon/WebMD,
Lifeminders.com, Netpliance.com, OurBeginning.com, Oxygen Media and
Pets.com. Many have never advertised anywhere before, much less on
a Super Bowl, the premier event on the Madison Avenue calendar.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, only three dot-coms advertised on the Super Bowl
last year. The goal of the newcomers is to duplicate the success
enjoyed by the dot-coms in 1999; two, Hotjobs.com and the
Monster.com unit of TMP Worldwide, are returning to see if
lightning can strike twice.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes have never been higher for companies gambling that
the value of the impressions they make by exposing themselves to
the 130 million or so Americans watching the game _ typically the
largest audience of the year for any television program _ will
justify the high cost of commercial time. The biggest threat is
that consumers will be unable to distinguish one dot-com from
another, turning what was intended as a shrewd strategy to get
noticed into a marketing blunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-coms could negate each other and have a hard time
cutting through,'' said Robert Lachky, vice president for brand
management at Anheuser-Busch in St. Louis, the only beer advertiser
during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the leader in our industry, coming off a record year,
the Super Bowl is money well spent,'' he added. ``For the dot-coms,
the issue is who will have a distinctly branded message.''
Anheuser-Busch is paying an estimated $17 million to run
commercials in every quarter for Budweiser and Bud Light beers _
almost $30 million if production, agency and other costs are
included.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl is a tough place to stand out, period,'' said
Ted Sann, co-chief executive and chief creative officer at the BBDO
New York unit of BBDO Worldwide, the Omnicom Group agency that is
creating Super Sunday spots for Federal Express, PepsiCo and Visa.
</P>
<P>
   Sann continued: ``I was in San Francisco a month ago, driving up
101, and there was a billboard every two feet for a dot-com. It was
a blur. If it's a blur on the Super Bowl, you're going to be
throwing your money away.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers, dot-coms or not-coms, are spending an average of
about $2.2 million for each 30-second spot _ a heart-stopping
$73,333 a second. That's 37.5 percent more than a 30-second
commercial cost during Super Bowl XXXIII in 1999 and is believed to
be the largest year-to-year increase ever.
</P>
<P>
   The demand from dot-coms, amplified by the booming economy, led
ABC to charge the record rates; some spots sold for as much as $3
million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the advertising industry see the dot-com stampede as the
logical extension of the race into traditional media by Internet
marketers, a phenomenon that anyone who watched television,
listened to the radio or read a newspaper between Halloween and
Christmas could not help but notice.
</P>
<P>
   The frenetic demand for commercial time in the fourth quarter of
the Super Bowl game was initially perceived as ``a one-trick
pony,'' said Marv Goldsmith, president for sales and marketing at
the ABC Television Network in New York, part of the ABC unit of
Walt Disney Co. ``But now we're going to have the highest gross in
the history of our company for a first quarter,'' fueled by the
superior Super Bowl ad sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-coms are coming in as strong as they are for the same
reason as our basic, bedrock advertisers,'' Goldsmith said, ``to
build brand awareness, to introduce new campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have a Super Bowl once a month,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But others in the advertising industry worry that the dot-com
mania is a sign of outlandish excess in the way that wild gyrations
in the prices of mediocre stocks are a sign of a market top. They
wonder whether this might signal the beginning of the end of the
widespread presence of Internet marketers in mass-media
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these companies we haven't heard a lot about,'' said
Norm Rickeman, partner in the media and entertainment group at
Andersen Consulting in Minneapolis. ``They want to get their names
out there, make a big splash.''
</P>
<P>
   He questioned the wisdom of this strategy for some dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if the commercial drives someone to a site and the
experience is not what it should be?'' Rickeman asked. ``If you
don't deliver, maybe you would have been better off spending the $3
million'' on improving the computer user's experience at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Other signs indicate that some players in Dot-Com Bowl I might
not be ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, executives at Lifeminders.com, which offers a
personalized e-mail service, decided to buy Super Bowl time in late
November. But their agency refused to create a spot, complaining
that there wasn't enough time to produce anything worth running on
such a big event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not to say you can't do things fast, but we didn't feel
comfortable that we could deliver our best product,'' said David
Lubars, co-president and creative director at Fallon McElligott in
Minneapolis, the Lifeminders.com agency. ``It was not in our best
interest, or the client's.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lifeminders.com executives made a low-budget spot on
their own. Crude type on screen proclaims, ``This is the worst
commercial on the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Many dot-coms may be vying for that dubious distinction, and not
on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're putting a disproportionate amount of your ad
spending behind a Super Bowl commercial, and you're just putting
your name out there without saying what kind of company you are,
it's not enough,'' said G. Michael Sievert, vice president for
marketing at the Etrade Group, the online brokerage firm, which
will run three commercials during the game and be the first dot-com
to sponsor a Super Bowl halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people focus on dot-coms, it plays to our advantage,''
Sievert asserted, ``because we've been pounding away at our
message, the value of taking charge of your own financial future,
for a long time'' _ well, a long time in Internet time, since
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of these companies, the Super Bowl might work,'' he
added, ``and it might not.'' The Etrade spots, part of an offbeat
campaign by Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners in San Francisco, an
Omnicom agency, include one mocking the expectations for Super Bowl
commercials. The deliberately amateurish spot, featuring a monkey,
ends with this cheeky rejoinder: ``Well, we just wasted two million
bucks. What are you doing with your money?''
</P>
<P>
   One dot-com, Computer.com, is spending more than half the $5.8
million that is raised during its initial round of venture capital
financing to run three commercials before and during the game to
promote the startup of its Web site, which is aimed at novice
computer users. The spots were created by Merkley Newman Harty in
New York, part of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to write the check, so I took a big, deep breath,'' said
Mike Ford, president at Computer.com in Maynard, Mass., ``but it's
the only day of the year when everybody watches the commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Zapolin, chief executive at Computer.com, chimed in:
``Since our idea is to make computing easy for the 80 percent of
the people who say they don't feel comfortable with technology,
we're talking to a huge number of people. And the Super Bowl gives
you 100 million-plus people watching your commercial in a positive
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   That appealed even to dot-coms that, unlike Computer.com, are
seeking more sophisticated consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly the largest audience we've ever reached,'' said
Randy Kilgore, executive director for marketing and sales at The
Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition in New York, a unit of Dow
Jones &AMP; Co. that will run a commercial for WSJ.com by Arnold
Communications in Boston, part of Snyder Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Being one of many dot-com advertisers, said Neil Budde, editor
and publisher at WSJ.com, ``actually helps show the brand is part
of the dot-com world, a big player in the dot-com space.''
</P>
<P>
   Conventional advertisers appear to be comfortable with so much
dot-company. ``We've got to stand out regardless of who else is
advertising,'' said Dawn Hudson, senior vice president for strategy
and marketing at Pepsi-Cola Co. in Purchase, N.Y. The company will
run two spots for Mountain Dew by BBDO New York during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-coms, like any packaged-goods marketer, have to be
remembered and give the broad audience an idea of what their brands
are about,'' she said. ``The only difference is the consumer isn't
bumping into them in the supermarket, so the better dot-com
commercials will give viewers a feeling of what the site experience
is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
