A8619 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-KUROSAWA-REVIEW-LA     01-27 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KUROSAWA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUROSAWA, THE MAN AND HIS FILMS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Saturday, Jan. 29 _ tonight is Saturday in
this story. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alex Cox, whose own film career stalled after the initial
promise of the 1984 cult film ``Repo Man,'' essays the life of a
cinematic genius in tonight's ``Kurosawa: The Last Emperor.'' Cox
mixes the usual blend of clips from Akira Kurosawa's masterpieces _
``Roshomon,'' which introduced Japanese film to the West, as well
as ``Yojimbo,'' ``Seven Samurai,'' ``Throne of Blood,''
``Kagemusha'' and ``Ran'' _ with thoughts from colleagues and
industry heavy-hitters Francis Ford Coppola, John Woo, Bernardo
Bertolucci and Paul Verhoeven. The result is a serviceable
once-over for fans and the uninitiated alike, though a more
thoughtful, more thorough rumination would have been more
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Cox does some quick armchair psychology, matching moments from
the filmmaker's life to scenes they inspired in his films:
Kurosawa's brother's suicide becomes a moment in ``Kagemusha,''
while the bodies strewn across such films as ``Seven Samurai''
reflect the filmmaker's memory of a devastating earthquake in his
youth. Kurosawa's obsession with detail was such that he worked all
day with an actor to perfect the strut of a samurai for one simple
shot. The breathtaking hailstorm of arrows that rained upon Toshiro
Mifune in ``Throne of Blood'' is amusingly recalled _ the obviously
worried actor couldn't sleep the night before the sequence was
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   His mule-headedness is recalled as Russian filmmaker Andrei
Konchalovsky recalls that Kurosawa was insulted when he tried to
debate the virtues, or lack thereof, of Lenin _ he would not brook
disagreement with his pronouncements. Cox also touches on his
despairing suicide attempt after the filmmaker's disastrous
flirtation with Hollywood, on ``Tora Tora Tora.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurosawa was about film, and virtually nothing else _ if he
didn't have a project in the works, he had nothing to talk about,
one friend tells us. Another puts it, ``If he didn't work, there
wasn't any Kurosawa around.'' He made movies, one colleague recalls
him saying, because if he could make straightforward statements,
``I would have written it on a placard and held it up instead.''
And Verhoeven underscores that Kurosawa was also that rarity, an
artist: He returns to his films to see ``why I wanted to become a
filmmaker,'' and, he adds regretfully, ``and look what I'm doing
now _ special effects.'' &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The show: ``Kurosawa: The Last Emperor'' &QL; 
What: Documentary about the legendary Japanese filmmaker. &QL; 
Where: Independent Film Channel. &QL; 
When: 8:45 tonight &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8621 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-COMMON-GROUND-REVI     01-27 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COMMON-GROUND-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY HISTORY EXPLORED IN `COMMON GROUND'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Saturday, Jan. 29 _ tonight is Saturday in
this story. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Common Ground,'' premiering tonight on Showtime, is a
sometimes clumsy, sometimes pedantic anthology film essaying the
gay experience from 1954 to the present, all set in a sleepy New
England town. (HBO's upcoming ``If These Walls Could Talk 2'' will
offer roughly the same structure, but limits the drama to lesbian
stories).
</P>
<P>
   Its first story, ``A Friend of Dorothy,'' is both its oddest and
its least subtle, actually intimating in a strange way that old
bigoted saw, that gays in fact do try to recruit fresh blood. In
it, a gay Naval officer (Jason Priestley) assumes that a young
woman (Brittany Murphy) in the Navy is interested in him, a gay
man, because she herself is gay. He leads her to a gay bar that is
subsequently raided; she loses her commission and is rejected in
her hometown, except by a lesbian who suggests she head to
Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   The second segment, written by playwright Terrence McNally, is
the strongest, concerning a gay '70s-era high-school teacher
(Steven Weber) who allows his fear of being outed to prevent him
from helping a student (Jonathan Taylor Thomas) seeking his
counsel. Both Weber and Thomas do strong work, and the issues
tackled are both thornier and more realistically depicted than
elsewhere in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, a present-day vignette written by Harvey Fierstein is a
jokey, slight piece about a gay guy who gets cold feet on his
wedding day, and his mildly homophobic father (Ed Asner) who talks
him out of it. If this section is any indication, gay people
apparently can't spout three lines of conversation without
mentioning their homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   A heterosexual character played by Eric Stoltz narrates all
three vignettes, continually making a sane plea for understanding;
he's conveniently on hand when things wrap up too tidily with a
treacly conclusion cribbed directly from the movie ``Places in the
Heart.'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Common Ground.'' &QL; 
What: Anthology drama about gay life over a 50-year period.! &QL; 
The stars: Steven Weber, Jonathan Taylor Thomas, Ed Asner. &QL; 
Where: Showtime &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-CONSERVATIVES2     01-27 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CONSERVATIVES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain, Bush trade fire over tax cut proposal
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ Arizona Sen. John McCain brushed off
criticism from Gov. George W. Bush of Texas on Thursday that his
tax plan is too much like a Democrat's.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a line he first used in Wednesday's debate, McCain
said Bush ``keeps spinning like Bill Clinton.'' McCain has proposed
a $237 billion tax cut plan, but would devote more than 60 percent
of anticipated budget surpluses to Social Security and paying down
the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting his campaign's growing confidence in advance of
Tuesday's primary, McCain also urged Bush to refrain from negative
campaigning. ``I'd hope we discuss the issues and debate them,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Nashua, made an appeal to core Republican
voters. ``It's important to nominate somebody who will be able to
debate the Democrat nominee, not mimic them,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also picked up the endorsement of Jack Kemp, the 1996
Republican vice presidential nominee. Kemp criticized McCain as
being ``obsessed with debt reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp called another Bush rival Steve Forbes a ``good friend''
but said, ``Governor Bush is the one who can inspire the Congress,
who can inspire the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Large, enthusiastic crowds greeted McCain in eastern New
Hampshire, where he called his time in the Granite State ``the
greatest experience of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his proposal to ban soft money, unlimited and
unregulated donations to political parties, makes him better able
to hammer Vice President Al Gore on Democratic fund-raising abuses
in 1996. ``It's much easier for me to attack Clinton and Gore
because I have the high ground,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has called McCain's plan harmful to the GOP, but McCain has
vowed to fight for campaign finance reform ``to my last breath.''
He will begin airing an ad today that appeals to New Hampshire's
independent streak. The ad says voters ``can send a powerful
message to America'' by giving McCain a victory Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
