<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUN SAYS REFUGEE BOY SHOULD REMAIN IN THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERESA MEARS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The curious case of Elian Gonzalez took another
surprising twist Thursday when the nun who had provided her house
as a neutral meeting site for the 6-year-old and his grandmothers
declared that she thought Elian should remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a fear she sensed from the grandmothers, Sister Jeanne
O'Laughlin said, ``I do not think that this child will be able to
live without fear if he goes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the grandmothers revisted Capitol Hill Thursday and
again asked members of Congress to oppose legislation that would
grant US citizenship to Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The case is also playing out in federal court in Miami, where
district Judge William Hoeveler Thursday said he will rule in
mid-March on whether he has jurisdiction in a lawsuit by Elian's
Miami relatives seeking political asylum for the boy. Because
Attorney General Janet Reno has said the case should be allowed to
proceed in court, Elian appears likely to remain in this country
for at least another six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The comments of O'Laughlin, one of the most respected people in
South Florida, is yet another factor that could prolong the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant development because of her credibility
in Florida,'' said Dario Moreno, a political science professor at
Florida International University. ``The more time this takes to
develop, the higher the stakes become for each side.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin, the president of Barry University, is one of the
first civic leaders outside the traditional anti-Castro activists
to say that Elian, who was rescued from the sea on Thanksgiving Day
after his mother and 10 others drowned, should stay in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Most Miami leaders, including Catholic Church officials, have
stayed out of the controversy or issued measured statements
declaring that the case should be decided in court.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin comments were especially surprising because she was
asked to host the meeting by Reno, a longtime friend from Miami who
is urging Elian's return to Cuba. O'Laughlin plans to meet in
Washington Friday with Reno and Florida's two US senators, Connie
Mack and Bob Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in federal court here Thursday, the US Immigration
and Naturalization Service filed a massive brief urging the court
to dismiss the suit by Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents released were transcripts of the agency's
interview in Cuba with Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez. The
father said Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, had first said he
would return Elian immediately, but later said he could not do so
because it would look bad.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez also said his relatives had offered him $2
million, a house, and a car if he would leave Elian in the United
States, or come here to join his child.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying that I am being coerced by the Cuban
government,'' he said. ``However, you can see that they are the
ones being coerced by the Cuban community in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez, in a television interview, denied that he had
ever said any of those things.
</P>
<P>
   The INS interviewed Juan Miguel Gonzalez twice, Dec. 13 at his
home in Cardenas and Dec. 31 at the home of a UNICEF representative
in Havana. ``Based on his demeanor, I had no reason to believe he
was being coerced,'' wrote Silma L. Dimmel, who heads the INS
office at the US mission in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have neither my consent nor my permission to be taking
the child here or there,'' Gonzalez said in the interview.
``Imagine their insensitivity, in taking that child to Disney World
and putting him on a boat ride when he had already suffered such an
ordeal. They forced him on the ride while he was crying and
screaming, not wanting to do so. It's abusive what they are doing
to Elian. The boy needs me.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Washington, the grandmothers met with lawmakers and
recounted their meeting with Elian in Miami the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our grandson is a whole different boy. He has changed
completely. We have to save this boy as soon as possible,'' said
Mariela Quintana de Gonzalez, the paternal grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Raquel Rodriquez, the maternal grandmother, said the longer
Elian is forced to remain in Miami, ``the more he is going to
suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   But a group of the boy's Florida relatives also visited the
nation's capital, urging support for the citizenship bill. ``He
doesn't want to go back,'' said Marisleysis Gonzalez, a cousin of
Elian. ``I saw him approach his grandmothers and had the
opportunity to see his face, and it was still the face of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers disagreed. ``We told him we wanted to bring him
back to Cuba. He nodded his head yes,'' Quintana said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joan Brown Campbell of the National Council of
Churches, which is sponsoring the grandmothers' trip to the US,
said that barring any new developments, the women would return to
Cuba Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said support for the citzenship bill seemed
to have lessened in recent days. House Speaker Dennis Hastert, an
Illinois Republican, would not predict the outcome of the measure,
but said it would follow normal legislative procedures. Some
lawmakers now are lining up behind a bill that would confer
permanent residency on Elian.
</P>
<P>
   At her weekly news conference Thursday, Reno said the Justice
Department had not taken a position on the constitutionality of the
pending bills.
</P>
<P>
   But she continued to say that the boy should be returned to
Cuba. ``If we got into a situation where, if American children
ended up abroad, and American parents wanted them returned, and a
foreign country made them a citizen so they did not return,'' she
said. ``I don't think people in the United States would be very
happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporter Mary Leonard in Washington contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
