<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-GOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER GOODS COMPANIES FALL OFF THE FAST TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growth companies find it hard to stay on the fast track forever.
</P>
<P>
   That truism was made clear this week by Coca-Cola and Procter &AMP;
Gamble, two of the world's pre-eminent makers of consumer goods.
Coca-Cola announced sweeping layoffs, and P&AMP;G tried to make a deal
for American Home Products and Warner-Lambert. Both moves had one
goal: restoring the rapid growth in profits that investors once
took for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, shares of packaged-goods companies were on top of
the world. Profits were rising a predictable 15 percent a year, and
shares in companies like P&AMP;G, H.J. Heinz, Kimberly-Clark and
Coca-Cola were outpacing the overall market's gains by 3-1. Brand
names on products like Tide detergent, Clorox bleach and Colgate
toothpaste were as good as money in the bank. And consumer goods
companies soon became the subjects of big, frenzied takeovers by
other concerns eager for the fat profit margins and rapid growth
that soaps and cereals had long generated.
</P>
<P>
   Hot has now turned to ho-hum at many of these companies. Once
predictable profits are under pressure. Revenue growth has fallen
to the single digits for many.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer goods companies have become the victims of their own
past success and of significant shifts in consumer buying patterns.
Perhaps most ignominious, these masters of brand image have been
beaten at their own highly sophisticated game by retailers, the
very companies that used to be at their beck and call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like the momentum of success carried them so they
didn't have to face the hard decisions,'' said Patrick R. Fallon,
chairman of the advertising company Fallon McElligott. ``They have
to get faster and more accountable. They are in an in-between
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a nice place to be. Procter &AMP; Gamble's sales in its recently
completed second quarter, for example, rose 7 percent. But expenses
increased at twice that rate, because of the high cost of marketing
and selling new products. And the company told stock analysts that
only a big cut in its tax rate, from 34.4 percent to 29 percent
over the next several years, will help it meet the high end of its
earnings growth target of 13 percent to 15 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, P&AMP;G shares, as well as other consumer goods
stocks, still command lofty prices when compared to their earnings
growth rates. P&AMP;G shares trade at 34 times trailing profits, 2.4
times the earnings growth rate. Colgate's stock trades at an even
bigger premium: Its price-earnings ratio of 42 is almost 3.2 times
its annual earnings growth rate. In the past, investors have been
unwilling to pay much more than 1.5 times a company's growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola faces some similar problems. Its management said on
Wednesday that it would have to lower the company's long-term
growth targets for both sales and earnings. Jennifer F. Solomon, an
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, estimates that the company's
earnings growth target of 15 percent to 20 percent a year will be
reduced to 12 percent to 14 percent. But Coca-Cola's stock trades
at 45 times trailing earnings, 3.5 times the lower growth rate.
Volume growth in the most recent quarter rose only 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Growth has slowed at these companies for a variety of reasons,
both internal and external. For one, the U.S. population is growing
just 1.5 percent annually. Moreover, several years of low inflation
have left these companies unable to raise prices as they had in
years past.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding into overseas markets helped these companies'
performance in the 1980s and 1990s, but growth from foreign
operations has now leveled off as well. And the strong dollar is
hurting them, since they calculate foreign profits in U.S.
currency.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, companies have to find profit growth some other way
_ by cutting costs, as Coca-Cola is doing with layoffs, or by
acquiring faster-growing companies, as P&AMP;G hoped to do by combining
with American Home and Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-GOODS-2NDTAK     01-27 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-GOODS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and Warner-Lambert. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Managements of P&AMP;G and Coca-Cola get high ratings from some
quarters for addressing the issue of slower growth. ``It is the
real penalty of leadership,'' said Laurel Cutler, who has been a
consultant to both of these companies and is a former top
advertising executive. ``When you're that good and that successful,
your methods, your training, your code and culture have worked so
well for so long it is virtually impossible in the absence of a
major threat or some deep peril to force change.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies with stables of famous consumer brands face formidable
competition today from companies like Wal-Mart and Dayton Hudson's
Target unit that had once been thought of as customers. So-called
private-label merchandise from these retailers is giving shoppers
lower-cost alternatives to name brands in almost every consumer
product category.
</P>
<P>
   House brands are, as a result, an increasingly powerful force in
supermarkets, drug chains and mass merchandisers across the nation.
In 1998, the most recent period for which data are available, store
brands accounted for 51 percent of the unit growth seen at these
retailers, according to the Private Label Manufacturers
Association. In supermarkets, store brands accounted for almost 20
percent of unit sales in 1998, up from 18.4 percent five years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has been especially aggressive in developing its house
brands. It recently bought the White Cloud name from P&AMP;G to put on
its own brand of toilet tissue and introduced its own laundry
detergent to compete with Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers like house brands because they produce considerably
more profit than name-brand goods. Consumers find the brands
comparable to name brands in quality and usually lower in price.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation has also given retailers more influence with
manufacturers. The top 10 supermarket chains account for nearly 40
percent of stores in the United States today; a few years ago the
top 10 accounted for roughly 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a shift in power to the retailers,'' said Mary
S. Pollack, editor of Supermarket Strategic Alert newsletter.
``Retailers control the shelf space, and as retailers have
consolidated, they are using their buying clout with manufacturers.
That's put pressures on manufacturers not to raise prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the retailers were building their own brands,
manufacturers were cheapening theirs with heavy promotions like
discount coupons. Although coupons helped make name-brand products
more affordable, they encouraged consumers to switch among brands.
This helped destroy brand loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants also say that many large-company brand managers are
risk averse and make decisions based on data that reflect the past.
``They are being whipped by the entrepreneurial companies, where
you are dealing with people who know why they got into the business
and know what's different or better about what they're offering,''
Ms. Cutler said. ``They're beating the rear-view people all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer goods companies may also be finding it hard to compete
for talent with the siren song of the Internet start-up. Marketing
jobs with packaged- goods giants used to attract top business
school graduates. Now such old-economy jobs may pale next to the
chance to blaze a trail in the new economy. According to the
Harvard Business School, 18 percent of its 1999 graduates took jobs
with high-technology companies, double the portion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is counting Procter &AMP; Gamble, Coca-Cola or other big
consumer brand companies out of the game. But reinventing
themselves is not going to be easy. ``They've woken up,'' Fallon
said, ``and understand they have to make some pretty dramatic
moves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0374 </DOCNO>
