u f BC-DIESEL-PRICES-BOS &LR;      01-27 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIESEL-PRICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRRORING HEATING OIL JUMP, DIESEL PRICES ROAR UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE BUTTERFIELD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Driven by the same forces affecting heating oil, diesel fuel
prices have soared in New England over the last week, prompting
brokers and trucking companies to slap surcharges on the cost of
shipping everything from food to furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has yet to show up on supermarket shelves in the form
of higher consumer prices. ``But it will . . . if it lasts long
enough,'' said David Wyss, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI
in Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The latest survey of diesel prices in New England, conducted
Monday, found prices at the pump averaging $1.84 a gallon. By
Thursday, the price at stations on the Massachusetts Turnpike had
reached $1.91 a gallon. Drivers and trucking companies were
reporting prices of $2.00 and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we can remember, it hasn't been this high in 10
years,'' said Joseph Pendergast, supply analyst for the state
Division of Energy Resources. He said the rapid rate of the hike
was particularily alarming.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week ago, the average price in New England was $1.44 a
gallon. On Jan. 10, freight operators in Massachusetts say, it was
as low as $1.31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's skyrocketing,'' said Ted Parker, chief operating officer
of Parker Express Inc., an Avon freight carrier. ``No one ever
expected it to go this high this fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said his firm, which operates a fleet of 68 long-haul
trucks, was forced this week to add a 3 percent to 5 percent ``fuel
surcharge'' on loads it ships, depending on the load and the
contract. He said he delayed the action longer than many trucking
firms, gambling that rising rates would level off. ``I lost,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the surcharges, Parker and other freight operators say
they are having to stretch for credit to cover the fuel bills while
waiting for payment on shipping contracts. ``We just bought 10,000
gallons Thursday,'' Parker said. ``You have to front a lot of money
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of diesel is highest in the Northeast, government
officials say, but the price of the fuel is approaching record
levels nationally too. John Cook, head of the petroleum information
unit in the US Department of Energy, said the current national
average diesel price _ $1.42 a gallon _ is the highest since the
Gulf War in 1990 when it topped out at $1.50 a gallon. ``That's
pretty pricey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diesel prices are mirroring the runup in home heating oil
because both are so-called ``distillate'' from number two crude
oil. Petroleum specialists say the only difference is a lower
sulfur content in diesel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the demand on heating oil that is driving up the price
of diesel,'' said Jack Sullivan, chief operating officer for the
New England Fuel Institute in Cambridge, Mass. But the root cause
for the spike in the cost of both, he said, is a sudden surge of
cold in the Northeast and a shortage of oil stock due to a
production cap set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said his organization is lobbying Washington to have
OPEC remove the cap. In the meantime, he noted, up to 10 oil ships
are en route to New York, which should ease the immediate crisis
and result in lower prices in a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some really good signs that relief is coming,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
