<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS OR RAMS? TWO OPPOSING PREDICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WHY THE TITANS WILL WIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE FREEMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Williams, Tennessee's defensive coordinator, was asked how
difficult it is for an offense to play the week following a game
against Tampa Bay's hard-hitting defense. A smile went across
Williams' face.
</P>
<P>
   After St. Louis had beaten Tampa Bay in the National Football
Conference championship game, Rams players were limping around as
if they had just played two games instead of one. That is why
Williams was smiling. He knows that this season, teams did not fare
well the week after having faced Tampa Bay. They usually start
slowly because the Bucs' physical play would still be having an
effect. Tennessee coaches talked about this fact in their meetings
this past week, and Williams plans to be aggressive with his calls
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys like it when I tell them, `We're not holding back,'''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Said cornerback Dalnon Sidney: ``When you take it to the Rams
early, you can unsettle them. That's our approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee defense has not received its due for just how
daring, and good, it is. The Titans may not have the speed at
linebacker that the Buccaneers do, but over all, they still have
good quickness. And because of Williams and coach Jeff Fisher, they
have solid defensive schemes to match.
</P>
<P>
   The key will be the Tennessee's secondary _ and the beginning of
the game. St. Louis has scored 123 first-quarter points, most in
the NFL, and mainly through the air. Tennessee likes to play a lot
of man to man, a scheme that worked when the Titans defeated the
Rams earlier this season. In that game, St. Louis had 25 snaps with
four wide receivers and 20 snaps with three receivers. While other
teams have crumbled when St. Louis went to those receiver packages,
the Titans stayed firm. They will again. Titans, 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY THE RAMS WILL WIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By THOMAS GEORGE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The glamour offense in this Super Bowl belongs to St. Louis,
which in the regular season scored 526 points, the third-most in
National Football League history.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kurt Warner threw 41 touchdown passes, 12 of them to
receiver Isaac Bruce, 8 to receiver Az-Zahir Hakin and 5 to running
back Marshall Faulk. No Titan caught more than 4 touchdown passes.
Faulk rushed for 1,381 yards, 77 more than Tennessee's Eddie
George.
</P>
<P>
   Offense is the staple of today's pro game, but for those who
believe that defense is essential to winning championships, the
Rams defense is the front-runner there, too. It allowed an average
5.37 yards per pass attempt, the Titans 6.05. The Rams allowed 33.8
percent in third-down conversion percentage, the Titans 35 percent.
It gained 57 sacks, the Titans 54.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are balanced, but the Rams have more balance. And
their ability to strike deep from any spot on the field makes them
more suited to jump ahead or to climb from behind. St. Louis is
simply more dangerous and capable of coloring the complexion of
this game on both sides of the ball, even in its special teams,
masterfully coached by Frank Gansz. Expect the Rams to play with
more flash, with more flair. Rams, 27-23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
