<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The message of the dissolving
candidacy of former Sen. Bill Bradley is that if you hold yourself
out as more principled and high-minded than your opponent, it
better be true and you better stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to reverse his political slide, Bradley suddenly
dropped his mask of statesmanship in the New Hampshire debate,
negating the theme on which he had intended to distinguish himself
from Gore. No more Mr. Nice Guy. But Gore is smoother at the tough
guy tactics. A frustrated Bradley got too personal in his attacks
on Gore and came across as a mean-spirited whiner. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
