<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-PUBLIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK IPO A TOUGH SELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Hancock Financial Services Inc. met a chilly
reception on Wall Street Thursday, as the venerable Boston life
insurer entered a new era of public ownership amid a grim climate
for stocks in financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Hancock, now owned by investors after 138 years in
policyholders' hands, gained little on their first day of trading
after the company raised $1.73 billion in an initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball legend Hank Aaron stood next to Hancock leaders at the
New York Stock Exchange, where the insurer's chief executive,
Stephen Brown, rang the opening bell. Chicago Cubs slugger Sammy
Sosa failed to show up for a scheduled appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock shares, which opened at 17 3/4, rose nearly 8 percent
above their initial offering price of 17 before slumping to close
at 17 5/8. The final gain is a mere 3.6 percent above Hancock's
initial price.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was heavy, with nearly one-third of the company's 102
million shares changing hands in the morning. The activity, which
pushed Hancock to an early high of 18 5/16, made the Boston insurer
the second most active stock on US exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Despite temporary bragging rights to being the insurance
industry's second-largest initial stock sale _ an honor it will
soon lose to bigger competitors preparing for Wall Street listings
_ Hancock was a tough sell to investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't exactly a dot-com,'' said Ira Zuckerman, an
industry analyst at Nutmeg Securities, referring to the sky-high
returns of Internet and other technology stocks. Many such stocks
skyrocket on their first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of sex appeal to this story,'' added
Zuckerman. ``It's a value stock in a market where value has not
been too hot. But it's a good value _ if they can continue to
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the nation's 13th largest life insurer has an
enviable brand name, highly regarded management, and a relatively
high return on equity of 12 percent. Banc of America Securities and
Keefe Bruyette &AMP; Woods both rated Hancock a ``buy,'' with 12-month
target prices of $23 and $22, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the near-term prospects for Hancock shares, Brown
said, ``I don't worry a lot about the short-term. We think we have
the best story (among insurers) to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a depressed environment for shares in banks, brokerages,
and especially insurers made the timing of Hancock's debut tough.
</P>
<P>
   Fears over the effect of rising interest rates on profits
depressed stocks of property and casualty insurers by 23.9 percent
last year and pushed down life and health insurers 9.6 percent,
according to SNL Securities. By contrast, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
stock index rose 19.5 percent, and the technology heavy Nasdaq
soared 85.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With stock markets buoyant, ``it's a question of where IPO
investors want to put their money _ in a life insurer or in a tech
company,'' said Elizabeth Malone, an analyst at Friedman, Billings,
Ramsey &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   An insurance analyst at Waddell &AMP; Reed, a Kansas mutual fund
firm that bought an unspecified number shares in Hancock, said that
while Hancock had attracted lots of smaller investors, big
institutional investors seemed wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical portfolio manager has a weighting in financial
services,'' said the analyst, Kenneth McQuade. ``He has to ask
himself whether to add to it by selling maybe some technology
stocks, or by getting rid of depressed insurance stocks he already
holds for what is basically another depressed stock.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuade said demand for Hancock shares initially outstripped
supply by three to one. ``There was enough demand for them to get
the deal done,'' added one analyst who declined to be identified.
``The real question is to what extent this interest is going to be
sustained in weeks ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   A raft of giant insurers, including Metropolitan Life, are
expected to convert to shareholder-owned companies in coming
months, potentially glutting the market for life insurance stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock must also consider whether its plan to encourage some of
its 660,000 policyholders who are now stock owners, generally of
small lots, to sell their shares could hurt its share price. The
project, to be carried out in coming months, is designed to help
the insurer save on administrative costs. But it could backfire if
Hancock's share price languishes, prompting too many
policyholder-investors to cash out, depressing the stock price even
more.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly known as John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.,
Hancock went public to gain a currency for growth and acquisitions.
With lead underwriter Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Hancock went out
at 1.1 times book value _ a first for a mutual insurer, Brown said.
The company now has a market capitalization of $5.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock calmed some investors earlier this week by announcing a
$134 million after-tax charge for the last quarter to cover losses
on controversial reinsurance contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The insurer initially faced around $1 billion in gross exposure
before reaching settlements with reinsurance participants.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hancock must convince investors that it can prosper and
expand. The company has given itself two years to prove it can
boost earnings by 15 percent a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
