r s BC-BKN-HAWKS28-COX     01-27 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Knicks may still have Hawk's number
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been eight months and four days since the New
York Knicks completed their sweep of the Atlanta Hawks in the
second round of the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks exposed an Atlanta squad that was stripped _ by
injury, fatigue and advanced age _ of its will to win and ability
to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The new-look Hawks that will take the court tonight at Philips
Arena against the Knicks can look at the squad at the opposite end
and know that the Knicks are, in part, the reason so much has
happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Knicks did was make all our problems painfully
apparent to everyone,'' general manager Pete Babcock said Thursday.
``But the truth is, we all knew long before that series that we
would have to do some things to become younger, deeper and more
athletic.
</P>
<P>
   In successive losses, the Hawks scored 92, 70, 78 and 66 points
against the Knicks in the second round series; it was a record for
futility. And it is no coincidence that only Dikembe Mutombo and
Alan Henderson, who was injured for all but four minutes in the
series, return as the only starters from that team. Seven of the
current 13 Hawks are newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   To Atlanta's chagrin, change has not improved the Hawks
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Knicks, they are bolstered by the return of center
Patrick Ewing. They are comfortably winning 60 percent of their
games and are within a game of Atlantic
</P>
<P>
   Division-leader Miami, two victories behind Indiana for best
record in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks might be no closer to their goal of winning a title _
they were crushed again by the league champion San Antonio last
week _ but they remain in the upper echelon of their conference.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Hawks, even though recast in the Knicks' image of
speed and explosives with Jim Jackson at small forward and Isaiah
Rider at shooting guard, will have to fight merely to advance to a
playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks being the Knicks, simply playing and winning a large
share of its games is not sufficient. New Yorkers must wrestle with
nuances of gesture, phrase, demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, coach Jeff Van Gundy indicated that he had been
told to smile more often and express more optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Some people wondered about the wisdom of retaining Ewing, the
team's center since 1985. Ewing, an 11-time all-star is six points
away from 23,000 for his career and is 36th all-time in minutes
played with more than 36,000.
</P>
<P>
   Others wondered about Ewing's impact on the Knicks' speed game,
his intimidation of smaller, quicker teammates who want to play
more freely and his willingness to accept a lesser role in the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was the big name in FBI reports that claimed NBA players
have frequented the Atlanta Gold Club. The Charleston Post-Courier
reported that dancers from that club were sent to Charleston, S.C.,
in April 1997 to entertain certain Knicks while they were preparing
for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Van Gundy was pressed on matters of his
players' deportment before they arrived Thursday amid the social
whirl attendant to the Sunday's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked why the Knicks took a train back to New York on
Wednesday rather than fly directly here after Tuesday night's
Washington postponement.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy told reporters that he is viewing this trip as he does
any other. ``You can find trouble if you want to find it,'' he
said. ``If you have the right guys, the priority will stay on
winning. And if you don't have the right guys, it doesn't matter
where you go; the priority won't be on winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Charlie Ward acknowledged the situation of NBA
players. ``We always have time on our hands, and we always have to
be disciplined,'' Ward said. ``Some guys take advantage of it, and
some guys don't and make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
