<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-ROCKER-LETTER28-COX     01-27 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-LETTER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves flippant in response to Rocker
 &HT;    By Joseph Lowery, Timothy McDonald and Michael Langford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   An Open Letter to Ted Turner:
</P>
<P>
   We would like to express our deep disappointment that you, in
particular, and the Braves organization in general, seem to have
taken the racist and bigoted remarks by pitcher John Rocker too
lightly. You have taken no disciplinary action, and your remarks
that he is ``just a kid'' and that it would be easier to do
something ``if he were not such a good pitcher'' reflect a cavalier
if not supercilious posture.
</P>
<P>
   We consider the scurrilous and bigoted remarks to be serious and
potentially dangerous. As pastors and community workers, we have
seen what at first appears to be innocuous intolerance degenerate
into more than verbal violence.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation with two of your associates, we urged prompt and
definitive action that would send a clear message that the Braves
organization has zero tolerance for this kind of behavior.
Regardless of what the commissioner of baseball may or may not do,
you and the Braves have a responsibility to the players, the fans
and to the community to take the kind of action that leaves no
doubt about where you stand. When we spoke to your colleagues, we
suggested that there were those in the community who would work
with you to find ways and means to help this confused young man in
the process of forgiveness and redemption. We were expecting
no-nonsense disciplinary action by the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we hear you saying there may be no disciplinary action and
he deserves a second chance. Most of us do not wish to deny him a
second chance. However, be not deceived. There must be no mocking
of the grave and solemn process of forgiveness and redemption. We
agree with those who opt for forgiveness, but we are stunned by
what appears to be a flippant disregard for the vile offenses
against teammates, fans and almost everybody else. Our
understanding of forgiveness and redemption is that they embrace a
divinely inspired process that involves repentance, contrition and
penitence. You have dispatched a negative message that this
reprehensible behavior is inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot pretend nor assume that Rocker's remarks were simply a
``slip of the tongue'' when they resonate more as a ``spilling of
the gut.'' He did not speak to the reporter ``off the top of his
head.'' It was a planned interview, and he seems to have spoken
``from the bottom of his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   We cling to the belief that Rocker can be forgiven and the hope
he can be redeemed. This does not exempt the sinner from
accountability. David, sinner and saint of the Old Testament, was
forgiven his transgression, but he paid a heavy toll and was not
allowed to build the Temple. The likelihood of Rocker's change and
growth is enhanced when he experiences the travail of remorse and
healing.
</P>
<P>
   Your statement about no accountability has sent a wave of
negative feelings across the community. We remember, Ted, that you
hired an African-American as Braves general manager long ago.
However, it was long ago, and we must move ahead to a brighter
future. We urge you to do the right thing. When we communicated
concern at your merging into the Time Warner conglomerate, you
assured us that the expanded structure would not dilute your social
sensitivity. Remember?
</P>
<P>
   This unfortunate affair can provide the opportunity to lift the
discussion about race and ethnicity and diversity in the new
millennium to new levels of meaning and helpfulness.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be good for Rocker, it will not be good for
baseball, it will not be good for your organization, it will not be
good for the community for such behavior to be whitewashed.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery is former president of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference. The Rev. Timothy McDonald is
president of Concerned Black Clergy and Michael Langford is
president of the United Youth Adult Conference. Several other
prominent African-American activists also signed the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
