<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8647 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-FRANCE-PRISONS-2TAKES     01-27 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PRISONS-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE SHOCKED BY BOOK DETAILING CONDITIONS IN LA SANTE PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When Dr. Veronique Vasseur began working at La Sante
prison in Paris, the experience was so shocking that she started
keeping a diary.
</P>
<P>
   Within days she had met inmates so deranged or depressed that
they had swallowed rat poison, forks or drain cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Skin diseases were rampant because showers were only available
twice a week, though temperatures sometimes soared to more than 100
degrees in cramped cells holding four prisoners each.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates stuffed their clothes in the cracks in their cells to
keep the rats out, and most of the mattresses were full of lice and
other insects. Some of the weaker prisoners, Dr. Vasseur came to
understand, had been turned into slaves by their cellmates.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vasseur's account of her work at La Sante over the last
seven years has just hit the bookstands, and it has caused an
uproar, prompting even the justice minister, Elisabeth Guigou to
admit that France's prison system is not something it can be proud
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in a lot of our prisons is not worthy of a
country such as ours,'' Ms. Guigou said, shortly after the first
excerpts from Dr. Vasseur's book, ``Chief Doctor at La Sante
Prison,'' began appearing in the press.
</P>
<P>
   While the French pride themselves on being standard bearers for
human rights, Dr. Vasseur's book has brought home some hard truths
</P>
<P>
   To start with, nearly half of the country's 55,000 prisoners
have never been convicted, a fact that has repeatedly drawn
criticism from the European Court of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, 124 inmates committed suicide in 1999, giving French
prisons one of the highest suicide rates among European
penitentiaries. By comparison, California, with a state inmate
population of about 160,000, had 24 suicides in 1999, according to
the Department of Corrections. (American prison experts point out,
however, that a large proportion of such suicides in the United
States occur in local jails and thus are not reflected in state
figures.)
</P>
<P>
   While the presumption of innocence is a benchmark of most
democratic states, the law here allows investigating magistrates to
put suspects in jail indefinitely without trial or bail. On
average, inmates who have not yet been tried spend four months in
jail. But some have spent far longer, and then been freed when the
magistrate has decided that there is not enough evidence to bring
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any effort to keep those awaiting trial from
sharing cells with those serving long sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot work and see the things I saw and not speak out,''
said Dr. Vasseur, who seems completely overwhelmed by the attention
she is getting. ``If I said nothing, I would be an accomplice to
all this, and that I cannot tolerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, some of France's most famous former prisoners _
including former ministers, top business people and the political
activist Jose Bove, who went to jail for vandalizing a McDonald's
restaurant _ signed a petition deploring prison conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Foul cells, systematic rape, humiliation of visiting families,
crude health care, drug dealing by guards and detention of young
offenders in cells with seasoned criminals has turned the country's
prisons into factories of crime and misery, the petition said.
</P>
<P>
   One former mayor who signed the petition, Jean-Michel Boucheron,
said that when he was jailed for corruption, his cell at La Sante
was just above the punishment blocks. ``My eyes stung regularly
from the tear gas thrown into isolation cells by guards,'' he said.
In another prison, he said, he had to ``paddle'' through ``blood
left by a prisoner who committed suicide after banging on his cell
door all night without getting help.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding last week to a mountain of inquiries, French
officials allowed journalists a rare look inside the walls of La
Sante, a penitentiary that has in its 133-year history housed such
famous prisoners as the poets Paul Verlaine and Guillaume
Apollinaire and, more recently, the convicted assassin known as
Carlos. Public guillotinings used to take place just outside its
gates. During World War II, Resistance fighters were executed
there.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials contend that Dr. Vasseur's book fails to take
into account the improvements that have been made in recent years,
including a fresh coat of paint and an increase in educational and
entertainment activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an element of generalization that gives a very wrong
impression,'' said Alain Jego, the warden of La Sante, before
offering a two-hour tour of the building. ``I'd be an idiot if I
said there was no violence, no rape. But the book gives the
impression it's 10 a day, and that is not so.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was built in the 1860s, La Sante was considered a model
of reform and humanity.
</P>
<P>
   But little has changed there since. Inmates, often grouped in
threes and fours, spend all but four hours a day in their cells,
which are usually about 30 feet square, with solid metal doors and
tiny peepholes. Even those with prison jobs like sorting pamphlets
or assembling gadgets often do the jobs in their cells. And what
goes on behind the doors is impossible to see.
</P>
<P>
   Among other horrors, Dr. Vasseur describes rapes, bizarre
self-mutilations, attempted suicides and the practice of turning
the weakest cellmates into slaves.
</P>
<P>
   When prisoners want something, they can activate lights outside
their cells. But during the tour, many lights were on, and it was
clear that responding to them was not a priority. At the moment,
the prison holds 1,236 inmates, only 36 more than it was built for.
But over the last seven years, the count has sometimes exceeded
1,800.
</P>
<P>
   In Cellblock C, which has yet to receive the new coat of paint
visible in other areas, inmates said they had been cleaning since
early in the morning in preparation for visitors. They said the
chicken being handed around for lunch that day was rare treat.
</P>
<P>
   In some cells, inmates had managed to cover their flaking walls
with posters, bits of magazines and even shopping bags. But they
said bug infestations and rodents were still common. At one point
during the tour, a mouse scuttled down a hallway undeterred by the
crowd of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates said that Dr. Vasseur's descriptions could not be
faulted: violence, disgusting food, overcrowding and beatings from
guards are all a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old prison,'' said one man, who had been arrested on
drug charges three months earlier and who shared a tiny cell with
two other inmates. ``We can't move in here. It is disgusting, but
nothing is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Another inmate said it was easy to get a pill for psychiatric
disorders. ``But if you need a dentist or you are in pain forget it
_ you wait a month.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jego said France spends about $20,000 a year per prisoner,
compared with $29,000 in New York state, for example.
</P>
<P>
   France is actually in the midst of trying to revamp its justice
system, which has been under attack on many fronts. One measure
meant to end political meddling in the appointment of judges died
recently when President Jacques Chirac could not get his party to
back it.
</P>
<P>
   But a bill meant to strengthen the presumption of innocence is
working its way through Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The new measures would shift the right to put a suspect in
custody from the investigating magistrate to an independent judge.
It would also allow preventive detention only for crimes carrying
at least a three-year prison term, instead of the current two. And
a defendant would have the right to see a lawyer from the moment of
detention, instead of after 20 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   In Dr. Vasseur, who wrote her book in diary form, described a
system filled with abuse. Some entries are pages long, others just
a few paragraphs. One day she discovers dozens of prisoners with a
skin disease related to eating the prison's rotting food. It is a
disease that most doctors had not seen in France since World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Another day she watches eight guards trying to hold down an
inmate, so they can give him a shot. He hurts several guards and is
thrown in the punishment block. Fifteen days later she finds him
severely dehydrated. She realizes the guards have shut off the
pipes delivering water to his cell.
</P>
<P>
   One guard systematically puts inmates with lung diseases in a
cell next to the laundry room, where the walls sweat from the
humidity, which aggravates their condition. There are empty cells
elsewhere, but he refuses to move them.
</P>
<P>
   Another guard forces prisoners working in the laundry to have
sex with him. But the prisoners are too terrified to testify
against him. A 21-year-old man is put in a cell with two older,
hardened criminals who rape him the first night. One of the older
men has AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Dr. Vasseur, who began her career working for
France's Social Security Administration, still works at La Sante,
though she is not sure that she will be able to continue to do so.
As a doctor, she does not report to the warden. But she said that
the atmosphere could become so poisoned that she would lose her
effectiveness. Still, she said, she has been amazed by the
outpouring of support she has received.
</P>
<P>
   Some guards signed a petition calling her a liar, but many, she
said, have applauded her courage. ``They say keep it up when I walk
by,'' she said. ``It has been very heartening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8649 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-HOWE-HNS &LR;      01-27 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOWE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
When Art Howe managed the Astros from 1989-93, he gained a
well-deserved reputation for his patience with young players.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Howe gets ready for his fifth season as manager of the
Oakland Athletics, the main strength cited again is his steady hand
with a developing team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, Howe is running out of patience. Not with his
players, of course, but after nine seasons as a manager, Howe wants
to shed the notion that he's merely someone who is adept with a
young team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough of this building stuff,'' said Howe. ``I want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be the breakthrough year for Howe and the Athletics.
After going 87-75 in 1999 and challenging Boston for the American
League wild-card berth down the stretch, Oakland is being mentioned
as a contender for the AL West title.
</P>
<P>
   Howe, who has made his home in Houston for more than 20 years,
dating to his time as an Astros player, will be honored tonight at
the R.B.I. Foundation's annual banquet at the Adams Mark Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Howe, Astros manager Larry Dierker and Astros pitcher Jose Lima
will be roasted and toasted as R.B.I.'s Sportsmen of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three seasons, Howe has guided the Athletics from 65
wins to 74 to 87. Oakland has one of the top farm systems in
baseball and in the last three seasons has put into the majors such
talented young stars as outfielder Ben Grieve, the 1998 AL Rookie
of the Year; third baseman Eric Chavez; and shortstop Miguel
Tejada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment to developing players is one of the keys for a
small-market team,'' said Howe. ``In my first three years, whatever
our (payroll) budget was, we always had to save $3 million for the
scouting department. We suffered a little on the major-league
level, but you can see it's paying off.''
</P>
<P>
   The big difference this year is that team owners Stephen Schott
and Ken Hoffman allowed general manager Billy Beane to increase the
payroll by $10 million, to about $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Beane re-signed potential free-agent
pitcher Omar Olivares, who was 7-2 for the Athletics after coming
from Anaheim in a deal July 29.
</P>
<P>
   With more money available, the Athletics were able to keep
potential free agents John Jaha and Randy Velarde and to re-sign
pitchers Kevin Appier, Doug Jones, Gil Heredia and T.J. Mathews.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround began last July, when the Athletics pulled off a
series of surprise moves by acquiring Appier from Kansas City,
Olivares and Velarde from Anaheim and pitcher Jason Isringhausen
from the New York Mets in a three-day period before the trade
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals came a week after the Athletics had traded pitcher
Kenny Rogers to the Mets. After that deal, it appeared Oakland was
selling out on the season, though the A's were still in the
wild-card hunt. Instead, the Rogers trade freed up enough money for
Beane to make the other acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For about four or five days, everyone was on our case,'' said
Howe. ``But that (Rogers) deal was more like a matter of getting
the stone out of your shoe. Once we made that deal, it freed up
some money to get players like Olivares and Velarde and Appier.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then this winter, we were able to keep them all. I think
they liked what they saw here last season, they liked the direction
the team was headed and how we run things. That was a nice
compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   For once, Howe will go to spring training without numerous
questions about his lineup and starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' he said. ``We've got a good club,
but we still don't have the finances other clubs have. Our depth
will be limited, but we're going to make it miserable for people.
And if things break right, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best club I've had here on paper going into the
season, hands down.''
</P>
<P>
   From a personal standpoint, Howe is rightfully proud the
Athletics decided to retain him beyond the rebuilding stage,
something that didn't happen in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1998 season, when the Athletics went 74-88, it
appeared Howe's job might be in jeopardy. First baseman Jason
Giambi, now an established four-year player, led a group of players
who went to Beane and strongly recommended the Athletics keep Howe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason and a few others went upstairs and spoke on my behalf,''
said Howe. ``I didn't ask them to, of course, but it meant a lot to
me. I think the decision was made that continuity was going to be
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe was given a one-year contract for 1999 with an option for
the 2000 season. The Athletics picked up that option midway through
last season; Howe currently is negotiating a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   Beane also mentioned the continuity factor when asked about Howe
this week. Beane, too, brought up the patience and steady hand his
manager has demonstrated with teams that had no chance to contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of this situation is that when Art started here,
there wasn't much of anything in the way of talent either in the
farm system or on the major-league team,'' said Beane. ``Patience
is one of his greatest virtues. Through that patience, he's been
here as we've developed a good major-league team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've brought along a lot of good young players and signed
some selective free agents that have helped. Art got here on the
ground floor, and he's been a big part of it. Right now, we've got
some continuity in terms of guys like Giambi and (Matt) Stairs, and
we're adding to our talent base both from within the system and
from outside.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, Howe might be able to lead the Athletics into
the postseason for the first time since the late 1980s and early
1990s when Tony La Russa was the manager and Mark McGwire, Dave
Stewart, Dennis Eckersley, Rickey Henderson and Jose Canseco were
among the best players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Howe is due a trip to baseball's October. He was fired
by the Astros after the 1993 season despite an 85-77 record. Howe
was instrumental in the development of players such as Jeff
Bagwell, Craig Biggio, Darryl Kile and Luis Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Drayton McLane Jr., however, decided after one season of owning
the club that he needed ``a more dynamic leader.'' He fired Howe
and hired Terry Collins, who failed to deliver a championship team
in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, who is more like Howe than Collins in the way he treats
players, got the Astros into the playoffs in 1997, starting a
three-year run of National League Central titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that team in Houston was going to win some titles,''
said Howe. ``Every year, you could see the improvement. We went
from something like 65 wins to 85 wins in three years (1991-93), so
it was obvious the talent was there, that something good was going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   While Howe takes satisfaction in seeing his ex-players succeed,
he listens to the sports talk shows in Houston and is appalled by
fans who deride the players for their lack of production in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the makeup of those players, and I know how much they
want to win, and it makes me sick to my stomach to hear people
criticize those players,'' said Howe. ``These guys are winners.
Bagwell and Biggio are two of the best in the game. They're giving
their all to win, and to hear people say they're choking, that
sticks in my craw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: There are 29 other teams that would be
happy to take those guys right now if the people here are tired of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe had those players during their formative years, much as he
now has Grieve, Tejada and Chavez in Oakland. He is quick to point
out, however, that McGwire has said several times that among the
happiest times he spent in baseball was the 1996 season and half of
1997 in Oakland, when Howe was manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can manage the veterans as well as the young guys,'' said
Howe. ``It's really just a matter of never having that many
veterans. I think one of the key things with any player _ young or
old _ is giving them their space. The clubhouse is their domain; I
don't bother them too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I'm behind them 100 percent, and my coaches are that
way, too. We're a team. We're going to make mistakes, they're going
to make mistakes, but we're all going to work on improving and
getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more improvement by the Athletics, and Howe's legendary
patience won't be as much of a story this season.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
