<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULLIGAN-DAMAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ALLOWS LAWSUIT BASED ON GOLFER INJURED BY WAYWARD
`MULLIGAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you try sneaking in an extra shot on the golf
course, be aware that if you shank your ball into somebody, you
will likely be held liable for any injuries, at least in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court in the Garden State has ruled that a golfer can
be held responsible for injuries caused by an unannounced shot if
other players are not given ample warning.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even bellowing ``Fore!'' when you hit what is
known as a mulligan _ a supplementary shot usually from the tee
that magically leaves no trace on the scorecard _ would not
automatically spare you from the courts if your ball goes amok.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in Newark Monday by the Appellate Division of the
Superior Court of New Jersey stems from a July 27, 1994 incident.
(There is an argument of course, whether the shot was actually a
mulligan.)
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Jeffrey Schick and his father,
Wolfgang, of Livingston, N.J., where the family runs a factory that
makes airplane parts, were playing on the public course. As is
often the case on crowded public courses, on the 10th hole they
spontaneously joined Tom Gonella and John Ferolito, a founder of
the company that makes Arizona Iced Tea.
</P>
<P>
   The somewhat inexperienced foursome _ all said they had been
playing for a year or less _ golfed together without problems until
the 16th tee.
</P>
<P>
   There, Schick, and his father hit their balls, followed by
Gonella. Those three then stood behind Ferolito while they claim he
sliced his ball into the woods on the right of the course. At that
point, the court papers say, the two Schick men moved their golf
cart about 10 to 16 feet in front of the tee, about 45 degrees off
to the left.
</P>
<P>
   They say at that point Ferolito took a mulligan, but the heel of
the golf club hit the ball and it hooked left, hitting Schick
between the eyes. A plastic surgeon reconstructed his nose and some
of his facial bones. Chisholm said his client, now almost 30, faces
over $30,000 in medical bills and suffers from repeated nightmares
about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Ferolito, 49, denies that his shot was a
mulligan. (The term comes from the name of a Canadian hotelier,
David Mulligan, who apparently started the practice of extra,
uncounted shots.)
</P>
<P>
   `` Mr. Ferolito told the people that he was about to take his
tee shot and gave them a waving gesture like here I go, but this
was not a mulligan,'' said James M. DeMarzo, the lawyer for the ice
tea magnate who whacked the errant ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it is a bad day for duffers, but I do think
it is a bad decision for duffers,'' said DeMarzo. ``Whenever you
take to a playing field, whether it is a baseball field or a
football field or the golf links, you are subject to certain risks
inherent to the sport itself,'' he said. ``We don't want to have
the door open to litigation every time someone gets hit on the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   But Richard M. Chisholm, the lawyer for the man hit by a golf
ball on the East Orange Golf Course, a public course in Millburn,
N.J., disagrees that the case will have such a far reach. He thinks
only demonic individual playing style might lead to damage cases,
not randomly crowning someone on the next fairway with an wayward
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anticipating that someone is going to hit a mulligan at
point-blank range is not a standard part of the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers involved said that since sports injury cases are
generally decided under state law, it is impossible to assess what
impact the case might have on golfers across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But to take at least one infamous golfer who has been know to
take his fair share (at least on a presidential scale) of
mulligans, there was no sense that the ruling will affect President
Clinton's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``His use of mulligans has been exaggerated in the press, but he
certainly reserves the right to use one from time to time,'' said
Jake Siewert, a White House spokesman. ``The president is pretty
vocal, so when he makes a bad shot he usually lets people know. I
don't think he would surprise everyone if he decided to take
another shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Ferolito, 49, denies that his shot was a
mulligan. (The term comes from the name of a Canadian hotelier,
David Mulligan, who apparently started the practice of extra,
uncounted shots.)
</P>
<P>
   `` Mr. Ferolito told the people that he was about to take his
tee shot and gave them a waving gesture like here I go, but this
was not a mulligan,'' said DeMarzo.
</P>
<P>
   Judge F. Michael Caruso of the Superior Court of New Jersey in
Essex County had thrown out the case in a 1998 summary judgment on
the grounds that the accident was part of the game. The higher
court reversed that decision, but ruled that the shot was not so
wantonly reckless that Schick could sue for punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear at this point whether the defendant will get the
New Jersey Supreme Court to review the decision or whether the
lawsuit will proceed in the lower court.
</P>
<P>
   Both lawyers said there are plenty of legal precedents when it
comes to sports injuries, although not for golf which in its ideal
form doesn't involve contact. The usual standard for lawsuits has
been that players involved assume a certain amount of risk, unless
the others in the game seem deliberately and recklessly trying to
wound them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly everyone feels bad whenever anyone gets hurt,''
DeMarzo said, before adding a quote from an unidentified sports
writer, ``But if you knew where the ball was going to go every time
you hit it, it wouldn't be much of a sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
