<HEADLINE>
SURPRISE SNOWSTORM STOPS N.C. IN ITS TRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 New York Times Regional Newspapers 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ A return to normalcy seemed to take forever
after Hurricane Floyd flooded this state four months ago, and it's
beginning to feel that way again.
</P>
<P>
   Most state offices and schools here in North Carolina's capital
and the surrounding area were closed for a third day Thursday
because of a snowstorm that had taken just about everybody by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The snow, which began falling late Monday and continued into
Tuesday afternoon, left an accumulation of 20 inches, a Raleigh
record for any 24-hour period. And an additional accumulation, of
ice or snow, is expected from a storm due this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For some students, this was the sixth school day called off by
snow in the last two weeks, a stretch of cancellations that has
forced districts to consider holding classes on Saturdays and on
Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   Power had been restored by Thursday to most of the 150,000
people who lost service in the Raleigh area. But it had been slow
going, and more than 300 people spent the night in one or another
of 15 emergency shelters that the state opened in the city or
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Raleigh-Durham International Airport resumed service late
Thursday after being closed for 60 hours, but only a few flights
were available: American Airlines, Delta, Northwest and US Airways
all chose to wait until Friday morning before resuming service.
</P>
<P>
   It was first prolonged shutdown in the airport's 61-year
history, and it snarled travel plans for thousands of people who
had been ready to fly on the 900 daily flights into and out of the
Raleigh-Durham area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been incredible,'' said an airport spokesman, Mike
Blanton. ``We removed over 20 inches of snow from a 10,000-foot
runway, and then we found a 3-inch layer of ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Two snowstorms hit the Raleigh area a week ago, but unlike
those, Blanton said, this one found the airport unprepared. State
troopers were also surprised, and many became stuck in the snow
early on. And the state Transportation Department quickly ran out
of salt and lost valuable road-clearing time waiting for more.
Remarkably enough, only one storm-related fatality was reported, in
a traffic accident about 20 miles south of Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters had predicted a light snowfall, and those who were
caught off guard responded angrily. ``The weather reporting on this
storm was an abysmal failure,'' said Gov. James B. Hunt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   As with Hurricane Floyd, Hunt has spent most of the week urging
people to stay home, unless they are checking on elderly neighbors
or using their four-wheel-drive vehicles to assist hospitals.
Medical centers issued desperate pleas for vehicles, to reach
either staff members or patients needing treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Raleigh area was hit hardest, other locales around
the state also struggled. Several inches fell in Charlotte, far to
the west, where Union County lost power to its water plant and had
to request bottled water from state emergency officials.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors at the area's hotels were stranded by the snow, but not
all of them lamented it. At the Sheraton Imperial in Research
Triangle Park, guests held an impromptu dance in one of the
ballrooms. And at the Radisson Governors Inn in Durham, Gelinda
Sorrell, assistant manager, said: ``We're just having fun with it.
The guests are so bored they've even filled out our comment
cards.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With snow forcing the cancellation of just about everything,
Elaine Marshall, North Carolina's secretary of state, was not
surprised that she had to postpone both the filing of her
re-election papers on Tuesday and a political fund-raiser that
evening.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, an undeterred Ms. Marshall showed up to file at
the state elections office and was greeted by the sole employee
there. Ms. Marshall had considered a further delay, but thought the
three-block walk from her office through the snow might be a good
way to start her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a group of hale, hardy farm folks,'' she said.
``Who am I to wimp out?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
