u i BC-GERMANY-HOLOCAUST-NYT     01-27 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANS DEDICATE HOLOCAUST MEMORIAL SITE IN BERLIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Germany on Thursday ended a decade of turbulent debate
over how to commemorate the Holocaust in its new capital by
formally dedicating a site beside the Brandenburg Gate for a
memorial designed by a New York architect.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the German government stood in icy winds beneath newly
unveiled billboards announcing the ``Memorial to the Murdered Jews
of Europe'' as Wolfgang Thierse, the president of the lower house
of Parliament, explained that honor had to be accorded to the 6
million Jewish dead ``in the heart of our capital city.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the project, designed by Peter Eisenman, will
begin next year on the 4.9-acre site. A field of over 2,000 stone
pillars of varying dimensions will be flanked by a ``documentation
center'' whose precise role remains unclear. Resistant to the last,
Eberhard Diepgen, Berlin's Christian Democratic mayor, snubbed the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Diepgen has been a leader of the large, often silent, body of
German opinion that believes the memorial is too big, too central
and perhaps redundant in a city that commemorates the Jewish dead
in many other smaller ways and in a country that thirsts to look
forward even as it is obliged to look back.
</P>
<P>
   His absence was a discordant note on the 55th anniversary of the
liberation of Auschwitz _ a day Germany has marked as ``Holocaust
Remembrance Day'' since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Germany chose to mark its formal remembrance of the Holocaust by
inviting Elie Wiesel, the author and Nobel Peace Laureate, to
address the lower house of Parliament. He brought an extraordinary
hush to the chamber in the refurbished Reichstag building with the
urgency of his memories and his pleas.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is one to comprehend the hate that flourished in this
country?'' asked Wiesel, a survivor of Auschwitz. ``If I were to
begin naming all the Jewish children who were killed _ 1.5 million
children _ I would be in this room for months and years.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiesel concluded his speech by urging Parliament to pass a
resolution formally requesting, in the name of Germany, the
forgiveness of the Jewish people for the crimes of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it publicly,'' he said. ``Ask the Jewish people to forgive
Germany for what the Third Reich had done in Germany's name. Do it,
and the significance of this day will acquire a higher level. Do
it, for we desperately want to have hope for this new century.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, at a private ceremony in Berlin marking an agreement
on compensation for victims of Nazi forced labor, Johannes Rau, the
German president, said, ``I pay tribute to all those who were
subjected to slave and forced labor under German rule and, in the
name of the German people, beg forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   While Germany has expressed remorse for Hitler's crimes in
countless forms since World War II _ perhaps most memorably in
Willy Brandt's unscripted genuflection at the Warsaw Ghetto _ its
president had not previously requested forgiveness in this way.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Wiesel asked Thursday that this remark by Rau at a
private ceremony be given the public resonance and gravity of a
parliamentary declaration. There was no immediate response _ only a
respectful silence.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the ceremony at the memorial site, Wiesel watched
Thierse explain that Germany had decided in the end to commemorate
the attempted annihilation of European Jewry in central Berlin
because modern German identity was inextricably tied to the
recognition of the horror of what Hitler perpetrated.
</P>
<P>
   It was a point that Wiesel had made in slightly different form
earlier as he explained the inextricable bond of Jews and Germans.
``No people,'' he said, ``ever inflicted such suffering as your
people on mine in such a short period. Until the end of time,
Auschwitz is part of your history and mine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
