<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8656 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BCS-ABC-DEAL-COX     01-27 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BCS-ABC-DEAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABC inks four-year extension with BCS
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans screaming for a Division I football playoff are going to
have to scream a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ABC announced Thursday a four-year extension to televise the
Bowl Championship Series through the 2005 season.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS features four bowls _ Sugar, Orange, Rose, Fiesta _ that
rotate as host for the designated national championship game. Last
season's game between Florida State and Virginia Tech was held in
the Sugar Bowl. Next season's game will be in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the BCS want college football to adopt a 16-team
playoff. But the six major conferences guaranteed slots in the BCS
_ ACC, Big East, Big Ten, Big 12, Pac-10, SEC _ have found the BCS
format better to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   TV ratings for the four BCS games were up 4 percent this season
and 9 percent over the past two years, BCS chairman and SEC
commissioner Roy Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Sugar Bowl) did a rating of 17.5 compared to a 17.2 for
the (basketball) Final Four last spring,'' Kramer said. ``We were
very pleased with that and felt it was time to move forward with
ABC.''
</P>
<P>
   The conferences recently signed off on a three-year option to
extend the contract. ABC added another year so that all four bowls
would host the championship twice during the contract. The Fiesta
and Sugar have hosted once.
</P>
<P>
   The extension also will bring more dollars to the BCS schools.
Under the old agreement, ABC paid approximately $78 million per
year to televise the four games. The new agreement raises that
figure to about $100 million. The per-team payout of those four
bowls is expected to jump from $12.5 million to more than $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   The contract goes through the 2005 season. The Rose Bowl
contract, with the Pac-10 and Big Ten champions, also is set to
expire after that season. Only then could football contemplate some
kind of postseason playoffs, according to several athletics
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement ``solidifies postseason football at the Division I
level until 2006, at which time we can evaluate where we are and
either continue in the current format or go in a different
direction,'' ACC commissioner John Swofford said. ``I think it's
fair to say the BCS has been very successful the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Critics of the BCS say that focusing all
the attention on one championship bowl detracts from, and lowers
attendance at, the other bowls. They also say that a playoff would
generate more overall money than the current bowl system, which
returns about $150 million a year back to the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ISL, a Swiss-based marketing firm, continues to peddle to
college administrators a playoff proposal, but a majority of the
university presidents have been against it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-COLD28-COX     01-27 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-COLD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL: Cold won't cost Atlanta
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue and a few league
owners said Thursday that this week's frigid weather should not
damage Atlanta's efforts at hosting future Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always understood that Atlanta was part-Southern,
part-Northern,'' Tagliabue said. ``The key thing is having a great
stadium and a domed stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Titans and Rams have complained about practicing
outside in near-freezing temperatures the past two days. The teams
will move inside the Georgia Dome for today's practice and have
one-hour, walk-through sessions on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa, New Orleans and San Diego have been awarded the next
three Super Bowls, respectively. Houston, with a new franchise
beginning play in 2002, is the favorite to host the game in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which also hosted Super Bowl XXVIII in 1994, is bidding
for the 2005 game. Jacksonville, Miami and Tampa also could compete
for the game when the NFL's 32 owners vote in March on the 2004-06
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Three NFL owners contacted on Thursday said this week's bad
weather would not affect their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a nor'easter, as they like to call it, or when
you get cold weather coming up into the east, it's cold
everywhere,'' Steelers owner Daniel M. Rooney said. ``I've got two
brothers living in Florida and they say it's cold down there,
comparably.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to do? Start playing the game in the
Caribbean and Hawaii? I think we should continue moving the game.
... I think Atlanta is fine. I spoke for Atlanta to get it when
they were awarded (this year's) game. It's just one of those things
where it's cold everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Bengals owner Mike Brown and Colts owner Jim Irsay agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be playing indoors, so I don't know why the
teams would be concerned,'' Brown said. ``The kind of weather you
get is going to impact what people are going to do when they get
there, like playing golf. But I don't think it's going to affect
the parties and the game, which is what it's supposed to be
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Steeg, the NFL's senior vice president for special events,
said no Super Bowl-related activities were canceled through
Thursday. A golf tournament in Alpharetta went off fine Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that can happen,'' Irsay said. ``We can't
control the weather. We knew when we came to Atlanta something can
happen. When you go to Tampa and Miami, you can have a lot of rain,
and New Orleans doesn't always have the best weather.''
</P>
<P>
   But Titans owner Bud Adams, whose team is playing its first
Super Bowl in the 40-year history of the franchise, says the league
needs to look closer at its criteria for hosting the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, these are all things the NFL must take under
consideration,'' Adams said. ``I don't think you normally have this
kind of bad weather (in Atlanta), but I think you may have to weigh
this strongly. ... It's a big factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Another big factor in Atlanta getting the Super Bowl twice was
late Falcons founder Rankin Smith Sr. He was instrumental in
bringing the game here in 1994, two years after the Dome opened.
Many league owners voted for it as a tribute of sorts to the man
who brought the NFL to the South in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, before his death in 1997, Smith was invaluable in
winning the 2000 game for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the weather probably won't hurt Atlanta, but it
might thwart bids by other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have some impact on some Northern cities that
wanted to hold the game in open-air stadiums,'' he said. ``This
shows that winter is still winter in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
