r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-CRYGAME-COX     01-27 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-CRYGAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shed no tears for Dick Vermeil
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The forecast calls for 4 inches of snow today ... or
10 inches if Dick Vermeil starts crying.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the NFL's most famous tear ducts are backed up. Vermeil
didn't shed a single drop after the Rams pulled out a victory in
the NFC title game last weekend. And he has made it through every
media session this week without even a moist eye. So you know what
that means ...
</P>
<P>
   If the Rams win Sunday, the Georgia Dome could look like the set
of Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to say Vermeil sheds a lot of tears, but if you
locked him in a room with Barbara Walters, you would have to keep a
lifeguard stationed nearby just to make sure nobody drowned in the
undertow.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when a water main broke and flooded the Trans World
Dome a few years ago? Well, that was the ``official'' story. My
sources say that Vermeil had just finished watching ``Old Yeller.''
</P>
<P>
   (OK, never mind that he wasn't the team's coach yet. Work with
me here).
</P>
<P>
   Somehow it seems fitting that at games in St. Louis, Rams' fans
wave hankies.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil makes Jana Novotna seem icy.
</P>
<P>
   He makes Sally Field look stoic.
</P>
<P>
   And I love it.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago that NFL coaches fell into two molds.
Tom Landry or Vince Lombardi. Statue or Screamer.
</P>
<P>
   And you pulled for the statue, because when a screamer
succeeded, the ripple effects were scary. Suddenly, youth coaches
across America decided that they needed to be like Mike Ditka or
Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   This season gives us hope. Look at the NFL's final four. Throw
out Jacksonville's Tom Coughlin and you have a group of head
coaches _ Tampa Bay's Tony Dungy, Tennessee's Jeff Fisher and
Vermeil _ that actually illustrated that you can mix traditional
staples, like discipline and hard work, with once-rare NFL traits.
Like sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of the Titans can picture their coach getting
weepy. Not even if they win Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' linebacker Barron Wortham said Thursday. ``Jeff's
more an IBM type. He's one of the guys that's on time every day.
Briefcase. Very conservative. That's just his style. He's not
wishy-washy like Dick Vermeil.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about wishy. But washy, yes. To recap this soggy
season, he cried when starting quarterback Trent Green got hurt. He
cried when Green was declared out for the season. He cried when the
Rams won their first game with Kurt Warner was quarterback. He
cried at San Francisco. He cried a season-high five times _ once in
the locker room and four times in the press conference _ when the
Rams clinched the divisional title at Carolina. He cried when
Warner won the MVP. He cried when his players were voted to the Pro
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just me,'' Vermeil explained earlier this week. ``It's
embarrassing sometimes. ... I can't help myself sometimes. I have
prepared myself emotionally mentally not to do it, and I still do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil's players have become accustomed to the tears through
the years. Herman Edwards, who played for Vermeil in Philadelphia,
recalls that on Saturdays the defensive linemen would have a little
pool _ the prize was pie a la mode _ on how long it would take for
Vermeil to break down. The typical over-under was 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And although Vermeil was out of the game for 14 years, some
things haven't changed. Rams linebacker Mike Jones laughs when
asked if he remembers the first time he saw Vermeil get choked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I was here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones recalls that after finishing signing his contract, Vermeil
got up from behind the desk and walked around to greet him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, 'He's not going to hug me, is he?''' Jones said.
``Sure, enough he hugs me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Jones wasn't sure what to make of Vermeil. With
time, though, he has grown to appreciate him. He says those who
think he is fake have it all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's genuine,'' he said. ``That's why it works, because he's
just being himself. He's sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a special year for Vermeil. It began with
win-or-else threats from management. And when Green went down, it
looked like it would be the or-else. But the Rams went 13-3 in the
regular season, and Vermeil was named Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is talk that if the Rams win Sunday, he will call it
quits. There's no way you can top a season like this. So why not
walk away and do something more sane? Relax, maybe do a few
commercials. (''Hi, I'm Dick Vermeil and I use No More Tears'
shampoo'').
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this could be his going-away party.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, he'll cry if he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
