<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-HORAN-COX     01-27 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-HORAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horan keeps Columbine in his thoughts
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He can see the high school from his front porch.
</P>
<P>
   The high school he drives past almost every day when he's home
and on the way to the gym for a workout or on the way to his
off-season job as a mortgage company's loan officer or on the way
to almost anywhere doing almost any errand.
</P>
<P>
   His three children of grade-school age probably will never
attend the high school St. Louis Rams punter Mike Horan sees every
day from the family's front porch, because it's located across a
county line and therefore not in the assigned district for their
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't change things.
</P>
<P>
   That won't ever change things.
</P>
<P>
   That won't ever change how Horan thinks about that day last
April, or why he thinks about it.
</P>
<P>
   That horrible day is the reason Horan _ during a Thursday
morning media session in advance of his team's Sunday date in Super
Bowl XXXIV _ was wearing a white baseball cap with a high school's
name stitched across the front.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBINE
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to bring a sense of pride and enjoyment to anyone
at Columbine who might see me,'' Horan said. ``I just want them to
know somebody's thinking of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Horan was working at a buddy's mortage company on April 20,
1999, when the news spread across Littleton, Colo., and then across
the country and globe that there had been a shooting at Columbine
High School. He wasn't worried for his own children's safety _ no,
it wasn't that _ but he raced to them anyway to where they were
locked down in their own classrooms and hallways until word came
that the rampage was only at one place.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve students and a teacher. Shot. Dead. And then the two
murderers killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go through that without feeling violated in some
manner,'' Horan said.
</P>
<P>
   His message was that the devastation, though obviously deepest
at Columbine, melted through the community. One of his own
children, in fact, chose not to return to her school when given the
option to stay home when classes resumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you tell them?'' Horan said. ``You tell them you love
them and want always to be part of their lives and know what
they're doing. And you want them to be able to tell you things.
Parents need to be more invovled in their kids' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   How could the parents of the perpetrators of the massacre not
have known is what Horan was thinking but not exactly saying.
</P>
<P>
   Horan's connection to Columbine _ beyond the view from his front
porch, that is _ was that he had been working with Rebels punter
Doug Brace in informal practice sessions. Someone who knew Horan,
who once punted for the Denver Broncos, had arranged the contact.
</P>
<P>
   Horan's involvement at the school these days has to do with
raising money for a project to demolish the library where the
shootings occurred and erect in its place a two-story atrium
opening to the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   He is 40 years old now, Horan is, and will be 41two days after
he plays in his fourth Super Bowl (he's winless in three previous
appearances with Denver and the New York Giants). His football life
has taken many turns to failure and resurrection, and one of the
things that bothers him most in quiet moments months removed from
the Columbine tragedy is that so many young people died before ever
getting real chances at recovery from disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Those kids, he mourns, will miss out on so much of what the
Columbine atrium project is named for and hopes to symbolize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope,'' Horan said.
</P>
<P>
   He should know.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time long ago in 1982, Horan was drafted in the
ninth round by the Atlanta Falcons. He was released, signed the
next year with Green Bay and failed a physical. He went to camp in
Buffalo, but was released. He punted for Philadelphia for a couple
of years, latched on in Denver late in 1986 and stayed with the
Broncos until injurying a knee in 1992. He went to the Giants the
next year and stayed through 1996. He was with the Rams after they
cut a punter in 1997 and with the Bears in '98 when a punter got
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   He signed with St. Louis again this season on Nov. 10, 1999,
when punter Rick Tuten was placed on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   How's all that for hope?
</P>
<P>
   How's all that for a circuitous route back to another Super
Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, a victory, finally, would be memorable for
Horan. But he might not appreciate it any more than he appreciated
a football title earned elsewhere last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on the road in Charlotte when I called home and found
out Columbine had beaten Cherry Creek for the state championship,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to get lost in the Roman numeral madness and excess of
these pro football extravaganzas.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, a guy with a baseball cap, a front porch and
hope has himself a pretty good map.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
