<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFCNEWS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thigpen holds out hope
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yancey Thigpen can accept a broken foot but not a
broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   He still hopes to lineup as a wide receiver for the Titans in
the Super Bowl despite fracturing the fifth metatarsal in his right
foot in the AFC Championship Game victory against the Jacksonville
Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the biggest game of my life, and, if I can't
play, it's going to be the biggest letdown of my career,'' Thigpen
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Super Bowl XXX with the Pittsburgh Steelers in 1996
and has yearned for another chance since that 27-17 loss to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The decision about playing Thigpen, still listed as the starter,
could be made as late as Sunday afternoon, when Titans coaches and
trainers run him through his paces. They are in no rush to decide
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel like I can play, I'll tell them,'' said Thigpen, who
also is valued as a team leader. ``And I think, by me telling them
that I feel like I can play, they will let me play because they
trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's any uncertainty, he said, he probably will sit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that will be the best decision for the team,'' said
Thigpen, who has spent two of his eight pro years in Nashville.
``I'm here to win a Super Bowl, not just to play in one.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Jack Youngblood of the Los Angeles Rams once
played in an NFC Championship Game with a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen said he hopes adrenaline will block any pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yancey wants to play in the worst way, and we've all got our
fingers crossed for him, hoping that he can,'' wide receivers coach
Steve Walters said. ``The fact of the matter is, can you perform?
Right now, we just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen said the swelling has subsided. He's wearing a walking
cast, and his shoe will be fitted with a plate to take pressure off
the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for me to play and be productive, I gotta have my
wheels,'' Thigpen said.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he missed six games because of a hamstring injury
and an ankle sprain so severe that it tore the cartilage. On a team
that throws sparingly, he still tied for the lead in touchdown
receptions and was second in receiving yards. In one quarter
Sunday, he caught two passes for 16 yards, one a 9-yard touchdown
reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, a lot of guys wouldn't even have been playing with
that (ankle injury),'' Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   If Thigpen can't play, Isaac Byrd will step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing the biggest game of the year,'' Byrd said,
``you're going to have to be put in a wheelchair not to want to go
out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said Thigpen might play a limited role, such as coming in
on third downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can give us anything, it's going to give a boost to the
team,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't play, Thigpen won't suit up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need all the bodies we can get,'' he said, ``and me
standing on the sideline in a uniform is not going to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
