<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-KEMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEMP ENDORSES BUSH, AND FORBES CALLS IT `POLITICS AS USUAL' 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ The Bush campaign Thursday unveiled its
latest prominent supporter, Jack Kemp, the 1996 Republican
vice-presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp's endorsement, announced at a news conference in Nashua,
underscored the degree to which members of the Republican
establishment, no matter what their divergent views, have coalesced
around Bush in the party's desire to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It was also an embarrassment for Bush's rival Steve Forbes, who
had won Kemp's endorsement in the 1996 primary campaign before Bob
Dole picked Kemp to be his running mate. Kemp had been one of the
early advocates of the flat income tax, which is central to the
Forbes campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was not endorsing Forbes this year, Kemp said
Thursday: ``I did briefly support Steve Forbes in 1996. He is a
friend. He is an outstanding human being. He has terrific ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here against John McCain,'' Kemp continued. ``I'm
certainly not here against Steve Forbes, a dear friend, who I think
would make a great secretary of the treasury,'' and he added, with
tongue firmly in cheek, ``and I'd make a great chairman of the
Fed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, humorously suggesting an ambassadorship, interjected,
``Have you ever heard of Chad?''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign had been passing out copies of a book
written by Kemp and Forbes' national campaign manager, Kenneth
Blackwell, at campaign stops. And one of Forbes' top strategists,
William Dal Col, is a longtime Kemp associate, having worked for
Kemp both at the Department of Housing and Urban Development and at
Kemp's private organization, Empower America.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their past ties, Forbes said Kemp's endorsement Thursday
was an example of ``politics as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack is a nice fellow,'' Forbes said at a news conference at
the Puritan Back Room Restaurant here. ``And we worked together.
But he is part of the party establishment. So it is no surprise
that they are rallying around their own. It shows that we are
mounting a real challenge to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he's endorsed the principle of the flat tax, why does he
go with the weak compromise?'' Forbes continued, referring to
Bush's tax cut plan. ``If you start watering things down, it will
lead to nothing at the end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In his endorsement Kemp said: ``I am not here suggesting that we
can pass a flat tax immediately. I really believe that Governor
Bush is the one who can inspire the Congress, inspire the nation
and win a mandate for bringing down the Clinton tax rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, referring to Republican defeats in the 1992 and 1996
presidential elections, said: ``What cost us was having a muffled
message, no clear agenda. With no message, there is no victory.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Forbes portrayed himself as the lone Republican
candidate with a strong message. ``I'm the only candidate with the
true pro-life, anti-tax message,'' he said. ``With an inspired
message, we will win. If not, we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Bush's message would lead to defeat in November,
Forbes replied: ``Clearly, that's the direction that he's headed.
You see he's putting out muffled messages on the tax code, the life
issue, on Social Security. It's tempting to say as little as
possible and hope that the poll lead stays and eke out a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who has run for no office other than the presidency, has
been at odds with the Republican Party establishment since he used
his considerable personal fortune in 1996 to run harsh
advertisements in the primary race attacking Dole. Party officials
believed that the advertisements damaged Dole in his general
campaign against President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
