<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFCPASS28-C     01-27 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFCPASS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Too short, too slow, also too valuable
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first time Titans defensive coordinator Gregg
Williams saw Blaine Bishop, he couldn't figure out why the team had
drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw him in drills, I couldn't believe we'd taken
him,'' Williams said. ``He couldn't backpedal, he was stiff and
couldn't turn his hips (and run).''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't anything Bishop hadn't heard before. A 5-foot-9,
203-pound safety, he always had been told that he was too small to
play football.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, 29, was a first-team all-state player at Cathedral High
School in Indianapolis. He dreamed of playing at Notre Dame or
Michigan, but his best offers came from Purdue and Indiana, which
said he could walk-on to their teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess everybody thought I was too small,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bishop accepted a scholarship from St. Joseph's
College, a Division II school in Rensselaer, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   After one season at St. Joseph's, Bishop walked-on at Ball
State, a Division I school in Muncie, Ind. He was selected an
honorable mention All-American as a senior, but he still fell to
the eighth round of the 1993 NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't even have an eighth round anymore,'' Bishop said.
``We have a lot of talented young players, and I tell those guys
that I'd be a free agent if I came out right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop was taken with the 214th pick in the draft by the former
Houston Oilers. He played in all 16 games as a rookie, mostly on
special teams but had two starts at strong safety in place of
injured Bubba McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop started 13 games the next season and has been in the
starting lineup since then. He was voted to three Pro Bowls in a
row, 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blaine's my all-time favorite guy that I've coached,'' said
Williams, who was the Oilers' special-teams coach when Bishop
entered the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone _ coaches, the media, everybody _ has told him that
he couldn't play at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, a seven-year pro, has excelled in the NFL. He averaged
103 tackles over the past five seasons, including 115 this season,
when he tied linebacker Eddie Robinson for the team lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop also is the field general in the Titans' secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blaine is a guy who is going to let you know how he feels,''
said free safety Anthony Dorsett, who will start Sunday in place of
injured Marcus Robertson. ``He's not a guy who's worried about your
feelings. If he doesn't think you're getting the job done, he will
let you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is doing his job in the postseason, tying for the team
lead with 23 tackles. Two weeks ago in the divisional playoffs, he
had a team-high 11 tackles in the Titans' 19-16 victory against the
Colts in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out (of college) as a cornerback and they said I wasn't
fast enough,'' Bishop said. ``They said I was too short to play
safety. They didn't realize I'm a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
