<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE PROFITS SINK 22% IN 4TH; SEES REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Again insisting that better days are just ahead,
Gillette Co. said Thursday fourth quarter profits fell 22 percent
to $339 million on sales of $3.03 billion, a 4 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-based maker of such products as Mach3 razor blades,
Duracell batteries, and Parker pens said it should see a sales gain
in ``the high single digits'' for the year 2000 and added that it
expects to meet earnings forecasts for the first and second quarter
as well as for the full year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our global business fundamentals in all core categories are
very strong, and our market shares are at record levels,'' said
Michael C. Hawley, Gillette's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter results were in line with reduced expectations.
In the fall, Gillette warned investors that results would be hurt
by a reduction in razor blade shipments.
</P>
<P>
   As retailers in Europe and South America consolidate and upgrade
their inventory systems, they are cutting back on the amount of
razor blades they stockpile, Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last decade, Gillette was a Wall Street darling,
but more recently, economic problems in key foreign markets,
unfavorable exchange rates, and disappointing results for the
company's stationery and some of its Braun small appliance lines
have been a drag on overall performance.
</P>
<P>
   Even before reports surfaced this week that Gillette had
rebuffed an acquisition overture from Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. _
something Gillette again declined to discuss Thursday _ Gillette
has been under pressure to unload its subpar product lines and
concentrate on the highly profitable businesses of making razor
blades and batteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Gillette, less equals more, and less would equal more
focus,'' said Fredric E. Russell of Fredric E. Russell Management
Co. in Tulsa, Okla., a Gillette shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Gillette said it would consider selling or
discontinuing product lines that failed to meet performance
targets, though it has hinted it plans to hang on to the Braun part
of its oral care business.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Gillette said it continued to vigorously pursue these
options but added it had nothing more to say at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement on the subject should come ``sooner than later''
this year, said Eric A. Kraus, Gillette's vice president of
corporate communications.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette announced its fourth-quarter results after the market
closed. Gillette shares rose 11/16 to close at 40 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-REACT-700&AMP;ADD     01-27 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REACT-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS ASSAIL PRESIDENT'S SPENDING PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-SPEECH; will be updated after State of Union, set for
9 p.m. EST) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on Thursday assailed the agenda
President Clinton outlined for his last year in office as
spendthrift, and heralded the GOP as the true steward of fiscal
responsibility, guardian of the elderly and champion of millions of
uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Clinton delivered his last State of the Union
address on Thursday evening, Republicans seized on details that
seeped out during the day to warn voters that Democrats could not
be trusted to oversee the nation's prosperity and the federal
budget surpluses that have accompanied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that if you listen carefully, what you'll hear is a
litany of spending,'' Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican
presidential front-runner, told a Chamber of Commerce breakfast in
Nashua, N.H. ``If the past is any judge of today, it is going to be
spending after spending after spending, which proves my point. If
there is money left in Washington, it is going to be spent.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois, expressing amazement
at a litany of proposed initiatives, from a $50 million plan to
clean up the Great Lakes to a $20 million proposal to fight
infectious diseases, said before the speech: ``If we enacted all
the new programs the president has talked about, we'd spend just
about the entire surplus on bigger and more expensive government.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's reaction from Republicans previewed the
year-long battle between the two parties over how best to use the
trillions of dollars in projected surpluses _ already a core theme
on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have vowed to protect Social Security and pay down
the $3.6 trillion national debt, but Democrats would use much of
the non-Social Security surplus to boost spending on domestic
programs, while Republicans are eager to plow much of that money
into tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   For the televised Republican response to Clinton, however, party
leaders picked Sens. Bill Frist of Tennessee and Susan Collins of
Maine, experts on health care and education, issues usually
associated with Democrats. The choice underscored Republicans'
desire to show a moderate face on two issues that have emerged as
immensely popular with voters.
</P>
<P>
   The two senators took dramatically different approaches. Collins
never even mentioned Clinton or the more than $3 billion in
education spending increases he proposed. She indirectly criticized
the administration for ``dictating to communities how they should
run their schools,'' advocating instead pushing more control over
education decisions to local communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans want what all parents want for their children's
schools: more federal help but less federal interference,'' Collins
said in remarks prepared for her response.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Frist, a physician, repeatedly attacked Clinton's
health-care proposals, including a $110 billion health-care package
over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time he proposed a health plan was seven years ago,''
Frist said in remarks prepared for his response, referring to the
ill-fated effort headed by Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``And then it
amounted to a federal government takeover of our entire health
system.''
</P>
<P>
   But Frist also edged closer to embracing a version of two
Democratic health-care proposals _ a patients' bill of rights that
allows patients to sue their health-care plan under certain
conditions, and expanding Medicare to include prescription drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep doctors first, lawyers second,'' Frist
said of the Republican plan to regulate health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers in tough re-election fights were quick to
embrace Clinton's education and health-care aims, while distancing
themselves from domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I am in agreement with many of his goals _ for example,
improving the quality of education for our children and creating
some kind of prescription drug benefit for America's seniors _
generally it is important that we restrict increases in spending,
lest we seriously slow our economic growth,'' said Sen. William V.
Roth Jr. of Delaware, who heads the Finance Committee and is facing
a bruising campaign this fall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Virtually absent from Thursday night's Republican reaction was
any mention of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, which dominated
discussion outside the chamber at the last two State of the Union
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   And while Republicans were not ready to give Clinton a hearty
send-off, some lawmakers held out a symbolic olive branch, partly
perhaps to avoid being labeled a ``do-nothing'' Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans, including Representative David Dreier of
California, cheered Clinton's support for bringing China into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' said Dreier, who heads the House Rules
Committee. ``Republicans will work in good faith with this
president and every Democrat in Congress who puts ideas ahead of
politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-LOGUE-BOS &LR;      01-27 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-LOGUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARD J. LOGUE, URBAN PLANNER WHO REMADE BOSTON, AT 78 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDGAR J. DRISCOLL JR.  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Edward J. Logue, an urban planner who remade the face
of Boston in the 1960s as director of the city's redevelopment
authority, died at his West Tisbury home Thursday. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Logue was recruited by the late Boston Mayor John F. Collins
to build on programs initiated in the Hynes administration of the
1950s and create a comprehensive development program for a ``New
Boston,'' and then make it happen. Which he did, with aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   What followed were Government Center, the Prudential Center, and
a revitalization of the waterfront region, an overhaul of key city
neighborhoods that gave Boston a new image, for itself and for the
wider world beyond its borders.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Walkway to the Sea'' _ the Faneuil Hall-Quincy Market
restoration _ was another project conceived, approved, and funded
under his aegis. It became one of the best-known and most-imitated
community development projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Other Logue-led projects included the razing of the elevated
portion of the `T' in Charlestown and the rebuilding of Washington
Park in Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   Of medium height and stocky of frame, Mr. Logue, who lived on
West Cedar Street, Beacon Hill, was a lightning rod for criticism
in his heyday, considered brash and confrontational by those who
opposed his plans. But in the larger framework of urban planning,
he was widely praised as a master strategist and builder whose
enduring vision helped give a proud old city a distinct and
attractive new vitality.
</P>
<P>
   His admirers cited his ability to recruit top-quality
professionals from many different disciplines and mold them into an
effective, productive team; his ability to relate sensitively to
the concerns of the community (``planning with people,'' he called
it); his role as one of the first public officials to stress
rehabilitation and adaptive re-use of old buildings; and his
administrative creativity in getting difficult projects done, or as
one observer put it: ``He was a master of the ins and outs of
everyday politics and was particularly successful in dealing with
agencies of the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Logue resigned his post with the Boston Redevelopment
Authority in 1967 to run for mayor, a bid that fell short. In
January 1968, he became one of the first research associates at the
Institute of Politics, founded two years before at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University. He also was
Maxwell Visiting Professor of Government at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Mr. Logue left Boston for New York to head
Nelson Rockefeller's newly formed New York State Urban Development
Corp. There he presided over the creation of 33,000 housing units
in the state, including 2,000 units of mixed-income housing on
Roosevelt Island in New York City's East River. He was president
and chief executive officer of the corporation from 1968 to 1975,
when the job ended in a cloud of criticism about financial
mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Then he formed his own company, Logue Development Company, Inc.,
a consultant firm, and took on the gargantuan task of rebuilding
New York's South Bronx, a project funded in part by the Department
of Housing and Urban Development. He was appointed director of the
South Bronx Development Office by New York Mayor Ed Koch in 1978,
and in 1981 became president of the organization. But the days of
massive infusions of federal money, which he had been so adept at
channeling to Boston, were over. And in 1985 the Bronx project was
disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Coyle, one of Mr. Logue's successors as head of the BRA,
recalled encountering him in 1983 on a field visit to the South
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was evolving,'' said Coyle, an admirer of his
predecessor's bold vision for Boston, ``was a reflective and
extraordinarily thoughtful man who was seeing first-hand the
failure of urban planning in the South Bronx. You had a sense of a
promethean figure doing penance _ the master builder surrounded by
urban decay, with the federal government abandoning him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Mr. Logue's accomplishments in Boston, Mr. Coyle said: He was
``the best of his generation. The replacement of old Scollay Square
with Government Center has to be placed at the top of the list of
plans that succeeded around the country. A different generation of
planners might have done it with more preservation in mind. But as
a stimulus for the economy, the Government Center plan worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyle also noted that Mr. Logue was often criticized for the
wholesale razing of the West End _ even though he had nothing to do
with it. That neighborhood was cleared for renewal before Mr. Logue
arrived in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Logue returned to Boston in 1985 as a lecturer at MIT's
School of Architecture and Planning. Then he became president of
Logue Boston, a firm he started with two longtime Boston friends,
the realtor John Ryan and the lawyer John Bok. Among the projects
they took on were the proposed relocation of Suffolk University to
two monumental state facilities, the Hurley Building and the
Lindemann Center in the Government Center area, and, in turn, the
development of Suffolk's seven Beacon Hill buildings into luxury
housing. Another project was the building of a 126-unit condominium
known as ``Savin Hill Green,'' in the Savin Hill section of
Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Logue was born in Philadelphia on February 7, 1921, the son
of Edward J. and Resina (Fay) Logue. He was a graduate of Yale
College in 1942 and Yale Law School in 1947. During World War II,
he served as an Air Force bombardier and was awarded the Air Medal
with clusters, eight Battle Stars, and a Presidential Unit Citation
for his service in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation from law school he was legal secretary to
Connecticut Governor Chester Bowles from 1949 to 1951 and later a
staff aide to the Senate majority in the 1951 session of
Connecticut's General Assembly. In 1952-53, he served as chief of
staff to Mr. Bowles when he was US Ambassador to India. On
returning to this country in 1954, he became development
administrator of the city of New Haven, where he worked until John
Collins called him to Boston in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Mr. Logue summered at Chilmark, Martha's
Vineyard, where he was active in conservation and rehabilitation
efforts. In 1971 he founded the Vineyard Open Land Foundation,
which he served as a longtime trustee. In addition he was a trustee
of the Institute for Architecture and Urban Design and Pratt
Institute, New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The author of numerous essays, articles and reports on housing,
planning, community development, government organization and
related matters, Mr. Logue also was a visiting professor at New
York University Law School, the University of Pennsylvania, the
University of Rhode Island, and the University of Cincinnati; and
visiting lecturer at Yale Law School, Princetown University, and
Cleveland State University.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Margaret (DeVane) Logue; a son, William
Devane Logue of West Hartford, Conn.; a daughter, Katherine of West
Tisbury; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
