<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-ART-775&AMP;ADD-N     01-27 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY'S NEW MESSAGE: GORE CAN'T BE TRUSTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT7 and NYT8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, N.H. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley was a candidate
transformed Thursday, stumping with renewed vigor across snowy New
Hampshire and planning to begin a sharp new attack against Vice
President Al Gore on one his most vulnerable areas, campaign
finance.
</P>
<P>
   At almost every stop Thursday, Bradley hammered at the theme he
unveiled at the final New Hampshire debate with Gore on Wednesday
night: that the vice president is a dishonest candidate who could
not be trusted to honor campaign pledges if elected. And in
comments to reporters, Bradley made clear that his performance on
Wednesday was a signal that he was coming out fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't care about the people enough to tell them the
truth in a campaign, then how are they going to trust that you're
going to care about them enough to fight for health care reform?''
Bradley told several dozen shivering supporters outside his
campaign headquarters in Concord Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Bradley said he would step up that attack on Friday,
when he was expected to criticize Gore's role in the aggressive
fund raising for the Clinton-Gore campaign of 1996. Gore made phone
calls from the White House to solicit contributions and appeared at
a fund-raiser at Buddhist Temple in Los Angeles during that
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley has chastised the administration's 1996
fund-raising tactics before, he had avoided attacking Gore on the
issue. But his advisers said Thursday that they expected Bradley to
take on Gore directly on Friday, at an event in which Bradley will
be endorsed by former Gov. Lowell Weicker of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's advisers described his new line of attack as part of a
carefully calculated strategy developed in the past two weeks. They
said it was born partly out of Bradley's anger with what he
perceived as Gore's unrelentingly distortions of his record and
positions. But it was also the result of their growing concern that
Bradley's support in New Hampshire was slipping away, and with it,
his chances of upsetting Gore for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley had decided to be more aggressive before the Iowa
caucuses on Monday, he waited until reaching New Hampshire to begin
because his advisers feared that it would not receive much
attention in Iowa, where Bradley was trailing badly in the polls.
He lost to Gore in the caucuses by 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Bradley himself acknowledged that the timing of his
new attack was carefully planned. Asked why he had waited so long
to criticize Gore's integrity, Bradley replied, ``I felt it had to
be made in the last week of the primary, so people would know.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, referring to Wednesday's debate, ``Last night was a
way of saying, enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In his meticulous way, Bradley avoided blasting Gore in the
hours just before the debate, even though a radio talk show host
had repeatedly offered him opportunities on Wednesday morning.
Bradley's aides said he wanted to hold fire until the nationally
televised debate, to ensure his remarks received the largest
possible audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign called Bradley's new remarks a sign of
desperation. ``After 12 months of above-it-all politics, he's
clearly started listening to his pollsters and consultants and
decided to wage a negative campaign,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's comments Wednesday night and Thursday seemed aimed not
just at winning over wavering voters, but also at bolstering his
core supporters, many of whom have been saying that they wanted
Bradley to show that he is willing to fight fiercely for a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he did it,'' said Patricia Lorio of New Hyde Park,
N.Y., 65, who showed up at Bradley's rally in Concord. ``If you're
just sweet and nice, you're not going to get their passions up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Taylor, 76, a supporter of Bradley's who shook his hand
in a parking lot in Exeter, said, ``I was glad to see he had a
little life.''
</P>
<P>
   But having tried to cast himself as a ``new kind of politician''
who abhors attack politics, Bradley runs the risk of appearing
inconsistent, or of alienating undecided voters, in slashing at
Gore now.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Laura Davies, a 37-year-old independent voter from
Exeter, said she was somewhat turned-off by Wednesday's contentious
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the confrontational stuff,'' she said after
shaking Bradley's hand in a grocery store. ``I want to hear what
they have to say on issues rather than their bickering.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Attacking Gore on campaign finance could also infuriate
Democratic primary voters, many of whom think that the Clinton-Gore
campaign's aggressive fund raising in 1996 was done in the good
cause of defeating conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   With an energy reminiscent of Bill Clinton during his underdog
New Hampshire campaign of 1992, Bradley made repeated impromptu
stops Thursday, bounding out of his bus to grab hands and chat up
voters.
</P>
<P>
   In a supermarket in Exeter, Bradley, trailed by hustling
photographers and television camera crews walked up and down
aisles, checking out produce and potential voters. In a bar in
Portsmouth, he shook hands with the beer-drinking college crowd.
</P>
<P>
   At an event with environmental activists on the shores of a
frozen bay, and later in a speech before more than 400 employees at
a Timberland shoe factory in Hampton, Bradley spiced his stump
speech with blasts at Gore's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you conduct a campaign is very important,'' he said at the
Timberland event. ``That's the point I tried to make last night at
the debate. After absorbing months of misleading statements and
misrepresentations, last night I threw him an elbow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
