<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-NFCFEATURE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Success won't make Rams' Timmerman forget his roots
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a year that the NFL's image has taken an
old-fashioned whipping, a heart-warming story comes from the
heartland.
</P>
<P>
   An Iowa farm boy has turned Super Bowl offensive lineman, three
times over. Because of notorious players like Rae Carruth and Cecil
Collins, the timing couldn't have been better.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Timmerman made two Super Bowl trips with the Packers and
he's back again. This time he's with the Rams, his favorite team as
a child, which fits with his version of the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Timmerman grew up on a 1,000-acre bean and corn farm in
northwest Iowa and played on a partial scholarship at Division II
South Dakota State. Only by some urging did he stick around for his
last season of eligibility, instead of returning to his family farm
with his degree in agricultural business. He was rewarded as the
top Division II lineman in the country.
</P>
<P>
   That got him a call from the Packers, seven rounds and 40
linemen into the 1995 draft. He played 17 games in his rookie
season and when left guard Aaron Taylor got hurt in a wild-card
game against the Falcons, and Timmerman hasn't come out of the
starting lineup since. The Rams signed him as a free agent last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   With his first signing bonus, which he estimated to be $15,000
after taxes, he bought farm equipment. With his second signing
bonus of $5 million, to go along with his $19 million package for
five years, he did more of the same. He traded in his tractor for a
better version and bought a new field cultivator. He still heads
back to Iowa on breaks and during the offseason, for little rest
and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't too many people within a square mile out there,
so you get some time to yourself,'' Timmerman said. ``For me, too,
it makes you realize how hard it is to make a buck out there.
Sometimes you lose track of that. In professional sports, you see
all these people making all this money. You get a game check, and
that's more than some people make all year. You kind of lose sight
of that, so for me to go back there and see that corn's a buck and
a half and beans are four bucks, it brings a lot of things back to
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   When football is over, this 29-year-old knows where he's headed
_ the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'd like to return,'' Timmerman said. ``My brother's
like, `What are you waiting for?' He's like, `You can't buy more
equipment. You've got to have a guy to go along with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Timmermans' neighbors will be watching over their farm this
weekend, while the family makes the trek to the Georgia Dome to
support the player they and the Rams know was a key to St. Louis'
turnaround from 4-12 to 15-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really liked him for his pass-protection ability, but we
really didn't know the guy,'' offensive line coach Jim Hanifan
said. ``As soon as he arrived, we knew we had something special.
... Adam is a very genuine individual.''
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-4, 300-pound lineman with the crew cut, he does have
some heartbreak in his story. Four months after his second trip to
the Super Bowl with the Packers in 1998, his father died from head
injuries suffered in an accident on an all-terrain vehicle on the
family's farm. Timmerman was home at the time, and it's a place he
goes back to, to draw strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to be there at first,'' Timmerman said. ``You're
out there, and you expect to see him pulling up with a fresh load
of beans to go plant. We were always out there working together,
that's what made it fun. You really miss him. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You start to look at things in life a little differently. You
stop complaining about things that don't matter. I have a son of my
own now, and there are some father-son things it would have been
nice to talk to him about. You value things, differently, family
and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   No mention of football. No need. After three trips to the Super
Bowl, Timmerman still talks as if he's never been far from the
farm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
