u k BC-EDITORIAL-SURPLUS-BOS     01-27 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SURPLUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEND IT WISELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Congessional Budget Office, well known for its caution on
fiscal matters, has predicted a federal budget surplus of as much
as $1.9 trillion over the next 10 years. The announcement has
heated up debate about how to use the surplus _ in tax cuts,
additional spending, or paying down the national debt. Before
euphoria sweeps through the political world, certain important
factors ought to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among these is uncertainty. The CBO estimates are based
on a number of reasonable assumptions about economic growth,
inflation, interest rates, world conditions, and so on. While the
assumptions may be reasonable, they cannot be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The number itself, though large, is well below the national debt
of $5.6 trillion. It is small compared with federal budgets over
the 10 years that will probably total around $20 trillion and gross
domestic product of more that $80 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts are politically attractive but should be targeted where
they will do the most good. Increases in personal exemptions
deserve high priority because they provide the greatest
proportional benefit to lower- and middle-income taxpayers and
because they have tended to lag behind inflation. Cutting basic
percentage rates locks the system into lower revenues that may be
politically difficult to recover in some future restructuring of
the overall system _ trading slightly higher income tax rates for
lower payroll tax rates, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Spending to stabilize Social Security or Medicare makes sense,
but starting costly new initiatives that cannot be sustained would
create more hardship in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the national debt helps by lowering federal interest
costs, allowing support for other programs. Perhaps more important,
it makes future deficit spending to stimulate the economy in
sluggish times more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   The choices are not simple, and politicians may treat them like
a buffet by sampling a bit from each dish. The most important
consideration is to avoid overeating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
