<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES FAR-REACHING PLAN ON DRUGS AND THE UNINSURED 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: With CLINTON-SPEECH; will be updated after State of Union.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Wednesday night proposed an
ambitious, multifaceted health care agenda, calling on Congress to
provide prescription drugs to the elderly, new government subsidies
to help people buy health insurance, new tax breaks for long-term
care and a new federal law to define the rights of people in health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address, Clinton touched on a
half-dozen other health care proposals, including his desire for a
new tax credit to reward pharmaceutical companies for developing
vaccines and drugs to treat AIDS, malaria, tuberculosis and other
diseases that afflict millions of people in the third world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also highlighted his request to spend more on mental
health care, as recommended by Tipper Gore, the wife of Vice
President Al Gore. And without giving details, Clinton stressed his
desire for government action to prevent medical errors that harm
tens of thousands of people a year.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said Clinton would ask Congress to dedicate nearly $400
billion of the expected budget surplus over the next decade to
shore up the finances of Medicare and to pay some of the cost of
new outpatient drug benefits under that program.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, the White House disclosed many of the
president's health care proposals. But Wednesday night, Clinton
discussed the package as a whole for the first time and wrapped it
together with a common theme.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare finances health care for 39 million people who are
elderly or disabled. When Clinton unveiled his pharmaceutical plan
in June, he said it would cost $118 billion over 10 years. But the
Congressional Budget Office said the cost would exceed $165
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that all Medicare beneficiaries should have access
to an affordable option for insurance coverage of prescription drug
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifesaving drugs are an indispensable part of modern
medicine,'' Clinton declared, in excerpts of the speech released
beforehand by the White House. ``No one creating a Medicare program
today would even consider excluding coverage for prescription
drugs. Yet more than three in five seniors now lack dependable drug
coverage, which can lengthen and enrich their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In good conscience, Clinton said, ``we cannot let another year
pass without extending to all seniors the lifeline of affordable
prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the guests invited by the White House to the congressional
session Wednesday night was Pat Brown of Johnson City, Tenn., a
retiree who spends $4,000 of her savings each year on prescription
drugs for heart and thyroid ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's health care proposals will set the tone this year for
campaign debates and will influence the agenda of Congress.
Republicans, while favoring different approaches, said Wednesday
night that they wanted to address many of the problems cataloged by
Clinton: the growing number of Americans without health insurance,
the frustrations of HMO patients and the desperation of elderly
people seeking affordable prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has already laid some groundwork for legislation on
these issues, and many of the president's proposals have some
election-year appeal to voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican response to Clinton's speech, Sen. Bill Frist
of Tennessee endorsed many of the president's goals, but said
Clinton's approach was too costly and heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Frist recalled Clinton's plan in his first year as president to
guarantee health insurance for all Americans, which Congress
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now tonight, 84 months later,'' Frist said, in the text of
remarks made available Wednesday afternoon, ``the president has
unveiled a similar plan just as bad as the first. It makes
government even bigger and more bloated because each new program we
heard about tonight _ and there were about 11 of them in health
care alone _ comes with its own massive bureaucracy. And each will
cost you, the taxpayer, billions more of your tax dollars, more
than $1,000 for every man, woman, and child.''
</P>
<P>
   One new item in Clinton's package was a proposal for a tax
credit to accelerate the development of vaccines for malaria,
tuberculosis and AIDS. Jennings said the tax credit would create an
incentive for the pharmaceutical industry to invest in development
of vaccines for poor countries, which often cannot afford to buy
the vaccines they need.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and the House passed different versions of
legislation defining patients' rights last year. But only the House
version, which would make it easier for patients to sue HMOs for
injuries, is acceptable to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Wednesday night that any legislation on
this issue must include ``an enforcement mechanism, to ensure
recourse for patients who have been harmed as a result of a health
plan's actions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
