<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-AIRFORCE-SUIT-NYT &LR;      01-27 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SUES TO HALT LOW-LEVEL TRAINING FLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A coalition of environmentalists, outdoorsmen and
rural landowners sued the Air Force Thursday, seeking suspension of
low-level training flights that they say have gravely disrupted
wildlife, livestock and recreation, especially in the wild deserts,
canyons and forests of the West.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court here, is the most
serious legal challenge so far to the Air Force's training program,
which has been beset by political and legal attacks around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   From cattle ranchers in Texas and American Indians in Idaho to
hikers in New Hampshire's White Mountains, complaints about fighter
jets and bombers roaring overhead have steadily increased in recent
years, forcing the Air Force to scramble to keep its training
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every Air Force proposal to find new places to train
or to expand the use of existing spaces has faced increasingly
vehement local opposition, but the coalition's challenge is the
first to try to suspend all low-level training.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition hopes to force the Air Force to complete a broad
environmental study of the impact of its training flights on
wildlife, as well as on tourism and other economic activities, in
areas under or near its training areas. While the Air Force has
conducted limited studies for individual areas, the lawsuit accuses
it of violating the National Environmental Policy Act by not
studying the cumulative effects of training flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence has been mounting for years that these flights
are not compatible with a lot of land uses,'' said Peter J. Galvin,
a biologist with the Center for Biological Diversity, a
conservation group in Tucson, Ariz., that is one of the plaintiffs
in the suit. ``And the Air Force has never studied the cumulative
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The case underscores the difficulties the Air Force and the
other services have had competing for the nation's increasingly
crowded airspace _ as well as for public lands for bombing runs and
firing other weapons _ as commercial airline traffic has increased
and areas that were once remote have become more populated.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges have intensified since the end of the Cold War.
Citing national security has proved less persuasive than it once
was when it comes to sonic disruptions caused by jets and other
military activity.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawsuit's prospects are not clear, a suspension of all
training is remote. But the lawsuit could force the service to
conduct the broad environmental impact study, which the coalition's
leaders said was their main objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least then, we would have a public process we can interact
in,'' Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force did not respond directly to the lawsuit, saying it
would not comment on pending litigation. But officials released a
statement saying that the service regularly analyzed the impact of
low-level flights and that a suspension is not warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistic training is essential for the United States Air
Force,'' the statement said. ``It provides the combat edge that
enables victory in battle and reduces American casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is not alone among the services in facing these
challenges, nor is the United States the only place where citizens
have taken issue with the noise _ and potential danger _ of such
training.
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rico, the Navy has become mired in a political dispute
over using the island of Vieques as a bombing range. In Germany,
public outrage over NATO training flights forced German pilots to
train at a range in New Mexico, prompting new legal challenges from
residents there.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force began a broad study of the environmental impact of
low-level flights in 1988, but abandoned it and never made the
results public, Galvin said. An internal Air Force memo, obtained
by the coalition under the Freedom of Information Act, concluded
that the study's preliminary finding ``does not put the Air Force
in a favorable light.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force pilots fly roughly 2 million hours a year around the
world. In the United States, aviation regulations restrict military
aircraft flying faster than 250 miles an hour to proscribed routes
and operating areas, forcing them to stay away from cities, for
example. Some of those areas are set aside exclusively for military
use, but in most, military aircraft mix with commercial airliners,
though at different altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force defines ``low level'' as below 500 feet, and
officials said that only 5 percent of its training flights dip
below that. But the coalition is seeking to suspend training
flights below 2,000 feet, the voluntary standard for all flights
that the Federal Aviation Administration recently established for
national parks and other wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims that low-level flights ``are having
cumulative and synergistic environmental impacts on many facets of
the nation's environment.'' The shock of jets soaring overhead has
disrupted protected species of birds and mammals, as well as
livestock, causing herds to stampede and female cattle to abort
calves, it says.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also cites reports by the National Park Service and
the Fish and Wildlife Service that raise concerns about the
disruption flights cause to hikers, hunters and others in parks and
wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sudden, violent aural and visual intrusions of all these
low-level training flights is eroding the ability of visitors to
use these sensitive public lands for the purposes for which they
were set aside,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force spokesmen disputed the impact on wildlife or
livestock. They said scientific studies had shown that animals
adjusted to the noise of jets, and they noted that many of the
nation's bombing ranges had attracted abundant wildlife escaping
human development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
