<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-NYT &LR;      01-27 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CITES BRADLEY'S `ATTACKS' AS HE GOES ON THE OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore continued his drumbeat
against former Sen. Bill Bradley Thursday, accusing him of using
negative attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign seemed stung at Wednesday night's debate when
Bradley accused Gore of lying and distorting Bradley's record.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp was fighting assertions not only by Bradley but by
the debate moderator that Gore has been distorting Bradley's record
and his health care proposal. During the debate, Bradley compared
Gore to former President Richard M. Nixon, the emblem of dishonesty
in high office.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to about 25 employees at Silknet, a software company
here, Gore lashed out at Bradley. ``Regrettably, I'm not sure that
Senator Bradley wants a real debate on the substance of the
issues,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Gore accused Bradley of contradictory behavior, of attacking
while complaining of attacks. But Gore got in his own digs at
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gore referred to Bradley's statement last week
before the Iowa caucuses that Iowa ``rewards entrenched power,'' a
reference to Gore's lock on organized labor. Gore Thursday
interpreted that statement in words that Bradley never used.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Iowa,'' Gore said, ``he attacked the voters by saying that
they were puppets of entrenched power.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore added: ``Now in the closing days of this contest, he has
raised another phony issue, condemning negative attacks while
launching negative attacks himself. I don't quite understand how
someone can condemn so-called negative attacks while in the next
breath launching real negative attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   And he continued to hammer at Bradley's proposals for Medicaid.
``I am going to fight to protect Medicaid,'' Gore said, adding:
``Senator Bradley's plan would eliminate Medicaid and replace it
with an inadequate substitute. That's a fact, not a negative
attack.'' Bradley has proposed replacing Medicaid with a larger
health insurance program that would cover more people.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was put on the defensive himself Thursday during an
interview with New Hampshire Public Radio. The first caller, who
identified herself as Sarah in Nashua, questioned his credibility:
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the debate last night and I heard you say you have
always supported a woman's right to choose,'' the caller said. ``I
understand if you've changed your position during your career, but
I'm just having a hard _ I don't know how I can support your
candidacy if you're dishonest about such an important subject and
especially on national television.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who declared in the debate that he had ``always been for a
woman's right to choose,'' said that he has always supported Roe
vs. Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion. But
he acknowledged that he had wrestled with the question of whether
public money should be used to pay for abortions for poor women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always supported keeping abortion legal, and it's true
that earlier in my career I voted to restrict the use of federal
funding in some circumstances, but over the years I have come to
the very strong view that federal funding should also be available,
and that has been my position for quite a long time,'' Gore
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the radio interview, Gore was asked about his apparent
shift away from Clinton earlier and his shift toward him now.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we're friends, and that friendship is genuine,''
Gore said of the president. ``Secondly, I have been critical of the
personal mistake that the president made, which I've been asked
about from time to time in this campaign. Third, I have fought
alongside the president for this strong economy and for the other
improvements that we've seen during the Clinton-Gore
administration. And fourth, I have to win this race on my own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he continued, ``depending upon the question that's
asked or the perspective of the questioner, they may focus on one
of those four aspects of the relationship and not really hear the
complexity of it with all four, and if they hear only that I'm
running on my own, they may say, `Oh, he's distancing himself.' If
they hear I fought with President Clinton for a strong economy,
they may say, `Oh, he's embracing President Clinton.' Well, all of
those things are true, but it's not true that I'm either distancing
myself from him or that I am trying to run as a derivative
candidate. So it's a complex relationship, just as most human
relationships are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
