<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8689 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-VEGAS-COX     01-27 1617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-VEGAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBy Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Shortly after dawn, Cesar Robaina pulls into the lot
outside a two-story brick building a couple of miles off the Strip
and enters his office.
</P>
<P>
   The door reads: Las Vegas Sports Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, a half dozen desks, topped with computer terminals, are
crowded into what he describes as the ``war room.'' The neon lights
and hulking Vegas hotels are visible in the distance. Robaina flips
on the bank of five TV sets lining the front wall. The Jacksonville
Jaguars and Tennessee Titans will tee up for the AFC championship
in a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Office hands begin to trickle in. The most important on this
Sunday morning are Robaina, trailed by Scott Kaminsky and Jason
Been. They are the oddsmakers, the ``dream team'' of sporting
prognosticators. Before the day is done, they will create the
official betting line for Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   These are serious people; there is serious money at stake. The
Super Bowl game is in Atlanta but the Super Bowl action starts in
Las Vegas. Last year, $76 million was wagered legally here on the
Atlanta Falcons-Denver Broncos game. At least as much is thought to
be wagered illegally around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Only March Madness, the college basketball tournament, draws
anywhere near as much betting action, and it is spread over most of
a month.
</P>
<P>
   Robaina, 35, a Las Vegas native, ranks as the odds manager. He
studied drafting at a technical school after high school but has
been in the gambling business since hiring on with a tout service
when he was 21.
</P>
<P>
   Does he bet? ``Only when the line moves considerably, and it's
out of whack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminsky, 46, migrated to the desert from Pittsburgh in 1982 to
``make some money'' and was the first employee hired by Las Vegas
Sports Consultants. He had kicked around as a bartender, sold
lithographs on the street and played poker to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Been, 26, is the greenhorn, a UNLV graduate and oddsmaker here
for just a year. The Milwaukee native majored in hotel and gaming
management, working part-time as a ticket writer for Vegas sports
books to help pay his way through college.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every Las Vegas sports book _ and there are more than 90
_ works off the opening line posted by Las Vegas Sports
Consultants. It's the same for the nearly 200 Internet wagering
sites, all of which sit outside U.S. borders. Many are clients of
the consulting company, paying contracted fees for its oddsmaking
expertise and its reputation for setting a good line. The cue from
Las Vegas Sports Consultants is also taken by neighborhood bookies
from California to New York.
</P>
<P>
   For seven solid hours of doubleheader football, from the opening
kickoff to the final whistle of the St. Louis Rams-Tampa Bay Bucs
game for the NFC title, the oddsmakers are perched in front of the
TV sets, breaking only to munch on pizza and chicken fingers. They
kibitz back and forth, weighing strengths and deficiencies of the
aspiring Super Bowl teams, much like stock analysts toss around PE
ratios and earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis isn't showing me much,'' Robaina said just before
the Rams eke out an 11-6 win in the NFC title game. ``No offense,
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bookmakers up and down the Strip agonize with indecision over
St. Louis. While the Rams mean greater wagering volume than if
Tampa Bay had survived, Vegas sports books have significant dollars
tied to futures that come due if the Rams win the Super Bowl. St.
Louis was a preseason 200-to-1 choice and even as high as 150-to-1
two weeks into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted St. Louis out for that reason,'' Robaina said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Robina and his guys play with potential
Super Bowl lines, at one point having the Rams as much as 10
1/2-point favorites. The team's sour performance is reflected in
the number opening at 8. The early action from the professional
bettors, however, is mostly on the Titans and the line drops to St.
Louis minus-7 at most Vegas sports books. (That means that for a
bettor wagering on St. Louis to win, the Rams must beat the Titans
by more than 7 points.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl tends to bring in more of the general public,
plus we have to still play against the wise guys, the professional
gamblers,'' Robaina said. ``So we put out a number that we hope
will balance the action on both teams.''
</P>
<P>
   In a cluttered 10-by-10-foot office behind the sports book at
the Excalibur Hotel and Casino, Eric St. Clair is in front of his
computer when the official line flashes across his screen. St.
Clair is race and sports-book director for the Excalibur and six
other Nevada properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not so much line makers as line adjusters,''
acknowledged St. Clair, mindful of the science that went into
making the line. ``But the guys making the line don't have quite
the same pressure as somebody who runs a sports book. They don't
have somebody over them saying, `How'd we lose $50,000 on this
game, $40,000 on this game?'''
</P>
<P>
   To protect themselves, St. Clair and other Vegas sports bosses
might tweak the opening line slightly and then let the action move
it. But for the Super Bowl, sports books also put their personal
touch on so-called proposition bets. ``Props'' range from the
intriguing to the ridiculous, everything from which player will
score the game's first points to who will win the coin toss.
</P>
<P>
   Intertops.com, an Internet sports book operating out of Antigua,
does Vegas one better on proposition bets, posting 10/11 odds _ win
$10 for every $11 bet _ on whether the Super Bowl national
television audience will exceed 40 percent of American households.
It usually does, but that level is in question for Sunday because
of the small-market teams.
</P>
<P>
   The sports books operate to minimize potential losses, and often
they adjust the line in a defensive manner. Up to the kickoff
around supper-time Sunday, the Super Bowl line will be constantly
monitored and inched ahead or pulled back. The goal is to have an
equal amount of money wagered on St. Louis and Tennessee, to
balance the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there starts to be an imbalance of money on the Rams, we'll
move the line in order to draw money in on the other side,'' said
Robert Walker, race and sports book director at the Mirage Hotel &AMP;
Casino. ``There are a lot of factors, including the possibility
that it was a single bettor. Your screen will tell you how many
bets and what the total amount bet is. So if you go from 13 bets at
$20,000 (total) to 14 at $120,000, you know real quick what just
happened. You don't want a knee- jerk reaction to anything, but it
is constantly monitored.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is turning away business, though.
</P>
<P>
   Up and down glitzy Las Vegas Boulevard, Super Bowl Week is
filling most of the hotel properties and luring the sports players
and high-rollers into the casinos. More than 225,000 people are
expected to take up temporary residence this weekend, making it the
city's third busiest weekend behind New Year's and the Chinese New
Year.
</P>
<P>
   People attracted to the Vegas action plan vacations around Super
Bowl weekend. The hotels invite VIP guests. Two days before the
game, hotel vacancies along the Strip are as hard to find as
tickets for Siegfried &AMP; Roy.
</P>
<P>
   The non-gambling economic impact alone probably will exceed $65
million, according to the local convention and visitors authority.
For those who didn't finagle a ticket to hear the snap count in the
Georgia Dome, Vegas sells itself as the place for the serious fan
to catch the action. It has more parties than Atlanta could ever
imagine. And you can bet the game, hassle-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is a great city, but it's a little different than
coming to Las Vegas for the weekend,'' said Allan Feldman, a Mirage
vice president. ``You can buy show tickets, go to the restaurants _
bet the game. You can watch the game in the sports books and work
yourself into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need an invitation to the parties, either,'' Feldman
said. ``Here, things are more democratic. You can buy a ticket for
the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Super Bowl crowd isn't afraid to splurge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go down to the executive side at McCarran''
International Airport in Las Vegas, said Ray Koon, president of
Associated Gaming Consultants, ``you will see any number of
corporate and executive jets in there this weekend. Some of the
major hotels have their own airplanes, like the MGM and Imperial
Palace, and they will use them to go pick up key players and bring
them in.''
</P>
<P>
   They're the risk-takers the betting houses love, and this
weekend is what they play for.
</P>
<P>
   All this is bad news to the support groups that deal with
compulsive gamblers. The Super Bowl is both the biggest one-day
sporting event and a nightmare for the down-and-out gambler,
looking at a last chance to make up for his losses.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone driven to get a bet down probably can _ whether it's
buying a plane ticket to Vegas, tracking down a local bookie or
hopping on the Internet. More than $20 million will be bet via the
Internet on the Super Bowl, industry analyst Sebastian Sinclair
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Arnie Wexler, who runs a national hotline for compulsive
gamblers (1-888-LAST BET), says he gets 20 percent of his calls at
Super Bowl time. The National Council on Problem Gambling averages
more than 30,000 calls on Super Bowl weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Bowl Sunday to the compulsive gambler is like New Year's
Eve to the alcoholic,'' said Wexler, who is a recovering compulsive
gambler. ``I don't think people even care about the teams in the
game. The Super Bowl is the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
