<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TAX PLAN COULD LEAD TO CUT IN `MARRIAGE PENALTY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With CLINTON-SPEECH; will be updated after State of Union.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In proposing Thursday night to reduce the marriage
penalty that the tax code levies on many two-income couples,
President Clinton embraced an issue that has been pushed for years
by Republicans and so opened the door to a compromise on an
election-year tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The approach set out by Clinton would help fewer couples than
alternative changes preferred by most Republicans, and in
particular would do little for couples in higher income brackets.
But with Republicans in the House having vowed to make a marriage
penalty bill one of their first priorities this year _ and with
Democrats in Congress loath to vote against such legislation at a
time of swelling federal budget surpluses _ Clinton's plan could
provide the seeds for a bipartisan compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that this issue has a lot of political resonance,''
said Stephen Moore, director of fiscal policy studies at the Cato
Institute, a conservative research group. ``Clinton is very adept
at taking politically popular Republican ideas and embracing them
as his own. This is a strong signal to me that we will see marriage
penalty relief this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty proposal was one of dozens set out by
Clinton in his State of the Union address, but one of the few that
he had not previously announced.
</P>
<P>
   The others included a revised version of a plan he first offered
last year to create incentives for retirement savings among low-
and middle-income people. They also included initiatives to make
health insurance more affordable, provide prescription drug
coverage within the Medicare system, increase funding for school
construction, expand the tax credit for the working poor and
provide more money for medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the proposals _ few of which have much chance of
becoming law in their present form _ are intended to channel money
toward problems facing low-income people, reflecting Clinton's
emphasis Thursday night on spreading the benefits of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But the marriage penalty is mostly an issue among middle- to
high-income voters, and one that is more complex than it is often
made out to be.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty hits many two-income couples, especially
those in which the two partners make roughly the same amount of
money, pushing them into a higher tax bracket than they would face
if they could file individual tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   A study last year by analysts at the Treasury Department
concluded that 24.8 million couples paid a marriage penalty in
their 1999 returns, or 48 percent of the 51.4 million joint returns
filed. The average penalty was $1,141, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   But the study also found that the same quirk in the tax code
that hurts many couples also helps many others, mostly those where
only one spouse works or where one spouse makes substantially more
than the other. The study found that 21 million couples, or 41
percent of all couples filing jointly, actually received a marriage
bonus, which averaged $1,274. About 11 percent of couples pay
neither a penalty nor a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The main component of Clinton's plan would help 9.1 million
two-income couples that pay a marriage penalty, those that claim
the standard deduction on their federal tax returns. It would
address the marriage penalty by increasing the standard deduction _
$7,200 in 1999 for couples filing jointly _ until it is twice as
much as the standard deduction for single filers, currently $4,300.
The change would be phased in over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would do nothing for couples who itemize their
deductions, as most higher-income households do.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would also give a break to some taxpayers that do
not pay a marriage penalty. It would increase the standard
deduction for all couples by an additional $500 in 2005, and by
$250 for single filers.
</P>
<P>
   When fully phased in, Clinton's proposal would increase the
standard deduction for couples filing jointly by $2,150. For
someone in the 15 percent tax bracket, the tax savings would be
$322 a year when fully phased in.
</P>
<P>
   The White House estimated the cost of the proposal at $45
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have offered a variety of proposals to address the
marriage penalty in recent years. Republicans in the Senate last
year proposed eliminating the penalty altogether by giving couples
the option of filing joint or individual returns. They estimated
the cost at $117.7 billion over five years starting in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republican presidential candidates, Sen. John McCain
of Arizona backs a plan similar to what Clinton proposed. But Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas would take a different approach. He would
create a deduction for two-earner couples of 10 percent of the
lower-earning spouse's income, up to a maximum deduction of $3,000.
The cost of Bush's proposal was estimated at $40 billion over five
years and $12.5 billion a year after being fully phased in.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton plan, said Bruce Bartlett, a Treasury Department
official in the Reagan administration, ``is a minimalist approach
to dealing with the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress said they were glad to see Clinton
acknowledging the importance of tax cuts in general and the
marriage penalty in particular. But they said they would insist on
a bigger and more extensive tax cutting package than the president
offered Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``think all Americans deserve tax relief, not just
the handful the president picks,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R- Texas,
who is chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also proposed a number of other tax initiatives in his
address. He would provide tax incentives for charitable giving,
including allowing taxpayers who do not itemize deductions to claim
a 50 percent deduction for charitable contributions above $500 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed a series of tax incentives to encourage the
development and distribution to poor countries of vaccines to fight
diseases including malaria, tuberculosis and AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-NFCNEWS28-C     01-27 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-NFCNEWS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lyle may return to starting lineup for Rams
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An official decision may wait until shortly before
Super Bowl XXXIV starts Sunday, but the possibility is increasing
that Rams free safety Keith Lyle will return to the starting lineup
for the first time in more than two months, replacing Devin Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If it happens, it would be the second straight bum Super Bowl
for Bush, who was phased almost completely out of the gameplan last
year by the Falcons in a Super Bowl played in his hometown of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle, 27, had started 73 straight games before a Nov. 14
shoulder injury caused nerve problems and weakness in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   He missed the final seven games of the regular season, but
played about 15 snaps in last Sunday's 11-6 win over Tampa Bay in
the NFC Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Bush, a first-round draft choice of the Falcons in
1995, the St. Louis defense didn't miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   He had 50 tackles, two interceptions, and a fumble recovery
while starting seven games.
</P>
<P>
   But for the second straight day, Bush and Lyle split repetitions
in practice Thursday, although neither claims to know who's
starting.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle had 40 tackles, two interceptions, and a sack while
starting nine games.
</P>
<P>
   That and his reputation were good enough to earn him Pro Bowl
alternate status. He tied for the NFL lead with nine interceptions
in '96, and has a reputation for being near the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Bush started playoff games against Minnesota and Tampa Bay,
getting in a nasty altercation after the Bucs game with Tampa guard
Frank Middleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lyle) did well,'' Rams coach Dick Vermeil said Wednesday of
Lyle, whom St. Louis drafted in the third round in '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took some good hits on (the injured shoulder), and came
away fine. I'm pleased with the progress he showed, and we'll get
him prepared to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans running back Eddie George and quarterback Steve McNair,
who both weigh 225 pounds or more, figure to try to run the ball a
lot Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who's 6 feet, 210 pounds, is probably the equal of Lyle
(6-2, 210) as a tackler, but the durability of Lyle's shoulder
could come into question.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle is the better ``ball hawk,'' as he has 27 career
interceptions to Bush's five, but the Titans don't figure to test
the deep middle much.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who signed a four-year, $7.2 million contract with the
Rams shortly after last season, started 36 games at both safety
spots in his first three years with Atlanta, including 31 of 32 in
'96-'97.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons signed Eugene Robinson before the '98 season,
and he took Bush's free safety job.
</P>
<P>
   As Robinson went on to the Pro Bowl, Bush's role in nickel and
dime defenses diminished to the point where he barely got on the
field in a 34-19 loss to Denver in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
