<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8694 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFCNOTES28-     01-27 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFCNOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cold keeps players' minds on preparation
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service The Titans were feeling the heat
<TEXT>
Thursday.
<P>
   Their once-frigid interview tent outside the Grand Hyatt in
Buckhead was equipped with machines blowing more hot air than the
players.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive back Donald Mitchell even peeled to his T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big relief,'' Mitchell said of the almost balmy
conditions. ``You don't want to sit in a building that's just as
cold as it is outside.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he didn't mind the chilly air at their first practice
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't affect us all that much,'' he said. ``It was just
like a normal day of practice. It gets cold in Tennessee _ but it's
not this cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Josh Evans even said the weather ``is a plus for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not too much to do right now because of the weather,''
he said, ``so we stay in watching film and going over a lot of
different things about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of heat, Evans said the constant refrain the Titans
get no respect ``is like pouring gasoline onto the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Practice report
</P>
<P>
   The Titans went through a 2-hour, 15-minute workout in helmets
and sweats after another short walk-through. The temperature at
Georgia Tech was 20 degrees warmer than it was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McNair took about 80 percent of the snaps _ more than he
did last Thursday _ and did not seem to have any mobility problems
despite his sore toe.
</P>
<P>
   However, backup Neil O'Donnell handled the opening 2-minute
drill.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Fisher attributed that to ``superstition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not done it in eight weeks and we've continued to
win,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   No exceptions
</P>
<P>
   For Jevon Kearse's brother to hear who wins the Super Bowl, a
prison guard will have to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Kearse, who is serving 7 1/2 years for armed robbery at
DeSoto Correctional Institution in Arcadia, Fla., is under
disciplinary confinement for fighting with another inmate on New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, whose brother is the star rookie defensive end for the
Titans, was moved from an open dorm to a cell in an isolated
section of the prison. He is not permitted to watch television,
listen to the radio, read a newspaper or use a telephone until Feb.
5.
</P>
<P>
   Warden Linda Williams said officials will not make an exception
to let him watch the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not fair to the other inmates, just because he's got a
brother in the Super Bowl,'' Williams said. ``We can't say, `We'll
let you watch,' and not let someone else watch because they don't
have a brother in the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Par 3
</P>
<P>
   Al Del Greco is always trying to hit the ball straight. He's a
scratch golfer as well as the Titans' kicker. Kicking the ball
between the uprights is like driving a ball down the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al is as serious about his golf game as he is about kicking
footballs,'' said Craig Hentrich, the Titans' punter who is also
Del Greco's holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's golf season, yeah,'' said Del Greco, who shoots
68-75 during the offseason, 72-78 when the Titans are playing.
``This time of year, Craig likes to make fun of the fact that when
I don't hit a good shot, I get upset on the golf course. I
shouldn't say upset, but I don't like it. He fondly calls me the
bulldog because of my aggressive nature. We have a lot of fun
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco said playing with Hentrich, who is also a good golfer,
helps them be better teammates as well because they can share
something outside football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the reasons I've been more successful the past
two years is because of him,'' Del Greco said. ``We spend so much
time together day after day that if we didn't like each other, it'd
be a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Hentrich said he expects to see Del Greco on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Del Greco said, ``the Celebrity Players Tour, because
I'll make more money doing that than competing against good guys.''
</P>
<P>
   There is superstition
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco remembers a kicker with garlic in his socks, though he
can't remember the guy's name.
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco has the same routine on game day because it's worked
for the past seven or eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really consider them superstitions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He eats basically the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, I eat spaghetti, a couple of pieces of bacon and a
glass of orange juice,'' Del Greco said. ``At 7 o'clock in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   You want fries with that?
</P>
<P>
   Eddie George said he knows his life would be much different if
he hadn't gone to Fork Union (Va.) Military Academy and found the
discipline to work hard as a student athlete. But, he pointed out,
he'd still be on the straight and narrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be in jail,'' George said. ``I might be a manager
at McDonald's or something, not that it's a bad job.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell me why
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's philosophy is to be a leader on the field, not a drill
sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe players have changed,'' he said. ``Ten years ago,
you could tell a team to line up on the goal line after practice
and run 10 100-yard dashes, and they'd do it. Now you tell them to
do it and they ask, `Why?' That's the difference in the athlete.
Now, you have to give them a good reason (to do it). Ten or 15
years ago, I think trust and respect were synonymous with a coach.
It's not any more. You have to earn their trust and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
