<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-BELICHICK-NYT &LR;      01-27 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BELICHICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HIRE BELICHICK, ENDING JETS' BORDER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Bill Parcells in the unfamiliar role of peacemaker, the New
York Jets and New England Patriots each got what they wanted
Thursday. The Patriots hired Bill Belichick as their head coach,
and the Jets received the Patriots' first-round draft pick for the
2000 draft in exchange for releasing the former Jets'
coach-for-a-day from his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement ended what had been a bizarre month in which the
Jets (not in this order) lost two head coaches in two days, hired a
third, gained a new owner and defended themselves before the
National Football League commissioner and a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells took the initiative to broker the deal that led to
Belichick's hiring when he called the Patriots' owner, Robert
Kraft, on Tuesday night. ``I told him it was Darth Vader calling
and he said he knew who that was,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first meaningful conversation the two have had since
Parcells _ with Belichick, his assistant head coach, in tow _ left
the Patriots for the Jets in a wave of acrimony that has lingered
for three years. But in a conversation that lasted about 40 minutes
_ one that Parcells described as amiable _ the two buried their
personal animosity.
</P>
<P>
   They were both aware that finding a compromise for Belichick's
services benefited both teams. They talked about their stormy past
and shared a few laughs. Parcells acknowledged Thursday that he has
regrets about how his career in New England ended and said he hopes
he may someday return to watch a game in New England, perhaps from
the owner's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mended a lot of fences,'' said Parcells, the Jets' director
of football operations. ``We came to an agreement that regardless
of what happened with Bill Belichick, this border war with the Jets
and Patriots needed to come to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was anxious that we make an attempt to repair the
relationship. He's a good businessman, and I knew that if there was
an opportunity, regardless of who is presenting it, that would
improve his franchise, he would consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who consulted with the Jets' owner, Robert Wood
Johnson IV, said that he and Kraft only briefly negotiated that
night, with the Jets adamant in their demand for a first-round pick
and the Patriots not offering it. By Wednesday, Parcells was
convinced that a deal could not be done, that Kraft would end up
hiring someone else and that Belichick would likely be out of
coaching for a year and the Jets would lose his rights with no
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The start of free agency for NFL players is in two weeks, and
the Patriots, without a general manager or a coach, were under
pressure to put a staff together. But Kraft was reluctant to give
up the first-round pick before knowing the outcome of the antitrust
lawsuit Belichick filed against the Jets and the NFL on Monday. On
Tuesday, the judge in the case refused to issue a temporary
restraining order that would have freed Belichick from the Jets and
allowed him to negotiate with other teams. Parcells called Kraft
that night.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Belichick and his attorneys dropped the suit. The
Patriots interviewed Dom Capers, Jacksonville's defensive
coordinator, for four hours that day. At about 11 p.m. that night,
Kraft called Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, the two completed the agreement. They
informed the NFL, which will review the final deal. The Jets gave
the Patriots permission to talk to Belichick early Thursday
morning. Belichick said he did not know what was going on until he
got a call from Parcells at 7 a.m. Thursday. Kraft called him at 10
a.m. and, within hours, Belichick was in Foxboro, Mass. At 6 p.m.,
Belichick was introduced as the Patriots' coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this press conference will go a little better than
the last one I had,'' Belichick said, alluding to the rambling
monologue he delivered when he resigned from the Jets. ``The
opportunity to be in coaching was something I wasn't sure I would
have as late as 24 hours ago, and I'm extremely grateful for the
opportunity to coach in the 2000 season. It was quite an ordeal,
but it's behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the first-round pick, which gives the Jets the
16th and 18th overall picks in this year's draft, the Jets will
receive the Patriots' fourth- and seventh-round picks next year,
while the Jets give the Patriots their fifth-round selection in
2001 and the seventh-round pick in 2002. In 1997, the Jets gave the
Patriots four draft picks over three years, including their
first-round pick in the 1999 draft, to secure Parcells, who had
just led the Patriots to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's win-win for everybody,'' Parcells said. ``If I
were him and things were reversed, I would have paid it, too. Now,
we're in a position to help our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had wanted Belichick all along and asked for
permission to interview him the Monday after the regular season
ended. They were told it was too late, that Parcells had resigned
on Sunday night and that Belichick was already the Jets' head coach
because his contract stipulated that he would get that job
automatically upon Parcells' resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The teams had been talking intermittently since Belichick
stunned the Jets organization by resigning Jan. 4 as the Jets' head
coach, one day after he was publicly introduced in that role.
Belichick claimed when he quit that he was concerned about
Parcells' future with the team and the Jets' unstable ownership
situation, which was resolved several days later when Johnson
bought the team from the estate of Leon Hess.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he took Belichick's reasons for quitting at face
value and said the two have never discussed the resignation.
Parcells said he did not feel there were any hatchets to bury with
Belichick and that he was happy that Belichick would not be out of
coaching for a year. He added: ``The Patriots got a good man. He'll
be a formidable adversary.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Thursday, Belichick used measured
language to describe his relationship with Parcells. ``Bill and I
have had a good professional relationship throughout my entire
career, and I feel that's still in place,'' Belichick said. ``We
won a lot of games together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My diplomacy is directly proportional to the scoreboard,''
Parcells said. ``I don't think anybody won. I think we made a
business deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
