<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-27 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WE are not here to disparage the motives of Delton Carter or
question the opportunities he should receive, given the right
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone deserves a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   D.C., as the Westside Tennis Club security and maintenance man
is known, has a checkered past, but that should not preclude him
from trying to establish a productive future.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the way it should be done. These are not the
right circumstances for Carter to forge his trail, much less
troubled 19-year-old NBA phenom Leon Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant, this is no way for the NBA and its players
association to send a message that it cares anything about its
young players except for what they produce on the court.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several weeks, Carter, who has been convicted of
forgery, theft and solicitation of prostitution in various
incidents from 1990-1997, has aligned himself as a mentor of sorts
for the 6-11, 235-pound Smith.
</P>
<P>
   D.C.'s motives seem sincere, and he has earned the confidence of
several Rockets players and his employer, Jim McIngvale, but he has
no proper training in counseling from the NBA or its players
association.
</P>
<P>
   He is not employed by any club or league organization and knows
little about the demanding and often seductive off-court world of
NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Some might hear of Carter's criminal record and believe he is
just another hanger-on hoping to wedge his way into the elite NBA
fraternity. That might be true.
</P>
<P>
   But what is true is scary: Carter's only apparent qualifications
for taking Smith under his wing were his willingness to help and an
endorsement from union director of player programs Purvis Short.
</P>
<P>
   That's no way to counsel any young NBA player, much less one
like Smith, the tormented Mavericks rookie. Since being drafted out
of Chicago's Martin Luther King High School last summer, Smith has
been suspended from the Mavs for defying the coach's orders, has
been charged with assault against his former girlfriend and has
attempted suicide with an overdose of some 250 aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is confused, emotionally vulnerable and struggling to find
his way. He has problems that can be overcome. But Carter is the
best the NBA and the Mavs could come up with?
</P>
<P>
   That Carter has become so involved and was directed to Smith by
Short is only symptomatic of something bigger and more dangerous
for the league.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest-growing pool of talent in the NBA consists of those
players who can score and jump but cannot walk into most sports
bars. Including Smith, there are 14 players in the league under 21.
Dozens of others are 21 and 22, like the Rockets' Steve Francis and
Kenny Thomas, and also have been thrown into the gluttonous world
of the NBA at a tender age.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, NBA players come into contact with those who hover
around teams, trying to squeeze themselves into players' personal
lives. Every day, there are influences and temptations, whether
it's someone hanging outside the practice facility offering to be a
new best friend, someone offering something illegal or improper or
someone curvy, but whose motives are unknown, waiting outside the
locker room asking for a date.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous coaches, veteran teammates and executives regularly
offer advice to NBA youngsters, and the NBA offers guidance through
its player programs department. But the league has no organized
network of trained counselors or former NBA players who can devote
themselves to directing young players down the smart path.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Leon Smith-Delton Carter saga should slap the
league in the face like a splash of cold water. It needs to wake up
and acknowledge that kids, even drop-stepping, slam-dunking kids,
need guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fortunate that the vast majority have not had a
series of problems,'' NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said.
``There have been and there will be a lot more (teen-age players).
We're looking seriously at creating our own minor league to deal
with some of those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The likes of Carter are not the biggest problem the league
faces. Neither is Smith. At least Carter seemingly had Smith's best
interests in mind when he became involved and Smith was looking for
someone who cared.
</P>
<P>
   But the league and players association should not have to turn
to the Delton Carters of the world _ those who are untrained and
unwise to the ways of the NBA. Too many people would exploit such
an opportunity, and in the end the tragedy would be a wasted career
and, perhaps, a life.
</P>
<P>
   Every NBA franchise has at its disposal retired players who have
been through the wars, earned more money than they ever imagined,
made the long six-night trips and learned how to handle the
lifestyle. The league should tap into this pool of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said to me, What conclusion do you draw from Leon
Smith?'' Granik said. ``To me that's a unique case.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, caring ex-players such as Calvin Murphy and Mike Newlin
here, or James Silas and Mike Gale in San Antonio, or Jamaal Wilkes
and Michael Cooper in Los Angeles, could be trained as
club-appointed advisers for the growing number of young players.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has long been at the forefront of perpetuating a good
image. Now is a good time to face something potentially bad. Smith
has problems, but so do other young ones.
</P>
<P>
   Now is a good time for the NBA to address its youth movement and
come up with a network of mentors _ and we're not talking
maintenance men and security guards.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
