<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECH-SUPREMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES MISS PRESIDENT'S STATE OF THE UNION ADDRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sending regrets, the Supreme Court broke with
longstanding tradition and missed President Clinton's final State
of the Union address Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The court, whose attendance at the yearly event is ceremonial,
sent its unexpected regrets early Thursday in a brief note to House
Sergeant at Arms Wilson Livingood, who oversees the guest list for
the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justices of the Court had planned to attend the State of the
Union address, but travel changes and minor illnesses have
intervened,'' the court's message read. ``No justices will be in
attendance, but they do thank you for the invitation to be present
for the address.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices on the nation's highest court have been an annual
fixture in the House chamber during the presidential speech. Not
since 1986 has the court been unrepresented. That year, President
Reagan's address was rescheduled following the Challenger shuttle
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, appointed for life and in keeping with the court's
independence from the elected branches of government, sit stoically
through the address, even as members of the Cabinet and Congress
interrupt the president's speech with raucous applause.
</P>
<P>
   But not this year.
</P>
<P>
   The court's public information office disclosed the whereabouts
of four of the justices, leaving the activities of the other five a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's two Supreme Court appointees, Justices Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer, were feeling under the weather.
Ginsburg, who had colon-cancer surgery in September, was coping
with the side-effects of radiation therapy, and Breyer had a touch
of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas remained near his boyhood home inSavannah, Ga., following the death Sunday of his younger brother,
Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy was traveling to New York for a
speech he was scheduled to deliver at St. John's University.
</P>
<P>
   The public information office declined to comment on Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra
Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and David H. Souter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
