<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SUNDANCE28-COX     01-27 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Psycho' one of the few sure things at Sundance
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ Sandra Bullock and her beau's band, the Scabs,
were supposed to be there. So were Matthew McConaughey, fellow
University of Texas alum Renee Zellweger and Austin-born Ethan
Hawke. That's what the publicists told us and that was the canard
panted on the snow-sloshy streets at the Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. In sincerest consideration for our necks (all
that whiplash craning) and eyeballs (pingponging just can't be good
for them), none of the above paragons of superior dental hygiene
showed at the overflow bash. Rocking Austin band the Agency and
folkie Shawn Colvin did play, but, you know, they're musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The hot-ticket wingding _ thrown not as part of Sundance but of
its bratty stepchild Slamdance _ was the premiere party for the
Austin-filmed comedy ``What I Like About You,'' whose cast and
crew, including director Jeff Stolhand, hail from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   They all showed, as did actors Rachel Ward and, briefly, a
full-bearded Jason Priestley. Scott Von Doviak, ``What I Like's''
co-screenwriter and co-star, said that the film's single screening
at Slamdance had been sold out since Saturday and that two foreign
distributors were already biting. Co-star Dee-Dee Stirneman happily
informed me she was able to get fliers for the film into the hands
of Kevin Smith, Roger Ebert and James Woods, who were common sights
down the road at Sundance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about connections,'' says Von Doviak. ``It would be
amazing if the film is picked up. This is just one step. Maybe not
the big leap, but something.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the average moviegoer may never see or hear of ``What I
Like About You,'' whose budget was in the low six figures, both
Sundance and Slamdance have been quaking with acquisition deals, or
near-deals. Much palm sweat has been swapped, promises made and
nerves frayed in the smarmy sport of let's make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   I spent almost all of my five days in Park City at Sundance,
where the clarion buzz for a sackful of new movies is flying. Most
of those films are being plucked by hungry distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night, the vice president of Artisan Entertainment
excitedly told me that his company had picked up the seriously
strange comedy ``Chuck &AMP; Buck'' for around $1.5 million. Variety
reported that rave drama ``Groove'' was purchased by Sony Pictures
Classics and that the features ``Girlfight'' (which some have bets
on to win top festival awards), ``Two Family House,'' ``Panic'' and
``Love and Sex'' are on the verge of deals.
</P>
<P>
   Other major titles, such as Kevin Spacey's ``The Big Kahuna,''
the Nick Nolte vehicle ``Trixie'' and the female ensemble dramedy
``Things You Can Tell Just By Looking at Her,'' with Glenn Close
and Cameron Diaz, arrived as studio-project premieres headed for
theaters. Arriving this weekend on a wave of expectation is
SofiaCoppola's ``The Virgin Suicides.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are highlights of the films I saw that will likely make it
to theaters in the coming months:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``American Psycho'' _ The big-buzz flick at Sundance drew
turnaway crowds at its premiere last Friday night at the 1,400-seat
Eccles Theater. Some of those told to walk had waited four hours in
line. (I was turned away and had to see it at a stuffy Saturday
morning press screening.) Coming to theaters in April, ``Psycho''
is a bracing pitch-black parody of Trumpian Manhattan in the 1980s.
Evidently, it's significantly different from Bret Easton Ellis'
notoriously gruesome novel, but director Mary Harron (``I Shot Andy
Warhol'') retains a thrilling pungency that's not overly explicit.
(Sex content earned it an NC-17 rating, which to me could be
mellowed to an R with nanosecond deletions.) A spectacular
Christian Bale plays the title character to unctuous perfection.
The hilarious, harrowing script is air-tight and beautifully
written. Harron's sleek direction thrums with menacing elegance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Chuck &AMP; Buck'' _ This aggressively offbeat tragicomedy by
Miguel Arteta (``Star Maps'') disarms and dislocates with its
bizarrely deadpan tone and low-budget complexion (it was shot
entirely on digital video). It's about a semi-psychotic gay man,
Buck (played by the film's writer Mike White), who stalks his best
childhood pal, Chuck. Too long by 15 minutes, ``Chuck'' is sad and
amusing, creepy and affirmative. It's very good and festival
audiences loved it, but it's so idiosyncratic marketing it will be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Nowhere to Hide'' _ Lee Myung-Se's Korean action-art film
was screened in the World Cinema program and unjustly remained a
work of unsung genius during its run. A challenge to describe, this
blazing crime story is a frenetic, funny, violent, rock 'n' roll
homage to John Woo's action spectaculars, riddled with visual
allusions to other movies (from ``Ikiru'' to ``The Third Man'') and
filmed with as much formal dazzle as ``Run Lola Run.'' No other
film I saw was half as fun.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rated X'' _ Emilio Estevez directs and stars in this lemon.
Estevez and brother Charlie Sheen portray the real-life Mitchell
Brothers, who produced some of the most successful porn in the '70s
and '80s. It's a who-cares biopic that's so poorly crafted it can't
be taken seriously. Like ``Psycho,'' it was a hot ticket with
turnaway crowds. Seen in the audience at the Tuesday night
premiere: Roger Ebert, Anne Heche, Ellen DeGeneres, Edward James
Olmos, Estevez and Sheen.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye'' _ RuPaul narrates this heavily
buzzed bio of Tammy Faye, chronic weeper and former
wife/co-conspirator of crooked TV evangelist Jim Bakker. The cheeky
movie draws a dubiously sympathetic portrait of its subject, who
proudly claims she buys all of her signature makeup at swap meets.
Playful, funny and featherweight, the Ewok look-alike comes across
as both sweet and woefully vacuous. The eyes have it: ``Without my
eyelashes I wouldn't be Tammy Faye,'' our heroine chirps.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Filth and the Fury'' _ Danny DeVito, who co-produced
this jittery Sex Pistols documentary, introduced it at its Tuesday
premiere in apt Pistols fashion, pronouncing it ``a great
(expletive) film!'' Julien Temple (``Absolute Beginners'') directed
the Pistols-sanctioned chronology of the life and crimes of the
legendary punk band. Swirling with distracting random images, it
flitters between archival concert footage, savage band in-fighting
and irrelevant stock film. For all its ``punk'' quick-cutting
chaos, ``Filth'' is conventional history, at once engrossing and
unsatisfying. Pistols John Lydon (formerly Johnny Rotten) and Steve
Jones, looking thick and ragged, gave a spicy postscreening Q and
A.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
