<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JAN. 28
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Jan. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Jan.
26, about the selection of Hans Blix as the chief inspector of the
United Nations' new disarmament commission for Iraq rendered a word
incorrectly in a quotation from John Ritchie, the United States
ambassador to the International Atomic Energy Agency. He said that
new inspection authority and investigative technologies acquired by
the agency when Blix was its director were ``now'' being put into
effect worldwide; he did not say ``not.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-GENE-THERAPY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Jan. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Jan.
26, about problems with gene therapy experiments, especially one at
the University of Pennsylvania, referred incorrectly to information
given to one research subject, Jesse Gelsinger, and his father,
Paul Gelsinger. Far from having being unaware that the experiment
was risky, Paul Gelsinger said, they knew there were serious risks,
including risks of hepatitis, liver damage and even death.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-CELLS-EVOLUTION-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 24,
about the use of mitochondrial DNA to track evolution misstated the
relationship between mitochondria and human cells. The mitochondria
became structures within ancient ancestors of human cells more than
a billion years ago; humans did not yet exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
