<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8709 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-SPEECH-GORE-HNS &LR;      01-27 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECH-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVERING GORE STANDING WITH CLINTON _ FOR NOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ In a New Hampshire debate last fall, Al Gore
couldn't wait to express his ``disappointment and anger'' at
President Clinton's sexual escapades. But in Gore's final face-off
with Bill Bradley before the state's presidential primary, the vice
president was eager this week to tout his ties to Clinton and the
economic good times during the seven years of the Democratic
administration.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, there was Gore, getting ``heavy face time'' on
national television, sitting behind Clinton on the dais in the U.S.
House chamber in Washington as the president delivered his last
State of the Union message. The link between the men seemed as
politically inextricable as it was physically obvious.
</P>
<P>
   For now, as Gore courts Democrats on the nomination trail, his
role in the Clinton administration has become a highlighted item on
his political resume. But could that change again, if Gore becomes
the Democratic nominee and the connection to Clinton becomes more
problematic in the general-election campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Gore's wavering view of what Clinton means to his own White
House aspirations is one of the most interesting and closely
watched features of the national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a tough one'' for Gore, said George C. Edwards
III, director of the Center for Presidential Studies at Texas A&AMP;M
University. ``It's inevitably awkward.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by so strongly associating himself with Clinton in the
debate Wednesday, was clearly playing to Democrats, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Polling suggests the association is welcome at this point in the
campaign. A survey of Democratic caucus attendees in Iowa on Monday
found that 84 percent approved of Clinton's job performance, even
though less than half approve of him personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a short-term gain,'' Edwards said of the inter-party
pitch. ``That can come back to haunt you.... You give the
Republicans a sound bite'' for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, including presidential front-runner George W.
Bush, the governor of Texas, can't wait to try to put Gore in a box
on his service with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he can figure out how to handle his relationship
with the president,'' Bush said Thursday. ``He distances himself,
he doesn't distance. He distances himself, he doesn't distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's going to send confusing signals to the
voters.'' Bush said. ``I look forward, if I'm the (Republican)
nominee, to debating the vice president and talking about
distancing and not distancing.''
</P>
<P>
   If pressed as the campaign progresses, Gore is expected to seek
to link himself to administration policies rather than to Clinton
personally, as he did in the debate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of the whole discussion about the president's
personal mistake,'' Gore said in the debate. ``They think that, by
and large, he has been a great president in turning this economy
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's contention was borne out by an independent voter who
heard the vice president speak Thursday at Silknet, a new software
company in an old textile mill along the Merrimack River in
Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hall, a Silknet product manager, said Clinton's scandals
did not affect his view of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't play into my thinking,'' said Hall, 35. ``But his
connection with the last seven years and the economic prosperity,
that is good. I've gone from five years ago earning $10 an hour to
today living in a very prosperous neighborhood. You don't want to
remove a variable for success ... I don't want to change the
policies and take chances with the prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeming to pick up on such sentiments, at least in New
Hampshire, Gore has warmed to discussing his ties to Clinton's
policies. But it has not always been thus.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Gore signaled that he was ready to go it alone,
telling The Washington Post in October that the campaign was a
``very personal quest.'' The translation offered by most analysts
was that the vice president acknowledged Clinton was a negative.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, in the debate at Dartmouth College, after
expressing his ``disappointment and anger'' at Clinton's
indiscretions, Gore said the president was, of course, his friend.
But he painted his service during the Monica Lewinsky scandal as
being more a fulfillment of his constitutional duty than his
standing up for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took an oath under the Constitution to serve my country
through thick and thin, and I interpreted that oath to mean that I
ought to try to provide as much continuity and civility during (the
Lewinsky scandal) as I possibly could,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   It is also in his constitutional capacity as presiding officer
of the Senate that Gore was on the House podium Thursday night,
sharing in whatever reflected glory Clinton could generate. State
of the Union addresses almost always bring a spike in a president's
approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are thinking more long term and already pondering
how to present the Clinton-Gore link in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore represents essentially a third Clinton term,'' said
Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes. ``So the question is: Does the
country want a third Clinton term? I think the answer ultimately
will be no.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandals aside, Gore seems to have another view of that
question.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that in an Iowa debate Bradley had asked voters if
they were better off than when the Clinton administration took
office, Gore said Wednesday in New Hampshire: ``I think the answer
to that question is yes, but I don't think that's the question. I
think a far more important question in this campaign is, can we do
even better?''
</P>
<P>
   Strategists for Bradley, Gore's only Democratic challenger,
express a lack of interest in Gore's Hamlet-like musings on his
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't care about things you can't do anything about,''
said Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser, but he quickly added that
``it's been pretty clear that (Clinton) has been very actively
supportive'' of Gore's effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our minds it's one of the institutional advantages the vice
president has,'' Hauser said. He cited suspiciously
``coincidental'' White House initiatives on health care and
agriculture that filled in some gaps in administration record on
which Gore was getting flak and the president's renomination of
Alan Greenspan as chairman of the Federal Reserve six months before
the decision had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are 'good news from the White House,''' Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
