<HEADLINE>
THE SCENE: SUPREME COURT JUSTICES ALL ABSENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With CLINTON-SPEECH; may be updated after State of Union.) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton
had to be there, and were. The justices of the Supreme did not, and
weren't.
</P>
<P>
   In what may charitably be seen as a remarkable series of
coincidences and scheduling flukes, not one member of the Supreme
Court attended President Clinton's final State of the Union address
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The court sent the justices' regrets in a two-sentence message
to the sergeant-at-arms of the House of Representatives Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justices of the Court had planned to attend the State of the
Union Address, but travel changes and minor illnesses have
intervened,'' the letter stated. ``No Justices will be in
attendance, but they do thank you for the invitation to be present
for the address.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Clinton appointees to the court, Justices Stephen G.
Breyer and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, cited health reasons for skipping
the speech. Ginsburg has been undergoing radiation treatment after
colon cancer surgery. Breyer sent Clinton a note saying he wanted
to attend, but was homebound with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens is taking care of his wife, who
recently had hip replacement surgery. Justice Clarence Thomas is in
New Orleans, where his brother died Sunday. Justice Anthony M.
Kennedy has to be in New York to deliver a speech on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There was no explanation from the court for the absences of
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist or Justices Antonin Scalia,
Sandra Day O'Connor and David H. Souter.
</P>
<P>
   No one takes attendance at the State of the Union, but news
accounts indicate that at least five or six members of the court
have attended each of Clinton's previous addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the entire court missed the speech was in 1986,
when President Reagan hastily rescheduled his State of the Union
after the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger.
</P>
<P>
   The court prides itself on its work ethic. In January 1996, when
a storm dumped 2 feet of snow on Washington, the court was the only
government institution in the region to remain open. Rehnquist
dispatched four-wheel-drive police vehicles to fetch members of the
court.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had no comment on the court's truancy, but
others did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just astonished,'' said Theodore B. Olson, a Washington
attorney and former Justice Department official in the Reagan
administration. ``On the other hand, these things have become so
ritualistic and boring that it would be easy to find more
entertaining alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' Olson added, ``enough of them saw what the chief
justice went through during the impeachment trial that they decided
they didn't want to go near the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has no more campaigns ahead of him and the justices
serve for life, but Gore and Mrs. Clinton are in the middle of
heated battles for high office. Gore's aides were unhappy with the
image of the vice president standing behind the president and
serving as his chief cheerleader, but there was no way he could
decline to attend.
</P>
<P>
   The event, they winced, served as a visual reminder of the vice
president's subservient role in the Clinton administration as he
essays on the campaign trail to establish his own identity as a
potential president.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, aides said, was not expecting a political lift
from the event and was approaching the speech as she has all
previous such addresses, as a chance to make her husband look good.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was careful not to overdo the president's
tributes to his wife and his sidekick. A top adviser said that
speechwriters counted the mentions of Gore in previous State of the
Union addresses (usually from two to four) and tried not to be too
obvious about patting him on the back this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited Gore's contributions five times _ on computer
literacy, expanded health care for poor families, support for gun
control legislation, environmental activism and proposals to
improve the ``livability'' of American cities and suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton got virtually the same salute she gets every year,
for her work on family issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Clinton said a little before the halfway point of
his 9,400-word oration, ``I am especially grateful to the person
who has led our efforts from the beginning, and who has worked
tirelessly for children and families for thirty years now: my wife,
Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden, D-Del., said that Thursday night's speech
was unlikely to provide a boost for either Gore or Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think this is Clinton being Clinton,'' said Biden, who
is officially neutral in the Democratic presidential race but who
is close to former Sen. Bill Bradley. ``I don't think he's sitting
there thinking of Gore or his wife. I think this is about him going
out big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
