<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8714 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-MCCAIN-NYT &LR;      01-27 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 JUDGE THROWS McCAIN OFF PRIMARY BALLOT IN MUCH OF UPSTATE NEW(lh) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a decision that puts Sen. John McCain's
presidential campaign in New York in jeopardy, a state judge on
Thursday night threw McCain off the primary ballot in a wide swath
of upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Joseph R. Cannizzaro of state Supreme Court in Albany,
ruled that the McCain campaign had failed to gather enough valid
signatures on nominating petitions in eight congressional
districts, and overturned a move by the state Board of Elections on
Wednesday to keep McCain on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   After the successful challenges by the state's Republican
establishment, which is backing Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
McCain is now out of the March 7 primary in at least 13 of New
York's 31 congressional districts. Even if McCain wins the primary
on Tuesday in New Hampshire, where he is in a close race with Bush,
the expense of waging a campaign in a patchwork of districts could
force him to all but withdraw from New York's contest.
</P>
<P>
   If he wants to appear on the ballot across the state, McCain's
only hope now is to win a federal lawsuit that he has filed to
overturn the state rules, which are so complex that candidates not
favored by the state party usually fail to comply. A federal judge
in Brooklyn is to hold a hearing on the case Friday, and the
wrangling over the ballot could continue well into next month.
</P>
<P>
   While Cannizzaro was handing a victory to the Bush forces, the
campaign of another candidate, Steve Forbes, was going on the
offensive, charging in a separate state lawsuit that Bush should be
kicked off the ballot in six congressional districts in New York
City because his campaign had engaged in widespread fraud in
assembling its nominating petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Muir, a lawyer for the Forbes campaign, said he had
identified Bush petitions with numerous signatures that appeared to
have been written by the same person. He said that on some
petitions, the signatures appeared last name first, as if they had
been copied directly off a list of registered voters. Jeffrey T.
Buley, chief counsel for the Republican State Committee, which is
spearheading the Bush campaign, said the petitions were valid.
</P>
<P>
   Cannizzaro's decision on the upstate districts was the latest in
a battle over the New York ballot that has flared on several fronts
_ from election boards to the state and federal courts to the
Legislature _ all the while rekindling a debate over whether the
rules are unfair to insurgents. In many states, widely recognized
candidates like McCain automatically gain a ballot spot.
</P>
<P>
   Cannizzaro ruled that McCain's campaign had failed to obtain
enough signatures in the districts, and he implicitly criticized
the state Board of Elections for validating the petitions. The two
Democrats on the board had blocked the challenges filed by the
Republican State Committee, in what appeared to be an effort to set
up a more fractious Republican primary, which could hurt Bush and
help the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the rules, which were approved by the state
Legislature at the behest of the state party, were reasonable, and
as a result, he said, it would be wrong to allow McCain on the
ballot after he failed to comply with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hold otherwise,'' he wrote in his decision, ``would
unfairly and unreasonably treat the McCain delegates differently
than other possible candidates who obeyed the clear and unequivocal
letter of the law and complied with the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry T. Berger, a lawyer for the McCain campaign, attacked the
decision. ``It demonstrates the absurdity of the election law,''
Berger said, ``when a candidate such as John McCain, who is a
leading candidate in the race, can't get on the ballot in more than
a third of the election districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Buley, the state party's counsel, said the decision showed that
the Democrats on the state Board of Elections had abused their
authority. ``The petitions didn't meet the requirements in the
law,'' Buley said. ``The court did what the Board of Elections
should have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the New York primary is 31 separate contests, and
even if McCain is not on the ballot in some districts, he can win
delegates in the others. But as a practical matter, that is
difficult. It would not be worth buying television time to air
commercials in upstate counties because they would be shown in many
districts where McCain would not appear on the ballot. In the New
York City media market, McCain is off the ballot in four districts.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain mounted his petition effort with volunteers, Forbes
spent at least $750,000 to comply with the rules. The Republican
State Committee, which views Forbes as less of a threat to Bush,
had promised not to challenge the Forbes petitions, and the Forbes
campaign had expected to be on the ballot in all 31 districts.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans on Long Island filed their own objections,
knocking Forbes off the ballot in three districts. In retaliation,
the Forbes campaign filed objections against Bush in the six city
districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
