APPLES-MINNEAPOLIS-3 -- Frank Gehry's Weisman Art Museum at the
University of Minnesota. A kind of dress rehearsal for his Bilbao
Guggenheim, which changes color with the changing weather. Clad in
brushed stainless steel, its lopsided cubes and irregular cylinders
tumble down the east bank of the Mississippi like Marcel Duchamp's
``Nude Descending a Staircase'' in three dimensions. (Steve
Woit/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ST. PAUL, Minn. -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- APPLES-MINNEAPOLIS-2
-- Summit Avenue in St. Paul, where F. Scott Fitzgerald once lived
in a homely brownstone which he described as ``a house below
average on a street above average.'' Fitzgerald, a St. Paul native,
spent the summer of 1919 finishing ``This Side of Paradise,'' the
novel about Princeton that made him famous. (Steve Woit/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MINNEAPOLIS, Minn. -- Jan. 27, 2000 --
APPLES-MINNEAPOLIS-1 -- ``Spoonbridge and Cherry,'' by Claes
Oldenburg and Coosje Van Bruggen, at the Walker Art Center in
Minneapolis. The center is one of the nation's foremost museums of
modern art, second only, in some people's thinking, to the Museum
of Modern Art. It rotates its collection constantly, to make space
for special shows, so many of its iconic pictures. (Steve Woit/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- GUATEMALA-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W --
Portrait of a Mayan woman (circa 1895) by the Guatemalan
photographer Alberto G. Valdeavellano, from the show ``Picturing
Guatemala: Images From the Cirma Photography Archive, 1870-1997.''
The 100 or so images in the show come from the extensive
photographic archive of Cirma (Centro de Investigaciones Regionales
de Mesoamerica), a nonprofit organization founded in 1979 in
Antigua, Guatemala. (Americas Society Art Gallery/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- KOREAN-CERAMICS -- A
17th-century Korean porcelain jar, left; a 12th-century stoneware
ewer with celadon glaze. Both pieces are part of a serenely
beautiful show at the Met called, ``Korean ceramics from the Museum
of Oriental Ceramics, Osaka,'' which displays the masterworks of
the Osaka museum's extensive Korean holdings. (Metropolitan Museum
of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LONDON -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- ART-NOTES -- A room in Ilya
Kabakov's ``Palace of Projects,'' to be shown at 69th Regiment
Armory. The show was originally commissioned and exhibited by
Artangel, a nonprofit group that organizes art projects in England
and at the Reina Sofia Museum in Madrid. (The Roundhouse,
London/The New York Times)
</P>
