and a man into a gentleman,'' explains Tennard. Club meetings also
cover financial topics and try to inspire their young charges to
something more. (Karen Warren/The Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) HOUSTON -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- KIDS-ETIQUETTE-1-HNS --
DaJuana Outland practices how to hold utensils properly at the
Three Gentlemen School of Etiquette. ``We're not teaching anything
new,'' says Robert Hayes III, one of the three teachers at the
school and a resident adviser at Covenant House. ``We're teaching
something that gets passed down from generation to generation, but
is getting lost.'' (Karen Warren/The Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ATLANTA -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- FBN-SUPER-TEAMS-2 --
Tennessee Titans quarterback Steve McNair at a press conference
Thursday in Atlanta. The St. Louis Rams, by way of Cleveland and
Los Angeles, and the Titans, via Houston and Memphis, meet Sunday
in Atlanta's Georgia Dome in Super Bowl XXXIV. The conclusion of
Relocation Bowl I will be a benchmark occasion of sorts, crowing
for the first time with a Super Bowl victory the paragon of the
modern, vagabond sports enterprise. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- FBN-SUPER-TEAMS-1 -- St.
Louis Rams coach Dick Vermeil was honored as the NFL Coach of the
Year on Thursday. ``This is a humbling experience that I share with
my entire coaching staff,'' says Vermeil, who joined the Rams in
1996 after 14 years away from coaching, guiding a team that was
4-12 last season to the NFC's best record and into Super Bowl XXXIV
against the Tennessee Titans on Sunday. (Michelle V. Agins/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) STRATHAM, N.H. -- Jan. 27, 2000 -- BRADLEY-3 -- Bill
Bradley, running for the Democratic nomination for president, is
surrounded by supporters on Thursday. The democratic presidential
hopeful stepped up his assaults on Vice President Al Gore's
credibility Thursday, driving home his assertion that Gore is a
dishonest candidate who could not be trusted to honor campaign
pledges if elected president. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
