<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE'S STRUGGLES BECOME CLEAR IN EARNINGS DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gillette not so proudly affirmed its place within the ranks of
struggling consumer products companies Thursday, reporting lower
sales and earnings for the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Gillette, which is best known for its razors but
makes everything from Duracell batteries to Right Guard deodorant,
said earnings dropped 22 percent, to $339 million in the final
three months of 1999 from $435 million a year earlier. Quarterly
sales slipped about 4 percent, to $3.03 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On a per-share basis, Gillette earned 32 cents, in line with the
expectations of Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, the picture was nearly as grim. Gillette's sales
fell about 2 percent, to just under $10 billion, and profits dipped
12 percent, to $1.26 billion, or $1.15 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette has been buffeted by the aftereffects of the economic
crisis in Asia and Latin America, which caused inventories of its
products to swell worldwide. Reducing those inventories lowered
sales and earnings throughout 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, profits for the company's Braun electric razors
division fell sharply last year, and sales and profits from
toiletries like Right Guard remain weak. Even the Mach 3 razor,
rolled out with fanfare two years ago, has not been the panacea the
company hoped.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call to discuss the earnings, a Gillette
spokesman said that the company believed its worst problems are
behind it and that it was comfortable with analysts' estimates that
its profits and sales would rebound in 2000. Analysts estimate that
Gillette will earn $1.28 a share in 2000, up 10 percent from 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company will probably continue to face pressure from
investors to sell off its weakest divisions or even to consider a
merger with Procter &AMP; Gamble. Gillette officials have declined to
comment on a Wall Street Journal report of an overture made by P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had operating problems,'' said Timothy Ghriskey, a
senior portfolio manager at Dreyfus, which owned almost 4 million
Gillette shares as of September 1999. ``It was a
very-high-valuation blue-chip that has certainly come down, and I'm
not surprised that Procter took a look at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette and P&AMP;G have ``the same distribution channels, the same
ability to innovate on a product,'' he continued. ``I think they
could probably help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette has said it may sell or restructure Braun and its
stationery products division. In the most recent quarter, Braun
sales fell 4 percent, and profits dropped 55 percent, while
stationery sales and profits fell 17 and 89 percent, respectively.
In the conference call, the company said it would decide what to do
about Braun and stationery products this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gillette's got a lot to prove,'' said Erik Gustafson, a senior
portfolio manager of Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham, which owned 1.8 million
Gillette shares in September, all of which it has sold. ``Unless
they can prove to their investors that they can show consistent
quality earnings, this stock is going nowhere.'' In trading
Thursday before earnings results were released, Gillette closed at
40, up 11/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
