<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of 401(K) investment options is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MICKEY MEECE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Tides Are Rising In Retirement Plans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Employees have long been asking for more facts and more choices
when it comes to retirement plans. It seems that many employers
have heard them loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   Research from Hewitt Associates, a management consultant in
Lincolnshire, Ill., indicates that companies are offering more
investment options and bolstering education efforts. The level of
employer matches in 401(k) plans has risen slightly since 1997,
Hewitt found, with 19 percent of employers providing
dollar-for-dollar matches. Still, the most common match is 50 cents
per dollar, the survey found, at 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1999 survey of 491 employers with a total of 3.3 million
participants and $295 billion in assets, Hewitt found that plans
offered 11 investment options, on average, up from 8 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Michael B. McCarthy, a 401(k) consultant at Hewitt, said
employers were adding options ``purely to remain competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   With greater choice, McCarthy added, comes a need for more
education. ``While some people love it, some are overwhelmed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-six percent of the employers said they provided
investment education, up from 59 percent in 1997. And 62 percent
use the Internet for such purposes, up from 20 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet allows companies to fill a gap in investment
education, McCarthy said. Previously, the fund companies providing
the plans would advise employees on how to allocate funds by asset
class, he said; now, on the Web sites, the fund companies help with
the ultimate decision _ how much to put in each fund. ``It's a
simple choice,'' he said, ``but a lot of times it paralyzes
people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2155EST &QL; 
