<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8744 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      01-27 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MAKE PEACE AND GET THEIR MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs for MCDONOUGH-COLUMN that moved earlier.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Peace at last for this region's own little version of
``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him up and told him it was Darth Vader calling, and
Bob laughed,'' New York Jets head of football operations Bill
Parcells said of the first step toward ending his long-running feud
with Patriots owner Bob Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hatchets have been buried,'' said Parcells. ``The border
war is over. In fact, when I called Bob that first night (Tuesday),
I told him I thought it was time to end the border war. He
agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   So after three years of icy relations, and three weeks of
wrangling over the services of Bill Belichick, Parcells and Kraft
came together to reach an agreement that allowed the Patriots to
name Belichick their head coach late Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   New England gave up a first-round draft pick as part of the deal
that allowed Belichick out of his contract with the Jets. The teams
were forced to work out a similar compensation package after the
1996 season, when Parcells wanted out of New England and his
contract with Kraft on the heels of leading the Patriots to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   As result of the Parcells defection, the Patriots-Jets rivalry
became a white-hot rivalry for both sets of fans, fueled largely by
the cold war between Kraft and Parcells. The issue dominated the
talk before the games, before the seasons, even.
</P>
<P>
   So now that it's over, where does all this leave Kraft and
Parcells?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better about our relationship right now than I have,''
Parcells said. ``I know for my part there's a good feeling about
him, and I think it's the same way with Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Darth Vader?
</P>
<P>
   That's the nickname the assistant coaches on Pete Carroll's
staff gave Parcells because of the fear/contempt with which he was
held in Foxborough. They kiddingly referred to the Jets as the Evil
Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was amused when he learned of the Darth Vader label and
used it to open his first conversation with Kraft in nearly three
years.
</P>
<P>
   At Belichick's introductory press conference Thursday at Foxboro
Stadium, an elated Kraft spoke of how ``it did surprise me'' when
he received Parcells's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone came in and said `Bill Parcells is on the phone,'
I said, `You'd better give it to Helena (Movsesian, Kraft's
executive secretary),' because I've got a buddy who says he's
Donald Trump and uses different names,'' Kraft joked. ``But
(Parcells) said, `It's really me.' When the phone call came in, I
was very delighted to receive it. It was an excellent phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point, Kraft indicated, both men proceeded to
repair their frayed relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells decided to reach out to Kraft after Belichick's bid to
gain a temporary restraining order against the Jets, freeing him to
negotiate with other teams, was denied by a federal judge Tuesday.
``I didn't want to see him out of football, and knowing that Bob
liked him, I thought that Bob didn't want that either,'' Parcells
said. ``So I made the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the first 30 minutes mending fences, and then
we talked about Belichick. Bob said he still had interest but would
like to get something done fast, because if we couldn't, he had to
move on and get something done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a few good laughs about some of the things that
happened. I told him that I'd wished things had turned out
differently when I left New England, and I think he felt the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed (compensation) ideas. I told him what I wanted,
and he didn't want to do that, so we both agreed to think about it.
The next day, Bob didn't call so I thought it was over, that we
couldn't make a deal. But Bob called back late that night
(Wednesday), and we made the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kraft, ``I was delighted that he called and made that
opening gesture for two reasons. One, is we were moving on and we'd
seen some excellent candidates and (Thursday) morning we were ready
to make an offer. Until (Parcells) called Tuesday night, I didn't
know that there was any chance that we could get Bill Belichick.
But the conversation, he opened it up in a way that was top drawer
and allowed us to have a talk for about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reviewed a lot of things, and I think each of us agreed
that if we had to do it over again, we both might've handled a few
things differently and perhaps the New England Patriots . . . well,
maybe they'd be playing down in Atlanta, I don't know. But it was
good to be able to mend the fences.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots gave up their No. 1 pick in this year's draft (16th
overall), and a fourth- and seventh-round choice in 2001. New
England received the Jets' fifth-round pick in 2001, a
seventh-round pick in 2002 _ and Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the situation was reversed, I would have done the same
thing,'' Parcells said. ``Belichick is a good man. He'll do a good
job up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke with Belichick twice on the phone (Thursday) morning.
I told him what was happening. I told him I didn't want to see him
out of football, and he said he appreciated that. We talked again
after the trade was passed by the league, and I wished him well and
told him to go up there and show what he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells also said, ``I want to feel good about going back to
New England and be able to sit in that stadium and watch a game. I
loved my time in New England. I left a lot of my blood there. We
were getting very close to doing some special things when I left
there. I wish now it could've ended differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft publicly extended his gratitude to Parcells for taking the
Patriots to the Super Bowl in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our family was privileged to buy the team in 1994, he had
been here for a year and he brought respectability and stability to
this franchise,'' Kraft said. ``He gave us a chance to go out and
market it and do the things we wanted to do to help win, and I will
forever be grateful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The finalization of the Belichick deal took some time because of
its unusual features, a coach being exchanged for draft picks.
Kraft and Parcells first put together a letter of agreement to
release Belichick from his Jets contract that had to be approved by
NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Then Andy Wasynczuk, representing New England, and Mike
Tannenbaum of the Jets, each team's salary cap expert, put in
writing the compensation agreement Kraft and Parcells had reached.
Parcells said he pressed for a No. 1 pick because he didn't have
room under the salary cap to sign veterans.
</P>
<P>
   When that was done, Belichick was on his way to Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Kraft spoke how ``an added bonus'' of Belichick's
hiring was the fact he and Parcells finally were able to establish
a line of communication. When asked if he intended to go so far as
to have Parcells as his guest in his owner's box, Kraft smiled and
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, ``but only if we aren't playing the Jets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Vega of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2156EST &QL; 
