<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candidates for the White House have to slog through the snows of
New Hampshire, shaking hands over and over again and submitting to
a job interview that goes on for more than a year. In the virtual
world of professional football, all it took for the Patriots to
hire a commander in chief was a few feints toward the judicial
system and a pragmatic conversation between those two old buddies
Bob Kraft and Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the acerbic Jersey coach and the owner of the Pats
settled on a price for the services of Bill Belichick, the master
of defensive game plans who for many years had been Parcells's
protege. The Pats will give the Jets New England's first-round
draft choice this April _ the 16th pick in the round _ and there
will be a trivial exchange of lower picks over three years.
</P>
<P>
   This method of acquiring a leader would be unthinkable in the
real world, but as every player and every fan knows, the NFL is not
a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   What is remarkable about the melodramatic saga of Belichick's
escape from New York is not only that one of his jilted bosses with
the Jets suggested he was loco but that he is the popular choice
among Patriots players.
</P>
<P>
   They have had three years under Pete Carroll, a nice guy who was
unable to take them back to the Super Bowl. They want the kind of
compulsive, monomaniacal coach who can lead them to the top of the
mountain again. And having had Belichick as their defensive
coordinator in their salad days, they know he is a defensive
schemer capable of throwing a scare into Napoleon himself.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Kraft's pursuit of Belichick amounts to a tacit
admission that the owner was wrong not to hire the Wesleyan
graduate in 1997, when Parcells lit out for the Jersey swamplands.
This is the era of the obsessive techie executive, not the
well-adjusted company man. The slogan of the coming Belichick era
might be: Don't communicate, dominate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
