<SLUG> BC-SHOCKWAVE-SHOCKWAVE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 `Sleepy Hollow' Director Takes Act to the Web  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Tim Burton, the director of ``Batman,'' ``Edward Scissorhands'' and
``Sleepy Hollow,'' will bring his edgy sensibility to a new
animated series for San Francisco's Shockwave.com, an online
entertainment site.
<P>
   Officials at Macromedia, Shockwave's parent company, will
announce at the Sundance Film Festival today that Burton will
create 26 ``Webisodes,'' or online comics, for the site
(www.shockwave.com).
</P>
<P>
   The series, which will debut this spring, will revolve around
Burton's ``Stainboy'' creation, a simply-drawn character that
appeared in his recent book, ``The Melancholy Death of Oyster Boy
and Other Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Shockwave has been working feverishly to land high-profile
artists as entertainment content becomes a more important feature
in luring 18- to 34-year-old Web surfers. The company recently
signed similar deals with Spiderman creator Stan Lee, and Trey
Parker and Matt Stone, the creators of the raunchy ``South Park''
show.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for its graphics development software and Shockwave
plug-in, which lets Internet users play clips of video, games,
music and other forms of media, Macromedia spun off Shockwave.com
this summer to separate the entertainment- and game-oriented site
from its traditional business.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's two- to five-minute animated shorts will appear
periodically on Shockwave.com, and will be free to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Though Burton's often moody, dark work in movies has gained him
the most attention _ he produced the films ``Mars Attacks!''
``James and the Giant Peach,'' and ``Ed Wood'' _ he is also an
author and animator who likes to delve into stories and characters
outside the traditional Hollywood system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have the kind of freedom to try out an idea
without having to have a lot of meetings,'' he told the Associated
Press. ``I get to do shorts with a character I want to explore, and
this medium seems perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Shockwave officials didn't give plot or other details of
the series or character, including how often new ones will be
available, a drawing of the character depicts a smiling, portly
fellow with an ``S'' on his chest and what looks like a cape.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal weren't disclosed, but Macromedia
chief executive Robert Burgess said Burton will receive an equity
stake in the company, which is expected to offer its shares to the
public in the next year. Burton will also retain control if the
series jumps to other media like TV or films.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sign of the times,'' Burgess said. ``You're going to
see the greatest storytellers of our day targeting the Internet and
it will change people's minds about what the Internet can be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
