r f BC-WEBVAN-WEBVAN_SFCHRON     01-27 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN-WEBVAN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Webvan Sees Sales Surge 136%  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Bolstered by a growing customer base, Webvan Group Inc., the
Foster City e-tailer that delivers groceries to homes, reported
yesterday a 136 percent jump in sales in the fourth quarter to $9.1
million from $3.8 million a year ago.
<P>
   Webvan, which launched its service in June with Bay Area grocery
delivery, racked up $13.3 million in sales in 1999. The company
more than doubled the number of customers it has to 47,000 in the
fourth quarter from 22,000 in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan, which accepts orders for groceries over its Web site and
delivers them to peoples' homes, also announced an acceleration of
its national expansion plans yesterday. It intends to operate in 15
U.S. markets by the end of 2001, up from an earlier estimate of 11
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive George Shaheen said the company does not need to
raise additional financing for the faster rollout. ``We're good to
go on capital through this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan raised more than $400 million in an October stock
offering and completed additional rounds of private financing. As
of December 31, the e-tailer had $638 million in cash and
marketable securities, according to financial statements released
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really impressed with their desire to increase the speed
of the rollout,'' said Lowell Singer, an e-commerce analyst with
Robertson Stephens. ``This will ultimately make Webvan a bigger
company sooner than we had thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Webvan also reported net losses that were in line with Wall
Street expectations. For the year, Webvan posted a loss of $144.6
million ($1.27 per share) and a fourth-quarter loss of $49 million
(22 cents per share).
</P>
<P>
   The pro-forma loss for 1999, which excludes expenses related to
executive compensation and other onetime charges, totaled $76.3
million (28 cents per share) while the pro-forma fourth-quarter
loss totaled $25.7 million (8 cents per share).
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made after markets closed yesterday. In
after-hours trading yesterday evening, Webvan shares rose to $15,
up from the market closing price of $13.75.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who try Webvan are coming back. Repeat orders
accounted for more than 75 percent of fourth-quarter orders, up
from 65 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Order sizes grew to an average of $81.31 in the fourth quarter
from $72.53. Shaheen said Webvan needs average orders of $103 to
meet its financial goals.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its announcement, Webvan said it had finalized deals
to enter four new markets: Boston, Denver, Philadelphia and
northern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The company will launch in its second market, Atlanta, this
spring, and is currently setting up automated distribution centers
in Chicago, Dallas, Seattle and Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Webvan announced alliances with grocery
manufacturers Pillsbury, Quaker and Kellogg, which will pay fees to
Webvan in exchange for being able to offer promotions on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers will also sell Webvan discounted merchandise
``so we can be cost-competitive'' with supermarkets, Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar deals with Nestle and General Mills were announced late
last year.
</P>
<P>
