<P>
   &UR; BIKE _ &LR;  ``Remember,'' said bike messenger Andrew Brady before
hitting the wet, windy streets, ``if it's made of metal, it's
trying to kill you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes for cars, doors, manhole covers, tracks,'' he said,
tightening the strap on his shoulder bag. ``What do you do? You
crash, you roll, you bounce, you get up. That's the way it works.''
</P>
<P>
   And with those encouraging words, Brady pedaled off on his first
run of the morning _ a pick-up at a dot-com company south of the
new Pacific Bell ballpark at China Basin. While fast-riding,
red-light-running bike messengers have long been a fact of life in
downtown San Francisco, these samurai of the streets have been
making headlines lately for a different reason: disputes with
employers over pay and benefits. By David Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WEBVAN _  &LR;   &LR; Bolstered by a growing customer base, Webvan Group
Inc., the Foster City e-tailer that delivers groceries to homes,
reported yesterday a 136 percent jump in sales in the fourth
quarter to $9.1 million from $3.8 million a year ago. Webvan, which
launched its service in June with Bay Area grocery delivery, racked
up $13.3 million in sales in 1999. The company more than doubled
the number of customers it has to 47,000 in the fourth quarter from
22,000 in the third quarter. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SHOCKWAVE  &LR; _ Tim Burton, the director of ``Batman,'' ``Edward
Scissorhands'' and ``Sleepy Hollow,'' will bring his edgy
sensibility to a new animated series for San Francisco's
Shockwave.com, an online entertainment site. Officials at
Macromedia, Shockwave's parent company, will announce at the
Sundance Film Festival today that Burton will create 26
``Webisodes,'' or online comics, for the site (www.shockwave.com).
By Kelly Zito
</P>
