<HEADER>
A8751 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-ART-2N     01-27 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: our children.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the president's proposals have been suggested before but
have never gained traction in Congress. Clinton urged renewed
action on ``unfinished business,'' including hate-crimes
legislation, a minimum wage increase from $5.15 an hour, a bill of
rights to give patients more say with their health maintenance
organizations, and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mauser, the father of a teen-age boy killed last April at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., was one of the guests
invited to sit beside Mrs. Clinton in the balcony. The president's
speech pushed the gun-control measures that Congress failed to act
on last year, along with money to enhance the enforcement of
existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime in America has dropped for the past seven years _ the
longest decline on record, thanks to a national consensus we helped
to forge on community police, sensitive gun control and effective
prevention,'' the president said. ``But nobody believes America is
safe enough. So let's set a higher goal: Let's make America the
safest big country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's various tax-relief ideas would supplement
working families' retirement savings, assist with child care
expenses, encourage charitable giving and make up to $10,000 of
college tuition tax deductible. In another helping hand for
struggling families, Clinton proposed $21 billion to expand the
earned income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of undoing the marriage penalty is always politically
popular. But the president's plan, which would be phased in over a
decade and would double the standard deduction for two-income
couples to twice the amount of a single filer's deduction, is more
limited than various Republican proposals. It would not benefit
couples who itemize on their returns.
</P>
<P>
   The president also proposed measures to encourage drug companies
to develop vaccines to combat AIDS and tuberculosis. He pushed
again for prescription-drug benefits under Medicare, one of a
handful of health care proposals. And he vowed to pay off the debt
by 2013 _ two years ahead of his previous predictions _ and resist
reckless spending that chips away at Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing one of his biggest legislative defeats last year,
Clinton called for a ``bipartisan dialogue'' on the comprehensive
test ban treaty, conciliatory language indicating that he did not
intend to push the matter again. He stressed the importance of
engaging countries like China and Russia, which still maintains a
nuclear-missile arsenal. And he addressed the dangers of biological
warfare and ``cyberterrorism,'' without offering any specific
solutions to those dangers.
</P>
<P>
   One facet of Clinton's vision of a ``new America'' entails
closing what he has called the ``digital divide.'' He renewed his
requests for government aid to help poor people gain access to
computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In length and breadth, the speech reflected Clinton's basically
centrist political instincts, the advice of many people in the
White House and on Capitol Hill _ and the president's desire to
savor his last big moment in the spotlight before the nation's
attention turns inevitably to the next president.
</P>
</TEXT>
