<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO SETTLES BELOW DOLLAR FOR FIRST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The value of Europe's single currency, the euro, plunged 1.3
percent Thursday to finish trading for the first time below the
psychologically important level of $1. Since its debut, one year
and 27 days ago, the euro has fallen 15.3 percent against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between a euro at 98.86 cents, where it was in
late trading in New York on Thursday, and its $1.0013 value on
Wednesday is small. But the decline is an emotional blow to a
currency that was expected to rally after its birth and even
challenge the supremacy of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is turning into the little currency that couldn't,'' said
Ann Mills, senior foreign economist at Brown Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the $1 level has been pierced, foreign exchange
analysts expect the 11-nation currency to fall further. Some are
scaling back their expectations for a rally later this year as
well. Karen E. Parker, director of currency research at Chase
Securities, now expects the euro to fall as low as 95 cents and
bounce back by the end of the year to $1.07, instead of $1.10, as
she predicted late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense that there is a policy of benign neglect,''
said David Gilmore, a partner at Foreign Exchange Analytics, a
consulting firm in Essex, Conn. ``The Group of Seven just met and
didn't mention the euro in the communique,'' he said, referring to
the meeting of finance officials of the seven leading industrial
nations.
</P>
<P>
   With the break below parity, which the euro had done in intraday
trading on Tuesday and Wednesday and twice more in early December,
the currencies represented by the euro are at their weakest point
against the dollar since the mid-1980s and earlier. This is good
for American tourists, as the cost of travel to Europe becomes
cheaper. But it is tough on American exporters, whose products
become more expensive on the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   What is mystifying about the euro's decline is that the economic
fundamentals are positive. The 11-nation euro bloc, known as
Euroland, is growing again, albeit slowly, and inflation is low.
The pace of American growth, meanwhile, is expected to slow this
year, as the Federal Reserve tries to cool the economy by
continuing to raise short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies, though, can suffer even when economic fundamentals
are positive. The dollar was quite weak in 1995 and 1996, as the
current economic expansion was gaining a full head of steam and the
U.S. stock market was taking off.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's weakness is aggravated by its recent record.
Investors who bet on it early have lost a lot of money. Those
losses serve as a reminder to investors to sell quickly when the
euro fails to meet expectations. ``When people start to see it go
down, they don't have the heart to stay with it,'' Ms. Mills said.
The beginning of the year was particularly disappointing. The euro
rose 2.7 percent as the American stock market fell. But that rally
sputtered after just seven trading days, and the euro has gone
downhill since.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, a weak currency is not bad right now for Euroland
(Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal and Spain). It helps exports,
which are critical to Europe's economic recovery, by making them
less expensive abroad. A weak currency can add to inflationary
pressures by making imports more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But Europe is at the beginning of an economic rebound, while the
U.S. economy is days away from setting a record for the longest
expansion in its history. This means price pressures will build
more slowly in Europe than they would in the United States. In
addition, unemployment remains high in Euroland, and core
inflation, excluding food and energy, remains low at about 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of a weaker euro and the dearth of inflationary
pressures put the European Central Bank in a tight spot. A rate
increase could help strengthen the euro. But with no hint of
out-of-control price pressures, there is no strong reason to raise
interest rates aggressively to curb growth. Otmar Issing, chief
economist of the European Central Bank, made it clear on Wednesday
that the central bank would not worry about the level of the euro
unless it was adding to inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they can afford to raise interest rates,'' said
Jeremy P. Fand, senior foreign exchange strategist at BankBoston.
``The economy is still too weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many analysts expect the European Central Bank to raise
short-term rates modestly this year to assure that the economic
rebound does not ignite inflation. A factor in the bank's decision
will be the results of key wage talks, starting with IG Metall,
Germany's largest union.
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers of the European Central Bank are meeting on Feb. 3
to discuss whether to raise rates. Ms. Parker of Chase Securities
said that the latest fall in the euro ``may mean that they do half
of a percentage point instead of a quarter of a percentage point,
or do it earlier.'' She is still expecting policy-makers to wait
until March before acting.
</P>
<P>
   Given that U.S policy-makers are expected to raise the key
short-term interest rate target at least a quarter-point on
Wednesday, the European Central Bank may have some added pressure
to respond sooner, rather than later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
