<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8755 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIKE-BIKE_SFCHRON &LR;      01-27 1837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-BIKE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Road Warriors Deliver the Goods  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
``Remember,'' said bike messenger Andrew Brady before hitting the
wet, windy streets, ``if it's made of metal, it's trying to kill
you.
<P>
   ``That goes for cars, doors, manhole covers, tracks,'' he said,
tightening the strap on his shoulder bag. ``What do you do? You
crash, you roll, you bounce, you get up. That's the way it works.''
</P>
<P>
   And with those encouraging words, Brady pedaled off on his first
run of the morning _ a pick-up at a dot-com company south of the
new Pacific Bell ballpark at China Basin.
</P>
<P>
   While fast-riding, red-light-running bike messengers have long
been a fact of life in downtown San Francisco, these samurai of the
streets have been making headlines lately for a different reason:
disputes with employers over pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A brief strike last week at the leading courier firm, DMS Corp.,
highlighted the growing discontent among the city's bikers. About
30 DMS messengers stayed off the job for a week to press demands
for better pay and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The DMS strike followed votes to unionize at two other local
courier outfits, Professional Messenger and UltraEx, where
follow-up negotiations with management are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our hope we can get an industry-wide contract and
industry-wide standards,'' said Howard Williams, president of the
San Francisco Bike Messengers Association and a rider for UltraEx.
``But it's difficult. We're not going to beat around the bush on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to perceptions, San Francisco's roughly 300 bike
messengers aren't just a bunch of scruffy, pierced, tattooed
anarchists flying at breakneck speed along roadways.
</P>
<P>
   They are in fact scruffy, pierced, tattooed anarchists who bring
a unique set of skills to a job that requires split-second decision
making, in-the-field problem solving, a strong sense of personal
initiative and a pace that makes most vocations look positively
sedentary.
</P>
<P>
   After whizzing down the middle of streets, through a variety of
intersections and past about a dozen stop signs, Brady steered his
mountain bike into the flooded parking lot of Gazoontite.com, an
online company specializing in allergy relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh man,'' he moaned as his bike sank about two feet into the
water, soaking his sneakers. ``It's too early for this.''
</P>
<P>
   When it rains, and even when it pours, as was the case earlier
this week, bike messengers remain on the job, racing from gig to
gig.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, 35, who is director of operations at King Courier and has
been working as a messenger for 18 years, was dripping from head to
toe as he jumped off his bike at Gazoontite's back door and charged
up the stairs. He made his way through the office to the
receptionist's desk, where he received an envelope that had to be
delivered across town in just minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good day for swimming out there,'' one of the workers
commented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Brady agreed, already making for the door.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds he was once again on his bike and churning
through the flooded lot. ``Let's go!'' he shouted over his shoulder
before beginning a sprint through Multimedia Gulch to the offices
of a well-known venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Most courier companies pay messengers on a commission basis. In
King's case, it's a straight 50-50 split, with the average delivery
_ or ``tag,'' in messenger parlance _ worth about $8. The typical
bike messenger aims to pocket about $100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a messenger will handle literally dozens of
tags, and in so doing ride about 30 miles, every single day. For
$100.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why the DMS messengers were up in arms is because
that company doesn't use commissions. Instead, it employs a
``universal pricing grid,'' which is designed to compensate bikers
using a complex formula that considers the size of the package, the
distance covered and the effort required to make a delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works,'' said Terry Hird, who runs the San Francisco office
of DMS. ``The problem is that it's very complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he insisted that DMS pays ``more cash to bikers than
any other company in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   DMS messengers, who declined to give their names, confirmed that
the company does pay pretty well, with the average DMS biker making
about $120 a day. But they said that the universal pricing grid,
due to its complexity, makes it difficult for them to know just
what their rates are.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep it complicated on purpose,'' one DMS messenger said,
``so we don't know how much we get and how much the company is
getting.''
</P>
<P>
   To clear up the confusion, not to mention introduce more stable
pricing, the Bike Messengers Association approached the
International Longshore and Warehouse Union a couple of years ago
for help in unionizing the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way the industry is going to change is through a
combination of regulation and unionization,'' said Peter Olney, the
ILWU's director of organizing. ``Unless a union comes in, the
companies are going to keep competing by driving prices and costs
down.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, there is no official government oversight of the
bike-messenger side of the business because there is no licensing
for messengers. The Department of Motor Vehicles and California
Highway Patrol regulate the trucking side of things.
</P>
<P>
   The courier companies are resisting unionization, and have
brought in outside consultants to assist in their dealings with
workers. At UltraEx, for example, nearly eight months have passed
since the workers voted 27-15 to unionize, with no end to the talks
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're negotiating in good faith'' was all UltraEx President
Ernie Holbrook would say on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   While bike messengers may be the most visible facet of the
courier business, they account for only about 10 percent of revenue
for the larger companies. Approximately 4,000 other
delivery-industry workers in the Bay Area drive trucks and vans or
see to logistical concerns, and they have been less vocal than the
bikers in seeking to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   They also don't go through what the typical messenger copes
with. Inclement weather aside, the biker's average day consists of
a series of confrontations with lobby security guards and corporate
receptionists, punctuated by hops on the bike and almost daily flat
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Brady got his flat after a drop-off at Gap Inc. on Harrison
Street. He made the repair in about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is without a doubt the funnest job you can ever have,''
he said. ``You go, you bust ass, you go home tired, you feel good
about yourself. It's an honest day's work for an honest day's
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also really dangerous. All bike messengers have their
horror stories about getting ``doored'' by parked cars or wiping
out in the rain. But in many cases, they're on their own if they
get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   While just about all courier companies have plenty of insurance
to cover accidents involving pedestrians or vehicles, only a
handful offer health benefits to riders. Most even require
employees to supply their own bikes.
</P>
<P>
   And in the event of a fatality, the best send-off most riders
can hope for is a fond farewell from their colleagues. When a
messenger dies, Brady said, the city's bikers gather at South Park
for a wake and then ceremoniously toss their slain colleague's
cycle into the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of bikes have gone in,'' he observed, ``but they usually
get fished out by some homeless person.''
</P>
<P>
   Such brushes with mortality are often the extent of a bike
messenger's contemplation of the future. Most live for the moment _
so much so that they usually have little in the way of savings, let
alone a retirement plan.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dunn, a 37-year-old messenger, said he's been riding for
more than 10 years. ``I like being outside,'' he explained with a
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn figured he has another eight years in his legs before being
too old to keep working. After that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``That's eight years away. I try not
to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   What's usually uppermost on the minds of messengers? Over a
quick lunch at the International Restaurant and Mini Mart on
Battery Street _ a favorite among bike messengers, not least
because most items on the menu cost only a buck or two _ the answer
became clear.
</P>
<P>
   Money.
</P>
<P>
   As Brady and several other messengers gathered out on the
sidewalk to wolf down their food, the conversation centered on how
much people in the business are making, or not making, and which
companies currently offer the best pay for deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Heitkamp, 28, fielded a few questions about his latest gig
as in-house messenger for a printing company. ``It's boring,'' he
said. ``You go to the same places over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but there's a lot of cash,'' Brady pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Heitkamp nodded as he lit a cigarette. Despite their awesome
physical condition, nearly all bike messengers smoke like chimneys.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation shifted from money to one of life's other
necessities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are your favorite bathrooms?'' Brady asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep my favorites a secret,'' Heitkamp replied. ``It's hard
to find a good bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   After some prodding, he revealed only that his favorite rest
stop, in the office of a client, ``has a beautiful view of the Bay
Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady nodded appreciatively. ``My favorite used to be in 3
Embarcadero,'' he said. ``They kept it stocked with all the latest
newspapers and magazines. It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady next headed over to ``the wall'' _ the spot at Sansome and
Market where messengers congregate between deliveries. To stay out
of the rain, the bikers had moved across the street to the portico
of 1 Citicorp Center, where they were busily smoking cigarettes and
other substances.
</P>
<P>
   The talk was about the strike at DMS and whether it was truly
feasible to unionize the industry. Some riders were skeptical that
further strikes would work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rookies will always take the jobs,'' complained a
20-year-old messenger who asked to be identified only as Rebecca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, missing a day of work is the difference between
paying the rent and not paying the rent,'' noted a 24-year-old
messenger going by the street name of Slugger.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's radio crackled and he was dispatched to Japantown and
then to an address near the Marina. The rain was coming down in
sheets as he muscled his way up the hill on Laguna Street and then
sped down the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Heading back to the Financial District, he said, ``Let's take
the tunnel,'' and proceeded toward the Broadway tunnel, where a
heavy mist from the rushing traffic hung in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``One piece of advice,'' Brady shouted. ``Ride fast.''
</P>
<P>
   And he took off at full throttle, his bike just inches from
passing vehicles, the surface of the tunnel slick with rain and
oil, broken glass in the gutter waiting to slash another tire.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hell of a way to make a hundred bucks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
