<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGERS STILL MATTER IN INVESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent strength of Coca-Cola and Walt Disney stock is a
hopeful sign that dot-com mania hasn't entirely obliterated the
market's regard for meaningful measures of investment value.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, before frenzied speculators began throwing
money at loss-ridden Internet enterprises, there was a saying on
Wall Street that recognizing good management was key to successful
investing. Conventional wisdom held that while earnings did indeed
drive stock prices, the purchase of a company's shares was a bet on
its management.
</P>
<P>
   Without imaginative top managers, a corporation's ability to
sustain dynamic profit growth was suspect. Therefore, in the final
analysis, the anticipated stream of earnings that drove demand for
a stock depended on management's perceived capacity to deliver
ever-larger earnings numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's recent reaction to management moves for two
components of the Dow Jones industrial average indicate that the
investment community still hews to this conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   At Coca-Cola Co., management missteps had led to declining
confidence in its chairman-chief exec, sending its stock into an
extended swoon. The board of directors reacted to what it saw as a
threat to Coke's venerable brand image by naming Douglas Daft to
replace Douglas Ivester as the company's commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Daft has moved quickly to make his presence known by engineering
key personnel and strategy moves. One of his most important actions
came last week when he named a second in command, which was
something Ivester had resisted doing.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting vote of confidence by the investment community
since the top management shuffle was initiated has been a stock
price rebound of about 30 percent in just a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Something of the sort also has happened at Disney, whose stock
has been languishing for more than a year. Part of the problem was
chief exec Michael Eisner's seeming reluctance to appoint a No. 2
since Michael Ovitz's departure as president in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eisner is only in his late 50s, some past health
problems have no doubt exacerbated Wall Street's concern about his
insistence on running a one-man show. Eisner this week took a
convincing step toward addressing the need to ensure an eventual
orderly transfer of power by promoting ABC chief Robert Iger to
president and chief operating officer and making him a director.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a stunning $5-a-share pop in Disney's stock
price Tuesday. It didn't hurt, of course, that Disney also released
almost simultaneously a relatively strong earnings report for its
fiscal first quarter. Nevertheless, the profit improvement alone
wouldn't have been enough to launch a one-day 15 percent jump for
the stock price.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial aspect of Wall Street's enthusiasm seemed to be
Eisner's perceived willingness to at long last begin grooming a
successor, even though the company was careful not to characterize
Iger's ascension as such.
</P>
<P>
   Given how the Internet stock market has undermined traditional
confidence in tangible measures of corporate value, these
developments are reassuring. It's even quite possible they signal
the beginning of the end of the market's recent manic phase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
