<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FTC Postpones Decision On Amoco-ARCO Merger
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission decided to postpone a decision on
whether to block the proposed $30 billion merger of BP Amoco and
Atlantic Richfield after the companies made a new offer to sell
additional assets, people involved in the discussions said. While
the agency's decision represented the first significant progress
for the companies in their talks with government officials, people
involved in the talks said the two sides still appeared to be far
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive of Sara Lee to Retire
</P>
<P>
   John H. Bryan, the chairman and chief executive of Sara Lee who
helped transform the company into one of the world's largest
consumer package goods companies, announced that he would step down
as chief executive in July. C. Steven McMillan, the company's
54-year-old president and chief operating officer, who has worked
under Bryan for 24 years, will become chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Online Bank Finds Security Flaw
</P>
<P>
   X.Com, an Internet banking company, said an intruder had
exploited a security flaw to move another person's money into an
online account and then withdraw it. The security flaw, which the
company said was corrected earlier this week, highlights the
potential risks inherent in moving traditional commerce systems
into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Shares Decline in Volatile Session
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell in another volatile session on Wall Street as
investors looked ahead to next week's Federal Reserve meeting and
anticipated that an interest rate increase will be the first of
several this year. The Dow Jones industrial average slipped 4.97
points, to 11,028.02. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
5.53 points, to 1,398.56, and the Nasdaq composite index declined
30.35 points, to 4,039.56.
</P>
<P>
   Durable Goods Orders Rose 4.1 Percent
</P>
<P>
   A leap in demand for airplanes and electronic equipment pushed
up orders for durable goods 4.1 percent in December, helping
manufacturers to their best year since 1997, the Commerce
Department said. In another report, the Department of Housing and
Urban Development said the home ownership rate climbed to an
all-time high of 66.8 percent in 1999, further evidence of the
economy's strength.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Coke Continue to Decline
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for eight workers who have sued Coca-Cola for racial
discrimination contended the company was improperly coercing black
employees to sign away their right to be part of the lawsuit and
any eventual judgment. And the day after Coke announced that it
would dismiss 6,000 workers as part of a reorganization, investors
reacted with dismay. Coca-Cola shares continued to decline, falling
$3.563, to close at $59.50.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette Reports Lower Sales
</P>
<P>
   Gillette reported lower sales and earnings for the fourth
quarter. The company, which is best known for its razors but makes
a variety of products from Duracell batteries to Right Guard
deodorant, said earnings dropped to $339 million from $435 million
a year earlier. Gillette earned 32 cents, in line with
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Lilly said its fourth-quarter profit rose 20 percent as
newer drugs like the schizophrenia treatment Zyprexa made up for a
decline in sales of the antidepressant Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   EToys, the most-visited Internet toy store last Christmas, said
its fiscal third-quarter loss widened because of higher costs of
doing business on its Web site. Shares of eToys fell $4.375, or 21
percent, to $16.875, a record low close and below the initial price
of $20 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Scotland to Sweeten Bid
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland, hoping to bolster its bid for National
Westminster Bank, said it would sweeten its offer to $47.87
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
