u f BC-COKE-NYT &LR;      01-27 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RACIAL COMPLAINT OVER CUTBACKS AT COKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after the Coca-Cola Co. said it would dismiss 6,000
employees worldwide, lawyers for eight workers who have sued the
company for racial discrimination contended Coke was improperly
coercing black employees to sign away their right to be part of the
lawsuit and any eventual judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Coke said on Wednesday that it would cut 6,000 people, or
one-fifth of its workers, in an effort to make the company more
profitable and decentralize many of its operations. Coke plans to
take an $800 million charge against earnings in the first half of
this year to cover severance payments and other costs associated
with the move. The company also said its earnings would shrink
further because of less demand for concentrate from bottlers in
Japan, Germany and Eastern Europe, and some expect more bad news
once the company completes its review of business in other areas,
including India.
</P>
<P>
   The actions at Coke were met with dismay by many investors,
although some Wall Street analysts have said the moves are
necessary to improve performance, which has been disappointing for
the last two years. On Thursday Coca-Cola shares continued to
decline, falling $3.563, to close at $59.50.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers filed a motion Thursday in federal court in Atlanta,
asking the court to ``reject the company's attempt to buy the
silence of its African-American employees.'' One lawyer, Pam
Coukos, said she did not know whether any of the plaintiffs in the
lawsuit had been laid off, or how many people who might be part of
the lawsuit if it is granted class-action status had lost their
jobs or would lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know everybody's status at this point,'' she
said. ``We've asked the company for that information.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a waiver, standard procedure at many companies, that
employees who are laid off must sign if they want to receive a
severance package. Anyone who signs the waiver acknowledges that he
or she is giving up any future legal action against the company
under various statutes, including the Americans With Disabilities
Act and the Equal Pay Act. It goes on to specify the
racial-discrimination lawsuit, which was filed in federal court in
April, and lists the telephone numbers of two Atlanta-area lawyers
representing the plaintiffs that employees might want to consult
before signing the release.
</P>
<P>
   A Coca-Cola spokesman said the company had tried to be as
thorough as possible in notifying people about the lawsuit in the
waiver. ``Because of the pending litigation, we went above and
beyond what is required by law to make prospective class members
aware of the situation and encourage them to talk to plaintiffs'
counsel before signing the release,'' said the spokesman, Ben
Deutsch. ``Our goal is to treat everyone who is affected by this
realignment fairly and equally.''
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer in New York City said such waivers were not unusual
as part of a layoff. ``It's absolutely legal,'' said Allen Fagin,
the co-chairman of the labor and employment law department at
Proskauer Rose. ``It sounds like Coke was being not only careful in
how they structured the waiver, but provided to their employees the
disclosure that was required.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees have 45 days to decide whether to sign, and seven days
to revoke their decisions, according to a sample waiver that was
attached to the motion. Executives who want to accept
early-retirement packages must sign a similar waiver.
</P>
<P>
   But because the judge in the case has not yet ruled on the
request for class-action status, employees faced with the choice
may decide the severance package is the surer thing, another lawyer
said. ``If I were counseling an African-American I would say to
leave that out, and probably not get the benefit,'' said Judith P.
Vladeck, a specialist in employment law. ``It's a little bit of a
Catch-22, because the employee at this point doesn't really know
whether he or she is part of the class, and even if he is, it
doesn't guarantee a benefit.'' The severance packages represent
``something in hand,'' while what becomes of the lawsuit is much
less clear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
