<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY: ENOUGH'S ENOUGH AS PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFUL GOES AFTER GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATHAM, N.H. _ Presidential hopeful Bill Bradley said Thursday
he'd ``had it'' with opponent Al Gore and would no longer refrain
from the kind of attacks he has said drag down American politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``After absorbing months of misleading statements and
misrepresentations, last night I decided, well, it's my turn, and I
threw a little elbow,'' the former basketball star and senator
said, referring to Wednesday's feisty debate between the Democratic
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had said for weeks that he was avoiding attacking the
vice president because noble politics required that he tell voters
what he is for, not against.
</P>
<P>
   But one day after using a televised debate to accuse Gore of
practicing dishonest campaign politics, Bradley's new refrain was:
The vice president can't be trusted to reform health care, protect
the environment or reward the public's respect if he can't be
trusted to tell the truth about Bradley in the race for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, whose New Hampshire lead has largely evaporated since
Gore's decisive win in Iowa on Monday, made one of his newly
aggressive points as he stood on the icy shore of the Great Bay
estuary with environmental activists who support him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a candidate doesn't take a long enough view to trust the
people by telling them the truth in a campaign, a long enough view
about democracy, how can you trust a candidate to take a long
enough enough view that will focus upon the kind of things that we
need to do now to protect our natural world for the coming
generation?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't quite understand how someone can condemn so-called
negative attacks while in the next breath launching real negative
attacks himself,'' Gore told workers at Silknet, a Manchester
software developer specializing in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley's plan would eliminate Medicaid and replace it
with an inadequate subsidy. That's a fact, not a negative attack,''
the candidate said. ``Senator Bradley's health care plan does not
devote a dime from the surplus to protect Medicare against the
impending doubling of Medicare recipient population when the baby
boomers retire. That's a fact, not a negative attack.``
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has disputed those facts.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is usually low-key, intellectual and sometimes remote on
the campaign trail. Gore is the one known for pumping up the crowd,
pouring coffee at diners, recalling his lawmaking battles against
congressional Republicans and shadow-boxing with his election
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Bradley bagged groceries for a voter, portrayed
himself as a legislative fighter, ad-libbed jokes and tackled a few
new policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he presented a passable imitation of the daily
approach used by the more energetic and aggressive Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to workers at the Timberland outdoor apparel
headquarters, Bradley described his Wednesday night confrontation
with Gore, in which the contenders argued about which one has
deployed ``negative'' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he complained about Gore's criticisms, he
linked Gore to President Richard Nixon's discredited claims of
innocence, and alleged that Gore had lied about Bradley's health
care reform proposal as well as his legislative record. Gore denied
it and said Bradley is the one who has been on the attack, in
violation of his own campaign principles.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore again pointed out that Bradley has refused his offer
for more detailed debates in lieu of 30-second TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, I'm not sure Senator Bradley wants a debate on
the substance of the issues,'' Gore said, adding that if he wins
the Democratic Party's presidential nomination, he would offer the
same challenge to his Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling John McCain would say yes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his continuing effort to match his lawmaking credentials with
Gore's, Bradley told the employees he led the fight in the Senate
to close income tax loopholes and develop a blueprint for
international trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   In response to audience questions, Bradley tread on new policy
ground. He said the minimum wage should be raised and tied to the
average national wage, so that it floats upwards without periodic
approval from Congress. He also said the United States lacks the
resources and the wisdom to intervene in ethnic wars in other
countries, so it should fully fund the United Nations and rely on
such international organizations to deal with the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking his campaign style as well as the tone of his rhetoric,
Bradley made a few impromptu, Gore-style visits to a doughnut shop
and a supermarket, where he bagged groceries and bantered with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he showed a lot more vitality'' in the debate,
customer Sherry Taylor said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But another customer, Laura Davies, said, ``I really don't like
the confrontational stuff.'' She said that after chatting with
Bradley, she remains undecided about the primaries and may vote
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
