<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8781 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-McNAIR-HNS     01-27 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-McNAIR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BARRON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ When the Tennessee Titans unveil their four-wide-receiver
set in Sunday's Super Bowl XXXIV, the St. Louis Rams still must
worry about two of the most dangerous, prolific running backs in
the National Football League.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie George you know about. But what chills the Rams' defense
during practice sessions on these frigid January mornings is the
threat posed by the Titans' other running back _ quarterback Steve
McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a scarier weapon than Eddie George, because once Eddie
George has the ball there's not much he can do but run with the
ball,'' Rams defensive lineman D'Marco Farr said. ``When McNair
drops back, you hold your breath and just hope you can get to him
before he gets loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Good plan, since when McNair gets loose, the goal line
frequently beckons. He enters Sunday's game with 11 rushing
touchdowns _ eight during the regular season, three during the
playoffs _ despite missing five games after undergoing back surgery
following Tennessee's season-opening victory over Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a running back who can throw the ball very well,'' George
said. ``He can make you miss, he can run you over, and he can spin
out of tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair came to the team then known as the Houston Oilers in 1995
with the well-earned moniker of Air McNair, based on his 14,496
career passing yards at Alcorn State. Five years later and 12
pounds heavier at 237, he brings every dimension to the game these
days except for, strangely enough, blockbuster passing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In 11 regular-season games, McNair threw for a relatively
pedestrian 2,179 yards and 12 touchdowns with a so-so 78.6 passer
rating. He returned from surgery Oct. 31 with 186 yards and two TD
throws against the Rams and had four 200-yard passing games the
rest of the way, including a five-TD performance against
Jacksonville in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   In the playoffs, however, he had only 76 passing yards in the
Titans' miracle win over Buffalo, 112 against Indianapolis and 112
against the Jaguars in the AFC Championship Game with his only TD
pass of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But his touchdown run against the Bills was Tennessee's only TD
of the game from scrimmage, and his 91 yards rushing against
Jacksonville tied Earl Campbell for fourth place in franchise
playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he doesn't put up Hall of Fame numbers doesn't
matter to Steve,'' Titans tight end Frank Wycheck said. ``That's
what so special about the guy. He goes out and makes big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the uncertainty that worries defenses _ and inspires
McNair himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think even McNair knows when he's going to run. It
just happens,'' Farr said. ``If he has any kind of hole or if he
sees any kind of hole, he's going to take off. His first deal is to
run. It puts so much stress on your defense, and that is what got
them to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Titans' presence in the Super Bowl continues to amaze
those who followed their star-crossed days as the Oilers, McNair's
development as a star is no surprise. He was groomed carefully and
methodically for the starting job by coach Jeff Fisher, sitting
through two years as a backup to Chris Chandler before taking over
for good in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous change from throwing for 4,000 yards a
year in college and throwing the ball at least 40 or 50 times a
game,'' he said. ``But now it's like playing in a more controlled
offense, and that's something that I had to get used to and get my
mind focused on the fact that it's something we have to do as a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've come a long way from my first two years, sitting
on the sidelines and learning the game mentally. My most improved
aspect of this game has been to be a leader. I'm doing what it
takes to lead this team to victory each and every Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his undeniable physical skills, teammates think
McNair the leader may not have gotten his just due.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's usually no one in the huddle who's getting antsy. It's
more of a laid-back thing,'' offensive lineman Jon Runyan said.
``People are in there making jokes. But he's a quiet leader. When
the ball is snapped, you know he's going to run around and try to
make a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to have someone like that back there who
is not going to just see someone in their face and hit the deck.
He's going to run out of there, break tackles and try to get the
ball down the field, try to run the ball and get the first down.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the cold can't get to him. In fact, McNair jokes that the
cold weather here this week has hastened his efforts to recover
from a nagging case of turf toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stick it in the cold tub every morning, and as cold as it
has been outside, I can just take my shoe off and have some extra
treatment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The injured toe and the recent tendency to be more Hare and less
Air have shifted attention from another quiet milestone for the
Titans' quiet leader. He jokes mildly about being the second
quarterback from a Southwestern Athletic Conference school to start
in a Super Bowl, which is another way of saying that he is the
first black Super Bowl starter at his position since Doug Williams
of Grambling State in Super Bowl XXII with the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   It is a legacy that he embraces. And it led to a special phone
conversation Wednesday night between the two trail blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Williams) told me not to go out there and do something
that I haven't been doing all year,'' McNair said. ``I should
continue to do the things I've been doing all year to get here and
not change things. He said I should go out and play my game and
don't try to force the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a young guy when Doug was in the Super Bowl, but I
remember watching the game. To be the only other one to start in
the Super Bowl is a great inspiration to me. It's only happened
once, and I'm the second one. Any time you can have a long trend
like that, with a long distance from one person to another, it's
special.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
