<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPERTEAMS-1STLD-     01-27 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERTEAMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN CALL THE SUPER BOWL THE `RELOCATION BOWL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (REMOVES reference to drowning being mysterious in 3rd graf; ADDS 3
grafs at end with reaction of fans in Houston) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT12,13 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ In the star-crossed, luxury box revenue chasing
world of professional sports, there is nothing so fitting as this
football season's grandest spectacle, Super Bowl XXXIV, which is
not sponsored by U-Haul, but ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams vying for the NFL championship, the Tennessee Titans
and St. Louis Rams, have relocated three times, leaving rankled
fans and civic leaders in their wake in the pursuit of a
publicly-funded stadium. Each has an owner who could be described,
charitably, as colorful.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' Georgia Frontiere, the only woman to be the principal
owner of an American professional sports franchise, is a former
lounge singer who inherited the team when the sixth of her seven
husbands, Carroll Rosenbloom, drowned in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently if she felt badly for fans of the old Los Angeles
Rams abandoned in Southern California, Frontiere replied: ``The
fans there are still able to watch on television. They watched on
TV and didn't come to games anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans owner Bud Adams, a Texas oilman and a charter owner of
the renegade American Football League, once won three division
titles in four years with three different coaches and ended a
stalled negotiation with a prized lineman by throwing in a herd of
cattle as a signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd get them cattle, girls, whatever it took,'' Adams said
Thursday. ``Back then, you didn't need a contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, by way of Cleveland and Los Angeles, and the Titans,
via Houston and Memphis, meet Sunday in Atlanta's Georgia Dome. If
this is the Relocation Bowl I, it will be a benchmark occasion of
sorts, the crowning of a Super Bowl champion who is the paragon of
the modern, vagabond sports enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   As the Rams and Titans have shown, the curious economics of
today's pro football make it possible, even likely, a franchise
will flourish by choosing a smaller market, like Nashville or St.
Louis, over bigger ones, like Houston and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   While small market teams in Major League Baseball have sagged
and now find it nearly impossible to compete, in the NFL, smaller
may be better. A smaller city like Nashville was hungry for the
status a professional team can convey and happily built a $292
million stadium for Adams with taxpayers money. They also let Adams
dictate the key revenue-generating terms of his lease.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's Adelphia Coliseum has 144 luxury suites, the most
precious commodity for a sports franchise owner. With billions of
dollars in national television money shared equally by NFL teams
and with a rigid salary cap restricting every team's payroll, the
rules of the game make small markets equal to their big market
brethren. With newer, more favorable lease agreements they are even
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike a baseball team, which is trying to fill its ballpark
and parking lots 81 times a year, the small market NFL team only
needs area fans and corporations to take an interest in eight home
games a year. Given the daylong carnival atmosphere that envelops
most NFL games these days, that is not asking too much.
</P>
<P>
   This model of the new commerce in sports, where NFL franchises
sell for more than $600 million, was on exhibit last weekend when
Frontiere's Rams earned their Super Bowl berth. They did so with a
victory before a sellout crowd inside the Trans World Dome, a $280
million facility built to lure a NFL franchise back to St. Louis,
which had lost its Cardinals to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking Georgia to Georgia,'' the Rams coach Dick Vermeil
shouted to the crowd in an on-the-field ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Frontiere, honored in St. Louis for bringing pro football back
to the area and active in a variety of philanthropic ventures, was
cheered by the Rams fans in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta this week, Frontiere has kept a low profile and not
appeared with the team or during the many press conferences
orchestrated by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil has occasionally spoken for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been a wonderful owner, wonderful to me and my staff
and our families,'' the coach said. ``She has done whatever it took
to make this franchise a winner and she deserves credit for that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Frontiere, whose exact age is not known although she is believed
to be in her early 70s, has been vilified for leaving Los Angeles
in the Southern California newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Frontiere owned the Rams, they had established a
standard for the carpetbagging sports franchise. In 1946, as league
champions, they deserted Cleveland and relocated to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Years before baseball's Brooklyn Dodgers or basketball's
Minneapolis Lakers went west, the Rams became a Hollywood
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Their running back star Elroy ``Crazy Legs'' Hirsch was
recruited by movie directors and a linebacker, Mike Henry, played
Tarzan. Their T-formation quarterback Bob Waterfield married the
starlet Jane Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team flights were events by themselves,'' said Rams
quarterback Roman Gabriel of the Rams' Hollywood halcyon days.
``You would just wait to see if Jane was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams became such a hot property that Rosenbloom, who owned
the storied Baltimore Colts, swapped his Colts for the Rams in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   On Apr. 2, 1979, the Rams were nine months away from their first
Super Bowl appearance when Rosenbloom drowned swimming in the ocean
by himself. Because Rosenbloom was known as a strong swimmer, there
were rumors of foul play and a series of celebrated investigations,
but the case has remained officially an accidental drowning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams moved from Los Angeles' Memorial Coliseum to Anaheim
Stadium 35 miles away and had several winning playoff seasons. But
Frontiere had fired most of her former husband's football
executives and her management style was erratic. She once told a
gathering of fans that she consulted an astrologer on player
trades.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, the Rams had lost 10 or more games for five consecutive
years. Although there was a ``Save the Rams'' movement in the Los
Angeles area, Frontiere took her team home to St. Louis, where a
new domed stadium awaited with a sweetheart lease.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams then lost every season in St. Louis far more than they
won, until this season's magical ride to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lesson in perseverance,'' Vermeil said of the Rams
saga.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but the result in St. Louis is a misplaced mix of
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Trans World Dome, they have a sort of Football Hall
of Fame. But it is half St. Louis and half Rams, so Hirsch, who
played in Los Angeles, is next to Larry Wilson, the Cardinals
safety who played in St. Louis. Before last Sunday's playoff game,
Lawrence McCutcheon, the former Los Angeles Rams star, was a
ceremonial captain on the field with Dan Dierdorf, the ex-Cardinals
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Whose team is this anyway?
</P>
<P>
   That's today's NFL, you can't know your franchise's history
without an atlas.
</P>
<P>
   Adams knows as much. Thursday, he talked about his 40 years in
pro football and made no apologies for turning his players into
gypsies who jumped from Houston to Memphis in 1997, then to
Nashville's Vanderbilt University football stadium in 1998 before
settling into Adelphia Coliseum this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we had to do, I didn't want to leave Houston,''
Adams said. ``But we couldn't get the revenue we could with a new
stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   While the move has been prosperous and the Titans have made it
to the Super Bowl _ something the Oilers never did _ Adams Thursday
almost seemed to bemoan the loss of innocence in pro football.
</P>
<P>
   He told a story of how he negotiated with players, baiting them
with stacks of money in his desk. He would place $100 bills on the
top of several piles of $1 bills to coax players to sign. Adams,
who like Yankees owner George Steinbrenner attended Culver Military
Academy, also used to take media relations into his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bashed a reporter in the jaw back in '62,'' he said. ``You
can't do that these days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Adams did watch one of his assistant coaches, Buddy Ryan,
throw a punch at another assistant coach, Kevin Gilbride, during a
game. And he had a head coach, Jerry Glanville, who left Oilers
tickets at will call for Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've seen a lot in 40 years,'' Adams said Thursday.
``I've seen the game change. I can't say it's changed for the
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I know where we were. And look where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, where Adams's team used to be, fans of the old
Oilers said they would be rooting hard for the Titans on Sunday,
though not for their owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Oilers,'' said Marcus Ramirez, a patron at Champs
Americana, a popular sports bar. ``I hate the owner, Bud Adams.
He's the one person I'd want to fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see people wearing old Oilers jackets. Until we get our
own team again in Houston, everyone will be pulling out the stops
for the Titans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
