<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     01-27 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE RAM'S CLIMB: NOT QUITE TO THE TOP
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Trent Green is the St. Louis Rams' forgotten man. He
is the flip side of Kurt Warner and his amazing story, a resident
of a terrible parallel world where the want of an inch, here or
there, results in disappointment and loss.
</P>
<P>
   Green, the 29-year-old quarterback who was going to be the Rams'
starter, was injured last summer in a preseason game against the
San Diego Chargers. When he went down, the Rams' players, fans and
management felt cursed. No one knew this was a blessing in
disguise. Isaac Bruce, the fleet wide receiver, slammed his helmet
on the turf; Dick Vermeil, the head coach, wept the next day, and
St. Louis mourned.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later Bruce is Pro Bowl-bound, Vermeil is the
National Football League's coach of the year, and St. Louis is
floating on gossamer wings.
</P>
<P>
   And Kurt Warner, the former Arena League and NFL Europe
quarterback, is the Super Bowl Cinderella. ``I don't think anybody
could have predicted the type of season he had,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The maddening question for Green is whether the Rams would have
reached the Super Bowl had he not injured his knee.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing to suggest that Green would have been as
successful as Warner; no other quarterback in the NFL this season
has done as well as Warner. Green enjoyed a good preseason, that's
all. Before that, he was just another quarterback teetering on the
brink between permanent journeyman and starter.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who went to high school in St. Louis, was drafted out of
Indiana University in 1993 by San Diego. In the 1994 season, the
Chargers went to the Super Bowl, but Green spent that year in the
Canadian Football League and the next four seasons with the
Washington Redskins. Green did not attempt a pass or start a game
until 1997, when he did both for Washington, starting one game and
throwing one pass. An incompletion. In 1998, he started 14 of 15
games for Washington, passing for 3,441 yards and 23 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   He signed a four-year, $16.5 million free-agent deal with St.
Louis last February and prepared for a fabulous homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams made all the right moves: they signed offensive lineman
Adam Timmerman, acquired the elusive Marshall Faulk in a trade and
drafted receiver Torry Holt. Green enjoyed a marvelous preseason,
completing 28 of 32 passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all falling into place really nice; unfortunately I
wasn't able to finish,'' Green said. ``That makes it tough to deal
with: going home, the high expectations and the way we got
everything turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's season ended on Aug. 28 when the Chargers' Rodney
Harrison rolled up on the back of Green's left knee, tearing a
ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Green if he thought the Rams would be in the Super
Bowl if he were the quarterback. ``I think so,'' he said. ``I was
feeling real confident. I was playing as well as I've ever played.
The preseason was going extremely well for me when I got hurt, and
I think the offense was doing extremely well. To say I would have
the same type of numbers that Kurt put up this year, I can't say.
Maybe they're worse numbers, maybe they're better. But I did feel I
was playing well, and I think the team would have been successful
if I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Green has given up on the idea of being the starter in
St. Louis. Warner earned it. ``It's not realistic at all,'' Green
said. ``I'd be kidding myself if I thought that coming into
training camp it would be an open competition. A guy plays as well
as Kurt has, one of the best single seasons in NFL history, and
he's the MVP, there's just no way he doesn't go into the season as
a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Green says all the right things _ and at an intellectual level,
believes what he says. Still, ``I would love an opportunity to play
for the Rams,'' he said. ``But I also want an opportunity to start
in this league. I've proven that I can be a successful starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the organization has to decide is if they're going to
keep me to be the backup. Obviously you never know on what play a
season-ending injury might happen. So from an organizational
standpoint, they need to determine if they want to keep both of us,
or if there is an opportunity for me to start out there if they're
going to trade me, or do whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Zygmunt, the Rams' executive vice president, admitted that
the situation was awkward. ``We expect to have both under contract
next year. We'd like the ability to have depth at that position,''
he said. ``While it might be awkward, we feel it's a pretty good
problem to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe for the organization. But for Green, the injury and
Warner's success and acclaim have made this Super Bowl the most
bittersweet experience of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely mixed emotions,'' Green said. ``You have times
when you do the `what if' thing, but you can't afford to dwell on
that. You have to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like an opportunity to start somewhere. I'm not one to
make demands, stomp my feet and pound the table and that kind of
thing. I'm not going to demand anything. We've agreed that after
the season we'll sit down and talk about what the organization
wants to do, what I want to do and just see what's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   As Green fielded question after question and dug deep for new
ways to express his joy and frustration, someone wondered if he had
divined a lesson in this setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to figure it out, because I thought I had
paid my dues up to this point,'' he said. ``I didn't know I had any
more to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the lesson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
