u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      01-27 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS AGREE TO END PARLIAMENT WALKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Leaders of three Russian political parties agreed
Thursday to end their boycott of the Russian Parliament on Feb. 9,
thereby avoiding an open-ended confrontation with the acting
president, Vladimir V. Putin, and his parliamentary allies.
</P>
<P>
   Putin had interceded in the parliamentary dispute earlier this
week by meeting separately with two former prime ministers, Yevgeny
M. Primakov and Sergei V. Kiriyenko. The men, together with Grigory
A. Yavlinsky, leader of the liberal Yabloko party, led a
parliamentary walkout last week to protest what they called
strong-arm tactics by Kremlin tacticians.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parties headed by Primakov, Kiriyenko and Yavlinsky
together control about 140 of 450 seats, they had been allotted
chairmanships of only two of Parliament's 27 committees.
</P>
<P>
   With their walkout, they had hoped to create a parallel rump
parliament. While that effort turned out to be short-lived, the
leaders suggested Thursday that their protest had fulfilled its
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider that it is now clear to all, what kind of majority
has formed in the Duma,'' Yavlinsky said, referring to the lower
house of the Russian Legislature, ``what position is taken by the
president's administration, and what position is taken by the
acting president. At this stage, we have done all that we could
do.''
</P>
<P>
   By joining with the Communist Party, a pro-Putin faction known
as Unity was able to put together a blocking majority. Until the
resignation of President Boris N. Yeltsin on Dec. 31, the
Communists had the largest parliamentary faction and were the core
of anti-Kremlin opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance between Unity and the Communists was seen as an
effort by Putin _ now the clear favorite in March 26 presidential
elections _ to bring Parliament under his control. But in a
television interview aired last Sunday, Putin insisted that the
arrangement with the Communists had been strictly temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Putin this week sought to defuse a political crisis that in the
opinion of many political analysts was caused by tactical blunders
by top Kremlin staffers emboldened by Unity's surprisingly strong
showing in parliamentary elections on Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko, leader of the Union of Right Forces, a party of
liberal economists, was the first to seek a compromise with Unity,
after meeting with Putin. Thursday, he said he would have led his
party back into Parliament if he had not given his word to stand
firm with Primakov, leader of the Fatherland-All Russia faction,
and Yavlinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Members of another parliamentary faction that had participated
in the walkout last week, so-called regional deputies led by Oleg
Morozov, returned to their seats earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Putin, Kiriyenko said he had been assured
that the government would press ahead with reform legislation,
including a bill to amend Russia's tax code, labor and land laws.
But so far, Putin has not committed himself publicly to any
specific legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   According to news reports, the opposition leaders were pressing
for a compromise that would create new legislative committees and
chairmanships, but that idea has been rejected by the parliamentary
speaker, Gennadi Seleznyov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
