u a BC-HOME-OFFICE-SAFETY-NY     01-27 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-OFFICE-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME OFFICE ISN'T LIABILITY FOR FIRMS, U.S. DECIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Labor Department said this week that employers would not be
held liable for any health and safety violations occurring in the
homes of telecommuting employees.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department officials announced this policy clarification
after the department sent out mixed signals in recent months over
whether U.S. companies could be fined thousands of dollars for
safety violations at the homes of the nation's estimated 20 million
telecommuters, who use computers and modems to do work outside the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mixed signals was a letter that was sent in November
by the Occupational Health and Safety Administration to a Texas
credit services company stating that companies would be held
responsible for federal health and safety violations in the homes
of employees working at home.
</P>
<P>
   That letter alarmed thousands of corporate executives and
angered many lawmakers, especially Republicans, who raised the
specter of Big Brother banging on doors to examine whether chair
seats were too high or keyboards too low.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in early January, Labor Secretary Alexis Herman created
further confusion by issuing a statement that partly backed off
from the November letter.
</P>
<P>
   The issue became an embarrassment to the Clinton administration
and Republicans were using it against Vice President Al Gore,
asserting that the Labor Department had adopted the policy to
please Gore's powerful union supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Jeffress, the director of OSHA, an arm of the Labor
Department, took pains to reassure employers in testimony he was to
give to Congress on Wednesday, although the testimony was delayed
because of the snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's clarifications were first reported in
Thursday's editions of The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the Occupational Safety and Health Act does not
apply to an employee's house or furnishings,'' Jeffress said in his
prepared testimony. ``OSHA will not hold employers liable for work
activities in employees' home offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Admitting that his agency had sowed some confusion on the
matter, Jeffress added that OSHA did not expect employers to
inspect home offices and that OSHA did not and would not inspect
home offices.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, vice president for labor affairs for the United
States Chamber of Commerce, applauded the policy clarification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction,'' he said, adding that the
chamber would like to see legislation barring the government from
ever holding employers liable for home-office safety.
</P>
<P>
   In its policy clarification, the Labor Department has sought to
balance century-old concerns about the dangers of blue-collar
workers' sewing and doing other manufacturing work at home against
the privacy concerns of the growing number of white-collar
telecommuters.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffress made clear in his testimony that the Labor Department
would hold employers responsible for health and safety violations
that occur in home workplaces other than home offices, for example,
in homes where employers ask employees to work with hazardous
materials.
</P>
<P>
   He cited an incident in which 17 workers were injured in 1998
when fireworks being manufactured in a California home exploded and
destroyed the house.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffress also cited disclosures last year that a dozen Silicon
Valley electronics manufacturers had assigned assembly piece work
to employees working at home. Those operations often involved using
lead solder and acid flux, which sometimes produced dangerous
soldering fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffress said, ``Where work other than office work is performed
at home, such as manufacturing operations, employers are
responsible for hazardous materials, equipment or work processes,
which they provide or require to be used in an employee's home.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department officials said OSHA would conduct inspections
of hazardous home workplaces only when the agency received a
complaint or a referral.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffress said, ``The bottom line is, as it has always been, that
OSHA will respect the privacy of the home and expects that
employers will as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
