u f BC-SARALEE-NYT &LR;      01-27 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARALEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARA LEE SETS TIMETABLE FOR SHIFT IN POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ John H. Bryan, the longtime top executive at Sara Lee
who helped transform the company into one of the world's largest
consumer packaged goods concerns, said Thursday that he would step
down as chief executive in July.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sara Lee have been suffering for more than a year,
partly because of weakness in a mature food and consumer products
industry. But Bryan, whose tenure of 25 years as chief executive is
one of the longest at a major U.S. corporation, said Thursday that
the recent performance of Sara Lee Corp. was solid and that his
departure was part of a succession plan put in place three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said I would retire at 65, and it seems to me this
is a fairly orderly way to do it,'' said Bryan, 63. ``I've never
felt better. The management is in good shape, and the company is
performing at a very high level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan will remain chairman until he retires in October 2001. The
chief executive duties will be assumed by C. Steven McMillan, Sara
Lee's 54-year-old president and chief operating officer, who has
worked under Bryan for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praised the decision, saying it was indicative of a
company that charted a cautious and predictable course of solid
earnings growth throughout Bryan's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as a revolution at this company; things
evolve,'' said William Maguire, an analyst at Wassterstein Perella
Securities. ``McMillan is a fine operator, adroit politically.''
Maguire added, though, that the new chief executive would probably
look at whether Sara Lee had the right structure for the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sara Lee, based in Chicago, fell 37.5 cents Thursday,
to $18.4375.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan will take over a $20 billion conglomerate that owns
brands like Hanes underwear, Playtex bras, Coach leather goods,
Ball Park hot dogs and Sara Lee baked goods.
</P>
<P>
   When Bryan became chief executive in 1975, the company was
called Consolidated Foods and had revenue of about $2.4 billion.
Now, after a series of big acquisitions, Sara Lee has leading
brands in everything from coffee and tea to cosmetics and
pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company has had a string of quarters with
double-digit percentile earnings growth, it stumbled badly last
year after a huge recall of bacteria-tainted hot dogs resulted in
millions of dollars of write-offs and a battery of lawsuits. Shares
of Sara Lee are down more than 35 percent the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings growth has since strengthened, but analysts say an
important question is whether Sara Lee has the right mix of
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee's meat division has struggled the last year, while
branded goods, including L'eggs pantyhose and Coach accessories,
have recorded strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said he was not looking to make any major changes, and
the fact that Sara Lee is a huge conglomerate may rule out a big
merger in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee will grow through takeovers, he said. The company,
which recently bought Chock Full o'Nuts, the coffee marketer, said
its year, which ends in July, should be among its most acquisitive.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan, a graduate of Rhodes College in Mississippi, came to Sara
Lee from Bryan Foods, a company begun by his father. He has been
active in the arts in Chicago and was an early supporter of
President Clinton. In 1992, he was considered a candidate for
commerce secretary.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan has an undergraduate degree from Auburn University and
an MBA from Harvard Business School. He began his career at
McKinsey &AMP; Co. in Chicago. He joined Sara Lee in 1976 and has run
nearly every division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
