<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DRAFT CHOICE TERMINATES BORDER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's not nominate Bill Parcells and Robert K. Kraft for the
Nobel Peace Prize for speaking to each other on the telephone. They
were just playing out the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Bill Belichick slugged the Jets' organization in the
solar plexus with his resignation this month, it has been a matter
of ``Show me the draft choices.''
</P>
<P>
   All the meetings and all the legal briefs were just Xs and Os _
dust on a chalkboard. The judge could have giggled when Belichick's
lawyers claimed his contract was invalid. It was up to Parcells to
identify himself on the telephone as Darth Vader and for Kraft to
know exactly who it was.
</P>
<P>
   Because of guy-stuff machinations like this, the Jets have been
the most entertaining team in pro football this month, even more
exciting than the Rams and the Titans, who will meet in the Super
Bowl on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For all the legal maneuvering, it was essentially a foregone
conclusion. Coaches with good reputations do not languish in
never-never land. They move to the next job, as soon as the lawyers
work out the details.
</P>
<P>
   This does not necessarily mean that all sporting contracts are
worthless. Players are not going to be able to jump while they
still have contracts, because a team can live with a player who
feels used. They just tell him, ``Take it out on the other team,
big fella.''
</P>
<P>
   In football, however, when a coach blows the whistle and demands
a few gassers at the end of practice, he'd better not show
indifference on his face. Yes, it's a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I want to see Bill Belichick out of coaching?'' Parcells
asked magnanimously Thursday. ``No, but he probably could have
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said that if he had not called Kraft on Tuesday night,
Belichick would have been out of work. Belichick more or less
agreed with that last evening when he said, ``The opportunity to be
coaching was something I wasn't sure I'd have 24 hours ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, however, did not put Parcells up for any humanitarian
award. The fact is, Parcells wore out his welcome with the Giants
and the Patriots because of his needs and his ego, and he
understood the power play Belichick set in motion. In his own
strong-willed way, Parcells probably respected Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they got a real good man in Bill Belichick,'' Parcells
said about his former assistant who was finally named coach and
general manager in New England last evening. ``We both realize this
is a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells showed his shrewdness by trying to wait out Belichick's
appeal for liberty. Then he called Kraft, with whom he had not
spoken in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good businessman,'' Parcells said Thursday of Kraft.
``Regardless of what went on in the past, if he sees a good deal,
he's going to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells characterized the first-round draft choice as a
nonentity _ the 16th-best college senior in the next draft. The
most recent nonentity chosen 16th was Jevon Kearse from Florida,
who may be noticed on Sunday flinging various Rams around from his
position on the Titans' defensive line. Nevertheless, Parcells
would like it to seem that he held out for this high-draft choice
strictly on principle.
</P>
<P>
   There were no innocents in this confrontation. Belichick had
been turned off by the hasty events after the last game of the
season, when Parcells abruptly retired as head coach only to stay
on as chief football executive. It did not escape Belichick that
the suddenness of the move corresponded with Pete Carroll's being
dismissed in New England, and that he had been capitulated into
honoring his contract to coach the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft had been second-guessing himself ever since he and the
obstreperous Parcells butted heads three years ago. Thursrday
Parcells said it was time to end this ``border war'' and he
conceded, ``Hey, there were a few things I could have done
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the hard feelings toward Parcells, Kraft had not
thought it appropriate to retain Belichick as head coach, but now
he has followed his original instincts. The Jets go forward with Al
Groh, and the Patriots move forward with Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound sentimental to say Belichick wanted to go ``home''
but he and his wife, Debby, have moved eight times in his career,
and their house in Nantucket, Mass., has become the family retreat.
Belichick will be making far more money in New England than he
would have been as head coach with the Jets. He will also be far
from the turbulent shadow of the man who calls himself Darth Vader,
but is only joking, you understand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
