<HEADLINE>
BANK OF SCOTLAND SWEETENS OFFER FOR NATIONAL WESTMINSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Hoping to bolster its bid for National Westminster
Bank, the Bank of Scotland said Thursday that it would sweeten its
24.8 billion pound offer for NatWest, Britain's third-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish bank, which is competing with its in Edinburgh
rival, the Royal Bank of Scotland, for control of NatWest, said it
would improve its hostile bid by replacing a special dividend with
a guaranteed special stock unit, effectively raising the bid's
value to 29.2 billion pounds, or $47.87 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NatWest, which wants to remain independent, rejected Bank of
Scotland's latest offer. ``This is nothing more than tactical
maneuvering by a bank that is struggling to achieve credibility for
an inadequate and risky proposal,'' said Sir David Rowland,
chairman and chief executive of NatWest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the move may still force Royal Bank of Scotland to increase
its (PS)26.5 billion bid, which now trails the bid of its rival.
Both banks have been scrambling to win shareholder support before
the deadline expires Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Scotland replaced a 120 pence special dividend once it
sold several NatWest assets with a stock unit worth a guaranteed
126 pence. Because Bank of Scotland's original special dividend was
contingent on the sale of several NatWest assets, many shareholders
and investors did not include the dividend in the offer price. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Explaining his sweetened offer, Sir John Shaw, governor of the
Bank of Scotland, said, ``In making this new offer we are pleased
to be able to remove uncertainty as to the value and timing of our
proposed special dividend and to provide more value to NatWest
shareholders.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that they had expected Royal Bank to win the
bruising bidding war, but that Thursday's move by Bank of Scotland
kept it in contention. ``It seems to have gone down well with the
institutional investors,'' said Tom Rayner, an analyst at SG
Securities in London. ``It gives their offer a lot more
certainty.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investors sent shares of all three banks up. Bank of Scotland's
latest move is expected to raise the ante for NatWest. ``I wouldn't
rule out both Scotts increasing their offers,'' Rayner said. ``At
the very least, Royal Bank needs to find 2 billion pounds over the
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, independence remains a possibility for NatWest. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
