<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ELDERLY-0128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SPEECH INCLUDES PROPOSALS AFFECTING ELDERLY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - President Clinton's State of the Union message
included numerous proposals affecting the elderly. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Social Security _ Crediting the interest savings from reducing
the federal debt to the Social Security Trust Fund. This accounting
measure would extend the life of the trust fund from 2034 to 2050.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare_ Dedicate more than $300 billion in projected federal
surplus to the Medicare Hospital Insurance Trust Fund, extending
its solvency until 2025.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prescription drugs _ Offer a voluntary prescription drug
benefit under Medicare that would be privately administered.
Employers who currently give retiree drug benefits would receive
incentives to maintain coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare buy-in _ Allow people between 55 and 65 _ the fastest
growing group of uninsured _ to buy into Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nursing Homes _ Allocate $16.8 million to help states
strengthen nursing home enforcement and increase federal oversight
of nursing home quality and safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Long term care _ Provide a $3,000 tax credit for people with
long-term care needs or their care-givers at a cost of $28 billion
over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Lipman can be reached by e-mail at:
LarryL(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
