<HEADER>
A8799 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      01-27 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TWILIGHT OF PRESIDENCY, CLINTON REMAINS PRIMARY FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ That was not an optical illusion Thursday night.
Bill Clinton still does hold center stage in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Four times in his presidency, Clinton's State of the Union
address has competed with compelling events offstage: the O.J.
Simpson civil trial, the first suggestions that Clinton had had an
affair with a White House intern, his impeachment and trial, and
now the presidential campaign to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   But with candidates braving chill winds and snowy streets in New
Hampshire and with voters preparing to make their selections in the
first primary, the president's annual report to the nation was also
a reminder that, even in his twilight, Clinton remains the central
figure in the nation's politics _ shaping the substance of the new
presidential contest, affecting the tone of the political debate,
coloring his vice president's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And though the 2000 campaign is being conducted in a different
millennium from Clinton's breakthrough in 1992 and his reelection
in 1996, there was a whiff of familiarity to the proceedings, which
were breathtaking in length and in detail even by Clinton's own
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The principal economic issue on the campaign trail is how to
sustain the boom that began in Clinton's first term. The principal
moral issue is how to wipe away the tarnish that Clinton's private
comportment put on the White House. The principal domestic issue is
how to address the health-care problems that first became
incendiary during the early years of the Clinton presidency. The
top political issue is how to deal with the campaign-finance
scandals that flowered during the Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's address was full of the broad declarations of
principle _ a ``more perfect union,'' in the president's paraphrase
of the preamble to the Constitution, for example _ and the precise
policy prescriptions. _ to include prescription drug benefits for
seniors on Medicare _ that have become standard fare for a Clinton
address to Congress and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The destiny of the president's plans for a $110 billion plan to
broaden health-care coverage, a $30 billion package of college tax
breaks and scholarship aid, and the patients' bill of rights _ all
proposals being pressed by a president with his eyes on his legacy
_ will be determined by a Republican-controlled Congress with its
eyes instead on the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Americans the president was addressing Thursday
night, none has more riding on Clinton than the man who sat behind
him and just over his shoulder. Vice President Al Gore slogged
through a full day of campaigning in New Hampshire before speeding
back to Washington; he knew that his presence on television
throughout a Capitol Hill spectacle that lasted more than an hour
was worth more than a town meeting in Derry or a stroll around the
Green in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big focus this week is on New Hampshire, but the State of
the Union still takes place on the greatest podium in the world,''
said Representative Jim Leach, an Iowa Republican. ``The president
has the Republicans at his feet, he's proposing popular programs,
and the economy is in good shape. All that has got to help Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans by a substantial margin believe that, in the long run,
the accomplishments of the Clinton administration will outweigh its
failures. When the Pew Research Center surveyed Americans on that
question this month, 51 percent agreed, with 37 percent in
disagreement. Gore has floated in and out of the president's orbit
since he began his presidential campaign, but in recent weeks, as
he has appeared before Democratic loyalists, he has once again
moved closer to Clinton. Thursday night, on television, the
distance between them could be measured in quarters of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is a lame duck, it is the last year of his term, his
party doesn't control Congress, and a lot of the things he is
talking about are designed to assist his loyal vice president,''
said Kathryn Dunn Tenpas, a political scientist at the University
of Pennsylvania. ``He can help Gore, especially with minority
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore apparently agrees. Earlier this month, during a
presidential debate in Des Moines, former senator Bill Bradley of
New Jersey challenged Gore to demand that Clinton sign an executive
order banning racial profiling. Gore bellowed back that Clinton's
record with minority voters spoke for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Clinton's rhetoric Thursday night matched his vice
president's. Throughout the campaign, and again in a Manchester,
N.H., debate Thursday night, Gore has spoken of Social Security and
Medicare. And so when the president said his new ``investment''
proposals and tax-cut plan should be considered ``only in the
context of a balanced budget that strengthens and extends the life
of Social Security and Medicare and pays down the national debt,''
he was singing from the Gore campaign hymnal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
