<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8800 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-ADDRESS-BOS &LR;      01-27 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ADDRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES $350   BILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN AND MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Basking in the nation's vibrant economy, President
Clinton Thursday night offered Americans a $350 billion tax cut,
urged generous new spending on a host of domestic initiatives, and
proposed licensing handguns ``to make this country the safest big
country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final State of the Union address, Clinton appealed to
Congress for a bipartisan effort to pass a package of ideas
``worthy of a great nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fortunate to be alive at this moment in history,''
Clinton said in an advance text of his speech. ``Never before has
our nation enjoyed, at once, so much prosperity and social progress
with so little internal crisis or so few external threats.''
</P>
<P>
   The televised speech carried a heavy nostalgic and historic
tone, as the president laid out an ambitious agenda for the final
lap of what has been a tumultuous, two-term presidency. This one,
the White House hopes, will be a victory lap for a president eager
to seal his legacy and advance his policy agenda. It could also
boost the presidential candidacy of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's proposals will face a tough road in a Congress
controlled by Republicans who want to regain the White House, they
were nevertheless ambitious and included targeted tax cuts,
expanded health-care coverage, incentives to develop new vaccines,
and measures intended to reduce gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   While crime has dropped steadily for the last seven years,
``nobody believes America is safe enough,'' Clinton said. ``So
let's set a higher goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been reluctant in the past to push for handgun
licensing, saying it would never get past Congress. But after
several gun-related tragedies, including the Columbine High School
massacre last April, the administration has put a greater emphasis
on guns.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was in stark contrast to last year's. In 1999, a
battered Clinton, fresh from being impeached by the House and in
the midst of being tried by the Senate, was faced with a country
and a Congress emotionally and politically wounded from the Monica
S. Lewinsky episode.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night featured another side of Clinton: that of the
survivor, a man whose political career has endured and even
flourished despite scandals, foreign policy crises, and legislative
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   The president took advantage of perhaps his single greatest
success _ the robust economy _ to remind Americans that they could
afford to help the poor, protect the environment, and develop new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   When he first took office, Clinton said, ``it was not clear to
most Americans that there would be much to celebrate in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the best traditions of our nation, Americans determined to
set things right,'' Clinton added. ``We restored the vital center,
replacing outdated ideologies with a new vision anchored in basic,
enduring values: opportunity for all, responsibility from all, and
a community of all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the ideas in Clinton's speech _ such as the patient's
bill of rights and his desire to increase the minimum wage _ have
been put forth before, without being passed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the enormous budget surplus, Clinton faces a tough fight
getting his agenda passed by the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we enacted all the new programs the president has talked
about, we'd spend just about the entire surplus on bigger and more
expensive government,'' said House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert,
Republican of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering the GOP response to the president, Senators Susan
Collins of Maine and Bill Frist of Tennessee promised Republicans
would put education first on their agenda, protect Medicare and
Social Security, reduce taxes, and build a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good education is the ladder of opportunity,'' Collins said.
``It turns dreams into reality. That's why education is at the top
of the Republican agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin Meehan, a Lowell Democrat, said, ``I think
the president's agenda has a fighting chance in this Congress. I
doubt the Republican majority wants the distinction of having
presided over the mother-of-all `do-nothing' Congresses. For
Republicans to have any sort of a record to run on, they'll have to
work with the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton laid out a strong agenda that is good for
the country and good for Massachusetts,'' said Senator Edward M.
Kennedy. Kennedy has been the leading Capitol Hill force behind
many of the president's proposals, and would carry much of the
burden in getting them passed.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut, totaling about $350 billion, includes easing of the
so-called marriage penalty, in which two working spouses end up
paying more in taxes than if they had filed separate returns.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Clinton plan, married, working couples would be able
to take a standard deduction twice as much as the single filer
deduction. More than 9 million married couples would benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Further, by 2005, the personal deduction for taxpayers would
increase by $500 for couples and $250 for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the tax plan is aimed at low-income Americans. One
provision would create retirement savings accounts for low-income
families, with the government offering a 2-for-1 match for the
first $100 contributed by each individual. The plan also would
expand the Earned Income Tax Credit for low-income taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   For wealthier taxpayers, the plan includes tax breaks and
incentives to encourage charitable giving, including a provision to
allow taxpayers to deduct gifts to charity from their gross income,
even if they do notitemize.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the $350 billion, 10-year tax cut would actually cost
the federal government $250 billion, said Gene Sperling, director
of the National Economic Council, because it would be offset by the
closing of loopholes in corporate taxes. Congress has in the past
rejected White House efforts to close such provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for a long list of social policy
initiatives. Remarking on the success of Boston's gun-tracing
program, Clinton proposed a federal version so US agents can trace
the origin of a gun used during a crime. The president also
proposed a $280 million expansion of the federal firearms
enforcement program, as well as a $10 million investment to fund
``smart guns,'' weapons that can be discharged only after the user
``unlocks'' it with a code. The idea is to keep guns from being
fired accidentally, especially by children.
</P>
<P>
   Other programs include a total of $4.5 billion in education
programs, including money to vastly expand the Head Start program,
which helps needy pre-school children; new funds to hire 100,000
more teachers and improve training; an expansion of an after-school
program for struggling schools; and money for a program focused on
teacher accountability.
</P>
<P>
   In the area of higher education, Clinton proposed a $31 billion
plan to help people afford college, as he already had announced.
Much of that money would fund a $10,000 personal tax deduction to
pay for higher education.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, Clinton proposed making China's Most Favored
Nation trading status permanent. He also outlined providing $1
billion in tax credits to help developing countries combat disease.
The money would be used as an incentive to develop vaccines against
malaria and tuberculosis, and to help people who have AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The State of the Union address, somewhat political in the best
of years, takes on an overtly political tone in a campaign year.
This year was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who took a break from campaigning in New Hampshire to take
his seat behind Clinton, was mentioned several times in the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's tax-cut proposal comes at a time when the leading
Republican presidential candidates are sparring over how big a tax
cut to offer Americans. Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona,
has proposed a $237 billion tax cut over five years, while Texas
Governor George W. Bush wants a $483 billion cut over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the ideas Clinton mentioned in his speech buttress
Gore, who has made the Clinton administration's economic record a
central theme of his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also has been attacking his opponent, former New Jersey
Senator Bill Bradley, on his sweeping health-care proposal that
would replace Medicare with a subsidy averaging $150 a month for
families to purchase health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan, announced Thursday night, would dedicate $400
billion to Medicare; $300 billion toward ensuring the solvency of
Medicare, and the rest for coverage of prescription drugs _ a Gore
campaign item.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
