<SLUG> BC-POLAROID-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CAMERA SALES SOAR, POLAROID WAITS FOR GAINS TO REACH BOTTOM
LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can selling razors really guarantee that razor blade sales will
soar?
</P>
<P>
   That is the make-or-break question for Polaroid Corp., the
photographic equipment company that faces the challenge posed by
the classic razor-and-blades marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Polaroid was dismissed as a has-been by numerous
analysts and investors. But last year the company, which announced
its 1999 results on Wednesday, sold 9.7 million instant cameras,
topping its 1978 record of 9.4 million. Fourth-quarter sales alone
were up 20 percent from the quarter a year earlier, driving revenue
to $650 million, easily surpassing analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a 20 percent sales increase since 1986,'' said
Gary T. DiCamillo, Polaroid's jubilant chief executive, whose
contract was just renewed through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   It is a vibrant rebound, and one reflected in the company's
shares, which rose $1.625, to $24.1875, Thursday. One problem,
though: while sales were well above analysts' forecasts, earnings _
$28.5 million, or 64 cents a diluted share _ were exactly what Wall
Street expected.
</P>
<P>
   So why did the sales gain fail to filter down to the bottom
line?
</P>
<P>
   The problem, apparently, is that most of the revenue increase
came from cameras. For imaging companies, cameras are practically
loss leaders; the lucrative ``razor blades'' are the films.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not clear how much of an impact camera sales will
have on film sales,'' said B. Alexander Henderson, an analyst at
Prudential Securities Research who still maintains a strong buy
recommendation on Polaroid stock.
</P>
<P>
   Clouding the crystal balls is the fact that most of Polaroid's
increased sales came from new cameras, whose market longevity is
untested. Polaroid, which significantly increased its marketing and
advertising budget in October, had promised $120 million to $200
million in sales of brand new products in 1999; the actual number
was $240 million.
</P>
<P>
   After good sales in Japan, for example, Polaroid began three
months ago to offer the I-Zone, a $25 camera that takes
matchbook-size pictures, in Europe and the United States. I-Zones
were originally aimed at teen-agers, but have become a fad item
among adults, and Polaroid has sold as many as it could make.
</P>
<P>
   DiCamillo is certain that film sales will follow. ``First you
sell the camera, then you sell the film, and remember, no one
else's film can be used in our cameras,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts agree. ``You are really going to see the benefit
of increased film sales in the second quarter,'' said Ulysses
Yannas, an analyst with Mercer, Bokert, Buckman &AMP; Reid and one of
Polaroid's biggest fans on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But it may not be that cut and dried. Polaroid's fourth-quarter
sales were helped mightily by Christmas gift-giving, and gifts
often wind up in a drawer when the season is over. Moreover, the
I-Zone's success with adults notwithstanding, many of Polaroid's
new products are aimed at children, who are notoriously quick to
discard fads.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the films do sell well, profits may take a while to
catch up. The films for the I-Zone, for example, sell for about $7,
far less than traditional Polaroid film. And, since the films are
new, many analysts say it will take a while before Polaroid can
manufacture them profitably.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dollar of I-Zone sales is just not equal to a dollar in
sales of films that they can make in their sleep,'' said Michael W.
Ellmann, an analyst at Schroder &AMP; Co. who is lukewarm about
Polaroid shares.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that Polaroid sold a lot of product last year,
but several analysts note that the company did not subtract the
cost of a huge mail-in rebate program from its revenue figures.
``They account for them as marketing expenses, and that practice
really inflates their top line,'' said Gibboney Huske, an analyst
with Credit Suisse First Boston who is neutral on Polaroid stock.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mood is cheery around Polaroid headquarters in
Cambridge, Mass. The company spent a lot on cultivating retailers
last year, and the push has paid off. Polaroid products, once sold
primarily through mass merchandisers, are now found in toy and
convenience stores; all told, some 60,000 U.S. stores sell the
cameras and film, up from 40,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   DiCamillo said that both camera and film sales remained brisk in
January, ``so this was not just a Christmas phenomenon.'' He
predicts the company will sell at least 10 million cameras this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the company's near-term future may be answered
next month at the Photographic Manufacturers Association's annual
trade show in Las Vegas, where retailers usually make their
commitments to carry film and cameras for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid expects to introduce even more products before the
show. ``That's when we'll see how much re-upping of the ante
they'll get,'' Henderson of Prudential said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
