<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-UNION28-COX     01-27 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CALLS ON NATION TO 'SET GREAT GOALS'
 &HT;    Eds: Will be updated by 11:30 p.m. EST.
 &HT;    With UNION-SCENE and UNION-GORE.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Challenging a prosperous nation to strengthen its
future by aiding its poor, President Clinton called Thursday for
$350 billion in tax breaks aimed at helping low-income families
gain a grubstake in the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of unprecedented wealth and budget surpluses, Clinton
said, the country can afford to help the millions of families still
struggling to get by, even as it commits to paying down the biggest
portion of the federal debt by 2013 and shoring up Social Security
and Medicare for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   He also called for a new slate of gun controls, including the
requirement that purchasers be required to pass a firearms safety
course before being issued a license to buy a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In his eighth and final State of the Union address before
Congress and a national television audience, Clinton cast a
backward glance at his seven years in office, hoping to obscure the
pall of scandal lingering over his tenure, while asking his
countrymen to embrace a broad array of goals unlikely to be met
until long after he leaves the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight let us take our look long ahead, and set great goals
for our nation,'' said Clinton, speaking in the ornate House
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``America again has the confidence to dream big dreams,''
Clinton said as Al Gore, his vice president and possible successor,
sat behind him and listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as our dreams outweigh our memories, America will be
forever young,'' Clinton said. ``That is our destiny, and this is
our moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning from national destiny to personal legacy, Clinton
portrayed his own time in office as a record of achievement
mirroring, even largely responsible for, the nation's broader
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Richer, more influential and more secure than at any time in its
history, the country has traveled a fortunate road, Clinton said,
since he first took office in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fortunate to be alive at this moment in history,'' said
Clinton. ``Never before has our nation enjoyed, at once, so much
prosperity and social progress with so little internal crisis and
so few external threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Not content simply to let the clock run out on his waning
presidency, though, Clinton dropped back and threw long. Calling
for ``a 21st Century American Revolution,'' he challenged the
nation to adopt seven dozen separate goals and initiatives, from
improving elementary schools and preserving federal lands to
combating hate crimes at home and bringing peace to foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans immediately denounced Clinton's agenda
as an overly costly approach that set the country on a course of
big government programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we enacted all the new programs the president has talked
about, we'd spend just about the entire surplus on bigger and more
expensive government,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said
before Clinton's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the past is any judge of today, it is going to be spending
after spending after spending, which proves my point,'' Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential front-runner, told
reporters in Nashua, N.H. ``If there is money left in Washington it
is going to be spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed and clearly enjoying himself, Clinton shrugged off such
sentiments Thursday night, leaving the political fights he knows
await him for another day.
</P>
<P>
   While he appeared engaged, Clinton's speech also lacked much of
the tension that invigorated his past two State of the Union
addresses, both given under the duress of a 15-month scandal over
his relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in the past, Clinton drew on the cast of Americans for
symbols of the triumphs and tragedies the nation has borne on his
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Basking in the reflected glory of one of the nation's newest
sports heros, Clinton tipped his hat to Julie Foudy, co-captain of
the U.S. women's soccer team that won the World Cup last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the NATO air campaign he spearheaded last year
against Serb forces in Kosovo, Clinton led the Congress in a
standing ovation for U.S. Air Force Capt.. John Cherrey, who was
awarded the Silver Star for courage in his efforts to rescue an
American pilot downed over Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also paid tribute to a grand old man of the Democratic
Party, his former Treasury secretary, Lloyd Bentsen. The Texan, who
suffered a stroke in 1998, struggled to raise his right hand in an
emotional response to Clinton's gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Turning toward the issue of race relations, Clinton acknowledged
the contributions made by former Atlanta Braves slugger Hank Aaron,
a pioneer in African-American participation in professional sports,
who was seated at a place of honor directly to Mrs. Clinton's
right.
</P>
<P>
   And, in one of the most dramatic moments of the speech, Clinton
introduced Tom Mauser, whose son, Daniel, was one of 12 students
killed last April by a pair of armed teenagers at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a large lapel button with a photo of his late son,
Mauser rose as Clinton implored Congress to approve an ambitious,
and controversial, slate of new gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that his courage and wisdom will move this Congress to
make common-sense gun safety legislation the very next order of
business,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned limits on ammunition clip size, background checks
for sales at gun shows and child safety locks on handguns _ a group
of measures Clinton proposed, the Senate passed, and the House
killed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the ante on gun controls, Clinton also asked Congress to
require that every purchaser of a handgun first pass a gun safety
course and that states issue photo identification cards indicating
whether a potential purchaser had passed a background check.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton devoted much of Thursday night's speech to well-worn
themes: calls for increased spending on the nation's schools,
funding to put additional police on the beat in crime-ridden cities
around the country and a so-called patients' bill of rights, giving
increased leverage to Americans who are sick or injured.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Clinton's message, though, was a clear directive
for the country to dedicate a growing portion of its wealth to help
low-income Americans pay for child care, college tuition and health
care and save, like their higher-paid countrymen, for their
uncertain futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built a new economy,'' said Clinton, ticking off the
strengths of the country's commercial machinery set to kick out
more than $9.5 trillion in goods and services this year, and
spinning out record levels of tax revenues that congressional
analysts project will to generate up to $1.9 trillion in federal
budget surpluses over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``To 21st Century America,'' said Clinton, ``let us pledge that
every child will begin school ready to learn and graduate, ready to
succeed. Every family will be able to succeed at home and at work,
and no child will be raised in poverty,'' an admonition that drew
one of many standing ovations during a speech lasting more than an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Clinton laid out an extensive package of
targeted tax cut proposals, the details of which will be contained
in the 2001 budget recommendations he submits to Congress on Feb.
7.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
