<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-FASSEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' FASSEL GETS ANOTHER YEAR, AND A MESSAGE: WIN MORE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Giants coach Jim Fassel got a one-year contract
extension Thursday, but it came with a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to win next year,'' Fassel said. ``It's a bottom-line
business; that's the first thing you learn about coaching. You
better win. I don't want to not be in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, who was entering the final year of a four-year contract
worth $3.2 million, is now under contract through the 2001 season.
His new deal pays him $1.2 million annually and includes various
incentives that can be earned if the Giants make a playoff run next
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it is highly unlikely Fassel will remain with the Giants for
the extra year added Thursday unless the Giants improve
dramatically on last season's 7-9 record. The Giants' ownership and
management support Fassel, but they also agreed to offer the coach
no more than a one-year extension because they didn't want to be
committed financially past 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, through his lawyer, Tom Curtin, had sought a multiyear
extension, even as much as three extra years. But Fassel didn't
seem ruffled by the outcome of the negotiations and insisted the
talks were amicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am satisfied with the contract,'' Fassel said in a
conference call from his Giants Stadium office. ``If we had made a
playoff run or won the conference championship, sure it might be
different. Everything is a reflection of what you do. But we
didn't. And whether I signed a five-year deal or whatever, I'd want
to win this next year just as badly. So I think this is very
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel was not pressured to fire or reassign anyone on his
staff, and he said Thursday that he did not expect there to be
changes among his assistant coaches, although his defensive
coordinator, John Fox, has interviewed for the head coach's job
with the New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he planned some shuffling of roles within his staff.
People familiar with Fassel's plans said Thursday that the coach
would soon promote the quarterbacks coach, Sean Payton, to
offensive coordinator. Payton took over the team's play-calling
duties from Fassel late last season.
</P>
<P>
   Making the 36-year-old Payton the offensive coordinator is also
a pre-emptive move by the Giants. It will mean a significant raise
for Payton and should head off other teams who might have tried to
hire him.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Skipper, currently the Giants' offensive coordinator, helps
in a variety of roles, especially with the running backs and the
deployment of personnel groupings during games. He will be given a
new post, perhaps head assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday to evaluate his three years as Giants coach,
Fassel said he thought the team did better than he expected his
first season when they were 10-5-1 and won the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from last place to first place in 1997,'' he said.
``Then, the next year, we dropped back down to reality. This year
the disappointing part was that we didn't get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel referred to the team's three-game losing streak at
midseason, with defeats to Indianapolis, Washington and Arizona, as
particularly disheartening. And he mentioned the team's rash of
late-season injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last four games, we had a lot of guys out,'' Fassel said.
``And we were playing four playoff teams, three of them on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, who had a 25-22-1 record with the Giants, also added:
``You are what you are in this league. And we were 7-9. But we came
down to the last game with a chance at the playoffs in each of the
last two years and I still have a winning record.''
</P>
<P>
   As for other changes on the team, Fassel acknowledged that he
and General Manager Ernie Accorsi have begun mapping a general
strategy for what players to keep and what free agents to pursue.
The Giants themselves have 20 restricted or unrestricted free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   And Fassel said he would spend more time during the off-season
talking with his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I'm going to work on is to spend a
tremendous amount of time with these guys to get our attitude
right,'' Fassel said. ``I'm going to start doing that now and keep
doing it on through training camp so we go into the season with the
right attitude.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
