<SLUG> BC-SCI-YOUNG-SMOKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1 OF 8 MIDDLE-SCHOOL STUDENTS HAS SMOKED OR CHEWED TOBACCO, SURVEY
FINDS
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first national survey on smoking among children 11 to 13
years of age has found that one of every eight has used tobacco in
some form, including unfiltered Asian cigarettes that are
considered more hazardous than American brands, the Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, another national study, of high school
students, recorded a decline in tobacco use since 1997. But a
spokesman for the agency said a drop had been expected after
tobacco companies raised cigarette prices to help pay for last
year's $206 billion lawsuit settlements and cautioned that the
decline might not be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the study of younger children _ sixth, seventh
and eighth graders _ were ``startlingly high,'' said Sherryl
Healton, president of the American Legacy Foundation, which
conducted the survey with the Centers for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are so young,'' Ms. Healton said. ``And combined
with what we know about young people of high school age, we can
expect that 5 million children under the age of 18 alive today in
the United States will die prematurely as a result of addiction to
cigarette smoking _ unless we can reverse the pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the foundation, set up with money for research and
education provided by the tobacco settlement, had set a goal of
lowering the percentage of young people who smoke by 2 percent a
year until 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said 9.2 percent of these 11- to-13-year-olds had
smoked cigarettes and 6.1 percent had smoked cigars within a month
of the time surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted in September and October, found that 2.4
percent of middle-school students were smoking bidis (pronounced
BEE-dees), cigarettes from India that are hand-rolled and flavored
with chocolate or cherry, and 1.9 percent were smoking kreteks
(KRAY-teks), clove-flavored cigarettes from Indonesia. The foreign
brands often require more puffing and thus pull more smoke into the
lungs than American cigarettes, said Dr. Terry Pechacek, associate
director for science in the Centers for Disease Control's office of
smoking and health.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 7,529 high school students, conducted last spring,
found that 28.4 percent reported using tobacco products in the
preceding month. In 1997, the last time the agency looked at high
school smoking, 36.4 percent of students said they had smoked in
the preceding month. At the time, teen-age smoking was on the rise.
The percentage of high school students who smoked was 34.8 percent
in 1995 and 27.5 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pechacek said one matter of particular concern in the study
of 11- to-13 year-olds was that ``in the last few years surveys
have been noting that African-Americans were smoking significantly
less than whites and Hispanics, and this was viewed as a
public-health success.'' But he said that in the middle-school
survey, children in all three groups were found to be smoking at
virtually the same rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8806 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-2000-HNS &LR;      01-27 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE CREDENTIALS, 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH, McCAIN APPEAL FOR CLEAN CAMPAIGN AMID SNIPES OVERBy CLAY ROBISON 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ The two front-running Republican presidential
candidates argued Thursday over who was more like Democratic
President Clinton as they pleaded for positive campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., are
jockeying for first place in Tuesday's New Hampshire primary. While
appealing to Granite State voters' desire for a clean campaign,
they also appealed to Republican primary voters' distaste for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeatedly tried to link McCain's tax proposal to the one
Clinton was laying out in his State of the Union address Thursday
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``When John said that he embraced the president's tax, or the
president embraced his tax plan, I think that shows a clear
difference between my view of tax cutting and his,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party ought to nominate someone who will be
able to have a stark difference, a clear difference on basic issues
with the Democratic nominee, not someone who will mimic the
Democratic nominee,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides later said they were considering running ads on the
subject in the Boston-New Hampshire media market.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed a $350 billion tax-cut plan Thursday. McCain,
with his $240 billion plan, and Bush, with a $483 billion plan,
have been arguing over their proposals for weeks, even while voters
say the humming economy dampens their desire for tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   If the Texas governor continues to compare him to the vice
president and Democratic presidential candidate, McCain said:
``Then I will keep my comment from (Wednesday's debate): He spins
like Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was endorsed by 1996 vice presidential nominee Jack
Kemp, who campaigned for the presidency with a flat-tax proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp said he still believes in a flat tax but that it would not
be possible to pass one at this time. Kemp called Bush's plan
``practical and realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   As they sniped over their conservative credentials, McCain
pleaded for a clean campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a town hall meeting in Plaistow, N.H., McCain said, ``I hope
that Governor Bush and all the others will maintain that level now
in these last few days. I challenge them not to get into a negative
campaign. I know you don't like negative campaigns in New
Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're interested in is our views on the issues, and
that's what I'll do,'' he told reporters before touring the Simplex
Technologies plant, which manufactures fiber optics cable in
Newington.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to another opponent, magazine mogul Steve Forbes, Bush
reacted angrily when one man asked him about Forbes' charges that
he broke his Texas tax pledge and that education has declined
during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell half the story in politics or you can tell the
whole story. I laid out a plan in my state of Texas that cut the
taxes by $1 billion,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that is exactly what happened,'' he maintained, although
few Texas voters actually saw a reduction in their taxes because of
a corresponding rise in many school districts' property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hope people do is run on their own record and not try
to tear people down,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
