<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-UNION-SCENE28-COX     01-27 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-SCENE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPEECH GENERATES CHEERS, BUT LITTLE PASSION
 &HT;    With UNION.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Out from the shadow of scandal but approaching the
valley of irrelevance, President Clinton stirred the usual
stick-it-to-'em standing ovations Thursday night, but not the
passions of past State of the Union addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats roared when Clinton boasted ``the state of our union
is the strongest it has ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans jumped to their feet when he added, ``As always, the
credit belongs to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Clinton's final such address, and everybody knew their
parts after two terms.
</P>
<P>
   There were empty seats on the House floor, even on the
Democratic side. Notably absent were all nine members of the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justices of the court had planned to attend,'' the court said
in a note to Congress. ``But travel changes and minor illnesses
have intervened.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who came heard a lot of words. The fidgeting seemed to be
not only for a conclusion to a long speech but also for the end of
a presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Come next January, Vice President Al Gore hopes to be at that
podium and Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., plans to be
standing behind him as speaker of the House. First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton wants to trade her gallery perch for a floor seat as
a Democratic senator from New York. Congressional Republicans are
ready be rid of Clinton because he outsmarted them so often, and
congressional Democrats are tired of their moral dilemma in
defending him.
</P>
<P>
   None of this impatient ambition inhibited the traditional
jack-in-the-box ovations. Democrats stood and cheered for a laundry
list of new and expanded federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans liked the notion of paying down the national debt
and loved it when Clinton misspoke and said, ``last year the vice
president launched a new effort to help make communities more
liberal.'' The word was ``liveable'' in the text.
</P>
<P>
   This choreographed exuberance is aimed at the television
audience, of course, with even Clinton's entrenched enemies not
wanting to come across as party-pooping sourpusses. Someday a
network should produce a VH1-style ``Pop-Up Video'' of a State of
the Union address with message bubbles revealing what the members
of Congress were really thinking while applauding.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton clearly relished these moments _ or hours _ in the
national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The State of the Union _ dubbed ``SOTU'' at the White House _ is
the president's ``favorite time of the year,'' says Michael
Waldman, Clinton's former top speechwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves the policy, the politics, the polling, the
showmanship and schmaltz,'' Waldman wrote in the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   His flair for the dramatic was illustrated when he looked toward
his wife, the Senate candidate, in the gallery and mouthed ``I love
you.'' Sitting on one side of Mrs. Clinton was their daughter,
Chelsea, and on the other was baseball home run king Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan began a tradition of introducing a hero in the
gallery in 1982 when he introduced Lenny Skutnik, who had jumped
into the icy Potomac River to save victims of a plane crash.
Clinton has expanded the practice, adding guests who personify his
political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Pat Brown, a 72-year-old retiree from Johnson
City, Tenn., said she was there ``to represent all of the many
older people in this country who are being hurt financially by the
cost of prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Another presidential guest was Tom Mauser, father of Columbine
High School shooting victim Daniel Mauser. He has taken a leave of
absence from his job with the Colorado Department of Transportation
to advocate gun-control legislation _ another Clinton priority and
a wedge issue with Republicans in the upcoming congressional
election.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
