<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GLENN-SPACE28-COX     01-27 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-SPACE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn, crew mates discuss mission
 &HT;    By Ginger Livingston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Some 14 months after NASA sent John Glenn back
to space, the public fascination continues just as strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 people showed up Thursday night at Natcher
Auditorium on the campus of the National Institutes of Health for a
symposium featuring Glenn and three of his crew mates discussing
their high-profile 1998 mission aboard space shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Another 300 waited outside the auditorium, which prompted
officials to add a second session. Videos were shown detailing some
of the experiments, the retrieval of a satellite that was launched
for a four-day study of the sun and how they lived on the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The results of Mission STS-95 are being presented over two days.
Glenn served as a test subject for 10 experiments studying space-
and age-related problems. He spent four nights in a wired-up sleep
suit, provided 17 blood samples and also swallowed a capsule
holding a tiny radio transmitter and temperature sensor.
</P>
<P>
   Those results were not to be released until today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to say it's encouraging to send other old
people into space,'' Glenn, 78, said when asked what he thought the
results might yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus we got our toe in the door on research into
osteoporosis,'' muscle atrophy and protein loss and other physical
problems associated with aging and space flights, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see more of the elderly go into space so that we
would have more of a database.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, the scientists behind the experiments
described the findings of tests on plants, proteins and tumor cells
performed by the former senator and his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The flight contained more scientific experiments _ 88 _ than any
previous shuttle mission, said NASA Associate Administrator Dr.
Arnauld Nicogossian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission was packed, really packed,'' he said as he opened
the scientific gathering. ``By one of those good fortunes we had,
all of the experiments worked except one.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA scientist Dennis Morrison described an experiment that
compressed a tumor-fighting drug into a special miniature balloon
and directing the drug into the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually on the right track,'' he said, explaining that
such a system could enable future cancer patients to avoid the side
effects of chemotherapy by receiving drugs only where tumor cells
have grown and not through their entire bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn did not attend the first day of scientific presentations.
But he said in a telephone interview that Morrison's experiment on
microencapsulation was one of the tests that he found most
fascinating during the nine-day mission in October and November
1998.
</P>
<P>
   NASA expanded its experiment itenerary after Glenn was added to
the crew, with the stated purpose of exploring the similarities
between what happens to humans in the zero-gravity environment of
space and what happens naturally on Earth during the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   He was 77 when he became the world's oldest spaceman.
</P>
<P>
   _ Information from The Associated Press is included in this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
