u a BC-COCHRAN-LAWYER-FIRM-3     01-27 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCHRAN-LAWYER-FIRM-355&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TV, COCHRAN PITCHES HIS 63-LAWYER PERSONAL INJURY FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Ga., Ill., Ala.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once again, the familiar visage of Johnnie L. Cochran
Jr. is appearing on television screens here. But this time, the
lawyer who made his name defending O.J. Simpson is offering himself
as the champion of the common man, not the lawyer of the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest misconception anyone can have about me is that all
of my clients are rich and famous,'' Cochran intones in a new
television commercial. ``I'm committed to helping everyday folks
get justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad is for the Cochran Firm, which last month became the
largest personal injury law firm in the nation. The venture merges
Cochran's long-running personal injury practice in Los Angeles with
others in New York, Atlanta, Alabama and, soon, Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of contemplating retirement at age 62, the a
multimillionaire Cochran is starting several new ventures: in
addition to practicing law, he makes many paid speeches, and
recently took on another new enterprise, Johnnie Cochran Sports
Management.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts and other personal injury lawyers question how,
with an already mushrooming client list of police misconduct
victims and celebrities, Cochran can effectively represent even
more people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he's going to do it,'' said Anthony Gentile,
a personal injury lawyer who has practiced in New York since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on one's perspective, the new national firm could be
derided as a manipulative move by a celebrity lawyer or an attempt
to help average Americans by a skilled litigator. Avaricious or
altruistic, Cochran's new venture takes the melding of lawyering
and celebrity to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran's firm has 63 lawyers and already represents more than
1,000 clients nationwide. While not all his cases are well
publicized, in New York alone, his clients include Abner Louima,
the police torture victim; the rap impresario Sean Combs and the
family of Thomas Pizzuto, who died last January after he was beaten
by guards at the Nassau County jail. He also represents two men,
one black and one Hispanic, who were shot at by state troopers on
the New Jersey Turnpike in April 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some signs of strain have emerged. Last year the family of
Amadou Diallo, the unarmed African immigrant killed by the police
in the Bronx in February, replaced Cochran and his Simpson trial
co-counsels, Peter Neufeld and Barry Scheck, amid reports that the
family felt the three lawyers were paying too little attention to
their case. And some civil rights lawyers in New York have accused
Cochran of using his fame to dazzle clients and muscle his way into
their cases, but then doing little legal heavy lifting himself.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran, in New York last week, said he would be able to take on
additional clients, and that inattention was not the issue in the
Diallo case. He denied muscling into other lawyers' cases. ``That's
not my style,'' he said. ``We have enough business. We turn down
more cases than we take.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the new firm the ``logical next step'' in his career.
While best known for his defense of O.J. Simpson in 1995, Cochran
has devoted nearly all his career to personal injury work. His
goal, he said, is to extend skilled lawyering to the disfranchised,
particularly minorities. ``The client base is diverse, but we want
to make it more so,'' he said, referring to the people already
represented by his personal injury firm.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's new television ads clearly play on the hope of the
common man's being represented by an anything-but-common lawyer.
``What's the least-known fact about America's best-known
attorney?'' an announcer asks in a second ad, which shows Cochran
in a courthouse and meeting with partners and clients. The answer:
``That Johnnie Cochran built his reputation winning big personal
injury cases for the little guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcer adds, ``You don't have to be high profile to get
high quality representation'' and offers an 800 number for callers
with ``serious personal injury cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is little chance those callers will end up having
Cochran personally handling their cases, legal experts said. While
tens of thousands of personal injury cases are filed each year in
New York, most result in settlements of several thousand dollars.
Those cases will be handled by junior lawyers, they predicted,
while Cochran will be involved only in the handful of potentially
multimillion-dollar cases that emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The new firm, like nearly all personal injury firms, will charge
its clients a percentage of any rewards they receive, according to
Cochran's partners.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran cited his results to show his effectiveness. Last year,
he won a $3 million settlement for the family of Junious Roberts,
an unarmed black man shot dead by the police in suburban Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said the new firm would primarily handle standard
personal injury cases, including medical malpractice and product
liability cases. ``You want to be altruistic,'' he said. ``But you
have to do things that make money for the firm.'' He declined to
comment on how much he would earn.
</P>
<P>
   For the few clients lucky enough to be personally represented by
Cochran, the new venture could be a boon.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with Cochran's reputation for swaying juries and
generating press attention, some of the businesses and local
governments being sued may opt to settle. But for most people
spurred to the phone by Cochran's new ads, he is likely to remain a
distant celebrity on the television screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take every case because sometimes you end up
spreading yourself too thin,'' Cochran said, adding. ``I have to
pick and choose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
