<SLUG> BC-OIL-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DELAYS ITS DECISION ON AMOCO-ARCO MERGER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Alaska)   (rk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government decided Thursday to postpone
a decision on whether to block the proposed $30 billion merger of
BP Amoco and Atlantic Richfield after the companies made a new
offer to divest themselves of further assets, people involved in
the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission had been set to approve a staff
recommendation to seek a court order blocking the deal at a hearing
of the commissioners on Friday morning. But after a new proposal
was advanced Thursday by Sir John Browne, the chief executive of BP
Amoco, in a conversation with Robert Pitofsky, the chairman of the
Trade Commission, the agency agreed to postpone the meeting until
Monday to spend a few days analyzing and considering it. Further
discussions between the two companies and government officials also
remain possible.
</P>
<P>
   While the agency's decision represented the first significant
progress for the companies in their protracted discussions with
government officials, people involved in the talks said that the
two sides still appeared to be far apart, and that it would be
inaccurate to characterize the day's events as serious
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the pause announced Thursday gave company
executives some hope that they might be able to avoid a courtroom
confrontation. The companies have given the agency until Feb. 3 to
decide whether to approve the deal, although executives have the
authority to extend that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, staff officials at the agency recommended
blocking the deal, raising concerns that the proposed merger could
undermine competition and lead to higher gasoline prices on the
West Coast. While a move by the FTC to block a corporate merger
often has the effect of killing the deal, executives at the two oil
companies have asserted that they have a strong legal case and that
they will not abandon the merger.
</P>
<P>
   If the case goes to court, a central issue will be the
relationship between the companies' oil production in Alaska and
gasoline prices in California and other states on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies combined produce about 70 percent of the 1.1
million barrels in Alaska each day, and under an agreement reached
with Alaska authorities, have agreed to reduce their combined
ownership to about 55 percent. Government officials have expressed
concerns to the companies that their control over Alaska production
could lead to higher prices on the West Coast, which has among the
highest gasoline prices in the nation and gets most of its oil from
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives say they are puzzled by the government's
opposition because there are no substantial retail or refinery
overlaps of the two companies. The executives and other analysts
also maintain that prices in California are not set by Alaska
production but by world crude prices, and that the West Coast has
higher prices because of certain peculiarities of that market. For
instance, California has higher state taxes and requires
cleaner-burning, and thus more expensive, types of gasoline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0492 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-FAULK28-COX     01-27 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-FAULK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Versatility, vision drive Rams' Faulk
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The subject is St. Louis Rams tailback Marshall Faulk,
and his playing style is an endless stream of adjectives _
exciting, elusive and electrifying _ just to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   From running to catching to blocking, Faulk does it all. The
5-foot-10, 211-pounder set an NFL record for total yards from
scrimmage with 2,429 _ 1,381 rushing and 1,048 receiving _ this
season. So he's two great players in one.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he's headed to his fourth Pro Bowl in six seasons.
That's why the Rams (15-3) have reached Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   What makes him unique? Is it his blend of speed, strength and
desire that leaves defenders in his wake? Yeah, it's all that _ and
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision,'' Faulk said. ``I can see everything.''
</P>
<P>
   All great teams are well-balanced offensively and Faulk is the
perfect complement to quarterback Kurt Warner and fleet wide
receivers Isaac Bruce, Torry Holt and Az-Zahir Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   But don't ask Faulk to compare his style with anyone else's. He
won't budge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't assessed my style,'' he said. ``I don't know how to
describe it. I just try to make people miss. That's all I think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams pulled off the greatest coup of the 1999 offseason when
they traded their second- and fifth-round draft choices to
Indianapolis for Faulk, whom the Colts grabbed with the second
overall pick in '94 _ behind Dan ``Big Daddy'' Wilkinson of the
Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The trade allowed the Colts to draft tailback Edgerrin James,
who led the NFL in rushing (1,553) as a rookie this season, but
Faulk's presence in St. Louis solidified the Rams' devastating
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marshall is such a threat as a receiver and as a runner that
you need to account for him whether he's getting the ball or not,''
Rams offensive coordinator Mike Martz said. ``One of the big values
of having Marshall in there is that it takes pressure away from the
wide receivers and tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system is conducive to a guy like him because of his
versatility. We can move him around. He'll run routes with the same
speed and crispness of a wide receiver. He doesn't limit you in any
way. He's the consummate back.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates praise Faulk for his ability to make things happen. He
raises everyone's level around him because he knows each player's
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great back and a smart back,'' offensive tackle Orlando
Pace said. ``I think he reads the linebackers the best I've seen.
If you give him a little crack, he'll make it happen and probably
take it to the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulk grew up in a housing project in New Orleans, then exploded
onto the national scene as an All-American at San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' he said about his childhood. ``Not always did
I walk a straight line. I am not going to say that I am an angel,
but I did make some right decisions along the way that got me where
I am today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things I had to go through makes dealing with
football easy because football is a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked his favorite memory growing up, Faulk just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have one, but it's about to happen, though,''
he said. ``This weekend, I'm going to have some favorite Super Bowl
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
