<SLUG> BC-NY-TRIAL-CAMERAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING ONE TRIAL TO TV LEADS TO REQUESTS FOR MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the two days since an Albany judge approved the
televising of the trial of four police officers charged with
murdering Amadou Diallo, news organizations have asked judges
around the state to open their court proceedings to cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The results so far have been mixed. An Albany judge agreed to
allow cameras to cover the final day of a trial there on Wednesday,
but Thursday, a Manhattan judge rejected a request to allow cameras
at the coming trial of Sante and Kenneth Kimes, the mother and son
charged with murder, conspiracy and fraud in the disappearance in
July 1998 of Irene Silverman, an Upper East Side millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   News organizations also asked a judge in Queens for permission
to use cameras at a hearing for Carmine Agnello, the son-in-law of
the imprisoned mob boss John J. Gotti, but the judge ruled the
issue moot because Agnello did not appear in court Thursday. In
Rochester, a judge had yet to decide on whether to allow cameras
into a murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts predict that the spate of requests and divergent
court decisions will continue until the Court of Appeals, the
state's highest court, rules on the issue or the state Legislature
enacts a law legalizing cameras in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, state Sen. James J. Lack, R-Suffolk County, who is
the chairman of the Judiciary Committee, said he would introduce a
bill to open up courtrooms across the state to cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, the lawyer who successfully argued for the opening
of the Diallo trial to cameras, said that any speedy resolution of
the issue was unlikely. It can take months, or years, for an issue
to wind its way through New York's appellate courts until it is
heard by the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising that there are applications being made in
different courts with difficult rulings being handed down,'' he
said. ``The ruling in the Diallo case was the beginning of the end
of the ban on cameras in New York. The end can only come with a
ruling with the New York Court of Appeals.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the state Legislature declined to extend a 10-year
experiment allowing cameras in courtrooms. Opponents cited what
they called the circuslike atmosphere of the O.J. Simpson murder
trial in Los Angeles, saying it was an example of the harmful
effects that cameras could have in courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Since the decision on Tuesday in the Diallo case, Gov. George
Pataki; the Senate majority leader, Joseph L. Bruno; and the
Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, have all expressed support for a
new law that would authorize cameras in courtrooms. But whether the
two sides can agree on legislation remains to be seen. Pat Lynch,
Silver's spokeswoman, said he would support only measures that
include provisions that protect the identities of jurors and rape
victims, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Legislature or the state Court of Appeals acts, a
confusing series of court decisions is likely to continue. In
Manhattan Thursday, Justice Rena K. Uviller of state Supreme Court
denied a request from defense lawyers, The New York Post and New
York television station WNYW to allow still and video cameras to
cover the Kimeses' trial, which began Thursday with jury selection.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Uviller said that the Diallo ruling was an exception because
a court order to move the case from the Bronx to Albany had caused
``tremendous community concern'' about the fairness of the
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   But in a ruling on Wednesday, Acting Justice Dan Lamont of state
Supreme Court in Albany allowed local television cameras to cover
the trial of a young woman accused of killing her child. In a
decision that reaches the opposite conclusion of Ms. Uviller's,
Lamont said that the Diallo ruling did allow him to grant cameras
access to a local trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
