<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-UNION-HNS &LR;      01-27 1555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UNION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS SWEEPING PROPOSALS IN FINAL STATE OF THE UNION
ADDRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton offered the nation a sweeping
farewell agenda Thursday, using his last State of the Union address
to push unfinished priorities on health care, education and gun
control that Republicans have opposed.
</P>
<P>
   But while trying to generate momentum for a legislative agenda
in his final year to help seal his legacy, Clinton also used his
message to help boost the 2000 presidential campaign of Vice
President Al Gore, whose election-year proposals are virtually
identical to initiatives Clinton outlined before a joint Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton boasted of America's unprecedented
prosperity and challenged the Republican-controlled Congress to
join him in even greater ``goals for our country'' that would help
ensure the nation's economic well being and its national security.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking of the work ``yet to be done,'' Clinton asked the
Republicans to join in a plan to pay off the nation's public debt
of $3.7 trillion by 2013 while providing a $350 billion tax cut
over 10 years and investing more than $110 billion in new funding
to provide health care insurance for the poor and prescription drug
benefits for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton asked Congress to support his call for
nearly $5 billion in new education spending to expand the Head
Start program for needy children, increase funding for afterschool
and summer programs, and to help reduce class size by building more
schools and hiring more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fortunate to be alive at this time in history. Never
before has our nation enjoyed so much prosperity and social
progress with so little internal crisis or so few external threats.
Never before have we had such a blessed opportunity _ and therefore
such a profound obligation _ to build the more perfect union of our
founders' dreams,'' Clinton said, citing the nation's economic
strength as evidence that the government can now afford to and
should do more to help its neediest citizens.
</P>
<P>
   But while urging more spending and targeted tax relief, Clinton
stressed the importance of keeping to ``the path of fiscal
discipline that got us here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must make these investments and tax cuts in the context of
a balanced budget that strengthens and extends the life of Social
Security and Medicare and pays down the national debt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While many of Clinton proposals were re-submissions of previous
initiatives to which he has attached a higher price tag, some were
new and took members by surprise, including a call for
gun-licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, every handgun buyer would need a valid,
state-issued photo license indicating that he or she had passed a
background check and gun safety class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all seen what happens when guns fall into the wrong
hands,'' Clinton said, noting the tragedy last year at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke, Tom Mauser, the father of slain Columbine
student Daniel Mauser, listened from the gallery of the House
chamber where he sat next to first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
Teen gunmen killed more than a dozen people at the Colorado high
school his son attended.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Clinton's licensing proposal, which would
require congressional approval, is aimed at reducing gun violence,
accidental shootings, and keeping guns out of the hands of
criminals and the underaged.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposals were predictably hailed by Democrats, who
embraced as their own the themes of community, responsibility and
opportunity. The Democrats are hoping to use popular issues such as
health care, prescription drug benefits and paying down the debt to
their advantage as they seek to retake control of Congress in this
year's elections.``
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has outlined an agenda that will preserve our
prosperity and take advantage of a historic opportunity to invest
in America's future,'' said Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, who heads
the House Democratic caucus. He added that the priorities outlined
in Clinton's speech would make ``a difference in the lives of
everyday Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were skeptical of Clinton's proposals, calling his
tax cut package too small and his spending proposals too costly.
But at the same time, Republicans leaders spent much of the day
ahead of Clinton's speech promoting their own health care and debt
relief initiatives, which indicated a willingness to compromise
with the president later if the congressional races tighten up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we enacted all the new programs the president has talked
about, we'd spend just about the entire surplus on bigger and more
expensive government,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert acknowledged, however, that there may be a number of
areas, including education, where Republicans and Clinton have more
agreements this year than differences.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other Republican leaders cautioned their colleagues not
to provide Clinton with any help in trying to secure a legacy that
seeks to dismiss his impeachment for the Monica Lewinsky affair or
other scandals that have marred his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton apparently intends these final months in
office to be spent buffing his image for history,'' Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, said, adding that most of Clinton proposals should
be ``discreetly discarded'' by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm suggested the country would be better off if Congress and
the president did little between now and election day to give the
American people time to ``decide the direction of the country with
their votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took the podium in the House chamber for his eighth and
final State of the Union address in remarkably better spirits than
he was last year when he delivered his annual address to a joint
session of Congress as his impeachment trial was about to begin in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances surrounding his appearance Thursday night were
also stunningly different from when he delivered his first State of
the Union speech in 1993. The nation was still saddled then with a
budget deficit of more than $260 billion, and there was little
inkling that the current economic expansion would prove to be the
longest-running in the nation's history and would lead to
projections of non-Social Security surpluses totaling nearly $2
trillion by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   He pronounced Thursday to a standing ovation that ``the state of
our union is the strongest it has ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We begin the new century with over 20 million new jobs. The
fastest economic growth in more than 30 years. The lowest
unemployment rates in 30 years. The lowest poverty rates in 20
years. The lowest African-American and Hispanic unemployment rates
on record. The first back-to-back surpluses in 42 years,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton also offered a host of initiatives aimed
at improving the general well-being of Americans. Republicans
criticized most of them, saying the Clinton would use up all of the
future surpluses trying to provide ``something for everyone''
regardless of need.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his tax cut and health care initiatives, Clinton
called for passage of a consumer protection ``patients' bill of
rights,'' an increase in the minimum wage and campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   But his tax cut and health care plans appeared to be at the
heart of his legislative wish list. Some of the more important
provisions included phasing out the marriage tax penalty; up to
$10,000 in tax credits per family to cover college tuitions; a
$3,000 annual credit to help cover the cost of long-term care; and
expansion of the earned income tax credit for the working poor by
$21 billion. His tax cut initiative also included incentives to
spur more charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would cost $350 billion over 10 years. But it
also calls for closing tax loopholes and shelters that could reduce
the cost by $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other proposals included:
</P>
<P>
   _ A prescription drug benefit that could cost as much as $50
billion over the next 10 years to help elderly Medicare patients.
``We cannot allow one more year to pass without providing this
life-line to seniors to help them afford prescription drugs,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   _ A plan that would expand the Children's Health Insurance
Program by $110 billion to cover not only poor children, but their
parents. If approved by Congress, it would amount to the largest
increase in government-funded health care coverage in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ An initiative that would help people 55 and older buy Medicare
coverage by providing them with a 25 percent tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton focused his remarks primarily on domestic policy issues.
But he did call on Congress to approve normal trade relations with
China and to increase foreign aid to Colombia by $1.6 billion to
help in the fight against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   He also unveiled a plan to help developing countries in Africa
and elsewhere fight malaria, AIDS and other diseases by providing
$1 billion in tax incentives for drug companies to develop new
vaccines and treatments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
