<HEADER>
A8820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-FORUM-NYT     01-27 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-FORUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVOS FORUM OPENS WITH QUALIFIED EXUBERANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVOS, Switzerland _ A year ago, when the very rich and the very
powerful gathered by the ski slopes of this Swiss resort for the
annual hyper-schmooze called the World Economic Forum, their
gathering fell under the shadow of the financial damage in Russia
and Latin America and the lingering economic weakness in much of
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   This year, at least in the opening hours, it was feel-good time.
</P>
<P>
   A survey released by PricewaterhouseCoopers Thursday showed that
1,020 chief executives who control companies with stock worth
billions were overwhelmingly optimistic about Internet-driven
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, the Goldman, Sachs market strategist, said
soaring U.S. stock prices were not overvalued and the American
economy would grow, too.
</P>
<P>
   As if to punctuate the initial exuberance of the conference, the
Boston Philharmonic's conductor, Benjamin Zander, led participants
in a rousing rendition of Beethoven's ``Ode to Joy.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there was a looming issue to tinge the crisp, blue skies
of Davos a darker shade, it was this: how will the haves, who
benefit most from the fast-moving era of technological advance,
continue to do so without courting the backlash of the have-nots _
evident at the World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   This is not the kind of gathering where people come expecting to
frame stirring resolutions. Rather, said one participant, the
investment banker Udayan Bose of Lazard India Ltd., it is a place
where people meet the people who will be making the deals of
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But with a heavy lineup of politicians _ including Bill Clinton,
the first American president to attend, and Prime Minister Tony
Blair of Britain _ plus a strong sprinkling of labor leaders and
rights activists invited to leaven the capitalist mix, the debate
surrounding globalization's future will impinge on many among the
300 politicians, 1,200 business leaders and 400 academics, writers
and others gathered here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot forget that we are entering this new age with a lot
of unfinished business from the 20th century,'' said Klaus Schwab,
the Swiss academic who founded the economic forum as a foundation
30 years ago and has since turned it into one of the world's most
glittery gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, such are the worries about Seattle-style protests that
the Swiss Army has been deployed in the pine-clad valley
surrounding Davos and American helicopters have been seen in the
skies above. ``U.S. pilots practice for C-Day,'' said the tabloid
Blick, referring to Clinton's arrival Saturday for a six-hour
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly seeking to stir opposition to the president's visit,
anonymous hoaxers sent a forged letter to homes and hotels saying a
curfew would be imposed during that time, Swiss television reported
Wednesday night. A few days ago, a projectile, described variously
as a firecracker or gasoline bomb, was thrown at the bunker-like
center where the forum meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization can be a process which can be of benefit to
everybody,'' Schwab said. ``So what we have to see here is how we
can create the policies and actions in order to make sure that
there are no losers of this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Losers are not much in evidence here. Only the wealthiest and
most successful corporations are invited; their executives pay more
than $20,000 to attend; and the guest list this year includes such
luminaries of the markets and the Internet era as Steve Case of
America Online, Bill Gates of Microsoft and the financier George
Soros.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the draw of this gathering, moreover, that the American
delegation includes not only the president but Commerce Secretary
William M. Daley, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Treasury
Secretary Lawrence H. Summers, and the White House trade
representative, Charlene Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence has reinforced a trend perceived by other
participants in the event, once dominated by Europeans, that it has
become a forum reflecting the political, technological and economic
weight of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the central theme this year is supposed to be the
human impact of Internet technology and biotechnology. Thursday's
survey from PricewaterhouseCoopers, for instance, said 64 percent
of chief executives who responded were ``somewhat optimistic''
about their companies' prospects for the next three years and 27
percent were ``extremely optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   But here, too, social perspectives intruded: 50 percent said
they expected Internet-based business to widen the gap between the
world's rich and poor. while 38 percent said the gap would
narrow.Schwab urged that the Internet and biotechnology revolutions
become ``beneficial and acceptable to all.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a statement, labor leaders from Europe and the United
States _ including Bill Jordan, head of the International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions, and John J. Sweeney of the
AFL-CIO _ urged the elite here to ``commit themselves to work
toward universal social justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
