u k BC-EDIT-NYC-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      01-27 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYC-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR GIULIANI'S ELECTION-YEAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, Jan. 28: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An ebullient Mayor Rudolph Giuliani took the press and other
onlookers through an elaborate slide show of his new four-year
financial plan, missing no opportunity to congratulate himself for
saving New York City from the financial mess left by his
predecessors. He pointed with pride to this year's $2.2 billion
surplus and said his plan would keep spending growing in line with
inflation, cut taxes, avoid accounting gimmicks and reform the way
the city negotiates with unions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these contentions are fair. Others exaggerate. Over all,
the budget he offered is responsible but flawed, with elements
designed for election-year politics. The budget will surely
irritate the unions. The city council, though objecting to some of
the details, will embrace many of the tax cuts and other major
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's big news Thursday was to propose to eliminate the 14
percent personal income tax surcharge starting as early as this
year. He also called for cutting a number of business taxes, for a
total tax cut that would reach $2 billion a year by 2004. The plan
calls for spending more on Medicaid by enrolling more eligible
families.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial provision proposed to replace
across-the-board pay increases with a system of merit pay. The idea
would be to offer substantial wage increases to good workers and no
increases to poor workers. Details of the merit pay plan, including
who would control the grading system, would be left to collective
bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is both unrealistic and nakedly political, designed
to appeal to conservatives and union-bashers in the upcoming
senatorial campaign. The unions will not accept the proposal, and
it is disruptive to introduce it into labor negotiations when the
mayor is approaching the end of his time in office one way or
another. It would be far better for him, in dealing with
public-employee unions, to use wage increases to push for general
productivity gains, as he has in the past, instead of singling out
a minority of workers for merit raises.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also wants workers to pick up some of their medical
costs, as is common in private industry. Additionally, he wants the
board of education, in return for more money, to turn over some of
the city's worst-performing schools and some summer programs to
private contractors, and has set aside $6 million for a school
voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   The budget's most serious flaw is that it leaves a long-term
financial imbalance largely in place. The mayor's own projections
show the city running deficits in excess of $2 billion by 2002. By
cutting taxes, the plan would make those deficits worse. It
proposes to use the current surplus to cover ordinary operating
expenses over the next two years _ another fiscally imprudent idea.
The surplus is temporary. Sound budget policy would use it to pay
off debt or create a ``rainy day'' fund to offset the revenue loss
from a future slide on Wall Street or an economic downturn. The
plan does little to bring the city's long-term spending in line
with expected revenues. The longer the imbalance is allowed to
fester, the steeper and harsher the eventual cuts will be.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts and tough stance toward unions will play well in
Giuliani's senatorial campaign. But however well the plan serves
the mayor's political ambitions, it will leave his successor with a
needlessly deep financial hole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
