<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RECKLESS-DRIVER-38     01-27 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RECKLESS-DRIVER-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CONFISCATE FIRST CAR UNDER RECKLESS DRIVING POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)   (bl)  
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn man accused of driving a Buick LeSabre at
117 miles per hour early Thursday became the first person to lose
his car under a new city policy aimed at confiscating the vehicles
of reckless drivers, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, identified by police as Peter Ruggeri, 38, of 112
Avenue T, was pulled over by two highway unit officers at 2:40 a.m.
as he sped west on the Belt Parkway near the Flatbush Avenue exit,
a stretch of roadway where the speed limit is 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   After Ruggeri's four-door 1988 LeSabre was pulled over, he was
charged with reckless endangerment, a felony punishable by seven
years in prison upon conviction, and reckless driving, a
misdemeanor, police said.
</P>
<P>
   He was also charged with driving while intoxicated, a
misdemeanor. Police said that they administered a Breathalyzer test
after detecting alcohol on his breath and that Ruggeri had a blood
alcohol level of 0.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, police were citing the case as a prime
example of why reckless drivers should face charges and the loss of
their cars, a policy that is closely modeled on the nearly year-old
city program of seizing the vehicles of drunken drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Ruggeri was pulled over about 100 yards from where a
reckless driving incident occurred Jan. 16 in which two young
people died when a Mercedes-Benz traveling at least 73 mph slammed
into the compact car in which they were riding.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kelleher, the first deputy police commissioner, called
Thursday's arrest ``a perfect example of what our aggressive
enforcement policy is all about, getting people off the highways
and taking their cars from them if they don't show the
responsibility to utilize them properly.'' He added, ``we did what
we thought was the correct thing in taking his vehicle away from
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruggeri remained in custody Thursday afternoon awaiting
arraignment. New York Department of Motor Vehicle records show that
he has one conviction for speeding in Brooklyn in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to records from the Department of Motor Vehicles in
Florida, where Ruggeri lived before moving to Brooklyn and where
his Buick was registered, he was charged twice with driving while
under the influence of alcohol and on separate occasions faced
speeding and other charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Word of the first arrest under the reckless driving crackdown
drew criticism from Norman Siegel, the executive director of the
New York Civil Liberties Union, who contends that the program is
unfair and not based on state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's fundamentally flawed, the initiative, because
you're supposed to have your day in court before the government can
punish you,'' Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Liberties Union has already filed suit on behalf of
drivers whose cars were seized as a result of the drunken driving
policy, but the program has withstood two court challenges. Siegel
said the reckless driving policy might be more vulnerable to a
legal challenge because arrests and car seizures in such cases _
for example when a driver has been spotted weaving in and out of
traffic _ are based on subjective observations by the police.
</P>
<P>
   The police, however, have countered that before arresting
drivers and confiscating cars, officers look for signs of
potentially lethal driving _ either three dangerous moves or
traveling at twice the speed limit. Police then later decide
whether to seek forfeiture of the car in a civil action, a course
they say they could take even if the driver is acquitted of the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher and other police officials marveled that no one was
hurt by Ruggeri on Thursday before he was pulled over. Although his
LeSabre is 12 years old, Kelleher said it had reached a speed far
above the safe level for a highway like the narrow and curvy Belt
Parkway. Officers followed Ruggeri's car, police said, clocking him
on their speedometer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember the Belt Parkway and other roads like
this were built many, many years ago,'' he said. ``They are not
meant to be traveled on at such speeds, with bumps and gaps and
such. Even if it was a flat road, which it is not, it would have
been dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
