<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-GEORGE28-CO     01-27 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-GEORGE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Somber memory, happy ending
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's the one story Eddie George has refused to talk
about this Super Bowl week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't discuss it,'' the Tennessee running back said politely
but uncomfortably as he was leaving an interview session for
Sunday's Super Bowl XXXIV match-up with the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   The week preceding the championship game is all about festivity,
grand expectation and crowning glory. It's a time to think of
reward, not loss, and it was one reason George wouldn't stray from
the warmth of the spotlight to what has become one of life's
darkest moments for so many other families . . . and almost his
own.
</P>
<P>
   Few NFL players have a tighter bond with a parent than the
former Heisman Trophy winner from Ohio State does with his mother.
After splitting up with her husband in 1981, Donna George raised
her two young children _ Eddie and his sister, Leslie _ on her own.
She worked as a model and, Thursday, she told of how she brought
both kids to fashion shoots and made them sit backstage doing their
homework as she worked the runway.
</P>
<P>
   She's the one who later packed her balking, begging, blubbering
15-year-old son into her aging orange Mustang and drove him from
their Philadelphia home to Fork Union Military Academy in Virginia
so he would get some discipline and higher goals in his life.
</P>
<P>
   And 15 years ago, she was the one who began a career as a TWA
flight attendant. It provided her with the financial means to keep
her son in that private prep school, a tenure that straightened out
his life, got him into Ohio State and gave him the building blocks
he's used to become one of the NFL's best young running backs.
</P>
<P>
   The story George stiff-arms back into the past happened in the
summer of 1996. Just two days before he was to sign his first pro
contract _ a five-year deal worth about $7 million _ his mom was
scheduled to work a July 17 flight from New York to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   TWA Flight 800.
</P>
<P>
   The jet that crashed into the Atlantic Ocean, killing everyone
on board.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Donna wasn't on board was because of that strong
bond with her son. After two months of arduous contract
negotiations, Lamont Smith, Eddie's agent, wanted Donna there when
her son signed the deal that would change their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Smith called Donna twice and each time she refused him, saying
she was scheduled to fly. He kept insisting, playing on how she
always had been the rudder on Eddie's ship and how now he needed
more direction than ever before. Finally Donna relented. Instead of
Paris, she would go to Texas for the signing.
</P>
<P>
   She was still in Philadelphia when a friend called and told her
to turn on CNN. Learning of the crash, she went numb. She had
several friends on the flight _ including flight attendant Paula
Carven, a single parent who was flying with her own 9-year-old son
_ and the memories haunted her.
</P>
<P>
   In a private moment Thursday, her son finally admitted the
memories unsettle him as well: ``I still thank God my mother was
kept safe. I just can't imagine . . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Smith can. He knows how close mother and son are and he knows
how sensitive Eddie George is. ``I think it would have destroyed
his career,'' Smith once told a Houston newspaper. ``I don't think
he would have played football again.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that had happened, the unlikely Titans almost certainly
would not be in the Super Bowl. In his first four pro seasons,
George has become one of the most prolific running backs in NFL
history.
</P>
<P>
   He was the NFL's Rookie of the Year in 1996 and, in each of the
three seasons since, he's been voted to the Pro Bowl. Coming into
this season, he'd rushed for 4,061 yards. This regular season he
had 1,304 rushing yards and 458 yards in pass catches, and has
added another 354 rushing yards in the Titans three postseason
wins.
</P>
<P>
   As much as what he's done on the field, he's been an equal force
off of it. ``One of the concerns I had going into this season was
that I thought we lacked leadership,'' said Tennessee coach Jeff
Fisher. ``Our group of guys would do anything for you, but we
needed someone to stick his head up above the clouds and take
charge. Eddie did it for us this year and it had profound impact,
especially on our young guys like Jevon Kearse.''
</P>
<P>
   When Walter Payton died this fall, George approached Fisher _
who had been one of Payton's Chicago Bears teammates _ and asked
the coach to talk to him about Sweetness. Fisher said he told him
that Payton ``always wanted to play the perfect game and live the
perfect life.'' It was a philosophy George soon adopted for his
own.
</P>
<P>
   During the playoffs, George has become the vocal leader on he
sidelines. Last Sunday, he gathered his teammates just before
kick-off and, mixing a scowl with a from-the-heart plea, he urged:
``Go out there, kick some (butt) and play like it's our day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans did and now they're in the Super Bowl. In the
process, Eddie George is working his way onto the NFL marquee long
reserved for elite backs like Terrell Davis, Emmitt Smith and Barry
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I stand among the rankings of the elite
backs,'' George said. ``But I know people are beginning to notice.
</P>
<P>
   Even Amin Bey, a 13-year-old Atlanta kid who won a Weekly Reader
essay contest about the Super Bowl. His prize was an exclusive
interview with George and Thursday morning he got it at the Titans'
Buckhead hotel.
</P>
<P>
   After a few prepared questions, Amin ad-libbed a final: ``I play
running back for my team. You got any pointers for me?''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans back nodded and told him to have fun. As the boy
turned to leave, George suddenly thought of something else and
called him back: ``And make the most of the breaks you're given in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie George still wouldn't get into that one story, but as you
listened, you sensed he was telling how it ended . . . for him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
