<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-UNION28-1STLD-COX     01-27 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION28-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CALLS ON NATION TO 'SET GREAT GOALS'
 &HT;    Eds: Adds quote in graf 5. Minor editing throughout.
 &HT;    With UNION-SCENE and UNION-GORE.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Challenging a prosperous nation to strengthen its
future by aiding its poor, President Clinton called Thursday for
$350 billion in tax breaks aimed at helping low-income families
gain a grubstake in the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of unprecedented wealth and budget surpluses, Clinton
said, the country can afford to help the millions of families still
struggling to get by, even as it commits to paying down the biggest
portion of the federal debt by 2013 and shoring up Social Security
and Medicare for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for a new slate of gun controls, including
the requirement that purchasers first pass a firearms safety course
before being issued a license to buy a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In his eighth and final State of the Union address before
Congress and a national television audience, Clinton cast the
occasional backward glance at his term in office, hoping to obscure
the pall of scandal lingering over his tenure spent presiding over
seven years of peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans,'' he declared with evident pride, ``the
state of our union is the strongest it has ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of his 90-minute speech, however, looked forward
aggressively. Clinton asked his countrymen to embrace a broad array
of goals unlikely to be met until long after he leaves the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight let us take our look long ahead, and set great goals
for our nation,'' said Clinton, speaking in the cavernous House
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``America again has the confidence to dream big dreams,''
Clinton said as Al Gore, his vice president and possible successor,
sat behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as our dreams outweigh our memories, America will be
forever young,'' Clinton said. ``That is our destiny, and this is
our moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning from national destiny to personal legacy, Clinton
portrayed his own time in office as a record of achievement
mirroring, even largely responsible for, the nation's broader
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthier, more influential and more secure than at any time in
its history, the country has traveled a richly blessed road,
Clinton said, since he first took office in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fortunate to be alive at this moment in history,'' said
Clinton. ``Never before has our nation enjoyed, at once, so much
prosperity and social progress with so little internal crisis and
so few external threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Not content simply to let the clock run out on his waning
presidency, though, Clinton dropped back and threw long. Calling
for ``a 21st century American Revolution,'' he admonished the
nation to adopt seven dozen separate goals and initiatives, from
improving elementary schools and preserving federal lands to
combating hate crimes at home and bringing peace to foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans immediately denounced Clinton's agenda
as a budget-busting approach that set the country on a course of
big government programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we enacted all the new programs the president has talked
about, we'd spend just about the entire surplus on bigger and more
expensive government,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said
before Clinton's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the past is any judge of today, it is going to be spending
after spending after spending, which proves my point,'' Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential front-runner, told
reporters in Nashua, N.H. ``If there is money left in Washington it
is going to be spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed and clearly enjoying himself, Clinton shrugged off such
sentiments Thursday night, leaving the political fights he knows
await him for another day.
</P>
<P>
   While he appeared engaged, Clinton's speech also lacked much of
the tension that invigorated his past two State of the Union
addresses, both given under the duress of a 15-month scandal over
his relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in the past, Clinton drew on a cast of Americans for
symbols of the triumphs and tragedies the nation has borne on his
watch.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the NATO air campaign he spearheaded last year
against Serb forces in Kosovo, Clinton led the Congress in a
standing ovation for U.S. Air Force Capt. John Cherrey, who was
awarded the Silver Star for courage in his efforts to rescue an
American pilot downed over Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also paid tribute to a grand old man of the Democratic
Party, his former Treasury secretary, Lloyd Bentsen. The Texan, who
suffered a stroke in 1998, struggled to raise his right hand in an
emotional response to Clinton's gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Rising to the issue of race relations, Clinton acknowledged the
contributions made by former Atlanta Braves slugger Hank Aaron, a
pioneer in African-American participation in professional sports,
who was seated at a place of honor directly to Mrs. Clinton's
right.
</P>
<P>
   And, in one of the most dramatic moments of the speech, Clinton
introduced Tom Mauser, whose son, Daniel, was one of 12 students
killed last April by a pair of armed teenagers at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a large lapel button with a photo of his late son,
Mauser rose as Clinton implored Congress to approve an ambitious,
and controversial, slate of new gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that his courage and wisdom will move this Congress to
make common-sense gun safety legislation the very next order of
business,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned limits on ammunition clip size, background checks
for sales at gun shows and child safety locks on handguns _ a group
of measures Clinton proposed, the Senate passed, and the House
killed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the ante on gun controls, Clinton also asked Congress to
require that handgun purchasers first pass a firearms safety course
and that states issue photo identification cards indicating whether
a potential purchaser had passed a background check.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton devoted much of Thursday night's speech to well-worn
themes: calls for increased spending on the nation's schools,
funding to put additional police on the beat and a so-called
patients' bill of rights, giving increased leverage to sick or
injured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Clinton's message, though, was a clear directive
for the country to dedicate a growing portion of its wealth to help
low-income Americans pay for child care, college tuition and health
care and save, like their higher-paid countrymen, for their
uncertain futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built a new economy,'' said Clinton, ticking off the
strengths of the country's commercial machinery set to kick out
more than $9.5 trillion in goods and services this year, and
spinning out record levels of tax revenues that congressional
analysts project will to generate up to $1.9 trillion in federal
budget surpluses over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``To 21st century America,'' said Clinton, ``let us pledge that
every child will begin school ready to learn and graduate, ready to
succeed. Every family will be able to succeed at home and at work,
and no child will be raised in poverty,'' an admonition that drew
one of many standing ovations during a speech lasting more than an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Clinton laid out an extensive package of
targeted tax cut proposals, the details of which will be contained
in the 2001 budget recommendations he submits to Congress on Feb.
7.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8957 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-HNS &LR;      01-27 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LEWINSKY, NO SCANDAL: CLINTON PUSHES AMBITIOUS AGENDA IN THIS
ADDRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What a difference a year, or two, can make for the
state of the union.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton last addressed Congress a year ago, the
federal government was working with its first budget surplus in
three decades. And the president had been impeached and was on
trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, balancing the federal budget was only a
possibility. And Clinton had just wagged his finger at the
television cameras and denied having sex with a White House intern,
a claim he later acknowledged was a lie.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton stepped to the rostrum in the House of
Representatives for the eighth and probably final time, delivering
a State of the Union message that lays out an ambitious agenda for
his final months in office.
</P>
<P>
   The president used the nationally televised forum to signal,
once again, that he intends to remain an activist president. He
urged congressional action on his unfinished priorities and a raft
of new proposals. Many of Clinton's new programs are designed to
help low-income Americans, reflecting Clinton's emphasis on
spreading the benefits of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before have we had such a blessed opportunity _ and
therefore, such a profound obligation _ to build the more perfect
union of our founders' dreams,'' Clinton said, borrowing liberally
from the preamble of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lengthy speech carried the unspoken message that his
vision for the nation and its booming economy can best be carried
on by the man television viewers saw perched directly over his
right shoulder, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As titular head of the Senate, Gore sat just behind Clinton and
next to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. For millions watching
from home, there was a visual link between candidate Gore and his
president, whose policy announcements in recent weeks mesh neatly
with Gore's campaign proposals.
</P>
<P>
   As the president described a surging economy, declining crime,
shrinking welfare rolls and U.S. efforts to bring peace to far
corners of the world, Gore led the applause. Clinton, whose legacy
would benefit from Gore's ascension to the White House, singled him
out for praise and credited him with several administration
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful for the opportunities the vice president and I
have had to work hard to protect the environment and finally to put
to rest the notion that you can't expand the economy while
protecting the environment,'' Clinton said in one of the five
references to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, many of them facing re-election campaigns this year,
already have put the president on notice that only a handful of
issues are likely to emerge. Republicans are working with only a
five-vote majority in the House, where Democrats see a chance to
take control, a formula that threatens partisan gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Americans ``will have to decide if we are watching a president
taking up the Republican Congress on our offer to work together or
is he simply trying to buy himself a legacy?'' said Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at the Brookings
Institution, said Republicans will ``insulate themselves'' from
charges of being a do-nothing Congress by offering their own
versions of proposals likely to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things will get done. They will tend to be relatively
modest, and the rather big things will not be done. And that's not
such a bad proposition,'' Hess said. ``A lot of these programs
should be filtered through another national election to get a
reading on what people viscerally feel about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the House and Senate already are proposing
a tax-cut larger than what Clinton wants, a package that would
provide relief for two-earner couples and college students.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to trump Clinton in two key areas of his agenda,
Republican congressional leaders recruited a former educator and a
surgeon to provide the televised GOP response to his State of the
Union speech and to tout their plans for education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Susan Collins, R-Maine, and Bill Frist, R-Tenn., also
promised that their party would work to pay off the $3.6 trillion
national debt in the next 15 years, build a missile defense system,
balance the budget and still cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a former college administrator, repeated the Republican
mantra that better education must come through more local control.
``The debate in Washington is not about money. It's about who makes
the decisions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, a heart-transplant surgeon, said Republicans would work
to reform Medicare and pass a patients' rights bill that makes
lawsuits against HMOs a last resort. At the same time, he cautioned
against additional federal spending or creation of new
bureaucracies. ``Mr. President, please no more red tape,'' Frist
said in the televised response.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from Republican reaction Thursday night was any mention
of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, which dominated discussion outside
the House chamber before and after Clinton's last two State of the
Union addresses.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton spoke a year ago, the effort to remove him was
still playing out in the Senate. The House had debated whether to
invite Clinton to speak about the State of the Union, an address
traditionally delivered when Congress returns from its holiday
recess each year.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Clinton spoke to the joint session only days
after reports of his White House trysts with Lewinsky, a former
intern half his age. It was the Lewinsky affair and Clinton's
effort to conceal it that prompted congressional Republicans to
impeach him in the House and put him on trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
