<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8960 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-1STLD-     01-27 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(1200)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STAKES CLAIM TO U.S. PROSPERITY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS throughout to update text, add details on proposals and
color from scene; no pickup.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Delivering his final address to Congress, President
Clinton boasted Thursday night that the state of the union had
never been better and proposed using some of the nation's wealth to
provide modest tax relief for lower- and middle-income Americans,
particularly married ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economic revolution has been matched by a revival of the
American spirit,'' Clinton said pumping his fists for emphasis.
``Crime down by 20 percent, to its lowest level in 25 years. Teen
births down seven years in a row and adoptions up by 30 percent.
Welfare rolls cut in half to their lowest levels in 30 years. My
fellow Americans, the state of our union is the strongest it has
ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton stepped to the rostrum, the House chamber was
crowded, as always, although the entire Supreme Court was
puzzlingly absent, some without any stated reason. But the drama of
his address a year ago, delivered on the eve of his impeachment
trial, was gone. Instead, Clinton's main adversary was the
calendar, which shows less than a year to go until his successor's
proposals are the ones that matter.
</P>
<P>
   With Vice President Al Gore seated behind his right shoulder and
Hillary Rodham Clinton in the balcony above, Clinton did much to
try to help their political fortunes and the effort of other
Democrats to take back the House from the Republicans who had
impeached him.
</P>
<P>
   So packed full of proposals was the speech that it lasted 89
minutes, breaking Clinton's record of 81 minutes, which he set in
1995's speech. The president also received more than 100 ovations,
far more than he has received in his seven previous State of the
Union addresses.
</P>
<P>
   In one applause-winning proposal, Clinton, as he has done so
often during his tenure, seized an issue dear to the Republicans
and made it his own. He announced a proposal to alleviate the parts
of the tax code that penalize married couples, forcing them to pay
higher rates than if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   That makes such a change likely, since Republicans on Capitol
Hill had previously said that ending the marriage penalty was one
of their principal goals this year and had appeared to have enough
Democratic backing to enact it even before Clinton embraced the
measure Thursday night. The proposal was one of a series of tax
cuts that aides said totaled $350 billion over 10 years, measured
against an estimated $2 trillion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise announcement held back until just before the
speech, Clinton urged federal legislation to require state licenses
for all handgun purchases, one of numerous proposals the president
borrowed from Gore. Saying that states now license hunters and
drivers, Clinton recommended similar photo identifications for
handgun buyers once they pass a background check and complete a
gun-safety course.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Clinton took credit for the extraordinary health
of the American economy _ and shared credit lavishly with Gore _
while warning that the prosperity not be squandered.
</P>
<P>
   But while last year's address was built around a pledge to save
Social Security before taking any other actions or cutting taxes,
this year, Clinton felt times were good enough to call for both tax
cuts, although modest ones, and more social spending.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, an area in which he hopes to be remembered,
Clinton urged lawmakers to give China most-favored-nation trade
status on a permanent basis, and he reiterated his view that
America must stay engaged in the world, especially with former
adversaries still struggling to enact democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in previous speeches, Clinton devoted far less time to
foreign policy and national security issues than to his domestic
agenda, quickly surveying America's role as a mediator in the
Middle East and Northern Ireland and as a defender of human rights
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the trend toward globalization was ``the central
reality of our time. He called for a new consensus on trade, urging
Congress to pass legislation easing trade barriers with African and
Caribbean nations and to approve the agreement his administration
reached with China last year to join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open markets and rules-based trade are the best engines we
know for raising living standards, reducing global poverty and
environmental destruction, and assuring the free flow of ideas,''
Clinton said. ``There is only one direction for America on trade:
We must go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Russia had been held back from its full potential by
economic turmoil and ``a cruel and self-defeating war in Chechnya''
but said the United States should help ``those Russians struggling
for a democratic, prosperous future.''
</P>
<P>
   The president vowed to protect vital computer systems from
cyberattacks and pledged to continue developing a national missile
defense system, although he repeated his previous assurances to
preserve the Antiballistic Missile treaty with Russia. He also
called for ``a constructive bipartisan dialogue'' on the
Comprehensive Test-Ban Treaty, which the Senate voted to reject
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the points he made were not new, but he did announce a
proposal to offer tax credits to pharmaceutical companies to speed
development of vaccines against malaria, tuberculosis and AIDS in
poorer nations. He also said his budget would include $150 million
to fight disease around the world.
</P>
<P>
   With his speech coming between this week's Iowa caucuses and the
New Hampshire primary on Feb. 1, Clinton unveiled a legislative
shopping list aimed to some degree at ensuring his relevance as the
country's attention shifts to the campaign. Time after time during
the speech, Democrats jumped to their feet in applause, while
Republicans responded to many proposals with silence.
</P>
<P>
   Election-year Congresses are notoriously unproductive ones, but
Thursday night Clinton advanced some proposals designed to win
congressional backing this year and other initiatives designed to
linger for the Democrats until well beyond Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are great goals, worthy of a great nation,'' Clinton
said in excerpts of the speech released in advance by the White
House. ``We will not reach them all this year. Not even in this
decade. But we will reach them. Let us remember that the first
American revolution was not won with a single shot. The continent
was not settled in a single year. The lesson of our history _ and
the lesson of the last seven years _ is that great goals are
reached step by step, building on our progress, always gaining
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   On education, Clinton borrowed heavily from Gore's campaign
platform, proposing $3 billion in new spending for the politically
popular Head Start program and new after-school initiatives, as
well as school construction and enhanced teacher pay. He reiterated
his $31 billion plan to make college more affordable through
enhanced federal grants and by making part of tuition tax
deductible. He has credited Mrs. Clinton with twisting him arm to
make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a 21st century revolution in education, guided by our
faith that every child can learn,'' he said. ``Because education is
more than ever key to our children's future, we must make sure that
all our children have that key. That means universal preschool and
after-school, the best trained teachers in every classroom, and
college opportunities for all our children.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some of the president's proposals have been suggested before but
have never gained traction in Congress. Clinton urged renewed
action on ``unfinished business,'' including hate-crimes
legislation, a minimum wage increase from $5.15 an hour, a bill of
rights to give patients more say with their health maintenance
organizations, and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mauser, the father of a teen-age boy killed last April at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., was one of the guests
invited to sit beside Mrs. Clinton in the balcony. The president's
speech pushed the gun-control measures that Congress failed to act
on last year, along with money to enhance the enforcement of
existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   The president's licensing proposal stands little chance of
passage this year, and raises constitutional issues, but it put
Clinton clearly in Gore's corner in the presidential campaign, in
which former Sen. Bill Bradley has touted his gun control proposals
as more effective than the vice president's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime in America has dropped for the past seven years _ the
longest decline on record, thanks to a national consensus we helped
to forge on community police, sensitive gun control and effective
prevention,'' the president said. ``But nobody believes America is
safe enough. So let's set a higher goal: Let's make America the
safest big country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's tax-relief ideas would supplement working
families' retirement savings, assist with child care expenses,
encourage charitable giving and make up to $10,000 of college
tuition tax deductible. In another helping hand, Clinton proposed
$21 billion to expand the earned income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of undoing the marriage penalty is always politically
popular. But the president's plan, which would be phased in over a
decade and would double the standard deduction for two-income
couples to twice the amount of a single filer's deduction, is more
limited than various Republican proposals. It would not benefit
couples who itemize on their returns.
</P>
<P>
   The president also proposed measures to encourage drug companies
to develop vaccines to combat AIDS and tuberculosis. He pushed
again for prescription-drug benefits under Medicare, one of a
handful of health care proposals. And he vowed to pay off the debt
by 2013 _ two years ahead of his previous predictions _ and resist
reckless spending that chips away at Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In another reach to Gore, the president talked about global
warming, an issue that he has said the vice president often brings
up with him. The president proposed giving tax incentives to
businesses for the production of clean energy and to families that
buy energy-saving appliances, automobiles and homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fail to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases, deadly
waves and droughts will become more frequent, coastal areas will be
flooded, economies disrupted,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing one of his biggest legislative defeats last year,
Clinton called for a ``bipartisan dialogue'' on the comprehensive
test ban treaty, conciliatory language indicating that he did not
intend to push the matter again. He stressed the importance of
engaging countries like China and Russia, which still maintains a
nuclear-missile arsenal. And he addressed the dangers of biological
warfare and ``cyberterrorism,'' without offering any specific
solutions to those dangers.
</P>
<P>
   One facet of Clinton's vision of a ``new America'' entails
closing what he has called the ``digital divide.'' He renewed his
requests for government aid to help poor people gain access to
computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In length and breadth, the speech reflected Clinton's basically
centrist political instincts, the advice of many people in the
White House and on Capitol Hill _ and the president's desire to
savor his last big moment in the spotlight before the nation's
attention turns inevitably to the next president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
