<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0506 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-VOICES-NYT &LR;      01-27 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY WATCHING A SPEECH STILL SEES SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOUND BROOK, N.J. _ Al Gomolka thinks President Clinton has done
a good job managing the economy and gave him credit in foreign
affairs, for requiring background checks for gun purchases and for
having a strong foreign policy. But he cannot buy the president's
support for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Shelley Gomolka, agreed with the president on equal
rights issues, particularly for women and for abortion rights, and
she was willing to admit that the Clinton administration has done a
good job managing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Gomolkas let their two older boys stay up a little later
than usual Thursday night to watch Clinton's final State of the
Union address.
</P>
<P>
   The couple often agreed with the president, but their views of
the president had been obscured by the president's moral scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``His moral character is just pitiful,'' said Mrs. Gomolka, 44,
a part-time landscape horticulturalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit that economic issues aren't too bad,'' she
said, ``and I agree with him on women's rights, but it bothers me
that so many people say `Well, he did okay' and then vote for
him.'' The couple has three boys, Joshua, Jacob and Isaac.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton has started thinking about how American families will
remember him, he could start with the Gomolkas.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, they expressed much of the unspoken mix of often
contradictory feelings and beliefs about politics and public
policy.
</P>
<P>
   They are both lifelong Democrats but voted for Ronald Reagan
twice, for Ross Perot in 1992 and for Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gomolka said he believes he is ``on the conservative side,'' but
plans to vote for Bill Bradley, who is considered a liberal, if
Bradley wins the Democratic presidential nomination, because of his
tenure as a U.S. senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He strongly believes in the right to own firearms, but he nodded
approvingly when the president spoke of the success of the Brady
Bill gun control measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brady law was good,'' Gomolka said. ``It may bother the
criminals but to the person who just wants a recreational gun it's
not going to bother them how long it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The president is charismatic, they agreed, and persuasive, yet
his words Thursday were often discounted because of his record of
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it all sounds great, but it's just hard to believe
him,'' Mrs. Gomolka said, interrupting herself when the president
stopped to acknowledge his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh puh-leez, look at him smile,'' Mrs. Gomolka said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all comes down to truthfulness, and I have to ask, where
does fidelity come into all this?'' she said. ``It all just comes
down to credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   As the president ticked off his agenda, the bread-and-butter
economic issues hit home in the Gomolka household.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are solidly middle-class, with excellent medical
coverage and a generous pension for Gomolka, they are worried about
money and wish for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about helping low-income people but if she doesn't
work for two days, we're living paycheck to paycheck,'' Gomolka
said.
</P>
<P>
   And when the president urged a law to guarantee equal pay for
women, Gomolka picked up: his sister, Susie, works at one of New
Jersey's big pharmaceutical companies and often complains of
earning less than men in equal positions.
</P>
<P>
   Tax credits for college tuition also won praise from the couple,
but they were also concerned that, however bright the president's
promises, they might never become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all sounds good but I'd like to see it in writing,''
Gomolka said. ``It doesn't matter how good it sounds if he is not
going to be around to make it happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
