<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' HEAD COACH FOCUSES ON STAFF OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dave Campo spent his first day on the job as the
Cowboys' head coach in discussions about his staff.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-kept secrets around Valley Ranch these days involve
the hiring of Jack Reilly as offensive coordinator and the
promotion of secondary coach Mike Zimmer to defensive coordinator,
announcements that more than likely will come early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, New England's quarterbacks coach the past two seasons
after a one-year stint with the Cowboys in a similar capacity in
1997, has spent this week at the Cowboys' offices meeting with
owner Jerry Jones, and now Campo.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, 54, will bring in the Norv Turner/Ernie Zampese offense
that Troy Aikman has enjoyed his greatest success while winning
three Super Bowls during the 1990s. Zampese is expected to be used
in some advisory capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Two characteristics of this offense are spreading the field and
throwing the ball deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief,'' Aikman said, ``is that if you think you can just
line up and run the football down people's throats, and not be able
to throw the football, you're going to struggle,'' adding that the
Cowboys during their Super Bowl years ``were able to run the ball
... but we also were able to throw the football very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Chan Gailey, the Cowboys ranked eighth offensively and
16th in the NFL in 1998 and 1999, respectively. They slipped under
the league average (21.5) in touchdown passes with 20 this season
en route to an 8-8 record and a first-round loss in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis over the past couple of years has been placed on
the running game,'' said Aikman, a proponent of the offense that
Reilly will bring to the Cowboys. ``We have not been as proficient
as we need to be in the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved one thing last year. And that is that you can run
the football pretty good and not score points, and lose games.
You've got to be able to make big plays to score points ... and
that's what has lacked in our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he wants the 2000 Cowboys to have ``a pass
mentality.'' Campo said he wants to ``attack defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a member of the NFL's influential Competition Committee,
has reasoned: ``We go into those meetings and set up rules to make
the passing game go. That's where a lot of the excitement \Rof the
game\S is, so we're going to be very aggressive in the passing game
and make sure that it's emphasized.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo made it clear that he is on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a defensive coach,'' said the Cowboys' longtime defensive
specialist, ``I've studied every scheme that you can throw against
a team, every situation for 11 years in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that I can bring that to this football team,
supporting the offensive coordinator, whoever that may be.''
Briefly Cornerback/punt returner Deion Sanders underwent
arthroscopic knee surgery Monday to repair meniscus cartilage
damage. The procedure was done in Florida. Sanders will miss next
week's Pro Bowl in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys coach Chan Gailey interviewed with the New
Orleans Saints Wednesday. If he is unable to land the Saints'
head-coaching job, he then most likely will take a position as
offensive coordinator (or pass-offense coach) with either Miami,
New Orleans or Atlanta.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
