<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI OPPOSES REPUBLICAN HEALTH CARE PROPOSAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Republican leaders in the state Senate proposed
Thursday that the state pick up all costs incurred by local
governments, including New York City, to provide coverage for
hundreds of thousands of New Yorkers who do not have medical
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the Republican leaders puts them at odds with their
chief ally in the Capitol, Gov. George Pataki, who has argued that
the state should not foot the entire bill for providing medical
coverage to low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan is intended to quell a storm of protest that
erupted from local government officials in December when Pataki and
legislative leaders from both parties agreed to create a new health
insurance program for low-income residents, with the costs of the
program equally divided between the state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials have increasingly complained that their share of
the new insurance costs _ about $340 million over the next 3 1-2
years _ would ultimately force them to choose between two
undesirable options: raising local taxes or cutting crucial
services.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal is similar to one that has been made by
Democrats in the Legislature, placing greater political pressure on
Pataki to endorse it or face taking the blame for creating huge
fiscal burdens for local governments. New York City's share would
total about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Bruno, the majority leader in the Republican-dominated
Senate, said Thursday that the state could afford to pick up the
cost of the entire program because of a projected budget surplus of
at least $1 billion this fiscal year, which ends on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said that he would push for his proposal to be part of any
final state budget agreement between the governor and the
Legislature. He contended that it was the state's responsibility to
``take that extra burden off the backs of county taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Pataki administration responded coolly to the proposal,
even going so far as to privately suggest that the governor would
call for cuts in other programs dear to the Legislature to pay for
the Senate Republican plan.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office also released a statement in which Pataki
said that he had saved local governments more than $3 billion over
the last five years through his policies, chief among them his
drive to restrain state and local spending for Medicaid, the
program that provides medical care for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democratic leaders in the state Assembly responded
with delight, seeing an opportunity to draw Republicans to their
side in their annual fight with the governor over enacting a state
budget. Richard Gottfried, the chairman of the Assembly's Health
Committee, said that Democrats had pushed for a plan similar to the
one that Republicans in the Senate proposed Thursday, only to be
rejected by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of not having a local share was an Assembly
position from the start,'' said Gottfried, a Democrat from
Manhattan. ``I welcome the Senate on board. I think they are in the
best position to bring the governor on board.''
</P>
<P>
   The groundswell of complaints across the state is particularly
troublesome for Pataki because it involves Republican county
executives, who wield great influence within their party and
represent suburban and upstate constituencies that played crucial
roles in Pataki's victories in the 1994 and 1998 races for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Robert R. Gregory, the executive director of the New York
Association of Counties, applauded the proposal by the Senate.
``Counties have limited resources,'' he said. ``If more revenue is
needed, the only place for counties to go is a sales tax or a
property tax'' increase.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance program at the center of the dispute was created
in December after a series of protracted negotiations between
Pataki, Bruno and Sheldon Silver, a Democrat who is speaker of the
Assembly. It is one of the most ambitious efforts in recent memory
to deal with the growing number _ now more than three million _ of
medically uninsured New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for providing free coverage to families earning
up to 150 percent of the federal poverty line, meaning that a
family of four with an annual income of $25,000 or less could
receive coverage without paying premiums. The program would cost
nearly $700 million in federal funds over the next 3 1-2 years. The
plan also requires $700 million in state and local funds over the
same period. The localities and the state would split those costs
evenly _ if the Senate plan unveiled Thursday is not approved.
</P>
<P>
   The state expects as many as 500,000 uninsured New Yorkers to
apply for medical coverage over the next 3 1-2 years as a result of
the health care initiative. The state plans to pay for its share of
the insurance costs with revenue from a new 55-cent cigarette tax,
as well as a share of the $400 million a year that it is to receive
from the nation's settlement with tobacco companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
