u w BC-CLINTON-HEALTH-1STLD-     01-27 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HEALTH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES FAR-REACHING PLAN ON DRUGS AND THE UNINSURED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS throughout to update text, flesh out proposals, add
details; no pickup.) 
 (nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton proposed an ambitious,
multifaceted health care agenda Wednesday night, calling on
Congress to provide prescription drugs to the elderly, new
government subsidies to help people buy health insurance, new tax
breaks for long-term care and a new federal law to define the
rights of people in health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address, Clinton urged Congress to
``give every senior a voluntary choice of affordable coverage for
prescription drugs.'' But contrary to expectations, he did not
dwell on this proposal, and he did not accuse drug companies of
charging excessive prices, as he often has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's restraint may have indicated that he wanted to work
with Republicans and the drug industry to forge a compromise on
Medicare drug benefits. Or it may simply have reflected the fact
that his speech was packed with dozens of proposals on health care,
education, gun control and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, drug company lobbyists were saying they feared the
president would attack their industry before a national television
audience, but the attack never came. Alan F. Holmer, president of
the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, was asked
for comment tonight, but had no immediate reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The president proposed a new tax credit for pharmaceutical
companies that develop vaccines and drugs to prevent or treat AIDS,
malaria, and other diseases afflicting millions of people in the
third world.
</P>
<P>
   He also highlighted his request to spend more on mental health
care, as recommended by Tipper Gore, the wife of Vice President Al
Gore. And without giving details, Clinton said he wanted government
action to prevent medical errors that harm tens of thousands of
people a year.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said Clinton would ask Congress to dedicate nearly $400
billion of the expected budget surplus over the next decade to
shore up the finances of Medicare and to help pay the cost of new
outpatient drug benefits for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, the White House disclosed many of the
president's health care proposals. But Wednesday night, Clinton
discussed the package as a whole and wrapped it together with a
common theme.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare finances health care for 39 million people who are
elderly or disabled. When Clinton unveiled his pharmaceutical plan
in June, he said it would cost $118 billion over 10 years. But the
Congressional Budget Office said the cost would exceed $165
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that all Medicare beneficiaries should have access
to an affordable option for insurance coverage of prescription drug
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifesaving drugs are an indispensable part of modern
medicine,'' Clinton said Wednesday night. ``No one creating a
Medicare program today would even think of excluding coverage for
prescription drugs. Yet, more than three in five of our seniors now
lack dependable drug coverage, which can lengthen and enrich their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The president referred to drug prices in only one sentence of
his speech, and did not call for government price controls.
``Millions of older Americans who need prescription drugs the most
pay the highest prices for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In good conscience, Clinton said, ``we cannot let another year
pass without extending to all seniors the lifeline of affordable
prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the guests invited to Wednesday night's session was Pat
Brown of Johnson City, Tenn., a retiree who spends $4,000 of her
savings each year on prescription drugs for heart and thyroid
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's health care proposals will set the tone this year for
campaign debates and will influence the agenda of Congress.
Republicans, while favoring different approaches, said Wednesday
night that they wanted to address many of the problems cataloged by
Clinton: the growing number of Americans without health insurance,
the frustrations of HMO patients and the desperation of elderly
people seeking affordable prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has already laid some groundwork for legislation on
these issues, and many of the president's proposals have some
election-year appeal to voters.
</P>
<P>
   One new item in Clinton's package was a proposal for a tax
credit to accelerate the development of vaccines for malaria,
tuberculosis and AIDS. Jennings said the tax credit would create an
incentive for the pharmaceutical industry to invest in development
of vaccines for poor countries, which often cannot afford to buy
the vaccines they need.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and the House passed different versions of
legislation defining patients' rights last year. But only the House
version, which would make it easier for patients to sue HMOs for
injuries, is acceptable to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Wednesday night that any legislation on
this issue must include ``an enforcement mechanism, to ensure
recourse for patients who have been harmed as a result of a health
plan's actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The president asked Congress Wednesday night to help millions of
Americans get health insurance by creating new tax breaks and by
expanding existing programs. He would, for example, let parents
enroll in a children's health program created in 1997. These
initiatives, taken together, would cost $110 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   That would be ``the largest investment in health care in the 35
years since the creation of Medicare,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
