<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-SUPER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS AND AGGIES JOIN FORCES ON RAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You know things are good with the St. Louis Rams when
former Aggies players and ex-Longhorns players are pulling in the
same direction.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' improbable ascent from a 4-12 last-place team in 1998
to NFL's biggest showcase in this season has former Texas players
Taje Allen (third-year cornerback) and Derek Lewis (rookie tight
end) and former Texas A&AMP;M standouts Cameron Spikes (rookie guard)
and Rich Coady (rookie safety) doing their best rendition of ``we
are the world'' togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's more like ``we are in the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat up on Taje and Derek after Texas A&AMP;M beat Texas,''
said Coady, who went to high school at Richardson Pearce.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are teammates now. We are all just happy to be in the
Super Bowl. I went to three Super Bowls as a fan growing up. Coming
as a player has always been a dream. To be here is exciting to
me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spikes echoed Coady's sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing bigger than the Super Bowl,'' Spikes said.
``Playing in the NFL has been my dream since starting playing
football as a kid. But to be here is unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Spikes and Coady, who were part of Texas A&AMP;M's improbable
Big 12 title-game victory over Kansas State last year, this is also
not the first time Lewis and Allen have experienced the feeling of
achieving something no one else thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a Lubbock native, and Lewis, from New Orleans, were on
the Longhorns' team that shocked two-time defending national
champion Nebraska in the 1996 Big 12 championship game. Lewis, a
member of the Rams' practice squad, made the catch on the
now-famous fourth-down pass that sealed the victory.
</P>
<P>
   While those moments were special, each of the four says those
games don't even come close to the Super Bowl experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Nebraska victory was something else,'' said Allen, who
suffered through two lean years in St. Louis. ``But nothing
compares to the Super Bowl. The Rams have been losing for a long
time. To do what we did this year is unbelievable. We are trying to
savor the moment. We've got a chance to win this thing and be the
world champs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, known as much for his comedic flair at Texas as his play,
gives the game its proper spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can touch this, man,'' Lewis said. ``This is the show.
This is the biggest show on earth here. What is it, 800 million?
Billions are going to be watching. It's going to be China, Japan
and Australia. Man, this is bigger than Ringling Brothers in their
prime. You dream about going to the show. This is it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Aggies and Longhorns living together in harmony.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
