<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MAYOR-POLITICS-750     01-27 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-POLITICS-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A BUDGET THAT LOOKS BEYOND THE 5 BOROUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced Thursday that
he was not proposing anything in his new budget ``for political
purposes'' and was ``very offended'' that people could think
otherwise, the response from city Democrats was a collective roll
of the eyes. The mayor's budget, Democrats said, was an even more
political document than usual, with an income tax cut and an
aggressive stance toward unions aimed at the upstate and suburban
voters Giuliani needs in his undeclared United States Senate
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics? What politics?'' said a facetious Peter Vallone, the
speaker of the City Council, in his reaction to Giuliani's spending
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Although budgets are always political maps in which mayors lay
out their priorities and vision, Giuliani's newest spending plan,
full of the surpluses of prosperous times and seemingly with
something for everyone, is different from his other budgets in that
it reaches beyond the five boroughs to appeal to voters statewide.
The mayor's call for a 16 percent reduction in the municipal income
tax rate, although benefiting city workers only, would, for
example, burnish his credentials across New York as a tax-cutting
Republican who understands the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love cutting taxes,'' Giuliani said, then concluded with a
defense of the kind of supply side economics not usually embraced
in an overwhelmingly Democratic city: ``So, tax cutting can produce
more revenues. You need to think about it a little, but thinking
about it is really what makes for intelligent human beings.'' If
people cannot understand the relationship between reduced taxes and
an improved economy, the mayor said, ``then you should be studying
the economy of Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists generally viewed Giuliani's budget as
smart Senate politics intended to put the mayor just to the right
of center. ``Who is he talking to when he talks tax cuts?'' said
Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic political consultant. ``He's not
talking to Manhattan liberals, who aren't going to vote for him.
He's talking to outer-borough Catholics, outer-borough ethnics.
He's talking to people in the suburbs, he's talking to people in
Nassau County. He's telling them he's a good manager and he shares
their values.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, who said he did not oppose the income tax cut, which
could take effect as early as July, also said he understood its
purpose. ``If it wasn't an election year, would he have mentioned
it?'' Vallone said. ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Giuliani's proposal to give city workers wage
increases based solely on merit, not across the board, will
probably be seen by upstate and suburban voters as a desirable
crackdown on the city's powerful unions. Giuliani was in effect
saying that he is an enemy not of all teachers, just bad teachers.
``The city will not agree to a single-percentage pay increase,''
Giuliani said. ``That era is over.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the city would require, in labor negotiations,
that city workers be offered up to five levels of merit pay
increases, including no increase at all. He also said he wanted
more flexibility to remove the worst employees. Across-the-board
increases, he said, mean that ``the very best teacher gets the same
raise as the very worst teacher,'' and therefore, teacher
``performance descends to the lowest common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's budget presentation was also striking for its lengthy
complaint, worthy of a senator, about how much more New York state
sends to Washington in federal taxes than it gets back in revenue.
Quoting a study by the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard
University and Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., Giuliani said
the state sent $15 billion more to Washington than it got in
return. He added, to no one's surprise, that states like Arkansas _
the home of his likely opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, before she
moved this month to Westchester County _ end up with a surplus.
``So essentially what's happening is New Yorkers are subsidizing
other places,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, responded that she had
been speaking out about New York's unfair tax burden since last
summer, and added, ``It sounds like they're stealing a page from
our playbook.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate race, Giuliani has a narrow edge over Mrs. Clinton
in statewide polls, but his vulnerable areas with voters remain his
policies toward the homeless and the state of the city's schools.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Thursday, the mayor offered more details on a variety of
education proposals he made in his State of the City speech earlier
this month, including spending $45 million to privatize failing
schools and $6 million for a school voucher program. He also
suggested that the city could save money by selling the Brooklyn
building that houses the Board of Education's headquarters, and by
reducing the school bureaucracy by 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to sell that damn building,'' said Giuliani,
promising that the city would introduce a resolution for the sale
to the board in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also said he would expand his program for the homeless,
although his budget calls for only a modest increase in funds for
the Department of Homeless Services, from $176 million in fiscal
year 2000 to $181 million in fiscal year 2001. But Giuliani, who
spent the fall defending his policies toward the city's homeless,
said he was spending ``significantly more on less people,'' and
those who say the city is not compassionate are engaging in
``political spin.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added, ``There are people who make their money out of
the welfare industry,'' but as the lives of the homeless improve,
their advocates ``have less money, less budget, less authority, and
you put them on television less, which might actually be the thing
that motivates them more than anything else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
