<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CAMPAIGNS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HINTS ON AD
</P>
<P>
   With his camp clearly concerned about anything that might swing
enough voters to deny him a clear victory in New Hampshire, Sen.
John McCain told reporters Thursday that he thought Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas was about to ``go negative.'' But a minute later
said, ``I believe he's a decent man and I believe he won't do it.''
Bush aides said his campaign had considered, but then rejected, the
idea of a television advertisement based on McCain's suggestion in
Wednesday night's debate that President Clinton had based his tax
cut plan on McCain's own plan.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES GOES NORTH
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes Thursday made what is for most candidates a rare
visit to the sparsely populated and very snowy New Hampshire north
country. ``It takes more than distance to stop this campaign,''
Forbes told about 120 people at the Opera House in Littleton, 83
miles north of Concord.
</P>
<P>
   PRAISE FOR A NATIVE SON
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the New Hampshire House of Representatives, Alan
Keyes, the only black presidential candidate, Thursday paid homage
to Daniel Webster, the 19th-century abolitionist senator and New
Hampshire native. ``If Webster had not spoken,'' Keyes, a
Republican, said, ``Lincoln would not have succeeded. The heritage
here in New Hampshire is awesome.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BAUER ON TOUR
</P>
<P>
   Gary L. Bauer toured small businesses in Manchester, Hooksett
and Nashua, N.H., Thursday and appeared on a radio talk show.
Later, Bauer addressed the Strafford County Republican Lincoln Day
Dinner in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY CANCELED
</P>
<P>
   Having challenged the South Carolina Republican Party to open
all polling places in the Feb. 19 primary, the state's Democratic
Party has decided it cannot afford to do the same, and has canceled
its March 9 primary. It will hold caucuses the same day. A
Democratic state legislator, in a complaint to the Justice
Department and Thursday in a lawsuit, accused the Republicans of
violating the Voting Rights Act by failing to open polls in black
areas. A party official said Thursday that the party would try to
open all polls, using 6,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
