<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ACLU-MOTORISTS-KAN &LR;      01-27 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACLU-MOTORISTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACLU STUDIES CITATIONS FOR RACIAL PROFILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It is not uncommon, civil-rights advocates
say, to hear minority motorists say they are unfairly singled out
by police when driving in Kansas City's suburbs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, the American Civil Liberties Union has collected
accounts from those who say they face such discrimination _ black
and other minority commuters _ who believe police automatically
cast them as suspicious outsiders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But until now, no effort has been made to gather evidence to
determine whether motorists are stopped simply because of the color
of their skin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To get at that question, the ACLU is examining thousands of 1998
traffic citations issued by police in Leawood and Prairie Village
in Kansas and Grandview in Missouri, all suburbs of Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling is a practice by some police of making
decisions, in part, based on ethnicity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, we have received complaints on a regular basis
from individuals stopped by police in certain jurisdictions where
those stops seem to be based, in part, on racial profiling,'' said
Dick Kurtenbach, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union in Kansas and western Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to determine whether there is some pattern we can
identify in a more scientific way,'' he said. ``We need to put some
meat to the anecdotal information.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A similar study, though much larger, was proposed in a bill
before the Kansas Legislature. Under the bill introduced last week,
the Kansas attorney general would compile a report on the race,
gender, ethnic background and age of those stopped in Kansas. The
report would be based on information supplied by all Kansas law
enforcement agencies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU study is being done by statisticians at the University
of Missouri-Kansas City. A report on their conclusions still is
three months off, Kurtenbach said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prairie Village, Leawood and Grandview were chosen, he said,
because those are the communities where the ACLU has received the
most complaints over the last several years. The ACLU does not
document how many grievances it receives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police officers in those communities deny racial profiling takes
place and say they are eager to prove that point with the help of
the ACLU study. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dickey, deputy police chief in Grandview, said some
minority motorists use the issue as a smokescreen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In a majority of the cases, people just use it as an excuse,''
he said. ``But nobody's perfect and this is not a perfect world.
I'm sure things like (racial profiling) go on in places. But we
don't do that here, not to my knowledge anyway.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sid Mitchell, Leawood police chief, said all city officials are
receiving mandatory racial sensitivity training this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good business to treat people in a discriminatory
fashion,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several attempts this week to reach Charles Grover, Prairie
Village police chief, were unsuccessful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 years that he has been with the civil-rights group,
Kurtenbach said he had received fewer than 10 racial-profiling
complaints from those living in Kansas City's urban core, an area
with a larger percentage of minority residents. But in the suburbs,
he says he gets ``several'' complaints a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, Kurtenbach said, it's difficult to draw broad
conclusions about unfair police practices, or whether racial
profiling is simply a matter of bad decisions being made by
individuals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to indict the suburbs,'' Kurtenbach said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Crew, director of the ACLU's Campaign Against Racial
Profiling, said profiling has emerged as the new face of racism,
simmering just below the surface of polite society. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is law enforcement by blind guesswork and hunches,'' Crew
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of focusing on probable cause, police officers look
for a minor excuse _ a broken turn signal or crossing the center
line _ to go fishing. We believe those hunches are inevitably
infected by unconscious racism and unconscious stereotype.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But hard numbers are not easy to come by. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An ACLU study in Maryland revealed a disparity in motorist stops
and searches. Although minorities account for 22 percent of all
drivers on the highway studied, they were more than 70 percent of
those detained and searched, the ACLU reports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also, a /{Wichita Eagle/} study found that 18 percent of the
motorists ticketed in 1997 and 1998 in that city were black, even
though black persons make up 12 percent of the population. The
newspaper found percentages were even higher on area interstates,
where 19.5 percent of the ticketed motorists were black. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU study puts Kansas City in the middle of a roiling
national debate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Results of a Gallup poll released in December show Americans
strongly disapprove of profiling. The poll found that 59 percent of
Americans believe police officers use racial profiling, and 81
percent disapprove of the practice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has called the practice ``morally
indefensible'' and last June signed an executive order for federal
law enforcement agencies to gather data on race, gender and
ethnicity of people they stop to question. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley both
say that if elected they would ban the practice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, North Carolina became the first state to adopt
legislation requiring law enforcement officials to collect racial
data on traffic stops. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Voluntary efforts are under way in major U.S. cities such as San
Francisco, San Diego, San Jose and Houston. And in Oregon, two
dozen Portland-area police agencies have endorsed a resolution
against racial profiling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Haley, a Kansas City, Kan., Democrat, helped
introduce a bill that would require police agencies in Kansas to
collect and report to the state information on the race, gender,
ethnic background and age of those stopped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to hold any sector of our community to greater
scrutiny than another,'' Haley said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the attorney general would report the traffic-stop
information to the governor and the state Legislature in 2002. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas would be one of only five states in the nation with such
a law, said Kurtenbach. The ACLU supports the bill. Missouri has no
such legislation pending. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Racial traffic data, both sides of the national debate say, will
help calm simmering tensions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Darden, former Los Angeles prosecutor and a staunch
critic of racial profiling, has said he is convinced that the first
African-American motorist who owned a Model T was pulled over for
no reason. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crew said: ``That story conveys the kind of weariness the public
has of racial profiling. This is a problem that we should have left
behind an awful long time ago.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2340EST &QL; 
