<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MAYOR-BUDGET-ART-N     01-27 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-BUDGET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI PROPOSES TAX CUTS AND NEW SYSTEM OF PAY RAISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-MAYOR-POLITICS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani called Thursday for an end
to automatic pay raises for unionized city workers, from trash
collectors to teachers, and proposed $2 billion worth of tax cuts
over the next four years to residents and businesses as part of a
$36.8 billion budget he released.
 &UR;  &LR;  The spending plan for the 2001 fiscal year is balanced in part by
relying on an expected record surplus generated in the current
fiscal year by the city's supercharged economy.
 &UR;  &LR;  The mayor devoted a large portion of his budget speech to
education and the city's public schools, insisting once again that
the school system was out of control and its management bloated. He
singled out teachers in proposing a new system based solely on
merit pay raises _ a plan opposed by union leaders who either
object outright or insist that any merit system be at least linked
to base raises tied to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani further roiled Board of Education officials and union
leaders by proposing to privatize failing schools and some services
like summer programs, and he once again advocated a pilot program
that would offer some parents vouchers to allow their children to
attend private schools.
 &UR;  &LR;  He proposed a cut in the city's income tax rate for all New
Yorkers that would average 16 percent. Although his administration
had said on Wednesday that the cut would not take effect until
2002, after he leaves office, the mayor said Thursday that his
critics in the City Council had persuaded him to accelerate the
sizable reduction to this fiscal year, which begins in July. That
cut would eventually cost $784 million a year, and it would save a
New Yorker making $75,000 a year about $290.
</P>
<P>
   City Council leaders and budget watchdogs offered unusually
generous praise for the mayor's plan. But they warned that it left
the city vulnerable to potentially severe deficits if the economy
faltered. At the same time, the critics said, the mayor's perennial
plan to reduce spending for cultural groups, parks and libraries is
unacceptable and unnecessary when the city is flush with cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like using an inheritance to pay your mortgage,'' said
Diana Fortuna, president of the Citizens &UR;  &LR; Budget Commission,
referring to Giuliani's plan to use $1.5 billion of the expected
$2.2 billion surplus to balance next year's budget. ``It is
short-run thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders on Thursday also condemned the mayor's so-called
revolution in labor relations, saying that if the city replaced
automatic raises with pay increases based exclusively on merit,
employees would be vulnerable to arbitrary decisions and political
pressure by their superiors.
</P>
<P>
   The union leaders and Council Speaker Peter F. Vallone, one of
their most powerful allies, said they were not in principle opposed
to tying compensation in part to worker performance, an
increasingly popular bargaining tactic among mayors and governors
across the United States. But they said that city workers had
already agreed in 1995 to help balance the budget by accepting two
years of wage freezes, cutting their pay relative to the private
sector and other local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Merit-pay provisions do encourage many employees to work harder,
labor experts say. But these provisions can also sow divisiveness
within a work force, often creating resentment when one group of
unionized employees receives more than another. Union officials
usually attack merit pay systems, arguing that they are based on
subjective criteria and often lead to punishments for employees who
speak out against management and rewards for employees who toe
management's line.
</P>
<P>
   Overall school spending would rise to $11.3 billion, but it
comes with a number of strings attached. Giuliani offered the
school system $45 million to improve the performance of its 97 most
troubled schools, but only if it agrees to turn at least 19 of them
over to private management companies.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions in cultural programs and social services include
a proposed $42 million cut for libraries, $18 million in cuts for
museums and dance, opera and other performing arts groups, and a
$7.5 million cut in youth programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
