<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MCGOWEN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Ill.) 
DEANE McGOWEN, 83, A NEW YORK TIMES SPORTSWRITER 
 (rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deane McGowen, a sportswriter for The New York Times for more
than three decades, died Saturday at North Country Hospital in
Newport, Vt. McGowen, who lived in Newport, was 83.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications of emphysema, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   McGowen covered a wide range of sports, most notably boxing and
college athletics, and was a recipient in 1997 of the Boxing
Writers Association of America's A.J. Liebling Award for
outstanding coverage.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Rock Island, Ill., he attended Dartmouth College,
served in the Army during World War II and became a reporter for
The Times in 1949. His father, Roscoe McGowen, covered the Brooklyn
Dodgers for The Times for almost 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   McGowen is survived by his wife, Anita; a son, Richard Deane, of
River Vale, N.J.; a daughter, Sharon Stoll, of Montvale, N.J., from
his marriage to his first wife, Irene, who died in 1970; five
stepchildren, Allan Andrews of Chandler, Ariz., Douglas Andrews of
Kalispell, Mont., Stephen Andrews of Stockholm, N.J., Susan Olmsted
of Middleton, Mass., and Andrea Downard of Minerva, Ohio; 13
grandchildren; and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-27-00 2343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000127.0518 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     01-27 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S NOW THE FISHER KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jeff Fisher has come a long way since graduating in
1976 from Taft High in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, where he
was an extraordinary receiver his senior season. His team was
beaten in the playoffs by a Charles White-led San Fernando High
powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   He has come a long way since 1980, when he was a starting USC
cornerback who inadvertently tipped an almost certain interception
away from his teammate, Dennis Smith, on a play in which UCLA's
Freeman McNeil made a game-winning catch.
</P>
<P>
   He has come a long way since he retired from the Chicago Bears
after the 1985 season and went to work for a fledging computer
software company called J.B. Systems _ now known as Mainsaver _ in
Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   He has come a long way since he was coaxed by his Chicago
defensive coordinator, Buddy Ryan, to join Ryan at his new
head-coaching position with the Philadelphia Eagles in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who in subsequent seasons lived the gypsy life of an NFL
assistant with stopovers with the Los Angeles Rams and San
Francisco 49ers before joining the Houston Oilers in 1994, has come
a long way since the beginning of training camp last July when his
boss, Bud Adams, issued an ominous public statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down to the nitty-gritty this year and I really don't
need to tell them (the score),'' said the Tennessee Titans owner,
referring to Fisher and the team's general manager, Floyd Reese.
``I think they understand where we're coming from ... with this
idea of being 8-8 three years in a row and with the talent we have
on this squad right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Fisher, who assumed control of the Oilers 10 games into
the 1994 season after Jack Pardee was fired, and had to endure the
vagabond existence the franchise went through after moving to
Tennessee in 1997, was at a crossroads in his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   The talented Titans, playing for the first time in their new
Adelphia Coliseum, were expected by Adams to have a successful
season, or there would be consequences.
</P>
<P>
   As Reese said: ``We knew what Mr. Adams expected. I've spent a
lot of years in the NFL and that's just the nature of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's doubtful even Adams expected what has unfolded:
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!!off!A Super Bowl appearance by his team Sunday against
the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!!off!A 13-3 regular-season record.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!!off!A dramatic, final-second victory against the Buffalo
Bills in the postseason opener.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!!off!An unexpected road playoff victory over the
Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!!off!A stirring AFC Championship Game upset of the
Jacksonville Jaguars on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Fisher, perched on that perennial scorching seat
endemic to those in his craft who have fashioned mediocre records,
has become one of the NFL's reigning coaching geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great coach who's done just a great, great job,'' said
Adams, quickly changing his tune.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher has kept this storybook season in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's nice what has happened to us _ a great
testimony to the dedication and resilience of my players,'' said
Fisher. ``But I know how difficult it is to win in this league.
There are some good coaches around who have had a hard time. There
is such a fine line between winning and losing. In every win this
season, I can point to two or three plays that, if we don't make,
we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning, of course, usually begets unrestrained fondness by
athletes for their caretaker _ and the Titans aren't exceptions. At
Thursday morning's news conference in a huge tent next to their
hotel in Buckhead, the Tennessee players had nothing but positive
things to say about Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is a gutsy coach who goes about his work in a mellow but
intense manner,'' said Steve McNair, the Titans' quarterback. ``You
always know where Jeff stands. And he has tremendous courage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like most about Jeff Fisher is he lets you know exactly
where you stand,'' said Lorenzo Neal, the Titans' blocking
fullback. ``And he has a way of keeping everyone loose. He told us
players before the Jacksonville game that if any of the assistant
coaches were acting uptight to let him know about it so he would
get on them. It broke everyone up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In coaching, you have to earn trust and respect from your
players,'' said Fisher. ``It doesn't come automatically. You have
to show your players that you're fair and that you're strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even back in high school, you just knew Jeff Fisher was
destined for big things in life,'' said sports talk-radio
personality Steve Hartman, who graduated in the same Taft High
class as Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tessalone, the longtime sports information director at USC,
knew Fisher was a special person on that day a long time ago at the
Coliseum when the player was victimized by that 58-yard McNeil
scoring reception that resulted in a 20-17 UCLA victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget going up to Jeff in our dressing room
afterward and seeing his head bowed and how unhappy he was,''
related Tessalone. ``I told him, `You know all the reporters will
want to talk to you about that play. But you don't have to talk to
them if you don't want to.' And Jeff said, `Let's go. I'll talk to
them now.' I knew right then this wasn't an ordinary person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
